<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2992 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-DEM-BASE-1STLD-WRITET     08-16 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-BASE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS FACE LEFT TO APPEASE LIBERAL WING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Mass., Mich., Ark., Minn., D.C.)   (Eds.: UPDATES to add Jackson's speech, background on Lieberman's
meeting with Waters, 2nd take of new material; no pickup.) 
By JAMES DAO and KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Faced with an undercurrent of grumbling about the
centrist tone of its ticket and platform, the Democratic Party
devoted much of its convention Tuesday to reassuring its liberal
base, sending its vice-presidential candidate, Sen. Joseph
Lieberman, before black delegates to declare his unequivocal
support for affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was for affirmative action, am for affirmative action and
will be for affirmative action,'' Lieberman, who has been critical
of racial preference programs, told the convention's Black Caucus.
Immediately afterward, Rep. Maxine Waters of Los Angeles, who had
voiced strong doubts about Lieberman this weekend, declared she
would support him wholeheartedly.
</P>
<P>
   But other leading liberals continued to express doubts about
Gore himself. ``The most important thing to me is that Gore is not
emotionally in touch with the party's base,'' Mayor Willie Brown of
San Francisco said in an interview. ``If he's smart, he'll go to a
black church every Sunday from now until Election Day.''
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to gauge the depth of discontent among black
voters, union members and other core Democrats with the ticket and
its agenda. But Gore's selection of Lieberman, a Connecticut
senator who has staked out centrist positions not only on
affirmative action, but also on school vouchers, military spending
and Social Security, seems to have crystallized their worries that
Gore is taking them for granted.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign moved swiftly Tuesday to address worries
within the party, not only through Lieberman's appearance before
the Black Caucus, but also by dispatching two black Cabinet
secretaries, Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater and Labor
Secretary Alexis Herman, and other prominent black Democrats to
declare their strong support.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the list of convention speakers Tuesday night
was almost a Who's Who of leaders from the party's liberal wing,
including two union presidents, a prominent environmentalist, gay
rights and abortion rights leaders, and the Rev. Jesse Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Jackson alluded to the party's fault lines,
saying, ``Within our party we can fight for the right to do what's
right. We can change, we can challenge, we can agree to disagree,
we can agree to be agreeable. But we are family.''
</P>
<P>
   Discontent among core Democrats poses a potentially significant
problem for Gore because black voters and union members are among
the party's largest and most loyal constituencies. And while some
of those voters might defect to Ralph Nader, the Green Party
candidate, the Democrats' greater fear is that some base voters
will stay home on Election Day, making it difficult to win swing
states like Michigan and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are saying, `We don't see the Democrats standing for
us,''' said Sen. Paul Wellstone of Minnesota, a leader of the
party's liberal wing. ``It is a hurdle to overcome. And the vice
president needs to do it soon.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' liberal lineup represented a sharp contrast from
the Republicans, who carefully choreographed their convention two
weeks ago to keep conservative activists backstage, making it
easier for their presidential nominee, Gov. George W. Bush, to
reach out to moderate swing voters.
</P>
<P>
   But many Democrats say that the Republicans appeased their core
voters in other ways: with the party platform, which remains
staunchly conservative on issues like abortion, gay rights and
military spending, and in the selection of Dick Cheney, who
compiled a consistently conservative record in Congress, as the
vice-presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Gore reached toward the political center with his
selection of Lieberman, a leader of the party's centrist ``New
Democrat'' wing. And his aides rebuffed repeated efforts by
liberals to insert language into the platform calling for universal
health care, cuts in defense spending, a moratorium on capital
punishment and increased spending on the poor.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign's efforts Tuesday to reassure black delegates
about Lieberman's record took place in typical Democratic fashion
amid public displays of discontent and ego politics.
</P>
<P>
   His comments to black delegates were prompted, for the most
part, by Waters' decision to voice her concerns about his record in
public forums on both Sunday and Monday. Shortly after she showed
up for Tuesday morning's caucus meeting at the Westin Bonaventure
Hotel, she was cornered by Herman, one of the Gore campaign's
leading emissaries to black Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Standing nearly nose-to-nose with Waters, who had her back to a
ballroom door, Herman began laying out the case for Lieberman until
aides realized the scene was being watched by reporters. They then
ushered the two women into the closed ballroom. When Lieberman
arrived to address the caucus, he was brought into a backstage
holding room to personally address Waters' concerns.
</P>
<P>
   As he did, Slater was speaking to the caucus members and
crediting Lieberman for voting against a 1998 Republican amendment
aimed at ending a federal program that reserves a portion of
highway spending for minority-owned firms. Then Eleanor Holmes
Norton, the delegate from the District of Columbia, vouched for his
civil rights credentials.
</P>
<P>
   She acknowledged that they had occasional policy differences,
but said they were ``overwhelmed by the many things we have in
common.'' And she said that President Clinton, who also embraced a
centrist agenda, had taught her how to live with disagreements
within the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, if you're with me most of the time, you my man,'' she
said. ``Don't go too far now. But if you're with me most of the
time, you the man.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Lieberman took the stage to a prolonged standing ovation
from the black delegates. After leading the crowd in singing a
round of ``Happy Birthday'' to Waters, he told of his religious
belief that ``every human being is created in God's image'' and
recounted his participation in the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King
Jr.'s 1963 March on Washington and in Mississippi voter
registration drives. He dropped the names of civil rights leaders
and said that equal opportunity was ``the most fundamental
principle of American life.''
</P>
<P>
   That being said, he joked that the recent scrutiny given to his
every past word and vote was ``like having a medical procedure
without an anesthetic.''
</P>
<P>
   That record includes comments he reportedly made in 1995 that
affirmative action programs that reward people strictly because of
race or gender were ``patently unfair.'' He also was quoted then as
saying, ``You can't defend policies that are based on group
preferences as opposed to individual opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   And when asked his views on California's Proposition 209, which
banned state-financed affirmative action programs, Lieberman
reportedly said, ``I can't see how I could be opposed to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Later that year, when Clinton proposed his ``mend it, don't end
it'' approach to tinkering with affirmative action, Lieberman
supported the initiative in a speech on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately after Gore selected Lieberman last week,
campaign aides began explaining those stands to minority group
leaders. Just hours after word of the decision leaked on Aug. 7,
they arranged a conference call between Lieberman and leading
blacks in Congress. Waters did not participate in the call.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking Tuesday, Lieberman said that he had been troubled by
racial quotas but had supported affirmative action ``because
history and current reality make it necessary.'' He noted that he
had declined a request for a letter stating his support for
Proposition 209 and had voted against two Senate measures that
would have eliminated federal affirmative action programs.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding vouchers, Lieberman said, as he has repeatedly in the
last week, that he supported pilot programs aimed at providing
alternatives for children in failing schools. But he added that he
strongly supported public education and Gore's spending proposals
to reduce class sizes.
</P>
<P>
   After Lieberman's speech, Waters said that she would now feel
comfortable supporting and campaigning for the Democratic ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democratic officials are particularly concerned that Gore's
centrist agenda will dampen enthusiasm in swing states where a
large turnout of blacks, who were Clinton's most loyal supporters
during impeachment, and other core Democrats is vital. That agenda
includes staunch support for global trade and the death penalty,
increased military spending, an incremental approach to expanding
health coverage and a focus on using the federal surplus for debt
reduction, more than on expanding social programs.
</P>
<P>
   By and large, the party's progressive leaders said they planned
to work hard for Gore's election. But their concerns about how the
ticket is playing among rank-and-file Democrats were expressed in
their tendency to focus on the perils of a Bush victory more than
on the benefits of a Gore administration.
</P>
<P>
   But some liberals said a campaign built mainly on raising fears
about the Republicans would fail to win over independent voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``That just conveys the idea that this is a lesser-of-two-evils
election,'' said Tom Hayden, a state Senator from California and a
Gore delegate. ``My recommendation is to reach out to the Nader
constituency instead of trying to become more Republican. The
Democrats are Republican enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
