r s BC-OLY-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     08-16 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALL THRIVING WITH NEW OUTLOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The black leather motorcycle pants are gone,
replaced by a black terry cloth robe. Gary Hall Jr.'s habit has
changed and so have his habits. The madcap kid of four years ago
has become much more sedate. He has stripped his life down to its
skivvies.
</P>
<P>
   Diabetes can do that to a dude. Hall, 25, discovered he had the
blood-sugar disorder in March of 1999. The diagnosis forced Hall to
seriously consider the consequences of his actions, something he
wasn't wont to do in his wild-child days when he was carving donuts
on a golf course in a car or smoking marijuana (he served a
three-month swimming suspension in 1998 after testing positive for
the substance) or tuning out the world to the strains of the
Grateful Dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was invincible before,'' Hall said. ``Finding out
I had diabetes was a real shock. It gave me a taste of mortality.
That can be a very sobering experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Through insolence and insulin injections, one thing never
changed: Hall always has been able to haul butt in the water.
</P>
<P>
   A second-place finish in the 100 freestyle on Sunday put Hall on
his second Olympic team. His swim Tuesday in the 50-meter freestyle
at the U.S. Olympic Swimming Trials punctuated his revival
emphatically.
</P>
<P>
   Hall broke Tom Jager's 10-year-old American record in the
one-lap sprint by .05 seconds with a 21.76 clocking at the IUPUI
Natatorium. His training partner, Hart High graduate Anthony Ervin,
also finished under Jager's record at 21.80 to qualify to swim the
event at the Sydney Games next month.
</P>
<P>
   Hall's time was the fastest recorded in an eight-man final;
Russia's Alexander Popov set the world record of 21.64 in an
individual time trial. Hall didn't believe the timing of his record
swim was a coincidence; he'd like to think his standing up to
diabetes was what ultimately made surpassing Jager's record
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``There the saying that what doesn't kill you makes you
stronger,'' Hall said. ``Maybe what I've been through has made me
stronger. Maybe that's why I was able to break this record.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 Hall got a lot of press because he was the Steve
Prefontaine of swimming; a free spirit in a regimented sport that
spits out in cookie-cutter fashion the quiet, clean-cut and
uncontroversial types _ athletes not unlike Gary Hall Sr., who won
three medals at three Olympics, then became a model husband, father
and dentist.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Jr. made headlines because he was his father's son in the
pool and his father's diametrical opposite out of it.
</P>
<P>
   That made for good copy then, but now we find Hall infinitely
more interesting.
</P>
<P>
   His antics these days are largely confined to shadow boxing an
imaginary adversary before stepping to the blocks for his race. We
trust that's so. Because the truth is, Hall is sparring every day
with an opportunistic opponent that is not above throwing the
occasional sucker punch.
</P>
<P>
   Hall has to stay on his toes _ and toe the line. Failure to do
so could result in the loss of limb or even life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diabetes is the leading cause of blindness and amputation and
one of the leading causes of heart disease,'' Hall said, slipping a
public service announcement into his postrace interviews. ``That's
in the back of my mind. That's a motivating factor to take care of
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Every day Hall checks his blood-sugar levels as often as a
bodybuilder checks his physique in the gym mirror. Some days, the
lean, 6-foot-6 swimmer said, he has to give himself as many as
eight injections of insulin to maintain an energy equilibrium that
most of the rest of us take for granted.
</P>
<P>
   As Hall has said, diabetes is not a disease that can be cured.
At best, it can be contained. Hall is wed to diabetes for the rest
of his life, which is an awfully scary commitment for somebody his
age.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who goes through as much as I've gone through the last
four years is going to (emerge from the experience) different,''
Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   Hall doesn't see anything the same anymore. How could he? The
ambivalence he once used to have about swimming and his place in it
is as yesterday as Jager's record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have a better understanding of what the Olympics is
and the importance of it,'' Hall said. ``I may be a little more
appreciative of the experience this time around.''
</P>
<P>
   It bugs him that people may see him the same as they always
have, as the guy blessed with his father's Olympic genes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of resentful about the whole talent thing,'' Hall
said. ``People take it too far and expect me to be a great swimmer
just because my father was. I've been working hard just like
everyone else who made the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Given what he has gone through the past 16 months, the very
least that can be said of Hall is he has toughness to match his
talent. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Karen Crouse's column appears in the Daily News four days a week.
She can be reached at (818) 713-3619. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
