<HEADER>
A2997 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-WEBTV-TECH-LADN     08-16 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBTV-TECH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I WANT MY PC_TV
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MONROE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A medium offering music videos, news, cartoons and
animated series sounds like television -- but comes over another
screen in the house.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the era of the Web as freestanding entertainment
source and the gradual removal of the division between the living
room and the computer room.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the ``webisodes'' created by Brilliant Digital
Entertainment that could be coming soon to a television station
near you.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least to that television station's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   In a recently announced deal, a division of USA Networks will
syndicate the Woodland Hills company's animated feature series
based on such television shows as ``Xena: Warrior Princess.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This continues to bring together television and Web-based
resources,'' said Brilliant vice president of marketing and
communications Mary Lou Hotsko. ``It continues to expand our
syndication model.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts consider Brilliant one of the few companies
successfully finding a market for entertainment specifically meant
for Web users. The San Fernando Valley, however, features a growing
number of entertainment content producers making ``convergence'' a
common buzzword.
</P>
<P>
   The new genre has mostly seen failure -- witness the stumbling
Pop.com, an online film site that has had no product since its
October launch, despite the backing of studio giants like Steven
Spielberg -- but that doesn't stop content producers from trying.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Glendale's entertaindom.com launched an all-online
mock campaign ``Duke2000,'' a bid by the ``Doonesbury'' comic strip
character for the presidency. At the end of February, Burbank-based
FMiTV launched KIISFMi.com, a Web site based on the Los Angeles
radio station offering original programming, music and the latest
dance steps. Crucial to both is interaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's supposed to be a two-way environment,'' said FMiTV
Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Laurence Norjean. ``Let the
Web be what it's supposed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   In FMiTV's case, Norjean said sites like his are the first
places most people will see Web and television entertainment start
to blur. Kids will ``watch'' TV on their computer screens first,
but inevitably, their TV screens will carry Internet programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Web-based entertainment is in transition to become iTV,'' said
Norjean.
</P>
<P>
   But before it becomes commonplace, Web entertainment players and
analysts say streaming, the solution to herky-jerky Internet video,
must improve. Web entertainment companies also must retain ties
with traditional entertainment producers like television networks,
movie studios and radio stations. Duke's campaign adventures are
all available on the Web, for example, but he'll also appear on
``Larry King Live'' and on syndicated radio talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good entertainment is good entertainment,'' said Damon
Danielson, whose company, Dotcomix, is jointly distributing the
Duke2000 site with Entertaindom. ``It can come from a number of
sources.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Bills, an editor following entertainment and information
for Web-based analyst Hoovers Online, says the Studios USA deal is
the kind that keeps the 4-year-old Brilliant going.
</P>
<P>
   Studios USA will sell webisodes, centered on such characters as
Xena, the rock band KISS or movie character Ace Ventura to Web
sites operated by television stations in 220 markets around the
country. In Los Angeles, for example, the animated shows could
appear on the Web site operated by KTLA-TV (Channel 5), where the
televised version of Xena airs currently, said company officials.
</P>
<P>
   Brilliant also has distribution agreements with entertainment
conglomerate Time Warner and cable music channel VH-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think where Brilliant Digital has a leg up is that they have
very, very familiar characters and they've really been helped by
all these high-profile distribution agreements,'' said Bills.
</P>
<P>
   Norjean thinks the future of Web entertainment will require it
to offer more variety than mere TV shows modified for the Web. He
agrees, however, that Brilliant's ties with old school
entertainment are necessary -- for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can hear about it on TV, or in a magazine, or radio,
that's what's going to make people go to it,'' he said. ``You're
not on the Web until you turn on your computer.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
