<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 00:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3004 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEM-LIEBERMAN-1STLD-W     08-16 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-LIEBERMAN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN PLEDGES TO AVOID `NASTY' ATTACKS ON GOP'S BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Subs for earlier version to focus on candidate's pledge
regarding campaign conduct)  
(ART ADV: Photos CVN3, CVN12 and CVN13 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Pledging to avoid ``nasty'' partisan attacks on
the Republican presidential nominee, Gov. George W. Bush, Sen.
Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut said in an interview Tuesday that
he would use his Democratic convention address Wednesday night to
start ``a conversation with the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, who's been selected as Al Gore's runninng mate, said
that while he would not hesitate to ``respectfully'' point out
policy differences with the Republican Party, he would not play the
traditional role of the vice-presidential candidate as the attack
dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to Al about this,'' he said, ``and we're very
intent on talking about progress, not partisanship. This is not
going to be a campaign of personal attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Later Lieberman said, ``It doesn't have to be nasty; it doesn't
have to be partisan. I'm going to speak from the record of Al Gore,
the record of George Bush and the plans they've described.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he described Bush and Dick Cheney, the Republican
vice-presidential candidate, as ``decent and likable people'' who
represent ``a step backward for America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The choices here are very clear,'' Lieberman said. ``And these
choices I think will significantly affect the future of the people
of this country. Government doesn't do it all, but government sets
a tone, sets a direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, 58, conveyed a sense of easy anticipation as he
relaxed in a chair in a small room under the main convention stage.
About an hour later, he made an unscheduled foray onto the floor of
the convention, where he was mobbed by photographers. He waved and
blew kisses to the crowd, which responded with a delighted ovation.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Lieberman framed his role in the campaign
partly in the language of transition, of helping Democrats move
beyond the Clinton era.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud of what he's accomplished,'' Lieberman said of
President Clinton. ``And I feel I'm really able to work with Al
Gore to continue the prosperity that he's built. But even though
the Republicans seem to want to run against Bill Clinton, he's not
on the ballot, and part of my role, and my opportunity here, is to
sort of continue to talk about the smooth transition to keep the
prosperity going.''
</P>
<P>
   But his first task in his speech, Lieberman said, would be to
introduce himself to the American public _ ``who I am, what my
values are.'' He said he also planned to reintroduce Gore to the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in him,'' Lieberman said of Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think, certainly when I look at opinion polls, that a lot
of people don't know Al Gore,'' he said. ``And I think the more
they know him, the more they're going to like him. He's a person of
great strength, honor and tremendously creative intellect.''
</P>
<P>
   Through these themes, Leiberman said he hoped to foreshadow the
role he sees for himself in the campaign. By talking about his
values and his faith, he said he would try to help Gore reach swing
voters at the political center. By vouching for Gore's character,
he would try to neutralize the effects of the White House scandals.
</P>
<P>
   But Lieberman is learning how difficult it can be to stay
focused on those roles. In forging a reputation as a centrist
Democrat, he had taken positions and made statements that are
unpopular among more liberal Democrats. On Tuesday, he found
himself defending his views on affirmative action and school
vouchers to members of the Democratic National Committee's black
caucus.
</P>
<P>
   But otherwise, Lieberman reveled in what he calls ``my new
life,'' a life of arriving at airports past midnight and finding 25
reporters waiting, of being whisked about in motorcades as if
lifted on a magic carpet, of carrying the full measure of
expectation that comes from being the first Jew to be a
presidential running mate on a major ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is as if you've been touched, called,'' Lieberman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Nine days ago he and his wife, Hadassah, awoke to reports that
he had been chosen as Gore's running mate. Even now, he said, the
notion comes as a sort of surreal surprise, one that had seemed
beyond reach. And yet on Wednesday night, Lieberman will stand
before the nation and deliver the most important speech of his
life, one, he said, that he hopes a lifetime in politics has
prepared him for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though the scope is obviously enormously larger, in many ways
my 30 years of public life have prepared me for this moment,'' he
said. ``I don't mean that anyone is ever fully prepared, but I feel
as if all the experiences, all that I've learned are coming
together, are being tested, and frankly I find it exhilarating. ''
</P>
<P>
   This morning, when Lieberman walked to the convention podium for
a brief rehearsal, he grinned broadly and spread his arms wide, as
if eager to embrace this strange new life.
</P>
<P>
   ``An only-in-America moment,'' he said to a group of
photographers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 0031EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
