<HEADER>
A3007 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-SHOOTING-FATAL-LADN     08-16 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-FATAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN KILLS MOTHER OF HIS THREE CHILDREN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LISA VAN PROYEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Enraged that his relationship was ending, a man
sprayed bullets at the mother of his three children as she ran
through her office and across the street Tuesday in Studio City,
fatally shooting her after she tripped on a curb and fell, police
and co-workers said.
</P>
<P>
   He then turned the gun on himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him shoot three times at the girl. Then he put the gun
to his head once,'' one witness said, declining to identify
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Cortez, 34, was killed near her job at MedStar Foot and
Ankle, police said. She had repeatedly told friends and co-workers
that she could handle her boyfriend's longtime abuse on her own,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, this guy was capable of a lot more than we thought.
She felt like she could handle it -- and then this happens,'' said
Allen Selner, a podiatrist at MedStar on Laurel Canyon Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   The boyfriend, who was not identified, apparently followed
Cortez to work from their home in Los Angeles, where they lived
with their son, Brad, 8, and two daughters, Jennifer, 12, and
Kelly, 5.
</P>
<P>
   As Cortez stepped out of her car to report to work about 8 a.m.,
he fired several rounds at her in the parking lot behind MedStar,
said LAPD Detective Mike Coffey of the North Hollywood Division.
</P>
<P>
   She ran inside, but he chased after her, firing one round just
feet away from other workers, Coffey said.
</P>
<P>
   He momentarily pointed a handgun at a worker but Cortez quickly
diverted his attention, Selner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She saved one of the girl's lives,'' the podiatrist said. ``He
had a gun pointed in one of the other girl's face. She hollered for
her co-workers to get out of the way, and to protect the other
girls as she ran outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Cortez ran across Laurel Canyon Boulevard, with her boyfriend
following and shooting off more rounds, Coffey said. A co-worker
said Cortez tripped and fell on the curb, where her boyfriend shot
her three times before quickly killing himself in front of a row of
businesses on Laurel Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   Cortez was transported to Providence Holy Cross Medical Center,
where she was pronounced dead, Coffey said.
</P>
<P>
   The man was pronounced dead at the scene, with the gun found
next to him.
</P>
<P>
   MedStar closed for the day, only taking emergency cases,
employees said.
</P>
<P>
   Cortez worked for seven years at the podiatry office, where she
managed the back office. At night, she worked a second job,
stocking shelves in a grocery store to build a better life for her
three children, Selner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the sweetest, loving person ... There isn't a harder
working person. She's the best. You just don't find people like
this,'' Selner said.
</P>
<P>
   Cortez and her boyfriend would argue in the company parking lot
and he would sit waiting for her for hours at a time in the lobby,
friends and co-workers said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, within recent weeks, she called their relationship off,
said Dennis Colonello, a chiropractor at MedStar.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was trying to find a way to get away from him,'' Colonello
said. ``She didn't know what to do. She was afraid to incite him
... I think what provoked him was her telling him that it was over
in the last two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, she went to the Police Department, but did not file a
restraining order out of fear, her co-workers said.
</P>
<P>
   After the attack Tuesday, teary-eyed co-workers watched
investigators at work, expressing guilt about how they could have
done more.
</P>
<P>
   But other workers said Cortez turned down offers of help.
</P>
<P>
   The employees offered to have somebody protect her, Selner said.
But she insisted that she could handle the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing we could do,'' Selner said. ``We felt
frustrated because we didn't know what to do with this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Selner arranged for counselors to talk with employees about the
shooting. The employees have set up a fund for Cortez's three
children.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
