</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES CRUSH RANGERS, 10-2 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ David Cone was sitting in the steamy
third-base dugout in the first inning on Tuesday night, surely
contemplating the importance of his start against the Texas
Rangers. Cone realized that he had to follow up his first victory
in 104 days with another positive effort or all of the doubts and
all of the questions about him would come creeping back.
</P>
<P>
   Then Cone saw the Yankees pummel Doug Davis and he saw several
reasons for instantly feeling comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   There was a leadoff single by Derek Jeter, a run-scoring single
by Paul O'Neill, a bloop single by Jose Canseco that knocked in a
run and a monstrous two-run homer by David Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Cone's anxieties gradually dissipated.
</P>
<P>
   Before Cone had dug in in front of the pitcher's mound, the
Yankees scorched Davis for four runs.
</P>
<P>
   By the third inning, they had seven runs and Cone's comfort
level had grown immeasurably.
</P>
<P>
   Cone wound up pitching five innings, the Yankees wound up
prevailing, 10-2, and Cone was elated to win a second straight
start for the first time since he topped the Baltimore Orioles on
June 26 and July 2, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Cone can salvage something from what was a dreadful season
until two weeks ago. Cone would also be thrilled to become a
footnote in a game like Tuesday night's. The Yankees won with a
relentless attack and they stymied the Rangers for the 10th
straight time, including the 1999 division series. Not only that,
but with Boston losing to Tampa Bay, the Yankees also widened their
division lead to five games.
</P>
<P>
   If Cone had not experienced a 15-start streak without victory
from April to August, he would have been a minor part of recapping
this game after tossing five sound innings in the 93-degree
weather.
</P>
<P>
   But Cone's performances have given the Yankees hope that his
tinkering in Tampa, Fla., has helped resurrect him. Cone has
allowed seven earned runs in his last 17 innings (3.71 earned run
average) and improved his record to 3-10.
</P>
<P>
   With Orlando Hernandez trying to recover from injuries and Denny
Neagle struggling, Cone might manage to slip back into the equation
for the postseason rotation. That option seemed inconceivable
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Cone pitched the way a pitcher should work with a large lead by
throwing strikes and not trying to be too perfect. The Rangers had
a runner on second in the first, but Cone struck out Rafael
Palmeiro with a 3-2 curveball.
</P>
<P>
   Cone gave up two runs and four hits in the fifth, but he got
Gabe Kapler to fly out to end the inning. Since Cone had thrown 92
pitches, seemed like he was tiring and already felt good about his
effort, Torre summoned Dwight Gooden for the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Cone gave up seven hits, struck out three and walked one.
</P>
<P>
   When O'Neill was asked about Davis before the game, he admitted,
``I don't know anything about him.'' Apparently, the Yankees knew
enough about the rookie left-hander. Davis barely got a chance to
take a breath in the first. Jeter lined a single to left, Luis Sojo
blooped a single to right center and O'Neill ended an 0-for-15
slump by belting a single to left for a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I'm going, I'm due for a 15 for 30 soon,'' said
O'Neill, who went 3 for 5.
</P>
<P>
   After Bernie Williams rapped into a double play, Davis induced
Canseco to hit a 200-foot pop-up that dropped in front of right
fielder Ricky Ledee to put the Yankees ahead, 2-0. It was a
devastating bloop because it enabled Justice to come to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Before Justice batted, a fan near the crowd microphone outside
the press box shouted, ``You stink, Justice.''
</P>
<P>
   A few seconds after the fan finished his rant, Justice hammered
Davis's 1-0 slider, dropped his bat and watched the ball soar about
10 rows deep into the right-field upper deck.
</P>
<P>
   The 443-foot homer was the longest ever hit to right field here,
and it gave Justice 10 homers in 38 games as a Yankee.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred, the fan yelled, ``You still stink, Justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brosius, who turned 34 on Tuesday, stroked a two-run homer
in the third, Jorge Posada doubled in a run in the fourth, O'Neill
blasted a two-run homer in the fifth and the Yankees were cruising
with a 10-run cushion.
</P>
<P>
   So was Cone. His season had been on life support for at least a
month, but Cone has won twice in six days to revive himself and
make the rest of the season intriguing instead of painful.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
