<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3013 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEM-CAROLINE-KENNEDY-     08-16 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-CAROLINE-KENNEDY-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
 
(Subs 6th graf starting: But not surprisingly, etc. to correct
Caroline Kennedy's age at time of her father's death) 
uA CHILD OF CAMELOT LINKS HER FATHER'S DREAM TO AL GORE  
(ART ADV: Photos CVN 1, 14 and 15 is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Invoking the themes that her father offered here
40 years ago this summer, Caroline Kennedy Schlossberg stepped out
of her guarded private life and onto the stage of the Democratic
convention on Tuesday night to lend the family name to Al Gore's
presidential campaign and to thank the nation for its support
through what was another difficult year for the Kennedys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thank all Americans for making me and John, and all of our
family, a part of your families _ for reaching out and sustaining
us through the good times, and the difficult ones, and for helping
us dream my father's dream,'' Schlossberg said. ``As I look across
this hall, and across this country, I know that my father's spirit
lives on, and I thank all of you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, it is our turn to prove that the New Frontier was not a
place in time, but a timeless call,'' she said, referring to the
signature phrase of her father's abbreviated years in office.
</P>
<P>
   It was a poignant moment for Schlossberg. Her simple agreement
to speak here on Tuesday night _ she has all but disappeared from
public view since her father's assassination in November of 1963
-was a reminder that she is now the only surviving member of the
Kennedy family that occupied the White House from 1961 through
1963. Schlossberg's brother, John Jr., who enjoyed public attention
almost as much as his sister shunned it, died in an airplane
accident last year.
</P>
<P>
   Schlossberg was one of four members of the extended Kennedy
family who spoke here on Tuesday, and her official task was to
introduce ``Uncle Teddy,'' Sen. Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts.
She took the stage to the sound of the theme from ``Camelot,'' the
1960s musical that became identified with her father's
administration.
</P>
<P>
   But not surprisingly, her remarks were filled with mentions of
her father, who died when she was 5. They were a reminder of the
continuing sway that the Kennedy family in general, and John F.
Kennedy in particular, wields among Democrats, at a convention
where many of the delegates were not even born when Kennedy served
as president.
</P>
<P>
   She recalled her upbringing, saying, ``I was lucky enough to
grow up in a world where adults taught by example. They dreamed
impossible dreams, yet they fought hard each day to make those
dreams come true.''And she reminded the audience that her father,
40 years ago, wanted, ``not only to make better the world that
surrounds us but to dream of something more.
</P>
<P>
   Schlossberg delivered the speech in a city that is for the
Kennedys both a place of triumph, where Kennedy was nominated to
run for president, and of tragedy, because Robert F. Kennedy was
assassinated just blocks from where Schlossberg spoke on Tuesday
night, while campaigning for president in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, she alluded to the losses that her family has suffered
through violence, saying, ``If we believe that we have seen enough
gun violence in our land and in our lifetimes - that guns should no
longer take the lives of those we love - then it is up to us. If we
believe in these things, then it is up to us to elect Al Gore and
Joe Lieberman.''
</P>
<P>
   Schlossberg was poised, but seemed _ not surprisingly _ a bit
nervous as she looked over a conventional hall crammed to the
ceiling with delegates, onlookers, and reporters. She then
proceeded to quote her father, suggesting that what Kennedy said in
Los Angeles when he was nominated for president was as relevant
today as it was then: ``Our call is to the young at heart,
regardless of age,'' he said. ``The whole world looks to see what
we will do. We cannot fail their trust; we cannot fail to try.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
