A3015 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-BLUEJAYS-L     08-16 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-BLUEJAYS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GANT DOES IT ALL IN ANGELS' WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The Angels got Ron Gant for what he could do with his
bat, not his glove. But Tuesday night they got both in an 8-4
victory over the Toronto Blue Jays in front of 26,706 at SkyDome.
</P>
<P>
   Gant, acquired from the Phillies in a trade for pitcher Kent
Bottenfield on July 30, homered and drove in three runs. But the
play that might have been the difference was his Jerry Rice
impersonation in the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had taken a 3-0 lead on home runs by Garret Anderson
and Mo Vaughn, but were in danger of giving up that lead after the
Blue Jays loaded the bases on two singles and a walk with one out
against starter Matt Wise.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Batista, who began the night tied for second in the
American League with 34 homers, worked the count full before
hitting a liner deep to left field. Gant sprinted back and made a
wide receiver-like over-the-shoulder catch while crashing into the
chain-link fence, knocking him down like he was hit by Ronnie Lott.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Martinez tagged and scored on the sacrifice fly, but the
catch saved at least one and possibly two more runs. It also put
the brakes on what could have been a big inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had a chance to play defense yet since I've been
here,'' said Gant, who has started two games in left field and five
as the designated hitter. ``I told myself I wasn't going to let
anything stop me from catching it. I want to prove I can play
defense too, that if they need somebody out there, they've got a
solid guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not afraid of running into the wall you can make
that catch. I thought I was going to go through it. Thank God it
gives.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels got out of the inning with a 3-1 lead and increased
it to 6-1 with a three-run fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen Ronny play a long time,'' Angels manager Mike
Scioscia said. ``This guy is an aggressive outfielder. He's
certainly not afraid of diving for a ball or running into a wall.
That catch, you talk about a momentum switch. That was
tremendous.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels offense had a hand in it too, knocking starter David
Wells (17-5) out after only 4 innings. Darin Erstad and Anderson
each had three hits, and Troy Glaus and Vaughn had two apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Wise (1-1) got the win after going 6 innings and allowing three
runs and five hits. It was the first victory of his major-league
career, and he couldn't thank Gant enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was unbelievable,'' Wise said. ``When the ball left his
bat, at first I thought it was a grand slam.''
</P>
<P>
   Two innings earlier, Wise was involved in a staredown with Blue
Jays slugger Carlos Delgado. The Angels were using a dramatic
infield shift on Delgado with the third baseman Glaus closer to
second base, so Delgado squared to bunt. Wise's pitch was slightly
inside, but Delgado couldn't get out of the way and it hit him high
on the thigh.
</P>
<P>
   Delgado took a few steps toward the mound and had a few choice
words for Wise, who stared right back.
</P>
<P>
   When the Angels came to bat in the top of the third, the first
pitch from Wells hit Benji Gil on the right kneecap. Home plate
umpire Andrew Fletcher warned both teams any further incidents
would result in ejections, but Scioscia wasn't happy and went out
to argue with Fletcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The umpires) are saying (Wells) threw at Benji, but in no way
was Wise trying to hit Delgado,'' Scioscia said. ``It was obvious
to us and obvious to the umpires (Wells hit Gil intentionally). I
don't know what (the Blue Jays') reaction would stem from. If (the
umpires) thought (Wells) was throwing at a guy, they should have
thrown him out of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   After the incident, Scioscia made a trip to the mound to keep
Wise from losing his focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out there to calm him down and he calmed me down,''
Scioscia said. ``I said, `Let's get back on the beam,' and he said,
`The heck with that, let's go.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously I'm not trying to hit him,'' Wise said. ``That would
be ridiculous that early in the game. I'm glad it didn't escalate
from there. I just wanted to throw a good ballgame and win the
ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   Delgado said after the game he overreacted.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Delgado's) a lot bigger (6-foot-3, 225 pounds) than I thought
he was,'' Wise said. ``I'm not going to pick a fight with someone
that big. But I was a little fired up. When he came out I didn't
want to show I was intimidated.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
