<HEADER>
A3029 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-LIEBERMAN-ARRIVES-LAD     08-16 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-ARRIVES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN CLARIFIES STAND ON RACE, ENGAGES HOLLYWOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HARRISON SHEPPARD 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Taking time off from preparing for his ``only in
America'' moment accepting the Democratic vice presidential
nomination Tuesday night, Sen. Joseph Lieberman spent much of
Tuesday healing rifts with African-American leaders and meeting
with politicians and Hollywood executives.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut senator who harshly criticized the movie and
music industry for its overemphasis on sex and violence, offering
``Silver Sewer'' awards to the worst, spent the evening at a
Democratic party held at a producer's home in Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, he addressed 300 members of the
Congressional Black Caucus and won a reluctant pledge of support
from U.S. Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Los Angeles, by supporting
affirmative action -- but not quotas -- and leading the group in
singing ``Happy Birthday'' to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to say a word to you particularly about the rapport
that I have felt over my life with the African-American community
in my commitment to civil rights,'' said Lieberman, an Orthodox
Jew.
</P>
<P>
   ``It honestly begins with my religion because I believe as a
matter of faith, not just that God created all of us, ... I believe
that every human being is created in God's image.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman will have to reach deep for his powers of persuasion
when he takes the podium Wednesday night at Staples Center to
deliver his acceptance speech. Political analysts said he has to
walk a fine line between boosting himself and potentially
overshadowing Gore, as many analysts said Bill and Hillary Clinton
did in their speeches Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``His speech is probably huge in the sense of figuring out who
this guy is on a national basis -- beyond the snippets we've read
in the last couple of days as people have scurried to try to
understand this senator from a small state on the East Coast,''
said Richard Lichtenstein, a Los Angeles Democratic political
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think most people knew who Lieberman was, nor did
anyone expect he would ever be selected.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, his wife, Hadassah, and daughter Hana, 12, swept into
Los Angeles at 1 a.m. Tuesday, touching down at Burbank Airport,
where he was met by members of the state Legislature and the media.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first to greet him was Assembly Speaker Bob
Hertzberg, D-Van Nuys, widely known as the ``Hugger,'' who embraced
him with a big hug.
</P>
<P>
   Hadassah Lieberman got a taste of just how much press coverage
of her husband will escalate in the next few months as he seeks
national office.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she was speaking to us, she said, `You know, I'm amazed
all these people are out here at 1 in the morning. When they told
us there were throngs of press out there we were kind of stunned,'
'' recalled state Sen. Richard Alarcon, D-Van Nuys.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said she had to quickly throw on some makeup.''
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, Lieberman met with the Congressional Black
Caucus for the start of a series of constituent group meetings that
will continue Wednesday with meetings with Latino, gay and lesbian,
and Asian and Pacific caucuses, then greet Vice President Al Gore
upon his arrival at Burbank Airport, where the two will hold a
rally and press conference.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting with African-American leaders posed the biggest
challenge, since Waters and others had expressed concern over
Lieberman's stances on affirmative action and school vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman reminded the group that in 1963, he marched on
Washington with Martin Luther King Jr. and went into Mississippi to
register African-American voters.
</P>
<P>
   He said he opposes what he regards as racial quotas and sought
to explain his support for Proposition 209, the 1996 California
proposition that banned state-funded affirmative action programs.
</P>
<P>
   He said a reporter had read the proposition to him and that he
responded favorably, saying it sounded like a basic human rights
policy. He said he never campaigned for it even though he was asked
to do so and made crucial votes in the Senate in favor of
affirmative action in 1995 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has said enough, he has done enough and he has demonstrated
his willingness to deal with issues of concern to the black
community,'' Waters said. ``I feel comfortable in campaigning for
him. I was not going to do it and lose credibility if these issues
had not been clarified.''
</P>
<P>
   Before holing up in his hotel to rehearse his speech in the
afternoon, Lieberman went to Staples Center and mounted the podium.
He grinned broadly, spread his arms and told a group of
photographers, ``An only-in-America moment.''
</P>
<P>
   In the evening, he mingled with Hollywood insiders and
politicians in a reception hosted by The New Democrat Network at
the Beverly Hills home of producer David Salzman and his wife,
Sonia. NDN is described by reception organizers as a ``4-year-old
political venture capital fund for the Democratic Party (which)
makes strategic investments in a new generation of elected
officials at all levels of government.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hollywood community has had a somewhat schizophrenic
reaction to Lieberman. While the entertainment industry tends to
favor Democrats, many bristle at the senator's criticisms of the
industry's moral decay.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the industry, however, do support his views.
</P>
<P>
   Entertainer Steve Allen, for example, who has spoken out
frequently against violence in films and television and is now
working on a book titled ``Trash TV, Raunch Radio,'' agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm overjoyed about Mr. Gore's choice,'' Allen said. ``Because
Joe Lieberman, whom I've met on two earlier occasions in
Washington, strikes me as that rarity in politics, which both
parties have traditionally honored in the abstract: the true man of
principal. And a man to whom ethical and moral questions are of the
most fundamental importance. That is simply not the case with every
politician.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
