<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3031 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w BC-GORE-DELEGATES-KAN &LR;      08-16 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-DELEGATES-KAN </SLUG>
  
 CLINTON'S CLIMACTIC SPEECH PUTS PRESSURE ON gORE'S UPCOMING EVENT  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE and SCOTT CANON  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Look forward, not back. Be enthusiastic. Be
candid. Distinguish yourself. Above all, be yourself.
</P>
<P>
   One day after President Clinton's much-heralded farewell address
to the Democratic National Convention, the advice was flowing for
his would-be successor, Al Gore, who gives his own prime-time
speech Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The topic on the minds of many delegates and analysts around the
country: How can Gore top the rousing speech Clinton delivered to a
packed house on Monday night that had one Missourian calling the
president the ``Great Communicator?''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he can't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore is not a Bill Clintonlike speaker,'' said Edward
Rendell, general chairman of the Democratic National Committee.
``Neither is George Bush. Neither is Bill Bradley. There isn't any.
You maybe have to go back to Jack Kennedy to find someone who can
reach people the way Bill Clinton does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore just has to show the American people how smart he is,
how much he cares and what a decent person he is.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is easier said than done. Monday night Clinton
probably increased the pressure on Gore for the nominee's own
speech _ traditionally the final and most closely watched event of
any convention.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem for Gore is that Democrats already have
experienced something of a climactic moment with Clinton's speech.
Trying to generate the same kind of over-the-top enthusiasm
Thursday could be tough, especially for a speaker who doesn't
normally inspire that type of passion, said Charles Jones, a
longtime political scientist at the University of
Wisconsin-Madison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night it was Clinton, Clinton, Clinton, Clinton,'' Jones
said. ``I kept wondering how I would feel if I was Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's speech also provides Gore an opportunity,
Democrats said. By focusing on the last eight years _ and by
dealing with the Monica Lewinsky scandal in a talk last week _
Clinton has freed Gore to focus on the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to say what he'll do next,'' said Joe Carmichael,
chairman of the Missouri Democratic Party. `` &UR; `You ain't seen
nothing yet' needs to be one of the themes.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the trick for Gore will be to forget about Clinton,
forget about the expectations and worry only about himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is alike,'' said House Minority Leader Richard
Gephardt, a Missouri Democrat. ``Al Gore does not have to get over
any bar. Al Gore has to talk about what's in his heart and mind and
what he wants to do. I think he'll do that well.''
</P>
<P>
   One way to do that would be to focus on an issue or two that
Gore can call his own, delegates said. For example, many voters
already associate Gore with the environment, so that could be a
topic for Gore. He also could focus on campaign reform, an issue
Gore already has elevated to the top of his agenda and one that
never gained much of a toehold during Clinton's years in office.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to mention issues that distinguish himself,'' said
Thad Beyle, a political scientist at the University of North
Carolina at Chapel Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Many hoped Gore would be Gore, speaking to the convention and
the country without caution and with the enthusiasm that lets his
personality break through any political veneer.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Nelson Thompson, a leader of Kansas City's Freedom
Inc., recalled listening to Gore talk to black delegates four years
ago at the Democratic convention in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president charmed his audience with a cadence
resembling the classic oratory of a black preacher, he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got down, and he did it with power and meaning that
connects with people,'' Thompson said. ``It was real, and he was
himself. I just want to see him be himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Womack, who ran for the Missouri House in 1998, had the
same wish.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's himself, the experience shows through, and that's
what people will appreciate,'' said Womack of Kansas City, North.
</P>
<P>
   Gore needs to talk about the ways in which he will continue the
nation's economic prosperity, Womack said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want him to say he will continue what the team is doing,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   For state Sen. Ed Quick of Liberty, Mo., the key will be candor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to open up and let people know who Al Gore is. There
needs to be confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Rendell said voters needed to be realistic. He was confident
Gore would hit a round-tripper Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``And an Al Gore home run is different than a Bill Clinton home
run,'' Rendell said. ``But a home run is still a home run if it
goes 330 feet as opposed to 460 feet. It still counts as one run.''
</P>
</TEXT>
