<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWIMMERS, NOT SUITS, WILL MAKE SPLASH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Don Talbot already has an idea of what's in store
for him after the Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll either hang me, or ... '' Talbot said, his voice
trailing off in a sigh of grim possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 67, despite a long and golden career, Talbot has
been handed a job at which he can't win: head coach of Australia's
Olympic swim team.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine working for Bobby Knight, George Steinbrenner and Don
Corleone, all wrapped in one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever you do will not be good enough,'' Talbot confessed.
</P>
<P>
   In Australia, there is no NFL season or World Series to distract
the couch-ensconced masses. Rugby and tennis still draw headlines,
but swimming is king.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian Olympic Trials in May were shown on live,
prime-time television. Cable TV carried every morning preliminary
heat. The radio coverage of the nightly finals was broadcast
coast-to-coast.
</P>
<P>
   To Talbot, therefore, the assignment in Sydney is simple _ win
more medals, preferably gold, than any other country. And
especially win more than those bloody Yanks.
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, Talbot and his assorted mates have been curious
observers of these eight days of U.S. Olympic Swimming Trials. And
they have been impressed, Talbot said Tuesday night, but not
surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a little soft where I thought they might be soft, and
they're strong where I thought they'd be strong,'' Talbot assessed.
``I've had no surprises here.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago in this same Indiana University Natatorium pool,
the U.S. team was chosen, somehow, without breaking a single
American record. Amid modest forecasts, that same team went to
Atlanta and won 26 medals, including 13 gold.
</P>
<P>
   At these trials, meanwhile, with only Wednesday's two finals
remaining, nine American records have fallen, as well as 21 Olympic
trials records.
</P>
<P>
   Is it the new bodysuits?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're a red herring,'' Talbot said.
</P>
<P>
   The controversial reversal by USA Swimming to allow the new
form-fitting suits at the trials has produced, as predicted, a
parade of bodysuits in the IU pool. But as the meet has progressed,
and the faster swimmers _ surprise _ seem to still be beating the
slower ones, more and more swimmers have shown up at the starting
blocks without the new suits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting more info on the suits every day,'' said
longtime Australian coach Forbes Carlile. ``And from what we've
seen, the suits are not helping.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're seeing is a great marketing bonanza going on. The
companies are selling a lot of swimsuits.''
</P>
<P>
   The American coaches gathered here seem to be saying the same
thing. Swimmers Jenny Thompson, Dara Torres, Tom Malchow and Gary
Hall Jr. were the class of the field coming into the trials, and
nothing about their races here have suggested otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you could put a bloody G-string on them and they'd go
just as fast,'' Talbot noted.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian journalists covering the U.S. trials say that a
similar percentage of Olympic hopefuls wore the bodysuits at the
Aussie trials. But in the end, Ian Thorpe, Grant Hackett, Michael
Klim and Susie O'Neill still all swam like future gold medal
winners.
</P>
<P>
   Talbot has called his team ``Australia's greatest ever,'' better
even than the 1956 Olympic team that out-medaled the United States
for the only time. Carlile, whose coaching career spans 55 years,
dubbed it the ``third golden era of Australian swimming.''
</P>
<P>
   The Australians also figure to have a partisan nightly crowd of
17,000 to cheer them on in Sydney. Talbot believes that will be
worth much more than any bodysuits.
</P>
<P>
   For seven days, he has seen the Yanks break records and stitch
together an intriguing blend of veterans and teen-agers. Lenny
Krayzelburg still appears to be the class of the Olympic field in
the backstroke. Malchow, in the 200 fly, has the look of a gold
medal winner. And Hall, as he proved again Tuesday night in the
men's 50-meter freestyle, is going to give Klim and Russian
Alexander Popov a challenge in the sprints.
</P>
<P>
   ``The women, well, that's a different story,'' Carlile said.
</P>
<P>
   Australia's O'Neill should win both the 200 free and 200
butterfly. But the home team lacks the female depth that the
Americans will bring, especially now that Thompson and Torres _
ages 27 and 33, respectively _ have emerged as possible
show-stealers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a feel in the air back home,'' Talbot said Tuesday
night. ``I think it's going to be a very fast racing meet.''
</P>
<P>
   And if it is, Talbot repeated, it won't be the suits. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 0117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
