<DOCNO> NYT20000816.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3033 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-WATER-BREAK-KAN &LR;      08-16 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATER-BREAK-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KC'S WATER CRISIS PASSES, BUT RAISES OTHER CONCERNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 MATT CAMPBELL  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Kansas Citians once again can trust the
quality of the water coming out of their taps.
</P>
<P>
   But the city's emergency management director said that Monday's
water-main break has taught him to question the reliability of City
Hall's phone system in a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   City water officials on Tuesday also expressed concerns that
until they knew why the pipe failed, they could not assess the
potential for further ruptures.
</P>
<P>
   The break, believed to be the worst in the city's history,
closed businesses and affected 150,000 people. It prompted
officials to announce a boil order for drinking water, but the
order was lifted Tuesday morning after tests showed the water was
safe.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, authorities reviewed the response to the emergency
and said the volume of calls coming into City Hall overwhelmed the
telephone system the day of the break.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the governor's office was trying to reach the
city's emergency management director to coordinate precautions for
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't call out, and they couldn't call in,'' said the
director, Mike Karl. ``You just kept hitting redial, redial, redial
and eventually you got out....That should not happen.''
</P>
<P>
   State officials eventually paged a firefighter who walked down
to the basement emergency headquarters at City Hall to relay the
message.
</P>
<P>
   Karl said his report to City Manager Bob Collins would highlight
the communication problem. He said he had no specific remedies in
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It opens in my mind the possibility we could have a true,
citywide emergency and may not be able to coordinate as effectively
as we would like,'' Karl said.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he did not see anything fundamentally wrong with
the city's new telephone system. The city would look into the
situation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the phone system in any emergency is something that we
are going to have to anticipate is going to be difficult to rely
on,'' Collins said. He added that most city officials relied on
cell phones Monday to communicate.
</P>
<P>
   Karl said people should be able to telephone someone at City
Hall in emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the water crisis was more inconvenient than
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Water Services Department and the Missouri
Department of Natural Resources lifted a precautionary order to
boil tap water before drinking at 8:30 a.m. Tuesday, nearly a full
day after the pipeline break in the West Bottoms.
</P>
<P>
   Government offices and most businesses downtown were open and
back to normal on Tuesday. Some were evacuated on Monday over fears
that fire-protection systems, such as sprinklers, would not work.
</P>
<P>
   Tests on water samples collected all over the affected area
showed beneficial traces of chlorine and bacteria counts within
normal limits.
</P>
<P>
   That means anyone who drank tap water Monday need not fear
health consequences, said water department spokeswoman Susan Hall.
There were no reported ill effects.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Health Department advised that water outlets be
flushed by opening the cold-water taps and letting the water run
until it became cold.
</P>
<P>
   Ice cubes in automatic icemakers should be thrown out and the
system cleaned and sanitized. The first batch of ice produced after
cleaning also should be thrown away.
</P>
<P>
   The precautions are necessary for an area from the Missouri
River south to 63rd Street and from the state line east to Eastern
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   In the West Bottoms, water crews on Tuesday discovered three
breaks in separate 16-foot sections of the 48-inch water main near
25th and Allen streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``One section completely burst and two sections have serious
corrosion and were damaged as a result of the break,'' said Ron
Goold, water department assistant director for distribution and
collection.
</P>
<P>
   The 50-year-old concrete pipes were expected to last longer.
Replacement pipes were being trucked in Tuesday from Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   A pipe expert from Florida was brought in to investigate the
cause of the breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Answering that question will tell us the potential for
something similar to happen (elsewhere),'' said Goold.
</P>
<P>
   Beemer Construction Co. is ready to do the repair work in the
West Bottoms. Goold said the whole operation probably would take
another day or two and could cost $20,000 to $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Water customers should not be affected by the construction work,
because water is being pumped around the isolated break area.
</P>
<P>
   The potential for water contamination came not from the site of
the pipe break itself, but from the possibility of backflow at any
water outlet where the pressure dropped to zero, said Goold.
</P>
<P>
   A dishwasher in a restaurant, a hose in a back yard or any
pipeline connected to a potable water tap could have sucked up
contaminants in the absence of forward water pressure, Goold said.
</P>
<P>
   As a precaution, the city collected twice as many water samples
as usual on Monday and tested them overnight at its laboratory,
which is a backup lab for the state Department of Natural
Resources. The results were announced as soon as possible, said
Connie Hull, lab director.
</P>
<P>
   But by 8:30 a.m. thousands of people had already faced the task
of brushing teeth and preparing breakfast without tap water. And
some day-care centers had already decided to remain closed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot wash the children up after bathrooming and changing
diapers, and it's just not safe,'' said a recording at the Willow
Woods center on Westport Road.
</P>
<P>
   Other day-care centers in the affected area, however, did not
lose water and stayed open.
</P>
<P>
   ``We brought in bottled water to be on the safe side,'' said
Vicki Krapf, director of Global Montessori Academy on West 47th
Street.
</P>
<P>
   At the five hospitals that lost water, staff members Tuesday
turned on faucets to make sure pipes were flushed out before
patients and employees were allowed to use tap water.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, patients and employees continued to use bottled
water and to wash hands with waterless cleansers. The hospitals
also brought in coolers of ice while their ice machines were being
sanitized.
</P>
<P>
   Unsure when water would be restored, some of the affected
hospitals canceled surgeries and clinics on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The hospitals, Truman Medical Center, Trinity Lutheran Hospital,
St. Luke's Hospital, Children's Mercy Hospital and Veterans
Hospital, expected to be back in full operation today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
