r s BC-OLY-SWIMMING-NOTES-TE     08-16 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIMMING-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAINE TEEN OUT OF A SMALL POOL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ To put Ian Crocker's Olympic Swimming Trials in
perspective, you don't have to go far.
</P>
<P>
   When you live in Maine and dream of swimming in the Olympics,
you can't.
</P>
<P>
   There are no Olympic-size, 50-meter pools in Maine. To get
training time in a big pool, Crocker and his Portland Porpoise Swim
Club have to slip across the border each summer into New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't swim in a 50-meter pool, when you finally get in,
you notice there's no wall and your arms get a little tired,''
Crocker said, after swimming to victory in the men's 100-meter
butterfly last night.
</P>
<P>
   The problem doesn't seem to be hurting him. Crocker swam the 100
butterfly in 52.78 seconds and broke the trials record he had set
Monday in the preliminaries. He missed Texas ex Neil Walker's
American record by .02 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Crocker will follow in Walker's wake and attend Texas _ once he
returns from the Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   His calm reaction last night belied the fact that Crocker is
only 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I guess, I'm just kind of blown away,'' he said.
``I'm feeling so many different emotions. It's been such a long
road.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Crocker on the Olympic team is another UT swimmer,
junior-to-be Tommy Hannan, a native of Baltimore. Hannan took the
field out at a world record pace and ended up second in 52.81. Both
Hannan and Crocker swam under Matt Biondi's 1988 meet record of
53.09 that Crocker broke in the prelims.
</P>
<P>
   With Bryan Jones finishing fourth and Matt Ulrickson fifth, it
meant that four of the first five finishers in the race had
University of Texas ties. RECORDS SUBMERGED
</P>
<P>
   The record tally after last night's four finals shows nine
American records in these Olympic trials and 21 meet records.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Hall Jr. was the latest, shaving .05 off the American
record previously held by Tom Jager in the 50-meter freestyle.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 1,300 swimmers competing in the trials, 19
national age-group records have also fallen. One of them is the
national 11-12 age-group record in the women's 100-meter butterfly,
where 12-year-old Dana Vollmer of Granbury, Texas, swam 1:02.49 in
her preliminary heat. BREAK FOR VAN DYKEN
</P>
<P>
   With Jenny Thompson dropping out of the women's 50-meter
freestyle to concentrate on her two other individual events, the
door has been left open for veteran Amy Van Dyken.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't look as if she can catch Dara Torres, who led all
qualifiers to tonight's finals in 24.93 seconds. But Van Dyken's
25.11 was the second fastest of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Van Dyken, 27, was feeling her age after she was told by someone
``that I've been swimming longer than she's been alive _ that's
kind of sad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
