<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHERS-PROTEST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHER MARCH FOR PAY, GORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DONNA HUFFAKER and LISA MASCARO 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Thousands of teachers and their supporters took to
the streets Tuesday, marching peacefully downtown -- mostly for a
pay raise, but also in a show of support for Al Gore and in
opposition to a school voucher initiative on the Nov. 7 state
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The marchers, estimated at more than 2,000, drew support from
striking commercial actors and joined hotel workers seeking union
representation at the New Otani Hotel along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a perfect time for us to be out here when the Democractic
convention is here and we're in the public eye,'' said Ronda Kalan,
who teaches special education students at Lokrantz Elementary
School in Reseda.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that the Cold War is over, this is our big opportunity to
focus on children,'' said Tom Squires, a fifth-grade teacher at
Harding Street Elementary School in Sylmar.
</P>
<P>
   Squires, the father of two recent college graduates, said they
make more money waiting tables than they would as starting teachers
-- ``and they don't have homework.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying they want a pay raise on par with the 10 percent hikes
being won by educators across the county -- and pointing to the Los
School District's costly Belmont scandal and pay raises for some
administrators -- the marchers cheered local labor and political
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't it common sense and good, sound educational policy to
pay teachers what they're worth?'' asked Sandra Feldman, president
of the American Federation of Teachers. Higher pay also will solve
the current teacher shortage, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers, vowing to strike if district leaders do not meet their
requests, walked for several miles on downtown streets and chanted,
``We've got the power'' and ``No contract, no teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   The teachers, who have been without a contract since the end of
June, are asking for a 21 percent pay increase, which includes a 6
percent retroactive increase.
</P>
<P>
   Teacher Caryn Morisette said she hoped Democrats attending the
party's nominating convention at Staples Center heard the
educators' concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping for their support more than anything else. Our
beef is with the (school) district.''
</P>
<P>
   Police officers with helmets and clubs were posted along the
route, and some teachers said they were surprised by the police
presence. One teacher said a police officer told him authorities
were concerned about protesters disrupting the teachers' march.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was afraid at times,'' said Ana Valencica, a third-grade
teacher at City Terrace Elementary. ``We did have security, we did
have protection, (but) on the other hand it was a little
intimidating. ... I think it was uncalled for.''
</P>
<P>
   !dlim!!end! &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
