<HEADER>
A3039 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-WILLIAMS-     08-16 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-WILLIAMS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERIK WILLIAMS IS BACK AT WORK, SAYS HIS HEART `IS IN THE GAME'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Five true sentences about Erik Williams'
end of a four-week holdout with the Dallas Cowboys:
</P>
<P>
   1) The 31-year-old offensive tackle merely watched practice
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   2) Physically, he feels better after missing a full month of
training camp than he has felt in any of his nine previous NFL
preseasons.
</P>
<P>
   3) Williams' return will help Emmitt Smith and the Cowboys'
running game the most.
</P>
<P>
   4) A possible $5,000-a-day fine has been waived in Williams'
case.
</P>
<P>
   5) Cowboys' coaches and players needed to hear one thing in
particular from the four-time Pro Bowl selection: ``My heart is
still in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The organization knew all along that it needed Williams. But it
knew that it needed Williams to come back on his own terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't ``talk'' somebody into playing this game,'' coach
Dave Campo said. ``I've talked to Erik. His heart is in it.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if this sends a wrong message to the rest of the
players, Campo shook his head and said, ``Everyone is handled on an
individual case.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Campo is going with Williams' story of
contemplating retirement, not holding out for more money. He has a
contract that pays him $1.9 million each of the next two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he has ``just got my head right'' and that his
``only issue'' was over playing football. It had nothing to do with
seeking a trade, Jacksonville or otherwise, and nothing to do with
the wear and tear that 124 NFL games has on an offensive lineman's
body.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how much money you put in front of guy, if he
doesn't love the game anymore ... it's not worth it,'' Williams
said Tuesday. ``I have enough money. I was just at a crossroads.
The last nine years, I've been struggling ... more mentally than
anything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a tough decision, and I struggled with it. But I'm
back now and ready to move on. I decided my heart is still in the
game. I'm not ready to let it go yet.''
</P>
<P>
   For Williams, who made his fourth Pro Bowl last season, a
decision to quit football with two years left on his contract would
have cost him $1.6 million in bonus money-to-be-returned.
</P>
<P>
   By his own admission, Williams, who turns 32 next month, is
still two weeks away from being in ``football shape.'' He is fully
expected to be in the Cowboys' starting lineup at right tackle for
the Sept. 3 season opener against Philaelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, Erik is going to make us a better team,'' said
quarterback Troy Aikman, who was asked if he really believes that
Williams will be ready for Sept. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope so,'' Aikman replied. ``Physically, I think he'll be
ready to play, although I've been saying all camp that we're doing
a lot of different stuff this year with our protection (schemes).
Still, I think he'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Owner Jerry Jones said: ``Erik lost something (with the
holdout). But with hard work, I think he can be where we want him
to be. He never was going to be going twice-a-day in camp because
of his off-season (elbow) surgery. That wouldn't have been smart at
this juncture of his career ... but he would've been better off
having been around it since some of this is new.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams will receive his first limited work against St. Louis
in the Cowboys' preseason finale Aug. 24. Until then, Solomon Page
will continue at right tackle, where he has done a solid job in a
caretaker's role.
</P>
<P>
   When Williams is ready, Page will move to right guard, which
isn't the position that Page prefers. He is a natural right tackle.
Meanwhile, projected backup Jorge Diaz has started at right guard
all preseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more concerned about the 2 1/2 weeks that Solomon Page has
to work at both positions than I am with Erik Williams coming in
and being ready to play,'' Campo said.
</P>
<P>
   Center Mark Stepnoski believes that Page will benefit in
carrying out his new assignment when Williams returns because the
switch involves the same right side of the line.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys offensive line coach Hudson Houck said, ``I think Erik's
return can give us a tremendous lift right now. He brings to our
team some toughness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to have Erik back,'' Page said. ``Our main objective
is to get to a championship (game) and win the Super Bowl, so
whatever it takes to do that ... cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said Tuesday that he most missed the players. As long
as he gets ready, the feeling will be mutual. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 0125EDT &QL; 
