<HEADER>
A3040 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     08-16 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF SOUND MIND AND PLAYGROUND
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I hold in my hand the last will and testament of
Joseph P. DiMaggio, the Yankee Clipper.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, no bombshells therein.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio does appoint ``my dear friend and attorney, Morris
Engelberg, Esq., as Personal Representative of my estate'' in
connection with, among other things, ``the licensing and/or use of
any name ... .''
</P>
<P>
   So if you want to sell Joltin' Joe coffee mugs, you have to deal
with Mo.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody can be granted legal power of playground. If San
Francisco wants to dedicate North Beach Playground in honor of
native-son Joe, there's nothing in Joe's will or the law to prevent
it.
</P>
<P>
   And by the way, whose city is this _ Mo's or Willie's?
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Brown, with a phone call, could have swell Joe DiMaggio
Playground signs posted by tomorrow. How dead does Joe have to get
before his boyhood hometown honors him?
</P>
<P>
   The will, incidentally, cost me $33. That's a bargain because,
even though it's Xerox copies of the 33 pages, I now have 34
different notarized Joseph P. DiMaggio autographs. Maybe I can sell
'em.
</P>
<P>
   LOVED THE president's long walk through the backstage labyrinth
to the stage for Monday night's speech. Where was his dressing
room? Pasadena?
</P>
<P>
   The low camera angle was dramatic, and slimming. But I was
apprehensive, worrying that Clinton might take a wrong turn and
stride purposefully to the valet-parking kiosk.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton finally emerged from the concrete maze, it was a
little bit of a letdown that he wasn't confronted by snarling
lions, or a shadow-boxing Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   How will Gore top that entrance? He'll have to cartwheel and
handspring onto the stage. Or be borne to the podium on a sedan
chair carried by four Laker Girls.
</P>
<P>
   BAR HOPPING, seeking liquid fortification while he watched the
speech, Cuffs Corbett had no luck at the Gold Coast or at
O'Reilly's, where you could watch whatever you wanted as long as it
was Monday Night Football.
</P>
<P>
   That's where the real battle is brewing _ on MNF. Right now the
major polls show new TV analyst Dennis Miller running a distant
third behind the ghost of Howard Cosell and the memory of Dandy Don
Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone tunes in to MNF, even for worthless practice games, to
see how the new guy Miller is doing.
</P>
<P>
   And by now it's clear that Gore blew it by not naming Dennis
Miller as his running mate. Tell me who you'd rather watch give a
campaign speech _ Dennis Miller or Joe Lieberman?
</P>
<P>
   Miller could sit behind Gore when he speaks, whisper wise-ass
asides that would get Al laughing, cut through the wooden
seriousness that causes him to lag in the polls behind
loosey-goosey Dub.
</P>
<P>
   BESIDES, it's not like the VP has any real power.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood liberals fear Lieberman because he is an outspoken
critic of movie and record violence and sex. So they'd do better
with Bush and Cheney?
</P>
<P>
   Veeps are harmless. Gore's two-fisted agenda when he took office
was fixing the environment and cutting government waste and fat.
But he must have spent too much time in Buddhist temples. Plenty of
incense, and he did inhale.
</P>
<P>
   What major reforming did Dan Quayle, or any other VP, do in
terms of changing society?
</P>
<P>
   THE SECRET of the amazing gardens at Cayuga Playground was
unveiled in Monday's column. City gardener Demi Braceros has
sculpted and planted an acre of treasures.
</P>
<P>
   But how to get there? By BART, get off at the Balboa Park
station, walk downhill on Geneva three blocks, turn right on Cayuga
and go about a half mile, street ends, there you are. From 280,
take the Geneva/Ocean turnoff, go southeast on Geneva, right on
Cayuga.
</P>
<P>
   On maps it's listed as a playground, wedged between 280 and BART
tracks on North and Alemany Boulevard on South.
</P>
<P>
   TIMBERRRR. The city will be murdering between 18 and 27 big
trees in Pioneer Park, at the base of Coit Tower, at the end of the
month.
</P>
<P>
   They're paving paradise, putting up a tourist patio, critics
say.
</P>
<P>
   But the local group that put the project together says the new
flagstone terrace on the South side (opposite side of the Tower
from the parking lot) will replace an unplantable dirt hill, and
new stairways will prevent visitors from scrambling over rocks and
through brush.
</P>
<P>
   And the project will make the park more ADA-compliant.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's always good to see concerned citizens putting heat
on the chainsaw man. Just to keep him honest.
</P>
<P>
   WONDER IF his friends call him Sparky:
</P>
<P>
   In a Chronicle story about widespread vandalism of glass, this
quote:
</P>
<P>
   ``They use rocks, sandpaper, even the sharp edges of spark
plugs,'' said Allan Champion... .
</P>
<P>
   FLOWER THEFTS from local parks and gardens?
</P>
<P>
   It's a widespread organized crime now. But a guy named Earl says
that in college he would impress his dates with large bouquets he
happened to find lying around at a local cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   A handy tip from Earl: ``You have to make sure you remove the
card.''
</P>
<P>
   IT'S 49ERS vs. Seattle Seahawks Saturday, and Buchanan Grill
owner Bill Jamison is conflicted.
</P>
<P>
   Big 49er fan, but his boyhood pal and part owner of the Grill is
Mike Holmgren, Seattle coach.
</P>
<P>
   Whom to root for, and what to serve? When Holmgren coached the
Green Bay Packers and they played the 49ers, Jamison would put out
bratwurst and cheese.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you give a Seahawks' fan?'' he asks. ``Starbucks?''
</P>
<P>
   Nah. Light a match and set off the sprinklers, Bill, give 'em a
little rain.
</P>
</TEXT>
