<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3041 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-DEMOCRATS-ANALYSIS-SF     08-16 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRATS-ANALYSIS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DEMOCRATS CEDE CHARM CONTEST TO GOV. BUSH  &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Democrats are painfully aware that the man they
will nominate as their standard-bearer tonight lacks the political
charm of his Republican opponent.
</P>
<P>
   For all his efforts to appear informal, down to earth, sincere
and spontaneous, Vice President Al Gore still has trouble simply
being likable.
</P>
<P>
   So while Republicans used their party's convention in
Philadelphia two weeks ago to promote integrity, decency and
leadership as paramount presidential qualities, Democrats in Los
Angeles are obsessed with matters of policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't just want compassion,'' roared Rep. Patrick
Kennedy, D-R.I., mocking the mantra of the GOP nominee, Texas Gov.
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want access to safe schools, a Medicare prescription drug
benefit, a real patient's bill of rights, civil rights protections
and an environment that they can pass on to their children,''
Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Even as both parties hew toward the political center and exhibit
their talent for putting on events that refuse to stray from the
script, a clear-cut difference is emerging from their conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans believe if the 2000 election is fought over
character, they have the advantage, while Democrats believe if it
is fought over issues, they have the edge.
</P>
<P>
   At the risk of inducing yawns from the prime-time audience,
speaker after speaker in Los Angeles is taking on prescription
drugs for seniors, a patient's bill of rights, HMO reform, campaign
finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   A list of talking points distributed to delegates last night
referred to health care, the environment, targeted tax cuts, Social
Security, economic growth and education.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joe Biden of Delaware distributed copies of a 64-page paper
titled: ``A Choice for the Generations: Presidential Election
2000,'' which details the stark differences between the parties on
``judicial imperialism'' and a national missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win, we have got to draw distinctions,'' said Biden, who
was himself a candidate for president in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton had likability and the issues going for him,'' Biden
said. ``George Bush is a good guy. Right now, Bush is likable in
the minds of the public. ... I'm confident we can win, but it's no
slam dunk. It's going to be hard.''
</P>
<P>
   A poll published in Tuesday's Los Angeles Times provided fresh
evidence that while voters agree with Gore on the issues, they like
Bush better as a leader.
</P>
<P>
   The nationwide survey of 1,227 registered voters found that 6 in
10 respondents said they had a favorable impression of Bush. Even
among Democrats, 28 percent said they viewed Bush favorably. By
contrast, 54 percent of the respondents had a positive impression
of Gore, but just 17 percent of Republicans viewed him favorably.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why Gov. Bush is in the lead, because people sense he
is a leader,'' said Massachusetts Gov. Paul Cellucci, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said he believes that voters will be drawn to Bush's
position on tax cuts, school vouchers and a strong national
defense. But, he acknowledges: ``I think we're on stronger ground
on the character issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The same poll found that voters strongly back Gore's positions
on the issues. By a 5-to-1 ratio, voters said the federal budget
surplus should be used primarily to pay down the national debt and
stabilize Social Security and Medicare, as Gore advocates, rather
than for tax cuts as Bush has proposed.
</P>
<P>
   Other polls show that the public generally supports Gore's
positions on gun control, legal abortions, stronger environmental
protections and campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issues are on our side,'' said Sen. Dianne Feinstein,
D-California.
</P>
<P>
   Each party's effort to woo swing voters in the political center
may make it difficult to distinguish between their positions on
many issues. Both party platforms profess to strengthen education,
preserve Social Security and promote the e-economy, though their
approaches are different. On trade and national defense, each
candidate's position is far more similar than different.
</P>
<P>
   Still, stark differences remain on matters ranging from tax cuts
and gun control to abortion and gay rights. Feinstein, like many
other Democrats, has expressed confidence that Gore can overtake
Bush in the fall when issues will become more prominent and the two
candidates will meet in a series of at least three debates.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you need to know about this election,'' Kennedy said, ``is
that we want people to know what the issues are. And the
Republicans don't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
