<HEADER>
A3042 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-OLY-SWIM-TRIALS-LADN     08-16 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIM-TRIALS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALL, ERWIN PARTNERS IN SPEED   AT TRIALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Gary Hall Jr. has borne the weight of exorbitant
expectations since birth, the inevitable consequence of being the
namesake of a three-time Olympian. Anthony Ervin has faced the
weight of people's presumptions since, well, Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The two sprint teammates arrived at the starting blocks for the
50-meter freestyle at the U.S. Olympic Swimming Trials from
decidedly different planes Tuesday but wound up in the same place:
Under the existing American record set 10 years ago by Tom Jager.
Hall got to the wall first, touching in 21.76 to Ervin's 21.80.
Jager clocked a 21.81 in a special sprint event in March of 1990.
</P>
<P>
   No one has gone faster than Hall or Ervin in a competitive
eight-man race (Russia's Alexander Popov set the world record of
21.64 in June in a one-man time trial). Their dazzling two-man show
came as no great shock, considering there's arguably no more
conducive training atmosphere for sprinters than the one created
this summer by former USC standout Mike Bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, 25, and Ervin, a sophomore-to-be at Cal, are two of 10
world-caliber freestyle sprint specialists who work out together
daily in Phoenix. Cal head coach Nort Thornton, who recruited Ervin
out of Hart High, said the setup is tailor-made for Valencia's
human vapor trail, and Ervin had to agree.
</P>
<P>
   Left to his own, Ervin admitted, ``I set up standards a lot
lower for myself than what I'm capable of doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ervin's rise has been so meteoric, it's a small wonder he can
measure his ceiling at all. He was a two-time CIF champion in 1999
but came to Cal clueless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think before my first college year, I was kind of
overwhelmed by the whole thing,'' Ervin said. ``I had no idea what
was going on, really.''
</P>
<P>
   He proved himself a quick study. The 19-year-old won the 50 and
100 freestyles at the NCAA Championships in March as a freshman,
something not even former world-record-holder Matt Biondi was able
to do during his celebrated career at Cal in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The meet was conducted in a short course meters pool and Ervin's
winning time in the 50 established a new short course world record
and established himself as someone to watch here.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, a 1996 Olympian, has the thicker dossier but his swim was
in some ways more startling than Ervin's. Hall had been swimming
largely below Popov's and the rest of the swimming world's radar
since being diagnosed with diabetes in March of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   To battle the disease and at the same time beat Jager's mark was
an accomplishment so special, Hall struggled to make sense of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a record that up until not too long ago was almost
unattainable,'' said Hall, whose father, Gary Sr., won three
Olympic swimming medals between 1968 and 1976. ``It's something
I've been gunning for for a long time. To pass it is really
exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Ervin unwittingly had caused a commotion on Sunday when he
earned an Olympic berth as a member of the 400-meter freestyle
relay. Ervin's father, Jack, is three-fourths African-American and
so Ervin became the first swimmer of African-American descent to
grace a U.S. Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   It was of more significance to others than to Ervin, who
explained, ``It's not that I'm trying to understate the fact I'm
African-American. Hopefully I can be a role model for just about
anybody, whether they're black or white or brown.''
</P>
<P>
   IN OTHER FINALS: Ian Crocker set an Olympic Trials record in the
100 butterfly (52.78); defending Olympic champion Brooke Bennett
won the 800 freestyle (8:23.92); and Amanda Adkins edged Trojan
Swim Club's Lindsay Benko in the 200 backstroke (2:12.97 to
2:13.19). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
