<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3043 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-LIEBERMAN-AFFIRMATIVE     08-16 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-AFFIRMATIVE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE RUNNING MATE MOVES TO REASSURE BLACK CAUCUS ON
AFFIRMATIVE  ACTION
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW and CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In an early test of his skills on the national
political stage, Sen. Joe Lieberman moved Tuesday to extinguish
smoldering doubts about his commitment to affirmative action and
public education.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of a prime time address that will serve to introduce
the two-term Connecticut Senator to the rest of the country,
Lieberman assured black delegates that despite misgivings earlier
in his career, he would not stray from the party's orthodoxy on
either matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel as if I'm with family,'' Lieberman said as he faced the
delicate task of explaining his centrist positions to the decidedly
liberal members of the Democrat's African American caucus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't let the press or our opponents divide us,'' he said
before receiving a warm embrace from Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Calif.,
who had raised questions about Lieberman only a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight Lieberman faces the broader challenge of explaining to a
national audience why a man who was Stamford High School prom king
in 1960 and the Democratic Party's voice of conscience during the
Monica Lewinsky scandal four decades, later deserves the
opportunity to be a heartbeat away from the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Since his selection last week, Lieberman has displayed abundant
loyalty to Gore and enormous enthusiasm to be running for a job
often belittled by politicians for being of little consequence.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing at the convention podium for a brief morning
rehearsal, Lieberman smiled and spread his arms as if to embrace
his new campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``An only-in-America moment,'' he said to a group of
photographers.
</P>
<P>
   In a preview of his remarks, Lieberman said he would not
hesitate to ``respectfully'' point out disagreements with Gov.
George W. Bush, but that he would shun the traditional running mate
role of attack dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to Al about this, and we're very intent on talking
about progress, not partisanship,'' Lieberman said in an interview
with the New York Times. ``This is not going to be a campaign of
personal attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman is the first Jew to be named to either party's
national ticket. Has presence has helped cut into Bush's double
digit lead in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Rainbow Coalition leader Jesse Jackson applauded the selection
during an address to the convention last night, saying that by
choosing Lieberman ``Al Gore has brought the sons and daughters of
slaves and slave masters together with the sons and daughters of
Holocaust survivors.''
</P>
<P>
   A short time later, Lieberman entered the convention hall, where
he was greeted by a rush of supporters, news cameras, and a roaring
ovation from the delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Los Angeles, created the first crack in
the Democrat's show of unity Monday by suggesting that she was not
ready to support the Democratic ticket until she learned more about
Lieberman's record on affirmative action and school vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, who as a college student in 1963 spent a summer in
Mississippi working to register blacks to vote, strode into
Tuesday's meeting with African American delegates escorted by black
cabinet members Alexis Herman and Rodney Slater.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want Joe! We want Joe!'' chanted the crowd at the Westin
Bonaventure hotel which is hosting most of the California
delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Smiling, Lieberman responded: ``You've got him!''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said that ``there's been a misunderstanding'' on his
views on affirmative action. He explained that his initial support
for California's proposition 209 in 1996 was based upon a
preliminary reading over the phone by a reporter, and not a
thorough exploration of its implications. He said he later refused
to sign latter endorsing the measure, which banned preferences in
state hiring, contracting, and school admissions based on race, and
was ultimately approved by voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have supported affirmative action, I do support affirmative
action and I will support affirmative action,` he said, to
applause.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman acknowledged that he differed from Gore on whether
public money should be used to help students attend private
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a fact I have supported some demonstration programs for
vouchers,'' he said. ``But let me make real clear that the focus of
my attention and the main support that I've always given has been
to the public schools, because that's where most of our children
will be educated.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman then announced that it was Waters' 62nd birthday and
led the group in singing ``Happy Birthday.''
</P>
<P>
   Water later told reporters: ``I feel a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   `I'll campaign with him,'' Water said. ``I feel comfortable in
campaigning for him. I was not going to do it and lose credibility
if these issues had not been clarified.''
</P>
<P>
   Another group of influential Democrats may not be so quick to
embrace Lieberman. Executives from the entertainment industry have
expressed concerns about Lieberman's strong views regarding
violence on television and in movies, and his call for the industry
to either police itself or face some form of government action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I love the movies. I love music,`` he said on ABC's
``This Week.'' ``But there is still too much violence, too much
sex, too much incivility in entertainment, which makes it very
difficult for parents, who are working so hard to give their kids
values and discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle staff writer Lynda Gledhill contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 0135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
