r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-MARLINS-L     08-16 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-MARLINS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS FADING FAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Ismael Valdes pitched a mop-up ninth inning in which the
Dodgers were getting pounded by the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   It's not quite the role the Dodgers envisioned for Valdes when
they re-acquired him last month as the veteran pitcher needed for
the playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, getting trashed by the Marlins for the second
straight night, this time 7-3 Tuesday at Pro Player Stadium, brings
the Dodgers a little bit closer to a meaningless last few weeks of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely playing like (garbage). We're absolutely
playing like (garbage)'' second baseman Mark Grudzielanek said.
``We're not getting many bounces, we're not giving ourselves a
chance to win a game. We're too good for that to happen. We should
be in most of the games and we should have a chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making mistakes, making bad pitches. Everything that's
going wrong is going wrong at once. ... We're not hitting, not
pitching, no defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The floundering Dodgers (60-58) have lost eight of 10, with six
of the losses to Milwaukee, Chicago and the Marlins. They are now 6
1/2 games behind San Francisco in the National League West and have
as many wins as the young, energetic Marlins (60-59).
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have tried team meetings, have talked in small
circles in the clubhouse, and yet no remedy has been found. Not
even the clearing of the air with manager Davey Johnson being told
he'd be back for the remainder of the season has eased the cloud of
a long, often distraction-ridden season.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the get-go this year, things were just not right,''
Grudzielanek said. ``No question we do have a playoff team here,
and there's still time left. But there's no question the door is
shutting, and we need to do something about it. Are we going to
fall on our faces like we have the last week or are we going to
bounce back and make a run at it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody bought a ticket for a roller coaster ride.
It's like we're waiting for something to happen and it's not
happening.''
</P>
<P>
   The frustration certainly has bubbled over for all-star left
fielder Gary Sheffield, who was ejected for the first time this
year _ for laying his bat down after an eighth-inning strikeout to
show home plate umpire Dan Iassogna that he thought the ball was
outside.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield's seen fewer and fewer good pitches to hit because
nobody in the lineup is producing. The Dodgers have scored more
than three runs only six times in the last 17 games. And Sheffield
is 2 for 20 on the five-game road trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's three weeks of frustration building up,'' said Sheffield,
who didn't know he was ejected until he was told by crew chief Mark
Hirschbeck. ``I haven't seen a ball down the middle of the plate in
three weeks. I know the strike zone in and out. When I swing with
two strikes I make a weak out, and when I take it I strike out.''
</P>
<P>
   During a time in which the Dodgers are supposed to be whuppin'
up on the financially-challenged clubs that often occupy the
cellars, they are getting beaten up themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Marlins right-hander Ryan Dempster, a fine young pitcher with a
strong fastball and nasty slider, allowed three hits in eight
innings. The only run Dempster gave up came on F.P. Santangelo's
pinch hit homer to lead off the eighth. Except for Chad Kreuter's
two-run double in the ninth, the score would have indicated how
dismal this loss was.
</P>
<P>
   In the first two games of the series, which included a start by
Kevin Brown, the Dodgers have been outscored 18-5. The Dodgers have
also made four errors, allowed five unearned runs and played the
type of fundamentally inept baseball that's followed them the last
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't play good enough to win,'' Johnson said. ``We
didn't swing the bats well. We didn't set the table, didn't hit. If
you don't do that, you better catch it and you better pitch.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
