<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3049 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-PROTESTS-DNC-LADN     08-16 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROTESTS-DNC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABOUT 75 ARRESTED IN LATEST WAVE OF DNC PROTESTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY ANDERSON, DOMINIC BERBEO, JASON KANDEL and JORDAN SMITH 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Police clamped down on unruly demonstrations in
downtown Los Angeles on Tuesday, a day after the LAPD response to a
melee at a protest concert outside Staples Center sparked
controversy and threats of court action.
</P>
<P>
   About 75 people were arrested as riot-gear-clad police rushed
from one protest scene to another in conjunction with the
Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   The protests were by-and-large peaceful, mainly centering on
families, with groups of teachers, county employees and others
demonstrating for gay rights and more government help for families,
women and children.
</P>
<P>
   But police quickly responded to a handful of incidents:
</P>
<P>
   -- Forty-five anti-fur protesters, clad all in black with
bandannas covering their faces, were arrested on suspicion of
conspiracy to commit vandalism about 2:30p.m., several found with
firecrackers and other items police termed as weapons.
</P>
<P>
   -- Later Tuesday, about 30 bicyclists were arrested out of a
group of several hundred who rode through city streets supporting
more bike lanes and promoting the environment.
</P>
<P>
   -- Police toyed with a black-clad protest group called the Black
Block, surrounding the group several times in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   -- According to the Metropolitan Transportation Authority, some
subway runs were delayed because of protesters standing on the
tracks at above-ground stations.
</P>
<P>
   -- Police closed an intersection around 8:30 p.m. after a crowd
of 75 headed to Parker Center to demand the release of protesters
who were arrested earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Civil libertarians were critical of the afternoon arrests and
the police actions and threatened to go back to federal court to
restrain Los Angeles Police Department officers. But the day after
the melee, police were swarming to meet any potential problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a huge show of police force, and arrests today were
questionable,'' said Marlene Furth, observer for the National
Lawyers Guild. ``But other than that, there was generally
restraint.''
</P>
<P>
   She said officers were hiding their badge numbers and names,
against LAPD policy, ``but the fact that so many people have video
recorders is definitely a deterrent to the police. They know
they're being watched.''
</P>
<P>
   In the incident on Olive Street, police and witnesses said the
protesters pounded on the doors of Edward Borovay Furs, chanted
death threats to workers inside and destroyed a sign.
</P>
<P>
   But Sally Roeker, an office worker who witnessed the arrests,
said the group ``didn't seem to be doing anything wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of officers and cars poured into the area and police
detained the protesters.
</P>
<P>
   According to LAPD spokesman Cmdr. David Kalish, many of the
protesters were carrying aerosol cans converted to be ``mini-flame
throwers,'' containers with fuses, fireworks and flares altered to
be weapons, flammable liquids and sling shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not sure I would characterize this group as protesters,''
he said, but he declined to comment on how he would characterize
them.
</P>
<P>
   Kalish said police learned that the group, which one officer
called ``anarchist,'' planned to march to McDonald's and commit
vandalism.
</P>
<P>
   They were stopped after allegedly destroying a sign on Olive.
</P>
<P>
   Police slowly cataloged all the protesters' possessions,
photographed them and led them aboard three waiting buses.
</P>
<P>
   There were 15 juveniles and 30 adults arrested. There were no
injuries reported and only minimal damage, police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what happens when you stand up for what you believe
in,'' one protester yelled from the bus, trying to flash a peace
sign while cuffed. ``We were doing nothing wrong but walking down
the sidewalk.''
</P>
<P>
   Geoff Kerns, 17, was among those arrested. The Calabasas teen
said he's a spokesman for the Animal Defense League. Wearing a
shirt that read Vegan Militia, Kerns said, ``We are peaceful
demonstrators. We are protesting the use of animals for fur
coats.''
</P>
<P>
   In the evening, about 200 bicyclists streamed through downtown
on a Critical Mass bike ride, to show there is an alternative to
cars even in congested downtown L.A.
</P>
<P>
   The cyclists rode for about 45 minutes with a police escort of
about 80 officers on bicycles and dozens more in police cars.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said when the riders went under a freeway overpass,
officers cut them off and that motorcycles sideswiped riders and
officers on foot hit cyclists with batons.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were trapping people in alleys and under freeways, all
the dark places,'' said a Los Angeles woman who only gave her first
name as Lauren.
</P>
<P>
   Kit Reilly of Santa Cruz, a veteran Critical Mass rider, said he
never had any trouble on any ride before.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got off their bikes holding their clubs and told us to
get off our bikes,'' Reilly said. ``But they never gave us any
reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Police would not immediately comment on whether the riders were
being arrested and, if so, what they were being arrested for. Those
detained had their bikes impounded.
</P>
<P>
   A bike rider yelled that she was being arrested for ``reckless
driving.''
</P>
<P>
   Other protests went smoothly, all under the watchful eye of
hundreds of police officers.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,000 protesters in the ``queers and allies march''
traveled from Pershing Square to the Federal Building and back
without incident.
</P>
<P>
   They chanted, ``What do we want? Gay rights.''
</P>
<P>
   They lay in the intersection of Temple Avenue and Los Angeles
Street and outlined their figures in a ``die-in'' representing
death resulting from brutality against homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to express our demands for gay rights,'' said Ray
Fernandez, a participant. ``They have no reason to use violence. We
are peaceful.''
</P>
<P>
   Other activists stayed in and around Pershing Square, the center
of activity.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Campbell, a 36-year-old member of the Peace and Freedom
Party, rode from San Francisco on his BMW motorcycle to join the
protests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Protests are good for the media to let people know what the
issues are and who the players are,'' he said. ``But after the
convention's over, you've got to hook up, get in one of these
organizations and get into the long-term day-to-day issues.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
