<HEADLINE>
PERCIVAL NOT READY YET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Closer Troy Percival played catch Tuesday afternoon
but isn't ready to return to the active roster. Percival's inflamed
right elbow will keep him out at least two more weeks and probably
longer even though he's eligible to come off the disabled list on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Percival injured the elbow by compensating for his surgically
repaired shoulder. He said his shoulder went ``dead'' for a while
earlier this season, a normal reaction for somebody coming off
surgery. However, as a result, Percival dropped down from his
normal three-quarters arm angle to nearly sidearm, putting extra
strain on the elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Percival had elbow surgery in 1993 but said the current injury
``isn't the same area exactly. It's not the ligament. The elbow's
sound. The nerve flared up.''
</P>
<P>
   The inflamed nerve causes a sharp pain in Percival's elbow.
Although his velocity hasn't been affected, he has trouble locating
his pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Mike Scioscia met privately with Percival for nearly a
half-hour Tuesday afternoon, but Percival said the meeting was only
``semantics.'' Percival said he sees no reason he can't come back
100 percent. If not this season, then next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing left to fix in there now,'' he said. ``... As
long as I know I'll have time to rest in the offseason, my strength
will be back. I know I will be back where I want to be. There are
days this year I felt like the old me, but not for more than three
or four outings.''
</P>
<P>
   Percival, though, won't give up on returning to the mound this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we are in a race like we are right now ... I'm going to
be back out there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   TOUGH STRETCH: Despite going 3 for 5 on Tuesday, Darin Erstad
has hit only .225 (18 for 80) in his past 18 games, his average
falling from .382 on July 25 to .358.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad is working to get out of the slump, taking extra batting
practice with hitting coach Mickey Hatcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason during the course of a season you lose your
rhythm, your feeling,'' Erstad said. ``All I'm trying to do is get
my rhythm back. For whatever reason, it's not working together. But
I'm trying to get it back as quickly as I can. I just want to get
comfortable and get into a good flow.''
</P>
<P>
   With 184 hits in 119 games, Erstad is on pace for 250 hits,
which would equal the fifth-highest total in a single season in
baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   SHAKY START: Pitcher Brian Cooper gave up six runs and seven
hits in five innings in a start for Triple-A Edmonton on Monday, an
indication he isn't ready to rejoin the team and start Saturday
against the Yankees when the club needs a fifth starter.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' other options within the organization are few.
Relievers Mike Fyhrie and Al Levine were considered candidates, but
Fyhrie is on the DL and Levine will only be activated from the DL
on Saturday and won't be stretched out enough to go more than a few
innings. The club will not consider anyone other than Cooper among
minor leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia said they could ``piecemeal a game together,''
stringing together a series of relievers.
</P>
<P>
   The final option would be to acquire a pitcher off the waiver
wire, and there is growing speculation that will happen if the
Angels can find the right deal.
</P>
<P>
   NOT READY: Pitcher Seth Etherton (tendinitis right shoulder) is
eligible to come off the DL on Sunday, but he won't be ready.
Etherton has not resumed throwing. He's still working with weights
to regain strength. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
