<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3051 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i BC-CHAVEZ-OIL-SFCHRON &LR;      08-16 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAVEZ-OIL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 VENEZUELAN PRESIDENT A NEW LEADER IN OIL POLITICS  &HT;     By ROBERT COLLIER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a new power player on the world stage. He hangs out with
Washington's archenemies, and he causes American motorists to wince
every time they pull up at the gas pump.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez has used his country's oil
wealth as a springboard to notoriety, hobnobbing in the past week
with Saddam Hussein and Moammar Khadafy.
</P>
<P>
   But strangely enough, there's common ground between Chavez's
anti-Americanism and U.S. energy needs. Instead of winding up in
the U.S. doghouse, as might be expected, Chavez has become a tacit
ally.
</P>
<P>
   Since he took office in February 1999, Chavez has rallied the
world's oil powers to cut production and boost the price of crude
oil, causing international prices to triple.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have taken it in the pocketbook, with average gas
prices rising from about $1 per gallon to more than $1.50 in the
same period.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez ended a 10-nation trip Tuesday that included visits to
Iraq and Libya. He drummed up support within the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries _ which Venezuela currently chairs _
to resist pressure from the United States and other oil consumers
to boost production and thus lower prices, which now are near their
highest level since the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   In years past, the American reaction to such a Third World
upstart probably would have been harsh, many analysts say. This
time, however, two disparate factors _ liberal tolerance and
oil-industry pragmatism _ have combined to produce a different
stance.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has barely blinked at Chavez's
campaign, and its criticisms have been mild and infrequent.
</P>
<P>
   When Chavez last week became the first foreign leader to visit
Hussein since the Gulf War, criticizing U.S. sanctions,
Washington's response reflected frustration and ambivalence. State
Department spokesman Richard Boucher called the trip
``inappropriate'' and ``hard to understand.''
</P>
<P>
   But the White House later softened the tone, with a spokesman
saying U.S. officials understand that Chavez has a leadership role
in OPEC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chavez wouldn't have lasted long if we still were in the Cold
War,'' said Terry Karl, director of Stanford University's Center
for Latin American Studies, who is an expert on international oil
policy. ``The U.S. reaction to Chavez has been much more
moderate.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Falcoff, a Latin America analyst at the American Enterprise
Institute, a conservative Washington think tank, said: ``Chavez is
trying to provoke the administration into a very strong response,
very similar to what (Fidel) Castro was trying to do at the same
stage of the game (in the early 1960s).
</P>
<P>
   ``But the administration doesn't want to make the same mistake
as with Castro, causing a complete break. The United States needs
(Chavez's) oil, and he needs our dollars. It's a slap in the face,
but we've simply decided it's not a big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   When the populist firebrand Chavez took office in February 1999,
he overturned not just Venezuela's corrupt political establishment
but also the country's traditional role as a U.S. surrogate in
OPEC.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, Venezuela had acted as spoiler of the 11-nation
cartel, which produces about 40 percent of the world's oil. By
constantly exceeding its production quotas _ ``cheating,'' as
industry insiders say _ Venezuela had helped weaken OPEC and drive
oil prices down from their historic highs during the 1970s oil
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   When Chavez took power, oil prices were at $9 a barrel for
high-grade crude, the lowest price in decades. He quickly ended
Venezuela's cheating and joined with Mexico and Saudi Arabia to
convince fellow oil exporters to limit production growth. The
strategy succeeded beyond expectations, driving the price to $32.
</P>
<P>
   Although Vice President Al Gore has made a big campaign issue of
the current high oil and gas prices, he has not pointed up the role
of foreign oil prices in raising U.S. domestic energy costs. GOP
candidate George W. Bush has also not emphasized the issue.
</P>
<P>
   All three have ties to oil firms _ Gore's family owns stock in
Occidental Petroleum Corp., and Bush and Cheney are former oil
company executives.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign policy experts say the U.S. tolerance for Chavez is
partly prompted by the fact that he has not interfered with U.S.
oil companies' operations in Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite his rhetoric, Chavez has respected all (foreign)
contracts. His position has been cautious,'' said Luis Giusti, whom
Chavez fired as CEO of Petroleos de Venezuela, the state-owned oil
conglomerate, in a dispute over Giusti's support for privatizing
the firm.
</P>
<P>
   Even many U.S. foreign policy hawks take a pragmatic line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main U.S. interest is to get a continued, steady supply of
oil,'' said Robert Pastorino, a professor at San Francisco State
University and the National Security Council director for Latin
America for former president George Bush. ``All Venezuelan
governments, including Chavez, have been good at keeping the spigot
open. The price level is less important than that it continue to
flow.''
</P>
<P>
   Next month, U.S. tolerance will be tested again, as Chavez hosts
a summit meeting of OPEC heads of state. Chavez will use the
summit, OPEC's first since 1975, to rally support for his proposal
to create a price ``band'' for oil. Under the plan, producers would
cut production if the price of a ``basket'' of oil grades falls
below $22 per barrel, and would increase pumping if the price goes
above $28 (the basket's current price).
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want prices to fall below their current levels,''
Chavez said Monday. ``If that happened, it would be a death
sentence for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``OPEC isn't the devil that developed countries try to paint us
as. What we want is a fair price, not a high price.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Chavez gets a surprisingly sympathetic ear in
Washington _ although no one in power will admit it, say Karl and
other experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prices that fluctuate wildly are not a good thing for the
producing countries, but they're also not good for the oil
companies,'' said Karl, explaining that the firms need price
stability to be able to calculate their investments. ``If OPEC can
help deliver stability around $25, that's higher than U.S.
consumers want, but there would be no (government) complaints.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 0139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000816.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 01:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3052 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-DEMOCRATS-CONVENTION-     08-16 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRATS-CONVENTION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENNEDYS EVOKE CAMELOT IN ENDORSING GORE TICKET
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI and LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  LOS ANGELES _ Capping an emotional journey that recalled the
glories of Camelot, Sen. Ted Kennedy issued an impassioned plea
Tuesday night to continue fighting for the ideals of his late
brother's ``New Frontier'' by working to elect of Al Gore and Joe
Lieberman.
<P>
   ``You have it in our power to take America to new heights,''
Kennedy said to the cheers of sign-waving delegates at the
Democratic National Convention in the Staples Center. ``That is our
challenge. That is our new frontier. Cross it we can _ and cross it
we must.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's rousing call to action capped a parade of family
speakers _ including Caroline Kennedy Schlossberg, the only
surviving member of the late president's immediate family, and
Maryland Lieutenant Gov. Kathleen Kennedy Townsend _ all recalling
how, four decades ago, John F. Kennedy was nominated for president
by Democrats in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can make the world new again, if only we try,`' Schlossberg
said. ``That is what my father sought to do 40 years ago in this
city, when he stood before you and declared the opening of the New
Frontier.''
</P>
<P>
   The evening was designed to fire up Democratic progressives for
the coming election battles at a time when the party has taken a
clear turn to the moderate middle. But on the second night of the
convention here, informally dubbed ``liberal night,'' the Rev.
Jesse Jackson, former Sen. Bill Bradley and Tennessee Rep. Harold
Ford were among those who urged Democrats to cleave to their
party's ideals, fight for health care and stand up for the
dispossessed.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals capped a day in which Democratic vice presidential
candidate Joseph Lieberman managed to allay fears of a more
progressive delegation of African American Democrats by pledging to
support affirmative action and public schools.
</P>
<P>
   And, in a carefully scripted rally, President Clinton and Al
Gore appeared side by side in Michigan to commemorate a ``passing
of the torch'' as Gore made his way to the convention center.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, in a surprise move, created an uproar among delegates
when he made a impromptu tour of the convention floor to chants of
``Let's Go Joe.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was the appearance of Schlossberg, the only surviving
family member of the late president, who brought tears to the eyes
of many delegates. Arriving at the podium to the strains of
``Camelot,'' a resounding ovation and a sea of blue ``Caroline''`
signs, Schlossberg's voice occasionally trembled as she urged
Democrats to continue her father's dream.
</P>
<P>
   In a bittersweet moment recalling her late mother, Jacqueline
Kennedy and her brother, John F. Kennedy Jr., Schlossberg said: ``I
thank all Americans for making me, John, and all our family, a part
of your family... for reaching out and sustaining us in the good
times and the difficult ones.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But as I look out across this hall and across this country, I
know that my father's spirit lives on, and I thank all of you,''
Schlossberg said. ``Now it is our turn to prove that the New
Frontier was not a place in time, but a timeless call.''
</P>
<P>
   Schlossberg urged Democrats to fight for ``a president who is
not afraid of complexity, who believes in an open and tolerant
society, and who knows that te world can be made new again,'' she
said. ``And that president is Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the poor and underprivileged, she added, ``We cannot fail
their trust. We cannot fail to try.''
</P>
<P>
   Townsend, daughter of the late Senator Robert F. Kennedy,
likewise recalled her uncle's political legacy and the Democrats'
last meeting in Los Angeles four decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made history by summoning the best of our country,
challenging Americans to serve, and insisting that everyone have a
place in that new frontier,'' she said. ``This year, with renewed
resolve, we'll make history again.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was her uncle, the Massachusetts senator, who roused the
delegates into a near frenzy, asking: ``Will we dare to dream of a
far horizon _ or will we look inward, look backward, lower our
sights and narrow our vision? That is the choice we face in the
election of 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who just months ago engaged in a bitter battle for the
Democratic nomination, issued a gracious endorsement of his former
rival, asking Democrats: ``Are we going back to the politics of
haves and have nots?''
</P>
<P>
   Of Gore, he said to cheers: ``I support him, I endorse him. I'll
work hard for him.'' He called electing Gore and Lieberman ``the
right thing to do for our country.''
</P>
<P>
   The evening delivered Democrats with the red meat that many on
the floor clearly craved. Jackson had the crowd chanting ``Stay out
of the Bushes'' as he pointedly reminded them that the GOP is ``not
just Bush and Cheney, but grizzled old veterans such as Jesse Helms
and Dick Armey and Tom DeLay and Bob Barr and Strom Thurmond.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee Rep. Harold Ford, 30, an up-and-coming party star,
delivered a keynote address designed to showcase Gore and the work
he is committed to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say to all those in my generation and to all Americans who
share in our spirit: If you want a future that belongs to you _ if
you want a future that is for everyone _ then join with us to make
Al Gore and Joe Lieberman the next president and Joe Lieberman as
the next vice president,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the celebrities in the vast convention hall were Jerry
Springer, Tom Arnold, Christopher Reeve and model Christie Brinkley
_ a New York delegate.
</P>
<P>
   Protests outside the convention hall were mainly quiet as
demonstrators and police spent most of the day arguing over the
police's use of force the night before.
</P>
<P>
   The criticism came after officers fired pepper spray, tear gas
and rubber bullets at fleering crowds after 15,000 gathered for a
concert by the group Rage Against the Machine.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles police officials, however, defended their
department's actions, insisting that officers delivered a
``measured, strategic, appropriate response'' to the potentially
volatile action in the streets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 0146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
