<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For WEDNESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, Aug. 16.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEM-LOBBYISTS-NYT _ Democratic lobbyists are carefully hedging
their bets. While they flaunt their connections to Gore and the
Democratic Party in Los Angeles, they were also highly visible in
Philadelphia. Lobbying firms have become much more careful in
recent years to cultivate influence in both parties. By Don Van
Natta Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic ahs been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DEM-VOICES-NYT (Lombard, Ill.) _ The dedicated Democrats in the
convention hall in Los Angeles were not the only people who might
have grown a bit wistful as they listened to President Clinton on
Monday night. In the living rooms of Chicago's western suburbs,
even independent voters said the speech made them a bit nostalgic.
By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-CONGRESS-NYT _ There have been more senators,
representatives and congressional candidates speaking at the
Democratic National Convention than can be found on the floor of
either house most of the time. With the convention half over, 40
present and perhaps future lawmakers have spoken about everything
from campaign finance legislation to the environment to the minimum
wage to health insurance _ tracking the issues Vice President Al
Gore wants to campaign on. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-MEDIA-NYT _ The first night of the Democratic Convention got
more minutes on network television and pulled in more viewers, both
on the networks and on the cable news channels, than did the first
night of the Republican Convention last month. By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-PATRICK-KENNEDY-NYT _ Patrick Kennedy: a profile of the most
prolific fund-raiser in the party. By Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-GORE-DAUGHTER-NYT _ Karenna Gore Schiff is pondering the
biggest speech of her nascent political life _ and her
break-through role in the nation's political history _ as she
prepares to become the first daughter to nominate her father for
president. However daunting the speech-writing process, she has a
keen sense of her purpose. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-DIARY-NYT _ The convention diary column by Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-TV-NOTEBOOK-NYT _ Television critic's notebook on the
convention. By Caryn James.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-MISHAPS (Undated) _ A history of submarine
accidents. By Christopher Drew.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KIPP-EDUC (Undated) _ Successful schools for the poor have long
been written off as desert flowers dependent on charismatic leaders
or particular ideology. But Kipp Academy, a pair of extremely
successful middle schools in poor areas of Harlem and Houston, is
something different. Started by two Ivy League idealists and
honored by groups on both the left and right, Kipp is seen as a
model for replication. And now the owners of The Gap have donated
$15 million to create Kipp clones around the country. The process
is starting with a unprecedented year-long training period for the
principals. By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CEO-TENURE (Undated) _ The evidence seems compelling that chief
executives at America's largest companies don't last as long on the
job as they used to. The stock market is far more volatile than it
used to be, management experts say, and directors punish poor
results swiftly. But what everybody believes about the careers of
chief executives, at least at the nation's largest companies, is
probably wrong. A new study has put a kink in the widely held
conventional wisdom. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic has
been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TIRE-RECALL (Undated) _ How the recall of Firestone tires is
changing defective-tire litigation, luring big-name class-action
firms into a field once dominated by little-known general practice
lawyers. By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   LASKAWAY-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The chairman of Ernst &AMP; Young,
a major accounting firm that has been supportive of the Securities
and Exchange Commission effort to tighten rules on auditor
independence, said Tuesday that the SEC's rule proposal goes too
far and would create too much uncertainty about what activities
were permitted. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   RATINGS-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ They are everywhere, cluttering
the radio dial and the broadcast and cable television channels as
never before: commercials, lots of them, jammed by eager
advertisers into what seems to be every available second of
programming time. So is anyone actually paying attention? By
Bernard Stamler.
</P>
<P>
   EXEC-TURNOVER (Undated) _ The widely publicized ousters of
leaders like Durk I. Jager of Procter &AMP; Gamble, M. Douglas Ivester
of Coca-Cola and Jill E. Barad of Mattel suggest that chief
executives have less staying power than they did just a few years
ago. The reasons seem clear: The stock market is far more volatile
than it used to be, management experts say, and directors punish
poor results swiftly. But a new study concludes that not much has
actually changed at the helm of the nation's biggest companies in
the second half of the 1990s. The median tenure of leaders at 65
large companies was the same at the beginning of 2000 _ six years _
as it had been at the start of 1995. The average term actually rose
one year, to 8.3 years. The results of the study have left
corporate governance experts admittedly puzzled. By David
Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   EEOC-CASTRO (Undated) _ Ida L. Castro, the chairwoman of the
Equal Employment Opportunity Commission.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-NOTES (Undated) _ News and notes on television: a profile of
Richard, the ``Survivor'' attracting the most heat. Bill Carter and
Jim Rutenberg.
</P>
<P>
   LONDON-KINETIC-SCULPTURE (London) _ The British art scene is so
heady with hype, gimmickry and self-promotion these days that it
comes as something of a relief to discover the long lost world of
kinetic art at the Hayward Gallery on the south bank of the Thames.
By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   SALZBURG-MUSIC (Salzburg, Austria) _ Opera at the Salzburg
Festival. By Anthony Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   LONDON-THEATER (London) _ A Critic's Notebook: On London theater
this summer, where midlife resurrections are translating into big
box office hits with widely varied degrees of artistic success. On
the stage, at least, women rule, and not the fantastical, mannered
Mames and Dollys who have traditionally governed musicals. By Ben
Brantley.
</P>
<P>
   WAINEWRIGHT-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Wainwright the Poisoner,''
Andrew Motion's unusual biography of Thomas Griffiths Wainewright,
a minor English painter of the first half of the 19th century who
was convicted of forgery and transported to Australia, where he did
hard labor for seven years. He was an unusual criminal in that he
knew people like Samuel Taylor Coleridge, William Blake and Lord
Byron, and when his term of hard labor was finished he gained
recognition in Tasmania as a portrait painter. Reviewed by Richard
Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Los Angeles) _ Maureen Dowd on Bill and Al and
Hillary and Tipper.
</P>
<P>
   KRUGMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Paul Krugman looks at who was
responsible for the current economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BERKOW-COLUMN (New York) _ Sports of The Times column on the
Mets-Rockies' doubleheader. By Ira Berkow.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-PGA (Louisville, Ky.) _ With the start of the PGA
Championship three days away, Tiger Woods _ always the focus when
he's on the scene _ holds a news conference about his quest for a
third straight victory in a major. By Clifton Brown.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING (Moved in ``d'' category &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-GARDEN (Dateline to kum) _ The Chef's Garden in Ohio, where
amazing herbs and vegetables are grown for the most discriminating
chefs. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   XO-SAUCE-SOLVED (Undated) _ Dining out has its pleasure and its
mysteries. XO sauce is both. I recently developed an infatuation
with it. The flavor was intriguing: salty and sweet, hot and sour.
In it I could see tiny bits of dried shrimp, garlic, chilies and
scallop. There were very thin chopped-up noodles, too, and nearly
microscopic chips and flecks of unknown ingredients. If this was
XO, I had to get to the bottom of it. A critic's notebook by
William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   FLAVORED-ALCOHOL (Undated) _ Restaurants are borrowing a page
out of the Absolut book and infusing their vodkas and other alcohol
with an array of flavors. By Matt Lee and Ted Lee.
</P>
<P>
