<HEADER>
A3063 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-OLY-SWIM-TRIALS-HNS &LR;      08-16 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIM-TRIALS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hall displays old form with 50 freestyle mark
</P>
<P>
   By DANNY ROBBINS
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ From the moment he hits the pool deck, Gary Hall
Jr. sets off sparks.
</P>
<P>
   He wears Apollo Creed-style boxer shorts over his swimsuit. He
flexes his muscles when his name is announced. In the white-bread
world of swimming, he does not compute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten a lot of criticism for what I do,'' he said
Tuesday following another such performance, ``but it's something I
enjoy doing. It's a feeling few people get _ the adrenaline rush of
competing in front of a big crowd. I'm just living in the moment
and enjoying it.''
</P>
<P>
   Once counted out of swimming's elite, Hall's time arrived again
at this year's U.S. Olympic Swimming Trials, punctuated by
Tuesday's American record-breaking effort in the 50-meter
freestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Hall won the event in 21.76 seconds, putting him under the 21.81
recorded by Tom Jager 10 years ago and closer to Alexander Popov's
world record of 21.64. Hall's time is the fastest ever recorded in
a field of eight, according to USA Swimming officials, because
Jager's record occurred in a ``Dash for Cash'' exhibition, and
Popov's mark, set in June, came during time trials.
</P>
<P>
   For Hall, the record has special meaning because it represents
an upbeat end to a rocky two years, including a three-month
suspension for testing positive for marijuana and the realization
in March 1999 that he suffers from diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a saying, `What doesn't kill you makes you
stronger,''' he said. ``So maybe I'm stronger. And maybe because of
that, I broke this record.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall's performance was the highlight of an evening that included
a victory in the men's 100-meter butterfly by 17-year-old Ian
Crocker of Portland, Maine, the eighth teenager to qualify for the
U.S. men's team. Crocker, due to be a freshman at the University of
Texas this year, set a trials record and finished ahead of a future
teammate, UT sophomore Tommy Hannon.
</P>
<P>
   Considering he comes from Maine, a state that does not have a
50-meter pool, Crocker is one of the more unlikely members of the
2000 Olympic team. His club, Portland Porpoise, trains in a series
of 25-meter pools in the Portland area and travels to Dover, N.H.,
to use a 50-meter pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have nice facilities,'' said Sharon Power,
Crocker's coach, ``but obviously, they're not that essential.''
</P>
<P>
   In winning the 50, Hall touched ahead of University of
California sophomore Anthony Ervin, who recorded a 21.80. Former
Texas swimmer Neil Walker was third in 22.12.
</P>
<P>
   Hall and Ervin train together in Phoenix as part of a
multi-national group of swimmers known as ``World Team 2000.''
Coached by ex-Olympian Mike Bottom, the group is unique in that it
is geared for one type of swimmer _ sprinters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're able to push each other,'' Ervin said, ``and that makes
us that much better.''
</P>
<P>
   They are also doing some unconventional things. According to
Bottom, the group is eating protein ``horse bars'' similar to those
fed to Kentucky Derby champion Fusaichi Pegasus.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, runner-up to Walker in the 100 freestyle, said breaking
Jager's American record was something to celebrate because it had
stood for so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a record that, up until not too long ago, was almost
unattainable,'' he said. ``To pass that is really exciting. But now
there's a new fixture that Alex (Popov) has set, and that's next.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall burst into the public consciousness four years ago in
Atlanta, where, at 21, he finished second to Popov in both the 50
and 100. He was one of the marquee names on the 1996 U.S. team, son
of three-time Olympian Gary Hall Sr., and expectations were high.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm resentful about that whole talent thing,'' he said when
asked about the pressure of measuring up. ``People expect me to be
a great swimmer because my father was a great swimmer. I've just
been working hard, just like everybody else who's qualified for the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   With his future clouded by his diabetes _ he controls the
disease with daily insulin injections and glucose monitoring _ Hall
entered this Olympic year as something of a curioisity. But in the
end, he made it back, in position to battle Popov again.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about facing the Russian in Sydney, Hall smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can expect a great race,'' he said, letting the answer end
there.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
