<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-PIRATES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Astros buck trend with close call
</P>
<P>
   By CARLTON THOMPSON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   To watch the late-inning finagling, pitching changes and pinch
hitters, you hardly would have known this was a game between two of
the worst teams in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the Astros' good years, manager Larry Dierker often said
his Pittsburgh Pirates counterpart, Gene Lamont, provided one of
his biggest challenges, and Tuesday was no different.
</P>
<P>
   But when the scribbling on the lineup cards finally was done, it
was Dierker and the Astros who came out on top in a 5-4 victory
before the smallest crowd (30,020) to watch a game at Enron Field.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Lima won for the first time this month, and Octavio Dotel
worked the final 1 innings for his sixth save, tying Billy Wagner
for the team lead. Dotel struck out Jason Kendall on a contested
called third strike to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were close,'' said Dotel, referring to his final two
pitches _ the first of which was called a ball. ``(The umpire)
didn't give me the first one, but I put the next one in the right
spot and got the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kendall is a pretty good hitter. I was trying to stay away
from him. If you leave a pitch inside, you're going to be in
trouble. I didn't care if I (walked) him with two out. I just
didn't want to give in to a good hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Kendall, who started toward first base as if he had drawn a
walk, had words with home plate umpire Jerry Meals and had to be
restrained as players from both teams were leaving the field.
</P>
<P>
   The one-run victory was rare for the Astros, who have won just
seven of their 31 games decided by the slimmest of margins. The
Astros have won three in a row and six of their last 10, and they
are 17-16 since the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to have some fun and finish it off strong,''
Astros left fielder Daryle Ward said. ``We've played better during
the second half. I wish there was a championship for each half of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have to step it up. We don't want to lose 100 games.
To think that could happen is scary. Our attitude has been
different in the second half. We had this attitude earlier in the
season, but we didn't hold on to it. If we would have held on to
it, things might have been better.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we started losing, and we started making excuses about the
ballpark and this and that. Now that we're winning, there are no
excuses. We're just having fun playing baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros need to win 16 of their remaining 42 games to avoid
losing 100 games for the first time in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best sign that things might be turning around for
them is the fact Chris Holt and Lima (a combined 10-26) won in
back-to-back games for the first time this season, although they
received decisions on consecutive nights on seven previous
occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Lima (5-14), who always is looking for an edge, shaved his blond
hair, which he has worn proudly for almost two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that will be a good thing,'' Lima said. ``It was
starting to feel weird. And hot, too. But today I felt handsome and
good-looking.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates lost for the third consecutive game and for the
eighth time in their last 10 games. Wasted in the effort was Brian
Giles' bid for the cycle. He hit a homer in the first, a triple in
the third, and a double in the fifth. His final plate appearance
came in the eighth inning when he was hit by a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Pirates starter Kris Benson (8-10) took the loss, allowing four
runs on six hits and five walks in 6 innings.
</P>
<P>
   After getting pounded from the start in Monday's 14-run loss,
the Pirates appeared ready to turn the tables when they bombed Lima
for two solo homers in the first inning. Leadoff hitter Adrian
Brown and Giles did the honors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lima was dodging bullets the whole time he was out there,''
Dierker said. ``I took him out after six innings, and he probably
could have gone more, but I just thought it was time to make a
change. It was more about the pitches he threw rather than the
number of pitches (102) he threw.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima has allowed a club-record 38 homers _ most in the majors
this season. At his current pace, Lima will allow 51 homers this
season, which would break the major-league record of 50 set by
Minnesota's Bert Blyleven in 1986. The National League record is
46, served up by Philadelphia's Robin Roberts in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bagwell and Ward gave Lima new life in the bottom of the
inning with a pair of solo homers of their own. Bagwell, who has 34
homers, extended his hitting streak to 14 games. Ward's homer was
his second in a span of three at-bats and his 18th of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Lima's fielder's-choice grounder scored Tony Eusebio from third,
breaking the tie in the second inning. But Giles' two-out triple
tied the score at 3 in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Julio Lugo's two-out ground-rule double broke the tie in the
fourth inning, and Lima held the Pirates scoreless in his final
three innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros padded their lead in the eighth on Chris Truby's
sixth home run, a solo shot into the Crawford Boxes. Pat Meares'
solo homer off the railroad tracks in left field gave the Pirates
hope in the ninth, and the visitors had the potential tying run at
second base when the game ended.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
