<SLUG> BC-BKW-COMETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only Comets' title chase unites Swoopes, Cooper
</P>
<P>
   By JOSH GAJEWSKI
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   At halftime of Monday night's game against Sacramento, as the
rest of the Comets made final preparations for the second half,
there was Cynthia Cooper _ out on the floor, sitting on the bench
with a frustrated demeanor and a look of disgust.
</P>
<P>
   For the two-time WNBA Most Valuable Player, it was a sign of the
times. The Comets were winning as usual, but Cooper had contributed
only five points (on 1-of-5 shooting), while teammate Sheryl
Swoopes led the way with 18 to go along with three steals.
</P>
<P>
   It is, after all, Swoopes who has been stealing all the glory as
of late _ being named WNBA Defensive Player of the Year on Tuesday,
with an MVP announcement expected to follow soon. And on Tuesday,
both players openly acknowledged what everyone has known all along
_ that their relationship falls way short of being harmonious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, Cynthia and I might have our differences on the
court,'' Swoopes said in the closing moments of her news
conference. ``But for four years now, I've been very honored to
play with such a great player.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's very nice,'' Cooper said in response. ``People
say that we've had issues and other problems and all these
different things, (but) while we might not go out to dinner, we
have won three championships together. So I think we've shown that
we can be professionals and come out here and play the game _ the
game we both love and both respect.''
</P>
<P>
   But they certainly don't love each other.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper hasn't changed her plan to retire after the season, and
the look on her face at halftime Monday only signified the
bitterness she continues to feel about her diminished role on the
team. This is Swoopes' club now, not Cooper's. And while the two
continue to successfully coexist on the court, their relationship
off it is a bit of a different story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm paid to play basketball,'' Cooper said. ``I'm not paid to
have best friends. I didn't know Sheryl before the WNBA, and Sheryl
didn't know me before the WNBA. So what? Are you guys trying to say
we're supposed to be best friends?''
</P>
<P>
   Said guard Coquese Washington: ``To me, it's obvious that
sometimes when they play, they might not like what's going on out
on the court, but they play to win. They're willing to do whatever
it takes to get a fourth ring, and that attitude permeates
throughout the entire team. You don't always have to like the
person you're working with.''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly seems as though Swoopes and Cooper don't. Never
have, and probably never will.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Van Chancellor doesn't see the matter as having any great
bearing on the season's outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody asks me (about the two), and I don't see it as a
challenge whatsoever because when they have a basketball, they make
plays,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out at Sacramento, I thought about running a play that we'd
been scoring on every time. I was going to switch off because I
thought Sacramento was ready to defend that play, and the first
thing Sheryl said was, `Hey, coach, don't switch off on that play.
We've got to get Cynthia the ball.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's natural to want the basketball. They both want to
win, so when it comes to winning time, they're going to put
everything else aside and do what is necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a column written about everything, every day, about
things we don't necessarily know about, understand, or agree
with,'' she said. ``So I don't understand why it's such a big deal,
especially when we've been successful here in the arena of women's
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``That should be the center focus of any conversation between
Sheryl and myself. It should be, `You know, those two names helped
bring three championships to Houston.' And not anything negative.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
