<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-YANKEES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KAPLER EXTENDS STREAK TO 28 AS RANGERS CONTINUE SKID
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Streak is alive and well. Gabe Kapler
singled in the eighth inning Tuesday night, extending his hitting
streak to 28 games.
</P>
<P>
   As for Kapler's team, it remains dead and buried.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Rangers fell to the New York Yankees, 10-2, at The
Ballpark in Arlington, losing for the ninth time in the past 12
games. They dropped to 54-63, nine games under .500 for the first
time since Sept. 27, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   As it has been all too often lately, Kapler's hit was the lone
bright spot.
</P>
<P>
   He went hitless in his first three at-bats, hitting two routine
fly balls to right field and one to left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel too good at the plate,'' he said. ``For the
first time in a long time, I felt a little nervous. I don't know
why, but I had some nervous energy.''
</P>
<P>
   But when he came up in the eighth, he was able to bounce a
two-hopper up the middle and into center field off Yankees reliever
Dwight Gooden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I slowed it down on the last at-bat and saw the ball a little
better,'' Kapler said.
</P>
<P>
   While the hit sent the remnants of the crowd home happy, the
Rangers were hoping for a little more. Such as improvement from
starting pitcher Doug Davis, one of the youngsters the club is
hoping can develop enough this season to be a part of their plans
for next year.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Davis allowed seven runs on 10 hits in 22/3 innings,
including two home runs. One was a tape-measure shot by David
Justice in the first inning. Justice smashed a Davis slider 443
feet into the upper deck of the home run porch, the longest ball
hit to right in the history of The Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a little tired and started getting the ball up, and they
just crushed it,'' Davis said. ``They make you pay when you get the
ball up.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis has pitched decently as a reliever, going 3-1 with a 4.56
earned-run average. But as a starter, he has been pounded to the
tune of a 1-3 record and 11.69 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at his numbers as a starter and out of the bullpen,
and we've got to find the difference,'' manager Johnny Oates said.
``That's a good lineup, but to be successful in the big leagues
you've got to beat good lineups. He just hasn't got the job done as
a starter.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, 4-4 with an 8.02 ERA, was 8-3 with a 2.84 ERA in 12
starts at Triple-A Oklahoma before joining the Rangers. This was
his first start since Aug. 5, and he said he has struggled since
shuttling between the rotation and bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just need to get into a rhythm,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, he's disappointed he hasn't done better,
not just for this season but for the next.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at it as an opportunity for me to win a job in the
rotation for next year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   None of the trio of young starting pitchers have shown enough to
make the Rangers sign them into their plans for next season.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Glynn has been the best of the trio; he's 3-2 with a 4.70
ERA. But the Rangers have to be concerned about his health. He was
placed on the disabled list Tuesday to give doctors time to find
out the cause of his mysterious fainting spell in the dugout Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Perisho showed flashes of his ability when he struck out
eight Yankees in six innings, but he also gave up six runs. He's
2-5 with a 6.33 ERA and hasn't won since June 17.
</P>
<P>
   And Davis had the bad outing Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Helling and Kenny Rogers are entrenched at the top of the
rotation for next season. If the club signs a free agent or trades
for another pitcher, it still would need to fill the last two
spots.
</P>
<P>
   Either Darren Oliver and Justin Thompson must get healthy, or
Davis, Glynn and/or Perisho must improve.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent results, Oates hasn't given up on the latter.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to have patience,'' he said. ``You're going to have
growing pains. We were supposed to have Darren Oliver, Mark Clark
and Justin Thompson. These guys were thrown into the fray, and here
they are facing the world champions. I think it's good for them.
Hopefully, they'll learn from it and it will make them better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers hope so. Chances are, Kapler won't have a hitting
streak to keep the paying customers happy next season. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
