<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYBODY SAY `TOLD YOU SO,' THEN CONSIDER THE POSITIVE SPIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ The ``told-you-so'' echo became a
tiresome item here Tuesday as the Dallas Cowboys began their final
week of the training camp grind.
</P>
<P>
   Erik Williams, ending his retirement-holdout-vacation-whatever,
said his first hello of the summer to the campus of Midwestern
State University, just as the rest of the team was preparing to
give the place a goodbye kiss-off.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' timing was, well, both perfect and intentional. Yes,
everybody correctly saw it coming a month ago. Everybody knew he
was ducking the heat, ducking dorm life, and ducking Tokyo.
Everybody turned out to be right. All together now. Told you so.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Williams' absence showed a total disregard for the
team concept, and in some ways, displayed a lack of respect for new
head coach Dave Campo, who since January has preached a return to
football-related family values at Valley Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   But before the first whistle of the summer in Wichita Falls, the
veteran offensive tackle with the three Super Bowl rings (only
seven of that group remains), decided to shun whatever leadership
responsibility Campo wanted to give him, and sit it out back home.
</P>
<P>
   Let others bust butts, guts and bones while wilting in the blast
furnace. Williams was above all that. After nine years, you'd
figure something would sink in. Then again, after nine years, you'd
also figure Williams would have learned the snap count. Why expect
miracles?
</P>
<P>
   Surely, there will be a hefty fine imposed by Jerry Jones or
Campo. You'd think, huh? But a fine won't happen, because for
public consumption both Jones and Campo say they believe Williams'
alibi that he was thinking about retirement. (If that's true, both
Jerry and Dave should also volunteer to help O.J. find the real
killer.)
</P>
<P>
   Then, surely his teammates are livid with Williams for taking
the easy way out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will never personally hold it against him,'' said center
Mark Stepnoski, an 11-year vet with a well-known dislike for
everything associated with training camp. ``I'm just glad Erik is
here now.''
</P>
<P>
   But if every vet shared his attitude, training camp would be for
rookies only. ``That's true,'' shrugged Stepnoski, ``but I don't
know what else to say on that. My thinking is if Erik hadn't shown
up, we'd be wishing he had. The only thing I hope is he stayed in
shape. If he did, he'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   And here's where the Williams' saga takes a different spin. A
much more positive spin. Picking up where Stepnoski left off with
that last comment, if Williams did work out regularly while he was
sitting out, then he could well be the team's best player the first
month of the regular season. Seriously.
</P>
<P>
   It's all about having a fresh body and fresh mind, which, of
course, is the ongoing indictment of how long NFL training camps
carry on before the season actually begins.
</P>
<P>
   Hark back to the words of just-retired Daryl Johnston as the
Cowboys were beginning this camp without him:
</P>
<P>
   ``The best physical condition you will be in all season is on
the first day of training camp. The worst physical condition you
will be in all season is on the last day of training camp. You
spend the first month of the regular season trying to get your body
back to where it was when training camp opened.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepnoski couldn't agree more. ``I had a contract holdout one
summer, and another summer I didn't get on the field because I was
rehabbing my knee,'' he said. ``Both of those seasons turned out to
be the best I've ever felt. Physically, Eric is going to be very
refreshed. Mentally, he will have to get himself right, but that
shouldn't be a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The Deion-like message here is that the more training camp a
veteran misses _ valid excuse or not _ the better a season he is
likely to have. How out of whack is that?
</P>
<P>
   There's also no question that having Williams back at right
tackle puts the offensive line at optimum strength. But that's just
for now. In his absence, positive things started to develop as a
youngster, Solomon Page, took over at right tackle and others had
to fill in for Page at right guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only can Solomon handle it at tackle, his future there is
very, very bright based on what we've been seeing,'' line coach
Hudson Houck said.
</P>
<P>
   Message to Erik Williams:
</P>
<P>
   While you were laid out under the air conditioning back home,
your replacement for next season was found.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, a surprise at guard also developed in the form of Kelvin
Garmon, the Baylor and Haltom High product. ``With Erik not here,
we had to shuffle at guard when Solomon moved over,'' Houck said.
``What we found with Garmon pleases us all.''
</P>
<P>
   So while Williams' arrival brought out the ``told-you-so'' army
Tuesday, there were also other stories to tell.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 0303EDT &QL; 
