<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-HOGAN-MAGIC-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOGAN MADE MAJOR RECOVER IN MAGICAL '53 SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAN PILLER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Tiger Woods tees off at the PGA Championship in Louisville,
Ky., Thursday, he will confront not only the best professional
golfers in the world but also the mystical weight of Ben Hogan's
47-year-old feat of winning three major golf championships in a
single season.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1953 no golfer _ a group that includes Arnold Palmer, Jack
Nicklaus, Lee Trevino, Tom Watson, Gary Player, Nick Faldo and Mark
O'Meara _ has been able to advance beyond two majors in a season.
</P>
<P>
   With victories at the U.S. and British Opens in hand, Woods is
positioned to stride alongside longtime Fort Worth resident Hogan,
who died three years ago last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hogan was already known as America's best golfer in 1953,''
says retired broadcaster John Derr, who covered Hogan in 1953.
``But those three majors made him a legend.''
</P>
<P>
   Hogan's 1953 season concluded a remarkable period beginning in
1948 when he won the U.S. Open and PGA tournaments and was the
leading money-winner on the tour. He then lost almost all of the
1949 season when the car he was driving was hit head-on by a bus
near Van Horn in West Texas. He dramatically came back from that
setback in 1950, winning the U.S. Open. He won his first Masters in
1951 and repeated as U.S. Open champ, all while moviegoers were
watching an idealized version of the comeback story in the movie
``Follow the Sun.''
</P>
<P>
   But in 1952, Hogan's star appeared to dim.
</P>
<P>
   He failed to repeat at the Masters and the U.S. Open when he
faded in the last 36 holes. Noticeably poor putting that summer,
plus his 40th birthday in August 1952, generated speculation that
Hogan's comeback was complete. It appeared he was ready to slide
into the golfing sunset.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Hogan rebounded in 1953 by winning five of the six
tournaments he entered. As was his custom in the post-accident
period, Hogan didn't play in the 1953 PGA, which was held
concurrent with the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan started his 1953 season at the Masters in Georgia, where
he set a tournament record of 274 in a five-shot victory. His 274
stood for a dozen years as the Masters' 72-hole record until
bettered by three shots by Jack Nicklaus. Woods lowered the mark by
a stroke in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   After winning the fourth of what would be five Colonial National
Invitation tournaments in his hometown, Hogan journeyed to the '53
U.S. Open at Oakmont in Pennsylvania. Hogan opened with a 69 on the
first day and led all four rounds, finishing at 283 and beating
longtime rival Sam Snead by six shots. His winning margin was the
largest at the Open since 1938.
</P>
<P>
   The blowout wins at Augusta and Oakmont erased memories of
Hogan's frustrating 1952 season. At Augusta, he skied to 79 on the
final day when a simple par-72 would have tied him with the
eventual winner, Snead. At the U.S. Open, conducted at the
Northwood Club in Dallas, Hogan opened with two 69s for a 36-hole
record and a two-stroke lead. But on the 36-hole finale on
Saturday, he wilted in the hot weather with two 74s and finished
third, five shots behind winner Julius Boros.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan's last-day collapses at Augusta and Northwood, combined
with his 40th birthday two months later, generated
Hogan-is-finished speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Close observers, and many of Hogan's fellow pros, noted that
while Hogan still had the best tee-to-green game in golf that the
Texan's putter was suspect. Their observations about Hogan's
putting would have been more pointed had Hogan allowed public
knowledge of his accident-related problem in his left eye.
</P>
<P>
   The discussions of Hogan's putting was aired publicly. In
private, in locker rooms and press tents, the commentary on Hogan
centered on his finances. Hogan was known to have made considerable
money in the new postwar oil boom. He also was known to have
received a generous settlement _ estimated at least in the six
figures _ from the Greyhound Bus Company, whose vehicle had slammed
into Hogan's Cadillac on the morning of Feb. 2, 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan, it was believed, had proved his point with the Open
victories in 1950 and '51. His comeback complete and his finances
secure, Hogan's weak 1952 performance thus revealed in the minds of
many a new lack of competitiveness from the man whose intense
concentration and flinty stare had for years intimidated even the
most hardened professional competitor.
</P>
<P>
   But Hogan's victories at Augusta and Oakmont, combined with
another summer victory at the Pan American Open in Mexico City,
showed that Hogan's drive for victory had not abated. And at the
conclusion of the Oakmont Open, Hogan announced that he would play
in a third major, the upcoming British Open at Carnoustie in
Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Many figures influential in Hogan's life, led by wife Valerie
and British Open champions Bobby Jones, Walter Hagen and Tommy
Armour, had urged Hogan to travel to Carnoustie. As Valerie said 46
years later, on the eve of another Carnoustie Open, ``Ben was
getting bored. He needed another challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Carnoustie offered challenges aplenty, led by the 7,300-yard
course that was considered then and now the toughest of the British
Open venues. The difficulty of the course was compounded by its
condition, particularly the shaggy greens. Hogan also had to adjust
to the smaller ball then in use in Great Britain, a temperamentally
jumpy caddie, strange and sparse food and galleries that were
allowed to roam freely and jostle players.
</P>
<P>
   But Hogan played through those problems, plus rain and a heavy
head cold, to shoot a four-round 282 to win the British Open by
four strokes. His winning score would be eight shots lower than the
290 that Paul Lawrie would shoot on a much better conditioned
Carnoustie course to win the 1999 British Open.
</P>
<P>
   The 1953 season proved to be Hogan's last great year. With the
founding of the Ben Hogan Co. club manufacturing firm in Fort Worth
in October 1953, Hogan now had a full-time job. Tournament golf was
even more of a sidelight. Even so, Hogan remained a competitive
force in the game. He lost playoffs to Sam Snead for the 1954
Masters and Jack Fleck for the 1955 U.S. Open, and was runner-up by
a stroke at the 1956 U.S. Open. As late as the 1960 U.S. Open at
Cherry Hills in Denver, Hogan reached the 71st hole with a share of
the lead with Arnold Palmer and Jack Nicklaus when a wedge shot
fell into a moat in front of the green.
</P>
<P>
   The advent of jet air travel in the 1960s made the British Open
accessible to American golfers, creating the modern Grand Slam of
the Masters, the U.S. and British Opens and the PGA for the single
season.
</P>
<P>
   But beginning with Palmer, the 1960 Masters and U.S. Open
Champion, and continuing through the greatest players since, no
golfer has yet equaled Hogan's 1953 mark of three majors in a
season.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 0304EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
