<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BURCH-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGER HAS TURNED THE TALE FOR DAN JENKINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Considering the source, the comments border
on blasphemy. But don't question the tried-and-true, Fort
Worth-loving pedigree of Dan Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   The renowned author and golf writer remains the world's No. 1
supporter of Ben Hogan, the Fort Worth legend who stands as the
only professional golfer to win three major championships in one
season. Hogan turned the trick in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past 47 years, his ``Triple Crown'' has withstood
challenges from the likes of Jack Nicklaus, Arnold Palmer and Tom
Watson. This week, a new gunslinger takes aim at the standard.
Unlike his predecessors, Jenkins senses that Tiger Woods is equal
to the task.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I'd see a better shot-maker than Hogan or a
better winner than Nicklaus,'' said Jenkins, a Fort Worth native
and TCU graduate who has written about professional golf for six
decades. ``But I have. It's Tiger. My jaw is agape.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins said he reached that conclusion after watching Woods
dominate the competition at the U.S. Open and British Open. Woods,
24, won golf's past two major championships by a combined 23
strokes. The triumphs made him the youngest player in history to
complete a career grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   Next up is the PGA Championship, which begins Thursday at
Valhalla Golf Club in Louisville, Ky. A victory would give Woods
his third major championship of the season, matching Hogan's mark
from '53.
</P>
<P>
   Because Valhalla is a birdie sanctuary for PGA Tour
participants, it does not narrow the field of contenders in the
same manner as most major-championship venues. That is why Jenkins
said he's not sure if Woods will join Hogan on the short list of
Triple Crown winners this season.
</P>
<P>
   But he's convinced Woods will surpass Hogan some year when he
wins the Masters, the season's first major, and develops a hunger
to become the first professional golfer to win all four majors in
the same year. A grand slam by Woods? Book it, says Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Tiger will do it if he doesn't get hurt,'' Jenkins
said. ``He doesn't have any weaknesses in his game. The only things
that can stop Tiger are an injury or a bad marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins covered the U.S. Open at Pebble Beach Golf Links and the
British Open at the Old Course in St. Andrews, Scotland, this year.
In many ways, Jenkins found himself stunned more by Woods'
eight-stroke victory in Scotland than by his 15-stroke romp in
Pebble Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The win at Pebble could've seemed like a fluke,'' Jenkins
said, likening it to Woods' 12-stroke victory at the 1997 Masters,
when no pursuers surfaced during weekend rounds. ``You could say,
`OK, Tiger will have one of these tournaments every three years.'
But what he did at St. Andrews erased all doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Saddled with enormous expectations before the event, Woods
merely shot four consecutive rounds in the 60s and posted the
lowest total in relation to par (19 under) at any major
championship. He hit 200-yard shots from deep rough where
competitors struggled to move the ball 40 feet. At that point,
Jenkins became a convert. He accepted the notion that Woods,
barring catastrophe, will one day surpass Nicklaus and his beloved
Hogan, to be hailed as the greatest golfer the game has known.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins envisions Woods setting standards that will provide him
that status through public acclamation, with little regard given to
who competed in what era, using which type of equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, I put the over-under total for Tiger's major
championships at 12,'' Jenkins said. ``Now, I'd say 25. I'm
serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering that Woods has four to his name, 14 fewer than
Nicklaus' record for professional golfers, such a statement seems
outrageous. But don't ask me to volunteer to take the ``under'' and
be forced to live with the financial consequences in 2030, when
Woods might still be winning green jackets at 54.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan, rest assured, will always remain a golf icon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the greatest golfer who ever lived, at the time,'' said
Jenkins, one of the few journalists to witness Hogan, Nicklaus and
Woods at the top of their games.
</P>
<P>
   But times change. So do opinions. Jenkins, in fact, said Hogan
would have identified Woods as the man to beat in head-to-head
duels if they'd competed in the same era.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben was so much in awe of length, he would've said, `Tiger
Woods should win every tournament,' '' Jenkins said.
</P>
<P>
   No one, of course, will ever do that. But Woods has come closer
than anyone since Hogan, who won five times in six starts in 1953.
A victory at the PGA would be Woods' 14th title in his past 25
appearances at PGA Tour events, as well as his third consecutive
major championship.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins has long deemed Hogan's 1953 Triple Crown the crowning
achievement by any professional golfer in a calendar year. With a
victory at Valhalla, Jenkins said Woods' 2000 season ``would be
right up there with it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Woods, in the long run, appears destined for even bigger
things.
</P>
<P>
   ATTENTION MORE INTENSE ON WOODS THAN IT WAS ON HOGAN
</P>
<P>
   For the second time this season, history has linked Tiger Woods
with Ben Hogan, the golf legend from Fort Worth. And the stakes
keep getting higher.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Woods became the first golfer since Hogan in 1948
to win six consecutive events on the PGA Tour. It marked the
second-longest winning streak in tour history, behind Byron
Nelson's 11 consecutive victories in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   This week at the PGA Championship, Woods has a chance to join
Hogan as the only professional golfers to win three major
championships in one season. Hogan did it in 1953, when his
``Triple Crown'' earned him ticker-tape parades in Fort Worth and
New York City. Those who watched Hogan pull his trifecta said there
was a significant difference in public perception heading into
those events compared with what Woods faces heading into Thursday's
opening round of the PGA.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two months, rivals have openly questioned if anyone
can stop Woods' winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was never like that with Hogan,'' said Dan Jenkins,
renowned author and golf writer. ``The other guys were not afraid
of Hogan. They knew he'd be there at the end, but they thought they
could do it, too. Right now, Tiger has nobody pushing him. Hogan
had Sam Snead. That's a big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Ditto for the physiques of the protagonists. Hogan (5-foot-9,
145 pounds) never overpowered courses as does Woods (6-2, 180).
</P>
<P>
   ``Hogan had to strive for everything. He always struggled for
distance, even in his prime,'' Jenkins said. ``Tiger is a great
athlete. Everyone knows he's long off the tee, but what separates
him is that he's long through the bag. He's long with his mid-irons
and short irons, too.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1953, Hogan received little public acclaim until after he won
the British Open, the third leg of his Triple Crown. Woods has been
under the media microscope for two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``After he won the British, people all over the world were
talking about Tiger, even if they weren't golf fans,'' said Jerre
Todd, retired publicity director for the Colonial tournament whose
ties to professional golf trace back to the '50s. ``That was not
the case with Hogan. To knowledgeable golf fans, it was a big deal.
To everyone else, it wasn't. It was hard to work up a good
stampede.''
</P>
<P>
   But a publicity stampede will be inevitable if Woods matches
Hogan as a Triple Crown winner. Jenkins considers Woods the PGA
favorite, but not a lock to win. Todd believes Hogan will soon be
joined on one of the shortest lists in the golf history book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he'll win the PGA,'' Todd said. ``When you talk about
dominating peers, Tiger seems to be a step ahead of Hogan in that
regard. Hogan was invariably the favorite when he played, but the
other guys thought they could beat him. These guys today don't
think they can beat Tiger. And if he wins the PGA, it'll just
cement it in their minds.''
</P>
<P>
   CHIP SHOTS FAMILIAR FRIEND
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth resident Mark Brooks, winner of the 1996 PGA
Championship at Valhalla, said he expects warm memories this week
when he visits the 15th tee. Brooks finished 4 under par in four
visits to the par-4 hole in '96.
</P>
<P>
   During the third round, he holed a 6-iron from 170 yards for an
eagle. In the final round, Brooks' closing charge began with an
8-foot birdie putt at No. 15. Brooks took birdies on three of his
last five holes, including one in the playoff, to beat Kenny Perry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the holes I played that week, that was my hole,''
Brooks said. ``When I got to the tee box in the final round, that
gave me a boost of confidence. I hope I get some more good vibes
this week.'' VOLUNTEERS, GOLFERS NEEDED
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Bank One Senior Classic seek volunteers to work
at the Sept. 22-24 event, and golfers to participate in pro-ams
during tournament week.
</P>
<P>
   Tournament director Tim Erensen said organizers need 100-150
additional volunteers to serve as marshals or perform other duties
during the event at Bent Tree Country Club in Dallas. In addition,
Erensen said 20 pro-am spots remain for rounds on Wednesday or
Thursday of tournament week. Pro-am spots cost $2,500 each.
</P>
<P>
   Those interested in working at the event or playing in the
pro-am should contact Alexa Devine at (972) 661-1256. SPONSORSHIP
UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   Senior PGA Tour officials said Tuesday that they will examine a
sponsorship proposal forwarded by the Dallas Rotary Club and expect
to decide within the next two weeks whether the city will have an
event on the 2001 schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Bank One is dropping its title sponsorship of the Bank One
Senior Championship, scheduled Sept. 22-24 at Bent Tree Country
Club, after this year's tournament. Within the past week, Rotary
Club members have a secured three-year commitment from a potential
replacement sponsor to keep the event in Dallas, said club
president Buck Revell. Tour officials said they will examine the
proposal, but are unsure if an agreement can be reached in time to
land a date on the 2001 calendar.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Tour officials hope to finalize the 2001 by Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   LPGA GOLDEN MOMENTS
</P>
<P>
   ``To commemorate the LPGA Tour's 50th anniversary, the''
Star-Telegram ``will feature a significant moment in tour history
each week during the 2000 season.'' Aug. 30, 1987
</P>
<P>
   Ayako Okamoto of Japan won her fourth tournament of the season
(Nestle World Championship), giving her enough points to become the
first international golfer to win the LPGA Tour's Player of the
Year award. The triumph marked the start of a trend. Foreign-born
players have won the award the past five years, with Australia's
Karrie Webb or Sweden's Annika Sorenstam likely to extend the
streak to six at the conclusion of the 2000 season. nn
</P>
