<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Don't ever let a deer die in your yard'
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Nancy Linares, a grandmother who lives on a
cul-de-sac, has advice regarding allowing critters to croak on your
property.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't ever let a deer die in your yard in Austin,'' she said.
Unless you want to spend the day finding somebody to come pick it
up.
</P>
<P>
   Early Friday, the guy who cuts Nancy's yard told her that she
had a dead deer toward the back of her yard. In this heat, she
would have found it herself sooner or later. ``When I came home
Thursday night, I thought it was the worst smell,'' she recalled.
``I thought somebody had put some horrible fertilizer in their yard
or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Another clue? ``There were these huge black birds in the back
yard,'' Nancy said.
</P>
<P>
   So Friday morning Nancy began a string of phone calls in an
effort to get the deer taken away. She called the City of Austin
first. A woman on the line told Nancy to call the city's Utility
Customer Service Center _ and do the old Press 1, Press 2, Press 3
routine. None of which addressed dead deer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There weren't any numbers that had anything about dead
animals, so I punched zero,'' she said. Zero was what she got. She
ended up on hold for 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Switching gears, Nancy called the U.S. Fish and Wildlife
Service. ``They said, 'Oh, ma'am, if that deer is dead, call the
city or the county,' '' Nancy said. She said the Fish and Wildlife
person also asked her, `` `Just how did that deer die?' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, 'I couldn't ask him,' '' Nancy said.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Nancy called the city's Solid Waste Services. She says the
guy on the line told her that city workers weren't allowed to come
on private property to remove the deer and that she'd have to carry
the deer to the curb before it could be picked up.
</P>
<P>
   Lugging that much dead weight to the street seemed daunting to
Nancy. ``I was sure the deer weighed more than I do, besides
smelling,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So Nancy called the city's general number, and talked to a
female city employee about her dead deer. ``She said, 'Don't you
have a son or a neighbor that can drag that deer out?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy then enlisted the help of Mickey Benjamin, 82, who works
at the travel agency Nancy owns. Mickey managed to slide a sheet of
cardboard from a leaf blower box underneath the deer. Then Mickey
and Nancy dragged the deer from the back of the yard to the curb by
yanking on one of the deer's legs.
</P>
<P>
   This was no downstream deer, either. ``It was a great big one _
at least a Great Dane or bigger,'' Nancy said.
</P>
<P>
   By lunchtime, the curbside deer was becoming so ripe that
Nancy's 93-year-old neighbor called to complain about the stench.
``He said, 'I can't even eat my lunch, it smells so bad,' '' Nancy
recalled. `` `Can you call somebody back again?' ''
</P>
<P>
   By midafternoon, Nancy says, the city folks came and took away
the deer.
</P>
<P>
   So if you see a deer about to keel over in your yard, go out
there with a pie pan and a spoon and drive it into the neighbor's
yard.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso can be reached at jkelso(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
