<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    His type still takes pounding
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Doug Billheimer thinks he knows what it would have been like to
be a blacksmith at the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   When you take in the sign outside his store in Dayton, Ohio _
``The Typewriter Shop,'' with letters in the shape of keys _ you
can't help feeling a sense of anachronism, as if you've stumbled
across a soda shop or an authentic five-and-dime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since 1914,'' the sign says _ a reminder that the typewriter
is very much a creature of the 20th century. The shiny new
technology of 1900 has now become ``a dying trade,'' Billheimer
concedes.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get him wrong; Billheimer still loves his work, and he's
still quite busy, in part because his business is among a handful
of survivors from more than a dozen area typewriter shops in the
early '80s.
</P>
<P>
   But if he had to do it over again? ``I probably would have gone
a different way,'' says Billheimer, 56. ``It's a shame; it's a
dying art. Now I know how the guy who makes horseshoes felt.''
</P>
<P>
   Or the harness-maker. Or the lithographer. Or any of 1,000
trades once considered indispensable, and now considered archaic.
</P>
<P>
   Once all of them were seen as solid careers, sure bets. What
blacksmith, after all, could have foreseen all the ruckus caused by
that Henry Ford fellow?
</P>
<P>
   Billheimer in 1975 came to work for Ron Tateman, whose family
had owned the business since 1942. Typewriters were ``the thing''
then, computers the young upstart.
</P>
<P>
   When Tateman, 64, started working for his father, in 1950, the
Royal manual was ``king of the hill.'' Now Tateman can't imagine
life without his computer: ``It destroyed my business, but I love
my computer. I can fully understand why the computer replaced the
typewriter, just as I understand why the self-starter replaced the
crank.''
</P>
<P>
   Billheimer, who bought the business from Tateman in 1996, says
that typewriter sales have plummeted, but there is still a strong
demand for service. He makes house calls, office calls. He has
expanded his business to paper shredders and fax machines.
</P>
<P>
   All he needed, when he started out, was a good head for
mechanics. That's a challenge Billheimer _ the kid who always liked
taking things apart and trying to put them back together _ still
relishes: ``I like the challenge of fixing something I've never
seen before, diagnosing the problem and repairing it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's getting harder and harder to find parts for some of the
older machines. ``You have to scrounge parts off another machine,''
Billheimer said.
</P>
<P>
   Look around the Typewriter Shop, and you'll see what Billheimer
means when he says there are ``people who swear by their
typewriters and don't want anything to do with computers.''
</P>
<P>
   There's an Underwood from the '30s. There's a 1950-era Royal, in
shades of military-issue gray-green, that purrs to the touch, still
obviously well-used and well-loved.
</P>
<P>
   Taped to Billheimer's antique cash register is a newspaper ad
from December 1921: ``The Typewriter Shop. Guaranteed typewriters,
new and secondhand. 101 E. Third St.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's us,'' Billheimer chuckled. He feels a strong sense of
loyalty to customers who have been coming to the shop for years,
even generations: ``A lot say they come here because they've always
taken it here, and gotten a good deal and we've treated them
fairly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He still has work that absorbs him, skills that people have come
to count on.
</P>
<P>
   He feels, in a word, useful, and not archaic at all.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty can be e-mailed at marymccarty(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
