 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com. Please include your name and hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Much has been written about the Concorde in the wake of the
recent crash in France. I'm reminded of another supersonic
transport, the Tupolev 144, developed years ago by the Soviet
Union. Do you have any information about it? Is it still flying?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Tu-144 ``Charger'' never became the wave of the future
that its Soviet supporters and developers hoped.
</P>
<P>
   The first flight of the plane _ which would be dubbed
``Concordsky,'' because it looked so much like the Anglo-French
Concorde, complete with drop nose and delta shape _ was in 1968. On
June 3, 1973, on a demonstration run before it ever entered
passenger service, a Tu-144 exploded and crashed in view of
thousands of spectators at the Paris Air Show. All six crew
members, as well as several people on the ground, were killed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, after several modifications, the Tu-144 was put into
service on mail flights between Moscow and Alma-Ata (now Almaty,
Kazakhstan), basically to collect data and establish safe operating
procedures. Passenger flights began between the cities in 1977, but
after a second crash in that same year, the plane was withdrawn
from service.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the aircraft's troubled past, Tupolev, Russia's leading
aircraft manufacturer, announced plans last month to revive its
supersonic transport program with an updated version, the Tu-244.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, company spokesman Sergei Rayevsky said the July 25
Concorde crash near Paris would not affect research and development
of the Tu-244 which the company hopes to have in the air by the
end of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Which flag is or was called the Southern Cross?
</P>
<P>
   A: That name was applied to the battle flag of the Confederate
States of America.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How many seconds should I count between seeing lightning and
hearing thunder to determine how many miles away it is? Also, how
does the wind factor in? I live a mile from an interstate, and when
the wind blows one way it feels like the trucks are in my back
yard. When it blows the other way, there's no traffic noise.
</P>
<P>
   A: For every five seconds that elapse before you hear thunder,
the lightning strike was about 1 mile away, said Greg Forbes,
severe-weather expert at The Weather Channel.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing of highway noise as a function of wind direction is
complicated. The wind speed (usually a few miles per hour at ear
level) is nowhere near the speed of sound (about 700 mph), so wind
speed doesn't cancel out the speed of the sound wave. Sound waves
don't have to travel in straight lines, but also can curve upward
toward outer space or downward into the ground and never reach you.
</P>
<P>
   Both temperature and wind variations between the ground and a
few hundred feet above ground can cause sound waves to bend. When
these two factors cancel each other _ one bending downward and the
other upward _ the traffic noise reaches you. But when the wind
blows from the opposite direction, the wind factor and the
temperature factor bend in the same direction, the sound wave is
strongly bent, and the noise never reaches you.
</P>
<P>
   The nature of the ``thermal bending'' can vary with time of day,
too, because the bending is usually upward on sunny days and
downward on clear, calm nights. When both thermal and wind
conditions are optimal (usually on clear, near-calm nights), the
noise can be loudest of all.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported that TV networks have lost interest in
``infomercial'' national political conventions that ``. . . stay on
time like Mussolini's trains.'' What does that mean?
</P>
<P>
   A: The business about ``informercial'' political conventions
describes how they evolve nowadays, largely devoid of spontaneity
and with careful scripting to meet the timetable, and highlight
party themes and leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The part about ``Mussolini's trains'' refers to Fascist dictator
Benito Mussolini's accomplishment in improving the efficiency of
Italy's railway service in the late '20s and '30s, albeit through
such mechanisms as government control of industry and a Fascist
labor charter that abolished strikes.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the Italian people, tired of strikes and riots,
welcomed Mussolini's authority _ provided he could bring order out
of chaos with such moves as stabilizing the national economy,
decreasing unemployment, and improving train service. As a
dictator, he was able to claim success on all those points.
</P>
<P>
   While ``making the trains run on time'' became a defense of the
Fascist ``corporate state'' on the basis of its efficiency, the
expression is nowccessed online?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. Transcripts of all the president's speeches and remarks
_ the weekly radio address among them _ can be found on the White
House Web site (www.whitehouse.gov).
</P>
<P>
   In the list of topics at the bottom, click on The Briefing Room.
Then navigate to Virtual Library, where you can click on types of
different documents, including radio addresses. You can select the
date range to find the radio address of your choice, or you can
search radio addresses by topic. Also, the Latest Press Releases
are posted near the top of The Briefing Room, so if you check on a
Saturday, you'll find the radio address among the latest documents.
The address is given at 10:06 a.m., generally each Saturday, said
White House spokesman Steve Boyd.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've read that several new flu medicines have been developed.
What are they and what is their development status?
</P>
<P>
   A: The prescription medicine Relenza is on the market already.
It was approved by the Food and Drug Administration in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Produced by Glaxo Wellcome Inc., Relenza is an inhaled powder
spray that is said to reduce the duration of a bout of flu by a day
or two. It also cuts the chances of catching the flu from an ill
relative by 79 percent, according to a study.
</P>
<P>
   The drug is the first of a new class of anti-viral medicines
known as neuraminidase inhibitors that are effective against both
major strains of the disease, known as influenza A and B.
</P>
<P>
   Between 25 million and 50 million Americans typically get the
flu each winter. Doctors emphasize that the flu vaccine is the best
way to ward off the disease, but the new drugs should help when
people fail to get the shots.
</P>
<P>
   Relenza was the first of a new class of flu medicines to reach
the market. Another, Hoffman-LaRoche's Tamiflu, is a similar
medicine in pill form.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Sen. Joseph Lieberman has said he will not travel or work on
the Sabbath. If Al Gore and he win the election and something
happens to Gore, leaving Lieberman in command, will we have a
six-day-a-week president? What happens if there's a major crisis on
his Sabbath?
</P>
<P>
   A: As you say, Lieberman, an Orthodox Jew, observes the Sabbath
by not working, driving or writing from sundown Friday to sundown
Saturday. But there's an exception in Jewish law that allows work
when human life or national security is at stake. He already cites
that exception when he votes on those rare occasions when the
Senate meets in a Saturday session.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I remember reading in Q&AMP;A the ``core values'' created by
Charles Brewer when he founded MindSpring, but could you reprint
them? I hope such values will springboard his entrepreneurial
spirit and insight into his next great endeavor, and maybe inspire
others as well.
</P>
<P>
   A: These are the 10 values, chacterized as ``central to the
success'' of MindSpring Enterprises, which later became EarthLink
(and in which Brewer has sold his holdings):
</P>
<P>
   (1) We respect the individual, and believe that individuals who
are treated with respect and given responsibility respond by giving
their best.
</P>
<P>
   (2) We require complete honesty and integrity in everything we
do.
</P>
<P>
   (3) We make commitments with care, and then live up to them. In
all things, we do what we say we are going to do.
</P>
<P>
   (4) Work is an important part of life, and it should be fun.
Being a good businessperson does not mean being stuffy and boring.
</P>
<P>
   (5) We love to compete, and we believe that competition brings
out the best in us.
</P>
<P>
   (6) We are frugal. We guard and conserve the company's resources
with at least the same vigilance that we would use to guard and
conserve our own personal resources.
</P>
<P>
   (7) We insist on giving our best effort in everything we
undertake. Furthermore, we see a huge difference between ``good
mistakes'' (best effort, bad result) and ``bad mistakes''
(sloppiness or lack of effort).
</P>
<P>
   (8) Clarity in understanding our mission, our goals, and what we
expect from each other is critical to our success.
</P>
<P>
   (9) We are believers in the Golden Rule. In all our dealings we
will strive to be friendly and courteous, as well as fair and
compassionate.
</P>
<P>
   (10) We feel a sense of urgency on any matters related to our
customers. We own problems and we are always responsive. We are
custoEWS-QUESTIONS17-FILE2-COX 08-16  &UR; BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS17-FILE2-COX
</P>
<P>
   EDS: THIS IS FILE 2 OF 2
</P>
<P>
   Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
</P>
<P>
   c. 2000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Q: By constitutional requirement, the number of representatives
per state in the U.S. House is based on population. Does that mean
the number of U.S. citizens in the state, or the general
population?
</P>
<P>
   A: The latter, as determined by the census.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you settle another friendly family discussion? When was
the first color TV?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are several ``firsts,'' as explained in the book
``Famous First Facts.''
</P>
<P>
   The first public demonstration of color television was given on
June 27, 1929, in the Bell Telephone Laboratories in New York. Some
of the objects shown in color were an American flag, a watermelon
and a bunch of roses. The images were of low definition and
mechanically scanned, using three complete systems of photoelectric
cells, amplifers and glow tubes. Each system had a red, blue or
green screen, with a system of mirrors superimposing the three
images to make one combined picture in color.
</P>
<P>
   The first daily color program was Ivan T. Sanderson's ``The
World Is Yours,'' first broadcast on CBS's W2CBS (later to become
WCBS, Channel 2) in New York on June 26, 1951. It depicted the
earth's natural treasures.
</P>
<P>
   The first coast-to-coast live telecast in color was transmitted
on Nov. 3, 1953, from the Colonial Theatre in New York. It starred
Nanette Fabray.
</P>
<P>
   The first regular prime-time series broadcast in color was
``Bonanza,'' which aired on NBC from 1959 to 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have any details about Sen. Joe Lieberman's first wife
and their divorce? Is divorce common in Orthodox Judaism?
</P>
<P>
   A: Lieberman and his first wife, Elizabeth Haas, a psychiatrist,
were married in 1965. They had two children. Haas and Lieberman met
while they both worked as interns in the office of Sen. Abraham
Ribicoff (D-Conn.). Their marriage apparently became troubled in
the 1970s, while Lieberman served in the Connecticut state Senate.
His wife filed for divorce in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   The following year he met his present wife, Hadassah. She also
had gone through a divorce _ from Gordon Tucker, a rabbi _ and was
raising a 6-year-old son. They were married in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   In his book ``In Praise of Public Life,'' Lieberman, 58, wrote
about his divorce, saying he and Haas had taken different paths
personally and professionally. He blamed the divorce, in part, on
the demands of his political career. ``No one in my family had ever
divorced,'' he wrote. ``It wasn't supposed to happen to good
people, so divorce to me meant failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Divorce is not stigmatized in the Orthodox community, said Rabbi
Ilan Feldman of Atlanta's Congregation Beth Jacob. ``The divorce
rate is less common than in the general population, but it's not
uncommon,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How many balloons were released on the last night of the
Republican National Convention? Who supplied them, and how were
they dropped?
</P>
<P>
   A: The number of red, white and blue balloons was estimated at
about 150,000. The Republican National Committee purchased them
from Balloon Celebrations of Atco, N.J. They were held against the
ceiling of Philadelphia's First Union Center by netting, which was
pulled away to allow them to fall to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The first tropical storm this year was named Alberto. About
six years agotravels by radio airwaves on a cellular phone.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that, experts advise against using a portable/cordless
phone (or a land-line phone) if an electrical storm is in the
immediate vicinity. All of them are electrical devices with wires
associated and some common bonding to a power system. You
especially shouldn't have anything with metal in it connected to
your body _ such as a telephone held next to your ear _ when you're
outdoors during such a storm.
</P>
<P>
   Other tips can be found in your telephone directory, near the
front, on the page headed ``Emergency Preparedness.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: With all the current interest in the Confederate submarine
Hunley, we're wondering about something we saw in Columbus, Ga.,
several years ago. It was in a rather small museum and, as I
recall, was a wooden skeleton of a Confederate submarine. Do you
have any details on this piece of Southern history?
</P>
<P>
   A: You're undoubtedly referring to the Confederate Naval Museum,
which since 1970 has featured the salvaged remains of two
Confederate warships reclaimed from the bottom of the Chattahoochee
River in the 1960s. The 225-foot CSS Jackson, an ironclad ram, and
the 130-foot CSS Chattahoochee, a sail and steam wooden gunboat,
both were set loose in the river at the end of the Civil War and
burned to the waterline. What you probably saw when you visited the
museum was the skeleton of the Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Also featured in the museum is a collection of uniforms,
weapons, models, ordnance and art, all relating to Civil War naval
operations during the period 1861-65. A much larger new museum, to
be named the Port Columbus Civil War Naval Center, is expected to
open next March.
</P>
<P>
   Information _ including photos _ can be found online at
www.tourcolumbus.com/museum/naval.html or
www.portcolumbus.org/pcmain.htm; or call 706-327-9798 or
706-327-9798. Q: Weather forecasters sometimes predict ``isolated
showers,'' and sometimes ``scattered showers.'' What's the
difference?
</P>
<P>
   A: Both terms imply that precipitation will be localized,
meaning there will be precipitation-free space in between, said
Colin Marquis, senior meteorologist at The Weather Channel.
``Scattered'' implies that the coverage will be greater than
``isolated,'' even though they both imply that coverage will be
less than 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, Marquis added, is that ``isolated'' means
there's a better chance that your picnic will remain dry.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I often see the term ``statute of limitations.'' What exactly
does it mean?
</P>
<P>
   A: As defined by Black's Law Dictionary, it's a law establishing
a time limit for suing in a civil case, based on the date when the
claim accrued (meaning when the injury occurred or was discovered).
The purpose is ``to require diligent prosecution of known claims,
thereby providing finality and predictability in legal affairs and
ensuring that claims will be resolved while evidence is reasonably
available and fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   Another meaning: A statute establishing a time limit for
prosecuting a crime, based on the date when the offense occurred.
After that time period, a suspect cannot be prosecuted. There is no
statute of limitations for murder, however.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
