<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 10:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3204 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-HUTCHINSON0817-     08-16 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-HUTCHINSON0817-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Women on the verge of power
 &HT;    By Anne Morris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ If pop culture truly leads the way, a woman
being nominated for president by a major party may not be far away
_ though not this year. Promising signs include the President 2000
Barbie doll, a ``Simpsons'' episode in which Lisa grows up to be
president and Glenn Close's convincing appearance as Harrison
Ford's vice president in the 1997 movie ``Air Force One.'' Think
2004 for a woman.
</P>
<P>
   In the new book, ``Madam President: Shattering the Last Glass
Ceiling'' (Scribner, $26), journalists Eleanor Clift and Tom
Brazaitis consider that possibility. ``Getting more women into the
pipeline for the presidency means winning more Senate seats and
governorships,'' they observe. Such offices are the equivalent of
the farm teams in baseball. Currently there are only nine women
among the 100 senators, and only three female governors in 50
states. Why not more?
</P>
<P>
   ``Stereotypes are hard to shake,'' the authors say. And thus
far, few women have been taken seriously by our country as
candidates for higher office. Those who have _ Geraldine Ferraro,
Pat Shroeder, Carol Moseley-Braun _ have sometimes faltered.
</P>
<P>
   Another new book, ``Nine and Counting,'' puts a strong positive
spin on the stories of women who have served in the Senate.
Conscious of how limited their numbers are, the nine current female
senators have collaborated on a book to encourage others to join
them. A support group for one another, they meet monthly for dinner
to discuss the ups and downs they face as minority members of what
is still essentially a boys' club. ``Nine and Counting: The Women
of the Senate,'' by Barbara Mikulski, Kay Bailey Hutchison, Dianne
Feinstein, Barbara Boxer, Patty Murray, Olympia Snowe, Susan
Collins, Mary Landrieu and Blanche Lincoln, written with Catherine
Whitney, (Morrow, $25) shares these women's stories of triumph
against ``great odds.'' (Whitney earlier was the contributing
writer on ``Framing a Life: A Family Memoir'' by Geraldine
Ferraro). Readers will learn how Olympia Snowe of Maine went on to
succeed even after both parents died in a car wreck while she was a
child, and how Mary Landrieu of Louisiana overcame a serious
challenge to her election victory. (Down the road, perhaps Hillary
Rodham Clinton's difficulties will be included, as she assembles
credentials to run for president.)
</P>
<P>
   One name that appears prominently in both new books is that of
Texas Republican Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, giving a clue to her
national importance. With Sen. Barbara Mikulski, D-Md., she led the
effort to create ``Nine and Counting.'' In ``Madame President,''
Hutchison is named as a possible future presidential candidate and
as someone who might have been a vice-presidential candidate this
year _ had fellow Texan George W. Bush not been running for
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nine and Counting'' begins with an account of what each of the
current nine senators was doing in 1952, the year Democratic
candidate (and liberal god) Adlai Stevenson proudly proclaimed,
``In America, any boy may become president.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody even thought to encourage a girl,'' Hutchison commented
last week, by phone from Washington. ``The emphasis was all on
young men.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1952, Hutchison was 9 and living in La Marque, near
Galveston. ``Nine and Counting's'' description of her is a bit
simplistic. ``She was a busy, gregarious little girl, forever
organizing skits and projects among the neighborhood children and
participating in activities with her Girl Scout troop . . . Kay's
dreams of the future took her . . . to the exciting urban arenas of
Houston and Dallas, where she aspired to a profession in business
or the law.'' (Up, violins.)
</P>
<P>
   Right away, you miss what she's known for. Why don't they
mention her days as a Longhorn cheerleader and UT sorority girl?
</P>
<P>
   ``These kinds of things were a measure of success for a girl
when I was growing up,'' Hutchison admits. ``But when running for
public office, you want to emphasize other things _ that you can be
firm and credible, and also your experience level. You don't want
to be trivialized . . . In the early parts of my career, I had a
handicap of being trivialized.''
</P>
<P>
   When she attended UT Law School, she was one of five women in
her class. ``They didn't know what to do with us,'' she admits,
though a moment later she insists law school was a great
experience. When she graduated in 1969, she couldn't find a job as
a lawyer, because few firms were hiring women. She found a job
instead as a TV commentator, covering the state Capitol, and that
led her to run for the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   A minor theme running through ``Nine and Counting'' is that
chance plays a large part even in ambitious lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that you're the very best,'' Hutchison said. ``It's
that you're in the right place at the right time. I never intended
to run for the U.S. Senate. . . . It was luck, fate and timing _
with perseverance, hard work and preparation as an overlay.''
</P>
<P>
   She describes how those rejections from law firms were the
beginning of her future, ``even though at the time I thought they
were the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is the tone of the book. It's all about overcoming
obstacles. In ``Nine and Counting,'' Hutchison avoids bringing up
extra details like her failedm going to run for president,''
Hutchison said. ``I'm not a person who sits back and makes herself
available as a vice president. If you want the top job, go for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Read together, the two books create a strong picture of women
taking on political life. ``Madam President'' provides more gritty
details than ``Nine and Counting,'' but it also cheats by including
anonymous quotes from a Texas journalist/analyst who _ confronted
by Hutchison's supposed ambition for the top job _ says, ``I'm
saying a prayer for the republic.'' Footnotes at the end of the
book identify many sources, but allow others to remain anonymous _
hardly fair.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison prefers to talk about ``Nine and Counting,'' though
she notes that ``Madam President'' had a different purpose.
``Eleanor (Clift) was writing a book that had as its point: How are
women going to become candidates for president?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nine and Counting,'' on the other hand, reads like an
inspirational young adult book. The final chapter offers ``nine
lessons learned.'' Asked if the senators ever thought of turning
this into a children's book, Hutchison appears to consider it.
``We'll have to think about that,'' she said. Girls, after all, are
the target market.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
