<HEADLINE>
ATTACK OF THE NAUGHTY WEB SITES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY   
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: When I type in the first letter of a Web
address, another address appears below the address line. It has the
same beginning letter and is an objectionable site. How can I rid
my computer of the site?
</P>
<P>
   _ Embarrassed
</P>
<P>
   DEAR EMBARRASSED: Someone's been very naughty behind your back,
because I know with utmost certainty that none of my readers would
EVER think about going to smut sites. Or at least getting caught.
</P>
<P>
   You are a victim of Internet Explorer's AutoComplete, a dubious
``enhancement'' that attempts to guess what you're typing. It's
handy for filling in Web-based forms, but pretty annoying when it
starts guessing ``www.yasminenude.com'' when you're trying to get
to Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   Go to Internet Options in the Tools menu, then pick the Content
tab and look for the AutoComplete button. You'll be able to turn
AutoComplete off and dump what it's got stored.
</P>
<P>
   It's a lot easier if you go to www.swanksoft.com and download
HistoryKill 2000. It can clean out just about anything that
Internet Explorer and Netscape Navigator stash.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: How can I change a Word art extension from .Doc
to .Jpg or .Bmp? I can move the file into my photo program, but I
can't edit it because it still has the .Doc extension.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wassssssuuuupppp Doc
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DOC: Just changing the file extension isn't going to turn
the file into a graphic. Here's what I do every month when I get
the latest Yasmine Newsletter, which arrives as a Word document.
</P>
<P>
   The pictures of my wife _ well, she's not really my wife yet _
are components of the document that can be separated. I generally
right-click on the picture, then select Copy from the pop-up menu.
Then I paste the picture into Paint Shop Pro. I can either save it
in just about any format or print it out.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: How do I download the OPL3-SAx driver to fix my
laptop?
</P>
<P>
   _ Asleep at the Wheel
</P>
<P>
   DEAR ASLEEP: You, ummmm, download it. You'll probably find it on
the laptop manufacturer's Web site, along with installation
instructions. In general, click on the download link and save it to
a folder on your computer where you can find it later. Then read
the instructions. Even Yasmine knows enough to do that.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: About your recent column covering blank boxes
on the task bar. Well, a little dose of RegClean (download from the
Microsoft site) can handle that. Boxes are left over from very low
resources. I hope you don't get paid to do this column.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Answer Man
</P>
<P>
   DEAR THE: Actually, I get paid to KEEP doing it after reading
letters from all the pinheads out there who think they know it all.
Listen, Sparky, we already know the problem is caused by low
resources. We want to know what's draining the resources, and why
it seems to happen after doing a Windows update. RegClean is a good
tool for examining the Registry, but it only fixes known problems.
I run it every week, and I still have the boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, didn't mean to get that worked up. I need to review my
collection of Yasmine photos and relax.
</P>
<P>
   (Anybody with the real answer or Yasmine Bleeth's home number
can write Dr. Emilio Bombay at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com
(snail-mail: Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101). Fax: (817) 390-7257. In real life, Dr. Bombay is Michael
Gerst, editorial systems manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-11-00 1619EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
