<HEADLINE>
DUKE'S ON THE INTERNET STUMP, CAMPAIGNING TO BEAT THE BLAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By PATTI HARTIGAN   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You know what the presidential campaign needs? A little more
outrage, that's what. In years past, the Republican National
Convention was known to get the blood boiling in certain liberal
ZIP codes. But with all that hand-holding and hugging going on this
year, the only folks watching are the insomniacs _ and maybe the
saccharine manufacturers. It's hard to get riled up about
dispassionate complacency, or whatever it's called.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the Duke.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's a candidate worth hating. He's a compassionate
fascist who wants to make gun ownership mandatory. He proposes a
fat tax on people who take up too much room. The budget surplus:
He's all for it. Even his chief handler admits that the candidate
is a shallow opportunist who would sell out for the highest price.
</P>
<P>
   Get that man on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Duke, of course, is the gonzo creation of ``Doonesbury''
cartoonist Garry Trudeau. The chain-smoking character has stepped
off the comic pages to run for president with a high-tech,
multimedia campaign. Of course, he has a Web site,
www.duke2000.com. (``If you don't work that into your article in at
least six places, you're as ungrateful as you are drop-dead
gorgeous,'' the candidate says, speaking through Trudeau.)
</P>
<P>
   Duke is brought to life by the latest animation and
motion-capture technologies, which can add a bit of
unpredictability to the mix. The campaign was launched in February
at the US Comedy Arts Festival in Aspen, Colo., where a 3-D version
of Duke spoke to the audience in real time _ until the computer
crashed, that is. Duke, originally modeled after writer Hunter S.
Thompson, has ingested a fair share of pharmaceuticals over the
years, so it could have been an acid flashback.
</P>
<P>
   So what brings Trudeau, who won a Pulitzer Prize for drawing
``little pictures of the Nixon White House,'' to the Internet?
``I'm not drawn for the usual reasons _ greed and fear _ because
I'm neither poor nor scared about the future of my industry,'' he
says in an e-mail interview. However, he notes that when he gave a
talk at Stanford University earlier this year, some of the students
had never read ``Doonesbury'' in a newspaper, but had seen it
online. ``Although I personally love the little static black and
white drawings I've spent my life sketching on rag paper (and can't
foresee ever giving up), I am skeptical that a generation that's
grown up experiencing the world through screens will support comics
as I've known them.''
</P>
<P>
   That same generation, though, has also grown up with instant
``top 10'' lists, frank discussions of presidential private parts,
and dancing excretory products on ``South Park.'' How do you do
satire in such an age? ``This question _ how do you top reality? _
has been asked for as long as I've been working. I heard it a lot
during Watergate,'' says Trudeau, who contends that there are more
satirists working today than ever before. Indeed, anyone who feels
like it can produce parody on the Internet: Witness Zack Exley of
Somerville, who was threatened by George W. Bush for his mock
campaign site.
</P>
<P>
   But certainly, most amateur satirists don't actually have the
privilege of receiving such threats. It's hard to shock anyone
these days. ``The main difference is that the taste bar has not
only been lowered, but buried. Anybody can say anything,'' Trudeau
says. ``I think `South Park' might have marked the end of all
satiric restraint in mainstream popular culture. After all, if
you're not going to be offended by a singing turd, then what's
left? It's not political shenanigans that have become so extreme as
to resist parody _ it's the tools of parody that have reached their
limit.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Duke. He's always been what Trudeau describes
as ``a towering symbol of ignorance and bigotry,'' more of a
farcical figure than a satirical character. Trudeau insists the
whole campaign is strictly for entertainment. ``I mean, obviously,
we're trashing everything Duke stands for _ his naked opportunism,
his self-aggrandizement, his callousness and corruption. But it's
not with any grandiose agenda in mind,'' says Trudeau. He doesn't
want us to care one way or another about Duke: He just wants us to
be entertained by him.
</P>
<P>
   And you have to admit, that's what politics is all about these
days, anyway. Duke works as a candidate precisely because his
extremes are so entertaining. None of that bland,
middle-of-the-road pandering for this guy. (On censorship: ``You
have to remember that one person's porn site is another person's
social life.'') None of that namby-pamby multiculturalism for this
fellow. He's right out there with those recycled platitudes,
promising to ``be the ferret in the pants of the government'' and
``to build a bridge back to the 20th century.'' And he even
balanced out his ticket with the perfect prepackaged running mate:
Kathie Lee.
</P>
<P>
   If the Duke campaign proves anything (and Trudeau doesn't harbor
any pretensions here), it's that a candidate these days can succeed
only if he is a master of all mediums. His site (that's
www.duke2000.com, OK?) features a weekly video, and this week's is
a harangue about the Internet and personal privacy. It crashed my
computer just as Duke got to the part about abolishing the census
for women and minorities. As much as we love to hate this guy, his
candidacy is doomed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;  Back when Trudeau started drawing ``Doonesbury,'' college
kids were united around issues like civil rights and the Vietnam
War. What does the Net generation have? Napster. ``It hasn't
escaped me that none of my three kids has purchased a CD since
Christmas,'' he says. ``We're raising a nation of pirates. As a
professional troublemaker, I'm pleased, of course. But as a content
provider, I'm appalled. Either way, there's no turning back. We all
better adapt.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-10-00 1343EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 1130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000816.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 11:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3299 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-     08-16 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRMS AGREE TO BUILD A BETTER MODEM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By HIAWATHA BRAY   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I recently bought my last modem, a US Robotics device that
offers speeds of up to 56,000 bits per second, and usually delivers
about 50,000. But 50 kilobits is far slower than today's DSL and
cable modem systems, and I'm looking to step up to broadband.
</P>
<P>
   But what about those who can't? There are still millions of
people for whom high-speed digital Net connections are out of
geographic or financial range. For years to come, these people will
be saddled with slow analog modems.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the low speed of these modems may not be their worst
drawback. Ironically, nobody knows this better than those with
high-speed Internet access. I've got it here at the Globe, and so I
can download multimegabyte files in a minute or two. And yet, what
makes the service really valuable is that it's always on. That
means I can call up a Web page at a whim, or fire off an e-mail
with a click.
</P>
<P>
   Most Web pages come up almost as fast on a 56K modem as they do
here at the Globe, and it takes almost exactly as long to send a
brief e-mail. But with a modem, there's a dialing delay to clutter
up the process. And if you're stingy like me, and have just one
phone line, using the Internet stops you from getting or receiving
voice phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   DSL and cable modem services are popular in large part because
they eliminate the need to dial, free up your voice line, and
provide ``always-on'' service. These are pleasures that analog
modem users can never fully enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   But soon they'll be able to get pretty close. It turns out that
the 56K modem isn't the last word in analog data transmission after
all. By year's end, modem makers say they'll have prepared a new
modem standard called V.92 that can provide what might be called
``almost-always-on'' Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot to like about the new plan _ the absence of
fratricidal stupidity, for instance. In 1997, two incompatible
techniques were invented for making 56K modems, and the industry
practically self-destructed before finally adopting the uniform
V.90 standard.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the modem makers, fearful of repeating the 56K sales
slump of 1998, are all singing from one hymnal. They've already
begun tests to ensure their products all work together. The
official V.92 standard is set for final ratification by the
International Telecommunications Union in September, and the first
V.92 products should be on sale in time for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   So what will consumers get from the new standard? Well, there's
a bit of a speed bump. Remember that today's V.90s only receive
data at 56K; the fastest you can send data is just 33K. Under V.92,
the upload speed should rise to about 48K. Since most modem users
don't send a lot of data, this amounts to a marginal improvement.
</P>
<P>
   The other two enhancements look a lot more useful. When two
modems meet, they go through an elaborate ``handshaking'' process
to settle on the right speed and data protocols. They repeat this
process every time, as if they'd never met before. But most modem
users always dial the same number, so the protocols never change.
</P>
<P>
   V.92 takes advantage of this fact. ``The modem begins to become
intelligent and becomes familiar with the circuit you're dialing
into,'' says Mike Tramontano, marketing director of Motorola Inc.'s
modem software operation in Mansfield. A full handshake happens the
first time you dial a number; on redials, most of the process is
skipped. Tramontano says this cuts dial-up time in half.
</P>
<P>
   The new modems will also have a built-in ``hold'' feature. If a
phone call comes in while you're surfing, a signal will flash on
your monitor. You'll be able to interrupt the Internet connection,
take the phone call, then hop right back on to the Net without
having to redial. Again, the modem's ability to remember the
characteristics of a phone line is supposed to make the reconnect
quick and reliable.
</P>
<P>
   V.92 won't help you download three-megabyte music files any
faster. For tasks like that, there's no substitute for brute
bandwidth. But for the sort of workaday Web surfing and e-mailing I
usually do, a quick Internet connection can be more valuable than a
fast one. Besides, dial-up service is still cheaper than broadband,
and the new V.92s should hit the market in just a few months.
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, my new US Robotics box might not be my last
modem after all.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Hiawatha Bray is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached by
e-mail at bray(at)globe.com.
</P>
