<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 11:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3312 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CPT-CLASSICAL-ONLINE0     08-16 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-CLASSICAL-ONLINE0814-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Classical community tuning up for turn on Web's world stage
 &HT;    By Pierre Ruhe
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Almost everything you read about Napster, the
embattled software program that allows users to trade music over
the Internet, concerns the vibrant, commerce-driven world of pop
music. Napster has grown into a national fad by offering free tunes
and a sense of community for a youthful, computer-savvy crowd _
underscored by the rebellious thrill of ripping off major
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the profile of the typical classical music fan.
While a smattering of pieces by Bach and Brahms, Stravinsky and
Steve Reich are available on Napster, downloaded music has thus far
had a negligible effect on classical recordings.
</P>
<P>
   Frustratingly, it takes far longer to download a piece than it
takes to hear it. With a standard 56K modem, it takes about four
minutes to download one minute of music. Thus, the system is better
equipped to grab Eminem's ``Kill You'' (4 1/2 minutes) than
Mahler's Symphony No. 2 (80 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the Internet is woefully inconvenient for listening
to classical music,'' says Bill Rosenblatt, president of
GiantSteps, a media consulting firm in New York. ``It can take more
than four hours to get Beethoven's Ninth Symphony off the Web. In
that time you could drive to a record store, buy it, come home and
listen to the whole thing. Plus, you'd have the CD on your shelf,
with pictures and liner notes.''
</P>
<P>
   So the industry is awaiting broad access to the utopia called
broadband, which promises to fly at least an order of magnitude
faster. High-speed transmission is available now, although it's
expensive and still relatively uncommon. Yet when most houses in
America are broadband connected, the experts speculate, it'll
change how all recorded music is heard.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of free music and fear of the imminent demise of the
CD has been a staggering blow to the major record companies,
including Sony, EMI, Universal and BMG _ all of which have a
classical division loaded with rich back catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, these companies' e-commerce plans seemingly
consisted of suing Napster and another dot-com, MP3, which runs a
compression program that turns music from compact discs into small,
manageable computer files that can then be virtually swapped, one
song at a time.
</P>
<P>
   An appeals court is to rule in September on whether Napster has
violated copyright law and should be shut down. Yet, even if
Napster goes under, similar services _ many of which exist in the
unregulated ether of the Web _ will keep music piracy afloat.
</P>
<P>
   Now the major labels have launched plans to collect for
downloading their product. Last week, EMI announced plans to charge
full CD prices ($16.99) per album; Universal, the world's largest
record label, will soon charge $2 per song to download. A lot of
customers might wonder why bother with an expensive toll road if
it's no quicker, no more scenic, than the service lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet has created a mind-set that content is free,''
says Rosenblatt, ``and the longer this goes on, the more reluctant
people will be to pay. Only when the technology for paying becomes
transparently easy, then perhaps, maybe, people won't mind paying.
It should be as easy as making a long-distance phone call _ you
don't have to worry about the cost till later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are happy to be moral, so long as it's not
inconvenient.''
</P>
<P>
   Major players in the classical music community have been slower
to react, although administrators from orchestras around the
country have gotten together to calm their collective anxieties and
consider their options.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Symphony Orchestra is among the ensembles to have
signed on to what's touted as the Electronic Media Forum, which is
effectively a set of guidelines for each orchestra to develop a
unique path onto the Internet. The agreement was ratified in June
by the American Federation of Musicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``A subscriber said to me, `Wouldn't it be nice to hear a
concert one night and order a recording of it from the Web the next
day?' '' says ASO President Allison Vulgamore. ``Yeah, that would
be great, and that's one possibility. But right now the quality
hasn't caught up with the novelty.''
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Orchestra sees the Internet, in effect, as a
marketing tool, not an end in itself. Joseph Kluger, the
orchestra's president, notes that, ``Our primary goal with
technology is to ensure the success of the live concert experience.
Hearing what we do live in the concert hall gives you goose bumps
and a level of excitement that you just can't get from
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to services like Napster, the Internet has been described
as an equal-opportunity jukebox, where garage bands and
chart-topping stars share the same access to the public. Yet would
an esteemed ensemble like the Philadelphia Orchestra, one of the
oldest and most artistically refined in the world, dilute its
cachet if listed next to some Poughkeepsie Philharmonic on an
alphabetical list? These are very real issues an orchestra would
like to resolve before it's left to the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   So Philadelphia is taking the lead, with help from Online
Entertainment Network, a site partially owned by EMI.
</P>
<P>
   The orchestra will broadcast a live concert Thursday, touted as
the first pay-per-listen classical music event on the Internet. The
live netcast will cost $2. The star of the show will be violinist
Itzhak Perlman, who's one of EMI's best-selling artists.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear that orchestral administrators are forced to navigate
an unfamiliar field. The creative solutions they find might well
steer us into exciting and perhaps reinvigorating times for
orchestras.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most popular sites to download music without charge
are www.napster.com and www.gnutella.wego.com. To read the Internet
agreement between orchestras and musicians, go to www.icsom.org.
The Philadelphia Orchestra's Web site is www .philorch.org.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-13-00 1411EDT &QL;
</P>
