 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Old photographer ready to go digital
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The big thing for home computer users now is digital
imaging, which is a fancy way of saying home photographs and
movies.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, high on my wish list these days is a decent digital
camera. A still camera would be nice; a video camera would be
doubly nice so long as stills could be made from its output, and
generally, I believe, they can.
</P>
<P>
   With a computer of fairly recent vintage and an inkjet printer
capable of 1200 dpi printing _ which can be had for under $200 _
you have all the darkroom that will ever be needed.
</P>
<P>
   Digital cameras within the financial reach of most of us are
pretty simple things compared to your average single-lens reflex.
The latter will have interchangeable lenses, allowing you to
completely manipulate the exposure and the focus. There are digital
cameras that provide all that, too, but they are in the very
serious professional range.
</P>
<P>
   Most digital cameras have, at best, a lens with a zoom range of
3X, or three times normal. They are autofocus and offer only a
general kind of exposure control.
</P>
<P>
   One of the greatest advantages of digital cameras is that most
have a little screen on which you can get a look at the picture you
just made. If it doesn't suit you, it can be dumped from memory;
you don't have to take up the camera's limited memory with unwanted
photos.
</P>
<P>
   I used to make pictures for money as a sideline. I had my own
darkroom and all that. I gave it up when color became the standard.
Printing color, at that time, was more trouble and expense than I
cared to get into. My cameras were state of the art for the time.
</P>
<P>
   Now I would be delighted with a simple digital camera that
offered close to 2 megapixels of resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Two megapixels, according to the experts, separates the men from
the boys in terms of image quality. With 2 megapixels, you can make
nice 8x10 prints. Under that you had best stick with 5x7 images. I
could go with 5x7. The lower resolution is quite sufficient for
putting pictures on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   You can, however, make lovely prints with an inkjet printer and
the right paper. I've just finished testing some paper from a firm
called AGA Chemicals, which markets the stuff under the Pictorico
label.
</P>
<P>
   Using a stock picture in Adobe Photosuite LE, I ran three kinds
of paper through my LexMark 5700: Photo Gallery Hi-Gloss White
film, Premium Photo Glossy Paper and Premium Canvas.
</P>
<P>
   The results were spectacular. It's hard for me to see a lot of
difference between the Photo Gallery stock, which is terribly dear
at $75 for 40 sheets, and the Premium Photo, at a very reasonable
$12 for 20 sheets. Both presented a brilliant image.
</P>
<P>
   The canvas paper is a very heavy stock, with a strong canvaslike
texture, and it lent an entirely different feel to the photo. You
wouldn't use it often at 10 sheets for $22, but it would be grand
for certain painterly images.
</P>
<P>
   All those prices, incidentally, are for 8x10 sheets. You can get
more information, and order paper if you can't find it locally,
from www.pictorico.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
