 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    `Pac-Man,' other classics basking in 3-D updates
 &HT;    By Troy Oxford
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Classic video games like ``Pong,'' ``Frogger'' and
``Pac-Man'' still evoke a bit of nostalgia in me. These are the
games I grew up with. These are the games that spawned my love of
video games today.
</P>
<P>
   Technology has advanced a lot, however, and many video games
today make those vintage games look like cave paintings by
comparison. Game characters that were once simple, two-dimensional
representations have evolved into highly detailed, 3-D models.
</P>
<P>
   Game developers still lovingly embrace the spirit of those
arcade classics, however, and have united early titles with current
gaming technology to produce a beautiful marriage of nostalgia and
modernism.
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro Interactive is one of the enthusiastic developers
producing some of the new classics. A simple game like ``Pong'' has
been fleshed out considerably. What once was an amusement
consisting of two flat sticks and a blip for a ball is now a
multilevel 3-D game with more than 20 scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   Following the same scheme, Hasbro Interactive will add
``Breakout'' and ``Galaga'' to its new-classics roster next month.
Other notable Hasbro titles are favorites such as ``Frogger,''
``Missile Command,'' ``Centipede'' and ``Q-Bert.''
</P>
<P>
   One arcade veteran, Midway, has given the classic game
``Rampage'' a new face. The original arcade game put up to three
players in command of a trio of city-crushing creatures. The object
was simply to smash away and demolish buildings while avoiding army
units and pitfalls.
</P>
<P>
   Midway's new ``Rampage Through Time'' expands on the premise and
presentation. Now sporting twice as many monsters to choose from,
various minigames and city locations from throughout history,
Midway has given a classic new life.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best resurrections is ``Pac-Man World'' by Namco. If
there is one game that represents the classics, it would have to be
``Pac-Man.'' The little chomping hero recently celebrated his 20th
anniversary, and Namco has honored him appropriately.
</P>
<P>
   The basic elements are still there: mazes, power pellets and, of
course, the ghost pests Inky, Blinky, Pinky and Clyde. This time
around, however, Pac-Man's world is in 3-D, and he faces new
challenges and enemies in imaginative locations.
</P>
<P>
   Beautiful, stylized graphics, new game play and multiple game
modes enhance the classic title tenfold. There is even an original
version included in case you want to relive the good ol' days.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
