 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Yahoo strikes a blow for free music
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Music lovers _ not to mention the lawyers and rock
groups who want to sue them _ will be intrigued by Yahoo's new
category listing: ``Digital Distribution.'' They'll especially love
the subcategory: ``Peer to Peer File Sharing.''
</P>
<P>
   The phrase ``peer to peer file sharing'' has a nice ring to it,
but essentially it's a high-class way of saying: ``Hey, everybody!
Here's a list of places where you can swap music online for free.''
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo has a long and fairly comprehensive list of illegal places
to download music. It's a wonder the Recording Industry Association
of America hasn't filed suit against it for aiding and abetting
music-loving lawbreakers.
</P>
<P>
   One of the infamous places to download music is Napster
(www.napster.com), an entirely free service with literally
thousands of songs available, and every single download is free.
</P>
<P>
   As the RIAA has been saying for some time, and as we all know by
now, downloading the kind of music you'll find on Internet sites
such as Napster and several others is illegal. It violates
copyright laws and all of the fair-use statutes _ and that's just
for starters.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Peer to Peer File Sharing'' category lists 25 Web sites
where users can exchange music for free. One site, MyNapster
(www.mynapster.com/faq.php), is no relation to the infamous Napster
site, but its ``frequently asked questions'' area goes into detail
about how various file-sharing Web sites are built and how the
process of sharing your favorite tunes actually works.
</P>
<P>
   From Napster to relatively new schemes like Riffage and
MojoNation, the Yahoo list is revolutionary. It's not unlike when
Harold Ross, founding editor of The New Yorker magazine, printed a
weekly list of speakeasies in the ``Talk of the Town'' section
during Prohibition. Sure, it's illegal, but it's not going to go
away. As one of the panelists at Jupiter Communications' digital
music conference said, ``20 million pirates can't be wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind business-to-business or business-to-consumer or even
business-to-employee. This stuff is free. No money changes hands.
None. Zero. Nada. We've got ourselves a whole new category here,
``P-to-P'' _ no, not profits to profitability, that's P2P for those
of you keeping score at home _ but peer-to-peer. Yahoo knows people
are searching for these sites, as do other search engines.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of July, things weren't looking too good for
Napster, the most popular of these P-to-P sites. A lawsuit from the
RIAA could have shut it down permanently. But the lawsuit backfired
in the worst way possible for the labels. Users flocked to Napster
in record numbers, according to Web measurement service Nielsen
NetRatings.
</P>
<P>
   Napster saw a 92 percent increase in traffic. Eight hundred
thousand and forty nine music lovers all were swapping music for
free shortly after the ruling. Business _ if you can call it
business; there's no profit-taking after all _ at Napster has never
been better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The increase in the downloads of Napster on the heels of the
court stay is a strong indication that digital downloading has hit
critical mass among American Web consumers,'' said Allen Weiner,
vice president of analytical services at NetRatings. ``Rather than
fight this evolution, the entertainment industry should embrace it
and develop sensible solutions to capitalize on this market
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's not going to happen anytime soon. The major labels
are so obsessed with stopping Napster and other music download
sites that they can't or won't get together to offer consumers a
better, legal way to download music.
</P>
<P>
   In the real world, these same companies don't have any problems
selling their music to stores like Tower, HMV or the Virgin
Megastores.
</P>
<P>
   All of these stores have online sites, and Virgin especially is
ready to go with a site called JamCast, (www.jamcast.com). Users
register to use the site, download a player such as RealAudio,
LiquidAudio or WinAmp, and then shop the site for a variety of
tracks to download from bands as diverse as Smashing Pumpkins to
Duran Duran.
</P>
<P>
   But even though the Virgin Jamcast site is very hip, packed with
features and fun to use (it even has a decorative ``skin'' you can
download for your RealAudio player, changing its on-screen
appearance), it doesn't have anywhere near the number of songs
Napster has. Neither JamCast nor any other legitimate digital music
site will be able to take off until they can fill their virtual
shelves with as much music as they pack into their retail stores.
The Virgin Megastores aren't called Megastores for nothing. But
JamCast's shelves are still relatively empty.
</P>
<P>
   This is why so many music fans are still going the illegal route
_ the illegal sites have what fans want. Music, music and more
music. Now Yahoo has a category to help them find music faster and
more efficiently. How much longer will the record industry continue
with its posture of righteous indignation and endless lawsuits
before it realizes that the money spent on lawyers would be better
spent working on a digital music Web site and converting all these
``digital music pirates'' into happy, downloading, paid-in-full
consumers?
</P>
<P>
   Until that glorious day comes, there's always Napster and a long
list of other sites, neatly provided to you in list form from
Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-14-00 1033EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
