<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DAMASCUS UNVEILED: SYRIAN CAPITAL OFFERS HIGH POINTS OF ARAB
CULTURE
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With if-you-go box attached at end of story.
 &HT;    With SYRIA-PALMYRA-$ADV19.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (t) Travel categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Aug. 19 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria _ Whether they know it or not, when Westerners
try to conjure an image of fine Arab culture, it's probably close
to the courtyards and covered market streets of Syria's capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we go into the city,'' wrote travel writer Henry
Van Dyke, ``we step into a chapter of the 'Arabian Nights'
Entertainments.''
</P>
<P>
   That observation was made in 1908, but it still fits a city that
manages, amid its modernity, to stay alive with elegant detail.
</P>
<P>
   Cats slumber across finely carved tables with inlaid
mother-of-pearl oyster shell. Thick vines dangle over the walls of
the Old City. Diners smoke water pipes and sip tea in tile-lined
courtyards around quiet fountains. Swordmakers discuss their
ancient craft even as they consider advertising on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   As Syria slowly opens to the west, a small but growing number of
Americans are getting to know the exotic city of about 3 million
people.
</P>
<P>
   Damascus prides itself as the oldest capital in the world _
going back at least 5,000 years _ and as a showcase of Arab
tradition. It shows itself off with sometimes grand, and sometimes
funky flourishes. For the former, there's the stately tomb of
Saladin (pronounced, ``sala-DEEN''), probably the most heroic,
non-religious, Muslim figure in all history.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there's the army museum, where the power might go out as
you wander between the run-down artillery, tanks, rifles and the
dusty exhibit on Syrian Hamad Feris, who joined Soviet cosmonauts
in space. One of the few English signs at the exit states, with no
apparent irony, ``Tanks(CQ) for your visit.''
</P>
<P>
   For travelers, Syria is largely crime free. Arabic is the common
language and many Syrians also speak French. There are few
proficient English speakers, but some taxi drivers or hotel staff
will know a few words.
</P>
<P>
   Americans need to get a Syrian visa before departing. Those can
be obtained in about a week from Syrian embassies or consulates.
Syria still does not recognize Israel and will not grant visas to
people with Israeli stamps in their passports.
</P>
<P>
   The Syrian countryside is flush with archeological digs and
dozens of Crusader and Muslim castles. But the capital offers a
sampling of the great mix of cultures to come through this corner
of the Mediterranean. It's also a shopping wonder, offering rugs,
furniture and metal work from around the Middle East and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   A good place to start is the walled Old City. It's a large,
working district where Syrians shop for everything from clothes to
dehydrated Newts. Sold in jars in the medicinal herb stalls, a
paste of the little lizards is supposed to cure ills and provide
sexual vigor.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to other exotic venues where the locals serve the
tourists, in Damascus' Old City, the relatively few tourists and
locals line up together at the prime spots.
</P>
<P>
   That can be at Bakdash, a crowded ice cream parlor. It sells a
delicious firm ice cream that, for some reason, requires loud
pounding by fit men with wooden hammers.
</P>
<P>
   Or, it can be at the mausoleum of Saladin. He was the Muslim
general who ruled over most of the Arab world Baibars (pronounced,
``BAY-bears''). He was the Mamluke ruler who, before his death in
1277, defeated the Mongols and almost finished off the Crusaders
who had hung on after Saladin. He was violent and unforgiving, but
his tomb is decorated with the palaces and lush plants awaiting him
in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the Old City is the Omayyad Mosque, a huge
courtyard bordered by a large prayer hall built around 708 A.D.
Inside and out are mosaics of glass beads from as far back as the
12th Century.
</P>
<P>
   The mingling between I
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 1209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000816.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 12:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3332 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-SYRIA-PALMYRA-$ADV19-     08-16 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYRIA-PALMYRA-$ADV19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PIPELINES AND TAXATION, LEGACIES FROM THE OASIS CITY OF PALMYRA
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With SYRIA-TRAVEL-$ADV19.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (t) Travel categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Aug. 19 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALMYRA, Syria _ This was a working city, made rich from the
caravans that passed through and paid taxes on each goatskin of
oriental perfume and every camel-load of foodstuffs.
</P>
<P>
   It's more than 1,700 years past its prime. But Palmyra was once
the bustling home to 350,000 people. Water pipes of hollowed-out
stones still line the streets and an inscription urges locals to be
helpful to foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   It's an ancient example of the importance of location. Palmyra
was on the Silk Road between the Orient and the Mediterranean and
near a source of water, which travelers would pay for dearly.
</P>
<P>
   When its main competitor, the Nabataean(CQ) trading city of
Petra in what is now Jordan, fell to the Romans in the Second
Century, Palmyra blossomed. It reached its peak in the Third
Century, gaining freedom from taxation by the Roman rulers.
</P>
<P>
   But the city would decline starting 272 A.D. Zenobia, the shrewd
Arab queen who claimed her lineage from Egypt's Cleopatra, tried to
gain independence. Instead, Roman armies crushed her rebellion and
took her prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   The ancient city stands in the desert about a three-hour drive
northeast from Damascus. Among the sites on the way is a
Palestinian refugee camp (more than 370,00 refugees live in Syria).
Eventually, the road is lined by the modern pipeline bringing oil
to the Mediterranean from Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   About 35,000 people live in the new town of Palmyra next to the
ruins. There are several hotels. The ruins can be seen in a hurried
day. But, it's better to take two days for wandering through the
amphitheater, temples, public market and caravan stopping post,
museum and residential homes. The ruins are said to be magnificent
at dawn and dusk.
</P>
<P>
   Palmyra still possesses huge walls and spectacular colonnades
that stand out with a ghost-like presence in the dusty, hilly
desert.
</P>
<P>
   Palmyra is a Roman name, meaning city of palms. In Arabic, it is
Tadmor, meaning city of dates. Date palms abound.
</P>
<P>
   Intricate relief statues illustrate the city's people and gods.
</P>
<P>
   Near the Temple of Bel, the Babylonian god of the sky, one stone
panel shows women covered in swirls of cloth, a sign that veiling
took place even before Muslim times. Other panels show soldiers in
their armor and with their camels.
</P>
<P>
   Started in 32 A.D., the temple took 200 years to build. That's
longer than modern construction jobs but, then, most of the
structure has lasted nearly 2,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the building, still with its massive walls and many of
the surrounding columns, reliefs carved on the ceiling of an altar
show Bel surrounded by other gods and the signs of the Zodiac.
</P>
<P>
   The best look at the people of Palmyra _ a mix of Arab and Greek
bloodlines _ comes from their tombs on the edge of town. The
wealthy were entombed in towers, the poor in underground crypts.
</P>
<P>
   At the front of each tomb, lined with shelves where bodies were
laid on top of each other, were relief portraits of the people
inside. Those reliefs are in the Palmyra museum.
</P>
<P>
   The portraits are individual enough to make you feel like you're
meeting the inhabitants of the ancient city. Wealthy merchants are
portrayed with big bellies, a sign of prosperity. Some men have
curly hair, others straight. Women are shown holding their veils
slightly to the side to show their faces.
</P>
<P>
   About 480 feet above the desert floor, on a mountaintop, is the
12th Century Muslim Qala'at Ibn Ma'an castle. The castle,
surrounded by a moat and guard towers, provides a sweeping view of
the tombs, ancient Palmyra and the new city next door.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow can be reached at LarryK(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
