r d BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE17-COX     08-16 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pull together a scrumptious summer salad
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Summer is salad season. When heat and humidity put a crimp on
appetites and you don't want to spend a lot of time in the kitchen,
a main-dish salad is a healthful, tasty and creative way to get
dinner on the table.
</P>
<P>
   With supermarkets and roadside stands overflowing with wonderful
fresh produce, summer is also the time to take a breather from the
iceberg lettuce, tomato and cucumber drenched in bottled dressing.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you think your pantry pickings are spare, chances are
that if you look behind this and under that, you will find the
makings of a knockout summer salad.
</P>
<P>
   Do you have rice? Some kind of pasta? A potato or some lentils?
Surely your cupboard will yield cans of beans, corn, diced
tomatoes, salmon or tuna.
</P>
<P>
   Now check your freezer. Is it possible you have a couple of
sausages wrapped up in there or _ joy of joys _ maybe some frozen
shrimp?
</P>
<P>
   Now the fridge. Is there a bell pepper, a zucchini, a carrot or
squash hidden in the vegetable bin? Any packages of cheese lying
around?
</P>
<P>
   If you have any of these ingredients, just add a little
creativity and you are on your way to a tasty, cool and easy summer
meal.
</P>
<P>
   Check out these sites for loads of summer salad ideas.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lundberg Gourmet Brown Rice, at
www.lundberg.com/recipes/ssalad.html, has put together a number of
salad recipes using rice and other everyday pantry items and
spices. Cumin, cilantro, black beans, corn, peppers, tomatoes and a
mild salsa combine with rice to make a salad with a Southwestern
flair. Sun-dried tomatoes, olives, olive oil, balsamic vinegar,
Parmesan cheese, rosemary, basil and lemon juice inspire a
Mediterranean dish.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Surprising color and taste combinations are the order of the
day in several recipes at Fun Summer Salad,
www.ivillage.com/food/tools/recipe
</P>
<P>
   /articles/0,5370,6596,00.html.
</P>
<P>
   Your pantry may yield the makings of the unusual Tropical Tomato
Salad, which combines diced tomatoes, pineapple, hearts of palm,
green onions, blue cheese and olives _ a combo that goes especially
well with grilled chicken. Other colorful entries include an
unusual combination of blueberries, cherry tomatoes, olive oil and
balsamic vinegar. What about green beans and julienned beets or
sweet potatoes and canned green chiles?
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Some inventive salad recipes using pantry staples such as
canned fish, salmon, tuna and shrimp with summer fruit and veggies,
plus an inspired Asian vinaigrette, are at Summer Salads at
lubbockonline.com/stories/061400
</P>
<P>
   /lif061400025.shtml.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tabasco's Sizzling Summer Salads, at www
</P>
<P>
   .tabasco.com/html/tastesummer00
</P>
<P>
   2release.html, include Avocado and Grapefruit Salad With Poppy
Seed Dressing, Mediterranean Chicken Salad, Warm Shrimp and Ham
Salad Over Seasonal Greens, Shrimp Louis Salad, Spicy Spinach
Salad, Tuna Cracked Wheat Salad _ all perfect for lunch or a light
summer supper.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Leave it to Food and Wine's Main Course Salads, at
www.pathfinder.com/FoodWine/tarticles
</P>
<P>
   /s23x1.html, to come up with inventive, sophisticated salad
recipes using unusual combinations of textures and flavors such as
smoked trout and horseradish dressing.
</P>
<P>
   SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Pasta Salad With Sweet Peppers and Dill
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: about 30 minutes Cooking
time: varies, according to package directions
</P>
<P>
   Our tester, Margaret Ann Surber, halved this recipe, found at
www.canoe.ca/CNEWSLifeArchive
</P>
<P>
   /may25salads2.html. It is from ``Smart Cooking'' by Anne Lindsay
(Macmillan Canada, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups penne pasta, cooked according to package directions,
drained, rinsed and drained again
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup snow peas or green beans, blanched 2 minutes in boiling
water and drained
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups small cauliflower pieces, blanched 2 minutes in
boiling water and drained
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup thinly sliced carrots
</P>
<P>
   1sweet pepper (red, yellow, green or purple), cored, seeded and
diced
</P>
<P>
   1green onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   3/4pound large cooked shrimp, optional
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup chopped fresh dill leaves
</P>
<P>
   1clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons balsamic or red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon crushed dried oregano leaves
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   In a large mixing bowl, toss together the cooked pasta, snow
peas, cauliflower, carrots, sweet pepper, green onion, shrimp (if
using) and dill until well-combined.
</P>
<P>
   To make the dressing: Combine garlic, vinegar, lemon juice,
sugar, oregano, salt and pepper in a food processor or mixing bowl.
While processing or whisking, add water and oil slowly, mixing
well. Pour over salad and toss to mix.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (without shrimp): 253 calories, 7 grams protein, 8
grams fat (percent calories from fat, 27), 40 grams carbohydrates,
no cholesterol, 171 milligrams sodium, 4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
