<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 12:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3341 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-SHRIMP17-COX     08-16 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SHRIMP17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    From raw fish with an exotic Latin flavor to peeled shrimp
dipped in simple or fancy sauces, cold seafood dishes are hot this
summer
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a scrappy sign and not much more. I was a first-time
visitor to Puerto Vallarta, Mexico _ shy but not unwilling to
venture up an unknown flight of stairs, away from the dust and sun.
</P>
<P>
   Then something cool happened.
</P>
<P>
   While a family looked at television in one room, I sat in
another watching an old lady make a ``coctel de camarones,'' my
first Mexican shrimp cocktail.
</P>
<P>
   Behind a bar that doubled as her kitchen counter, this lady _
this saint _ chopped white onions, avocado and cilantro and dropped
it all into a monster margarita glass. She peeled some shrimp and
tossed them in. Then she ladled on a mysterious elixir that I later
discovered was hardly more than ketchup, lime juice, water and hot
sauce. She put the cocktail before me and handed me a spoon.
</P>
<P>
   Forget sex on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   This was a veritable vacation in a glass: part cold tomato soup,
part Bloody Mary, part classic shrimp cocktail. Suddenly I felt
like the world's most adventurous traveler _ and that 5-year-old
boy in flip-flops who got his first taste of the sea in Panama
City, Fla., some years ago. Never had I felt so wholly at home in
the house of a total stranger.
</P>
<P>
   So when I want a quick trip to Mexico, I hit Buford Highway in
Atlanta, where shrimp cocktails and other cold-seafood concoctions
can be found at places like Mariscolandia, Marisqueria 7 Mares and
Taqueria Las Americas. Some cities have an ocean drive, but we've
got an ocean of delicious dives, where without spending your last
sand dollar you can get everything from pickled snails to oysters
in a glass.
</P>
<P>
   Another fine option is to make your own shrimp cocktails,
seviches and other engine-cooling salads at home. This time of
year, it's hard to go wrong with a classic shrimp cocktail. Or the
Northwestern standard known as Crab Louis: shaved iceberg, chunks
of sweet crab meat, boiled eggs, tomatoes and a puddle of pink
dressing.
</P>
<P>
   No need to get fancy, either. Some of us grew up dipping peeled
shrimp in a mixture of ketchup and mayo. One colleague tells me
that at her house, it was mustard and lemon sauce (to which I might
add a little capers and horseradish). Once at a vegetarian
restaurant, I saw a zany couple ask for an order of fake ``boiled
shrimp,'' then pull a bottle of cocktail sauce out of a backpack.
</P>
<P>
   And nowadays, thanks to the Latin trend, more people are
realizing there's nothing so beachy as a taste of seviche
(pronounced ``seh-VEE-chee''). Originally cooked _ or rather, not
cooked _ in Peru, seviche is essentially raw fish marinated in
citrus juice. Mixed with fiery chiles, aromatic herbs and colorful
fruits and vegetables (mangoes, avocados, tomatoes), it appears up
and down both coasts of Latin America, from Mexico to Chile. It
would be a challenge to conjure a more clean-tasting, restorative
and element dish _ in which the flavors of the ocean splash in the
mouth like waves.
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise that Salvadoran-born chef Ticha Krinsky has
Peruvian-style seviche on the summer menu at Tierra, her Nuevo
Latino restaurant in Atlanta. Yet it's also popping up at
contemporary places like Insignia in Atlanta and Marietta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   For its August issue, Gourmet magazine sent writer Calvin
Trillin 2,800 miles (to Peru and Ecuador) in search of perfect raw
fish. And at New York's Chicama, the latest venture from chef
Douglas Rodriquez (formerly of Patria), the pan-Latin guru has
installed a seviche bar with such rawsome combinations as squid and
tuna with lemongrass, ginger, lime leaves and basil. Or sole and
clams mixed with crunchy pork cracklings, ham, green tomatoes and
parsley.
</P>
<P>
   So I'm betting that seviche, and its 1,001 variations, will be
the next big trend, after sushi. ``It's just a very refreshing
dish,'' Krinsky says. ``The lime and the pepper make it a very nice
summer food. The heat really cools you off.''
</P>
<P>
   With a little lime juice, salt and imagination, you can stir up
a Latin-inflected cold seafood appetizer or main dish. If you're in
a retro mood, throw in a little ketchup or mayo, shred some
iceberg, and break out the jazz and cocktails.
</P>
<P>
   I'm feeling hungry. Peel me a shrimp.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell Brock writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
