<DOCNO> NYT20000816.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3361 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-SHRIMP-RECIPES17     08-16 1615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SHRIMP-RECIPES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fresh is best for seafood concoctions
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Sg time: 60 minutes
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once you've tasted this easy-to-make cocktail sauce, you will
never want the bottled stuff again. Lime juice imparts a slightly
sweeter flavor than lemon juice, but either will do. Of course, you
may doctor this up with additional hot sauce or a chopped chile
pepper _ whatever you like. Any medium to large shrimp will do, but
colossal shrimp will prompt the most ``oohs'' and ``ahs.''
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup ketchup
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons white onion, very finely minced
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, very finely minced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon horseradish
</P>
<P>
   1 lime, juiced
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon Tabasco, or other hot sauce of your choice, plus
more to taste
</P>
<P>
   Salt, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 pounds large shrimp, cooked, peeled,
</P>
<P>
   deveined and chilled
</P>
<P>
   1 lemon, quartered, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   4 sprigs parsley or cilantro or baby romaine leaves, for garnish
(optional)
</P>
<P>
   To make the sauce: Place ketchup in small mixing bowl. Add
onion, garlic, horseradish, lime juice, Worcestershire sauce and
Tabasco sauce. Mix well, and taste for salt. Cover and chill in
refrigerator for at least 30 minutes (sauce may be prepared one day
in advance).
</P>
<P>
   To make the cocktail: When ready to serve, place shrimp around
edges of 4 chilled martini glasses. If you don't have martini
glasses, any small dish, plate or footed compote will do. Spoon
sauce into the center of each dish, garnish with lemon wedge and
herbs or lettuce. Chill for 30 minutes and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 192 calories, 29 grams protein, 3 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 12), 13 grams carbohydrates, 215
milligrams cholesterol, 577 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Tierra's Peruvian Seviche
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30 minutes Chilling time: 10 minutes or longer
</P>
<P>
   This has become a summer favorite at Tierra, Dan and Ticha
Krinsky's charming Nuevo Latino restaurant near the Atlanta
Botanical Garden. The authentic Peruvian chiles (see note) are what
give the dish its essential flavors. As side bites, the slices of
cold boiled sweetay adjust your own accordingly. We decided that
pisco sours, made from the Chilean or Peruvian brandy called pisco,
would be the perfect potent potable.
</P>
<P>
   2 small sweet potatoes, washed
</P>
<P>
   2 ears yellow corn, cleaned and washed
</P>
<P>
   1 pound fresh sea bass fillets
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon garlic, finely minced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon rocoto pepper, finely minced
</P>
<P>
   (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon aji escabeche pepper (sometimes called aji amarillo),
finely minced (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 small red onion, sliced paper thin
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fresh parsley, finely minced
</P>
<P>
   (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Black pepper, freshly cracked (optional)
</P>
<P>
   To make the sides: Place the sweet potatoes in a pot of boiling,
salted water. Boil at high temperature for about 15 minutes, or
until the potatoes can be easily stuck all the way through with a
knife. After the potatoes have cooked for about 10 minutes, add the
corn and cook for 5 minutes. Drain the vegetables in a colander and
rinse with cold water until cool. Slice the corn into inch-long
pieces and chill in the fridge with potatoes until ready to serve.
Note: The potatoes peel better after they've chilled.
</P>
<P>
   To make the seviche: Wash the sea bass in cold water, and pat
dry with paper towels or clean cloths. Chop the fish into pieces
about 1/4-inch thick and 1/2-inch long. Place in a glass or metal
bowl. Add garlic, rocoto pepper, aji escabeche pepper, red onion
and lime juice (make sure the mixture is completely covered with
lime juice). Sprinkle with about 2 teaspoons of kosher salt and mix
very well. Chill for 10 minutes or longer in the refrigerator (it
needs at least 10 minutes ``to cook''). Before serving, taste for
salt.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble the dish: Assemble mounds of seviche in the middle
of serving plates, using a slotted spoon to drain most of the lime
juice. Peel potatoes and slice into 1/2-inch rounds. Place 2 pieces
of corn and 2 of potato around the seviche. Garnish with flecks of
parsley and a few grindings of black pepper if you wish. Note: You
may also serve the seviche in lettuce cups or compotes _ and
garnish with thin slices of leftover red onion, lime or chile
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Note on ingredients: Look for the peppers in the frozen-food
section of a Latin supermarket. We found ours at Tienda Las
Americas (3652 Shallowford Road, Doraville. 770-458-7962). Thaw,
peel and remove seeds. If you can't find them, substitute chiles of
your choice, but mash them first with a little lime juice and salt
in a mortar and pesing this method, you may add garlic during this
step).
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 267 calories, 24 grams protein, 5 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 16), 35 grams carbohydrates, 77
milligrams cholesterol, 91 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   BEVERAGE
</P>
<P>
   Pisco Sour
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 serving Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to go to Cuba or South America to enjoy classic
tropical cocktails like caipirinhas or pisco sours. You can find
pisco (Chilean or Peruvian brandy) and cachaca (the Brazilian sugar
cane liquor) at metro package stores (including Tower Liquor on
Piedmont Road). Pisco tastes similar to grappa _ and this drink is
a very distinctive mix of sweet and tart.
</P>
<P>
   The egg white makes it frothy, but you don't have to use it.
Personally, I prefer to forgo the egg and the bitters.
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon egg white (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons lemon (or lime) juice
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces pisco
</P>
<P>
   Crushed ice
</P>
<P>
   Angostura bitters (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Put the egg white, sugar, lemon or lime juice, pisco and plenty
of crushed ice in a cocktail shaker. Shake well. Strain into a
small glass and serve straight up. Or if you prefer, add more
crushed ice. Top with a few drops of Angostura bitters if you like.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 186 calories, trace protein, no fat, 5 grams
carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 1 milligram sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER OR MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Crab Louis
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 main-dish or 6 appetizer servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This makes a wonderful first course for the steak and martini
crowd. And it works equally well as a complete summer meal. Serve
with a chilled white wine and a basket of bread or saltines.
</P>
<P>
   1 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chili sauce (or ketchup mixed with your favorite hot
sauce)
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons onion, very finely minced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons capers, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon horseradish
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons parsley, finely minced
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup heavy whipping cream, whipped
</P>
<P>
   1 large head iceberg lettuce (or other
</P>
<P>
   lettuce of your choice)
</P>
<P>
   1 pound lump crab meat, well picked over
</P>
<P>
   1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   1 ripe avocado, peeled and sliced in thin slivers
</P>
<P>
   4 boiled eggs, peeled, chilled and quartered
</P>
<P>
   1 large ripe tomato, sliced into wedges
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons tarragon, roughly chopped
</P>
<P>
   Black pepper
</P>
<P>
   To make the sauce: In a small mixing bowl or large measuring
cup, place the mayonnaise, chili sauce, lemon juice, onion, capers,
horseradish and parsley. Mix well and taste for salt. Let it sit
for a while to mellow, then fold in whipped cream and mix well.
Chill in refrigerator for at least 30 minutes (may be made one day
in advance).
</P>
<P>
   Wash the lettuce, wrap in paper or cloth towels and place in
refrigerator for about 30 minutes to dry and chill. Squeeze a lemon
over the crab to freshen. Toss and chill.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble the salad: Place the lettuce on a cutting board and
shave into the thinnest possible slices. Divide lettuce onto salad
or dinner plates. Top with crab meat. Arrange the avocado, eggs and
tomato slices in a pattern atop the crab. Ladle on a copious amount
of dressing. Garnish with tarragon, and crack some black pepper on
top.
</P>
<P>
   Per appetizer serving: 486 calories, 20 grams protein, 41 grams
fat (percent calories from fat, 76), 12 grams carbohydrates, 208
milligrams cholesterol, 967 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER OR MAIN COURSE
</P>
<P>
   Mexican
</P>
<P>
   Shrimp Cocktail
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 main-course or 6 appetizer servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 3-5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Perfection in a glass. Feel free to experiment with this
fail-proof recipe. You may choose to use grilled shrimp _ though it
might be better to place them around the glass. You can put salt on
the glass. And you can add more cooked seafood or raw oysters, more
hot pepper, sliced olives, small canned English peas, a dash of
olive oil _ whatever you like. A bit of freshly squeezed orange
juice will impart another dimension of flavor. Serve with saltines
or tortilla chips.
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds medium shrimp
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup freshly squeezed lime juice
</P>
<P>
   salt, more lime juice or hot sauce to taste.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble: If you want salt on the rim, moisten tall
soda-fountain or other large glasses with a bit of lime juice and
roll the glasses in a saucer lightly covered with salt. Mix the
shrimp into the sauce; then carefully spoon the mixture into the
glasses. Chill for 15 minutes in refrigerator. When ready to serve,
place a lime slice on the side of each glass. Garnish with cilantro
sprig. Eat with a spoon.
</P>
<P>
   Note: If you don't have quite enough sauce to fill glasses, add
a little cold water.
</P>
<P>
   Per appetizer serving: 285 calories, 26 grams protein, 11 grams
fat (percent calories from fat, 35), 23 grams carbohydrates, 172
milligrams cholesterol, 435 milligrams sodium, 7 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Bra
</P>
