<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3363 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-VIDEONOTES-HNS &LR;      08-16 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEONOTES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ON VIDEO: ERIN BROCKOVICH, THE CIDER HOUSE RULES; NEW ON DVD:
NAKED GUN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
``Erin Brockovich''
<TEXT>
<P>
   This story of a struggling single mom who helps win a
multimillion-dollar lawsuit is based on fact. You'd think it would
be inspiring.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also a Hollywood product, and as such, it's turned into
a star vehicle for Julia Roberts, eclipsing what could have been a
rewarding, grounded yarn with mere high-concept trappings: ``A
Civil Action'' with cleavage.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts' Erin can barely make ends meet, yet she somehow can
afford to buy a wide array of flashy if trashy clothes _ just the
kind daughters bemoan on TV talk shows with the theme ``My Mom
Dresses Too Sexy!''
</P>
<P>
   When Erin coerces Albert Finney into giving her a clerical job
in his law firm, she stumbles onto a coverup of contamination of a
community's water supply.
</P>
<P>
   The film then becomes a satisfying David vs. Goliath battle,
only in this case, David wears push-up bras and stiletto heels.
</P>
<P>
   For an alleged heroine, Erin neglects her kids woefully, often
leaving them in the hands of her neighbor and boyfriend, a gallant
biker played by Aaron Eckhart.
</P>
<P>
   Like Finney and most men in the movie, Eckhart's mission in life
seems to be paving the way for Roberts to have her way. Isn't that
what the audience wants?
</P>
<P>
   With her star wattage turned up several notches, Roberts
radiates even more than her usual charm. But that's undercut by an
allegedly cute feistiness, which in truth is coarse and abusive.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, she curses so often and so loudly in public _ including
courthouse halls _ that we wonder why she isn't arrested, or at
least accosted.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a movie, where life's real rules don't always apply,
and the real Erin is submerged beneath Roberts' star trip _ not to
mention an aggressive sexuality that's all about marketing and has
nothing to do with the little guy, decency or basic integrity. &QL; 
Grade: C- &QL; 
2000, R, Universal, CC, VHS $22.98, DVD $26.98
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cider House Rules''
</P>
<P>
   Spending big bucks, Miramax tried to bully Hollywood into making
this the best-picture Oscar winner for 1999. But aside from
supporting actor Michael Caine and screenwriter John Irving, no
cigar.
</P>
<P>
   Though Irving's source novel is worthy, the film is like a
politician: It makes endless heart-tugging pronouncements, but it
doesn't really say anything.
</P>
<P>
   Allegedly, it concerns the morality of abortions, which are
supplied by a crusty doctor (Caine) at a New England orphanage in
the '30s.
</P>
<P>
   The orphan he tabs as his successor (Tobey Maguire) is pro-life.
But the film's stance is as vague as Maguire's listless line
readings.
</P>
<P>
   For him, it's a coming-of-age tale enshrined in handsome
production design and schmaltzy oversell.
</P>
<P>
   The movie has meaningful moments, to be sure, but it doesn't add
up to a satisfying whole, lacking the courage to follow through on
convictions _ if it has any. &QL; 
Grade: C &QL; 
1999, PG-13, Miramax, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $32.99
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Also due this week: ``Titus,'' ``Planet of the Apes,'' ``The
Evolution,'' ``Leon,'' ``The Professional,'' ``The Defender,''
``Family Tree,'' ``Ghost Dog,'' ``Agnes Brown'' and ``A Map of the
World.''
</P>
<P>
   Due next week: ``Supernova,'' ``The Tigger Movie,''
``Simpatico'' and ``Beyond the Mat.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Loaded with laughs
</P>
<P>
   If you've explored directors' commentary tracks on DVD, you know
how dull they can be.
</P>
<P>
   But hearing David Zucker's banter about his ``Naked Gun'' films
is almost as funny as the police spoofs themselves.
</P>
<P>
   This week brings all three ``Gun'' movies to DVD: 1988's ``The
Naked Gun: From the Files of Police Squad!,'' 1991's ``The Naked
Gun 2 1/2: The Smell of Fear'' and 1994's ``Naked Gun 33 1/3: The
Final Insult.''
</P>
<P>
   Each costs a suggested $29.99.
</P>
<P>
   Zucker co-wrote and directed the first two, and co-wrote and
co-produced the third. He recorded commentaries for all three,
flanked by other creators.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had fun,'' Zucker said. ``We sat on sofas with mikes in
front of a screen, and everything we saw brought back memories of
stories behind the scenes.''
</P>
<P>
   More memories returned when Zucker saw the horror spoof ``Scary
Movie,'' which used the same style as his own off-the-wall hits.
</P>
<P>
   But he doesn't claim credit. Instead, he traces the roots for
such films back to 1974's ``The Groove Tube'' (available on VHS and
DVD).
</P>
<P>
   Filled with nudity, drug use and unmentionables, that wild
parody of television was created by Ken Shapiro, who has now faded
into obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Groove Tube'' evolved from humor sketches Shapiro taped on
early home-video equipment and displayed, ``underground''-style, in
loft apartments around New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Zucker, brother Jerry and Jim Abrahams were inspired to create a
similar Kentucky Fried Theater in their home of Madison, Wis. It,
too, spawned a movie after they moved to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ```Kentucky Fried Movie' is far more known than `The Groove
Tube,' but that's where we got our inspiration,'' Zucker said.
``Ken led the way. We followed him every step.''
</P>
<P>
   The group's big breakthrough with 1980's ``Airplane!'' (due on
DVD Oct. 24), followed by the ``Naked Gun`` trilogy.
</P>
<P>
   But Zucker hasn't forgotten where it all began.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the '60s counter-culture humor crystallized in Ken's
movie,'' said Zucker, who feels ``The Groove Tube'' spawned two
genres.
</P>
<P>
   ``One was that whole tradition of `Saturday Night Live' sketches
(Chevy Chase appeared in `The Groove Tube'), and the other was
films like `Kentucky Fried Movie,' `Airplane!,' `Naked Gun' and
beyond.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Groove Tube'' pushed the limits of an R rating, much like
``Scary Movie'' today.
</P>
<P>
   Not so lucky was Zucker's ``BASEketball,'' a 1998 sports parody
he wrote and directed, starring Trey Parker and Matt Stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got an R, which rated us out of our audience,'' he said.
``I understand Matt's and Trey's frustration with these censors.''
(Their ``South Park'' film, finally an R, first got an NC-17.)
</P>
<P>
   Zucker is now working on a new parody: ``FBI Man 2000.'' Unlike
his ``Naked Gun'' films, which turned dramatic actor Leslie Nielsen
into a straight-faced hoot, it will star a true comedian.
</P>
<P>
   He's also devising a remake of 1964's ``Santa Claus Conquers the
Martians,'' in which Pia Zadora, at age 10, made her film debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``She isn't acting anymore,'' he said, ``but I'm sure we can
coax her out of retirement to be in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Beatlemania
</P>
<P>
   MPI has reissued four Fab Four films as ``The Beatles: The
Ultimate DVD Collection.''
</P>
<P>
   The discs are ``Help!,'' ``Magical Mystery Tour,'' ``The First
U.S. Visit'' and ``You Can't Do That: The Making of `A Hard Day's
Night.''' The set costs a suggested $79.98.
</P>
<P>
   The last two are especially gear (translation: great), but the
Beatles feature ``A Hard Day's Night'' is no longer available. MPI
lost the rights to make way for a theatrical reissue.
</P>
<P>
   But MPI is trying to gain rights to two Beatles documentaries:
``Let It Be'' and ``The Making of `Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club
Band.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yellow Submarine'' also is available _ from MGM, for $19.98 on
tape and $29.98 on disc.
</P>
<P>
   XXXENDOFSTORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
