<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3364 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-CVN-YOUNG-VOTERS-HNS &LR;      08-16 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-YOUNG-VOTERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A HIP GORE REACHES OUT TO VITAL VOTING BLOC: YOUNGSTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LARA JAKES  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was, like, so not a place for a political gig.
</P>
<P>
   The scene Tuesday was a dark music club in West Hollywood where
heads adorned with nose rings bobbed and bare midriffs swayed to
the free rhythm-and-blues warm-up act.
</P>
<P>
   The headliner, though prepped to talk politics to her young
audience, was no less hip. Blond and willowy like Britney, yet
worldly and savvy at age 27, Karenna Gore Schiff made her way
across the stage at the House of Blues in her latest attempt to
tear through the veil of cynicism shrouding the nation's largest
voting bloc _ 18- to 30-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our generation has been dismissed as being too self-involved
to be bothered with public life,'' Schiff, flanked by her younger
sister, Kristin Gore, told the crowd of several hundred 20-, 30-
and even a few 40-somethings at the Sunset Boulevard club.
</P>
<P>
   ``We volunteer and join political organizations more than the
famously idealistic boomers do,'' Schiff said. ``But it is also
true that there are a lot of young people who are completely turned
off to politics. And I've even felt that personally. Although I
come from a very political family, I've felt the flaws of our
modern political culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Schiff, who lives on Manhattan's Upper East Side and is one of
the higher-profile New Yorkers at the 2000 Democratic National
Convention, of course is an advocate of her father, Vice President
Al Gore. But she also is one of the most prominent young faces in
today's political arena _ a scene, observers note, still dominated
by older white men.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called Generations X and Y make up the largest age group
involved in elections, according to John Dervin of Youth Vote 2000,
which along with MTV's Choose or Lose campaign sponsored Tuesday's
event. Those voters outnumber the older baby boomers by an
estimated 10 million _ and could determine the election.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats do not have the monopoly on fresh young faces to help
reach out to those voters. Schiff's Republican counterpart is
George P. Bush, the 24-year-old nephew of Republican presidential
nominee George W. Bush, whose smoldering good looks earned him the
distinction of being one of America's most eligible bachelors.
</P>
<P>
   But the nation's youngest voters are also among the most
unreliable on Election Day. Only one-third of registered voters age
18 to 24 cast a ballot in the 1996 presidential election, compared
with half in 1972. For this reason, young activists like Schiff and
George P. Bush are trying to recruit their peers in what could be a
tight presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, Schiff touched on the issues of abortion rights,
pollution, Social Security and the economy. ``If the economy tanks,
it is those of us at the start of our careers or at the bottom of
the ladder who have the most to lose,'' she said. Her message
appeared to resonate with the crowd _ most of it highly educated
and already politically astute.
</P>
<P>
   Even in New York state, Schiff has faced voters of all ages who
are relatively uninspired by politics this year _ and by her
father. A recent poll showed Gore leading Bush by only five points
in New York _ where any Democratic candidate should enjoy the
upside of a 5-3 voter-enrollment ratio against Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only explanation is that people have not been able to
connect to him,'' said David Kaufmann, a 40-year-old history
professor at the University of Southern California who moved from
New York City just last week. ``That `Clinton fatigue' kind of set
up this lack of enthusiasm for Gore _ what's being called `Gore
fatigue.' I think as people see him, as they get a second look,
they'll say, `Yes, he's a political hack, but he's also a good
man.' That's what these two, what Kristin and Karenna can do for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Schiff, a mother of a 1-year-old son named Wyatt, put law school
on the back burner to advise her father's campaign this year. She
runs Gore.net, reaching out to young voters and Gore supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Convincing members of her generation to become more politically
active is not easy now, nor has it been for the last several
decades. ``But this year, in election 2000,'' she said Tuesday,
``we must buck that trend.''
</P>
</TEXT>
