<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3366 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-CVN-DEMS-RELIGION-HNS     08-16 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-DEMS-RELIGION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DEMOCRATS TEST NEW TERRITORY, MIXING POLITICS AND FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Forty years after John F. Kennedy came to this
city to accept his party's nomination, pledging allegiance to
America and not the Catholic pope, Democratic leaders are embracing
religion with chutzpah.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional fear against the mixing of church and state is
giving way to the more politically subtle _ if not cautious and
calculated _ use of religious imagery.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an indication that voters are eager for a candidate
who shows an appreciation of values, who recognizes the importance
of religion in public life,'' said the Rev. C. Welton Gaddy, a
Louisiana pastor and head of the Interfaith Alliance, a national
nonpartisan group of more than 50 religious organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can convey that kind of message without falling into
the pit of marrying religious conviction and partisan politics,
that is to be celebrated, because it is a maturing stance.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the choice of Sen. Joseph Lieberman of
Connecticut for the national ticket has worried some Democrats
about whether anti-Semitism will derail Vice President Al Gore in a
close election. Lieberman is an Orthodox Jew who became the party's
nominee for vice president Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of Lieberman has exposed other immaturities about
American political life and religion:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Dallas chapter president of the NAACP was asked to resign
last week after he said blacks ``need to be suspicious of any kind
of partnerships between the Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Nation of Islam leader Louis Farrakhan inaccurately said last
week that Lieberman has dual citizenship with Israel and questioned
``the ties that any Jewish person would have to the state of
Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Farrakhan's words echoed a 40-year-old concern from when
Kennedy, a Catholic, was running for president, saying at the 1960
Los Angeles convention that he would ``reject any kind of religious
pressure'' from the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that no American, considering the really critical
issues facing this country,'' Kennedy said, ``will waste his
franchise by voting either for me or against me solely on account
of my religious affiliation. It is not relevant.''
</P>
<P>
   But four decades later, religion clearly is relevant to
Lieberman and Gore, as well as Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the
Republican presidential nominee. Gore, a Baptist, and Bush, a
Methodist, consider themselves born-again Christians, and faith has
infused their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Now the mixture of politics and religion is low-key, less
strident, less threatening.
</P>
<P>
   Religious conservatives such as Gary Bauer and Alan Keyes, who
both sought the Republican presidential nomination, were hidden
during the Republican National Convention as it strove for a more
inclusive image. The image of religion in politics expressed by
conservative Pat Robertson railing against abortion and
homosexuality is giving way to religion as a personal guide.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his favorite philosopher was Jesus Christ, and he
consistently has advocated a Calvinistic blending of bootstraps and
religious faith in helping the poor. His ``compassionate
conservative'' philosophy emphasizes church and government
cooperation to help poor people.
</P>
<P>
   After he served in Vietnam, Gore entered the Vanderbilt
University divinity school but dropped out to become a newspaper
reporter in Tennessee. He still quotes the theologians he studied
at Vanderbilt in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   In the 2000 campaign, Gore consistently has talked about
religion, although he tends to take broad stances that avoid
ideological fights when he speaks of religion; the Bible, for
example, condemns homosexuality but Gore is more interested in
larger biblical themes of love and acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the Monica Lewinsky scandal and his opinion of
President Clinton, Gore often says: ``I'm taught in my religious
tradition to hate the sin and love the sinner.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, who invoked God a dozen times when he accepted Gore's
offer last week to join the Democratic ticket, is adept at steering
his religious talk to mild, nonspecific, uplifting messages rather
than a strident morality lesson that could turn away voters.
</P>
<P>
   An Aug. 7 Gallup poll among 667 registered voters found the vast
majority _ 88 percent _ said it makes no difference to them that
Lieberman is Jewish. Seven percent said it makes them feel more
favorably toward him, and 4 percent said less favorably.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish Americans said it seemed Gore picked Lieberman not
because his faith somehow will dictate administration policy, but
because faith guides the Connecticut senator's personal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to recognize that Gore didn't go out looking
for some Jew,'' said Rabbi Marvin Hier, founder and director of the
Simon Wiesenthal Center in Los Angeles. ``He selected Joe Lieberman
because, in addition to going to a synagogue, he is a man of great
integrity. That's why it's really a moment of pride.''
</P>
<P>
   And blacks said they saw the Lieberman pick as a victory for
civil rights more than a religious conversion within the party. In
his convention speech Tuesday night, the Rev. Jesse Jackson said
Gore ``has brought the sons and daughters of slaves and slave
masters together with the sons and daughters of Holocaust
survivors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a minority, too, so we love that,'' said Toye Moses,
president of the African-American Democratic Club of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   This clearly is the subject Democrats feel most comfortable
talking about: civil rights and minorities. But for some Democrats
at the convention, the new political religion from Gore and
Lieberman is something clearly new and uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Wallis, author of ``The Soul of Politics'' and founder of a
Call for Renewal, a national coalition of churches and community
groups, said a Democrat at the convention came up to him and said
all the talk of family values and sexual ethics made him nervous,
because ``that's not traditional Democratic real estate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's right, then the Democrats have a problem,'' said
Wallis, who believes Democrats need to accept a new political
ideology that includes family and faith, mixed with government
programs that work.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we identify with one particular partisan solution, that's
the problem,'' Wallis said. ``But to keep the heat on the moral
imperative, that's the solution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 1327EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000816.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3367 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-CVN-INTERN-HNS &LR;      08-16 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-INTERN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MOTHER, DAUGHTER TEAM UP TO BOOST DEMOCRATS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PEGGY FIKAC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When Rendi Norwood ran for student body president
at Texas High in Texarkana, she displayed a bit more political
savvy than most teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   She was the first to ever ask for a student voter registration
list, called her fellow students at night seeking their support,
and was at school at 6 a.m. the first day candidates could put up
signs to make sure she snagged the best spot.
</P>
<P>
   She won.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't hurt that her mother, Molly Beth Malcolm, is the
chairwoman of the Texas Democratic Party. Both are attending the
Democratic National Convention this week in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Now a 20-year-old government and sociology major at the
University of Texas at Austin, Norwood helped with President
Clinton's visit to Los Angeles after a summer stint as a White
House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the Monica Lewinsky jokes. This mother-daughter team
has heard them all.
</P>
<P>
   ``People make jokes, but it's one of the top internships in the
nation, and it's really a thrill to be in the White House,''
Norwood said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a wonderful president, and regardless of anything
that's happened, the White House internship is a great program,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm, 45, said it is sad that Clinton's sexual affair with
another intern _ Lewinsky _ cast a shadow on the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It did tarnish what people thought, and of course, yes, every
time you'd say, `She's a White House intern,' people would roll
their eyes,'' Malcolm said.
</P>
<P>
   But she added, ``I want you to know that that was the most
fabulous experience that any young person could ever have ... I
watched her just take on so much maturity this summer from the
opportunity she had in that job.''
</P>
<P>
   Norwood worked in the White House political affairs office.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood stood at the back of a meeting room at a breakfast for
convention delegates from Texas and watched her mother hold forth
on Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard George Bush say `Don't mess with Texas' until I'm
sick and tired of hearing him say that,'' Malcolm told an
enthusiastic crowd. ``The Texas values that I learned were that
telling the truth is not always the popular thing to do, but it is
the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm has passed her priorities on to Norwood, who calls her
mother her best friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned a lot in politics from my mother, and she's been
a great role model. And not only a role model, but she's a great
mother,'' said Norwood, who uses her father's name.
</P>
<P>
   She said her mother always makes time for her, and laughed as
she recalled that high school race for student-body president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely learned a lot from watching her when I ran for
that,'' Norwood said.
</P>
<P>
   But Norwood isn't planning a future as a politician. She plans
to go to law school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be wonderful to practice law for
underprivileged people, and if there's any way that I could afford
to do that, I would love to do that,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
