<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3371 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-DORM-DECOR17-COX     08-16 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DORM-DECOR17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Professional designers assist students in decorating a small
space
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The student: Danielle LeSure, a junior at Emory University
majoring in educational studies.
</P>
<P>
   Danielle's objective: ``I want a room that represents me and who
I am. I like the color purple and stuffed animals. I have about 15
in my dorm room.''
</P>
<P>
   Her advice to new students: ``Do something new and creative. I
wouldn't get a lot of shelves or storage containers. In my freshman
year, after I had taken exams, I had to take them all down. That
was not fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The designer: Amy Survant, home textile specialist for Rich's
department stores.
</P>
<P>
   Survant's solution:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  She made a section of the room a study area by placing a desk,
chair, phone and clock on one side of the room. A filing cabinet
was placed underneath the desk, making it accessible, yet out of
the way.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A butterfly chair was placed near the desk. This provides a
chair for company when you're studying or entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A mini-refrigerator, microwave and storage bin for snacks were
stacked on top of each other to save space. (Check school policies
to see which small appliances are allowed.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Monogrammed towels were placed near the door so that Danielle
can grab one on the way to the shower.
</P>
<P>
   Survant's tip: ``I would paint the entire room in magnetic
(colorless) paint. It's like a sealer. Then repaint on top of that
whatever color the school has designated. It makes the walls like
magnets, so you can stick mementos, magnetic picture frames,
posters and keepsakes. It makes the room fun and it doesn't hurt
anything when you move out.''
</P>
<P>
   The student: William HumphriesIII, a senior at Morehouse College
majoring in biology.
</P>
<P>
   William's objective: ``Space, comfort and function. I like
things I can just pick up, roll out or dump into a crate or box
when I'm ready to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   His advice to new students: ``Usually one side of the room is
better than the other, so get there early so you can claim it. If
you and your roommate can work together by buying things that
coordinate, it's cheaper. If you put carpet in the room, it seems
more like home. Just don't pick a light color, because it will be
brown by the end of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   The designer: Grant Breining, president of Renaissance Design
Group in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Breining's solution:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  He designed a room for the small fraction of students who
don't have a roommate. Breining replaced the standard issue
dormitory bed with a futon that folds out into a bed. (Check school
policies to see if dorm furniture can be removed. Another option is
to create a loftlike area by raising the bed off the floor and
making space for a futon underneath.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The room was divided into two spaces, one for studying and one
for entertaining. Breining put the stereo and television on
entertainment units. The computer equipment was placed in a corner
on a stand.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Plastic storage bins were mounted on each side of the window
to save floor space.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Modular storage cubes double as a nightstand and coffee table,
making the room look like a living room instead of a bedroom/study.
</P>
<P>
   Breining's tip: ``The most important thing to remember is to
move in and see what you need first. Don't buy everything before
you get there, because you could find that you have too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Eds: cutline information
</P>
<P>
   Plastic modular storage cube ($19.99). From the Container Store.
</P>
<P>
   Ridgewood audio stand with black steel finish and maple accents,
$49.99. From Kmart.
</P>
<P>
   Black metal futon with heavy twill cover, $179.99. From Kmart.
</P>
<P>
   Computer cart, $299. From the Container Store.
</P>
<P>
   The students: Jennie Bell, a senior at Agnes Scott College
majoring in English, and Kristin Haeger, a sophomore at Agnes Scott
who has not declared a major.
</P>
<P>
   Jennie and Kristin's objective: ``I picked some of the things
because they rolled. It makes things so much easier to move,'' said
Jennie. ``I also picked stuff that looked comfortable. Comfort is
key because you spend a lot of time in your room.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like tall stuff,'' Kristin said, ``because it utilizes the
space above your head.''
</P>
<P>
   Their advice to new students: Load up on chairs, ottomans and
pillows.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always need extra sitting space,'' advised Jennie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' added Kristin. ``In my freshman year I didn't have
anything to sit on. I got tired of eating on the floor all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The designer: Mary Mobley-Johnson, owner, MJA in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Mobley-Johnson's solution:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  She divided the room in half so that each girl could have her
own space. Then she used an area rug to make the room look warmer.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The sleeping area was separated from the study area by placing
the beds on either side of the wall at one end of the room. The
desks and computers are on the other end.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The arrangement provides more privacy for the sleeping area by
making the study area the first thing you see when you walk in the
room.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  By placing both desks at the same end of the room, one student
can study without disturbing a roommate who might be sleeping or
watching TV.
</P>
<P>
   Mobley-Johnson's tip: ``Don't spend a lot of money. There are
small things you can bring from home, like your aunt's old lamp or
your mother's old quilt, that can save you money and make it feel
like it reflects your own identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look for items that assemble by grooves, versus stuff you have
to screw. The stackable furniture is much more efficient, and you
don't have to worry about losing the screws when you move.''
</P>
<P>
   Alma E. Hill writes for the Altanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
