A3372 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-DORM17-COX     08-16 0252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DORM17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Students get dorm room decorating advice
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   At 12 feet by 15 feet, with an 8-foot ceiling, the average
dormitory room is about the size of a storage shed. When you add
two college students and a couple of carloads of personal
belongings, the room becomes more like a walk-in closet.
</P>
<P>
   Decorating can be a challenge, especially for people determined
to bring all the comforts of home. Take, for instance, the mother
of a former Emory University student.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mother was an interior decorator,'' recalls Joni Tyson,
Emory's assistant director of Residence Life who is responsible for
making dorm assignments.
</P>
<P>
   ``She pulled up the carpet, repainted the walls, brought in her
daughter's canopy bed and shoved the roommate's furniture up
against the wall. Luckily, we found the room before the halls
opened, but there were a lot of dropped jaws.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't have to be that way.
</P>
<P>
   With a little creativity and space-saving furnishings, you can
make a dorm room look cool and livable.
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate how it can be done, we had a staff artist draw a
typical dorm room. We then asked four students who have lived in
dorms to pick furnishings for the room. Next, we asked three design
experts to decorate the room using the artist's drawing and the
students' selections.
</P>
<P>
   Alma E. Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
