<HEADER>
A3373 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-DORM-FACTS17-COX     08-16 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DORM-FACTS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dorm facts
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Decorating a dorm room needn't cost your life's savings. Here's
how to spruce one up without spending a fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Buy a storage trunk. It can hold bulky items and off-season
clothes, as well as be used as an end table, coffee table or stereo
stand.
</P>
<P>
   Get a few plastic crates, boxes and stackable containers. They
provide extra storage and add to the decor when they coordinate
with the room's color scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Buy a clip-on lamp that can be moved from desk to bed.
</P>
<P>
   Purchase bedding and towels in like colors so they blend with
the decor and can be laundered in one load.
</P>
<P>
   Buy plants. They add life and color to a room.
</P>
<P>
   Use throw pillows, inflatable chairs and ottomans to provide
more seating.
</P>
<P>
   Shop thrift stores for inexpensive what-nots, lamps and pictures
that will give your room a unique style.
</P>
<P>
   Use wall hooks to hang pictures or make a valance for curtains.
</P>
<P>
   Make a desk both jazzy and functional by choosing file
organizers, shelves, pen cups and stackable drawers in bold colors.
</P>
<P>
   Find metal folding chairs that can be used when entertaining
friends. They don't take up much space when stored. Spruce them up
with bright enamel paint.
</P>
<P>
   Policies restricting what students can bring to a dormitory vary
by school. Here are some items you typically cannot have:
</P>
<P>
   Window air conditioners and space heaters.
</P>
<P>
   Strobe lights, black lights and halogen bulbs over 100 watts.
</P>
<P>
   Toaster ovens, hot plates, woks, deep fryers and crock pots.
(Some schools also prohibit microwaves.)
</P>
<P>
   Candles and incense.
</P>
<P>
   dorm facts
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  There are more than 32,600 beds at the 35 public colleges and
universities in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  There are three styles of dorms: traditional, which house two
to four students and have communal showers and restrooms;
apartments for two or more that have restrooms, living and cooking
areas; and suites, which may accommodate up to eight students and
have common living areas, kitchens and restrooms.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The average age of a residential building is 30. Some of the
newest dorms in the system are 4 years old at Georgia State
University. The oldest are 93 years old, at Abraham Baldwin
Agricultural College in Tifton.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A dorm typically comes with a desk, chair, ceiling light and
bed.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  All schools have some housing to accommodate students with
disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pets are typically prohibited. However, guide dogs for the
</P>
<P>
   visually impaired are allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Board of Regents,
</P>
<P>
   University System of Georgia
</P>
<P>
   on the web
</P>
<P>
   For more ideas about how to decorate a dorm room, check out
these Web sites:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.hgtv.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.gateway-va.com/colleges/dormtips
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.jsonline.com
</P>
<P>
   /homes/interior
</P>
<P>
   To shop for your dorm online:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.collegedepot
</P>
<P>
   .com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.target.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.lnthings.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www
</P>
<P>
   .bedbathandbeyond
</P>
<P>
   .com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.cominghome
</P>
<P>
   .com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.containerstore
</P>
<P>
   .com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
