<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIAMONDS AND OTHER GEMS . . . 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Picked-up pieces while remembering Babe Ruth and Elvis Presley,
who both died on Aug. 16 . . .
</P>
<P>
   --The new Fenway scapegoat is batting coach Jim Rice. The Sox
aren't hitting, so it must be somebody's fault. Rice makes himself
a target with his passive work ethic and poor communication skills.
The indefatigable Walter Hriniak was ripped here for working too
hard with the hitters. Now there's Rice doing little with a gang of
hitters who aren't selective and rarely make adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   --Jimmy Piersall, the Carl Everett of the '50s, is scheduled to
appear at a memorabilia show at the Ramada Inn in Woburn, Mass.
Saturday, noon-2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   --Jack Nicklaus and Tiger Woods are paired at the PGA
Championship in Louisville, Ky. Reminds me of Red Sox spring
training in 1960, when Ted Williams and Carl Yastrzemski were in
the same lineup. ``I played second base in those days, so we were
never in the same outfield,'' recalled Yaz. ``But I remember him
taking batting practice and yelling at himself.'' Williams retired
in 1960. Yastrzemski was a rookie in '61.
</P>
<P>
   --The Peter Gammons lookalike contest is Aug. 26 at LeLacheur
Park, home of the Spinners, in Lowell, Mass. Winner gets two air
tickets to anywhere in the United States. Twenty-dollar bills are
not eligible. Gammons this year is up for consideration for the
Baseball Hall of Fame. The man who reinvented the way his sport is
covered should be a lock.
</P>
<P>
   --What's the record for ex-Boston College players in one NBA
trade? Bill Curley, Howard Eisley, and Dana Barros are all part of
the proposed four-team, nine-player exchange. Jim O'Brien must be
proud.
</P>
<P>
   --I hate it when our readers write better than we do. One
intrepid Globe e-mailer wrote to ask if Sox infielder Mike Lansing
``is a product of some type of Mengele experiment designed to
create the most mediocre player in the history of baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   --More Neil Diamond at Fenway, please.
</P>
<P>
   --Manny ``It Wasn't My Stuff'' Alexander has been able to keep
his legal woes away from Fenway. It wasn't the same for infielder
Julio Valdez, who was cuffed in the clubhouse in full uniform a
couple of decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   --Hot Rod Williams will come in handy if the Celtics need a
representative for the Legends Game at All-Star time.
</P>
<P>
   --Former BC back Mike Cloud is expected to be Kansas City's top
rusher this year.
</P>
<P>
   --Speaking of running backs, that was some good move by the
Patriots letting Curtis Martin go all those years ago. Remember the
mantra: (itals)He's too slow to the hole . . . you can always get
another running back . . . it's better to have those draft
picks.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   --I know they are faster, but Olympic swim competition won't be
the same now that all the competitiors are wearing body suits.
</P>
<P>
   --The carnivorous Cincinnati media have finally gotten to Ken
Griffey Jr. He told foxsports.com, ``It's kind of tough when you've
got the media on you and you come to the ballpark and you have fans
yelling things that are off the wall.'' Poor Junior. Thought he
wanted to play closer to the home folk.
</P>
<P>
   --Rich Garces's first major league appearance was 10 years ago
when he hurled for the Twins. He fanned the first batter he faced,
George Brett.
</P>
<P>
   --Anybody else get the feeling that soon it'll be just Venus and
Serena Williams with nobody left to beat in women's tennis?
</P>
<P>
   --Is there a better story than homeboys Rico Brogna and Lou
Merloni leading the Sox to victory on the first night home after a
grueling trip? Brogna is a high school basketball coach in the
offseason, and it's only a matter of time before he's rumored to be
replacing Rick Pitino.
</P>
<P>
   --Do delegates arrive late and leave early to beat the traffic
when the convention is held in Los Angeles?
</P>
<P>
   --Ted, Yaz, and Bobby Doerr all plan to be on hand when the Sox
retire Carlton Fisk's No. 27 Sept. 4.
</P>
<P>
   --It's nice that the Sox protect pitchers by not letting them
use the slide step, but the thought of Boston facing any running
team in the playoffs is frightening. Imagine what Kenny Lofton or
(still) Rickey Henderson would do to the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   --John Williams was in the same draft class as Len Bias.
</P>
<P>
   --The Yankees _ with Roger Clemens and Jose Canseco _ are here
Sept. 8. Selling to the highest bidder, Roger says he'll go into
Cooperstown as a Yankee.
</P>
<P>
   --In ``I Am, I Said,'' Neil Diamond writes, ``No one heard at
all, not even the chair.'' Maybe the dumbest lyric in history.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail
at dshaughnessy(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
