<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3375 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-GARDENING-LIFE17-COX     08-16 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-LIFE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Think you're in charge? Look around, think again
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MCCAYSVILLE _ Living in a cabin surrounded by woods _ that is,
living with nature _ is in some ways like living with cats: You
quickly learn you're not in charge.
</P>
<P>
   During the last three growing seasons here on the ridge, I've
found that it's a waste of good time and energy to try making my
garden pristine. I've staked out a small space around the cabin and
declared it a weed-free zone _ and grown comfortable appreciating
what shows up on the rest of the land. The scrawny trees and hearty
brush that fell under saws and shears have, of course, returned
with renewed vigor. I fought them back for a while, then
discovered, as longtime mountain people knew I would, that mine was
a futile battle. So, the ``weeds'' pop up, grow tall and often
surprise in their flowering beauty. I prune saplings that shoot
from stumps when they get waist high, and I call them shrubs.
</P>
<P>
   I know who's not in charge here.
</P>
<P>
   The gardener certainly is not. Neither, however, are the weeds
and grass invaders and the trees that refuse to stay down. Fact is,
the insects rule.
</P>
<P>
   That is never truer than during the Bug Days of summer when all
of us, plants and humans and other animals, too, have been weakened
by drought and heat. When everything slows down like a (remember?)
45 rpm record played at 33 revolutions, the insects buzz and chomp
along, unfazed.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit No. 1: the amazing Japanese beetle. I've always known
these little iridescent flying bugs were at the top of many
gardeners' enemies list (years ago a friend described them with a
mix of hate and envy as ``living the perfect life; all they do is
eat and (make love)''). Before I got to know them intimately, I
thought these pests feasted and frolicked only on roses. I have
learned, alas, that their appetites range all over the garden. My
crape myrtle, for instance, opens only a few of its
watermelon-colored flowers before the beetles light into it,
feasting on blossoms yet to be. And beetles do not live by flowers
alone, finding the leaves of Yoshino cherry trees particularly
appetizing.
</P>
<P>
   When the temperatures reach August heights, I confine my
gardening mostly to appreciating (whatever the beetles and their
insect brethren leave unmunched). That, however, is easier said
than done.
</P>
<P>
   The good bugs always welcome company, of course _ butterflies
lending movement to the garden, the pest-eating ladybugs,
bumblebees that make you laugh as they shake stems when landing on
flowers. And, at, say, 7 o'clock in the morning, when the mountain
air is cool and even crisp, a stroll through the garden can be had
with pleasure. After that, however, it's a lot more dicey. After
that, the wasps nesting under the eaves are awake, along with
swarming, orifice-seeking gnats (it's not only in South Georgia
that you must learn to talk and blow bugs at the same time). Also,
particularly on still evenings, the mosquitoes come biting, though
I could have sworn we used to be mosquito-less up here on the
oft-breezy Blue Ridge. Always, unfortunately, there are the
redbugs, ticks and fleas.
</P>
<P>
   Given the challenges of outdoor life, it's not surprising that
many people spend so much time inside this time of year. And with
winter in such short supply, it's just about always this time of
year.
</P>
<P>
   How pesty are some insects? Just the other day, I saw a
hummingbird, a species that seems to thrive on ill-tempered combat
(at least with other hummers), get run away from the feeder by a
wasp.
</P>
<P>
   One day, just when I was beginning to think it was un-fun to be
outdoors, there appeared two insects that mesmerized. First came a
winged, pointy-beaked creature that looks like a dwarf hummingbird,
but actually is a hummingbird moth. Later came something even more
exotic.
</P>
<P>
   On wings big and gossamer, this brownish-gray, crabby-legged,
primeval-looking critter lit on the porch railing one sultry
afternoon, taking up residence for what must have been half an
hour, displaying itself without moving as much as a leg or an
antenna. What a dazzling treat, made better by its unfrenetic,
nonthreatening demeanor, contrasting dramatically with the tiny
bugs. While I'd never seen anything like it, Fannin County native
James Abernathy didn't hesitate when he saw the photograph: ``Oh,
that's a stonefly.''
</P>
<P>
   James added that this type stonefly (what a fly, several inches
long) is a creek-area breeder that preys on other insects.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be persuaded, perhaps, to take on a few Japanese
beetles? Combat the gnatty dread? Maybe scare straight a couple of
tyrannical city cats, named Vincent and Buuud?
</P>
<P>
   Lee May's column appears weekly in the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. E-mail him at leemay(at)att.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
