<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-ELS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERNIE ELS EAGER TO TASTE VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ You have a lot of time to think while flying
from South Africa to Hawaii, a journey that pushes you through
multiple time zones. ``The longest trip in the world,'' said Ernie
Els, who made that trek eight months ago en route to the Mercedes
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Given Els's world-class talents, the 1999 PGA Tour season hadn't
gone particularly well for him, and though it included a win at the
Nissan Open _ hence his berth in the Mercedes _ there had been too
many misses and four substandard performances in the majors,
including two missed cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Yet life was good, Els said to himself. His first child,
Samantha, was a daily reminder not to take his golf worries so
seriously that people would stop calling him The Big Easy. ``Relax,
have fun, and commit yourself to a great season in 2000,'' Els said
to himself.
</P>
<P>
   After four pure rounds of golf at Kapalua on Maui, Els had what
he had hoped for _ a 16-under-par effort that dazzled the field.
Except for Tiger Woods, that is. Woods also shot 16 under, then won
in a scintillating playoff.
</P>
<P>
   Els handled defeat in a manner that fit his personality _ openly
and graciously, even more amazing given the fact that he had struck
the ball better than Woods all four days. ``I feel so sorry for
Ernie,'' said Woods's coach, Butch Harmon. ``He played better than
Tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Els didn't know it at the time, it would be a scenario
that played out several more times in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At 6 feet 3 inches and 210 pounds, the 30-year-old Els, a gentle
man with a pleasant smile and a swing that is the envy of even his
fiercest competitors, is a dominating presence in the world of
professional golf. He owns two US Open titles, homes in his native
South Africa, England, and Orlando, and the respect of virtually
any person who has come in touch with him.
</P>
<P>
   So why is he bothered these days?
</P>
<P>
   Well, he isn't actually, though it's not any fun being treated
as if he's the Washington Generals playing foil to Woods's Harlem
Globetrotters routine. On the eve of the 82d PGA Championship at
Valhalla Golf Club, whatever small piece of the spotlight not being
devoted to Woods is being given to Els _ for reasons that intersect
at the major championships. Woods has a chance to win his third of
the year, while Els could finish second for a fourth time.
</P>
<P>
   After Tuesday's practice round, Els said, ``When you're playing
a guy who is playing out of this world . . .''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't complete the thought. He didn't have to. It is, after
all, a topic he has had to address time after time this year,
because Woods has been that dominating and Els has been the guy
coming in second _ five times in all, four of them to Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Els followed Hawaii with a stretch of golf that many would
accept, though poor finishes left a sour taste in his mouth. He was
in the hunt at the Masters but shot a third-round 74 and finished
second, three shots behind Vijay Singh. The next week at the MCI
Classic, he faded with a 74, lost his third-round lead, and settled
for third.
</P>
<P>
   A month later at the Memorial, Els posted a scorching 64 at
Muirfield Village in Dublin, Ohio, to reach the 36-hole mark at 7
under. Pretty good, except Woods shot 63 that day and was at 10
under. When they went out together in Round 3, Els relished the
chance to again go head-to-head, but things did not go well.
</P>
<P>
   After an even-par 72 that looked like an 82 compared with
Woods's 65, Els was beleaguered. He now trailed by a staggering 10
shots, and while reporters tried to tactfully ask him the painful
question, Els saved them the trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys, it's over,'' he said, waving off the suggestion of a
dramatic comeback. ``The guy is awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Els closed with a 65 that gave him the consolation prize _
second place, five shots behind Woods _ and plenty of practice for
what would come at the US Open and British Open, when the anguish
intensified.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're 15 shots behind (as he was to Woods), it's hard to
say you're second,'' said Els at Pebble Beach. A month later, Els
again shared second, eight strokes behind Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Never once has Els ducked the issue of Woods, and his praise for
the 24-year-old has always been direct and lavish. But when Els
opened the British Open with a sparkling 6-under 66, he faced a
question right away about Woods, who had shot 67.
</P>
<P>
   ``Geez,'' said Els, as close to being flustered as you'll ever
see him. ``Guys, I just shot 66. If you want to talk about Tiger,
call him.''
</P>
<P>
   No need, because Woods was soon back playing the lead role and
answering questions asked only of a winner.
</P>
<P>
   Els? He knows his role well, even if it's not what he auditioned
for. He has become so accustomed to it that when he broke through a
few weeks ago for his first win on the PGA Tour in more than a
year, Els could read the reporters' minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``For once I didn't mess it up or I didn't finish second,'' he
said after holding on at the International in Castle Rock, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the inevitable observation that Woods was not in the
field. Els fielded it gracefully: ``I think it would have been very
tough for him to beat me this week.''
</P>
<P>
   That win, however, was two weeks ago, and Els is back facing the
same questions about Woods. Again, he shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to play hard,'' he said. ``You don't have any
control over what he does. I've finished second three times in the
majors, and you have to feel pretty good about that. If I don't win
this week, I've still had a pretty good year, so I've got to look
at the positive side.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
