<SLUG> BC-DEM-RDP-650&AMP;ADD-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS PLACE LIEBERMAN IN THE SPOTLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This story will be updated by 9 p.m. EDT with a version
written by Richard L. Berke. Additional updates will add quotes
from late speeches. Complete text of the speeches will be available
at the New York Times on the Web: www.nytimes.com 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Democratic Party on Wednesday prepared to
celebrate the selection of Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman as Vice
President Al Gore's vice-presidential running mate, while assuring
the party's diverse constituencies that, despite a platform aimed
at the center to draw voters from outside the Democratic fold, the
party will not ignore the concerns of more liberal Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, whom Gore named as his choice last week, arrived in
Los Angeles early Tuesday from St. Louis, where he had been
campaigning with Gore. Lieberman promptly met with about 300 black
delegates who had expressed unease over his past criticism of
racial preference programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was for affirmative action, am for affirmative action and
will be for affirmative action,'' he told the delegates. He also
promised to defer to Gore on school vouchers, another volatile
issue on which the presidential candidate is more liberal.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut senator, who has expressed centrist positions on
those issues along with military spending and Social Security, was
likely to continue reassuring the party's more liberal base when he
addressed the full convention Wednesday evening. Some core
Democrats, union members and black voters among them, have been
worried that Gore is taking them for granted in moving toward the
political center to attract independents and liberal Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the convention approved a platform that promises to
make Social Security safe and secure; invest more in education and
training teachers; provide affordable healthcare for children and a
patient's bill of rights; strengthen Medicare; and protect the
environment. With both political parties criticized for taking vast
amounts of money from special interests to wage their campaigns,
the platform also declares that as president, Gore will submit a
campaign reform bill to Congress and fight until the bill becomes
law.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, following Lieberman's speech _ which could
be as critical of the Republicans as it is supportive of Gore _ the
4,402 delegates are scheduled to take up the formal business of
nominating Gore as the Democratic Party candidate for president.
</P>
<P>
   His onetime rival for the nomination, former Sen. Bill Bradley
of New Jersey, told the convention delegates on Tuesday: ``It's
absolutely essential that we get behind Al Gore. I support him. I
endorse him. I'll work hard for his victory.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Electing Al Gore and Joe Lieberman is the right thing to do
for our country,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's nomination was locked up in March by an unbroken string
of victories in the early state primaries, but a minority of
delegates came to the convention committed to Bradley and are now
free to support Gore. With the outcome assured, the nomination
process will be a colorful spectacle in which the delegates go
through the motions of being polled state by state on their
support.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Gore's daughter, Karenna Gore Schiff, a new law school graduate
who is one of his closest campaign advisers, has been asked to take
the podium and introduce the roll call that nominates her father
for president.
</P>
<P>
   The roll call has been structured so that the delegations from
Tennessee and Connecticut, the respective home states of Gore and
Lieberman, will declare the votes that give Gore the majority he
needs for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will speak on Thursday, the final night of the four-day
convention, when he accepts his party's nomination in an address
intended to rally uncommitted voters as well as the party faithful.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president and his wife, Tipper, are scheduled to arrive
in Los Angeles Wednesday afternoon and to be greeted at Burbank
airport by a contingent of California supporters.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lieberman distanced himself from other Democrats in 1998 when he
rose in the Senate to criticize the behavior of President Clinton
in the Monica Lewinsky scandal. His selection as Gore's running
mate was seen in part as an effort to inoculate Gore against
Republican charges that he is part of a morally tainted Clinton
administration. Lieberman is the first Jew to run for the vice
presidency on a major party ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Other prominent Democrats scheduled to address the convention
Wednesday include John Sweeney, the president of the AFL-CIO; Gov.
Gray Davis of California; the House minority leader, Rep. Richard
Gephardt of Missouri; and the television actor Jimmy Smits.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who spoke on Monday night to an enthusiastic audience
of convention delegates, met Gore on Tuesday in Monroe, Mich., to
pass the political torch and endorse his vice president's
candidacy. ``He is the right person to be the first president of
the 21st century,'' Clinton told the crowd.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
