<HEADLINE>
MR. FUSSY RELUCTANTLY FACES VACATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vacations are always a difficult time for Mr. Fussy. He really
doesn't want to go anywhere. Life at home is fine by him. And if he
is forced to travel, it mustn't be by airplane, and it mustn't be
to relax. Not for nothing does Mr. Fussy have a shirt monogrammed
with the words ``High on Stress.''
</P>
<P>
   The 300-pound writer G.K. Chesterton, in analyzing the three
kinds of leisure (it occurs to Mr. Fussy that the English have as
many words for rest and relaxation as the Eskimos have for snow),
concluded that the ``most rare and precious'' form of leisure ``is
being allowed to do nothing.'' But Mr. Fussy doesn't want to do
nothing. Like Mr. Chesterton, who trumpeted the glories of
inactivity while churning out over 100books, Mr. Fussy wants to
keep himself occupied.
</P>
<P>
   There are,of course,socially approved pastimes while on
vacation. For instance, you can spend more time with your children.
But Mr. Fussy already spends lots of time with his children, so
much that he can name upward of 60 Pokemon monsters (Snorlax!), to
say nothing of the three wizardry schools featured in Harry Potter
(Beauxbatons! Durmstrang! Hogwarts!). His children are begging him
to go off to work and get out of their hair.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, one can spend a vacation visiting new countries and
broadening one's horizons. But isn't that why God invented the
Discovery Channel?
</P>
<P>
   Many of Mr. Fussy's friends claim to spend their vacations
communing ``with a huge stack of books,'' which means one of
several things:
</P>
<P>
   1. Mr. Fussy's friends are very pompous.
</P>
<P>
   2. Mr. Fussy's friends are liars.
</P>
<P>
   3. Mr. Fussy's friends are speed readers who vacation
exclusively in rainy climes.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Fussy took two books on his most recent vacation and
finished them both. They were: ``Back Bay,'' William Martin's
wonderful page turner about three centuries of nefarious doings in
the blue-blood Pratt family, and Stanley Booth's recently reissued
``The True Adventures of the Rolling Stones,'' which a friend
assured him was the definite account of sex, drugs, and rock 'n'
roll in the 20th century. Well, yes.
</P>
<P>
   (Special bonus book excerpt: Mick Jagger to Stanley Booth, 1968
_ ``I mean, we're so OLD. . . . I've got to think about the future,
because obviously I can't do this forever.'')
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Fussy could not imagine vacation anywhere except for Canada.
You don't have to take a plane to get there, and the natives speak
two of the great languages of the civilized world _ the language of
Shakespeare, and the language of love. It's an interesting country,
but not distractingly so. For instance, a visit to the Potato
Museum in O'Leary, Prince Edward Island, is purely optional. Mr.
Fussy speaks from experience.
</P>
<P>
   Canada has plenty of rain to facilitate book-reading, and,of
course, it is a very neat and fussy place. Here is a not untypical
Canadian advisory for tourists journeying to ``Shipping News''-land
by ferry: ``Vehicles traveling to Newfoundland must have no more
than 3/4 of a tank of gas.'' Nominal purpose: to prevent gasoline
spills in high seas. Do they check your gas gauge? A staffer
assured me they are not that fussy.. . .
</P>
<P>
   After several decades of vacationing in Canada, Mr. Fussy has
grown attached to the place, and will miss it when it is gone. Its
imminent disappearance was recently predicted by Robert Kaplan in
his book, ``The Coming Anarchy.'' American territorial and cultural
hegemony will result in ``the peaceful dissolution of Canada,'' Mr.
Kaplan writes, not very convincingly. But Mr. Fussy doesn't like to
criticize people who have treated him graciously at parties, e.g.
Janet Langhart, wife of our poetasting Secretary of Defense, and
Mr. Kaplan fulfills this criterion.
</P>
<P>
   Once Canada is gone, Mr. Fussy will have nowhere to vacation.
It's conceivable that he could learn how to make triple-batter
onion rings in his kitchen, and engineer a mini-golf course in his
back yard. Perhaps ``Land of Giotto'' will be playing on the
Discovery Channel. Who needs anything more?
</P>
<P>
   (With gratitude and apologies to the late Roger Hargreaves,
creator of the wonderful children's book character Mr. Fussy.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Alex Beam's e-mail is beam(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 1337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
