<DOCNO> NYT20000816.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3387 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      08-16 1363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUPLE SHOULDN'T TAP HIGH-YIELD ASSETS UNTIL NECESSARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Q. We are about five years from retiring at age 59. We hope to
take as much income as possible from our assets, which we plan to
divide evenly between stocks and stock funds and cash and bonds.
But we would like the principal to keep up with inflation so we can
leave to our heirs the same value, if not more. You have often
suggested taking income from a GNMA or similar fund, yielding about
6.5 percent. What bothers me about that strategy is that due to
inflation the value of that side of the portfolio would erode in
the considerable number of years we will have in retirement. I
thought of taking the dividends from stocks and funds, and maybe
even the capital gains distributions, and then taking only 50
percent of the yield from the bond side of the portfolio,
reinvesting the balance. Do you perceive any holes in my plan?
</P>
<P>
   W.R., Hellertown, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   A. First off, you will draw less money from your assets if you
take half of the yield from the fixed-income side, plus dividends
from the equities and stock funds. If you average 6.5 percent on
your fixed-income portfolio, you would draw $22,750 there, plus
$14,000 from your stocks, presuming (and probably presuming quite
generously) an average 2 percent yield from your equity
investments. That would bring you a total of $36,750 in annual
supplemental income. That figure would rise if you took any capital
gains distributions, but that flow would be irregular, and
sometimes might represent a reduction in the principal value.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, taking that approach would mean you are drawing funds
both from the lower-earning, fixed-income portfolio and the
higher-earning stock accounts. In contrast, if you took all of the
yield from your fixed-income investments _ a maximum of about
$45,500 _ and left the stocks alone, all of the reinvestments would
go to the side of the portfolio that promises higher long-term
growth. In the end, the more money you leave in stocks, the higher
the long-term portfolio growth you can expect. Conversely, the more
money you withdraw from the stock accounts, the slower the
expectations of growth should be.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how I would arrange things. Begin by setting a
supplemental income stream you feel you need, presumably somewhere
between that low of $36,750 and the high of $45,500. If the amount
you need is less than the actual yield from your fixed-income
portfolio, you could invest the excess on the stock side.
Presumably, as time passes and as inflation erodes the value of
your income stream, you will be drawing more and more of the
fixed-income yield. Then, at some point, you will find that the
total yield is inadequate, and you will want to move more assets to
the fixed-income side. But in the meantime, you will have kept the
maximum amount of your assets on the side of the portfolio from
which you should expect the maximum growth.
</P>
<P>
   One further suggestion: If you can make the moves without
unpleasant tax consequences, you should arrange your portfolio so
the tax-deferred accounts not only contain just stocks, but also
your most aggressive stock positions. That is because you will not
be required to take withdrawals from these accounts for the first
11.5 years of your retirement, providing a lot of time for
tax-deferred growth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I work for a nonprofit organization and receive housing as
part of my job. My employer doesn't contribute to a retirement
plan. I also run a consulting business from which I earn $10,000 a
year, all of which I have been saving in balanced funds with an eye
toward buying my own housing. Next year, my employer will move the
403(b) account to Vanguard, which has a larger selection of funds
and lower fees. What Vanguard funds would you suggest I use? Should
I continue to use the fund in which I have my Roth IRA invested?
Where should I be investing the money from my consulting business
if I plan to buy a house within five years? Will I have sufficient
income to support myself in retirement if I continue saving at the
current rate?
</P>
<P>
   L.Y., Pittsfield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You might be able to go ahead with the home purchase, but it
strikes me as a bit foolish. To begin, let me spell out the
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   If you continue to save at current levels in the 403(b) and Roth
IRA accounts and realize 10 percent average annual market returns,
you would amass $932,390 over 16 years. That sounds impressive, but
it shrinks considerably when you consider inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose you decide you can live in retirement on 60 percent of
current earnings _ probably feasible only if you can look forward
to Social Security benefits. That would mean you would need your
savings to produce the equivalent of $33,000 in today's money. If
inflation averages 3.5 percent, it will take $57,221 to do the
trick. While there would, indeed, be enough to provide that income
stream initially, you would have very little remaining to protect
you against later inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Now let's suppose you add to your retirement savings both your
consulting income and the balance that has built up in the account
you have mentally earmarked for your home purchase. Your
accumulation at age 68 would then be $1,487,647, using the same
assumptions as above. This would not only support the target
lifestyle, but leave you with excess income _ which might then be
put toward a home.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the problem of building a sufficient nest egg for
retirement, there is another reason you might have second thoughts
about buying a home. If you abandon the free housing, it's unlikely
your employer will increase your salary enough to cover the costs
of the new place. So not only would your retirement savings be
accumulating too slowly, but your housing costs would increase,
probably dramatically, when you factor in real estate taxes,
maintenance, and insurance.
</P>
<P>
   To throw more cold water on this option: It would seem that if
you do not expect any significant retirement income from Social
Security, it probably would be a major mistake to go ahead with the
home purchase in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   OK, let's suppose you do anticipate Social Security income, and
you think I'm all wet. You go ahead with buying a home _ after all,
isn't owning your home the American dream? In that case, since you
set a five-year timeframe for this investment, I suggest you move
from the balanced funds into something much safer _ a short-term
bond fund at the most aggressive, but preferably CDs or
money-market funds. (The nation's highest rate on one-year CDs was
7.35 percent, and that looks very attractive to me if you decide to
go ahead with the plan to buy.) If you are going to use this money
within five years, even the relatively conservative balanced funds
are too aggressive as a savings vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if you decide to wait until retirement to buy
a home, you are investing the funds from your consulting business
too conservatively, and I would then switch from the balanced funds
to all-stock funds.
</P>
<P>
   As for how to invest your 403(b) money once the account is moved
to Vanguard, I would put 50 percent in Vanguard Index 500, and 12.5
percent each in Vanguard Mid-Cap Index, Vanguard Small-Cap Index,
Vanguard International European Equities Index, and Vanguard Health
Care.
</P>
<P>
   I do not, though, like Vanguard LifeStrategy growth fund for
your Roth IRA. Although this is the most aggressive of the
LifeStrategy group, take a careful look at what it holds. About 10
percent of its assets are in Vanguard's Total Bond Market Index
fund, and 25 percent-plus is in Vanguard Asset Allocation fund.
Asset Allocation, in turn, holds nearly 69 percent of its assets in
cash and bonds, meaning that between these two investments you have
nearly a quarter of this money in bonds or cash. That should put a
drag on long-term growth. I suggest you move this money either to
Vanguard's Index 500 or to its US Growth fund.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
