<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BROWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS PUTTING RECEIVERS IN MOTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ For eight years, he got to play alongside
someone he genuinely liked and respected, and now, as is often the
case in the cold world of the NFL, Troy Brown advances to No. 2
receiver for the first time in his pro career at the expense of his
best friend, Vincent Brisby.
</P>
<P>
   Roommates in their younger years with the Patriots, Brown and
Brisby (along with Drew Bledsoe and Todd Rucci) have had the most
seniority on the Patriots. Whenever there is a chipping away at the
veteran alliance _ as there was when Brisby was cut Monday _ there
is sadness among the inner circle, just as there was when Sam Gash,
Dave Wohlabaugh, Todd Collins, and Ben Coates were jettisoned for
reasons that the Patriots explained with cents rather than sense.
</P>
<P>
   One thing remains very clear in this organization: There's no
room for sentimentality.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a good friend of mine,'' said Brown. ``It's sad, we've
been together for eight years, but I'm sure he'll be someplace
soon. He's a good receiver and a professional guy.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Brown will be out of his trademark ``slot''
spot, where he made his mark. At times, he'll still line up there,
especially when Tony Simmons, the other beneficiary of Brisby's
departure, is on the field. But the Patriots feel having Brown on
the field all the time is better than having Brisby there some of
the time. Brown will join Terry Glenn as a starter, which means the
Patriots will go small at receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not too much has changed for me,'' said Brown. ``I just have
to go out and make plays. We have to shuffle some guys around, but
now we'll have Tony and Terry and Chris (Calloway) coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he was ``a little surprised'' by the move, given that
Brisby had worked so often with the first team. He said he spoke to
Brisby Monday night and wished him well.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bill Belichick said it was difficult to say goodbye to
someone like Brisby, whom he called ``a very professional player.
``I wanted to be fair to Vincent,'' said Belichick. ``I didn't want
to release him at the end of camp. Hopefully this will give him a
chance to hook on with another team. He's worked hard and he
deserves that.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown doesn't think his new role will be a difficult adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done work on the outside,'' he said. ``I do that all the
time in practice. I know what it's like. It's not a total change
for us and I'll still be in the slot at times.''
</P>
<P>
   What might be different is his special teams work. He may still
return punts but relinquish kickoff returns to Kevin Faulk, J.R.
Redmond, and Antwan Harris. Belichick said he will monitor Brown's
playing time and may ``relieve him'' of some special teams duties.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who signed a five-year, $12.5 million deal in the
offseason (with a $2.5 million signing bonus), said, ``I'm sure he
expects a lot of good things from me. I like the opportunity to be
on the field more. I didn't know how they were going to do it; now
it's clear-cut. I still have to earn it.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan now is for Calloway, who was signed as a free agent
Monday, to take Brown's slot role. He's a similar receiver to
Brown. Calloway is not yet in football shape, having sat a long
time since being released by the Falcons over the winter. He said
the Patriots first called him about two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie (Weis) has a wide-open scheme,'' said Calloway. ``He
gets the ball to a lot of receivers, and Drew is a great
quarterback. The potential is there.''
</P>
<P>
   Calloway, an 11-year veteran, had his worst season last year
after signing a three-year deal with the Falcons. He said he
started off on the wrong foot when he suffered a high ankle sprain
in camp and then had various knee and groin injuries during the
season that limited him to six starts and 11 games in all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've enjoyed my career, and if nobody called I would have been
comfortable in any situation,'' said Calloway. ``I've been working
out, but you always have to get in football shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was frustrating as an athlete to know I had a decent year
the year previous (62 catches with the Giants). I just have to be
in better shape and stay injury-free.''
</P>
<P>
   Calloway is far from a lock to make the roster. He must be in
shape, and he must be better than Sean Morey, who can play special
teams, and Dane Looker, who would cost the Patriots a sixth-round
pick in the deal they made with the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the case every year with me,'' said Calloway. ``You
have to prove yourself all over again. When I look at other teams
and other players, I can contribute _ no doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons has been handed his best opportunity for playing time.
Brown likely won't be doing what Shawn Jefferson did last year _
basically running deep to draw coverage away from Glenn. Brown's
strength is catching the quick pass and then making something
happen. The job of ``decoy'' belongs to Simmons, who can outrun
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   After expressing his sadness over Brisby's departure, Simmons
said the move ``opened up another opportunity to get on the field.
Yeah, it is a show of confidence, but you don't want a show like
that. It can happen to anyone in the NFL. It was a surprise to all
of us. It's part of the deal and part of our job.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons said he'll likely have more responsibility on special
teams and as the third receiver. In his third season _ a time when
many players are made or broken _ Simmons has learned to take the
criticism and just move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't go into the past,'' said Simmons. ``People will look
at me in a certain way: `He's a disappointment, he slipped his
second year.' I can't make what people say about me valid. I didn't
have a bad year, I was just put in a different situation. I have
the confidence I can be on this team. I've shown positive things,
but that's just preseason. I don't feel any pressure. Now I know my
role more.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if it all comes together, the Patriots, who had little
depth at receiver to begin with, appear to have less now. On a team
that has many other pressing needs, they have spent a lot of time
on the receiver spot the past few days, deleting more than they've
added.
</P>
</TEXT>
