<HEADER>
A3394 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-16 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     EDUCATION DOESN'T ALWAYS MAKE OR BREAK A CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ What sort of an education should you get if you
want to influence the nation's financial markets? Study the
clarinet and saxophone at the Julliard School of Music, which is
what Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan did.
</P>
<P>
   In the tech world, though, you are better off majoring in
medieval history and philosophy at Stanford. Just like Carly
Fiorina, the chief executive of Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
   Career paths are like that sometimes, and they should be. There
is no such thing as picking the wrong major in college or choosing
the wrong company or career.
</P>
<P>
   If you are in a career funk, here three questions to ask
yourself that might tell you if anything is seriously wrong:
</P>
<P>
   _ Why am I here?
</P>
<P>
   Write a sentence describing exactly why you are in your
particular career. People choose careers for all sorts of reasons,
and some don't stand the test of time. Were you pressured by your
parents to run the family business or choose a particular major?
Did you drift into the career because nothing else sounded
appealing? Did an unplanned pregnancy cause you to take a quick-fix
career rather than something you really wanted?
</P>
<P>
   There is certainly nothing wrong with taking over the family
business or choosing the same career as one of your parents did, as
long as you are doing it with eyes open. But if you are pushed into
it, you can end up resenting your career.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes you make a wise choice, but then the job or career
changes over time. Just about every career has gotten more hectic
because of layoffs and the tight job market, but has your
fundamental source of enjoyment changed? Have you hit a plateau? Is
there a logical reason to believe the situation will get any better
_ or worse?
</P>
<P>
   Your options also change. Just as some careers will continue to
go downhill, other opportunities are rising. If you settled on a
career just because it seemed like the best opportunity at the
time, re-evaluate your options every five or 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Don't assume that you will have to sacrifice for years to make a
change. The Internet has made it easier to study at home, and some
technology jobs like Web page design don't demand a lot of formal
training to learn the basics.
</P>
<P>
   _ Why can't I leave now?
</P>
<P>
   People will stay in jobs for years or even decades out of a
sense of obligation to someone else. That can be a perfectly noble
thing to do, but it can also be an excuse for your own inertia.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech in San Francisco earlier this year, Mae Jemison
described how she felt a sense of obligation to stay with NASA in
the early 1990s because she was the only black female astronaut.
Eventually, though, she decided to move on, starting a project that
improves technology in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I have to get only one opportunity and have to keep it for
life?'' she said. No, she decided.
</P>
<P>
   There are all sorts of ways you can serve humanity without
suffering yourself. Make sure you have explored your options.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you want to stay in your unsatisfying but high-paying job
so your children can go to college. That's fine, as long as you
have discussed it with them. Maybe they would rather pay for
college themselves than have parents who are working all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you have practical reasons to stay. You want to wait
because you will be vested in the pension plan in another year.
Fine. But what are you doing now so you will be ready to move in a
year and a day?
</P>
<P>
   One of the easiest things to do is play the martyr, to say that
you can't make a change because of your kids or your parents or
even your clients. That certainly can be true, but none of those
people would want you to have a miserable life.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure those explanations and others _ such as being too
harried to do any job hunting _ aren't just rationalizations for
your own inertia. It's possible that deep down, you don't want to
move because your job is truly fulfilling and you have been taking
it for granted. It's also possible that deep down, you are just
plain lazy and don't want to admit it.
</P>
<P>
   You make the call.
</P>
<P>
   _ Am I good at what I do?
</P>
<P>
   Call this a hunch, but golf is probably a lot more fun if you
shoot in the 70s than in the 170s. It's true with careers, too.
</P>
<P>
   If your boss doesn't appreciate you and you can never land a
good job or promotion, at least consider the possibility that you
aren't very good at what you do. That is nothing to be ashamed of.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you have talent but have gotten into a vicious circle. You
feel unappreciated, so you stop trying, which makes your boss
appreciate you even less. That leaves you with three choices: Get
out of the circle, get out of the company, or get out of the
career.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you can always do nothing, which will allow you to do
to the impossible: You can be in a circle but still manage to paint
yourself into a corner.
</P>
<P>
   Be honest with yourself. Maybe you have given the career a good
shot and have gotten the best training you could, but you just
don't have the talent to succeed. That is nature's way of telling
you it is time to move on. Pay attention.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
