<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3396 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HOCKEY-SURVIVOR-2ND &LR;  &UR;      08-16 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOCKEY-SURVIVOR-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 (a and s coding)  
 HANOVER, Mass.: ... physical therapy.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Mel Glenn is a specialist in physical medicine who has
treated Gilpatrick since 1998. ``Any spinal cord injury is better
if it's incomplete, since all function is not lost,'' he says.
``However, it's extremely unusual to make dramatic improvement
years after the injury. John had no good reason to think he'd walk
again.''
</P>
<P>
   For Elaine and Allen Jones, the reality of John's condition took
quite a while to sink in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we'd get John a treadmill or something and he'd be
OK,'' says Elaine Jones. ``But you could tell John was really
scared those first few days. My rule was, if you came to see him in
the hospital, you'd better have a smile on your face.''
</P>
<P>
   In the hallway outside her son's room, she adds, ``I'd see his
friends walk out and burst into tears.''
</P>
<P>
   For the next year and a half, Gilpatrick could not scratch his
nose, sit up, or feed himself. In 1998, the Globe's Dan Shaughnessy
wrote a column highlighting the fact that while Roy had become a
celebrity of sorts, Gilpatrick, who had also been the beneficiary
of fund-raisers and other outpourings of public support, was
relatively unknown outside Hanover and Suffolk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a competition of celebrity,'' Gilpatrick commented
then. ``I know there are other people that go through the same
deal,'' he added, ``and it's a lot harder for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, when pressed, Gilpatrick admits to being discouraged
about his condition for the first three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had down moments that were tough to handle, sure,'' he says.
``But the more things I did to keep myself positive, in school or
with my friends, the better I did. You can't change (what happened
to) your body.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilpatrick returned to school, majoring in criminal justice
while taking a part-time class load. His professors accommodated
him with lecture tapes and class notes. A specialized computer
allowed Gilpatrick to write papers and communicate with the outside
world. This spring, in what friends assumed was the dramatic
highlight of The John Gilpatrick Story, he rolled onstage and
picked up his diploma.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gilpatrick underwent two years of treatment at the
Shepherd Center in Atlanta, a world-renowned facility for spinal
cord patients where Roy was also being treated. Gilpatrick's four
visits lasted from six weeks to four months each. Allen Jones took
an apartment nearby, and John's friends flew in for visits. The
work was arduous: Gilpatrick's body could not even be moved into a
sitting position.
</P>
<P>
   At group sessions, says Gilpatrick, ``they'd always give you the
worst-case scenario. And that's basically what I got.''
</P>
<P>
   Shepherd Center doctors later confirmed that Gilpatrick's
failure to make much progress in the first two years meant there
was little hope he ever would.
</P>
<P>
   The family made changes that reflected that bleak prognosis.
They built an addition to their home that included a wheelchair
ramp and bedroom suite with handicap-access bathroom for John. They
acquired Ice, who not only helped with tasks like opening the door
or taking off John's shoes but also provided companionship and
emotional support. Over time, Gilpatrick's friends began to sense a
degree of resignation setting in. John was putting on weight. He
was not working out as devotedly. Michael Murphy, one of
Gilpatrick's closest friends, says it affected all of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my own mind, I was coming to grips with the fact that my
best friend would never be the same,'' says Murphy. ``My goal was
to buy a house with a wheelchair ramp so we could hang out at my
place, not just his.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilpatrick wears a small gold cross around his neck. Ask him
about it, and he'll warn you that he's not particularly religious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a bad Christian,'' he says with a warm smile. ``Other
people prayed for me, but I never really did.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not exactly true, says Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started going over to John's house and reading the Bible
with him,'' he says. ``Here we were, two guys who'd been wild and
crazy at the age of 19, 20, and now at 25, 26, we're looking in the
Bible for answers. It wasn't about religion to us so much as
spirituality. But yes, it meant a lot to John. And me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, John Gilpatrick woke up one morning and felt a
burning sensation in his spine, indicating recovery of some nerve
sensation. He knew he was going to walk again.
</P>
<P>
   He did.
</P>
<P>
   Miracle, maybe. But don't pencil him in for next year's Boston
Marathon just yet. His heels are painfully sore after years of
inactivity. Three weeks ago marked the first time he moved his
right arm in 4 1/2 years. He can't feel anything in his left arm,
and he's a little heavier than his hockey-playing weight. Balancing
on uneven surfaces is like skating on a Min-Waxed marble floor. But
who's complaining?
</P>
<P>
   Nobody in the Gilpatrick household, certainly. And the way he
chose to show off to his pals was classic Gillie. One by one, he
walked back into their lives. Literally.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Brinkman works at the Norfolk County sheriff's office.
Gilpatrick called him up there a couple of weeks ago and told him
to meet him out front, in the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got out of the car and said, `Brink, I'm walking again,' ''
Brinkman recalls. ``Then he did a full circle and sat down in his
wheelchair. I got chills.''
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Jones says she can live with whatever lies in store.
</P>
<P>
   ``John feels somewhat guilty that he's walking and others in his
condition are not,'' she says. ``But he was given a gift, for
whatever reason. And he worked so hard to earn it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilpatrick, headed for Suffolk Law School this fall, says his
goals are to drive a car and get back on skates this winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he drives,'' growls his stepfather, ``it had better be a
Humvee.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Glenn won't predict how much bigger the miracle gets. But,
he says, alluding to Gilpatrick's growing self-sufficiency, ``the
one I feel worst for is the dog.''
</P>
</TEXT>
