<HEADER>
A3410 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-OCEAN-ROW-ART-BOS &LR;      08-16 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCEAN-ROW-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (a and s coding)  
 HE'S ROWING TO EXTREMES  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARNOLD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ESSEX, Mass. _ Tom Mailhot, who plans to race across the
Atlantic Ocean in a rowboat roughly the length of a large canoe,
was sanding the unfinished hull of his plywood craft the other
night when a moment of introspection stopped him.
</P>
<P>
   It should be pointed out that Mailhot, 40, does not stop easily.
</P>
<P>
   He has paddled kayaks through gales off Cape Horn, giant
whirlpools in the Bay of Funday, 30-foot curling seas in the
Bearing Straight. Mailhot expects next year's transatlantic race to
be so rough that he and his rowing partner, John Zeigler, 50, are
padding the boat's watertight sleeping cubby with foam to minimize
injury when waves spin them like a rinse cycle. They may also
install seat belts.
</P>
<P>
   But at this moment, Mailhot had been stilled by a one-word
question: Why?
</P>
<P>
   After a long pause, he answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do it because I'm a survivor. And when you're a survivor,
you keep the challenges coming.''
</P>
<P>
   No question about it _ this time, Mailot's got himself a
whopper.
</P>
<P>
   Mailhot, of Ipswich, and Zeigler from River Edge, N.J., are the
only Americans entered in a race that on Oct. 7, 2001, will launch
49 pairs of rowers 3,000 miles from Tenerife in the Canary Islands
off Africa's coast to Barbados in the Caribbean. They will race
identical rowboats constructed from kits the racers purchased from
the British race organizer.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Chay Blyth has struck again.
</P>
<P>
   Blyth is the former British Army sergeant who has made a
business of extreme adventure contests. He has sent fleets of
identical sailboats hurtling around the world ``the wrong way'' _
against the prevailing winds _ with crews that pay tens of
thousands of dollars to compete and get beaten up by Mother Nature.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Blyth, who 11 years earlier had rowed across the
Atlantic with a partner himself, sponsored the first transatlantic
rowing race. Thirty crews _ none from the United States _ started;
24 crews finished, their times at sea ranging from 41 to 100 days.
Although the first tropical storm hit the man-powered fleet several
days out of Tenerife, there were no serious injuries reported.
</P>
<P>
   The 2001 Ward Evans Atlantic Rowing Challenge (the British
sponsor, perhaps appropriately, sells insurance) will begin with 50
boats. Each one started as 200 laser-cut pieces of marine plywood
that competitors bought for $3,800 _ after they ponied up the
$19,000 entry fee. Glued together, the pieces resemble a
1,650-pound hot dog some 23 feet long and 6 feet wide.
</P>
<P>
   But the kits don't include required extras: two rowing stations,
each with seats on slides; a solar-powered desalinator to make sea
water drinkable; a host of emergency gear including beacons,
flares, life rafts, and radios; and enough food for each rower to
burn an estimated 8,000 calories _ three to four times the norm _
daily for 100 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We figure that by the time we've equipped and shipped our
boat, we'll be about $140,000 into this thing,'' said Mailhot, who
expects to launch the rowboat next month from the Essex
Shipbuilding Museum, which has donated a boat house for the
assembly. The project has been funded with private donations and
T-shirt sales on a Web site (www.usrowboys.com).
</P>
<P>
   Mailhot, who is single, is a designer and project manager for
Treehouse Design, a Rockport architectural firm. Zeigler, the
father of two teenagers, is a food wholesaler who described himself
during a telephone interview as coming off a marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose this race is a kind of mid-life crisis thing,'' said
Zeigler. ``It has adventure, some risk, but after all the time
we've put into the boat (an estimated 300 hours), I'm really
beginning to trust it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mailhot and Zeigler each have won numerous canoe, kayak, and
rowboat races, most recently as the team that swept the pack in the
21-mile Blackburn Challenge that circumnavigates Cape Ann. They
plan to row to Barbados in two-hour shifts, one man rowing, one man
sleeping, 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   After subtracting storage space aboard the yet-unnamed rowboat,
the men will share quarters roughly equivalent to the interior of a
compact car for perhaps two months _ maybe longer.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone have any pet peeves exacerbated by the other?
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask me when it's over,'' said Mailhot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
