 INJURED HOCKEY PLAYER JOHN GILPATRICK IS A MIRACLE WALKER  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOVER, Mass. _ This is John Gilpatrick's life now, a handful
of days after the former Suffolk University hockey player revealed
his remarkable comeback from a spinal cord injury that put him in a
wheelchair 4 1/2 years ago:
</P>
<P>
   At a therapy session at Spaulding Rehabilitation Hospital,
Gilpatrick wills his legs to stay upright as he negotiates a set of
floor cushions _ tentatively, like a surfer balancing on a steep
wave face. A physical therapist holds his hips while Gilpatrick
tries to remain vertical. Shiftng onto his back, he does knee bends
as his stepfather, Allan Jones, blinks back tears. Petrocino
suggests a water break.
</P>
<P>
   Although he cannot perspire on account of his injury _
Gilpatrick's brawny body lacks a working thermostat _ he refuses
the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no-break therapy,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   And this is another part of Gilpatrick's life, in the brief time
since the 27-year-old law student and assistant hockey coach
demonstrated to family and friends _ and skeptical doctors _ that
miracles do happen, especially if you work at them.
</P>
<P>
   A Fox Net Sports reporter stands a few feet away, saying that
what Gilpatrick faces today is ``more challenging than any college
hockey practice'' as the camera zeroes in on him. Dissatisfied with
his delivery, the reporter smooths his hair and signals for another
take. And then another.
</P>
<P>
   If you are John Gilpatrick, this is the product of four years of
hard work and blind faith. Knee bends one moment, a ``Today'' show
interview the next. Calls and e-mail pouring in from around the
country. Reporters showing up at rehab to do play-by-play.
</P>
<P>
   Al Michaels made the line ``Do you believe in miracles?'' a part
of hockey history, and now Gilpatrick is living it. He's the new
gold-medalist of feel-good: Christopher Reeve in the Super Bowl ad
in which he walks again through the magic of digital technology.
Only these special effects are real.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody could have scripted this. Nobody knows, either, how the
next act turns out. Yet everybody around him says that if anyone
was going to beat the odds, it would be Gillie.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, the chance to walk again was a matter of when, not
if,'' says Gilpatrick in an interview at the family home in
Hanover. ``Not a miracle, more like a long shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Jones, his mother, won't rule out the miracle scenario,
however. She remembers driving to Boston City Hospital the night of
John's injury, taking one look at the crowd of parents and players
outside in the waiting room emergency room, and expecting to be
told that her son was dead. Walk again? How long do they make long
shots, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   ``The line between optimism and denial, I stopped walking that a
long time ago,'' Jones confesses. ``John always felt optimistic,
but I gave up around the third year on his ever walking again. You
alter your life to be one way, that's all you can do. Our attitude
was, we're fine with this. He's doing well in school. He's got
great friends. He'll be all right.
</P>
<P>
   ``John never gave up,'' she repeats. ``I had. Did he sense that?
Probably. But John is, ah, unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They say lightning never strikes twice, but you could not prove
that by Gilpatrick's star-crossed hockey career.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, while playing goalie for Hanover High School,
Gilpatrick was blindsided by another player. He broke his neck and
sustained a severe concussion, losing feeling in both arms yet
miraculously (that word again) not suffering any permanent
paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   He was, however, hospitalized for two months and told he might
not _ indeed, probably should not _ play hockey again. It took four
operations to repair the damage, including one to implant a pair of
steel stabilizing hooks in his spine. Doctors at one point inserted
a central line and pump in his chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't watch, but John never even blinked when they opened
him up,'' says his stepfather, a retired policeman. ``He went to
his school prom with that central line in.''
</P>
<P>
   The injury devastated Gilpatrick even more because he'd been a
rink rat all his young life. Growing up in the heyday of the
suburban hockey boom of the 1970s, Gilpatrick started skating when
he was in preschool. By 6, he was playing organized hockey; by 11,
he was going off to specialized goalie camps. John's father, Jim
Gilpatrick, had been a star athlete at Arlington High. All four
sons _ John, the youngest, was a toddler when his parents divorced
_ loved sports, too, yet none was more dedicated than John.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was mostly the competition I loved,'' he reflects, sitting
in the family living room next to Ice, his Rottweiler that is
specially trained to assist quadriplegics. Scattered throughout the
house are trophies and photos and autographed NHL hockey jersies
commemorating Gilpatrick's bond with the hockey community, from the
pros to the peewees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always had that competitive mentality,'' he continues.
``My heroes were sports stars, hockey players. But not the flashy
skaters, you know. I like the blue-collar guys.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother, herself a hockey nut, remembers John eating supper
in the car every night during hockey season. ``He thought it was
normal for a kid to eat that way,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Brinkman grew up with Gilpatrick. As aggressive as John was
on the ice, says Brinkman, away from the game he was a popular,
low-key, unselfish sort of guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody liked him, not just the jocks,'' says Brinkman.
``Even after the first injury, John was always smiling, always
asking you how you were doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The first injury cost Gilpatrick a shot at big-time college
hockey, but there was no qustion in his mind that he would play
hockey again as soon as he was physically able. Taking up karate
even helped sharpen his reflexes once he resumed playing his senior
year.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly he was just a regular guy, those close to Gilpatrick say.
He worked after school for an electrical contracting firm, had no
steady girlfriend, and had to work hard to earn decent grades.
</P>
<P>
   He chose Suffolk and its Division 3 hockey program because he
was confident he could play there. Brian Horan, then the school's
assistant coach, never heard Gilpatrick talk about his
sophomore-year injury. To Horan, who would later hire Gilpatrick as
his assistant, he was a hard-working kid whom teammates and coaches
liked and admired. ``John played the game in his head before he
actually played it on the ice,'' says Horan.
</P>
<P>
   Gilpatrick's life was shattered once again on Jan. 25, 1996,
during a game at Boston University's Brown Arena. Three months
before, BU freshman Travis Roy had broken his neck in the same rink
during his very first college hockey game. With that tragedy still
fresh in the minds of hockey fans everywhere, Gilpatrick _ now
playing center for Suffolk _ took the ice. Midway through the third
period, he was skating full speed toward the goal when he and an
opponent collided. Gilpatrick hit the crossbar, his head snapping
back in a violent whiplash motion. He crumpled to the ice and
stayed there, motionless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked down and knew it was bad,'' says Horan, who ran to
the player's side and held his hand. ``I was just as scared as he
was. But in the ambulance on the way to the hospital he kept
reassuring me it would be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilpatrick sustained what is known as central cord syndrome _
not a severed cord but one injured severely enough to render his
arms and torso useless. Gilpatrick's legs still worked, but he had
no way to control utilize them _ a reality he faced daily during
years of physical therapy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
