<SLUG> BC-CELEBRITY-SISTERS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 THE SHAGGS: FAMOUS LONG AGO _ AND STILL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (a and e coding)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EPPING, N.H. _ If ever there was a group of artists caught
flat-footed by the arrival of fame, it is the Shaggs, who have
taken to holding their meetings with industry people at the Dunkin'
Donuts off Route 125 in Epping.
</P>
<P>
   They file in from the parking lot locked in discussion of a
broken gas gauge, ordinary small-town moms in shorts and tank tops.
It was here, not so long ago, that they met with an envoy from Tom
Cruise's division of Paramount, and not far from here that they
opted to refuse his pitch in favor of another studio's. The Wiggins
_ once shy, rural girls who played their strange pop music for
derisive locals _ have sold the film rights to their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Dot, Helen, and Betty Wiggin had walked away from the Shaggs
without a backward glance in 1975, when their father and fanatical
promoter, Austin, died. But while they retreated into private
lives, their albums were spreading among underground musicians as a
classic of staggering do-it-yourself discord. Then, last November,
for the first time, their world intersected with their fan base.
Venturing onto a New York stage with their hearts in their throats,
they faced a crowd of hipsters who knew their songs better than
they did. One fan, a man from Los Angeles, had art from their album
cover tattooed on his leg.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the sisters have had the strange experience of
getting to know their own cult following. And they are making a
serious effort to understand the appeal of their music.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the sincere part, and the honest _ at least that's what
they say, the sincere and the honest, and the family part,'' said
Dot Wiggin Semprini, 52, a mother of two and part-time housecleaner
whose recent musical career has been limited to a church handbell
choir.
</P>
<P>
   ``Didn't somebody say innocent, or something?'' said Betty
Wiggin Porter, 49, who works as a group manager in a kitchen
equipment warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the word I was looking for,'' said her sister.
``Innocent.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are some of the nicer words that have been used to
describe the Shaggs' music. When they recorded ``Philosophy of the
World'' in 1969, the three sisters had had relatively little
musical instruction and asked their father to put off recording
until they were ready, but Austin Wiggin insisted. The album that
resulted is dissonant, arrhythmic and jarring from start to finish
_ a surreal contrast to naive lyrics like these from ``Who Are
Parents?'': Parents are the ones who really care/ Who are parents?/
Parents are the ones who are always there.
</P>
<P>
   The listener gets the impression that the artists are not only
unschooled in the techniques of conventional pop music, but that
they have never been allowed to hear it. Over the years, reviewers
have called the album ``stunningly awful,'' ``uncivilized,'' and,
in the New York Times, ``the best worst rock album ever made.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, Village Voice critic Lester Bangs likened Dorothy's
guitar playing to ``14 pocket combs being run through a moose's
dorsal'' and Helen's drumming to ``a peg-leg stumbling through a
field of bald Uniroyals.''
</P>
<P>
   But to a network of musical explorers desperate to shake
conventional influences, the Wiggins' nerve-jangling quality was
like catnip. Kurt Cobain, the lead singer of Nirvana who committed
suicide in 1994, was said to have listened to ``Philosophy of the
World'' as a ritual every morning. Downtown filmmaker Harmony
Korine, best known for the film ``Kids,'' paid homage by naming
characters in ``Gummo'' after the Wiggin sisters. Breathless Web
sites devoted to the Shaggs have sprung up like mushrooms, praising
``the spastic magic in these grooves'' and saluting the sisters'
``pure desire and drive. No talent necessary . . . . This is what
punk is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   All this has caused some bafflement in Fremont, where the Shaggs
played through the early '70s. The girls' father, a textile worker,
had pulled them out of the local high school so they could focus on
their music, which he felt was destined to make them famous. Jeff
Landrock, who was a sound engineer at the Fleetwood Studio in
Revere, Mass., where they recorded their second album in 1975,
recalled the girls' frozen looks when their father brought them
into the studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of weird,'' he said. ``They didn't say anything.
There was zero personality. It kind of looked like they didn't want
to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Their primary venue was Fremont Town Hall, where the fire chief,
Dick Heselton, 54, used to guard their Saturday night concerts for
$5 a night. Heselton remembered their music as ``rotten . . . (but)
catchy at times'' and said he chose to stand guard outside. Dick
Maloof, 54, said he has never developed a taste for the music, but
has watched the ebb and flow of ``Shagg-mania'' for the 30 years
he's lived here.
</P>
<P>
   ``These fans, I don't think they're people from Fremont who are
lining up to see them,'' Maloof said. ``All I can understand is
there's something about the lyrics to the songs, people think
they're Bob Dylanish or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of this sense of mystery is shared by the former Shaggs
themselves, who so thoroughly walked away from pop music that until
last year, many of their friends didn't know they had ever played
instruments. A fourth sister, Rachel Wiggin (now Gould), who
occasionally joined her older sisters on bass, kept her distance
from the band when other high school students teased her about the
music. Fred Semprini, who married Dorothy Wiggin, used to badger
his wife to play her album, but she would not allow it on the
stereo while she was in the house.
</P>
<P>
   But the reissue of ``Philosophy of the World'' last year, urged
by Terry Adams, keyboardist for the band NRBQ, set off a chain of
events that culminated in a bidding war over the film rights to
their life stories. At Adams's urging, Semprini and Porter agreed
to get up on stage at the Bowery Ballroom in New York last
November, although Helen Wiggin Bickford, who suffers from
depression, was not able to join them. The sisters signed
autographs for upward of an hour that night, and since then have
made contacts with a line of famous rock musicians without knowing
precisely who they are.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Shaggs' most evangelical promoters, for instance, was
Frank Zappa, who called ``Philosophy of the World'' ``better than
the Beatles.'' In a recent interview, Semprini asked a reporter if
Zappa's music could be described as ``heavy metal,'' and racked her
brain for the name of a bass player who had befriended her.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's that band? RMB?'' she asked, and finally came up with
REM.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't he the one who helped me get onto that high stool?''
asked their mother, Annie Wiggin, 73. ``He just picked me up and
stuck me on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Semprini laughed. ``I didn't know REM,'' she said. ``But they
knew us.''
</P>
<P>
   And they are rapidly becoming familiar with the entertainment
business. Since a magazine article last year sparked interest from
the film industry, the sisters have bolstered their flanks with two
new lawyers, one a film and movie specialist and one a music lawyer
who is helping them trace the rights to songs they had long ago
forgotten about. Several months ago, they opted to sell the rights
to their life stories to Artisan Entertainment, an independent film
company specializing in edgy projects like the upcoming ``Blair
Witch 2: Book of Shadows'' and John Waters's ``Cecil B. DeMented.''
According to Artisan, production on the film will begin early next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Semprini said the sisters have not made any profit from the
revival of interest in them, and only stand to do so if the movie
plans are realized.
</P>
<P>
   But even if they are, artists like the Shaggs will never really
be part of the world that embraces them, said Irwin Chusit, who
showcased the band in his new book ``Songs in the Key of Z: The
Curious Universe of Outsider Music.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The nature of being an outsider is you're not really going to
change _ I don't mean this in a demeaning way, but kind of like the
Beverly Hillbillies,'' he said. ``If the Shaggs go to Hollywood
they could go to every A-list party in the Hills and meet David
Geffen and Stephen Spielberg, and they're still going to be
outsiders by nature . . . bless their hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, some have hesitated to bring the sisters into the
public eye because of that. In his book, Chusit recounts a visit to
a mid-1970s Shaggs concert by a Boston music executive who was
interested in arranging live performances or maybe a record deal.
When he arrived at Fremont Town Hall, Harry Palmer found locals
dancing in ``a clumsy, arrhythmic, `Night of the Living Dead' sort
of way,'' and approached Austin Wiggin with a delicate question:
Didn't he understand that there were people who were laughing at
the Shaggs? Finally, Palmer went home without making a deal,
convinced that promoting the Shaggs to the wider public would be
the worst kind of exploitation, since they ``didn't know they were
being ridiculed,'' Chusit wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But 30 years later, the adult Shaggs, who now live in Epping,
seem serene in the face of their detractors: Everyone is entitled
to their opinion, and the true artists all like the music, Semprini
said. Gould, 46, of Maine, who was embarrassed of the band during
her teen years, now says that people who don't like the music
``just don't take the time to understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Wiggin sisters know what their audience is
looking for, and it's not skill.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want us to be good. They want us to be like we were
on the record,'' said Semprini.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if they could possibly re-create that chaotic sound,
Porter said she supposed they could.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not any better,'' she said, with a tiny smile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
