<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Locate hard to find items
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having trouble finding a particular item? We'll try to help you
locate it. But because of the volume of mail, we cannot track down
every request. Readers whose queries are answered in the column
will receive a blue-and-cream canvas Buyer's Edge tote bag. Write
us at Buyer's Edge Find It,The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O.
Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302; e-mail us at buyersedge(at)ajc.com
(please include your name, the city you live in and daytime phone
number); or call 404-582-7642
</P>
<P>
   Q: In an article in the Food section, a recipe for cream puffs
used Stella D'oro's Anginetti cookies. Can you find these cookies
for me?
</P>
<P>
   _ Gerry Murphy, Buford, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   And another cookie request: Please advise me where I might find
those delicious Stella D'oro Anginetti cookies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Elsie Burroughs, Peachtree City, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another query: We are a group on a search for Stella D'oro
Anginetti cookies. We have a cream puff recipe that uses them.
</P>
<P>
   _ Janet Bentley, Roswell, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: The search for your Stella D'oro Anginetti cookies is over.
Metro Atlanta Publix stores (within a 30-mile area of Atlanta) are
stocking these sweet treats (a 5-ounce package is $1.79), which are
light, puffed, sugar-coated cookies used to make cream puffs and
profiteroles. (Recipes for these desserts are on the package.) In a
recent Food section, reader Erma Cavigliano of Hampton told how to
make the cream puffs. Stuff Stella D'oro Anginetti cookies with a
filling made of 1 cup stiff whipped cream, 3 ounces cream cheese
and an 8 1/2-ounce can of crushed pineapple, drained. Blend
ingredients on low speed of a mixer for 3 minutes. Then fill and
chill and enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for 8 3-ply cotton cord or twine in white or
natural. I have looked everywhere, including craft stores, and
would really like to buy a lartile Enterprises, 216 Main St.,
Whitesburg, GA (770-834-2094). It's available in a natural-colored
cotton for $5.32 per 270-foot tube or in a natural/beige cotton for
$5.32 in a 270-foot ball. Reader Davis plans to make a rug with her
cord. Other uses include making handbags, belts and plant hangers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for Lolli-Pups Dog Treats by Pet Life. Kmart
used to carry them. We have not had any luck finding them in pet
stores or on the Internet. Our dogs love them. Please help us to
locate them.
</P>
<P>
   _ Debbie Pienkowski,
</P>
<P>
   Newnan, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   And another request: I can't find the treat Lolli-Pups for my
little dog Sassy. She really loves them.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jewel Crews, Tucker, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: We sniffed around and found Fido's treats at the Petsmart
location at 3221 Peachtree Road N.E. (404-266-0402). Other Petsmart
stores also carry them. A 12-ounce bag is $1.79. These colorful,
crunchy snacks contain crude protein, fat and fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Last fall my wife and I visited Phoenix and had a fish taco
for the first time. We have since tried in vain to find a Mexican
restaurant in Atlanta that sells these. Can you please help. They
are delicious.
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Livingston, Decatur, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: Sounded fishy to us at first, but we did find your tacos of
choice at Taqueria Del Sol, 1200 Howell Mill Road N.W.
(404-352-5811). One taco is $1.95. These tasty treats are made from
a flour tortilla (certified kosher) that's filled with batter-fried
fish topped with poblano tartar sauce made with jalepenos,
poblanos, mayo and lemon juice. One of the restaurant reviewers at
the Atlanta Journal-Constitution called the tacos ``addictive.''
Owners Mike Klank and Eddie Hernandez also own Sundown Cafe on
Cheshire Bridge Road, where you can chow down on a fish taco as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We are avid bird watchers and feeders. We have used Pine
Haven birdseed from Kroger, and they love it. But the store no
longer carries it. Can you find it for us?
</P>
<P>
   _ Claire Johnson, Powder Springs, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   And another inquiry: Kroger stores used to carry Pine Haven, a
birdseed that was produced in Atlanta by RLM. I can find no
information about the product or its availability. Can you help?
</P>
<P>
   _ Cecil Hudson, Watkinsville, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: A little birdie told us where to find your Pine Haven seed.
It's available on the Internet at www.ibackyardbirds.com. Or call
404-255-0110 and order the seed. Three 7.5-pound polyester bags are
$20.97 plus postage. The current mix in Pine Haven contains black
oil sunflower, hulled sunflower, raw peanuts and safflower.
Atlantan Ron Miller, who developed this mixture, says, ``Do not
store birdseed inside your home for any length of time. Instead,
store in galvanized garbage cans in a utility room. Storing the
seed in a warm area over several months will cause moths to appear
in bird food.''
</P>
<P>
   _Contributing: Michelle C. Brooks
</P>
<P>
   Marylin Johnson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
