<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOOTER-FAD-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 RAZOR SCOOTS TO THE TOP OF THE LIST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget Pokemon and Beanie Babies. A fad that began in Japan and
swept California has finally reached the East Coast and could
become the best-selling toy of the year, retailers say.
</P>
<P>
   The source of this fad? Collapsible, foot-propelled scooters
that sell for $70 to $130.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just children who are gaga over them. With adults
buying the scooters, too, retailers are already racking up big
sales, bracing for December, and wondering whether such an
expensive item can also be a holiday smash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the hot toy of Christmas, only it's here in the
summer,'' said Robin Reibel, a vice president of Filene's.
</P>
<P>
   Sandie Paradiso, a buyer for Learning Express Inc., a chain
based in Ayer, said, ``Based on sales so far, I think it's going to
be the number-one item on kids' Christmas lists.''
</P>
<P>
   The scooter fad may be nearly as hot now as J.K. Rowling's
bestseller, ``Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest phenomenon since Beanie Babies,'' said
chief executive Robert Hammer of Hammer-Pac Inc., a New York-based
supplier of Razor-brand scooters.
</P>
<P>
   It would be remarkable for a $100 item to be a holiday hit. Past
big sellers such as Tickle-Me-Elmo and Furby sold for about $30. As
Reibel noted, a Razor Scooter isn't something that most folks can
buy ``for every nephew on their holiday gift list.''
</P>
<P>
   But given recent scooter sales and the fact that some experts
see a big holiday for luxury items, many retailers are betting that
scooters will remain hot for another five months.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to novelties, Hammer claims to be a go-to guy.
Mood rings turned his bottom line green in the 1970s, and he says
he had a nice run with ``bubble umbrellas.''
</P>
<P>
   But nothing compares to the Razor Scooter, he said. ``It just
blows out the doors.''
</P>
<P>
   Hammer said he grasped the megabuck magnitude of the phenomenon
around Father's Day, when Macy's ordered 150 Razors from him. A few
days later, the chain was back wanting 10,000 more, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Razor weighs in at a mere six pounds. Folded up, it can fit
into a knapsack. Deployed for street action, it can turn a
25-minute walk into a 10-minute scoot.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike skateboards or inline skates, the scooters _ there are
several brands besides the Razor _ little skill seems to be
required for basic operation, hence, its popularity with adults.
</P>
<P>
   From Tokyo to New York, there have been numerous sightings of
scooter commuters, folks who use Razors to travel the several
blocks between a subway stop and the office.
</P>
<P>
   The Razor Scooter has ``become an icon of the dot-com world,''
said Tony Farrell of the Sharper Image, a chain based in San
Francisco. ``It's not like a bike. You don't have to lug it and
lock it. And you can carry it to your desk.''
</P>
<P>
   Adults see scooters as a fun form of transportation; children
see them as toys. The result? Strong demand from many age groups.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharper Image says it was the first US retailer to spot the
scooter's potential, and it gives Razor much of the credit for its
whopping sales gain in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The chain first stocked a noncollapsible scooter in 1998. Early
sales were respectable but not remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, a collapsible Razor Scooter was added to the line.
Sales began to take off in the spring, first in Hawaii, then in
California. About six weeks ago, the scooter became the company's
best-selling item, Farrell said.
</P>
<P>
   The Razor may have a multinational pedigree. According to
Farrell, a company in Taiwan bought the Razor's German design and
now has it mass-produced in Chinese factories.
</P>
<P>
   Hammer thinks a line of accessories will keep the scooter fad
fresh. Coming are running lights, shoulder straps, shock absorbers,
colorful handlebar trims, and wheel treatments.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go to Harvard or Yale, you'll be able to customize your
scooter in your school colors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dartmouth green might work for M.E. Johnson, a professor who
studies the toy industry at Dartmouth's Tuck School of Business. He
says that toys that become holiday hits often show the first signs
of catching fire months ahead of time, often in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to build awareness,'' Johnson said. ``And some
scarcity helps. If it's readily available, it's not nearly as
exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   After studying Silicon Valley startups while on summer break,
Johnson says scooters have been embraced by dot-com executives.
``It's the kind of thing the boss buys and rides around the office,
and everybody hoots and hollers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While there might be some hooting and hollering over high
prices, the scooter's initial popularity with parents may help make
the Razor a holiday hit.
</P>
<P>
   Past crazes have dismayed some parents. Many toys tied to
television shows and movies have been derided as unwholesome. And
not every mom was comfortable with her 9-year-old putting Mighty
Morphin Power Rangers and Hulk Hogan action figures at the top of a
holiday wish list.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are parents who fret that such items as inline skates
and snowboards may be a hazard to a klutzy child.
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, few parents have voiced any concerns about
scooters, said Paradiso of Learning Express. And that's another
sign that this craze may have legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a raging fad,'' said Farrell of the Sharper Image.
``We expect it to be our number-one seller for the holidays.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
