<SLUG> BC-CLINICAL-TRIALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG TRIALS BRANCH FROM TEACHING HOSPITALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LIZ KOWALCZYK  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a survivor of two heart-bypass surgeries, Warren McCollester
regularly receives missives from Boston teaching hospitals asking
him to become a human research subject. McCollester, a busy
retiree, can't be bothered and throws the letters into what he
politely calls ``circular file 13.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the family doctor he's known for 25 years out in rural
North Dartmouth, Mass. asked him the same question recently, he
signed right up.
</P>
<P>
   Now, suddenly, he's enrolled in a clinical trial on the front
lines of a gown-to-town experiment by the country's top teaching
hospitals. In an effort to expand their research operations,
hospitals in US cities are moving leading-edge trials testing new
drugs out to doctors' offices in the suburbs, on rural roads, or
simply on the way home from Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   Partners HealthCare, which includes Massachusetts General
Hospital and Brigham and Women's Hospital in Boston, is investing
$500,000 over four years to transform community doctors into
part-time researchers. Teaching hospitals in New York City,
Pittsburgh and Rochester, N.Y., are making similar investments.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching hospitals say they want to improve relationships
between academic and community physicians, who have long kept their
distance. But they also are aiming to gain access to thousands of
potential trial participants, a key selling point if they are to
win back $400 billion in research money lost in the past decade to
private industry.
</P>
<P>
   The shift to the suburbs could be a boon for patients, who will
be told about experimental treatments for heart disease,
depression, and diabetes during their regular office check-ups and
can enroll in those trials closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   But in cities where the research shift has been underway for one
to two years, doctors say training inexperienced researchers has
been far more difficult than expected and has raised ethical
questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much more involved than we ever imagined,'' said Dr.
Cynthia McGuire Dunn, director of the clinical research institute
at the University of Rochester. ``There is a misperception among
doctors out there that doing clinical trials is either an easy way
to get into research or an easy way to earn money. It's neither of
those.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn said she's also struggling with the ``reality that doctors
who ask their patients to participate in studies are blurring the
line between researcher and caregiver. The thing volunteers lose
sight of is that trials evaluate how groups respond. They're not
about what's best for that patient.''
</P>
<P>
   To some community doctors, clinical trials are not new. The
companies that oversee trials for pharmaceutical and biotechnology
firms have for several years paid private physicians to recruit
their patients. The companies promise speed and access to large
numbers of volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, teaching hospitals, which once conducted 80 percent
of all clinical trials paid for by industry, now claim just 40
percent of those trials. Ken Getz, a spokesman for Centerwatch, a
publishing company that monitors trials, said the shift has cost
hospitals $400 billion over the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've lost tremendous market share,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, there is early evidence that their attempts to
become more business-like is working: This is the first year in a
decade that academic medical centers reported an increase in
dollars coming from private industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doing a lot of things their competition is doing,'' he
said. ``They've already got thought leaders and greater access to
patients. If they can get their act together and better manage the
business side, and review contracts and protocols faster, they may
again be one of the best places for pharmaceutical companies to run
research.''
</P>
<P>
   Partners began its program _ called Partners Research and
Education Program _ a year ago to cement the organization's bonds
with the community doctors in its network. So far, they've signed
up 50 community doctors, who've enrolled 70 patients in six trials.
</P>
<P>
   Partners said it's trying to avoid the ethical problems that
have plagued its for-profit competitors, who have been criticized
for paying doctors large sums for each patient they enroll _ even
if the patient is not appropriate for the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Instead Partners pays its physician researchers a fee for each
individual test or exam they perform on a volunteer _ a fee that's
25 to 50 percent higher than what an insurance company would pay
for the same procedure on a regular patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our sites aren't geared to be factories,'' said Dr. Marc
Pfeffer, a cardiologist at Brigham &AMP; Women's Hospital and medical
director of PREP. ``Our objective is not to be the highest
enrolling center, but to export some of the excitement to doctors
who are not in the hospital. If we do it well, and we can move
people through the research programs safely, sure, that will give
us a leg up.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the first trials Massachusetts General Hospital floated
to community doctors was one comparing the anti-depression
blockbuster Prozac to St. John's Wort and to a placebo. It's $1
million funding comes from the German herbal company that's the
leading maker of St. John's Wort.
</P>
<P>
   The trial requires 180 patients with major depressive disorder,
but after an entire year Massachusetts General researchers had
recruited only 65 volunteers. With a good economy driving down the
number of uninsured, bad publicity about Prozac, and competition
from private trial management companies, the hospital was having
trouble finding willing participants. So in June, it opened the
trial to doctors in eight suburban offices.
</P>
<P>
   The primary-care doctors approach their patients about the
study, and if they are willing to participate and meet the
requirements, an Massachusetts General psychiatrist conducts a
telephone interview. Participants are seen weekly and then every
other week by their regular doctor, who monitors and records their
depression level and any side effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The life of a primary-care physician these days is kind of
rugged,'' said Dr. Jerrold Rosenbaum, chief of psychiatry at
Massachusetts General. ``They move from patient to patient to
patient. It's grueling. Many of them have had frustrated academic
aspirations. This is good for self-esteem and for staying fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Diane London, an internist in Natick, Mass. working on the
depression trial, said it's enabling her to provide better care to
her patients. ``The battery of psychiatric tests we're giving is
not something I would normally do in my practice,'' she said.
``This gives me a chance to delve deeper into a field.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Brian Schwartz, an internist and cardiologist in Natick and
a PREP investigator, said he felt he ``needed to do something
besides grind out patients every day.'' But he said he enrolls in
trials only patients for whom ``I feel I have done everything I can
for them with standard treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   It's crucial for physician-investigators to consider what's best
for the patient first, program directors said, because some
patients will enroll in clinical trials just because they trust
their long-time doctor.
</P>
<P>
   McCollester, 76, said that he was in no way pressured by his
physician, Dr. Alex Altschuller, to enroll in a study of a new
heart drug. Doctors are testing whether the drug, trandalopril,
already on the market for high blood pressure, will reduce heart
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   But having his doctor of 25 years ask added ``a personal touch''
that made him take the request more seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was also intrigued by the fact that he was trying to go out
into smaller towns to find participants, not just the big Boston
hospitals,'' McCollester said. ``The more diversity we get, the
more meaningful the results are going to be to the overall
population.''
</P>
<P>
   While the goal is clear, reaching it is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn said researchers at the University of Rochester complained
when she offered trials to community physicians first. Now she
gives the in-town doctors 48 hours to decide whether to participate
in a study before recruiting community physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, she's trying to decide whether investigators should
tell their patients how much they're earning from a trial.
Rochester pays doctors a per-patient fee, ranging from $500 to
$15,000, depending on the complexity of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Duke University has found that certain studies just don't work
out in the community. For example, trials testing drugs for the
flu, sinusitis, or other acute conditions require the hospital's
research coordinators to drop what they're doing and drive to the
doctor's office to interview the patient immediately _ a speedy
response that is not always possible. Duke, like Partners, sends
coordinators to doctors' offices to enroll patients and do the
paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Leahey, director of clinical trials at
Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center in New York City, said
academic medical centers must solve these problems _ even if it
means losing money in the short term. The medical center has
invested $3 million in his program to turn suburban doctors into
investigators _ and has yet to make any of it back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to bring research back where it belongs, to the
nonprofit fold, to where patient safety is more important than
stock dividends,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 1356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
