<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLVER'S DURST OUTBURST; HIP LIST IN REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a guy who might have spent his life asking the seemingly
immortal question, ``Paper or plastic?,'' Fred Durst sure is one
ticked-off dude. You'd think a self-described ``redneck'' who now
hangs with Playboy playmates and makes millions singing ``Break
Stuff'' would spend more time thanking his lucky stars than
swinging at his detractors. But there's Durst, lead singer of
rock-rap band Limp Bizkit, emptying a bellyful of bile in the
current issue of Revolver. While he's certainly combative _ Trent
Reznor, Courtney Love, and Lars ``I Hate Napster'' Ulrich shouldn't
expect any Christmas cards this year _ Durst also comes across as a
rube who relishes his role as spokesguy for the unspecific
frustrations of teenage Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch shoppers. Describing
Limp Bizkit's place in the world, Durst tells writer Matt Diehl
that his band is ``part of a movement that is helping blur the
lines between rock and hip-hop, which, in turn, will pave the road
for generations to come.'' No arguing with him there. But Durst's
ego runs amok when Diehl asks him about why the press seems to hate
him. Durst makes a cringe-inducing comparison between his band and
Martin Luther King (yes, that Martin Luther King) in that King
``came out of the crowd and said, `I'm speaking for you guys _ I'm
one of you.' So many people were there and feeling him, but at the
same time everyone hated him.'' As I recall, King did what he did
so his four children could be judged not by the color of their
skin, but by the content of their character; Durst did it all for
the nookie.
</P>
<P>
   In the same issue, Christopher Scapelliti takes a fascinating
look at Pete Townsend's unfinished rock opera, ``Lifehouse.'' Back
in 1971, Townsend wanted to out-Tommy his first rock opera,
``Tommy,'' but his obsession to create a career-defining work led
him to a breakdown and the brink of suicide. Though it was
bittersweet for Townsend, from the ashes of ``Lifehouse'' came the
Who's great ``Who's Next.'' By the way, after only a few issues,
Revolver is shaping up to be a pretty cool music magazine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of new magazines, there's Revolution, which fancies
itself as ``the new music manifesto'' _ it says so right on the
cover. That's new music, as in anything that isn't straight-ahead
rock. Revolution is dedicated to the head-boppin', hip-shakin' fool
in us all, especially those who spend their lives looking for the
perfect beat. To wit, there's this cover story: ``The 50 Albums
That Killed Rock, and Got Us Dancing.'' (Betcha thought all those
lists had faded with the millennium madness, didn't you?) As with
any list, there's much to squabble about _ if you're gonna pick a
Donna Summer album, then it should be ``I Remember Yesterday,''
whose classic ``I Feel Love'' is a template of electronic music,
not ``Once Upon a Time.'' But what makes the list fun is that its
creators know their stuff. So while you have the expected (Fatboy
Slim, Pet Shop Boys, Air), hip-hop, which created the DJ culture so
vital to today's dance music, is proudly represented by Run-DMC,
Beastie Boys, A Tribe Called Quest, Public Enemy, and Eric B. &AMP;
Rakim. Yes, kids, once upon a time there was hip-hop you could
actually dance to.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ah, there's track star Marion Jones on the cover of Women's
Sports &AMP; Fitness looking better than you ever will, no matter how
many stomach crunches you do, and how many desserts you don't. In
this issue on all things Olympian, Sally Jenkins looks at
controversy magnet Bela Karolyi, who coached the 1996 US women's
gymnasts to its first team gold. For all his successes, Karolyi is
considered by many to be a strict authoritarian who demands too
much physically and psychologically of his athletes. Mary Lou
Retton, whom Karolyi coached to a gold medal in 1984, recalls him
chiding her with, ``Meddy Loo, is no good what you eat. Makes you
fat. You should only eat air.'' But she also defends Karolyi. ``Is
he strict? Yeah. Does he have a demanding work ethic? Of course.
But you know that going in. He creates champions. You go to him to
come home with a medal.'' That's why Karolyi, who had retired from
elite coaching, will again lead the women's gymnastics team next
month in Sydney. Whatever his problems _ and anyone who tells an
athlete in a sport rife with eating disorders to ``only eat air''
has some problems _ he produces winners. Before Karolyi, US women
gymnasts had won just a single medal; since 1981 when Karolyi
joined the program, they've won 18. And if Karolyi can again spin
his particular magic into Olympic gold, no one will much care what
methods he used to get there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
