<HEADER>
A3428 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-BODIES-BOS &LR;      08-16 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BODIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFLECTING ON HUMAN SPIRIT AMID LIFE'S LOSSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
BODIES IN MOTION AND AT REST 
On Metaphor and Mortality 
By Thomas Lynch 
Norton, 276 pp., illustrated, $23.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are moments in this wonderful, wise, and witty book that
are the literary equivalent of blows to the stomach _ one is left
gasping for air from words that expose unvarnished, sometimes
painful truths. The heartache of love unraveling, the grief of
watching undertakers remove a dead father from his home, or the
agony of failing to rescue a son.
</P>
<P>
   In eloquent and lyrical prose, Thomas Lynch _ poet, essayist,
and funeral director of Milford, Mich. _ probes the losses we
suffer and the fortitude of the human soul that allows us to climb
out of the deepest well of despair.
</P>
<P>
   But this collection of essays is not just a rumination on the
grim moments of our lives. Lynch roams far afield, writing
passionately on the debt we owe Eve; the hated family cat that
simply would not die; and the coverage of John F. Kennedy Jr.'s
death. Ultimately, ``Bodies in Motion and at Rest'' is a meditation
on the human condition on the threshold of a new millennium, an age
punctuated by immense wealth, dazzling technology, intractable
poverty, and horrific violence.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all this, Lynch astutely observes, ``The facts of life and
death remain the same. We live and die, we love and grieve, we
breed and disappear. And between these existential gravities, we
search for meaning, save our memories, leave a record for those who
will remember us.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes these essays so powerful is that Lynch is unafraid to
admit to his own frailties and failures _ his divorce, his struggle
with liquor. And while we find it easy to deny and deceive, it is,
in the end, the truth that offers the best hope for redemption.
``The truth, even when it hurts, has a healing in it, better than
fiction or fantasy,'' Lynch notes.
</P>
<P>
   So it was one morning at the kitchen table, as a hungover Lynch
prepared breakfast for his three children, that he finally
recognized the damage alcohol had done to him and his family. ``I'm
slamming the apples and cookies in with the bologna sandwiches and
cursing my fates and barking out orders and wondering what a guy
has to do for a drink around here when I see my darling boy who is
nine in this memory sitting at the counter with his bowl of Froot
Loops and orange juice in his blue shirt and the look in his eyes
as he's looking at me is fear, godhelpus, and he is afraid of me,
of my anger and of my fear. I didn't know if I was an alcoholic.
But I knew that I didn't want to see that fear of me again in the
eyes of any of my children.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynch eventually joined Alcoholics Anonymous and ``in time I
went from dry to sober.'' But because life doesn't furnish tidy,
happy endings, Lynch must grapple with the fact that his son is
also sliding into alcoholism. As Lynch sadly describes, few things
are more devastating than being unable to save one's children from
self-destruction. Lynch finds an adolescent treatment center in
Cleveland; the son says he'll kill himself first. ``I said he was
killing himself already. . . . I said if he killed himself I would
miss him terribly, I would never forget him and always love him and
I'd hate to outlive him but I'd survive. And I'd call someone
before I'd drink about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of his shrewder essays, Lynch dissects our media-fed
hunger to be a part of public tragedies, from the deaths of
Princess Diana and JFK Jr. to the massacre at Columbine High
School. ``Tragedy-cam and Grief TV,'' he observes, give us the
chance to share in national mourning and healing from the comfort
of our couches, without our having to come face-to-face with the
bereaved. ``But every sadness does not belong to everyone,'' he
continues, and this mass sadness is not the same as true grief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grief is the tax we pay on our attachments, not on our
interests or diversions or entertainments,'' Lynch writes. ``We
grieve for losses only in games we play for keeps _ real love, real
hate, real attachments broken. Perhaps if we were more willing to
leave ourselves open to grief _ deregulated, unplanned, unruly,
potentially embarrassing grief _ and bear its burdens honorably,
we'd have less free-floating, unattached heartache to spend on the
increasingly `packaged' bereavement-ops the media serves up.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, what unifies this compilation as it meanders among
such disparate topics is Lynch's lust for life in all its splendor
and torment. ``Someone told me that I should just say `Thanks,' and
that all my prayers should begin that way and never stray far from
the notion that life was a gift to be grateful for,'' he writes. As
someone who has made his living dealing with the end of life, Lynch
has earned that particular wisdom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
