<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA AGREES TO ACCEPT HELP FROM BRITAIN FOR SUBMARINE RESCUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By SABRINA TAVERNISE and PATRICK E. TYLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The Russian navy agreed Wednesday to accept help from
Britain to rescue more than 100 crew members trapped aboard a
crippled nuclear-powered submarine that lies on the floor of the
Barents Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Russian rescuers made two attempts on Tuesday, two overnight and
at least one Wednesday morning to attach a rescue capsule to the
submarine Kursk. The navy planned to make one more attempt.
</P>
<P>
   But the Russian efforts seemed to be at a pause as rescuers
regrouped, strategized and waited for the arrival of a British
mini-submarine to help with the rescue efforts.
</P>
<P>
   President Vladimir Putin made his first public comments on the
disaster Wednesday, saying the situation was critical. Putin's
strong language and the decision to accept British help after days
of refusing proffers of aid indicates that the Russians are running
out of technological options and perhaps beginning to despair.
</P>
<P>
   It may be difficult for the British or anyone else to aid the
rescuers. The seas are high, the water bitterly cold and the
underwater currents strong and unpredictable. A further
complication is that the submarine is listing at a 60-degree angle,
making it difficult for any rescue capsule, pod or vehicle to
connect with it.
</P>
<P>
   The British rescue submarine arrived in Trondheim, Norway, from
Scotland on Wednesday. It must be shipped by boat to the site of
the accident, about 35 miles off the Russian coast. But it is
unclear whether the British craft can make it to the accident site
in time.
</P>
<P>
   The crew of the Russian submarine had been beating out an SOS
code on the hull, but the Russian news agency Interfax reported
that the taps had stopped, according to Deputy Prime Minister Ilya
Klebanov.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the silence of the crew, which has had no radio
contact since the accident on Saturday, did not necessarily mean
that the sailors were dead. He said they might be trying to
conserve their energy and oxygen, now that they have been alerted
that rescue efforts are underway.
</P>
<P>
   Information about what happened remains fragmentary and often
contradictory. The Kursk was apparently damaged by an explosion and
partly flooded on Saturday during training maneuvers by Russia's
Northern Fleet. The damage was likely compounded by the crash
landing of the 14,000-ton sub on the bottom of the sea.
</P>
<P>
   After examining the outside of the submarine, navy officials
said the most likely reason for the accident was an explosion,
possibly from a torpedo carried in the front of the vessel. The
Russian government at first said the accident occurred on Sunday,
but U.S. officials have said U.S. Navy submarines detected the
sound of an explosion on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   And news reports from Russia have been misleading and inaccurate
at times. On Wednesday the navy raised the official count of the
number of crew members from 116 to 118.
</P>
<P>
   During much of Tuesday, rescue efforts were hampered by winds
that reached 45 miles an hour and whipped up waves of 13 feet.
Water temperatures near the submarine hovered at 39 degrees.
Visibility under water was extremely low, the navy said.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians have been trying to use at least two small
bell-shaped rescue capsules, each able to hold 10 to 20 people, to
reach the crew.
</P>
</TEXT>
