A3441 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MESSINA17-COX     08-16 0267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MESSINA17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hitmaker Messina turns up the heat
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With her third CD, this Boston tomboy proves she is the female
vocalist destined to keep alive the working class spunk of Loretta
Lynn. As much as the stylists pile on the makeup for glam album
covers, Messina's powerful voice and take-no-bull lyrics break
through the makeover to stand up consistently for all the gals who
work two jobs and buy their cosmetics at Wal-Mart. In the giddy,
driving-around anthem ``Saturday Night,'' Messina hops into Mary's
Mustang with the naive passion of a small-town girl looking for her
dreams under a neon sign. The title track is a scorching ultimatum
to a mixed-up lover _ ``Be anyone you want to be/but I want
something in return/I want you to burn.'' The duet with producer
Tim McGraw, ``Bring on the Rain,'' layers a mournful cello over an
anthem of survival and beating hard times that rivals Scarlett
O'Hara holding her fist in the air. Throughout the CD, McGraw's
signature sounds _ soaring guitar solos, monster truck rhythms _
are fine tools that complement Messina's stunning (and refreshingly
country) voice. Though the tunes are slightly less consistent than
her last CD, Messina proves here she's not just a hitmaker, but a
career artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Burn''
</P>
<P>
   Jo Dee Messina Curb. 11 tracks. Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on Jo Dee Messina:
www.jodeemessina.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
