<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ Consumer prices rose 0.2 percent in
July, down from June's gain of 0.6 percent as energy prices
stabilized. Costs for food, housing and medical care rose, while
clothing fell for a fourth consecutive month. The core rate, which
excludes food and energy, also rose 0.2 percent. Overall, inflation
growth is slowing: In the year through July, consumer prices rose
3.5 percent, down from a nine-year high of 3.7 percent in June. A
separate report showed that higher interest rates are weighing on
the housing market. The Commerce Department says that slipped to a
1.512 million annual rate, down 3.3 percent from June and the
lowest level of starts since November 1997. July's was the third
consecutive decline. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
