<SLUG> BC-TRENDS-NEXTGEN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING FORWARD TO FALL TV WITH GENS X AND WHY  
</HEADLINE>
  (For release August 16, 2000.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's TRENDS-NEXTGEN column. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of TRENDS-NEXTGEN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By JANE RINZLER BUCKINGHAM  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sick of ``Survivor?'' Bored since the beginning of ``Big
Brother?'' Rather give away all your money than watch another
episode of ``Who Wants to be a Millionaire''? Well, have hope. The
new TV season is on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   My company, Youth Intelligence, recently conducted focus groups
with teens and 20-somethings in New York, L.A. and Chicago to see
which of this seasons new shows they preferred. One caveat _ our
savvy viewers were hesitant to cast votes based only on previews or
pilot episodes. Even THEY know that a shows success has much to do
with great scripts, good time slots and the support of its network.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the ones that seem to have what it takes to make a hit:
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON PUBLIC (Fox) _ If this series creates half as much buzz
as its executive producer David E. Kelley's prior hits, ``Ally
McBeal'' and ``The Practice,'' you'll want to make sure you're home
at 8 p.m. (EST)on Monday nights.
</P>
<P>
   This drama centers around a group of young teachers working at a
New England high school. Teens liked the idea of an accurate,
albeit exaggerated representation of high school life, while
20-somethings loved the idea of a high school where teachers were
dedicated to teaching. The lead actress, Jessalyn Gilsig, is
already being touted as the next Calista Flockhart.
</P>
<P>
   TUCKER (NBC) _ This sitcom may be ``The Wonder Years'' for
Generation Why. It has everything _ a dysfunctional family,
pubescent situations, a girl-next-door crush, thoughtful voiceovers
and a realistic setting. The show is an edgy, coming-of-age comedy
about a 14-year-old boy, Tucker, and his struggles to start a new
life with his aunt's crazy family. Katie Segal of ``Married With
Children'' plays Tucker's aunt, and the Fred Savage-esque Tucker is
a charmer. If you've ever been 14, you should be able to relate.
</P>
<P>
   THE $TREET (Fox) _ This show, which is set in a high-powered
Wall Street brokerage firm, capitalizes (pardon the pun) on the
current attention being paid to stocks and trading. Young TV
viewers are themselves playing the market, day-trading, starting
companies and developing portfolios _ so ``The $treet'' may well
have tapped into the right theme at the right time. With a cast
that includes Christian Campbell (``Trick''), Adam Goldberg
(``Saving Private Ryan''), Tom Everett Scott (``Boiler Room'') and
Jennifer Connelly (``Inventing the Abbots''), this show could be a
winner.
</P>
<P>
   QUEER AS FOLK (Showtime) _ Based on the British television
series of the same name, ``Queer as Folk'' is a risque drama about
homosexual life. The original series was highly controversial
because of its frequent nudity and edgy subject matter. Showtimes
series deals with the lives of a group of gay men in a
working-class city in the eastern United States. Young people
applauded Showtimes willingness to handle a controversial subject.
</P>
<P>
   THE FUGITIVE (CBS) _ Although this series has a tough act to
follow _ no one I know would want to follow Harrison Ford! _ ``The
Fugitive'' has a production team that may help it live up to the
film's legacy. In fact, some of our younger panelists didnt even
realize the movie itself was a remake of an original television
series. With all the hype surrounding ``The Fugitive,'' it may be
the action/drama of the season.
</P>
<P>
   JACKASS (MTV) _ Skateboarding Oompa Loompas? Self-mutilation
with red pepper spray and a stun gun? Stupid human tricks with
public toilets? Not standard fare for cable television (unless it's
public access). Following the success of his ``Praise You'' video,
public prankster Spike Jonze brings his 21st-century ``Candid
Camera'' to MTV. Taped with a hidden camera, innocent bystanders
fall into traps of public humiliation. Destined to be a hit with
the Tom Green set, it will undoubtedly cause many a parent to yearn
for shows like ``Father Knows Best.''
</P>
<P>
   DARK ANGEL (Fox) _ In this series, a genetically altered young
woman escapes from a lab experiment and joins forces with an
underground cyber-journalist in San Francisco to work against the
evil powers exploiting them. What that entails, we're not exactly
sure, but with James Cameron (``Titanic'') as executive producer
and sexy new star Jessica Alba, its got a leg up. As long as the
show doesnt get too dark, it could be a heaven-sent hit for Fox.
</P>
<P>
   OTHERS TO BE ON THE LOOKOUT FOR:
</P>
<P>
   Ed (NBC)
</P>
<P>
   Grosse Point (WB)
</P>
<P>
   Freedom (UPN)
</P>
<P>
   BE ON THE LOOKOUT FOR:
</P>
<P>
   Patterned stockings
</P>
<P>
   Skinny belts
</P>
<P>
   Music artist, Amanda Ghost
</P>
<P>
   Jane Rinzler Buckingham is the president of Youth Intelligence,
a market-research firm specializing in the 7- to 35-year-old
market. Her company publishes the Cassandra Report, a comprehensive
survey focused on identifying emerging trends among Generations X
and Why?
</P>
<P>
