<DOCNO> NYT20000816.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3455 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-OLY-ERVIN-HNS &LR;      08-16 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ERVIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ERVIN CARRIES THE WEIGHT OF BEING A SYMBOL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GWEN KNAPP  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Anthony Ervin represents all the awkward feelings
that Americans have about race, color and ethnicity. Anthony Ervin
also represents simply Anthony Ervin, U.S. Olympian, college
student and clutch competitor.
</P>
<P>
   He is a symbol, and he is a swimmer. He chose swimming. The
symbolism has been thrust on him, by the news media, by the history
of this country and the history of his sport.
</P>
<P>
   Never before has a black made the Olympic swimming team. Ervin
qualified tentatively on Sunday, when he took fifth in the
100-meter freestyle, positioning himself to be named a relay
alternate. On Tuesday, he earned a definitive spot on the team, in
the 50 freestyle, just four-hundredths of a second behind training
partner Gary Hall Jr. Both of them broke the American record held
by Tom Jager since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the 100 on Sunday, the announcer introduced
another finalist, Stanford graduate Sabir Muhammad, by saying that
he was trying to become the first African-American to swim in the
Olympics. No similar comment was made about Ervin, who had swum
faster in the semifinals and had a better chance of going to
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that was because Ervin is light-skinned. A brief mention
in Sports Illustrated had alerted reporters to his ethnic
background, but the audience had no other way of knowing. So after
the race, Ervin had to delineate his lineage. His father, he said,
was three-quarters African-American and one-quarter American
Indian. He described his mom as white.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud of my heritage,'' Ervin said. Asked Tuesday
whether he wanted to be a role model for young black swimmers, he
said he wanted to be a role model for all swimmers, regardless of
race.
</P>
<P>
   He is 19 years old, and he had just recorded a 50-meter time of
21.80 seconds, stunningly fast. Yet the salient number for Ervin
was this: 37.5 percent black.
</P>
<P>
   It seems absurd, another indication of our obsession with race,
how it distorts everything. If we're counting fractions, isn't it
possible that there have been other people with African-American
backgrounds on Olympic swim teams? What about his status as an
American Indian? Is that a first, too? Is anybody keeping such
close track on the status of Asian-Americans?
</P>
<P>
   In a country intent on thoroughly categorizing every identity,
isn't it just as important that Ian Crocker won the 100 butterfly
on Tuesday to become the first Olympic swimmer from the frosty
state of Maine?
</P>
<P>
   In a perfect world, none of it would matter. In an imperfect
world, swimming reflects some of the worst blemishes. Historically,
the sport has been a racial dividing line, specifically separating
whites and blacks. During his infamous ``Nightline'' meltdown,
Dodgers executive Al Campanis cited swimming as one of the things
blacks couldn't do, in the same way that they couldn't manage
baseball teams. He said it as if everyone would understand, as if
it were established fact.
</P>
<P>
   Campanis said that blacks lacked buoyancy. Years later, a black
friend of mine started taking basic swimming lessons. He told me he
was struggling in the water, that he couldn't stay afloat and he
wondered, however abashedly, whether there was some truth to the
stereotype.
</P>
<P>
   As a former swimming instructor, I told him that I believed the
reason he couldn't float was his age, not his race. Unskilled
adults have such a well-honed terror of the water that their feet
instinctively reach for the bottom of the pool. Children don't know
enough to be afraid. Adults have learned, and the knowledge makes
them rigid in the water. For my friend, the stereotypes only added
another layer of doubt.
</P>
<P>
   The silly myths don't take into account generations of
segregation at pools and beaches, or the fact that swimming came to
be perceived as a country-club sport. Consider what happened to
Muhammad, one of the best swimmers in the world, when he moved to
Hawaii to train and landed a small part on ``Baywatch.'' He was
cast as a basketball player.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad has stated that he wanted to break down racial barriers
by making the Olympic team. Some people wonder whether he would
swim better if he didn't have to carry the additional weight of
being a pioneer.
</P>
<P>
   Byron Davis, another longtime contender who is black, has been
reticent about the attention he gets. In print, he has wondered why
no one had made as much fuss over the ethnicity of Pablo Morales,
the 1992 gold medalist in the 100 butterfly. He would like to be a
swimmer, not a symbol.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Swimming, the sport's governing body, has tried to take on
some of the burden, bringing inner-city swimmers to the national
training center in Colorado. National team director Dennis Pursley
said he had noticed more blacks swimming at regional meets, the
starting point for Olympic dreamers.
</P>
<P>
   But in the summer of Tiger and Venus, swimming seems rather out
of step with the other country-club sports. Even figure skating,
which is judged by people in fur coats, has achieved far more
diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Ervin represents a breakthrough only for American
swimming. In 1988, Anthony Nesty, a black man from Suriname, won
the 100-meter butterfly at the Olympics. He could have been a giant
role model, but American TV doesn't pay attention to winners who
don't mouth ``The Star-Spangled Banner'' on the medals stand.
</P>
<P>
   And except for every four years, TV barely pays attention to any
swimmers. Obscurity doesn't help attract newcomers to a sport.
</P>
<P>
   Ervin might help a little. But that's not his job. He has
something special. His coach, Mike Bottom of the University of
California at Berkeley, calls him ``the best racer I've ever
seen.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a shame we can't ignore other labels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
