<HEADER>
A3457 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-RUSSIAN-SUB-HNS &LR;      08-16 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIAN-SUB-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CRITIC SAYS U.S. ANTAGONISM SPAWED RUSSIAN SUB EXERCISE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sinking of a Russian nuclear sub and the possible loss of
its 116-member crew could have been avoided if only the United
States hadn't been a menacing power perpetuating the Cold War, a
former Navy official said.
</P>
<P>
   While the United States may not have been responsible for
Saturday's sinking of the submarine Kursk, the Russians might have
been holding the maneuvers in which the boat participated as a
reaction to the threat of superior American power, said retired
Rear Adm. Eugene Carroll, a vocal critic of the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that Russia would be out trying to use 10 ships
to practice fighting World War III if it weren't for indications
that NATO was aggressive and NATO is threatening, and they'd better
have some military capability to deal with it,'' Carroll told the
San Antonio Express-News Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's laughable, it's pitiful that they should think that
NATO's going to attack them and that they have the means to defeat
that attack,'' he added, ``but it's understandable.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll bemoaned America's conduct in the post-Cold War era,
which he argued has put Russia on the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to build a national missile defense (system) that
the Russians abhor,'' he explained. ``We expanded NATO, the U.S.
was the driving force in expanding NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the driving force in attacking Serbia. We are going
out of our way to show the ex-Soviet Union, Russia, we are the boss
and in the driver's seat and they'd better mind their manners.
That's nothing but saying we won the Cold War and we're rubbing
your nose in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Declaring the chances of a successful rescue as ``pretty
dismal,'' Carroll said the incident might further prod the Russians
to improve their conventional forces, which have been on the
decline since the end of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Naval officials declined to comment on the statements made by
Carroll, a frequent critic of the service and an ardent foe of
expanding the U.S. submarine fleet. The sub force has 56 fast
attack boats today and the Navy has called for expanding to 67 or
even as many as 76 in 24 years.
</P>
<P>
   A one-time aviator and Pentagon war planner, Carroll made his
comments as Russian rescue teams made desperate attempts to save
the Kursk's crew, who have been trapped 354 feet below the surface
of the icy Barents Sea.
</P>
<P>
   The 500-foot-long boat, part of what one observer called the
biggest Russian naval exercise in years, sank after a torpedo room
explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Its air, water and power supplies have been running on batteries
since the Kursk's nuclear reactors were shut down. The Russians
repeatedly tried to lower a rescue capsule to the submarine, but a
number of American observers said the situation was grim for Kursk,
which has taken on large amounts of water.
</P>
<P>
   Naval analyst Norman Polmar and other observers said the crew
might have as little as one week left to live, depending on how
much oxygen and compressed air was in the sub at the time of the
accident as well as the state of the Kursk's battery and the
buildup of carbon dioxide, which is fatal at high levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say keep hope alive but I think the longer it goes on
the worse off they are,'' said Ivan Eland, director of defense
policy studies at the Cato Institute, a libertarian think tank in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fourth and long,'' said Sherry Sontag, co-author of
``Blind Man's Bluff,'' a best-selling book on the role of U.S.
submarines in undersea espionage during the Cold War. ``It's a very
precarious situation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
