<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3463 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-ARMY-FIRES-HNS &LR;      08-16 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMY-FIRES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FORT HOOD TROOPS EXCHANGE GUNS FOR FIREFIGHTING GEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DANE SCHILLER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PAYETTE NATIONAL FOREST, Idaho _ As a flame-spewing monster
roars through the canyons here, sweaty, soot-covered soldiers from
Fort Hood, Texas, realize they are fighting a battle they can't
win.
</P>
<P>
   They wear banana-yellow flame-resistant shirts instead of
camouflage, carry shovels instead of M-16s, and fear hot coals and
falling trees instead of snipers or land mines.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a real-life scenario, if something threatened my life, I
would kill it, take it down,'' infantryman Specialist Mitch Court
said during a grueling march up a mountain where towering fir and
pine trees had been burned into eerie charred skeletons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, it is different _ dig a little bit, dig a little more,''
said Court, who has twice been to troubled Bosnia and once to
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   About 18 new large fires were reported Tuesday, bringing to 85
the number of fires burning almost 4.9 million acres in 11 Western
states, according to the National Interagency Fire Center.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the fires are believed to have been touched off by
lightning and spread by high winds blowing through dangerously dry
and rugged terrain.
</P>
<P>
   While Army crews from the 4th Infantry Division help battle the
fires, officials concede that in many instances the best that can
be done is corralling the fires into remote areas and waiting for
winter storms to snuff them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fought the good fight and that is good enough,'' said Col.
Darryl Williams, the Task Force Thunder commander. ``We are not
trying to put this fire out, the fire will be put out by winter
storms.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 560 Fort Hood-based soldiers are halfway through their
mission to support veteran civilian firefighters here. Another 500
are training for positions in neighboring Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers are dropped by helicopter, then take Humvees into
remote places where they walk for hours searching for burning coals
and hot spots.
</P>
<P>
   The 2.3 million-acre Payette National Forest is usually home to
breathtaking views and world-class kayaking. But as a Black Hawk
helicopter hovered near the Salmon River on Tuesday afternoon, a
huge inferno spewing orange and gray clouds raged in a remote
canyon, as smaller fires rose from other canyons south of the
river.
</P>
<P>
   Back on the ground, a distance from the inferno, Court made his
way along a dirt trail cut to stop the blaze from spreading. Court
carries a 24-pound chainsaw to devour logs.
</P>
<P>
   A tank of gasoline is strapped to his buddy's rucksack, but the
soldier says he's not nervous.
</P>
<P>
   Other soldiers with shovels and picks dig up and smother
smoldering coals from portions of the fire already battled by
veteran civilian firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   The marches can be difficult, with as many as 30 percent of the
soldiers in some units suffering blisters or knee and ankle
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to marching in brand new lumberjack boots instead of
their combat boots, the soldiers have had a tough time breathing in
the thin air at 7,000-plus feet of altitude.
</P>
<P>
   They wear fire-retardant pants and shirts and leather gloves, as
well as the heavy lumberjack boots with a special bottom that
allows them to walk on hot coals.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers carry fire protection blankets on their belts for quick
deployment, and haul tools such as pick, shovels and hoses. Some
have the added weight of carrying bags of water on their backs.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, soldiers were forced to walk on their hands and
knees for hundreds of yards as they scaled a near-vertical
mountainside
</P>
<P>
   ``For these guys, it is not God and country, it is get through
the next 15 minutes,'' said Lt. Steven Miller, leader of a team of
19 men.
</P>
<P>
   Still, not all were feeling beat down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this stuff -- the outdoors,'' said Specialist
Christopher Vann, 21, a soldier from San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, soldiers rarely have worked side-by-side with elite
civilian firefighters. They had been carrying out ``mop-up duties''
to ensure already burned areas don't re-ignite and that undamaged
areas aren't set ablaze by coals drifting in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't have enough people. There are too many fires,''
said Paul Head, a U.S. Forest Service liaison with the military,
who said the soldiers have dramatically multiplied his manpower.
</P>
<P>
   What soldiers lack in firefighting experience, they make up for
with discipline, fitness and the ability to function as a unit, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Soaking and filthy, fire-seeking soldiers hike through canyons
in temperatures often as much as 50 degrees hotter than at the camp
sight. Only to return to their remote camp where they sleep on the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Clete Edmunson, a history teacher in Idaho who grew up in a
nearby logging community and has helped fight fires, said he is
thankful for the military's help, but that there is no way to
extinguish the blaze here.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are kind of at the mercy of Mother Nature,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
