A3469 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     08-16 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAR AL: JUST GIVE UP AND CAMPAIGN WITH HIM
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BILL THOMPSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hasn't anybody told Bill Clinton that he's not allowed to run
for a third term?
</P>
<P>
   The president's speech at Monday's opening session of the
Democratic National Convention was billed as a farewell address,
but it sounded a lot more like a plea for four more years than a
valedictory. Clinton spoke for 40-plus minutes and seemed
constantly on the verge of blurting, ``I accept your nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt about it: If the 22nd Amendment to the U.S.
Constitution limiting presidents to two terms hadn't been ratified
way back in 1951, Clinton would be asking the electorate for a
contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   And you know what's scary? He'd probably get it.
</P>
<P>
   Even as repercussions of the great White House sex scandal
linger on _ even as the tally of Clinton apologies for that
``terrible mistake'' climbs toward double digits _ the president's
job approval ratings remain sky-high. Even among those who believe
that Clinton is a devious cad, there is apparently no shortage of
Americans who like the job he's done as president.
</P>
<P>
   They couldn't like it any better than he likes it, of course.
The Great Prevaricator nearly broke his arm patting himself on the
back during that speech, which was supposed to be a rhetorical
passing of the torch to his vice president and would-be successor,
Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore got a mention here or there, but Clinton obviously was on a
mission to give himself a leg up on history, not to give his
ex-running mate a boost in the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Which should have surprised exactly nobody _ especially Gore,
who surely knows this self-serving president as well as anyone
does, if not better. Gore has labored alongside Clinton for nearly
eight years, acting as apologist in chief for the most
self-absorbed commander in chief since Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky for the country that the U.S. Senate didn't vote to
convict Clinton in that impeachment trial awhile back. We can only
imagine what might have happened once Clinton got the order to
vacate the White House. He could still be holed up in the Oval
Office.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the next president might need an eviction notice from
the Supreme Court and a contingent of federal marshals to drive
Clinton off the premises.
</P>
<P>
   Put down the phone, people. It was just a joke.
</P>
<P>
   All kidding aside, there is little doubt that Clinton would stay
if he could. We're talking about a man whose sole ambition in life
was to be president of the United States. It's understandable that
he would be reluctant to surrender the only job he ever wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has vowed _ threatened? _ to hang onto the reins until
the last minute of the last hour of the last day of his presidency.
Unlike most Clinton promises, this is one he clearly intends to
keep.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Clinton refused to yield the spotlight Monday night, he
will be unable to resist the urge to upstage Gore in the weeks and
months ahead. Clinton will seize every possible opportunity to
remind America and the world that he is still president of the
United States; that he is still calling the shots; that he, Bill
Clinton, is the man who gave the greatest nation on earth eight
years of prosperity, peace and progress.
</P>
<P>
   And that's a problem for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Or is it?
</P>
<P>
   David Gergen, a Republican who worked in Clinton's White House,
said on television the other night that Gore ought to stop trying
to distance himself from Clinton _ that the vice president ought to
grab hold of the president's coattails and try to ride those
Clinton job approval ratings right into the White House.
</P>
<P>
   He might have a point. Clinton has no intention of getting out
of Gore's way, and Gore's opponents have no intention of letting
him wash his hands of Clinton's less admirable adventures.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe Gore should take Gergen's advice. Maybe Gore should
invite Clinton onto the bus for one of those cross-country tours
that so captivated the electorate back in the good old days.
</P>
<P>
   Gore might as well run with Clinton. He's getting nowhere
running away from him.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7787 or e-mail:
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
