<P>
   DEM-RDP-NYT (Los Angeles) _ A roundup: Vice President Al Gore is
nominated; Joseph Lieberman speaks to the convention.
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: An early version of the roundup by Christopher S. Wren
will move by 3 p.m. ET and will be updated after 9 p.m. ET with a
final version written by Richard L. Berke, with quotes from late
speeches.)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Text: &LR;  Complete text of the speeches will be available the New
York Times on the Web: www.nytimes.com
</P>
<P>
   DEM-ASSESS-NYT (Los Angeles) _ A political analysis of the
convention. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-GORE-BIO-TRANSFORM-NYT (Undated) _ After Al Gore ran for
president in 1988 and lost, just as he turned 40, he organized a
series of dinners where he went around the room and asked each
person to tell him where he had gone wrong.
</P>
<P>
   It was excruciating, his friends said, but he insisted on
hearing the bad news _ in detail _ about a campaign that had
started out as an environmental crusade and ended as a New York
food fight. He heard that he had no economic vision and that he had
talked about technology and the environment in ways people couldn't
understand. Oh, and his speaking style needed a ton of work.
</P>
<P>
   Gore responded, as he always has, by going back to school. He
put together a graduate seminar for one, complete with a syllabus
and a heavy-duty reading list, and applied himself to the serious
study of tax policy and business history. He brought in a
mathematician to explain chaos theory. And he hired a speech
consultant and a dance coach _ ``a ballet type,'' he told one
friend _ to help him move more fluidly.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians often learn from and are even transformed by a good
drubbing at the polls, but few have pursued their lessons as
aggressively as Gore. And no one can say that the man who will
accept the Democratic Party's nomination for the presidency
Thursday night has not diligently prepared for this moment. By
Melinda Henneberger and Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Also scheduled: &LR;
</P>
