<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3484 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV2     08-16 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV20-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PAT BUCHANAN'S PITIFUL CRUSADE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, Aug. 20)   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For all their overblown rhetoric and inflated
promises, Al Gore and George W. Bush each hopes to lead the United
States into a future of continued prosperity and enlightened
policies.
</P>
<P>
   The bombastic Pat Buchanan, who was nominated for president last
week by one wing of the warring Reform Party, may have the same
hope. But the policies he espouses are not those of the future. If
put into practice, they would not perpetuate prosperity or
illuminate the way ahead. They would have exactly the opposite
effect.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan advocates the failed policies of yesteryear _ the
protectionist and isolationist policies that exacerbated the Great
Depression in the 1930s and, in the same era, led vicious dictators
to understand that they could subvert one country after another
with their military might, without fear of retribution.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's policies are bigoted and myopic. He worships at the
shrine of Ronald Reagan, his one-time White House boss, and claims
to be the inheritor of the Gipper's conservatism. But Reagan was
neither a protectionist nor an isolationist.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan understood quite clearly that the Earth is round and that
there must be a strong relationship between nations. It was Reagan,
working with the Soviet Union's Mikhail Gorbachev, who finally
ended the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Were Reagan well and able to communicate, he could explain to
the men and women of labor that the more American products
foreigners buy from us the more we can sell to them. And if we sell
to them, our own businesses and industries will flourish _
benefiting working men and women.
</P>
<P>
   It would be idiocy to claim that in the short run some jobs
which traditionally were performed by Americans will not be
performed by foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   All we need do is wander through stores that sell television
sets, radios, computers and clothing to see that our shops are
filled with products made in China, Korea, Taiwan and many other
nations.
</P>
<P>
   But to reduce American purchase of items from those countries
would hinder their ability to ascend the economic ladder _ and thus
reduce their ability to buy our goods.
</P>
<P>
   Globalism is a term that frightens and angers Americans who
believe we can prosper by closing our borders and going it alone.
But ours is _ and will continue to be _ a global economy; American
business and enterprise can be found everywhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Reforms can and should be implemented, but we cannot,
Buchanan-style, turn our backs on our future destiny.
</P>
<P>
   We stand at the pinnacle of world power because we have worked,
sometimes very successfully, sometimes less so, to ensure
cooperation among nations large and small.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan exudes hate for the United Nations and America's
alliances with other countries. Buchanan told his faction of the
Reform Party that if he were president, he would order the United
Nations out of the United States and dispatch American Marines to
New York to help pack the bags of U.N. representatives.
</P>
<P>
   To cheers and applause of his supporters, Buchanan lambasted the
``commissars of the U.S. Supreme Court,'' the ``Visigoths and
vandals of multiculturalism'' and the ``gods of the global
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan wants to withdraw American peacekeeping forces from
places like South Korea and Kosovo and reassign them along the
U.S.-Mexican border to halt illegal immigration. He also has
suggested constructing a wall or fence the length of the border.
</P>
<P>
   Illegal immigration from Mexico is a troublesome matter,
especially in border states such as California, Arizona, New Mexico
and Texas. Every recent administration in Washington has taken
steps to halt or curtail it. Yet, night after night, would-be
migrants are caught and returned to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's proposed solution would be outrageously expensive and
insulting to our good neighbor to the south. Mexico's
president-elect, Vicente Fox, has urged a new U.S., Canadian and
Mexican partnership that would view Mexican workers and resources
as ``an opportunity, not a threat.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Washington Post, Fox said ``we must be
better friends, we must be better neighbors, we must be better
partners.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not Buchanan's way. His way is to fence the United
States in and Mexico out, to end free trade that has proved so
beneficial to Americans, and to abandon scores of international
agreements and alliances that have helped spread democracy and
economic growth around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   That is not the American way in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Robert E. Thompson is a Washington-based columnist for the
Hearst Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
