<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Roberts plays a rebel with a cause
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Julia Roberts lets it all hang out _ thanks to some
cleavage-pinching support bras and low-neck dresses _ but delivers
a performance so fierce and funny, her breasts don't upstage her.
</P>
<P>
   She plays a smart, sailor-mouthed single mom who wangles her way
into a job at a small law firm (run by the estimable Albert
Finney). Following a hunch, she starts investigating health
problems in a small town and in the process launches what winds up
as a $33 million judgment against Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric Co. for
basically poisoning the local population.
</P>
<P>
   The movie goes for the obvious a few times, as it shows
Brockovich alienating her family as she becomes obsessed with the
case. But Roberts is terrific, and it helps that she's directed by
Steven Soderbergh, one of the best (and least heralded) directors
working in Hollywood. Priced to buy: $22.98 VHS, $26.98 DVD.
</P>
<P>
   `Erin Brockovich'
</P>
<P>
   Rated R / Our critic's grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
