`` Roger Miller and Nicholas Payton. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL/PROS
</P>
<P>
   FBN-FALCONS-CLARIDGE _ FLOWERY BRANCH, Ga. _ It didn't take No.
1 pick Travis Claridge long to earn his keep. He has enjoyed some
serious playing time on the offensive line since the exhibition
season began and he's turning heads with his play. (Winkeljohn,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 13.
</P>
<P>
   COWBOYS-KICKER _ Tim Ceder will be the opening-day place-kicker
for the Dallas Cowboys. Ceder was a high school teacher and coach
last year in Ohio, thinking he had no chance of playing in the NFL
someday. Steve Hoffman, the kickers coach, got a tape of Ceder when
he played in college at Ashland University in Ashland, Ohio, liked
his form, and invited him to a tryout. Four months later, he is the
Cowboys' first-team kicker. (Cantu, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL/COLLEGES
</P>
<P>
   FBC-SCAROLINA _ Road to College Football: South Carolina, coming
off an 0-11 season. Can it get any worse? (Barnhart, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-TEXAS-JAMMER _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Quentin Jammer began the 1999
season as an all-star caliber free safety. He drew a lot of
publicity in preseason magazines and around the Big 12. Then he
separates his shoulder in the first game of the season against
North Carolina State. The redshirt junior is back and could/should
be a main cog in the No. 7 ranked Longhorns secondary.
(Halliburton, Austin American-Statesman). 20.
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPICS
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SWM-TRIALS _ INDIANAPOLIS _ Final day coverage of the U.S.
Olympic Swim Trials in Indianapolis, will include a wrapup of
Trials and look a head to medal chances for U.S. team. (Tierney,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-GYM-TRIALS _ A look at the women's gymnastics trials and the
pressure created by the convoluted system of picking the team.
(Rosen, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   GOLF
</P>
<P>
   GLF-PGA-WOODS _ LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Tiger Woods: The Sequel. The
phrase prohibitive favorite is redundant around Woods these days.
He will play a Jack Nicklaus-designed course at Valhalla suited to
his game, requiring long, accurate drives and high fade approaches.
He will be defending his PGA title and could become the first to
successfully defend in the PGA since Denny Shute in 1936-37 and the
first to win three majors in a year since Ben Hogan in 1953. Even
with the hoopla, Woods won't go quietly. (Sheeley, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
