<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (w and a coding)  
 VETERANS ANSWER FAN MAIL FOR CLINTON PETS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER WALSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Dozens of retired veterans are serving their
country again _ this time armed with black pens and envelopes to
take on the thousands of letters sent to the White House each day.
</P>
<P>
   The mailroom duties for residents of the Soldiers' and Airmen's
Home include meeting requests for birthday greetings and get-well
cards. But one job is theirs alone: answering letters sent to
President Clinton's cat, Socks, and dog, Buddy.
</P>
<P>
   In the past seven years, the stark basement of the veteran's
home in Northwest Washington has been transformed into a decorative
tribute to the first feline and canine. The makeshift wallpaper
consists of items sent by letter writers, such as photographs of
look-a-like cats and dogs, oversized letters from kindergarten
classes, and children's drawings. The desks are adorned with Socks
and Buddy paraphernalia.
</P>
<P>
   It all began when the White House put out a call in March 1993
for volunteers to help handle the 35,000 letters to the Clintons
that arrive daily. The nation's oldest veterans retirement home
responded with 38 volunteers, but after a few months, the 3-mile
trip downtown and the formalities of the White House became
tiresome for the senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to wear a coat and tie all the time,'' said Bill D.
Woods, a retired Korean and Vietnam War veteran. ``So we said, `Why
can't we open an annex at the Soldiers' Home?' For the first time
in history, the president let his mail leave the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the veterans have answered about 1.9 million
letters, 320,000 of them for the president's pets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some are from children, and some are from adults pretending to
be cats,'' said veteran Allan H. Gordon, who acts as Socks's
unofficial secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who coordinates the mailroom annex, explained: ``They
don't want to write the president, but they want to write the cat
because they think they can get the message through to the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie, a youngster from Lonedell, Mont., wrote to Buddy on
light-blue stationery with puffy white clouds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gee, I wish I was the president's dog. It must feel really
neat. I mean being petted by famous people, riding in fancy cars,
or just living in the White House,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buddy'' responded on his standard portrait postcard with his
pawprint at the bottom and the message: ``Thank you for writing me.
Living at the White House is exciting, and I am enjoying my new
family.''
</P>
<P>
   A kindergarten class from Norcross, Ga., wrote a letter to Socks
on poster-sized ruled paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Socks, What do you look like? Do you wear socks? What
color are you? Do you like kids? Do you like to live at the White
House? We have 20 children in our class. Our teacher has a cat
named `Tinkerbell.' She is grey and white. We're glad the president
has a cat for a pet.''
</P>
<P>
   The children were sent a postcard with Socks's picture and
pawprint saying: ``Thank you for writing to me. I am honored to be
your `First Cat.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton thanked the volunteers about a month ago when he visited
the veterans' home to dedicate Anderson Cottage, President
Lincoln's summer retreat, as a national monument.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who live in this home open amazing volumes of mail
. . . A lot of that mail is the mail that very young children send
to Socks and to Buddy,'' Clinton said. ``It would be impossible to
respond to those children with the staff we have at the White House
if it weren't for the veteran volunteers here who do this and so
many other things to help the White House work.''
</P>
<P>
   About eight volunteers are in the office at any one time. For
many of these veterans, whose average age is 76, working every
morning for about four hours provides a welcome change from the
routine around the retirement home.
</P>
<P>
   Jewel Miggins, 76, started volunteering with her husband, James
Joseph Miggins. He stuffed envelopes and she addressed them. He
died in 1996, shortly after their 50th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   The memories linger as she opens mail without him, but the job
still invigorates her.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have something to do, it gives you a lift, it gives you a
nice feeling that you're doing something,'' Miggins said. ``To be
able to be kept busy, it's doing something worthwhile and it's
appreciated.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the end of Clinton's presidency looms, some veterans
worry that this White House annex could soon close. While it's
unknown whether the next administration would keep the volunteers
who answer the president's mail, there will probably be first pets
in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Governor George W. Bush of Texas has a English springer spaniel
named Spot Fletcher Bush, an offspring of his parents' famous dog
Millie, and two cats named Ernie and India. Vice President Al Gore
has two dogs, a mixed breed named Daisy and a black Labrador
retriever called Shiloh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll vote for anyone who has a pooch,'' Miggins said.
</P>
</TEXT>
