<HEADLINE>
IN COWTOWN, EVEN THE SYMPHONY ORCHESTRA HAS CASUAL DAYS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By WAYNE LEE GAY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ From the offices at Radio Shack's corporate
headquarters to the orchestra pit at Bass Performance Hall, Fort
Worth is dressing down.
</P>
<P>
   It's partly the heat, partly western custom and partly a
national trend _ and not everyone is happy about every day becoming
``Casual Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These days, you can't tell a banker from a trash collector,''
says Norman Warwar, the perturbed proprietor of Norman Tailors, an
upscale downtown men's clothing store that makes custom-made suits
and shirts. ``You can't tell the boss from the employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Casual Friday was popularized during the 1980s, when employers
designated the last day of the workweek for less formal work
attire. A decade later, some companies were allowing their
employees to abandon traditional business wear for a decidedly less
buttoned-down look every day.
</P>
<P>
   A look around Fort Worth reveals a diversity of dress, ranging
from the attorneys at the courthouse _ always in suit and tie _ to
the executive offices at Radio Shack, where casual rules.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing what is appropriate to wear has become so confusing that
even Fort Worth Mayor Kenneth Barr says he's sometimes perplexed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earlier this week, I went to a reception in a sports coat and
casual shirt,'' he said. ``There were people there in everything
from casual shirts to pinstriped suits. It almost makes you
uncomfortable. The rules are up in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr made fashion history in July 1998, when he removed his tie
at a City Council meeting and declared that casual business wear
would be appropriate for city offices until Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were well into the summer, and I was just hot,'' the mayor
says.
</P>
<P>
   He did not issue a casual edict last summer, but so many people
have asked him about it that casual wear is in vogue again this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been pleased that people have been smart about what to
wear,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   If the day the mayor removed his tie has become tied to the
beginning of dressing down in Cowtown, the trend gained real
momentum in January 1999, when new Radio Shack CEO Leonard Roberts
announced a year-round, all-week ``business casual'' dress code for
the corporate offices in Fort Worth. He also allowed the company's
retail sales force nationwide to shed their ties.
</P>
<P>
   And, for special occasions _ such as an increase in profits or
sales _ the company goes positively country with bluejeans as the
fashion statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our task force found that the trend in North Texas is for
business casual,'' says Laura Moore, Radio Shack's vice president
for public relations. ``People feel good if you don't have to wear
a tie and jacket if it's 105 degrees outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to abandon tradition entirely, Moore says that corporate
headquarters staff may dress more formally for meetings with
outside vendors, although the vendors are informed about Radio
Shack's business casual dress code.
</P>
<P>
   Dressing to identify with the customer _ within reason _ is a
fairly common principle in the retail world these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're becoming more casual,'' says Zig Kaminski, a sales
consultant at Mid-City Chrysler-Jeep in Arlington, a Fort Worth
suburb. Kaminski has worked in auto sales for 14 years and has seen
standard attire for auto sales personnel shift dramatically. At the
dealership, which is closed Saturdays, salesmen wear a shirt and
tie on weekdays and a golf shirt with a company logo on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   ``People used to go to buy a car dressed up for church,''
Kaminski says. ``We want to appear professional, but nowadays,
being professional doesn't mean wearing a three-piece suit.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, traditional business attire hasn't completely disappeared
from Fort Worth and surrounding areas. A stroll around downtown on
a recent 102 degree afternoon demonstrated that even the
combination of heat and casual Friday hasn't completely undermined
the custom of tie and jacket for men or business suit for women,
even if the dressed-for-success types looked a bit hot under the
collar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still fairly dressed up,'' says Barbara Ragland,
district director for U.S. Rep. Kay Granger's Fort Worth office.
Ragland says that some congressional offices require women to wear
dresses or skirts, but that women in Granger's Fort Worth office
can wear slacks as part of a suit.
</P>
<P>
   They may even wear western duds for Stock Show days, but there
are no casual Fridays because Mondays and Fridays are the days on
which Granger is most likely to be in Fort Worth and holding
important meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, Doug Ewert, vice president for merchandising at the
Men's Wear House, a chain that advertises lower prices for suits
than department stores, sees a definite trend toward casual
clothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're maximizing our sportswear,'' Ewert says. ``Casual office
is on fire.''
</P>
<P>
   But, like the mayor of Fort Worth, the typical customer at the
Men's Wear House is a little uncertain about acceptable business
casual, which is why Ewert's company is advertising the concept of
``casual know-how.'' This educates clientele about the differences
between totally casual and business casual _ the so-called third
wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   For women's wear, however, B.J. Wilson, a professional fashion
consultant and owner of the Dressoir boutique, an upscale women's
clothing store, says the trend may be coming full circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a lot of complaints about business casual,'' she
says. ``I think we're going back to more suits.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson says that it's very important that a woman in an office
with lots of men dress professionally: ``She needs the
credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the symphony orchestra, that last bastion of 19th-century
formal attire, is less committed to the traditional white tie and
tails. Although the old look prevails for the Fort Worth Symphony
at evening classical concerts, attire for Sunday afternoon concerts
changed 10 years ago to dark suits and ties for male orchestra
members. For children's concerts, the musicians wear bright colored
T-shirts, with a different color for each section of the orchestra;
for outdoor concerts, the musicians also wear more comfortable
T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, the Fort Worth Symphony may have more wardrobe
changes than a Cher concert. Although the orchestra will retain its
traditional theater-pit black-tie and tuxedo look when accompanying
the Fort Worth Dallas Ballet this season, male orchestra members
will be allowed to wear simple black shirts when accompanying the
opera, but not all in the name of comfort.
</P>
<P>
   There's a visual aspect to this dressing down, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sight lines at Bass Hall make the pit very visible,'' says
orchestra general manager John Toohey. ``And the black shirts make
less visual distraction.''
</P>
<P>
   So if you're feeling a little confused about how to dress for
work or play, or something in between, you're not alone. As Barr
says: ``It's not a revolution, it's evolution.''
</P>
<P>
   (Wayne Lee Gay is classical music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7756, or e-mail:
wlgay(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
