u i BC-DOMINICAN-UNDERDOG-AR     08-16 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOMINICAN-UNDERDOG-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (a and i coding)  
 HE'S THE DOMINICANS' HERO ON THE R.I. BALLOT  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He looked into the eyes of strangers, in a city 1,500 miles
away, a long-shot wannabe congressman short on cash. But at this
fundraiser in Miami, Angel Taveras stood before his people, meaning
he could forget _ for now _ being an everyman politican.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dominicano soy,'' Taveras bellowed. ``I am Dominican.''
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing lyrics from merengue crooner Fernandito Villalona,
Taveras continued, as the throngs of Dominican-Americans jumped to
their feet: ``I will never forget my roots. No matter how high I
climb, I will not forget my people!''
</P>
<P>
   In an instant, that Saturday in July, checkbooks flipped open.
Money poured into his campaign chest, adding to the thousands he's
gotten from fundraisers in Washington; New Jersey; New York.
</P>
<P>
   Taveras's face has been splashed on the front-page of newspapers
in the Dominican Republic. He's a household name among Dominicans
living in the United States. As the first Dominican-American to run
for Congress, he's hailed as the Great Dominican Hope.
</P>
<P>
   Back in his home state of Rhode Island, though, Taveras seems a
different man. There, outside of the small, but fast growing
Dominican community, he's relatively unknown and is said to have
little chance of winning the September 12 primary.
</P>
<P>
   Here, he does not shout ``Dominicano soy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a Latino candidate. I am not a Dominican candidate,''
he says with passion. ``I want to represent all people.''
</P>
<P>
   When Portugese-Americans ask, ``Taveras? Are you Portugese?'' he
tells them, with a wink, ``Of course.'' And if an Italian-American
asks the same question, he conjures similiar replies.
</P>
<P>
   Taveras said he doesn't change his persona to fit the audience,
but he knows he can't afford to come across as too Latino.
Hispanics make up just 5.1 percent of the district, with Dominicans
being a 1.6 percent chunk; plus they comprise an even lower
percentage of voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being latino has been an issue that continues to come up,''
Taveras said. ``I'm always concerned that people are going to box
me in. I am proud of my heritage and I wouldn't change that for
anything in the world. But I am much more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, Providence, and New York City, Dominicans are the
single largest incoming immigrant group. And they are the fastest
growing, too. In New York City, more Dominican babies were born
last year than any other ethnic group, according to tabulations by
the Dominican Studies Institute at the City College of New York.
</P>
<P>
   But Dominicans, as a bloc, do not vote in large numbers. Though
they contribute heavily to politicians in the homeland, they're
just beginning to use their growing wealth on US candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Dominicans raised $50,000 last October during two days of
fundraising in Greater Boston for Hipolito Mejia, who won the
presidency in the Dominican Republic. Scores of Dominican
immigrants flew from East Coast cities to the island on election
day to vote in the presidential elections. Mejia's party, the
Dominican Revolutionary Party, has a store-front headquarters in
Boston's Jamaica Plain neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   When Taveras speaks to other Dominicans, he scolds them, tells
them they can no longer focus just on homeland politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``People know more about politics back home than they do here,''
Taveras said. ``They can tell you in a second who is the vice
president of the Dominican Republic, but they can't always name the
vice president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Taveras spends most of his days traveling through Rhode Island's
Second Congressional district. As Taveras's campaign becomes a
rising call for Dominicans throughout the United States, the total
amount of out-of-state donations has edged out in-state
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   His last filing with the Federal Elections Commission shows 83
percent of donations came from outside Rhode Island. Just $1,045
came from his state, compared to $6,230 from New Jersey and $3,550
from New York. He's raised $120,000 so far, a quarter of the amount
of the candidate with the largest campaign chest.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction to his campaign has been jolting.
</P>
<P>
   Mejia called Taveras at home to invite him to his inauguration.
Spanish-language newspapers throughout the East Coast have run
profiles. Dominican Festivals, including one in Boston next month,
invite him to be a guest speaker. Strangers _ all of them Latino,
most of them Dominican _ plan fundraisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't expecting this outpouring,'' Taveras said.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Taveras, Dominican-Americans are running for the
Rhode Island State Senate, and for two seats in the New York State
Assembly. Backers give an almost knee-jerk embrace to the
candidates, because they so desperately want someone of their own
in office, any office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited because this kid, he's the future,'' said
entrepreneur Tony Barros of Jamaica Plain, a Dominican-American who
is one of Boston's most politically-connected Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   Taveras, who turns 30 next month, believes he can win. That's
because his whole life has been a crap shoot: raised by a single
mother in one of Providence's poorest neighborhoods, attended
public schools. Partly due to his mother's influence, and his shy,
bookish persona, he attended Harvard, then Georgetown Law School.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, he wore ``Steve Urkel'' glasses _ the name of the
nerdy character on the TV sitcom ``Family Matters.'' But he's
traded those in for Ralph Lauren.
</P>
<P>
   If his corporate attire gives one impression, his taste in music
and food, reveals another. He keeps the merengue music in his
mother's forest green Comanche playing. He comes home to a
Dominican meal every night, that his girlfriend, who is also
Dominican, prepares. He says he can never get enough deep-fried
chicken with heaps of pink beans on white rice.
</P>
<P>
   When he's on the phone with a non-Latino he uses his
Yankee-inflected voice. But if he's talking to another Latino, he
gives warm greetings like, ``Hola, hermano'' (hello, brother), all
in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Just the other day, as he was making a round of calls, asking
for support, he reached a Latino attorney in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was like, `You're the one! I heard of you,' '' Taveras
recounted. Before they hung up, he told him he would send him a
check.
</P>
<P>
   Another $200. More outside money for the Dominican underdog.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
