<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3517 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-CHIAPAS-$ADV20     08-16 2261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CHIAPAS-$ADV20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHIAPAS ELECTION THAT COULD FORCE NEW CHAPTER IN ZAPATISTA
CONFLICT
 &HT;    (1100&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    EDs: For purposes of a locator map, Yajalon is located about 90
miles north of San Cristobal de las Casas, in Chiapas state.
 &HT;    For Use Sun. Aug. 20 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   YAJALON, MEXICO _ Pigs snorted in mud and a chilly rain soaked
the mountains outside as Nicolas Lopez described how armed men
staged a terrifying raid on his hamlet earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Firing weapons into the air, the invaders claimed rights to the
villagers' land, setting fire to five huts, chasing about 30
families into hiding, and looting what little corn and clothes the
peasants had, Lopez said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as he shivered at the memory, Lopez managed a smile. On
Sunday(8/20) the Mayan Indian will vote in a historic election for
the new governor of Chiapas, one of Mexico's most impoverished and
volatile states. And if pre-election opinion polls are accurate,
Mexico's 71-year-old ruling party is headed for another defeat
after being trounced in July 2's presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are waiting for a solution to our problems,'' said Lopez,
who will vote for Pablo Salazar, candidate of an opposition
alliance that could unseat Mexico's Institutional Revolutionary
Party, the PRI, from a state considered a barometer of social
justice in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Chiapas is home to the Zapatista Indian rebels, who launched an
insurrection against the Mexican government here in January 1994
that still hasn't been resolved. Since that time, armed
paramilitary groups loyal to the ruling party have also evolved,
periodically attacking Zapatista sympathizers like Lopez's hamlet.
</P>
<P>
   ``All government ties to these paramilitary groups will end (if
the PRI loses). One way to dismantle these groups is to simply not
guarantee them impunity any longer,'' said a sweat-soaked Salazar,
pausing for an interview and quick lunch during one of his final
grueling all-day campaign swings along Chiapas' sweltering tropical
coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are fed up and want change. And change is contagious,''
he said, waving at a marimba band in a restaurant that played a
song as a tribute to the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   But Chiapas is considered a bulwark state for the PRI, and its
candidate, Sami David, has counted on a sympathetic state media
establishment that, as usual, offered slavishly favorable coverage
to him. A cordial man who is warm one-on-one, David also touched a
traditionally conservative nerve here with a campaign warning that
a Salazar victory could provoke even more instability.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Chiapas, an era of stability is at stake,'' David told a
recent gathering of PRI youth in the capital city of Tuxtla
Gutierrez.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the northern part of Chiapas is a checkerboard of Mayan
Indian villages divided between Zapatistas and PRI loyalists who
sporadically clash over land rights and political differences. The
collection of huts where Lopez lived _ nestled in rugged hills
above the city of Yajalon (pronounced, ``ya-ha-LONE'') _ was
eventually occupied by Mexican Army troops. But since the villagers
also fear the army, they refused to return.
</P>
<P>
   The election of Mexican President-elect Vicente Fox has sparked
hope for a peaceful resolution to the cycle of violence. Fox
ousted, for the first time in seven decades, the PRI, which the
Zapatistas blame for the squalid conditions the southern state's
Indians live in.
</P>
<P>
   Before the July 2 election, Subcommander Marcos, the primary
Zapatista spokesman, issued a statement reiterating the rebels'
position that they would negotiate again if a peace accord signed
in 1996 is implemented and federal troops are withdrawn from Indian
communities.
</P>
<P>
   Fox is a promoter of free-market economic policies, which the
Zapatistas oppose, but he has pledged to revive negotiations with
the rebels and send Mexico's Congress the stalled 1996 accord that
grants sweeping Indian rights. If elected, Salazar could also set
an example that change can be forced at the ballot box rather than
at gunpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one, not even the most radical person in the country can
dispute the legitimacy of a Fox government,'' Salazar said,
predicting that the Zapatistas can't dismiss electoral change.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent campaign stop in the gritty border town of Hidalgo
on the Guatemala border, supporters were enraptured with Salazar's
pledge to address the demands of the poor _ including the
Zapatistas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Zapatistas said our fight is against being forgotten. They
said there is a worse death than dying from diarrhea or from
curable diseases,'' the candidate shouted from the stage to wild
cheers. ``There is a worse death, say our Indian brothers, and that
is the death that comes from being forgotten. Well, you people are
about to do something about that painful reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Salazar is a federal senator and former member of the PRI, which
he says used to be the only option available to someone who wanted
to get into political office. But he left the party in May 1999
after a long string of disputes over the government's handling of
the Chiapas conflict.
</P>
<P>
   He is unaffiliated now, but is representing a four-party
alliance that includes Fox's conservative National Action Party, or
PAN, and the leftist Democratic Revolution Party, the PRD. The two
parties clash ideologically, but for the purpose of defeating the
PRI in Chiapas they pooled their funds and worked hand-in-hand for
Salazar.
</P>
<P>
   An exhausted-looking David said he isn't giving up, and he
dismisses polls like one conducted by Reforma newspapers, which
gave Salazar a 9-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Chiapas, the conditions to avoid confrontations or even
social collapse are being constructed with great difficulty,'' he
said an interview with Cox Newspapers. He had a badly bruised and
swollen ear, the result of an injury when someone threw a metal
weight at him in Salazar's hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a platform for electoral reform,'' he insisted. ``The
offers for change have to be based on clarity and not on
deception.''
</P>
<P>
   The PRI's presidential candidate, Francisco Labastida, won in
Chiapas last month. But Salazar is counting on the combined votes
of the PAN and the PRD to carry him to victory. His campaign pos
peasant farmers, Fox is now seen as Mexico's new ``tlatoani,'' the
Aztec word for ``maximum leader,'' Salazar campaign aide Mauricio
Gandara said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know that the 'Papa PRI' has died now. So they are
wondering who will be managing the money and resources. They are
thinking that now there is a 'Papa Fox,''' Gandara said. ``This is
the product of 71 years of domination by one party.''
</P>
<P>
   Araceli Burguete, a Chiapas sociologist, said the PRI still
controls many Indians in the state. It will probably be business as
usual in Indian towns where the local PRI leader habitually orders
residents how to vote, she said.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   But even in PRI strongholds, some residents appeared to be
bracing for change.
</P>
<P>
   Chenalrabian Nights' Entertainments.''
</P>
<P>
   That observation was made in 1908, but it still fits a city that
manages, amid its modernity, to stay alive with elegant detail.
</P>
<P>
   Cats slumber across finely carved tables with inlaid
mother-of-pearl oyster shell. Thick vines dangle over the walls of
the Old City. Diners smoke water pipes and sip tea in tile-lined
courtyards around quiet fountains. Swordmakers discuss their
ancient craft even as they consider advertising on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   As Syria slowly opens to the west, a small but growing number of
Americans are getting to know the exotic city of about 3 million
people.
</P>
<P>
   Damascus prides itself as the oldest capital in the world _
going back at least 5,000 years _ and as a showcase of Arab
tradition. It shows itself off with sometimes grand, and sometimes
funky flourishes. For the former, there's the stately tomb of
Saladin (pronounced, ``sala-DEEN''), probably the most heroic,
non-religious, Muslim figure in all history.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there's the army museum, where the power might go out as
you wander between the run-down artillery, tanks, rifles and the
dusty exhibit on Syrian Hamad Feris, who joined Soviet cosmonauts
in space. One of the few English signs at the exit states, with no
apparent irony, ``Tanks(CQ) for your visit.''
</P>
<P>
   For travelers, Syria is largely crime free. Arabic is the common
language and many Syrians also speak French. There are few
proficient English speakers, but some taxi drivers or hotel staff
will know a few words.
</P>
<P>
   Americans need to get a Syrian visa before departing. Those can
be obtained in about a week from Syrian embassies or consulates.
Syria still does not recognize Israel and will not grant visas to
people with Israeli stamps in their passports.
</P>
<P>
   The Syrian countryside is flush with archeological digs and
dozens of Crusader and Muslim castles. But the capital offers a
sampling of the great mix of cultures to come through this corner
of the Mediterranean. It's also a shopping wonder, offering rugs,
furniture and metal work from around the Middle East and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   A good place to start is the walled Old City. It's a large,
working district where Syrians shop for everything from clothes to
dehydrated Newts. Sold in jars in the medicinal herb stalls, a
paste of the little lizards is supposed to cure ills and provide
sexual vigor.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to other exotic venues where the locals serve the
tourists, in Damascus' Old City, the relatively few tourists and
locals line up together at the prime spots.
</P>
<P>
   That can be at Bakdash, a crowded ice cream parlor. It sells a
delicious firm ice cream that, for some reason, requires loud
pounding by fit men with wooden hammers.
</P>
<P>
   Or, it can be at the mausoleum of Saladin. He was the Muslim
general who ruled over most of the Arab world and drove the
European Crusaders out of Jerusalem. While his Crusader opponent,
England's Richard the Lion-Hearted, was known for brutality,
Saladin was honorable.
</P>
<P>
   He died in 1192 in Damascus. Though he is a hero of the Arabs,
he was an ethnic Kurd. You can still find Kurds _ who are mostly in
Turkey, Iraq, Iran and Syria _ visiting the tomb today.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the leader who conquered places taken by the
foreigners,'' said Kurd Ali Mohammed, 21, a laborer in Damascus.
``He was very powerful, but he was also very merciful.''
</P>
<P>
   There are actually two tombs. A faded box of carved,
walnut-colored wood appears to be the original. In 1899, Germany's
Kaiser Wilhelm II added a marble tomb beside it, in honor of
Saladin.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of streets away is the mausoleum of another central
figure in Middle Eastern history, Sultan Baibars (pronounced,
``BAY-bears''). He was the Mamluke ruler who, before his death in
1277, defeated the Mongols and almost finished off the Crusaders
who had hung on after Saladin. He was violent and unforgiving, but
his tomb is decorated with the palaces and lush plants awaiting him
in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the Old City is the Omayyad Mosque, a huge
courtyard bordered by a large prayer hall built around 708 A.D.
Inside and out are mosaics of glass beads from as far back as the
12th Century.
</P>
<P>
   The mingling between Islam and Christianity is apparent. The
mosque's minaret towers include the Jesus tower, where locals
believe he will return on judgment day. Inside the mosque is a
shrine to John the Baptist, revered and called Yahia by Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the mosque should remove their shoes, but keep their
arms and legs covered or borrow the robes offered at the ticket
office.
</P>
<P>
   The Old City also offers a Christian landmark. The underground
Chapel of Ananias is named after a disciple of Jesus who is
believed to have lived there. Ananias was ordered, according to the
New Testament, to go to ``the street can see Syria's ancient
history in the National Museum. Most explanations are in Arabic and
French, but the museum is excellent. Most interesting are the
expressive, big-eyed statuettes carveo stop and dash off some
postcards in the museum's tranquil archeological garden. Here,
under trees that quiet the city bustle outside the walls, you can
stroll amid detailed relief sculptures and statues that form the
foundations of today's Damascus.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow can be reached at LarryK(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ----------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   SYRIA: IF YOU GO . . .
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  VISAS: U.S. citizens need a Syrian tourist visa, which costs
$61. Visas can usually be obtained in a few days from the Syrian
embassy in Washington at 202-232-6313, ext. 106; the consulate in
Los Angeles at 949-640-9888; or the consulate in Houston at
713-622-8860.
</P>
<P>
   Visas are not given to people with Israeli stamps in their
passport.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  TRAVEL: Can be arranged for groups or individuals by
international trFrance and others do. ``Jordan and Syria, a Lonely
Planet Travel Survival Kit'' is a common and helpful guidebook.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  MONEY: The currency is the Syrian pound. Some hotels accept
American credANGUAGES: Arabic is the language of Syria, though some
Syrians speak French or English.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  WHERE TO STAY: Hotels in Syria cannclude Le Meridien, The
Sheraton and the Semiramis. All starting around $200 a night. The
Al-Faradis Hotel offers mid-range rooms starting at about $70 a
night. There are many other lower-cost hotels.
</P>
<P>
   In Palmyra, the Cham Palace is at the top end for $150 a night.
Mid-range hotels include the Heliopolis and the Zenobia for about
$80 a night. The Al-Najil is for backpackers as
</P>
