<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3519 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BETTE-0817-COX     08-16 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BETTE-0817-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Bette' sitcom could be divine or a miss
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - The Divine Miss M is going to squeeze her
oversized persona onto the small screen this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Although petite in stature, Bette Midler always seems bigger
than life, so the burning question is whether CBS's new sitcom,
``Bette,'' will blast off or bomb. Television has a long history of
rejecting movie and theater actors who loom large. Remember all the
failed attempts by James Earl Jones? Gene Wilder and Dabney Coleman
had tough runs, too.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Bette'' pilot has been generally well-received by critics.
Midler plays herself in a sitcom that pokes fun at her career, her
aging diva image in a youth-obsessed show business and her
real-life role as a wife and mother. There's some hilarious
physical shtick, which Midler does with ease, as well as some
vintage Midler singing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gee, I hope I won't be too far off the mark,'' Midler told TV
critics in a satellite press conference from Italy, where she was
vacationing with her husband, Martin von Haselberg, and 13-year-old
daughter, Sophie. ``It's a role I'm pretty comfortable with. A lot
of people have pitched ideas at me, but this was the truest.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS executives are high on ``Bette,'' but the show has drawn an
unenviable time slot - Wednesdays opposite ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire.'' It will take more than a good show and Midler's
famous name to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to promote, promote, promote, flog, flog, flog,''
she said laughing. ``Maybe Regis will get struck by lightning.''
</P>
<P>
   Midler, 54, has had a wild ride throughout her career, starting
with her offbeat stage shows and continuing through her more
mainstream recording and acting jobs. Her first album, ``The Divine
Miss M,'' went platinum and won a Grammy. She was nominated for an
Oscar for her first major role in ``The Rose'' but lost to Sally
Field (for ``Norma Rae'') _ a disappointment that's a running gag
in the sitcom pilot.
</P>
<P>
   If she wanted to, Midler could use her show to settle some old
scores in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I don't plan to do that at all,'' she said, wagging her
finger and allowing a sly smile to creep across her face. ``But if
it happens that way, it'd be great, wouldn't it? We'll be poking
fun at Hollywood, and I'd like to go as far as I can _ as far as
the network will let me go, which I assume will be pretty far. I've
had some very funny things happen to me and encountered some odd
people. I have a trunk full of stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Midler says she doesn't watch much TV _ just ``The Sopranos''
and ``Sex and the City'' on HBO, ``I Love Lucy'' reruns on
Nickelodeon and ``Friends'' on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I avoid anything that's saccharine or overly sentimental,''
she said. ``I like dry humor and physical humor.''
</P>
<P>
   But she's no stranger to the medium. She starred in several
splashy specials, including ``Clams on the Half Shell'' and ``Ol'
Red Hair Is Back,'' and guest starred on several sitcoms. She won
an Emmy for her touching guest stint on Johnny Carson's ``Tonight
Show'' farewell.
</P>
<P>
   Midler counts Jack Benny, George Burns and Jerry Seinfeld (all
of whom played themselves) among her TV heroes. And she's a huge
fan of Lucille Ball. What she hopes will distinguish her show from
other semiautobiographical series is music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a very firm intention to sing on this show,'' she said.
``There hasn't been a lot of pop music in sitcoms. That's something
special we can bring. I have a lot of songs and a lot of costumes
from the 30 years I've been in the business.''
</P>
<P>
   In the pilot, Bette is racked with self-doubt about her new
concert, her fading youth and her husband, who falls asleep while
she's putting on a sexy nightie one evening. One of the funniest
scenes in the pilot has Bette visiting a plastic surgeon for a
consultation and having her eyelids taped up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a good sense of what will embarrass my family,'' Midler
said. ``They're very good sports. They say, if it's funny I should
go for it. They liked the pilot, although they thought certain
things could be punched up. You know, everybody has an opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Midler has been scanning series scripts for years and decided to
do one now because Sophie is entering high school this fall, and
she wanted to be home for her daughter's ``tumultuous years.'' As
it turns out, however, filming will split the family for a while.
The show will be based in Los Angeles, rather than New York, where
the Midler trio lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crew and the rest of the cast didn't want to leave Los
Angeles, so I thought it would be better not to uproot everybody
else just so I could stay home,'' said Midler, who isn't the
flaming diva she's cracked up to be.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in real life, Midler is nothing like her stage persona.
She works tirelessly for AIDS awareness, literacy and environmental
causes, and she considers herself something of a homebody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a quiet soul who loves a good laugh,'' she said. ``My
behind-the-scenes life is pretty serious. I've been working hard to
lighten up a bit, but it's not easy, especially at my age.''
</P>
<P>
   If ``Bette'' clicks, Midler may take a break from plowing
through movie scripts. Like a lot of women her age, she's been
frustrated not only by the quality but also by the process of
moviemaking in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to wait 15 years in development and then try to get
the OK from some 25-year-old,'' she said. ``Forget about it. When
they learn to make movies, I'll be back.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dholloway(at)statesman.com or 445-3608.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
