<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-CONVENTION-CELEBRITIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD HAS AN UN-CONVENTIONAL RESPONSE TO DEMS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By MIKI TURNER 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Weeks before the Academy Awards, Los Angeles
becomes an even more glamorous city. The streets are swept at least
three times a week, Oscar banners adorn almost every available
light pole from Beverly Hills to South Central LA, and sometimes
the smog even goes on holiday.
</P>
<P>
   All of this so that the entertainment industry can applaud
itself while commoners, who camp out for days in one of the more
dangerous neighborhoods, jockey for position to catch a fleeting
glimpse of Brad and Jennifer, Tom and Nicole, or Gwyneth and her
boyfriend du jour.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing like improving your self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   The same scenario is repeated on a lesser scale before the
Emmys, Golden Globes, Screen Actors Guild Awards, Grammys, American
Music Awards and other celebratory events in which long, heartfelt
acceptance speeches are necessary.
</P>
<P>
   But this week, with the Democratic National Convention in town
for the first time since 1960, it doesn't look as if the City of
Angels has exactly rolled out the red carpet for Vice President Al
Gore, Sen. Joseph Lieberman and the party faithful. That's if you
don't count the new multimillion-dollar electronic LAX sign at the
airport and the red, white and blue lights at the top of the
Staples Center, where the convention is being held.
</P>
<P>
   The average Angeleno has greeted the convention with
indifference, or some resentment about traffic jams and other
impositions. Mayor Richard Riordan has been preoccupied with the
potential for violence by protesters and has had the police and
National Guard at the ready. The violence that marred the Lakers
NBA championship celebration in June is still fresh in the
collective memory.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a different story among the Hollywood set, which has an
ongoing love affair with politics. For celebrities, this has been
party week, with the entertainment industry pressing palms and
exchanging air kisses with Democrats from around the country. The
biggest affair was a $25,000-a-plate farewell to President Clinton,
but there have been numerous other festivities:
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Hefner has been holding bashes at the Playboy Mansion;
Arnold Schwarzenegger and Maria Shriver hosted a bevy of A-listers
at their Pacific Palisades estate; Barbra Streisand honored the
Clintons with a brunch at her Malibu digs; producer Yvette Lee
Bowser (''Living Single, For Your Love'') welcomed members of the
Congressional Black Caucus to her Encino home; and producer
Lawrence Bender (''Pulp Fiction'') held a fund-raiser for
Christopher Reeve's foundation.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget the flap caused by Orange County Congresswoman
Loretta Sanchez, who scheduled a Latino ``Get Out to Vote'' party
at Hefner's mansion despite Gore's objections. Sanchez, who was
going to lose her opportunity to address the convention as a
result, eventually relented and moved the party to Universal
Studios.
</P>
<P>
   There was more. The cast of NBC's ``The West Wing'' whooped it
up on a Warner Brothers lot; Gov. Gray Davis hosted a shindig on
the back lot of Paramount Studios; Sony feted Democratic governors;
and DreamWorks, which contributed $1 million to the Gore campaign,
saluted female Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there has been a convention going on, and if you're
watching any of it on TV, you might catch a glimpse of celebrities
who have free passes to the luxury boxes at the Staples Center.
They include Streisand, Steven Spielberg, Whoopi Goldberg, Richard
Dreyfuss, Martin Sheen, Patricia Arquette, Sheryl Crow, Alec and
Billy Baldwin, Woody Harrelson, Ben Affleck, Ted Danson, Quentin
Tarantino, Rob Reiner, Tom Hanks, Harry Belafonte, Danny Glover,
Christopher Reeve and Warren Beatty, who thought about running for
president earlier in the year. The less privileged, by the way, had
to pay a cool million for a luxury box.
</P>
<P>
   The celebrities _ as they sometimes do in their Oscar and Emmy
acceptance speeches _ have been using the convention platform to
trumpet their causes. Arquette, Danson and Harrelson are among
those pushing for better education; Reiner's endorsing more funding
for children's programs; and Reeve continues his quest to raise
awareness about spinal injuries.
</P>
<P>
   California Congresswoman Maxine Waters says that the celebrities
are passionate about those issues. ``These are all very legitimate
concerns that shouldn't be disregarded because celebrities are
behind them,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   But the convention isn't just a love-in. There is some
apprehension in Hollywood about the strong stance that Lieberman,
the Democratic vice presidential nominee, has taken in the past
against sex and violence in the movies. Jack Valenti, longtime
president of the Motion Picture Association of America, told
``Variety'' that there have been ``calls of puzzlement and
bewilderment and some anger and frustration.''
</P>
<P>
   But Valenti told ``The Hollywood Reporter'' he believes that
Lieberman's views are not politically motivated, but reflect a
genuine concern about the issue.
</P>
<P>
   None of this appears to trouble at least one studio _ DreamWorks
SKG _ owned by Spielberg, David Geffen and Jeffrey Katzenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg issued a statement saying that Lieberman is a
``tough, honest, independent man of the highest integrity, who is
ultimately fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Some in Hollywood were hoping that Lieberman would make an
outreach gesture and perhaps attend one of the back-lot parties.
``You know, just to show he was down with the cause,'' says Wesley
Parks, a 35-year-old production assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, though, that would be like a scene from a really bad
movie. Or it could be par for the course in LA.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
