<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3531 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-CVN-WHIP-RACE-HNS &LR;      08-16 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-WHIP-RACE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CALIFORNIAN CAMPAIGNS FOR HOUSE LEADERSHIP POST 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (ATTN: Calif., Md.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ZACHARY COILE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. _ Inside the ritzy ballroom of the Regent
Beverly Wilshire, across the street from the boutiques of Rodeo
Drive, Rep. Nancy Pelosi of California is working the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The event is a fund-raiser for EMILY's List, an organization
that supports female Democratic candidates who favor abortion
rights, and the crowd is mostly well-heeled women who have paid
$250 a plate for the luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi spots women she knows and tenderly squeezes their arms.
``Helloooo!'' she says, flashing a wide smile to each one. ``So
good to see you.''
</P>
<P>
   In the realm of politics and raising money, the seven-term
congresswoman from San Francisco is a master in the art of the
political schmooze. As a Democratic activist and money-raiser for
more than 30 years, she has built a formidable network of political
donors.
</P>
<P>
   This year's elections could be payback time for Pelosi, 60. If
Democrats win a majority in the House of Representatives, the
lawmaker hopes to become majority whip, the third-ranking position
in House leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi does not say she has a lock on the job, which in any case
hinges on her party regaining control of the House. But she said a
majority of House Democrats have committed to supporting her bid
for the post.
</P>
<P>
   At the Democratic National Convention this week, party leaders
are relishing the possibility. Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., drew a
roar at the EMILY's List event when she said: ``Wouldn't it be
incredible to finally have a woman in the leadership of the House
of Representatives?''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi is not unchallenged in her quest: Rep. Steny H. Hoyer of
Maryland is vying for the whip's position. He, too, has campaigned
for other Democrats and he has said he is confident of winning.
</P>
<P>
   If the Democrats win a majority in the House for the first time
since 1994, Richard A. Gephardt of Missouri, now the minority
leader, would become speaker. David E. Bonior of Michigan, now the
minority whip, would become majority leader. That leaves an opening
in the No. 3 job _ the person who counts votes and works to rally
party members to support the leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Any candidate would need a majority of votes from the Democratic
Caucus, which now has 210 members. There are 223 Republicans and
two independents in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are raising money at a record pace for the fall
campaign. Pelosi estimates she has raised close to $3 million
already for the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee and in
direct contributions to party candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi acknowledges her fund-raising prowess is a large part of
why she is in the running for the whip job.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be able to win and retain a majority,'' she said
Tuesday. ``You have to be able to pay the bills. If you can't pay
the bills, why would you say, `I should be a leader?'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi grew up around politics, the daughter of Thomas
D'Alesandro Jr., who represented Baltimore for five terms in
Congress before he became mayor of the city for three terms. Her
brother, Thomas D'Alesandro III, also served a term as Baltimore
mayor. But Pelosi says she never saw herself in public office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought in terms of being always involved _ a supporter, a
volunteer, a contributor _ but I didn't think in terms of
running,'' she said. While she raised five children, Pelosi rose
through the ranks of party politics in California, becoming
Northern California chairwoman and then state chairwoman of the
California Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   When Rep. Sala Burton became ill shortly after being sworn into
office in January 1987, Burton asked Pelosi to run to succeed her.
When Burton died several weeks later, Pelosi ran and won a special
election in June 1987.
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, Pelosi is best known for her vocal criticism of
China's human rights record and her push for more federal money for
AIDS research and treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know politics,'' Pelosi said. ``It's about understanding the
impact on a member of a certain vote, and understanding what it
takes for that person to win in their district. And that's in my
blood.''
</P>
</TEXT>
