A3532 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MINOR-COLUMN0817-COX     08-16 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINOR-COLUMN0817-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Movies! LEGOS! Harry Potter meets the big money machine
 &HT;    By Emily Minor
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - His name is Harry Potter and he's
magical and mystical and he has beckoned kids to books like few
before his time. He eats frog-flavored candy and plays football in
the air. He's a kind underdog with a tainted past. But the
simplicity of all that's about to change, because Harry's jumping
off the pages and onto our movie screens, our video screens, right
into our kids' fast-food meal bags.
</P>
<P>
   It's starting, the commercialization of Harry Potter. It isn't
omnipresent quite yet. Time Inc.'s Warner Bros. unit, which has the
rights for the movie and the paraphernalia, is starting out slowly.
T-shirts, backpacks, pens, book covers. ``We can't keep the stuff
in the store,'' says the clerk at the Warner Bros. store in Palm
Beach Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   But it won't be too long before the movie is out (November 2001)
and the T-shirts are everywhere and the magic of Harry has turned
into materialistic madness. Gone are the days when the child with
$4 and the child with $400 could absorb the exact same magic from
Harry's funny, fabulous life.
</P>
<P>
   The LEGO company has bought the rights for Harry Potter LEGOS.
Soon we'll all be stepping on little plastic Harrys and Rons and
Hermiones in the dark of the night. A California company has bought
the rights to the video games. Electronic Arts said it plans to
publish games based on all four Harry Potter books, the upcoming
movie and all subsequent movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``EA has accepted the challenge to create a series of
interactive games that reflect the incredible imagination of J.K.
Rowling's books,'' says Don Mattrick, president of EA worldwide
studios. ``We are extremely excited to become part of the Harry
Potter phenomenon by bringing our own brand of interactive magic to
this fantastic series.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, what he's really saying is, ``Honey, order that
Lexus. We're rich.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the world, the Potter books have done something many
teachers haven't been able to do for years. They've turned kids
into bookworms. I've watched my kid read book one, then two, then
three and four. Then I watched him do it all over again. And now
I'll watch, with heavy heart, as he stands 2 inches from the
television screen, maneuvering through a video-game inventor's idea
of Hogwarts. He'll clutch the plastic video controls with the same
hands that once held the hard-covered books.
</P>
<P>
   I hold no grudges against J.K. Rowling, the 34-year-old former
welfare mother who's richer than rich because of her books. She's
marvelous. She deserves all this fortune. The books are amazing.
</P>
<P>
   But gone are the nights when children snuggled under the covers,
the bedspread pulled up around their heads, to explore the silent
magic of Harry's world. Gone are the nights when his next crazy
adventure kept the pages flipping long after light's out. Harry
Potter was so wonderful when he was just words on a page. Now it's
come down to what it always comes down to. Money from our wallets.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: emilyminor(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
