<HEADER>
A3535 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS &LR;      08-16 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JUSTICE DEPARTMENT SAYS IT WAS UNFAIRLY CRITICIZED IN NEWSPAPER
DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB EGELKO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Stung by a federal judge's attack on the
government's investigation of the sales of the San Francisco
Chronicle and the San Francisco Examiner, the Justice Department's
antitrust chief wants all critical references edited out of the
court decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely no political considerations, nor any factors beyond
enforcing the law, influenced any aspect of the department's
work,'' Assistant Attorney General Joel Klein said in a letter to
U.S. District Judge Vaughn Walker.
</P>
<P>
   In a terse reply, Walker refused to change his ruling but said
the Justice Department was welcome to make a formal request to
reopen the case or have him reconsider his findings _ alternatives
that could subject the department to questioning about its motives
in the case. Department spokeswoman Gina Talamona declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   The department letter, dated last Thursday, and Walker's answer,
dated Monday, were both made public Tuesday by the judge.
</P>
<P>
   Walker approved the Hearst Corp.'s $660 million purchase of the
Chronicle on July 27 and also found no basis to interfere with
Hearst's sale of The Examiner to local publisher Ted Fang, despite
his doubts about the legality of the $66 million subsidy Fang will
receive.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge's 46-page ruling denounced the role of the Justice
Department, which objected to Hearst's proposal to buy the
Chronicle and close The Examiner when no buyer could be found. The
department dropped its objection after the Fang transaction was
announced in March.
</P>
<P>
   Noting Fang's alliance with Mayor Willie Brown, who had
previously written to Attorney General Janet Reno opposing a
shutdown of The Examiner, Walker said he reached ``the uneasy
inference that the cronyism that fueled the Fang transaction at the
local level also exerted influence over the (Department of Justice)
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Flaws in the department's analysis may have been due to ``lack
of knowledge and inexperience in the newspaper industry,'' but also
could justify an inference that ``its action or inaction in this
case was political favoritism masquerading as law enforcement,''
Walker wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Klein, appointed by President Clinton as head of the Justice
Department's Antitrust Division, said in his letter last week that
Brown's letter to Reno last year was ``wholly unremarkable'' and
had no effect on the department's investigation. Klein said he knew
nothing about Brown's relationship with Fang until he read Walker's
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Klein said the ``distinguished team of career department lawyers
and economists'' reviewing the case included two members with over
a decade of experience in newspaper cases and others with decades
of antitrust experience.
</P>
<P>
   He also spelled out, in greater detail than past communications,
the differences between the department's and Walker's views about
the effects of the newspaper sales on competition.
</P>
<P>
   Walker was particularly critical of the department's suggestion
to Hearst that any offer to sell The Examiner include the
newspaper's share of its joint operating agreement with the
Chronicle, which was scheduled to run through 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Klein said the department wasn't suggesting that the agreement
had to be preserved at all costs, only that The Examiner's value to
a potential buyer should include a sum that represented its right
to divide profits with the Chronicle for the remainder of the JOA.
A buyer willing to pay more than that sum would likely try to
maintain a competitive newspaper after the JOA expired, Klein said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nor did we require that Hearst divest assets to a particular
buyer,'' Klein wrote. ``Any suggestion that we supported favorable
treatment for ExIn (Fang's company), the eventual buyer of Examiner
assets, is unfounded.''
</P>
<P>
   He concluded by asking Walker to withdraw all portions of the
ruling that ``contain any statements about the Department of
Justice's motives or any suggestions of political influence on our
investigation and analysis of the Hearst matter.''
</P>
<P>
   In reply, Walker noted that the Justice Department had rejected
his two previous invitations to enter the case or provide a full
explanation of its views, instead sending brief letters that
outlined its actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it difficult to sympathize with your present concern
that the department's position was not adequately represented,''
the judge wrote. He also said he believed Klein had ``misread
portions of the decision.''
</P>
</TEXT>
