<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3547 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-VEGETARIANVIRTUOSO-TE     08-16 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VEGETARIANVIRTUOSO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPERCHEF DEBORAH MADISON ENCOURAGING US TO RECONNECT WITH THE
LAND
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BEVERLY BUNDY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA FE, N.M. _ Deborah Madison, her long fingers cupping an
imaginary bowl, is explaining the precepts of begging in Buddhism.
The student, it's now apparent, has become teacher.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a journey of discovery for this California girl, an
embodiment of one of the most lasting movements of her generation.
Founding chef of the nation's most important vegetarian restaurant
and author of seminal vegetarian cookbooks, Madison is a member of
the pantheon that also honors Alice Waters and Mollie Katzen.
</P>
<P>
   But on this clear August day in her New Mexico house, she
doesn't want to talk about vegetarianism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sick to death of vegetarianism,'' she says, tucking her
foot under her body on the denim-covered sofa. ``Vegetarianism is
fine, but I'm not a promoter. I've never been drawn to limits. I
think vegetarians can be very self-absorbed; it's just a little too
precious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of worrying about whether a cheese includes rennet or
not, we should be thinking about where that cheese came from, what
the land was like, how far it traveled.''
</P>
<P>
   This may sound like heresy to Madison's fans, baby boomers who
have followed her career through Greens restaurant in San Francisco
and her books such as ``Vegetarian Cooking for Everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Call her an accidental vegetarian.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, as a member of a Zen Buddhist study/living center
near Big Sur, Madison helped prepare the group's meals. Although
the tenets of Buddhism vary on the issue of consuming fish and
fowl, for the harmony of the center it was agreed that all the
meals would be vegetarian.
</P>
<P>
   With some encouragement from visitors who had enjoyed the food
at the center, it was agreed that a natural-foods restaurant in San
Francisco might be a good project. In 1979, Greens was born.
</P>
<P>
   Greens was an immediate success _ within three weeks of opening,
Madison, with only minimal restaurant experience, was feeding 300
people a day at lunch. No longer was natural food dark and drab and
heavy and mean.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very picky about what we served,'' Madison says. ``There
were no parsley and orange slice garnishes. We didn't serve sprouts
unless they were essential to the dish. I wanted the food to be
contemporary and bright and delicious.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, exhausted by her success, Madison left Greens
to be private chef for the director at the American Academy in
Rome. After a year, she returned to Berkeley to write the
``Greens'' cookbook because ``I had put 15 years of my life into
that food.''
</P>
<P>
   Madison's success with that book enabled her to have a writing
career and to press for her passion: re-establishing our
connections with the land. She is a fierce proponent of the Santa
Fe Farmers' Market, a 25-year-old twice-weekly market that
showcases the wares of as many as 100 northern New Mexico food
producers.
</P>
<P>
   And with her no-limits philosophy, Madison is inclusive with her
effusiveness over this booming enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the farmers are organic, some aren't. These farmers
are keeping local agriculture traditions alive _ and if we don't do
that, what will the land become? Another trailer park, a golf
course. We'll never get that land back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a local chicken farmer who has a fairly small
operation near Socorro. But he does have 10,000 chickens. You go to
his farm and you don't smell them, you don't hear them. Their huts
are moved twice a day so the land is more fertile and there's no
run-off of pollutants into the Rio Grande. He keeps the flocks
together as they grow, so there's no re-establishment of pecking
order every time they're separated, making for less stress for the
birds. These are important things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Food is really grown in the garden; it is only finished in the
kitchen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People tell me all the time that they don't have time to cook.
Well, how hard is it to slice a really good tomato? And how hard is
it to serve a wonderful, juicy peach? It's not. But when you have a
bad peach, what do you do? You make a crisp. So you have to have
cream and butter, and it gets very involved.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A connection to our food is a very fundamental thing; we need
to have a relationship with our food and its source, and I
shouldn't even have to be saying that,'' Madison says.
</P>
<P>
   But she does, and most likely, like the California girl that she
is, she will keep on saying that.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or e-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
