u i BC-INDONESIA-POLITICS-(T     08-16 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-POLITICS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT EMPHASIZES UNITY IN ADDRESS TO LEGISLATURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ With puns, jokes and a touch of naughty
wordplay, President Abdurrahman Wahid lifted the mood of
Indonesia's bitterly feuding legislature Wednesday, soothing its
members with the fundamental message of his presidency: debate and
disagreement are acceptable, even healthy.
</P>
<P>
   In an extemporaneous address that epitomized the sea change he
has brought to politics and leadership in Indonesia, Wahid drew
repeated laughter, sometimes chuckling himself as he spoke.
</P>
<P>
   The 700 legislators, who had greeted him mostly with hostility
throughout the bulk of a two-week special session, frequently
interrupted him with applause.
</P>
<P>
   Divided among themselves, against the president and along
religious and political lines, the lawmakers applauded when Wahid
stated his credo of ``tolerance, diversity and the rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia continues to struggle with widespread violence,
economic stagnation and political infighting ten months into
Wahid's presidency. Though he is disorganized and politically weak,
Wahid has offered at least a democratic compass as Indonesia seeks
to reorient itself after three decades of dictatorship under former
President Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid's message of the free exchange of ideas has not yet taken
root in a society where public differences can be seen as taboo and
disagreement can be taken as enmity.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Wahid was once again the Muslim teacher of his
roots, using humor, parables and indirection to make his points.
And he reminded the assembly, meeting on Indonesia's 55th National
Day, of the nation's credo: unity in diversity.
</P>
<P>
   The change he offers is a shift in emphasis. Where Suharto
employed the strong arm of the military and enforced unquestioning
unity, Wahid celebrates diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to defuse tensions, he joked about the multiplicity of
languages, ethnicities and religions in this sprawling archipelago
and its 210 million people.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Wahid startled the legislature into laughter by
making a pun on a political acronym and producing the words
``hanging out your underwear.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So here's an example of how we are different but we use
tradition in our daily lives to accommodate our differences,'' he
said over the laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Then, using a characteristic turn of phrase, he said: ``We
shouldn't make a big deal out of it. It's normal. I hope we can be
mature enough to discuss any kind of problem that we have, because
each of us has his own ideas. This kind of openness will preserve
the treasure of our diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The same diversity was welcome in the legislature itself, the
president said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been very impressed with this assembly,'' he said. ``We
have had an open debate, and this showed that we have a warm
brotherhood and people can speak their minds. We don't have to be
worried or suspicious because there is no regime to haunt us.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Making an example of one of the most contentious issues of the
moment, he said he welcomed opposition to his proposal to lift a
ban on communism, a move he has described as part of his philosophy
of inclusiveness. But he said he, too, had the right to his
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a good dialogue in the right place,'' he said, ``and in
full view of the public so that the public can contribute its own
ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``It's nothing to be ashamed of if we express
different opinions. It's something we should be proud of because it
is the realization of our credo, unity in diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   Wahid's remarks lasted only a few minutes. He was followed at
the podium by Vice President Megawati Sukarnoputri who read his
formal speech, calling for national reconciliation, promising
economic revival and saying Indonesia should learn from its
mistakes and move forward.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid is virtually blind, and all his speeches to the assembly
have been read for him by an aide. Megawati's agreement to read his
speech Wednesday, and her public contribution to its drafting,
signaled a rapprochement in the political standoff that has been an
undercurrent of the session.
</P>
<P>
   Facing concerted challenges to his authority, Wahid has shown
that he not only has a broad vision for Indonesia but that he is
also its most agile political infighter.
</P>
<P>
   As the assembly approaches its conclusion this week, its
politics have come full circle, with the power alignment at the top
much as it was before, despite Wahid's promise to give his vice
president more administrative duties.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats and political analysts said its main accomplishment
may have been to begin clarifying the political playing field and
the balance between executive and legislative power in post-Suharto
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Talk of impeachment has disappeared. The president has been
given a second chance. In the coming days, he is expected to name a
new Cabinet and a new economic team in what amounts to a fresh try
at making his government more focused and productive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
