   By giving Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman, a religious Jew, a chance to
enthuse about his maker on a campaign rally platform, Al Gore took
a big step toward legitimizing the public display of religious
fervor. Suddenly, God isn't just for Christians anymore.
</P>
<P>
   But what about all the Americans who don't think anybody's God
has a place on the public square? Do all these frank confessions of
faith by candidates, whatever their denomination, threaten to blur
the line between church and state?
</P>
<P>
   700 words: Slugged BC-LIEBERMAN'S-GOD-THING
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   3. ELITIST PREP SCHOOL IN D.C. IS GORE'S LITTLE SECRET, by David
Plotz
</P>
<P>
   Delegates to the Democratic convention will be harangued with
endless hay-strewn yarns about Al Gore's rustic Tennessee
childhood, but they will not hear one word about the place where
Gore spent most of his formative years: St. Albans School.
</P>
<P>
   The veep's in good company. The Washington, D.C. prep school has
become the spawning ground for the Democratic Party. Sen. Evan Bayh
of Indiana, who was short-listed for Gore's running mate, is a St.
Albans alumnus. Fellow short-listee Sen. John Kerry of
Massachusetts attended St. Albans for several years. Rep. Harold
Ford Jr., the convention's keynote speaker and the youngest member
of Congress, was in my class at St. Albans.
</P>
<P>
   1,260 words: Slugged BC-PREP-SCHOOL-DEMOCRATS-SLATE
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   4. THE PARTY OF LINCOLN IS NOT THE PARTY OF TODAY, by David
Greenberg
</P>
<P>
   Now that its convention is over, will the Republican Party keep
pretending that it likes black people? As the Philadelphia story
would have it, attracting black voters simply means returning to a
proud history from which the GOP has only recently deviated.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the history of the Republican Party's relationship
with blacks is one of a bright start followed by a gradual but
steady decline.
</P>
<P>
   1,630 words: Slugged BC-HOW-REPUBLICANS-LOST-BLACKS-SLATE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 1547EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000816.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3556 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-CONCORDE-0817     08-16 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-CONCORDE-0817-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STATUS OF CONCORDES IN LIMBO FOLLOWING FRENCH, BRITISH GROUNDING
 &HT;    (800&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ It could be months before the supersonic Concorde flies
again following Wednesday's official grounding by aviation
authorities, alarmed that a tire failure led to last month's fiery
crash near Paris that killed 113 people.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft's designers have begun the complex process of
developing a modification to the 30-year-old aircraft that will
assure regulators that there will be no repeat of the Air France
crash.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have determined that the accident was caused by a
chain of events set off by the rupture of one or more of the
Concorde's tires, a relatively routine event for passenger planes,
air safety officials said. The Concorde crashed less than two
minutes after the tire burst, which sent debris rifling through its
wings and rupturing fuel tank.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Malcolm Field, chairman of the British Civil Aviation
Authority, told reporters at a news conference that the burst tire
was the primary cause of the crash. ``What is uniquely different in
this case is that tire debris alone is thought to have led to this
catastrophic accident,'' Field said.
</P>
<P>
   Field said that a single tire failure should never be enough to
bring down a passenger aircraft, adding that it was only by ``the
grace of God'' that there had not been another Concorde crash.
</P>
<P>
   France' General Direction for Civil Aviation also decided
Wednesday to suspend the Concorde's certification, the Transport
Ministry said. The move was largely academic, because all Air
France Concordes have been grounded in the three weeks since the
accident.
</P>
<P>
   The BEA recommended that the certificated be suspended until
``appropriate measures guaranteeing a satisfactory level of
security as far as the risks linked to the destruction of the
tires'' can be implemented.
</P>
<P>
   ``The BEA has determined that it was the destruction of a tire _
a simple event which one cannot be sure will not happen again _
that caused various damages to the structure and systems of the
plane, leading to the crash less than one minute and 30 seconds
after the destruction of the tire,'' the agency said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Aviation officials said Concorde's manufacturers will have to
develop a way to end the risk that a burst tire will have the
potential of causing a crash, which is a requirement for a
passenger aircraft to be issued an airworthiness certificate.
</P>
<P>
   The companies that built the Concorde in the 1970s are now part
of European Aeronautic Defense &AMP; Space Co. and Britain's BAE
Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Once a solution is designed, it will then be a financial matter
for British Airways and Air France, the only airlines to operate
the Concorde. Even before the crash, both airlines said the sleek
supersonic aircraft would be retired in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, British Airways said it would meet with
manufacturers and air safety officials to develop measures to get
its flagship aircraft flying again. The airline said its seven
Concordes would be kept ready to resume service with 24 hours
notice.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Street, the airlines' director of customer services and
operations, pledged that British Airways would keep safety
paramount. ``We will only resume Concorde operations when we and
the airworthiness authorities are completely satisfied that all
necessary safety measures have been taken in the light of all the
latest information,'' Street said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Bell, another official with the British Civil Aviation
Authority, said he expected it would be ``months rather than
weeks'' before the Concorde flies again. British Airways, which
resumed flying its Concordes the day after the July 25 crash in
Gonesse, France, cancelled its flights until September. Air France
has not flown its remaining five aircraft since the crash, and has
given no indication when it expects to resume its supersonic
operations.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways said it may use the down time to carry out a $22
million re-fit of its Concorde cabins, a project originally
scheduled for early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Paul-Louis Arslanian, the head of France's Air Accident
Investigation Bureau, told reporters in Paris that he hoped the
supersonic aircraft would return to the skies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Concorde is an extraordinary symbol. A symbol of progress,''
Arslanian said at a news conference. ``I hope the Concorde will fly
again, but I am an investigator of accidents, not a witch doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   While investigators said last week the crash stemmed from a tire
blow-out caused by a 16-inch metal strip on the runway, experts
said Wednesday that a chunk of rubber from the tire _ not metal
from the undercarriage _ probably punctured at least one fuel tank.
</P>
<P>
   British officials said Concordes had suffered 70 previous tire
blowouts since entering service in 1976, seven of them rupturing
fuel tanks in the wings.
</P>
<P>
   But in each of these cases, the tire explosion had knocked off a
piece of metal that had pierced the wing. Consequently, regulators
have focused on reinforcing metal parts instead of the rubber
tires.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Devising modifications to prevent a similar catastrophe will be
a huge and potentially expensive technical challenge, aviation
experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Kieran Daly, the editor of the aviation website Air Transport
Intelligence, said the airlines and manufacturers would have to
consider strengthening the tires, which are made by Goodyear Tire &AMP;
Rubber Co. and Dunlop Tire Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other possible solution is strengthening the structure
around the fuel tank but that would have a very serious weight
penalty,'' Daly said. ``It would also take a considerable time to
devise that fix and get it on the aircraft _ months or more. The
most practical idea may be devising some sort of casing around the
tires _ a shield.''
</P>
<P>
   Jane's Aviation security editor Chris Yates said such a shield
might have to be made of titanium for the metal's strength and
lightness. However, Yates said this solution may not be financially
feasible for an aircraft that has a maximum of 15 years left to
operate.
</P>
<P>
   ``One has to question whether the cost of doing that would
outweigh the benefit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s E-mail address is: bertr(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.rati.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.bea-fr.org/
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
