<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3563 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX     08-16 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE THAT'S EASY TO MAKE AT HOME
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BEVERLY BUNDY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A couple of readers have recently written looking for simple
Chinese recipes. Chinese food is scary for some of us; the
ingredients seem odd and the wok and other equipment can be
intimidating.
</P>
<P>
   In such cases, I recommend books published by, for example,
Better Homes &AMP; Gardens, Sunset and HP. Geared to American kitchens,
these books take a realistic, hands-on approach without sending the
Asian cuisine novice to the far reaches of groceryland for
ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Try these recipes before moving on to books by Martin Yan and
Ken Hom.
</P>
<P>
   Our first letter-writer would like a recipe for fried rice.
Chinese cooking does not require a wok, although using one makes
you look as if you really know what you're doing in the kitchen. A
well-seasoned cast-iron skillet will work just as well; you'll
simply need to stir often. (The wok was invented to have sloping
sides with no hard-to-reach corners where food can stick at high
heat.)
</P>
<P>
   This week, we're running three variations of fried rice. Next
week it's on to wonton soup, pepper steak, and shrimp in lobster
sauce.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   FRIED RICE WITH PEAS AND HAM
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 slices fresh ginger, see Note
</P>
<P>
   2 scallions, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup peas, fresh or frozen
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup (4 ounces) ham, diced
</P>
<P>
   3 cups cold cooked rice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   Note: Fresh ginger is sold in the produce section. Don't buy
more than you will use in about a week. Simply break off the amount
you need at the grocery store. To use, peel off the brown, papery
outside, then cut off the amount called for in the recipe. Wrap
remainder in plastic wrap and store in refrigerator. Do not
substitute ground, dried ginger from the spice section.
</P>
<P>
   In skillet, heat oil until just smoking. Add ginger and cook
until golden, 1 to 2 minutes. Remove and discard. Add minced
scallions, peas and ham. Stir-fry over medium heat until warm,
about 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add rice and continue to stir-fry until hot, 3 to 5 minutes.
Season with salt and pepper. Toss to blend well, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 378 calories, 14 grams fat, 50
grams carbohydrates, 13 grams protein, 17 milligrams cholesterol,
1,060 milligrams sodium, 32 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _''365 Ways to Cook Chinese'' by Rosa Lo San Ross
``HarperCollins, $17.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SHRIMP FRIED RICE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6-8
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 scallions, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fresh minced ginger, see Note
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound medium shrimp, shelled, deveined and cut into 1/2-inch
pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup coarsely chopped water chestnuts
</P>
<P>
   4 cups cold cooked rice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon ketchup
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cayenne
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   Note: Fresh ginger is sold in the produce section. Don't buy
more than you will use in about a week. Simply break off the amount
you need at the grocery store. To use, peel off the brown, papery
outside, then cut off the amount called for in the recipe. Wrap
remainder in plastic wrap and store in refrigerator. Do not
substitute ground, dried ginger from the spice section.
</P>
<P>
   In skillet, heat oil until just smoking. Add scallions, garlic
and ginger. Stir-fry over high heat until aromatic, about 30
seconds. Add shrimp and water chestnuts. Stir-fry until shrimp turn
pink, about 3 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add rice and continue stir-frying until rice is hot, 3 to 5
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In small bowl, combine soy sauce, ketchup, wine and cayenne.
Pour over rice and stir to mix well. Season to taste with salt and
pepper. Remove from heat and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 220 calories, 6 grams fat, 32
grams carbohydrates, 9 grams protein, 43 milligrams cholesterol,
322 milligrams sodium, 24 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _''365 Ways to Cook Chinese''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   FRIED RICE WITH EGGS AND SCALLIONS
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6-8
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   4 cups cold cooked rice
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   2 scallions, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   In skillet, heat oil until just smoking. Add cold rice and
stir-fry over high heat until hot, 3 to 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Reduce heat to medium, pour in beaten eggs and stir constantly
so eggs coat rice grains as they set. Add scallions and soy sauce
and stir-fry 2 minutes. Season with salt and pepper to taste.
Remove from heat and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per tablespoon: 236 calories, 9 grams fat,
30 grams carbohydrates, 6 grams protein, 0 cholesterol, 289
milligrams sodium, 37 percent of calories from fat
</P>
<P>
   _''365 Ways to Cook Chinese''
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or e-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 1557EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000816.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3564 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX     08-16 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE THAT'S EASY TO MAKE AT HOME
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
