<DOCNO> NYT20000816.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3568 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i BC-WIDOW-THRESHER0817-CO     08-16 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIDOW-THRESHER0817-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Widow of Thresher officer recalls the fear and the loss
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - If there is such a thing as a primal
fear, a terror universal to mankind, this is it: to be trapped
alive, wrapped in a deadly embrace of the sea and cold steel,
perhaps to be entombed, at depths beyond escape, like the Russian
submariners in their boat at the bottom of the Barents Sea.
</P>
<P>
   People worldwide may hope, pray, wish for a successful rescue.
All can share in the hope, as well as imagine fear.
</P>
<P>
   But few, very few, can muster for the Russian sailors and their
families the empathy Joyce Smarz of Palm Beach Gardens possesses.
Her husband, Lt. John Smarz Jr., was lost with 128 crew mates when
the USS Thresher went down, April 10, 1963. Joyce Smarz knows more
than the fears. She knows the loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``John said submarines were the safest place to be on the
planet,'' she says. ``He loved the boats. He was one of the rare
enlisted men to come up through the ranks and become an officer. He
served on the first nuclear submarine, the Nautilus. And he served
on the Thresher. And he died on the Thresher.''
</P>
<P>
   John Smarz was right. Mile for mile, man for man, subs are safe
_ safer than airplanes and cars and trains. Only two American subs
have gone down since World War II _ the Thresher in 1963, and the
Scorpion in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Russian subs have not fared as well _ more than 20 Russian and
Soviet subs were heavily damaged and at least four sank during the
Cold War and the years following. One was seriously damaged in 1993
after colliding with a U.S. nuclear sub in the Barents Sea, an
incident that underscores a fact submariners know but Hollywood
can't abide: Even crammed full of modern sonar and radar, subs are
hard to find, almost impossible to ``see.''
</P>
<P>
   John Smarz was right. But aboard the Thresher, on that cold
spring day in 1963, everything that could go wrong did.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had just moved to New London (Conn.),'' says Joyce Smarz.
``Thresher was out of Portsmouth, New Hampshire, on a test cruise.
But it was going to be based in New London. It was two weeks to the
day since we moved into the house. Navy housing. The Navy gave John
a short leave to come home for a couple of days because our son was
sick. Then he went back to Portsmouth, to the Thresher. That was on
Sunday, I think.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three days later, on the 10th, a couple of Thresher wives
stopped over to the house. They were just moving in, too. We were
talking, about what I cannot remember. Kids and husbands, I
suppose. It was late afternoon. We heard a bulletin on TV. A U.S.
sub was lost. We knew. We knew it had to be Thresher. I shut the TV
off. That's exactly what I did when I heard a bulletin about the
Russian ship. I shut the TV off. It's too hard to listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I can feel for the Russian wives, the mothers, sisters. I
know what they are going through. But you know, it's the guys on
the boat I'm thinking of most. The guys.''
</P>
<P>
   She is sitting on a couch in her townhouse. She is 66, more than
half a lifetime removed from her husband, the Navy, the Thresher.
Many books on prayer and praying sit on side tables, along with
some porcelain knickknacks and a leather-bound Thresher memorial
book. She is not conducting an interview surrounded by letters from
John, Navy commendations, piles of photos of family and shipmates
and friends, by the usual remembrances of times past that are
pulled from boxes by military widows for inquisitive visitors. All
such connections and reminders were lost by the movers when she
left New London after Thresher went down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know what I got from the Navy, just two weeks after the
sub was lost? A notice to move out of the apartment within three
months. I guess when you're out of the Navy, you're out of the
Navy. Years later, when the boys were ready for college, I wrote
off to the Navy and asked about the Thresher fund. It was started
by friends and families. Much money had been collected, from
cities, towns, from all over the country, the world. A lot of
money. I was told the Thresher fund had been `merged' with another
fund, a scholarship fund. Who knows where the Thresher fund ended
up. It was as lost as the sub.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Smarz never wanted to know exactly what had happened on
board Thresher. One of her sons, Jimmy, who was 5 when the boat
went down, became a virtual expert on the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows for sure, but the usual explanation goes something
like this: For some reason, the nuclear reactor was shut down
during a deep dive test. Normally, without nuclear power, the boat
could be brought to the surface by battery power and by blowing the
ballast tanks free of water. But when air was released into the
ballast tanks, the air valves froze closed. The batteries couldn't
bring the sub up with flooded tanks. Thresher was doomed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimmy wanted to know what happened. I didn't,'' she says. ``I
knew it was quick. At least I heard it was quick. I suppose that's
a comfort. I heard it was a man-made problem. I suppose that
bothered me, because I remember that expression _ man-made. John
didn't die in war, which would be different. But he was gone. And
he was going to stay gone. So what's the point of knowing exactly
how?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russian boat, though. It's not quick, is it? It's
terrible. You'd think they could get the men off. You hope. You
pray.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: paulreid(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
