<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3569 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-PRESIDENTIAL-PERSONAL     08-16 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESIDENTIAL-PERSONALITY-MED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINPOINTING PRESIDENTIAL PERSONALITIES  
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (The following ``separate buy'' article from HealthScout, a
leading online source of health and lifestyle news, is available
from the New York Times Syndicate. Please contact syndicate sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;     BY NEIL SHERMAN  
 c.2000 HealthScout.com  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by The New York Times Syndicate) &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   When you're in the voting booth this November, you should
consider whether your candidate is stubborn or ambitious since
those traits are the mark of a great president, new research shows.
</P>
<P>
   You might also want to look at other character issues before you
pull the lever. Great presidents are more extroverted, assertive,
thrill-seeking and open to fantasy, the research suggests.
</P>
<P>
   As a final check, don't expect a great president to have a neat
desk or be very straightforward, researchers conducting the The
Personality and Presidency Project say. Historically, great
presidents rank low on being neat, being vulnerable or being up
front with the facts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at how our 41 presidents compared to average
Americans,'' says Steven Rubenzer, a psychologist with the Mental
Health &AMP; Mental Retardation Authority of Harris County in Houston.
Rubenzer and his colleagues used ``the hottest personality
inventory test out there for people who research personality,'' and
asked 115 historians and biographers to rate the nation's 41
presidents on 600 personality items.
</P>
<P>
   But before you bring a personality scorecard to the polling
booth, the study's method is flawed, says Stanley Renshon, noted
prize-winning author of High Hopes: The Clinton Presidency and the
Politics of Ambition.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who do these kinds of studies think that because they
put a number on these kinds of characterizations, they have
'science.' They don't,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Rubenzer used a number of standardized personality profile
instruments, including the Revised NEO Personality Inventory. The
raters were restricted to the five years before the men were
elected to the highest office.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we found is that they tend to be more extroverted, lower
in openness to experience, less agreeable and higher in
conscientiousness,'' Rubenzer says. ``But the one that really
drives the ranking is their high score on achievement-striving.
Similarly, great presidents had a low score on straightforwardness
and modesty, and a low score on tender-mindedness.''
</P>
<P>
   Lack of straightforwardness is not dishonesty, Rubenzer insists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lincoln was known as an honest person, but he was willing to
change his message to one audience or another, and he was good with
the use of language. He was using all his abilities to persuade the
country to move in a certain direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The findings were presented last week at the 108th Annual
Convention of the American Psychological Association in Washington,
D.C.
</P>
<P>
   But Renshon, who is also a professor of political science and a
psychoanalyst at City University of New York in New York City,
finds the finding on straightforwardness ludicrous.
</P>
<P>
   ``So by that standard, we should then elect somebody who
promises to lie to us,'' he asks. ``That's so dumb it's
unbelievable. One of the most important features of presidents is
our ability to trust them. They're saying trust is not important,
and that flies in the face of almost any study I can think of.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem with Rubenzer's study is it relies on the opinions
of historians and biographers, Renshon says.
</P>
<P>
   ``These presidents did not take the test themselves,'' he says.
``The biggest single problem is that they are giving people who are
not trained as psychologists these personality instruments and
asking them to make psychological analyses. What you are really
getting is their free associations.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (The HealthScout.com Web site is at http://www.HealthScout.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
