<HEADER>
A3583 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d THERE'SMORETHANFASTFOODB     08-16 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 THERE'S MORE THAN FAST FOOD BETWEEN HERE AND SANTA FE 
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BEVERLY BUNDY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You don't have to pull a ``Thelma &AMP; Louise'' to justify a road
trip. Being more of the Kathy Bates persuasion myself (''I'm older
and I have better insurance''), I've taken to the road, headed west
on Interstate 30, in search of American food.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the Route 66 food of our childhoods: pecan logs at
Stuckey's and root beer floats at A&AMP;W. Nor is it our children's
road food: chicken and dumplings at Cracker Barrel or nuked
burritos from the Exxon station. This is real American food that is
doing just fine, thank you.
</P>
<P>
   So for the next few weeks, you'll be following along on an
Excellent Adventure, a sampler of what we're eating from Texas to
New Mexico to Nevada to California and back again.
</P>
<P>
   Cornudas Cafe &AMP; Gift Shop, U.S. 180 between Dell City and El
Paso, (915) 964-2409:
</P>
<P>
   West of Pecos is a little dot on the map that has been pumping
gas since the 1920s. It took tough folks to settle this dry, flat
land, and it appears that their descendants are just as tough.
</P>
<P>
   When I first called the Cornudas Cafe to find out if they were
open on Sundays, the woman who answered the phone said, ``Who is
this?'' A few weeks later I called to get the exact street address
and the man who answered the phone said, ``Who is this?'' You can't
be too careful.
</P>
<P>
   And the greeting isn't too much friendlier when you pull up to
the RV park/gas station/home of the $5 blanket/restaurant. The
waitress presents a menu written on a brown paper lunch sack and
impatiently taps her pen. ``What's good?'' ``Everything,'' she
says, tapping away.
</P>
<P>
   Well, they may not be friendly, but they know how to cook. The
tacos, indeed, were wonderful _ freshly fried flour tortillas were
stuffed with coarse hamburger pumped with chili powder. The beans
on the side were served in their broth and punctuated with onions _
not the refrieds we more often see in our neck of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Don't let the door hit you on your way out, but do come back for
the burgers.
</P>
<P>
   Owl Bar Cafe &AMP; Steakhouse, U.S. 380, San Antonio, N.M., (505)
835-9946:
</P>
<P>
   We may think we take our chili seriously in Texas, but we're
only pretenders to the throne. It's the New Mexicans who are kings
of the mesa when it comes to chili.
</P>
<P>
   So to claim that San Antonio is home to New Mexico's most famous
green chili cheeseburger takes more than bravado.
</P>
<P>
   The burger is small by Texas standards, but what it lacks in
substance it makes up for in style. The patty is topped with a
slice of American cheese and finished with a spoonful from the
ever-bubbling caldron of green-chile chili.
</P>
<P>
   The mix of clientele is testament to the burger's renown. A
lopsided sign is pinned up behind the bar _ Sale to Intoxicated
Persons Prohibited _ but the attached Kappa Sigma sticker belies
the sign's effectiveness. The house wine appears to be the box of
Franzio white zinfandel on the shelf behind the bar. Yet a few
women of a certain age with pressed Bermudas, Marge Simpson hair
and straw bags politely waved at the help as they left the dark bar
for the blazing summer sun outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   Mariscos La Playa Restaurant, 537 Cordova Road, Santa Fe, N.M.,
(505) 982-2790
</P>
<P>
   You'd think that Santa Feans would do better with Spanish than
they do. However, this local favorite is referred to as Mariscos by
one and all. Mariscos, those of us who did the homework our
sophomore year know, means seafood _ an odd name for a restaurant.
Sort of like saying, ``Hey, let's go to Hamburgers for lunch,''
when what we mean is, ``Let's go to Kincaid's.'' But if you ask for
directions, don't say La Playa _ no one calls the restaurant that.
And since everyone in Santa Fe is rich, you don't want to look poor
and dumb.
</P>
<P>
   Stopping in after a workday _ some people in Santa Fe do work,
polishing crystals and throwing pots _ we found it packed with
locals. And for good reason.
</P>
<P>
   The seafood is squeaky fresh and beautifully served without a
soupcon of pretension. We had a yen for oysters, but since August
doesn't have an ``R,'' we were a touch leery. But the T-shirted
waiter was at the top of his game, and when we asked the home port
of that evening's oysters, he said ``Seattle.'' A wonderful detail
at a restaurant that tops out at $30 for a meal for two.
</P>
<P>
   The oysters were pristine and so plump that we couldn't finish
the dozen. Another winner was raw shrimp marinated in lemon juice _
shells and all. Ringed with cucumber slices that had been peeled
and scored, the Mexican take on sushi was just the thing for a hot
summer night.
</P>
<P>
   Mariscos (there I go) also serves a terrific guacamole along
with its pico de gallo. The mashed avocados are blended with some
``crema'' and kicked up with some of the pico de gallo, yielding a
salsa with the taste of avocados but the consistency of green
goddess dressing. It's a definite twist to try at home.
</P>
<P>
   Next week _ a righteous breakfast in Grants, N.M., and Thai to
die for in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or e-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
