<HEADLINE>
PICKING A WINE FOR A SATURDAY LUNCH
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The dish: Salad sampler of fruit salad, chicken salad, and tuna
and pasta salad.
</P>
<P>
   This is almost a trick question. The fruit flavors of the salad
complement almost every varietal. Chicken salad, with or without an
Oriental twist, belongs with dry chenin blanc, a riesling or a
sancerre. Add tuna and pasta, and a rose becomes the wine of the
moment. It's amazing when you realize the flexibility threshold. Or
try a viognier, a gewurztraminer or a pinot grigio. You are safe
and happy _ be it a Saturday lunch or Sunday night supper.
</P>
<P>
   The wines: Dry Creek Vineyards Dry Chenin Blanc 1998 ($8.75),
California
</P>
<P>
   Pascal Jolivet Sancerre 1998 ($18.99), France
</P>
<P>
   Paul Jaboulet Aine Tavel ($15.99), France
</P>
<P>
   Trefethen Dry Riesling 1998 ($15), California
</P>
<P>
   _ Renie and Sterling Steves
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
