<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3609 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-     08-16 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING GOOD NEIGHBORS, PART II 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week, this column focused on the preliminaries for building
a fence. When you have the necessary materials, you can begin
construction.
</P>
<P>
   The first step is to set the posts in the ground. Begin with the
end posts. Fence posts should be set to a depth of at least 32
inches. They can be held in place with either packed dirt or
concrete.
</P>
<P>
   You can use a clamshell-type posthole digger if you only have a
few holes to dig, but for a long fence you might want to rent a
power auger to bore holes. The holes should have flat solid
bottoms.
</P>
<P>
   Two problems that you may encounter are rocks and tree roots.
</P>
<P>
   Try to dislodge rocks with a pry bar and a pick. If the rock is
too large to be moved, you may have to relocate the fence post.
</P>
<P>
   Tree roots are less of a problem because you can cut the smaller
ones and shift the hole slightly to avoid the larger ones.
</P>
<P>
   Place each end post in its hole and fill it with about six to
eight inches of soil. Use a level to make sure the post is
perfectly vertical on all four sides, then tamp the dirt down
around the post with a piece of 2 by 2. Start gently on one side,
and then work around the post with more forceful strokes. Be
careful not to tamp too hard on any one side; you could push the
post out of plumb.
</P>
<P>
   When the end posts are in place, run a line between them and
locate the positions for the section posts. Dig the holes, then set
the posts in them, using the same tamping technique that you
applied to the end posts.
</P>
<P>
   After setting all the posts, step back and check their
alignment. Are they all in line? Are the tops even? Are they all
straight? If not, now is the time to make corrections.
</P>
<P>
   If you are satisfied with the posts, you can fill the holes with
either dirt or concrete. Whether you use dirt or concrete, it is
important to shape the top of the fill so it slopes away from the
post. This raked profile will shed water that might otherwise
collect around the post and penetrate the wood, causing rot.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is to nail the stringers in place with 10-penny
galvanized nails. The stringers are the long boards that run
horizontally between the posts to provide a support for the
pickets.
</P>
<P>
   They will have to be toenailed, that is, drive the nails at an
angle through the top of the stringer into the vertical side of the
post. Toenailing horizontal members like stringers presents a
problem because the downward force of the hammer blows tends to
knock the pieces out of alignment.
</P>
<P>
   There are two ways to prevent this. You can enlist the aid of a
strong-armed helper to hold each stringer as you nail it in place,
or if you are working alone, you can use spacer blocks to support
the stringers as you toenail. Start with the bottom stringer first.
It should be about 13 inches from the ground. Cut two pieces of 1
by 6 13 inches long and place them at the base of each post. Place
the bottom stringer so each end rests on a spacer block, then nail
it to the post.
</P>
<P>
   The top stringer should be about 38 inches above the bottom one.
Cut two more spacer blocks 38 inches long and place them at posts
so they rest on the bottom stringers. Place the top stringer on
these blocks and nail it in place. You can remove the support
blocks once both stringers are nailed in place.
</P>
<P>
   The final step in constructing the fence is to nail the pickets
to the stringers.
</P>
<P>
   The hardest part is positioning the pickets so they align
horizontally and so they are spaced evenly apart. This task can be
made easier if you make a spacing jig out of scrap lumber.
</P>
<P>
   The jig consists of only four boards and is relatively easy to
nail together. However, the pieces must be accurately measured and
assembled or else all the pickets will be out of alignment.
</P>
<P>
   Place the jig on the top stringer, then fit the picket in place
in the vertical slot with the top of the picket nestled against the
horizontal guide on the jig.
</P>
<P>
   Face nail the picket to the top stringer with two 7-penny
galvanized nails. Use two more nails to secure the bottom of the
picket to the lower stringer. Pick the jig up and move it along the
stringer to the next position and nail the rest of the pickets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
