<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERS QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   What Files to Back Up, And When and How
</P>
<P>
   Q. I understand that backing up files on my Windows 98 computer
is a good thing, but how do I figure out what I need to back up, as
well as when and how to perform the task?
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, backing up your valuable files is a very good thing, as
anyone who has suffered from a nasty system crash or hard-drive
failure can tell you. When and how often you back up depends on
your own needs and frequency of computer use. If you have files
that you work on and update every day, you may want to perform the
chore each night. If you do not use your computer so often, or
don't make frequent changes to the documents you use, a weekly or
monthly backup may suit your needs better.
</P>
<P>
   If you can afford it, consider investing in an external hard
drive or a tape drive to back up your system. Buying a drive that
is at least as large as your computer's hard drive will let you
back up your entire system and all its files, a move that is highly
recommended. Backing up by copying data to an extra drive is also
advised because even if your computer's main hard drive dies, your
files are safe on the other device.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy utility programs like Retrospect, by Dantz
(available for Windows or Macintosh), but Windows 98 comes with its
own built-in backup software, called Microsoft Backup. To find it,
go to the Start menu, then Programs and Accessories. Go to System
Tools and select Backup from the list. (If you do not see Backup
listed, odds are that it was not initially installed on your
computer, but you can add it to your system from your Windows 98
CD-ROM.) The Backup program will also let you restore your saved
files to your system in case something becomes corrupted or you
delete a document by accident.
</P>
<P>
   Once you start the program, the Backup Wizard will lead you
through a series of questions. You will be asked if you would like
to back up My Computer (which is just about everything) or just
certain drives, files or folders. The Wizard will ask you if you
want to back up all the files you have selected or just the ones
that have changed since your last backup. You will also be asked
whether you want to store your backup file on your main computer or
on an external device.
</P>
<P>
   The Backup program can also compress your files to save space.
After you give the backup file a name (like ``daily backup''),
click on the Start button in the Backup Wizard's box, and the
process will begin.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I know I can buy software to help fix my system, but are
there any resources within Windows 98 itself that will help me when
things just aren't right?
</P>
<P>
   A. Although it is tucked away, there is a handy suite of
diagnostic and utility programs included with Windows 98, and that
software may be of help when you are trying to sort out problems
with your operating system. To find these applications, go to the
Start menu, then to Programs, Accessories and System Tools. Select
System Information.
</P>
<P>
   The System Information box will give you plenty of details about
your hardware and software, like what kind of processor your
computer has and how much RAM is installed. Under the Tools menu in
this System Information box you will find the programs that can
help you trouble-shoot.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 10 or so different tools at your disposal, you will
find the System File Checker, a program that keeps track of your
system files and will help you replace any damaged ones from your
Windows 98 CD-ROM. If your computer crashes frequently, try running
the Dr. Watson utility, which notes what your computer was doing
when it crashed and may help with suggestions on the cause and cure
of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   The Registry Checker, which keeps a backup of your Registry file
and scans the current one for problems, can help you restore your
registry to better health in times of crisis or when a software
installation has gone wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
e-mail to Q&AMP;A(AT)nytimes.com or mail to Questions, Circuits, The
New York Times, 229 West 43rd St., New York, N.Y. 10036-3959. This
column will answer questions of general interest, but letters
cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
