<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLIANCE WITH A PURPOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER H. LEWIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   About half of all American households now have personal
computers, a trend that is astonishing considering that PC's are
expensive, complicated and unreliable, compared with other
household appliances. Conversely, about half of all homes have
managed to resist buying computers until now. That annoys the
Microsoft Corp., which hates the idea of the country being divided
in two. (Microsoft hates the idea of anything being divided in
two.)
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's mission statement calls for a computer _
Windows-based, naturally _ in every home. That sounds like a swell
idea to Compaq, the world's largest maker of Windows-powered PC's.
So earlier this week, Compaq and Microsoft teamed up to introduce
the iPAQ Home Internet Appliance IA-1, a $199 home computer
designed for people who don't like computers.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Compaq prefers not to call it a computer, referring to
it instead as ``the Internet in a box.''
</P>
<P>
   The catch is that to get the iPAQ IA-1 for $199 requires a
three-year commitment to Microsoft's MSN Internet service, which is
$21.95 a month, raising the total cost of the Internet in a Box to
nearly $1,000. If the buyer doesn't sign up for three years of MSN,
this cute little cow pie of a computer costs a ridiculous $599.
Even then, the owner will have to have an MSN account to use it.
But if someone already has an MSN account, there would be no need
to buy the iPAQ. Obviously, Compaq sees its audience as first-time
buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, some people may be willing to pay this much for a
device that is so simple to use. Much better computers are
available for less money, but they do not offer the push-button
ease of the iPAQ. Think of the price as a simplicity tax.
</P>
<P>
   The iPAQ Home Internet Appliance IA-1 belongs to a new category
of devices called Internet appliances, which are stripped-down
computers designed to handle e-mail, World Wide Web browsing,
online shopping and a few other simple tasks without the cost or
complexity of a personal computer. Specifically, the iPAQ IA-1 is
the first member of a subspecies of Internet appliances called MSN
Companions. Several other computer makers, including eMachines,
have signed up to make Internet appliances that link directly to
Microsoft's MSN network. Gateway, a Compaq rival, has a similar
alliance with America Online, an MSN rival. The Gateway-AOL
appliance is expected to reach the market later this year, as will
an improved model of the original Internet appliance, the
Netpliance i-Opener.
</P>
<P>
   According to Microsoft, most of the people who do not have
computers say they would like to have access to e-mail and the
Internet. They just don't like computers, which cost too much,
break down too often and are too darned intimidating. (Microsoft
blames the hardware for that, of course, which is almost as amusing
as the $599 price tag for the iPAQ Home Internet Appliance IA-1.)
</P>
<P>
   The role model for information appliances is the television set,
which is relatively cheap and simple to set up, turns on and off
instantly with the touch of a button, rarely breaks down and does
not require mastery of a lot of technical hocus-pocus. The TV set
is not particularly smart, but it does not have to be because all
the information it displays is pulled down from the network.
</P>
<P>
   The iPAQ IA-1 works the same way, sort of. It has no floppy
drive, no hard disk and no CD-ROM drive, all of which are standard
equipment on other Windows-based home PC's. It has a feeble little
brain with 32 megabytes of memory, but it doesn't need much more
because almost all of its consciousness is derived from the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   To keep things simple _ and to create a direct link between
Microsoft and your wallet _ the iPaq uses a stripped-down version
of Windows called Windows CE. The only major application on the
system is a generation-old Internet Explorer 4.0 Web browser, a
Microsoft product that automatically steers the user to the MSN
home page.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft calls this software bundle an MSN Companion.
</P>
<P>
   Heaven forbid you should decide that you want to try America
Online or Napster or Quicken or some other infidel software.
Because the iPAQ IA-1 has no local storage drives, the owner cannot
download and store files from the Internet or install other
applications, like games, educational software or personal finance
programs. Nor can the owner accidentally erase or move an obscure
Windows file. ``This makes MSN Companion devices very reliable,''
Microsoft says in a reviewer's guide. It also makes the device a
wholly owned subsidiary of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   MSN is actually the best thing about this little box. Although
only a fraction of the size of America Online, MSN offers a broad
array of interesting services, most of which are accessible through
the iPAQ.
</P>
<P>
   The iPAQ Home Internet Appliance IA-1 _ the awkward name
suggests that more, and perhaps cheaper, Compaq home Internet
appliances are in the works _ is a bone-colored, two-piece
contraption that is small enough to fit easily on a kitchen
counter. It's about the size of the average pocketbook. It has an
adjustable 10-inch (measured diagonally) color flat-panel display
screen, which is small even when compared with the screens on
laptop computers. To save costs, the iPAQ uses a passive matrix
screen, which is just barely acceptable for e-mail and Web
browsing.
</P>
<P>
   It has a 56K dial-up modem, a scratchy mono speaker and four USB
ports for attaching optional peripherals like an Epson 740 inkjet
printer (the only model it works with at this time), JBL speakers
and a mouse. The most intriguing feature is a Compact Flash Type 2
memory card slot, which has no use at this point. Presumably Compaq
and Microsoft have grand plans for it.
</P>
<P>
   The wireless keyboard is 13 inches wide and 7 inches deep.
Pressing on a rubber nipple about the size of a nickel controls the
cursor on the iPAQ's display screen if you don't want to use a
mouse. In my tests, the cursor control was clumsy and erratic. On
the bright side, the keyboard has a series of buttons dedicated to
specific tasks, which reduces the need to use the built-in pointing
device.
</P>
<P>
   One task button takes the user to a personal MSN home page,
which can be customized to display local weather and news, a stock
portfolio and other useful information. Another automatically opens
the MSN Hotmail e-mail service, which is set up for the people who
buy iPAQ's. There are buttons dedicated to news (MSNBC), finance
(MSN Money Central) and instant messages (MSN Instant Messaging,
which is not compatible with AOL's much more popular service, but
only because AOL will not allow it). There are also buttons for
online shopping (MSN eShop), searching (MSN Search) _ get the
picture? _ Compaq technical support, printing and tracking down
music files. You can listen to the music, but you can't store it.
</P>
<P>
   Although the personal MSN Web page is fixed as the default home
page, users can go to any Web sites after they are online. There is
also a button for storing favorite Web destinations. Microsoft has
stocked that feature with sites that include maps, weather,
greeting cards, Oprah's Books and Third Age, a Web site designed
for ``first-wave baby boomers.'' Huh?
</P>
<P>
   One day earlier this week, the headlines on Third Age's home
page pointed to rather explicit descriptions of how to improve your
sex life. While I am grateful for Microsoft's thoughtfulness in
including this Web site among the six preloaded favorites, perhaps
that is not the greatest bookmark for a family computer.
</P>
<P>
   The ``instant on'' appeal of the iPAQ IA-1 depends entirely on
your definition of ``instant.'' In my tests, it took almost 60
seconds after the power button was pushed for the home page to
finish loading, and that is much quicker than the startup time for
a standard Windows computer. But if it took 60 seconds to turn on a
TV or get a dial tone, people would riot.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
