u a BC-CIR-SURFING-NYT &LR;      08-16 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SURFING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURFING THE WEB FOR SITES ON THE REAL THING 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL POLLAK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are two excellent reasons to go Web surfing for the real
thing. The first reason is if you live along the Southern
California coast, or in Hawaii, or on the Outer Banks or anywhere
else with wave action and you want to find out whether the surf's
up and the sun's going to stay out.
</P>
<P>
   The other reason is if you live anywhere else, particularly if
you are chained to a desk and wouldn't know a Hobie from a hoagie.
In that case, you may need a surf site even more.
</P>
<P>
   For those whose image of surfing remains fixated on the Beach
Boys and ``Hawaii Five-O,'' it may come as a surprise that the
sport is now a big business. It is all over the Web, and some sites
evoke major advertising and venture capital as much as big kahunas
and woodies.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for instance, the aptly named Swell.com (www.swell.com),
which has acquired or linked to many weather, tournament
information, entertainment and merchandise sites and is promoting
itself as being a kind of one-stop shop for all things surf when it
expands later this summer. (Its slick online promotional video is
worth the look.) One of its notable acquisitions is
Surfline(surfline.swell.com), a forecasting service that provides
surfing and weather information for dozens of spots, including 37
sites in California alone, 4 in Hawaii, 17 in Florida, 20 elsewhere
on the East Coast and 3 from Costa Rica. Surfline says it has more
than 350,000 visitors a month.
</P>
<P>
   There are wonderful Webcams on many of Surfline's beach links,
so you do not have to trust the status reports; just look for
yourself. Moreover, there is something about staring at a live
color shot of the uncharacteristically low swells at the Pipeline
on Oahu's North Shore (a result of La Nina, the page's ``local
knowledge'' section explains) or a view of the three-to-five-foot
surf at Guaruja, Brazil, from Midtown Manhattan that is at least as
hypnotic as gazing into a lava lamp.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawaiian Lifeguard Association has its own site detailing
the lifeguard-protected beaches of Oahu
(www.aloha.com:80/(tilde)lifeguards/hla.html). Besides the great
pictures, there is a lot of advice that is short on surfer lingo
and long on good sense: reminders about sharp coral, waves breaking
on ledges and the need to respect high-surf warnings. There are
separate pages titled Sharks of Hawaii and Dangerous Ocean
Organisms. There are 18 of the latter, including stinging seaweed.
</P>
<P>
   Times have definitely changed. The East Coast Wahine
Championships (www.eastcoastwahines.com), an amateur contest for
East Coast surfing women that began in 1997, was held Aug. 12 and
13 in Wrightsville Beach, N.C., blessed by California-size waves
stirred up by Hurricane Alberto. There were short board (the more
acrobatic type), long board and bodyboard divisions and a novice
division for beginners. You can see photos of some of the
competition on the Southern North Carolina Surf page
(www.sncsurf.com). The U.S. Surfing Federation (www.ussurf.org) and
Eastern Surfing Association (www.surfesa.org) have schedules on the
major amateur events, including the Eastern Surfing Championships
in late September in Avon, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site of the International Surfing Museum in Huntington
Beach, Calif. (www.surfingmuseum.org), provides a nostalgic return
to simple joys. There is a camera box belonging to Bruce Brown,
director of the classic surfing documentary ``The Endless Summer,''
with its top that was painted by LeRoy Neiman on a trip to the
beach. There are pictures of Corky Carroll, world champion in the
1960s, in his prime, and a quote from him today: ``Yes, I still
surf all the time, and no, I still don't have a real job. Let's
hope it never comes to that.'' There are plenty of pictures of Duke
Kahanamoku, the Olympic swimming champion from Hawaii, and his
10-foot redwood board, with which he did more to popularize surfing
than anyone until Hobie Alter, perfecter of the fiberglass board,
and Brian Wilson of the Beach Boys.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's online exhibits include an Irish surfing poster
(County Sligo, 1984) and a surfboard used by the Swiss team (Swiss?
Well, why not?) in an international 1992 championship.
</P>
<P>
   For sheer escapism, it is hard to do better than the Costa Rica
Supersite (www.incostarica.net/docs/surf). Rent a four-wheel drive
to get to the best places, it advises, because ``mud and rivers
will become an important part of your journey, especially during
the rainy season.'' There are plenty of links, including some to
other Costa Rican surfing guides.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a partial description of Matapalo, on the Pacific Coast:
``Best waves are a 15- to 25-minute walk through the forest trails,
where monkeys, toucans, macaws and other tropical wonders can be
spotted.''
</P>
<P>
   With comments like that, who needs pictures?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
