<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3618 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-N     08-16 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COSMETICS WEB SITES OFFER SHOPPERS VIRTUAL MAKE-OVERS, BUT PROBLEMS
REMAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The writer's e-mail address is: Slatalla(AT)nytimes.com.) By
MICHELLE SLATALLA  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although I do not wear makeup, I live with two experts on the
subject. My 9- and 11-year-old daughters are so attuned to the
nuances of cosmetics that they can tell from a distance of 20 paces
if a woman gels her eyebrows.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does that level of eyebrow maintenance accomplish?'' I
asked, a question that unfortunately focused their attention
directly on my own unplucked visage one day last week.
</P>
<P>
   Within an hour, I was at the mall, sitting on one of those high
stools while my daughters applied blush and eye shadow from tester
pots in a quest to determine my ``colors.''
</P>
<P>
   I had to admit that it was a lot of fun, until a sales clerk
approached offering cleanser on a cotton ball and a free
consultation.
</P>
<P>
   One thing led to another, and I lost control of the situation
around the time the clerk announced that I had ``ragged, uneven
patches'' and ``fatty deposits'' that cried out for daily
applications of expensive creams.
</P>
<P>
   By the time I regained my composure in the parking lot 15
minutes later, my face had been replaced by the clerk's idea of ``a
sheer look for everyday,'' and I was clutching a shopping bag full
of makeup. The receipt said $122.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look good,'' lied Zoe, my 11-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   You might think the humiliation of slinking back to return the
stuff the next day (actually, to avoid the clerk I skulked to
another Bloomingdale's in a different town) would have jettisoned
further experimentation. But it only whetted my appetite: I had
seen my future and it included eyeliner.
</P>
<P>
   So when I heard about a growing number of Internet sites where
shoppers can perform virtual make-overs on themselves, I rushed
over to test three, eMakeover.com, MakeoverStudio.com and
EZface.com.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is that you take a digital photo of your face, send it
to the site and then point and click on different combinations of
products to apply them to the image. You can then see what goes
together and buy products you want online.
</P>
<P>
   I tried blond hair (a mistake) at eMakeover and yellow eye
shadow (ditto) at EZface. Then I clicked a button to clean it all
off. I could determine my colors without enduring a sales clerk's
sales pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The sites are still in development. Shoppers can purchase a
limited selection of beauty products at two of them, eMakeover.com
and MakeoverStudio.com.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, the EZface make-over tool (which is being tested, so
you can play with it but not purchase anything) will be available
at a jewelry site, Kirabo.com, where shoppers will be able to click
on earrings and necklaces to see how the gems look on them.
</P>
<P>
   That was so much fun that I thought I might be witnessing the
emergence of tools that would magically erase at least one of the
problems that have plagued the crowded online cosmetics market in
recent months and prompted mergers and buyouts of such high-profile
sites as Beauty.com and Gloss.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``The contenders in this market have been like pigeons scraping
for bread crumbs in a crowded piazza,'' said Evie Black Dykema, a
senior online retail analyst at Forrester Research.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a projected increase in Web sales, to $900 million by
2004 from $90 million last year, only 2 percent of nonmedication
health and beauty aids will be sold online, Dykema said.
</P>
<P>
   Many shoppers are reluctant to buy makeup they cannot test
before buying.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see how something looks truly on your own face, and how
it's blended with your own skin tone and your hair style and the
color of your eyes, is a major breakthrough,'' said Gary Savage,
EZface.com's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest hurdle? Getting the digital photo online. Only 8
percent of households in the United States have a digital camera or
a scanner, so the make-over tools' distribution is limited. (There
are other options: You can take a regular roll of film to a Kodak
PhotoNet outlet and then get access to the digitized photos through
AOL's ``You've Got Pictures'' service or take a printed photo to a
print shop to have it put onto a disk.)
</P>
<P>
   Even for a person like me, living in a household with at least a
half-dozen digital cameras lying around and a spouse who knows how
to use them, the project was an ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   I had to sit around playing solitaire on the computer for nearly
two hours as my husband fiddled with lighting, hunted for the
camera cord, persuaded his computer to recognize a smart card
reader, persuaded the smart card reader to recognize the digital
image, fiddled with the editing software to create a JPEG file and
transferred the image from his computer to mine through a home
network.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, I was exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   I then had to send the image by e-mail to both EZface.com and
MakeoverStudio.com so their software could reproduce my features
and my skin tone to ensure a realistic application of makeup.
</P>
<P>
   I had to wait for the photos to be processed. At EZface.com,
that took a couple of days, but at MakeoverStudio.com, my photo was
still ``in process'' after six days (so I tested that site's
make-over tool on digital images of models on the site).
</P>
<P>
   I also uploaded my digital image to eMakeover.com, which took
only a few minutes. The problem there, however, was that I had to
use the cursor to mark outlines of my own features on the digital
image so the site would know where to apply color. In the end, my
lips looked kind of crooked.
</P>
<P>
   Emakeover.com offered dozens of choices of lipstick colors from
Avon to test. I saved the ones I liked _ twig, rose marble and
shell _ in an online shopping basket. Afterward, eMakeover.com
connected me to Avon.com's site to complete the purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Transmitting color over the Internet to shoppers with
idiosyncratic computer systems running various operating systems
and different browsers is a tricky business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The colors are monitor-dependent, but, over all, monitors are
getting better and better,'' said Chrissie Kremer, a co-founder of
Makeover Networks, which owns MakeoverStudio.com. ``People with
modern-day equipment are getting really good representation.''
</P>
<P>
   I had been considering the Avon lipstick rose marble, which
seemed to really bring out my eyes, when Ella, my 9-year-old,
peered over my shoulder at the computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know something?'' she said. ``You look really good without
makeup.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
