<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERYDAY-ETHICS-COLUMN-ADV20-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV20 
 EVERYDAY ETHICS 
 FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 20, AND THEREAFTER.
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's EVERYDAY ETHICS column. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the EVERYDAY ETHICS column _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.) 
 By RANDY COHEN 
 c.2000 Randy Cohen 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE GUILDED RAGE
</P>
<P>
   Q: The unions that represent actors in television commercials
are on strike. I work at a recording studio, not party to the
strike, that has been hired for sessions using nonunion actors.
This makes me squeamish, to say the least. I have friends on both
sides of the conflict, including many producers from small ad
agencies. I could refuse to participate in nonunion sessions, thus
alienating my boss. I could call the union and it would picket my
studio, but that could imperil the livelihood of my boss and my
producer friends. Or I could do nothing. What do you suggest?
</P>
<P>
   _ Brian Hallas, Brooklyn, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A: Considering your convictions, you would do better to join an
effort against nonunion actors at all independent recording
studios, not just your own. That's the call you should make to the
union _ to ask how you can participate. That beats the alternatives
you have suggested. Eschewing nonunion sessions would jeopardize
your job but benefit no one; you would be replaced, and the
sessions would continue. Passivity is no better: it would allow the
strike to go on and on, something deleterious to the union actors,
the small producers, your employer and your conscience. Brice
Peyre, a spokesman for the Screen Actors Guild, one of the striking
unions (the American Federation of Television and Radio Artists is
the other), thinks you should blow the whistle _ softly. ``Quietly
tip off SAG and/or AFTRA so that their members can arrange to
picket the studio in advance and attempt to talk the actor out of
scabbing against the union,'' he says. I don't agree. Calling in
the pickets would be a selective action taken against a single
company _ yours. Worse still, you would be using privileged
information to harm your own boss. And there is something unseemly
in creeping around behind his back. That an action must be
undertaken in secret is sometimes a clue to its dubious nature, as
we also see in the nonunion actors' desire to remain unidentified.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Company policy allows me a certain number of vacation weeks
per year. My manager, in an effort to be generous (or liked),
offered me an extra week _ but I am not to mark it on my time
sheet. Do I take his offer, since he indulges in an extra week
himself, or follow company policy?
</P>
<P>
   _ Anonymous
</P>
<P>
   A: You ought not accept the extra vacation week unless your
manager can offer it without the need for false paperwork. A
manager should have the maximum flexibility to reward his
employees, but when his reward demands deceit, it's not
flexibility; it's fraud. Given your company's policy, an extra week
is no more his to give than is that nice Xerox machine down in the
copy room. Just because your manager takes an extra week himself,
deceiving his own boss, does not make the practice more legitimate
for you. As my mother always said, if your manager jumped off the
roof or engineered some kind of complicated kickback scheme, would
you jump off the roof or engineer some kind of complicated kickback
scheme? You may well deserve that vacation, but you should not lie
on your time sheet to get it.
</P>
<P>
   Do you have ethical questions that you need answered? Send them
to ethicist(at)nytimes.com, or Everyday Ethics, New York Times
Syndicate, 122 E. 42nd St., 14th floor, New York, N.Y. 10168.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on EVERYDAY
ETHICS and other features. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382. &QL;
</P>
