<SLUG> BC-CIR-MILITARY-BRATS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WEB HELPS MILITARY 'BRATS' FIND LONG-LOST FRIENDS
</HEADLINE>
  By MINDY SINK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carol Passar lived in Pennsylvania for only a year, when she was
13, but she left behind her best friend when the military moved her
family to yet another Army base in another part of the country.
Nearly 40 years later she was able to find her long-lost friend
through an online registry for military ``brats'' like herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw her name there in the registry list, and I said, `That's
Jeanie!'' Passar recalled. ``And wonder of all wonders, she
remembered me, too.''
</P>
<P>
   After exchanging a few e-mail messages, the two women met for
coffee earlier this year. ``I recognized her right away,'' Passar
said with a laugh. ``Her hair was grayer, but all these years later
she had the same fun personality that makes her fun to know.''
</P>
<P>
   The site Passar used, the Military Brats Registry
(www.military-brats.com), is one of a handful of places where
people who grew up in military families can try to find long-lost
acquaintances from childhoods that had them moving often, around
the country and the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're 13 years old, you don't really write a lot of
letters,'' Passar said, ``and these were the days before e-mail,
and you couldn't just zap somebody a message around the world. When
you travel around all the time, you can't grow attached to a place.
You can only become attached to people.''
</P>
<P>
   The Military Brats Registry is free to use and contains more
than 43,000 names, with about 15 to 20 names added daily. It links
to another site, Military Brats Online
(www.lynxu.com/brats/index.html), that posts reunion messages and
reminiscences on military base life.
</P>
<P>
   The registry was started by Marc Curtis of Redlands, Calif.,
whose father was an Army sergeant stationed at posts including
Yokohama in Japan; Fort Bliss, Texas; and posts throughout
California when Marc was growing up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Military bratdom doesn't leave your system,'' Curtis, now 49,
said. ``There's a whole mind-set that you're brought up with. For
me, after about 25 years, it started to become very important to
find friends I grew up with on military bases.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the missing links in Curtis' life were friends from his
elementary school in Texas, and on his site there is a page of
photographs from his fourth grade class. Of the 30 students in the
class, Curtis has found 12 and met with 4 of them. ``After 39
years, almost nothing has changed,'' he said. ``I started the
registry mostly as a way to find my own friends, and now wanting to
help others find theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis said the site ``pays for itself'' through a little
advertising and the sale of some items on the site.
</P>
<P>
   The site is organized by names _ maiden names for married women
_ and high school graduation dates. Once registered, a person can
scroll through the site to look for a familiar name or people from
a particular graduation year. Contact can be made via e-mail, which
is routed through the site rather than directly to the individual
for privacy reasons.
</P>
<P>
   `` After I registered a couple of months ago, I kept checking my
e-mail every week,'' said Amy Brown, 26, a schoolteacher in
Plymouth, Mass., ``and I got a couple from people that I knew in
high school in Scotland, but no really close friends. Then last
week I got a call from a good friend who had seen my name on the
registry and couldn't wait to e-mail. She had found out what town I
lived in and called information.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said she and her newfound old friend are now on a crusade
to find more alumni from the Holy Loch, Scotland, schools for a
reunion next year.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons people like Brown have difficulty tracking
down old classmates is that military-run base schools are often
prevented by privacy laws from providing alumni information, and
some international schools have closed, making their records
essentially inaccessible.
</P>
<P>
   There are dozens of individual sites for such schools, where
alumni can look for old friends and teachers, many of which are
listed on Military Brats Online. There is also the Canadian
Military Brat List (www.hub.org/brat(underscore)web), as well as a
site for those who grew up in foreign countries while their parents
worked as missionaries, diplomats or business executives
(www.tckworld.com). This site includes Schools Without Walls, lists
of military-base or overseas schools that have closed, grouped by
continent.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Defense Education Activity site
(www.odedodea.edu/alumni) has links to sites for many of the more
than 220 schools run by the department in this country and abroad.
The American Overseas Schools Historical Society
(aoshs.wichita.edu) is building an archive of the educational
history and memorabilia of an estimated four million American
children, and it also provides links to brats registries and
related sties.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are many stories of friendships _ and at least
one romance _ rekindled through the brats registries, sometimes
things just don't work out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found my best friend from the second grade who I knew in
Georgia,'' Passar said. ``She didn't remember me at all, though.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
