<HEADLINE>
GWYNETH SINGETH; WILL PEOPLE BUYETH?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Actors who want to be singers are, most often, like bears who
have been trained to juggle while hopping on one foot.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that they juggle and hop particularly well, it's that
they do it at all.
</P>
<P>
   Not that we're trying to denigrate the efforts of actress
Gwyneth Paltrow, whose duet with Huey Lewis on the old Smokey
Robinson hit ``Cruisin''' is released to radio this week.
``Cruisin''' is one of three tunes Paltrow recorded for the
soundtrack to the film ``Duets'' (which hits theaters Sept. 15),
and it's a pop/R&AMP;B classic.
</P>
<P>
   But come on _ the track record of movie stars becoming singers
is pretty poor, and Paltrow's efforts won't change that perception.
As a singer, she is a pretty good actress, although she fares
better than some other actors who attempted crossover success.
Remember:
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Willis as bluesman: Unlistenable.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Segal as rocker: Weak.
</P>
<P>
   John Travolta as pop star: Horrid.
</P>
<P>
   Don Johnson as ... well ... whatever that was he was trying to
do: Gag.
</P>
<P>
   We could go on, but why prolong the pain? Point is, pop-culture
history is littered with horrific examples of actors thinking they
could sing and inflicting that belief on innocent people.
</P>
<P>
   We don't expect them to be good _ because most of the evidence
says they won't be _ but we listen anyway, because of who they are.
</P>
<P>
   We're pleased to report that ``Cruisin''' is ``not awful.''
Paltrow's voice is thin and one-dimensional; it combines with
Lewis' to fashion a bland, white-bread, inoffensive stab at a soft,
sweet pop/soul classic without ever suggesting that Paltrow could
go the Jennifer Lopez route and have a successful solo career.
Which means that, considering its competition in the
actor-goes-singer pantheon, it's a raging success.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, in fact, has been thicker than most with
actor-turned-singer shenanigans. Witness Russell Crowe taking his
band, 30 Odd Foot of Grunt, to Stubb's Bar-B-Q in Austin for three
nights. Word is that TOFOG couldn't have gotten arrested in Austin
had Crowe not been the lead singer.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Keanu Reeves, whose band Dogstar has a new CD,
``Happy Ending,'' which has spawned a semihit with ``Cornerstore.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, ``Cornerstore'' has found a home at Fort Worth-Dallas
station KKMR/93.3 FM, according to program director Scott Strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play the Dogstar every day, more than once,'' Strong says.
``We played it once to see the reaction, and it was tremendous.
It's really a good-sounding, adult song that connects with the
listener _ and he's hot. He's got the new movie, and people are
buying ``The Matrix'' like crazy on DVD.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong remembers seeing Woody Harrelson at a small St. Louis
club years ago, when the ``Cheers'' star was touring with a
'50s/'60s party-rock band. He was, Strong says, ``really bad,''
but, hey, he drew a crowd, just as Crowe is doing this month in
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of our listeners went to see Crowe and they said
mainly it was bad _ and they didn't care whatsoever,'' he says.
``It was Russell Crowe, he looked great _ it was a campy evening of
drinking beer and being part of something. It's a guilty
pleasure.''
</P>
<P>
   But for those who would like to hear an actor successfully take
a stab at music, you almost have to go back to the late '50s and
the works of the late, great Robert Mitchum. Mitchum's musical
career is best remembered for ``The Ballad of Thunder Road,'' a
smallish pop hit in 1958. But it was his ``Calypso ... Is Like So _
'' LP that puts him head and shoulders among almost any other
thespian who dove into music.
</P>
<P>
   Assured, campy and often quite funny, ``Calypso'' _ rereleased
on CD in 1995 by Scamp Records _ is a kitsch/lounge/Latin classic,
a great party CD, and all the proof we need that actors need not
make fools of themselves when they step up to the michrophone.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they often do.
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman covers pop music for the Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
