<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3628 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX     08-16 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF RELIGIOUS BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOOK REVIEW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``King David: The Real Life of the Man Who Ruled Israel'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   by Jonathan Kirsch &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ballantine Books &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Biblical commentator Jonathan Kirsch sorts David out for us.
</P>
<P>
   He explains that Chronicles was intended to correct the
contradictions in Samuel. He makes it clear that David's selection
as king of Israel was rigged by humans and not necessarily ordained
of God. He clears up the problem of how David the slingshot champ
could have been unknown to King Saul, even though David the master
musician was a court fixture. (They were two different people!)
</P>
<P>
   Kirsch's work is immensely interesting, but it's possible that
only serious Bible scholars are ready for all this. Kirsch claims
David might not have slain Goliath; it's possible it was another
man.
</P>
<P>
   And that's not all. Kirsch maintains it's likely that David was
bisexual, since men as well as women were so strongly attracted to
him, and his affection for Jonathan was so celebrated.
</P>
<P>
   The book also has at times a humorous bent, as in the passages
about Saul, who preceded David on the throne but who began his
career ignominiously, getting lost while searching for his father's
stray animals.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone will be able to accept Kirsch's premise that all
the Hebrew Bible _ that's the Old Testament to some people _ was
written to prepare us for and to celebrate the greatness of David.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, ``King David'' is certain to cause a stir. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Betsy Friauf &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tarralyn Ramsey &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Tarralyn Ramsey'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Verity Records &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Drew Dawson, program director of KHVN/970 AM and a man who knows
more about gospel than I ever will, recommended I listen to this
CD, Ramsey's debut.
</P>
<P>
   You go, Drew. The 10 songs here are testament to an important
new voice in contemporary gospel, a woman whose vocal power will
immediately remind one of a young Whitney Houston _ and yes, she's
that good.
</P>
<P>
   Cut in a half-dozen studios (from Oklahoma to North Carolina to
Chicago) and the product of six songwriters (besides Ramsey) and
seven producers, the CD looks, on paper, like a cut-and-paste
effort.
</P>
<P>
   And to be sure, there are a few tracks _ such as the second
song, ``Heaven'' _ that are gussied up a bit too much. But this is
a minor quibble when set against the CD's overall excellence.
Ramsey's voice is equally adept at handling the easygoing lope of
``Tell It'' and the jazz-tinged balladry of ``Unconditional Love.''
Her voice is a powerful, supple instrument, and although the
backing tracks can get a tad too glossy, the vocal arrangements are
beautiful: Listen to how Ramsey works against the backing vocals on
``Shout About.''
</P>
<P>
   This CD has a strong local connection. Four of the tracks were
written and arranged by Carnell Murrell, the Dallas-based
singer/songwriter/keyboardist who was a member (along with Kirk
Franklin) of the DFW Mass Choir in its early glory days. Murrell,
who has released several solo CDs, is the CD's second star. He
penned ``Don't Be Weary,'' a duet with Ramsey, one of the CD's best
moments. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Dave Ferman &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
