<SLUG> BC-SCOOTERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW CRAZE IS AFOOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LILA LaHOOD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're sleek. They're hip. And as fads go, they're a lot more
fun than Furby.
</P>
<P>
   Why grumble about soaring gas prices when you can use a little
foot power and zip about on a motorless scooter?
</P>
<P>
   The scooters are manufactured under several names, including
Razor, Xootr and Kickboard. The Razor weighs in at just over 6
pounds, but the collapsible alloy aluminum frame can support up to
350 pounds. A telescoping handle extends to 35 inches and a rear
friction brake makes quick stops a cinch.
</P>
<P>
   I've been using one to get to the office, and it's turned a
seven-minute walk into a five-minute scoot. What's more, it's all
downhill going home _ a breeze of a ride in about three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But why relegate those speed-demon wheels to the asphalt and
concrete? They work even better on long, polished hallways at the
workplace. Just watch out for pedestrians exiting the elevator.
</P>
<P>
   Where do you get the wheels?
</P>
<P>
   Several retailers _ from the Sharper Image to department stores
_ price the Razor at $99. But I bought mine online for $75,
including shipping, through MobShop.com, a site where the more
people who join a buying cycle, the less you pay. The three-wheel
K2 Kickboard is $299 at www.rei.com.
</P>
<P>
   For ``high performance'' junkies, there's the Xootr scooter at
www.xootr.com. These luxury boards sport wheels made from ``an
exotic low-hysteresis polyurethane'' and come in three models
ranging in price from $269 to $489.
</P>
<P>
   Get rolling. I'll race you to work.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
