<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3632 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-SPACE-GAME-NYT &LR;      08-16 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SPACE-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SPACE CHANNEL 5': DANCE WITH ALIENS AND SAVE THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLES HEROLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With her pink pigtails, orange gloves and platform go-go boots
and a green ray gun worn like a garter, Ulala the space reporter is
enough by herself to make anyone want to play Sega's ``Space
Channel 5.'' At its heart is a simple memory game, but that is its
least important element. Here we have the ultimate victory of style
over substance, a little arcade game encased in glittering color
and driven by infectious dance beats.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Space Channel 5,'' aliens invade 25th-century Earth and
force the humans to dance. Ulala, an intrepid television reporter,
finds that she can save the human race by copying the alien dances,
move for move. With each victory, the ratings for her program,
``Ulala's Space Report'' (broadcast on Space Channel 5), go up, but
every misstep knocks the ratings down. If her dancing isn't up to
par, her program will be canceled, and the human race will be
doomed to an endless disco nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Playing the game involves hitting the right button at the right
time. The aliens _ short, colorful creatures with antennae and
faces like television screens _ do a little dance while calling out
their steps: ``Up, right. Left, down. Kick! Kick! Kick!''
</P>
<P>
   With their cute, high voices and endless jumping, the aliens
could be teaching line dancing to children on ``Sesame Street.''
Using the game controller, you make Ulala do the same little dance
as the aliens _ same steps, same rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   If she can keep up, she can free the humans, who will join her
for a victory dance while her director shouts, ``You go, Ulala!''
as if he were a morning DJ waking up his listeners. If she doesn't
do well enough, she does a dance of mourning, holding her hands to
her head and sighing deeply. As the game progresses, the dances
become more difficult, with more frequent changes in tempo and more
complex rhythms. At times you will have to shoot aliens and rescue
humans, making sure to shoot the aliens with your alien-killing
button and saving the humans with your human-saving button.
</P>
<P>
   It's a simple game, but often not an easy one. Usually when
people say something is dreamlike or has dream logic, they mean
that it is surreal, symbolic or unusual in its form and structure.
But ``Space Channel 5'' is like a real dream _ filled with
senseless events and a story that jumps from one idea to the next
in a disjointed fashion. Whether Ulala is rescuing a mesmerized
Space Michael (a Michael Jackson lookalike), outdancing the
ultimate robot reporter, Evila, or saving a group of children from
a giant dance robot, this game makes no sense whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   With chic visuals and music that is somewhere between a James
Bond theme and a James Brown hit, all horns and bass, it doesn't
matter whether it's really a reporter's job to outdance aliens or
whether 1960s fashions will be popular in the 25th century. As
Ulala strides along with the beat, walking like one of Robert
Crumb's ``Keep on Truckin''' characters, the player is carried
along, bouncing in rhythm in his or her seat, waiting for the next
round.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the game was created in Japan should come as no
surprise. Japanese game designers have a talent for fast-paced,
over-the-top entertainment unhampered by logic but informed by
impeccable style. ``Space Channel 5'' is a thrill ride with
flashing lights and explosions, psychedelic play masquerading as a
video game. It bypasses your brain's logic center entirely, making
a direct connection to its center for fun.
</P>
<P>
   The frenetic choreography, catchy music and Day-Glo colors _ and
phrases like ``Groove evening, ladies and gentlemen'' _ all seem
designed to shut down your thinking and have you rely entirely on
the primal dancer within. Perhaps it is Zen, tearing apart the
logical cage of our brain, or perhaps it is nothing more than the
video game equivalent of a good party, but whatever it is, it
works.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually Ulala, with the help of two fellow reporters, Pudding
and Jaguar, will blow to bits the giant robot made out of
televisions and save the world from the dancing aliens. Then you'll
be able to read the credits and discover that in keeping with the
surreal nature of the game, Ulala's voice is done by someone named
Apollo Smile.
</P>
<P>
   Like a particularly strange dream, the details of ``Space
Channel 5'' will evaporate when you wake up, and you'll find
yourself with only a vague idea of what happened. ``The aliens were
being hypnotized,'' you'll tell your friends. ``There was something
about ratings. There were space tourists dancing with cameras and a
space keyboard girl and, and well, it was weird.'' By the end of
the day, you won't remember even that much. But you'll find
yourself walking along the street singing, ``Up! Up-up-up! Right!
Left, down!'' And you'll always remember Ulala standing on the
launching pad, saying: ``What's this? Something's up. I'm feeling
kind of funky!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Space Channel 5,'' published by Sega for the Sega Dreamcast;
$39.95; for teen-agers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
