<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3633 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-PARISH-DESIGN-ART-1     08-16 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARISH-DESIGN-ART-1,120(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHIND THE CHINTZ CURTAIN, THE LEGACY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JOHN LELAND    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DARK HARBOR, Maine _ The centerpiece on the table was a humble
ceramic head of lettuce, just as Sister Parish, the grande dame of
American decor, had placed it there decades ago. But on a recent
afternoon, as the summer clouds finally parted to allow in the
buttery northern sunshine, everything else in the room was on the
brink of commotion. The chintz was about to hit the fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to squish 26 people into this room,'' said Apple
Parish Bartlett, the owner of the house, where her illustrious
mother had spent nearly all of her 84 summers. ``We'll just shuffle
things around a little. Then we'll put it back, inch by inch.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett, 66, is a painter and dealer in decorative furnishings,
but the coming occasion was a dinner to celebrate the publication
of ``Sister: The Life of Legendary American Interior Decorator
Henry Parish II'' (St. Martin's Press), by Bartlett and her
daughter Susan Bartlett Crater. The book is a loving oral biography
of Sister Parish, Bartlett's mother, who shaped the domestic
aesthetic of various Kennedys, Astors, Paleys and Whitneys, until
her death in 1994. The invited guests for the party included the
staff of Parish-Hadley, the upper-crust New York firm formed by
Parish and the Tennessee-born decorator Albert Hadley (it closed
last year). By any measure, this was going to be a tough crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, shutters lay on the rolling lawn, awaiting a new coat
of paint. But inside, what to do? The clutter of this old Maine
house _ ceramic parrots, carved wooden dogs, embroidered pillows
sprawled on mattress-ticking upholstery, flags and quilts
everywhere _ was just the sort of froufrou over which the
supertraditional Parish and the modern Hadley had not seen eye to
steely eye. She loved it, he did not, and this difference was a key
to their creative partnership, the yin and yang of it. Here in Dark
Harbor, the centripetal force of Parish whirled unchecked.
</P>
<P>
   Stuff was everywhere. Bartlett saw no need to do anything
drastic about it. ``Oh, it always looks like this,'' she said,
smiling at the bold clash of orange print wallpaper and
raspberry-colored flooring (evidently from the high-Yankee
psychedelic era). ``How do you improve upon perfection?''
</P>
<P>
   The Summer House, as it is known in family circles, is an
unpretentious clapboard ranch house on a gentle waterfront slope.
Bartlett, who is divorced, lives here until the season turns, when
she moves to the Winter House, just down the hill. The Summer House
was the center of Parish's world, the exemplar of generational
continuity she stressed in her work. In 1967, House &AMP; Garden
magazine ran spreads of the house, bursting with wicker and
needlepoint and other crafts. Seldom had old-fashioned looked so
revolutionary. ``This was where the whole American country style
started,'' Crater said, repeating a truism of decor lore. From her
mouth to Martha Stewart's ear.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, Crater and Bartlett pondered an often-reported
family legend. Did Parish really swat a young Caroline Kennedy,
precipitating a split between the decorator and her most
illustrious client? ``I don't know how it got started,'' Bartlett
said. In fact, the story appears in their book, in an excerpt from
Parish's journal. ``But we wouldn't want to get into that whole
thing,'' said Crater, an artist. The girl ``probably had her feet
up on the sofa, and Sister probably swatted them away. That would
not have been beyond belief at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett laughed knowingly. ``In a funny way,'' she said, Parish
``was just imperious.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy ``Sister'' Parish was for the last half of the 20th
Century the queen of American decoration, reigning over three
generations of design luminaries, including Mark Hampton, Keith
Irvine, Bunny Williams and Mario Buatta. Her influence trickled
down to Ralph Lauren and Martha Stewart. If you have a quilt, you
probably owe it to Parish.
</P>
<P>
   Decorating is a hand-holding business, and Parish held some
regal hands, from Babe Paley's to Betsey Whitney's. She nearly
decorated for real royalty, too. But anti-American outrage _ and
her high prices _ prevented her from decorating the home of the
Duke and Duchess of York.
</P>
<P>
   Born into the Eastern establishment _ her father was Edith
Wharton's doctor _Sister Parish used her fierce eye, strong ego and
social connections to impose her generous, florid, unpretentious
vision on a country shaking off the chill of Victorian stuffiness
in the postwar years. Her vision included chintz and plenty of it,
often in bewildering, unmatched plenty. Parish, her daughter said,
did not go in for ``matchy-matchy.''
</P>
<P>
   A word here about names. Apple was born May Appleton Parish.
Sister was the nickname given to a young Dorothy May Kinnicutt by
her three brothers. The sobriquet lent itself to occasional odd
constructions, like ``my aunt Sister,'' as well as to
misunderstandings: when Jacqueline Kennedy tapped Parish to spiff
up the living quarters on Pennsylvania Avenue, Bartlett said, one
newspaper reported that a nun was redecorating the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett and Crater said they intended their book to be a social
history, capturing the milieu of Murray Hill and Dark Harbor and
other closed social worlds before the democratic creep of
post-1960s modernity, to say nothing of gazillionaire rock stars
and dot-commers, penetrated the blueblood walls. Constructed in the
manner of Jean Stein and George Plimpton's ``Edie,'' with blocks of
quotations from friends and relatives alternating with excerpts
from Parish's journal, the book is a portrait of society without
the John O'Hara elements: no drinking, no adultery, no bad
behavior. And no dollar figures. ``We weren't interested in that
next level of psycho-biography,'' Crater said.
</P>
<P>
   They gloss delicately over a level of high-decor bloodshed,
including battles over the Kennedy White House, the commission that
so raised Parish's profile. James Abbott, author of ``Designing
Camelot: The Kennedy White House Restoration,'' said that shortly
into Parish's endeavors, Kennedy asked others, including the
Parisian decorator Stephane Boudin, to revise the rooms. ``A number
of times, Sister Parish threatened to quit,'' he continued, adding
that Parish ultimately obtained permission to take credit for one
of Boudin's window treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Such battles come with the territory, and with the fickle
clients who rule it, said the decorator Mario Buatta, who was
devoted to Parish. ``Those women weren't going to be faithful to
you,'' Buatta continued. ``I remember she called one client and
said, `It's going to kill my husband if you let someone else do
that room.' She was very controlling. You had to be.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The excerpts from Parish's journals reveal a more subtle form of
manipulation, the art behind the decorator's art. She stressed the
need to please husbands, who commonly paid the (often
stratospheric) bills. ``We did the largest, most elaborate job in
San Francisco for the Gettys, and Getty's sole interest was the
piano. We paid a great deal of attention to the acoustics in the
music room, and everything else just fell into place beautifully,''
she wrote, adding that once a decorator reels in the husband, ``he
becomes eager to keep going.'' And at that point, she concluded,
``you've won.''
</P>
<P>
   The book also offers a glimpse of an insular world that was
receding even as Parish was triumphing in it. It's a window
treatment on history.
</P>
<P>
   As Hadley remembers his introduction to the Kennedy White House:
``The first time I went there, the yellow room was being done. The
day we went was the day of the Bay of Pigs invasion.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dark Harbor house stands just as it did in Parish's day,
give or take a few new photographs and the odd crack in the walls.
In the master bedroom is the canopied bed on which she was born,
and on which she died. ``People can't believe that I sleep in the
bed someone died in,'' said Crater, who was in the middle of a
six-week visit. ``I don't think that's a strange thing.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of their research, Crater and her mother scoured the
family dressers and attics. They found letters from Edith Wharton.
They found recipes. ``She kept every one,'' Crater said, ``and she
was not a cook. We found one that said, `Rice: Put water in pot.
Put rice in water. Boil.'''
</P>
<P>
   Social histories are usually told after the fall, and the
influence of Parish has waned, eroded on one side by the mass
merchandizing of Americana and on the other by the triumph of
high-end modernism. The chintz, like the Social Register set that
championed it, has lost some of its glaze. ``The clients were
different then,'' Crater said of her grandmother's 1960s heyday.
``Now, a lot of people want to look rich, they want everybody to
notice where they are in the world. The Whitneys and the Paleys and
that crowd, they weren't proving that.''
</P>
<P>
   In Dark Harbor, though, Parish's influence still rules the homey
sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Bartlett finds her greatest happiness in yard sales.
She described a trip to the local dump, where she salvaged material
from a discarded sofa. Her eagle-eyed mother would have been proud
_ and might have grabbed some, too. And if the stories in
``Sister'' are any indication, she might have commanded a bundle
for it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
