<HEADLINE>
GEEK NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   New GPS Attachment Can Keep You on Track
</P>
<P>
   Lost while driving in a unfamiliar city? A new Global
Positioning System receiver slightly larger than a matchbox
attaches to a wide variety of hand-helds or laptops, enabling them
to provide directions like a native and a moving map that monitors
every turn.
</P>
<P>
   Pharos Science and Applications, based in Torrance, Calif.,
designed the $199 iGPS-180 receiver with road warriors in mind.
Business people need a GPS device that is portable, said James
Oyahg, the company's chairman. The iGPS-180 connects to any laptop
with a standard nine-pin serial port; there are custom cables to
connect the Palm and Visor hand-helds, as well as the Pocket PCs
(like the latest Cassiopeia models from Casio). The small receiver
has a cable that plugs into a car's cigarette lighter; when used
with a Cassiopeia, the lighter connection will power both the
receiver and the hand-held.
</P>
<P>
   Palm and Visor hand-helds and laptops can use any mapping
software that conforms to National Marine Electronics Association
Standard 2.0 or higher. For Pocket PCs, Pharos has an $89 mapping
program that lets the hand-held issue voice prompts like ``there is
a left turn ahead.'' In a test run, the Cassiopeia voice alerts
were somewhat unreliable, coming too early, too late or not at all
for some turns. And sometimes the device did not plot the best
route. But the map, which shows to its best advantage on color
screens, was always right on the mark.
</P>
<P>
   _ ROY FURCHGOTT
</P>
<P>
   E-Mail Fans Are Friendly Folks, A Sociology Study Indicates
</P>
<P>
   The more you use the Net, the more likely you are to be in
communication with friends and relatives, whether in person, by
phone or by e-mail. At least that's what Keith Hampton, an
assistant professor in the department of urban studies and planning
at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, and Barry Wellman, a
sociology professor at the University of Toronto, found after
analyzing a survey of 40,456 North Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that people who e-mail also talk more in person and
on the phone,'' Hampton said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the survey, which was presented at the American
Sociological Association's annual meeting, which ended Wednesday,
people who used the Internet only once or twice a year had 471
contacts of all kinds with friends and relatives who lived within
30 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Daily Internet users, by contrast, exchanged e-mail or had
conversations _ either in person or by phone _ with nearby friends
and relatives 1,312 times.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast became even more striking for more distant friends
and family members. People who rarely used the Net communicated
only about 75 times a year. Heavy Net users, however, had 997
exchanges a year. The two researchers considered about 40 Internet-
and community-related questions that were included in a survey
partly sponsored by the National Geographic Society and carried on
its Web site in October 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Wellman said other data from the study suggested that e-mail was
not, however, dislodging traditional forms of communications among
friends and family members.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is a huge add-on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Could it just be that heavy Internet users are just naturally
more friendly _ or chatty? ``I don't think you can tell at this
point if people who go online are inherently more communicative,''
Hampton said.
</P>
<P>
   _ IAN AUSTEN
</P>
<P>
   On Location: Reading Your Way Around the City
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Beller, a writer in New York, is putting literature on
the map. Beller's Neighborhood, a new Web site
(www.mrbellersneighborhood.com), divides an aerial view of
Manhattan into nine areas, then links essays, poems and stories to
the locations where they are set. If the viewer zooms in on the
Upper East Side, for example, a red dot at 77th Street and Madison
Avenue leads to W.H. Auden's poem ``In Schrafft's.''
</P>
<P>
   Beller, author of the novel ``The Sleep-Over Artist,'' said the
project, which was produced with the online magazine Word.com, was
``a narrative that sprawls in many directions.'' In other words,
it's all over the map.
</P>
<P>
   _ MATTHEW MIRAPAUL
</P>
