<SLUG> BC-CORPORATE-DAYCARE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAY CARE YOU CAN FEEL GOOD ABOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hooray for Amgen, like, totally.
</P>
<P>
   The Thousand Oaks, Calif., biotech firm recently gave all those
valley girls-turned-working moms something to kvell over: In June,
the company opened its newly expanded child-care facility, Camp
Amgen, a 44,856-square-foot romper room thought to be the largest
corporate day-care center in the United States. The facility can
handle up to 430 kids in 32 classrooms and offers its services to
employees for 10 percent to 15 percent less than comparable
day-care centers.
</P>
<P>
   Camp Amgen isn't just big; it's good. The National Association
for the Education of Young Children has given the facility
consistently high marks. It's a good thing for employees, the
company's getting good press, and the kids are in good hands. You'd
think other businesses _ and lawmakers _ would catch on.
</P>
<P>
   But high-quality, affordable child care still eludes many
working parents _ especially those of little means, advocates say.
Only one in 10 eligible low-income children are receiving federal
assistance for child-care services, according to the Department of
Health and Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   Even for middle-income families, day-care costs are a stretch. A
study co-conducted by the Children's Defense Fund in 1998 found
that the average cost of child care in Dallas was $4,838 a year for
a 12-month-old.
</P>
<P>
   And you thought the college fund would be challenging.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. House of Representatives and the Senate have passed
versions of the 2001 appropriations bill that includes child-care
funding, and a compromise bill is in the works. Although the Senate
and House versions both increase funding for child care in 2001,
the language of the House bill could threaten funding in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The Children's Defense Fund Web site, www.childrensdefense.org,
explains the details of the legislation and also offers Child Care
Challenge books that address the cost, quality and availability of
child care by state. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
