u l BC-HOME-COLUMN-COLORS-AR     08-16 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-COLUMN-COLORS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FURNISHING A NEW HOME WITH THE COLORS OF HER LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By TRISH HALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ She might not like the description, but some people
consider Bride Whelan something of a seer whose medium is color.
Tell her whether red, blue or green speaks most forcefully to you,
and she'll describe your personality, your style, your values. She
will insist, however, that there's nothing psychic about her
abilities, that ample evidence from science, history and psychology
explains the link between personality and color.
</P>
<P>
   Given her color-coded perspective on the world _ she has
consulted on color, taught, and written two books on the subject _
the question inevitability arises: What kind of colors does she use
at home?
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Whelan (who pronounces her first name BRI-dee) moved
from a 10-room house in Southport, Conn., where she had lived for
23 years, into a one-bedroom apartment in midtown Manhattan. The
move was precipitated, she said, by the classic causes: ``The
children left home, the dog died, and the cat ran away.''
</P>
<P>
   After 20 years of commuting, she wanted a place near her job as
the executive director of the Society of Publication Designers,
which has its office on East 42nd Street. A cheerful and engaging
woman who cannot walk down a block without running into someone she
knows, Whelan decided to forgo a broker in her search, figuring she
could do better on her own. She set out on foot, visiting buildings
and talking to doormen in the buildings that looked appealing.
</P>
<P>
   That tactic quickly turned up an apartment to rent on Park
Avenue near 39th Street, in a gracious building that is the epitome
of the old New York. The building has helpful doormen, an elevator
run by a human, and apartments with high ceilings, attractive
moldings and well-proportioned rooms. Whelan's apartment, a condo
that rents for $2,500 a month _ with a right of first refusal if
the owner decides to sell _ has a substantial foyer, a dining room
next to the galley kitchen, a large living room with an arched
entryway and a fireplace, and an equally spacious bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   The walls, surprisingly, are white. So are the couches in the
living room, and the spread and drapes in the bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the choices are temporary, others quite deliberate. She
always has white couches, Whelan says, because they provide a good
backdrop for the yellows and oranges she likes to use in rugs,
pillows and artwork.
</P>
<P>
   A multicolored quilt will eventually go on the bed, after she
makes some repairs to it. She is planning to paint one wall of the
living room a yellow orange, to give it the warmth and motion she
wants. ``Orange is a friendly color,'' she says. ``It says, I want
to be your friend. Orange means you like things to be pleasant and
happy. Yellow is always about motion.''
</P>
<P>
   But she'll do only one wall. ``I don't like a lot of color on
the walls,'' she says. ``I'd rather have a lot of color around
me.'' The bedroom, too, may eventually get a coat of a soft yellow.
</P>
<P>
   The colors she wears, she says, are quite different from the
colors she uses at home. To her office, she is likely to wear blue,
a color she says confers authority. When she shows up at a meeting
in a blue suit, she says, she is sending a message that she is in
charge. Black is something else. ``Black is always hostile, but's
it's very defining,'' she says, which may explain why it is the
color of New York.
</P>
<P>
   At home, she surrounds herself with warm colors like red, yellow
and orange. ``When you walk into my house, you feel very relaxed,''
she says. ``I think it's the color. I like to send a message with
color.''
</P>
<P>
   In her living room, there are patches of yellow and orange and
red everywhere _ in a chair covered with a paisley fabric, in a
carpet she found at the Tepper auction house, in the prints of
apples and oranges on the wall, in a batik cover over a corner
table. And especially, in a Majolica urn from Italy, from the
Victorian era, that is orange, yellow and green. ``I just like the
way it feels,'' she says. ``It looks happy.''
</P>
<P>
   People who are trying to figure out what colors they genuinely
like, and not what some style or fashion may dictate that they
like, should look for the one object in their home that makes them
happy, and then look at the colors, she says. If she were to pick
one thing in this apartment, it would be that urn.
</P>
<P>
   She has done little to the galley kitchen, except place her
toaster oven on one burner of the massive commercial-style Viking
stove. ``That's my level,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Not that she doesn't entertain. There is a roof deck atop the
15-story building that is rarely used by the other tenants, and on
New Year's Eve and the Fourth of July she had parties there. ``It
was just spectacular,'' she says, because of the views of the
Chrysler Building and the Empire State Building.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer, she has missed the garden she had in Connecticut,
but otherwise, leaving the suburbs was easy. ``It's a wonderful
life if you have children,'' she says. But later, it's not so
wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   ``The suburban life for a single woman was just deadly,'' she
says. ``In the city, you can do things by yourself. There doesn't
have to be that attachment factor.'' She has been divorced for 20
years, and with her three children all well into their 20s, it
seemed time to leave and move onto the next stage.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there is a sign over her front door that says it all,
something that was left by the owner that suits her perfectly. It
says: ``Though no one can go back and make a brand new start,
anyone can start from now and make a brand new ending.''
</P>
</TEXT>
