<HEADLINE>
FEMINIST GROUP PUTS ITS MONEY WHERE ITS VALUES ARE
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Tuesday, AUGUST 15, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADVISORY: With photo from fund-raiser (NNS2)
 By MILES BENSON  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES \A'' It was your typical Democratic National
Convention fund-raiser, under glittering chandeliers in a hotel
ballroom, with candidates in full cry at the podium and 1,000
well-dressed guests who paid $250 each for their cold chicken and
see themselves as big-league political power players.
</P>
<P>
   And they are. They hand-pick candidates, train them, supply them
with expert campaign staff, mobilize voters and deliver cash \A''
lots of cash. They put people in office.
</P>
<P>
   They are almost all women, from the candidates on the platform
to the check-writers in the audience \A'' the women of Emily's
List.
</P>
<P>
   The feminist political fund-raising organization that began as
one woman with an idea and a Rolodex in her basement has grown in
15 years into ``the biggest funder of federal candidates in the
country,'' according to founder Ellen Malcolm.
</P>
<P>
   Emily's List backs only pro-choice Democratic women candidates
running for congressional or gubernatorial office. With 60,000
members nationwide, the group can pump more than $1 million in
contributions to a candidate. The political action committee of
Emily's List has more financial muscle than the Teamsters Union.
About 10 percent of Emily's List contributors are men.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now a real financial powerhouse and obviously that's
translating into a historic number of wins for women candidates,''
Malcolm said with pride.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence is all around here in California. Malcolm welcomed
to the platform a succession of women elected with the help of
Emily's List money, including both of the state's senators, Dianne
Feinstein and Barbara Boxer, and Rep. Nancy Pelosi, one of the
state's 12 women members of the House. Pelosi could become the
majority whip next year if the Democrats regain control of the
chamber this November.
</P>
<P>
   Operating with a budget this election cycle of $28 million and a
staff of 41, Emily's List is backing 24 women so far this year.
Their marquee candidates are Hillary Rodham Clinton, running for
senator in New York, and Debbie Stabenow, who is seeking a Senate
seat in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Emily's List is ``very important and very effective,'' said
Democratic National Chairman Edward Rendell.
</P>
<P>
   In the battle to control the House, only 12 Democrats have been
able to raise more than $1 million so far, and eight of them are
women who are receiving Emily's List backing.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me it's just a delight to see these women run in these
tough races and come out the winner,'' Malcolm said. ``We've never
been able to do that before. We've made history in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always that way, of course. When she began the
organization, Malcolm recalls, it was common for the men who
dominated the Democratic Party to deny funding to women who wanted
to run for office on grounds that they were not viable candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because they wouldn't give them any money, the women couldn't
become viable candidates, so they were really trapped in this
vicious circle,'' Malcolm said. ``Emily raises early money for
women because our strategy was that if we could get them started
and put some money in the bank and get them a poll, they could
convince the old boys that they were viable candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   It worked. In the seven elections since Emily was founded, the
group has helped elect seven Democratic women senators, 49 members
of Congress and three female governors.
</P>
<P>
   The organization takes its name from a political slogan: Early
Money Is Like Yeast. (It makes dough rise.)
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I wondered who Emily was,'' laughed Pat Rich of
Beverly Hills, who became a member of the group five years ago.
``Who's the martyr we're named after, the poor, downtrodden `Emily'
victimized by the Republicans?''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Wright of Los Angeles said she is an Emily's List member
because the organization ``focuses on all the issues that matter to
women: abortion, guns, children.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Duff, a longtime activist from New York, said the
``smartest thing'' Emily's List did was broaden its role in 1994 to
include voter mobilization efforts targeting women with special
mailings and telephone outreach, in addition to fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi said the success of Emily's List may make it possible to
double the number of women in Congress by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Women have three vital interests in this year's presidential
election, according to Boxer: ``The Supreme Court, the Supreme
Court and the Supreme Court.'' She was talking about the
probability that the next president will appoint one or more new
Supreme Court justices during his tenure, changing the narrow
five-to-four majority that now upholds abortion rights for women.
</P>
<P>
   Republican George W. Bush is firmly opposed to abortion and his
party's platform calls for the appointment of judges who would ban
all abortions, though Bush has said he would not apply such a
litmus test to his judicial appointments.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Al Gore supports abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   But the Democrats are worried because Bush leads Gore among
women in most polls, a reversal of the trend in past elections when
Republicans suffered from a so-called gender gap among women
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to be concerned about the Democrats, the big
question is whether the women are coming back or not,'' said Robert
Strauss, a former Democratic national chairman. ``That's Gore's
problem, the women's vote. Is he going to be able to get it back?''
</P>
<P>
   Gore and the Democrats need not worry too much, according to
Malcolm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters are just bouncing around right now,'' she said. ``Women
think George W. Bush seems like a nice fellow and maybe they'll
vote for him. But when they really start focusing on their
decision, they're going to look at the issues, see who they agree
with and who they don't, and who is the leader who is going to take
the people forward. We're going to see a big shift. Women are going
to come back to the Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   The big test ahead for Emily's List is whether it can deliver on
that promise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
