u p BC-CVN-MCNEELY17-COX     08-16 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-MCNEELY17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ANN RICHARDS' CONVENTION FROM ON HIGH
 &HT;    By DAVE McNEELY
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If you're looking for former Gov. Ann Richards of
Texas at the Democratic National Convention here, you're better off
watching CNN than dogging the Texas delegation meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The woman who keynoted the 1988 Democratic convention in Atlanta
and chaired the 1992 convention in New York was on CNN's ``Larry
King Live'' show late Tuesday evening, paired with Bill Bennett,
who was President Bush's drug czar and Ronald Reagan's education
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Richards, who will be 68 on Sept. 1, was there to give the
perspective of a former Democratic elected official on the
convention. After four years as governor, she was beaten for
re-election in 1994 by George W. Bush, now the GOP nominee for
president.
</P>
<P>
   Richards called President Clinton's convention speech Monday _
and his administration _ the best she has ever seen. Bennett
replied that Clinton should have addressed lying about his affairs
in the White House, which make him ``a felon.''
</P>
<P>
   Richards chided Bennett for holding grudges, saying she both
bestows and has needed forgiveness. People have flaws, and so do
their leaders, Richards said.
</P>
<P>
   The woman who in 1988 said of Bush's father, ``Poor George _ he
can't help it _ he was born with a silver foot in his mouth'' said
Vice President Al Gore's speech Thursday night ``is the most
important speech that I have seen in my lifetime at conventions.''
</P>
<P>
   While conventions are now largely staged affairs, the
presidential nominee's acceptance speech ``does give the candidate
an opportunity to set before the public _ uninterrupted _ their
vision and their ideas about what they're going to do in the
country,'' Richards said in an interview outside the CNN anchor
booth at the Staples Center here.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Gore nor Bush can hope to compete with Clinton as a
speaker, Richards said. But if Gore is to have any chance of
beating Bush, he must use the speech tonight to seem presidential.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Clinton has built a bridge to the 21st century,''
Richards said, borrowing a line Clinton emphasized over and over in
his 1996 acceptance speech. ``Al Gore's going to have to walk
across that bridge. And when he gets to the other side, he's going
to have to look like a president. And how well he does is going to
shape the rest of this campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   What does she think about the man who unseated her?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I say to everyone that I could spend 24 hours of every
day responding to people who think I'm going to give them some
special insight into George Bush,'' Richards drawled.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, he is my governor, of my home state. And as a
consequence, it is inappropriate for me, because I have bias, to
comment on him or his performance,'' Richards said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what I want them to know is that they already know _ they
already know _ everything there is to know about George Bush.
There's no mystery here. There's no depths to plumb. And I tell
'em, `Trust your instinct. Because what you think now is accurate,'
'' she said with a low chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   Richards these days splits her time between high-dollar
Washington lobbying for the Washington law firm of Verner Liipfert
on behalf of high-dollar clients, including tobacco companies, and
making speeches, many of them gratis fund-raising appearances for
Democratic office-holders and candidates.
</P>
<P>
   She made her CNN appearances during the Republican National
Convention by remote hookup from Washington. But she is here in
person, seeing old friends like former Vice President Walter
Mondale, and even son-in-law Kirk Adams, a Washington-based
national labor organizer.
</P>
<P>
   Both before and after her 15-minute TV stint Tuesday, standing
in the halls outside the CNN skybox anchor booth, Richards is
interrupted every few seconds by an awe-struck, often reverential
well-wisher _ most of them wishing to get their pictures taken with
her. Richards readily obliges.
</P>
<P>
   Richards, sometimes besieged in the past by the news media,
isn't giving many interviews, other than with King. She says her
contract with CNN prevents it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm contracted out,'' Richards said, smiling. ``Isn't it
good?'' she added, and walked away, chuckling.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
