<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: This version includes the reporter's name which was
eliminated from the earlier version.
 &HT;    A refreshing dive into some of Florida's freshest, coolest
waters
 &HT;    By Mary Thurwachter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _
</P>
<P>
   GINNIE SPRINGS
</P>
<P>
   7300 N. E. Ginnie Springs Road, High Springs. Phone: (904)
454-2202.
</P>
<P>
   How big is the boil? A second-magnitude spring, Ginnie has a
flow of 29 million gallons per day.
</P>
<P>
   Average water temperature: 72 degrees
</P>
<P>
   Our view: While kids floated in bright-colored inner tubes and
boats, divers searched the caves below. We could see the bubbles
from the air tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Ginnie Springs is an extremely pretty place, with its turquoise
waters and its shady campgrounds. It's easy to understand why
divers from all over the world come here.
</P>
<P>
   You actually get seven springs for the price of one (Deer, Twin,
Dogwood, Ginnie and three that are part of the Devil Spring
system). All of them dot the Santa Fe River. The clear, blue spring
water provides a stark contrast to the dark, tannin-stained river.
When the two mix, as they do at the river's edge, the results are
spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   Interesting fact: More divers learn to cavern and cave dive at
Ginnie Springs than anywhere else, according to the Ginnie Springs
Web site. Be warned: If you want to explore the caves, you must be
certified. Cave diving can be dangerous. At least 27 divers have
lost their lives here.
</P>
<P>
   Activities: Swimming, diving, tubing, canoeing, kayaking,
hiking, camping, picnicking.
</P>
<P>
   Admission: $7 per person, per day.
</P>
<P>
   HOMOSASSA SPRINGS
</P>
<P>
   4150 S. Suncoast Blvd, Homosassa. Phone: (352) 628-5343.
</P>
<P>
   How big is the boil? A first-magnitude spring, Homosassa has a
flow of 113.8 million gallons per day
</P>
<P>
   Average water temperature: 75 degrees
</P>
<P>
   Our view: Unless you swim with them, you're probably not going
to get any closer to a manatee than you will inside the ``fish
bowl,'' a sort of reverse aquarium. The bowl allows visitors to go
below the surface of the water and watch the manatees as they munch
on carrots and lettuce and swim inches away from the glass windows.
</P>
<P>
   You'll also see turtles and a variety of saltwater and
freshwater fish that can travel unrestricted between the headwaters
and the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Also fun: the zoo, which features a 40-year-old hippo, a couple
of American bald eagles, a silver fox, a Florida black bear,
alligators galore, lots of flamingos and other birds.
</P>
<P>
   Interesting fact: The park is a rehabilitation center and refuge
for endangered West Indian manatees that have been orphaned or
injured in the wild. Most of the birds and animals living at
Homosassa could not survive in the wild.
</P>
<P>
   Activities: Educational programs about manatee, alligators, and
wildlife encounters. Picnicking, hiking.
</P>
<P>
   Admission: $7.95 for adults (age 13 and over), $ 4.95 for
children ages 3 through 12; free for kids under 3. Average water
temperature: 72 degrees
</P>
<P>
   Our view: Surrounded by cypress, gum, ash, and maple trees,
Manatee Springs is an ideal place for canoe rides.
</P>
<P>
   The morning we visited, the swimming area was beginning to fill
with children and their mothers. A trio of moms were doing some
serious toe-dipping and then retreating up the stairs to warm up on
the park benches. The kids didn't seem to mind a bit.
</P>
<P>
   Interesting fact: Located on the Suwannee River just 23 miles
upstream from the Gulf of Mexico, the park consists of 2,075 acres.
It opened to the public in 1955. At this spring, you need to visit
in fall or winter months to see the manatee.
</P>
<P>
   Activities: Picnicking, fishing, swimming, canoeing, hiking and
biking on the 8.5-mile north end trail system, scuba diving, nature
study and camping.
</P>
<P>
   Admission: $3.25 per vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   POE SPRINGS
</P>
<P>
   28800 N.W. 182 Ave., High Springs. Phture: 76 degrees
</P>
<P>
   Our view: In 1859, an archaeologist, John LeConte, wrote that
the most remarkable feature of this place was ``the truly
extraordinary transparency of the water ... surpassing anything
which can be imagined.'' His assessment holds true today, not only
for Silver Springs, but all of the springs we visited.
</P>
<P>
   During the summer, swimming is allowed only on weekends. And,
since we arrived on a Friday, we spent the day trough the gardens
and the petting zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Local legend has it that if people have their picture taken
standing surrounded by the trunk of the horseshoe palm tree at the
water's edge, they wour pockets and posed with the lucky tree. (No
winners, to date, but we have have our fingers crossed.)
</P>
<P>
   Interesting facts: The glass-bottom boat, invented in 1878 by
Hullam Jones, made its debut here in 1910 and has been a popular
attraction ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Johnnie Weismuller came here to film Tarzan movies. But he
wasn't the only star to work in Silver Springs. Others include
Gregory Peck and Jane Wyman for Marjorie Kinnan Rawlings' ``Tper
for ``Distant Drums,'' and Lloyd Bridges for more than 100 episodes
of ``Sea Hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   Activities: Reptile shows, boat rides,akulla Springs, 32305.
Phone: (850) 224-5950.
</P>
<P>
   How big is the boil? A first-magnitude spring, Wakulla has a
flow of 252 million gallons per day.
</P>
<P>
   Average water temperature: 73 degrees
</P>
<P>
   Our view: Tarzan movies were filmed here and Old Joe (a 1d in
the lodge. There's a great swimming hole, diving ramps, and a 1937
lodge with marble floors, an ornate lobby ceiling, antique
furniture and what looks like one of the first elevators ever made.
</P>
<P>
   But what really lifted our spirits was the glass-botale-telling,
had us applauding Henry, the pole-vaulting fish.
</P>
<P>
   After the guide hollered out to the reel star, (Hen-REEEEE!) we
watched as the black bass, less than a foot long, sailed out and
flopped over a cypress pole several feet under water. Henr
Interesting fact: Wakulla has been a tourist favorite since the
1930s. The park has the world's largest and deepest freshwater
springs and is surrounded by 3,000 acres of virgin forest. Ponce de
Leon discovered the springs in 1513 and thought it was the fountain
of youth.
</P>
<P>
   Activities: Hiking trails, picnic areas, swimming, diving, boat
rides ($4.50).
</P>
<P>
   Admission cost: $3.25 per vehicle
</P>
<P>
   WARM MINERAL SPRINGS
</P>
<P>
   Halfway betw the springs. Phone: (941) 426-1692
</P>
<P>
   How big is the boil? A third-magnitude spring, Warm Mineral has
a flow of 9 million gallons per day.
</P>
<P>
   Average water temperature: 87 degrees
</P>
<P>
   Ouy Warm Mineral Springs was Ponce de Leon's destination when he
cWe thought the resort, which is privately owned, looked like it
needed a face lift.
</P>
<P>
   Interesting fact: Warm Mineral Springs, which is listed in the
National Register of Historic Ppopcorn, but played the tambourine
during the performance and made sure kids weren't clogging up the
stairways. On the other side of the glass, the mermaids swam and
lip-synched to recorded songs, taking breaths of airr the
``geezer'' cruise, as I like to call it. Our grandfatherly guide,
with his Rodney Dangerfield delivery, told silly jokes that fell on
mostly deaf ears because most of the passengers were kids or from
foreign countries. You had to be over 45 to get his punch lines.
But more than the funny old man, the cruise was a delight because
pelicans and egrets guided the boat down the rivem were healthy,
but we saw some wounded guys, as well, at the pelican orphanage.
</P>
<P>
   Also spotted: a pair of manatee and a raccoon.
</P>
<P>
   Interesting fact: Mermaids began performing at Weeki Wachee in
1947 when Navy frogman Newton Perry built the underwater theater 45
minutes north of Tampa. Some of the famous guestlliams, Don Knotts
and Howard Cosell.
</P>
<P>
   Activities: Live mermaid shows, nature boat tour, swimming,
diving, canoeing, water slides, petting zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Admission cost: $14.95 for adults; $10.95 for children 3-10
</P>
