<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SUB-0817-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIA ACCEPTS HELP FROM BRITISH IN RESCUING SAILORS TRAPPED ON
SUB
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ A British rescue team is expected to begin a long
voyage Thursday to assist a stranded Russian submarine amid fears
that they may arrive too late to save the lives of 118 crewmembers
trapped in the vessel.
</P>
<P>
   A flurry of activity Wednesday _ including a reluctant call by
Russian officials for foreign assistance _ came after the only sign
of life from the submarine fell silent. For days Russian officials
have reported hearing tapping against the Kursk's hull, but the
sounds ceased Wednesday, suggesting the worst for the crew aboard
the submarine some 350 feet below the surface of the Barents Sea.
</P>
<P>
   However, Russian officials insisted that this didn't mean the
crew had perished. Deputy Prime Minister Ilya Klebanov told the
Interfax news agency that this could be a sign that the crew was
attempting to conserve oxygen. ``There is no sign of life,''
Klebanov said. ``But from this it is not necessary to conclude
something terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian Navy Commander Vladimir Kuroyedov said the crew might
have stopped tapping because the sailors knew rescuers were on the
way. ``One needs to take into account the mentality of submarine
officers,'' Kuroyedov said. ``Once they knew rescue capsules were
above them, they maintained silence.''
</P>
<P>
   The 20-member British team is expected to leave Trondheim,
Norway, Thursday morning for the 900-mile trip to the rescue site
in the Arctic Circle. The trip could take until Saturday evening _
the day after Russian officials have said the oxygen supply aboard
the Kursk would be depleted.
</P>
<P>
   However, a Russian admiral said Wednesday that the massive
Oscar-2 class submarine could have enough oxygen to sustain the
crew as long as another week.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the mini-sub, Britain dispatched to the site
three Hercules jets loaded with equipment and a navy survey vessel,
a British defense ministry spokesman said. Norway also sent a ship
with around a dozen civilian divers.
</P>
<P>
   Once at the site, the British team would within hours send down
its LR5 mini-submarine. Once the mini-sub links with the Kursk it
will be able to transport to the surface up to 16 people at a time.
It would take an additional 24 hours to recover all the
crewmembers, the Navy said.
</P>
<P>
   The rescue could be hampered if LR5's rescue hatch turns out to
be incompatible with the submarine's hatch. Russian and British
officials expect to meet Thursday to review such technical issues.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the dire circumstances, the British rescue team's leader
told reporters he had not lost hope. ``We would not be going unless
we thought there was something positive we could do,'' said
Commodore Tim Chittenden.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials who had initially refused to ask for foreign
assistance officially asked for help Wednesday, five days after the
submarine sank to the floor of the Barents Sea near Norway, which
shares an Arctic border with Russia.
</P>
<P>
   British officials said their rescue team had been preparing for
the call for days. The submarine foundered Saturday, apparently
after an explosion that followed the launch of a torpedo during a
training mission. The alarm was sounded after the Kursk failed to
make a scheduled radio contact Saturday and it was found Sunday,
Navy officials told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. Navy submarine monitoring Russian naval exercises in the
area heard an explosion Saturday that appeared linked to the Kursk,
U.S. officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Just before Russian officials officially requested foreign
assistance, the British team took off from an airfield in Scotland
with the LR5 aboard a giant Russian transport and arrived in Norway
in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The last-minute decision to accept aid _ which was offered on
Monday _ could open authorities to criticism that national pride
prevented them from calling for help sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Vladislav Ilyin, deputy chief of staff of the Russian Navy, said
on Russian television that President Vladimir Putin gave the order
``to accept help wherever it comes from'' after a 30-minute
telephone conversation with U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, on vacation in a Black Sea resort since the crisis began,
made his first public statement and defended the rescue effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the moment it became clear that something had happened,
all necessary and possible efforts to save the craft and its crew
have been carried out,'' he said in a television appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately the weather is very bad. A storm has raged for
two days, and sailors could not use all the means at their
disposal,'' he said. He described the situation as ``critical.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the navy established a hotline for relatives of
crewmembers, many of whom flew Wednesday to the submarine's base on
the Arctic Ocean. They were quartered on a boat that will put to
sea to greet the sailors _ if any are rescued.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian rescue capsules, operated by a crew of three or
four, can rescue up to 20 men at a time. But they have been unable
to dock with a cargo hold in the rear of the Kursk, which is tilted
60 degrees on the sea floor in waters with strong currents and low
visibility.
</P>
<P>
   The British LR5 minisub has never been used in a real rescue,
but was designed for just such a life-or-death situation.
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s E-mail address is: bertrcoxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
