<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Aug. 17, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A warm front pushing to the east will cause showers and
thunderstorms across the southern Great Lakes Thursday. Flooding is
possible in areas with poor drainage because some showers will
carry bursts of heavy rain.
</P>
<P>
   Breezes from the north will direct cool air into much of the
Northeast. Readings will be as much as 10 degrees below normal.
</P>
<P>
   The Southeast will turn very hot as high pressure along the
northern Gulf Coast promotes abundant sunshine. Many locations from
East Texas to the central Gulf Coast states will exceed 100
degrees. Farther west, the remnants of Tropical Storm Beryl will be
drawn into southern Arizona and New Mexico. Cloudy skies and
numerous showers will be all that is left from this system.
</P>
<P>
   The northern Plains will turn cooler in the wake of a cold
front. The West Coast will stay mostly sunny and mild.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: CHICAGO'S SUMMER
</P>
<P>
   Summer finally arrived in Chicago on Tuesday when the mercury
rose above 90 degrees at O'Hare International Airport for the first
time this year. There has only been one summer, 1875, when the
temperature failed to reach 90. The last time the temperature
stayed below 90 for most of the summer was 1979, when the
temperature only rose to that level twice. Before 1958, the
official temperature in Chicago was taken much nearer the lakefront
and was not as influenced by the urban heat island, making the
summer of 2000 even cooler by comparison than it seems.
</P>
</TEXT>
