<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0817-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Life's a speech
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sen. Joe Lieberman officially steps into the national spotlight
tonight, to deliver what could well be the most important speech of
his life. His speech is expected to last less than 20 minutes,
after an introduction by his wife, Hadassah. The speech will first
touch on his personal experiences including his early involvement
in the civil rights struggle. He is expected to talk about the
country's progress in the last eight years, talk about the Al Gore
he knows and respects, and draw sharp distinctions between the
Gore-Lieberman team and the George W. Bush-Dick Cheney team. But
Lieberman said he would not play the traditional role of attack
dog: ``I've talked to Al about this, and we're very intent on
talking about progress, not partisanship. This is not going to be a
campaign of personal attack.''
</P>
<P>
   HUMANIZING GORE
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore arrived in Los Angeles this afternoon in time to hear
his eldest daughter _ 27-year-old Karenna Gore Schiff _ deliver a
deeply personal convention speech designed to introduce to the
nation the personal side of the vice president. While sipping
coffee with teachers in a suburban Detroit restaurant this morning,
Gore confessed to being very nervous about his daughter's speech:
``I've got more butterflies about that than my own speech,'' he
said. Gore has a relatively light schedule in Los Angeles. He will
visit a couple of state delegations _ Tennessee was on tap for sure
_ and take time out to watch Joe Lieberman deliver his acceptance
speech tonight. Earlier in the day, he attended a rally in Burbank
with Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN DIAGNOSED WITH SKIN CANCER
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain has been diagnosed with a recurrence of skin
cancer on his arm and temple, Republican officials said this
afternoon. McCain plans a news conference Friday to discuss his
medical condition. During his presidential campaign, McCain
released hundreds of pages of medical records that detailed the
lingering effects of injuries suffered in a Vietnam prisoner of war
camp. The records also showed that in December 1993, McCain had a
cancerous mole removed from his shoulder that proved to be
melanoma, the most dangerous form of skin cancer.
</P>
<P>
   LAPD'S BLUES
</P>
<P>
   Police are maintaining a pervasive presence throughout downtown
Los Angeles as demonstrators protested for a third day around the
convention today _ this time against police brutality and
corruption in the Police Department. Hundreds of activists marched
to a LAPD station at the center of a growing corruption scandal,
chanting: ``Racist, sexist, anti-gay, LAPD go away.'' To add to the
department's woes, the American Civil Liberties Union said it would
file a lawsuit today, accusing the LAPD of shooting innocent people
in the back with rubber bullets during Monday night's
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   PERHAPS HE CAN SPEND THE TIME PRAYING THEY WIN
</P>
<P>
   For several crucial days right before the election, Joe
Lieberman will be sidelined from the campaign trail by religious
holidays. Rosh Hashanah (the Jewish New Year) falls on Sept. 30 and
Oct. 1. Yom Kippur (the day of atonement) falls on Oct. 9. Sukkot
(the Jewish harvest festival) arrives Oct. 14 and 15. Simchat Torah
(an annual celebration of finishing reading the Torah _ the word of
God _ and beginning again) comes on Oct. 22. Election Day is Nov.
7. ``Al Gore is a man of faith and he respects my faith and my
observance, and he's been very clear that he doesn't want me to
vary from my traditional practices, and I won't,'' Lieberman said.
Lieberman also observes the Jewish Sabbath, the traditional day for
worship and rest that stretches from sundown Friday to sundown
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICA FIRST
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of his religion, Joe Lieberman will favor U.S.
policies over those of Israel when they differ. ``My first and only
loyalty is to the United States of America,'' he said. While noting
that U.S. and Israeli policies on Middle East matters have
generally been similar, he said, ``If they ever diverge, as they
have occasionally, my record shows that I've supported, obviously,
the U.S. position.'' He cited as an example Israel's plan to sell a
quarter-billion-dollar advanced airborne radar warning system to
China. The Clinton administration opposed it, and so did Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   THE FIRST STEP IS ADMITTING YOU HAVE A PROBLEM
</P>
<P>
   Green Party Ralph Nader, running for president as the Green
Party candidate, is actually jeopardizing the environment by
threatening Al Gore's chances, Gore supporters said today. ``His
candidacy poses a high threat to the environment in this country''
because it could ensure the election of George W. Bush, said Robert
F. Kennedy Jr., senior attorney for the Natural Resources Defense
Council. Kennedy said Nader's candidacy could take a significant
share of the Democratic vote in Minnesota, Ohio, Oregon,
Pennsylvania and Wisconsin. Together those states have 72 electoral
votes. Polls show Nader garnering about 4 percent of the vote
nationally. However, pro-environment sentiment is stronger in some
states than in others, magnifying the effect of the Green vote in
the winner-take-all Electoral College.
</P>
<P>
   THE OLD 'SOME OF MY BEST FRIENDS ARE . . . ' DEFENSE
</P>
<P>
   The Anti-Defamation League is crying foul over an editorial in
the Amsterdam News that claims that Jews bought the selection of
Joe Lieberman as Al Gore's running mate. In the editorial, Wilbert
Tatum, publisher emeritus of the black-owned newspaper in New York,
wrote: ``Gore and his minions did it for the money . . . the Gore
camp went out all over the world to Jews of means: You've got to
show me the money. When you do, one of yours will be given the
second spot on the ticket.'' ADL national director Abraham Foxman
today called it ``the worst anti-Semitic rhetoric that I have read
in a long time, unless I want to plug into a hate Web site.''
Tatum, whose wife is Jewish, brushed off the ADL's accusations:
``My wife is a Holocaust survivor. My daughter is Jewish. I am not,
nor have I ever been, an anti-Semite,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   DEBATING THE DEBATES
</P>
<P>
   More than eight months after the presidential debate schedule
was announced, George W. Bush has not yet committed to any of the
three proposed debates and may participate in only two. Said Bush
communications director Karen Hughes: ``I believe President Clinton
and Bob Dole debated twice. I believe two times has been the
norm.'' Hughes also noted that while Bush plans on debating Al Gore
in some fashion, Bush aides have not really had a formal discussion
yet to determine what settings would be appropriate. For Bush,
rejecting one of the debates so late in the season can be risky,
opening him to accusations of being either scared or too arrogant
to participate. Already, Gore has pursued this line of attack,
creating a 'debate duck countdown' on his Web site.
</P>
<P>
   YEAH, BUT CAN HE PLAY THE SAX?
</P>
<P>
   Mixing politics with music, Al Gore's children visited the
legendary House of Blues in Los Angeles and said their father will
do an MTV town hall meeting on Sept. 26. ``I'm here to tell you
that my father is extremely tuned into the issues facing this
generation,'' daughter Kristin Gore told about 700 young people
attending MTV's ``Choose or Lose 2000'' party. The Gore offsprings
were there to register members of the cheering crowd to vote.
</P>
<P>
   JUST WHAT THEY NEEDED _ MORE AMMUNITION FOR THE 'LIBERAL BIAS'
CHARGE
</P>
<P>
   The first night of the Democratic convention got more minutes
and pulled in more viewers, both on the networks and on the cable
news channels than the first night of the GOP's. A farewell speech
by President Clinton was largely responsible for the increases. In
spite of Republican demands that the networks not carry more of the
Democratic affair, the three major networks devoted a total of 172
minutes more time to the Democrats on opening night. Said RNC
spokesperson Cliff May: ``We're not suggesting for a minute that
the networks shouldn't be covering Bill and Hillary Clinton. We
just think they also should have been covering Colin Powell and
Condoleezza Rice and Laura Bush. The opening night of the
Democratic convention is important, but so is the opening night of
our convention. Our only intention here was, quite frankly, to
remind them of their commitment to fairness and balance.''
</P>
<P>
   A VAST LEFT-WING CONSPIRACY
</P>
<P>
   Network executives are debating whether the Democratic National
Committee's opening night schedule fell behind because of poor
planning or a strategic ploy to get more airtime for its speakers.
The executives had been expecting that the night would go long,
because President Clinton is known for his lengthy speeches, but at
10:30 Eastern time, when all three broadcasters had expected
President Clinton, they instead got Hillary Clinton, who thus
received prime time coverage in New York, where she is running for
a Senate seat. If her speech had started at its scheduled time, it
would have received partial or no coverage on the three major
networks, which prompted the suits at these outlets to question
whether they had been tricked. ``They do what they do, and we do
what we do. I do feel that, inadvertently or deliberately, we were
manipulated, and it certainly turned out to be a favorable night
for the Democrats,'' said CBS News president Andrew Heyward.
</P>
<P>
   HERE'S THE TORCH, WHERE'S THE McCHICKEN?
</P>
<P>
   Mere moments after hugging Al Gore and leaving him alone onstage
in a symbolic passing of power, President Clinton made a beeline
for the local McDonald's and ordered a cholesterol-laden meal. When
the president pulled out a wad of $20 bills to pay for his crispy
chicken sandwich, french fries and Diet Coke, the young clerks
refused his money: ``It's on the house. They didn't tell you?'' For
a president who promised to lay low so that Gore could command the
spotlight for a couple of days, Clinton made quite a splash in his
new role as slumming second banana. He brought daughter Chelsea,
who informed an amazed patron that she is a vegetarian ``health
food freak'' before ordering an ice cream cone. Another patron
scanned the room for Gore's new running m News Campaign 2000 Web
site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
