<HEADER>
A3665 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-AOL-0817-COX     08-16 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-0817-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEW QUESTIONS WON'T SLOW MERGER, ADVOCATES SAY
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Regulators this week hit America Online and Time
Warner with a new round of questions, but consumer advocates doubt
the queries suggest the government will slow the companies'
proposed merger.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission's (FCC) persistent
questioning is ``just part of a charade,'' said Mark Cooper,
research director of the Consumer Federation of America. ``We don't
believe the FCC is going to do anything'' to protect consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said FCC regulators typically ask many questions about
mergers, but then take little action. He pointed to the
commission's recent approval of AT&AMP;T Corp.'s $58 billion
acquisition of MediaOne Group Inc., creating a cable powerhouse
with relatively few restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   When the FCC commissioners examined that deal, ``they waltzed
AT&AMP;T around for awhile...but then they let them do whatever they
wanted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   David Butler, a spokesman for the Consumers Union, said the
FCC's inquiries into the AOL and Time Warner deal ``are serious and
important.'' But he added that ``the fact that the agency is going
through several rounds of questions is no indication'' the deal
will be curbed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates fear that AOL, the world's largest online
company, and Time Warner, a cable giant with 12.6 million
customers, will impose their services and content on captive
customers if they are allowed to join forces. For example, a
combined AOL-Time Warner could force cable customers to watch only
Warner Brothers' cartoons and take only AOL's Internet access, they
warn.
</P>
<P>
   They want the FCC to ensure that cable customers can get ``open
access'' to the content and services of many competitors, just as
ph quoted unnamed industry sources as saying AOL executives are
uncomfortable with running a regulated business and would prefer to
focus on content and online services.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner spokesman Scott Miller dismissed that story, saying
the management of both AOL and Time Warner share an ``equally
strong'' commitment to the cable business.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocate Cooper said he believes a combined AOL-Time
Warner would sell off its cable operations only if the FCC were to
create an open access standard for the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the FCC had established a regime of true open access, then
it would make sense to be a content company,'' he said. ``But it's
exactly the failure of the FCC to act that means (AOL and Time
Warner) aren't going to give up their wires.''
</P>
<P>
   The FCC is reviewing the transfer of Time Warner's broadcast
licenses to AOL. Since the merger was announced Jan. 10, the FCC
has been focusing its investigation on AOL's instant messaging
software and its interactive television platform, as well as on
Time Warner's exclusive contract with Road Runner, a venture that
provides high-speed Internet access via cable lines.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives for the two companies said they expect the FCC,
the Federal Trade Commission and the European Union to wrap up
their investigations in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pleased with how the regulatory review is proceeding,''
AOL spokeswoman Kathy McKiernan said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Time Warner were to sell off its cable holdings, it's
unlikely one company would be able to buy them all. AT&AMP;T, the
largest U.S. cable company, might have the deepest pockets in the
industry, but regulators, mindful of the AT&AMP;T-MediaOne merger, are
likely to be careful about a deal that would make AT&AMP;T even bigger.
</P>
<P>
   Other cable providers might be interested in pieces of Time
</P>
<P>
   Warner's cable pie. For example, Atlanta-based Cox
Communications could expand its San Diego market by acquiring the
Time Warner cable system next door.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Federal Communications Commission site:
http://www.fcc.gov
</P>
<P>
   AOL site: http://www.corp.aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner site: http://www.timewarner.com
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
