<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Thursday, Aug. 17 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   DEM-RDP (Los Angeles) _ A roundup: Vice President Al Gore is
nominated; Sen. Joseph Lieberman speaks to the convention.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, CVN1.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-GORE-BIO-TRANSFORM (Undated) _ After Al Gore ran for
president in 1988 and lost, just as he turned 40, he organized a
series of dinners where he went around the room and asked each
person to tell him where he had gone wrong. It was excruciating,
his friends said, but he insisted on hearing the bad news. Gore
responded, as he always has, by going back to school. He put
together a graduate seminar for one, complete with a syllabus and a
heavy-duty reading list, and applied himself. Politicians often
learn from and are even transformed by a good drubbing at the
polls, but few have pursued their lessons as aggressively as Gore.
And no one can say that the man who will accept the Democratic
Party's nomination for the presidency Thursday night has not
diligently prepared for this moment. By Melinda Henneberger and
Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SUBMARINE (Moscow) _ Russia asked for help from the West
on Wednesday as its own rescuers desperately struggled through
swirling sand and strong currents, trying to reach 116 sailors
trapped in a crippled Russian nuclear submarine on the bottom of
the sea. After days of frustrated attempts to lower a rescue
capsule to the submarine, Russia, which had refused foreign aid,
relented and turned to Britain and Norway for help, the countries'
foreign ministries said. (Summary from wires). By Patrick E. Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   LAWYERS-PRO-BONO (Undated) _ Inundated by a hyperactive economy
that generates more business than they can often handle, and in
some cases actually turning away paying clients, many law firms
have cut back on pro bono work so sharply that they fall far below
professional guidelines for representing people who can not afford
to pay. The statistics are startling: The roughly 50,000 lawyers at
the nation's 100 highest-grossing firms spent an average of just 8
minutes a day on pro bono cases in 1999, according to a July survey
by the American Lawyer magazine. That comes out to about 36 hours a
year, down sharply from 56 hours in 1992. The decline is troubling
for many in the legal profession, especially because the American
Bar Association urges lawyers to do at least of 50 hours of pro
bono work each year. By Greg Winter.
</P>
<P>
   VODKA-SMUGGLE (New York) _ Over the last two years, a federal
investigation into Russian and Italian organized crime in the ports
of Newark and Elizabeth, N.J., turned up the expected mix of
mundane mob staples: extortion, cigarette smuggling, money
laundering. But federal agents said they also came across a bit of
criminal enterprise that, for pure creative corruption, struck them
as remarkable: a loose-knit web of companies was smuggling tens of
millions of gallons of American-made grain alcohol _ including
millions of gallons from one of the country's oldest distilleries _
to Eastern Europe to slake a seemingly boundless thirst for that
most Russian of spirits, vodka. By William K. Rashbaum.
</P>
<P>
   HIKER-HUT-ACCESS (In the White Mountains National Forest, N.H.)
_ Over slick boulders, across too-narrow bridges, through mud that
coated their limbs, three hikers in wheelchairs and two on crutches
braved a 12-hour struggle up the Gale Head trail here to arrive at
a hut that some had said they would never use. The moral being,
said one of the hikers: Do not tell us where we cannot go. Their
destination, the Gale Head Hut at an elevation of 4,300 feet, has
just been rebuilt by the Appalachian Mountain Club, and during the
process, some had ridiculed the idea that the club would go to the
expense of making the hut handicapped-accessible, complete with
ramp and bars by toilets. It was ridiculous, they said: no one in a
wheelchair was ever going to get there. They were wrong, it turns
out. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
</TEXT>
