<SLUG> BC-HOT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T SWEAT IT: HERE'S THE LOWDOWN ON AUGUST
</HEADLINE>
 TOPIC-AUGUST-TEX  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By LISA DAVIS 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ah, August. Sweltering heat. Back-to-school. Immortalized on a
Neil Diamond album, ``Hot August Night.'' On the whole, not a great
31 days, although it does have its moments &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You sunburnt sicklemen, of August weary, Come hither from the
furrow and be merry.'' _ Shakespeare's ``The Tempest'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NO, IT IS THE HEAT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   August is not the hottest month. (It just feels that way.) The
hottest day of the year is actually July 21, based on national
averages over the past 10 years. The average high for Fort
Worth-Dallas in August is 96 degrees _ same as in July. The hottest
temperature ever recorded in Texas was in August (120 degrees in
Seymour in 1936) _ although that matches the 120 degrees recorded
in June in Monahans in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Why is it so hot? In the summer, the northern half of the globe
tilts toward the sun, so we're closer to the heat source. Plus, the
longer days mean we spend more time absorbing heat. But take heart.
At least we don't live in Monahans. Source: U.S. National Climatic
Data Center, www.ncdc.noaa.gov &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE BOYS OF SUMMER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a masculine name, ``August'' means venerable and majestic.
Here are some famous Augusts. (Augie, Gus and Austin are all
derivatives of August, but we've limited this list to the latter,
because we're not sure Austin Powers belongs in such august
company).
</P>
<P>
   August Wilson: Pulitzer Prize-winning playwright
</P>
<P>
   August Strindberg: 19th-century Swedish author
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Auguste Renoir: painter of some renown
</P>
<P>
   Auguste Rodin: sculptor of some renown
</P>
<P>
   Auguste Comte: French philosopher who coined the term
``sociology''
</P>
<P>
   Garrett Augustus Morgan: inventor of the traffic signal
</P>
<P>
   Auguste Escoffier: innovative French chef; namesake of Les Dames
d'Escoffier
</P>
<P>
   Augusto Pinochet: former Chilean dictator &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHERE AUGUST GOT ITS NAME &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The month is named after Augustus Caesar, emperor of Rome from
27 B.C. to A.D. 14. He took over after his great-uncle, a guy you
may have heard of, Julius Caesar. Augustus was an administrative
genius who got Rome functioning again as an empire. He also oversaw
the golden age of Roman literature, which encompassed Virgil and
Horace. He was originally named Gaius Octavius, but adopted
``Augustus'' as a title to emphasize his superiority. (Joke's on
him. He's got a darn unpleasant month named after him.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOT DOGS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Early August falls within the dog days of summer, so named by
the Romans. For the six to eight hottest weeks of the summer (July
3-Aug. 11, or thereabouts), the dog star, Sirius, rises with the
sun. The Romans figured it only added to the sun's heat, hence, dog
days. Source: Brewer's Dictionary of Phrase and Fable &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AUGUST DOCTRINE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   St. Augustine (A.D. 354-430) was a pillar of the early Christian
church, serving as the Bishop of Hippo in North Africa. He is best
known for his book ``City of God,'' written partly to console
Christians who fled the fall of Rome. In it, he writes of two
cities: the heavenly and the earthly. Christians, as citizens of
the heavenly city, are not to be overly concerned with the earthly,
but are to live on Earth as pilgrims, ever conscious that they'll
be returning to their true home.
</P>
<P>
   Augustine lives on in ways beyond theological. Bob Dylan wrote
``I Dreamed I Saw St. Augustine.'' He also shares his name with a
grass.
</P>
<P>
   Source: James J. O'Donnell's Augustine Page,
ccat.sas.upenn.edu/jod/augustine.html &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOT CITIES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At least nine states are home to cities named Augusta, notably
Georgia (home of the Masters golf tournament), Maine (it's the
capital), Arkansas, Illinois, Kansas, Kentucky, Montana and
Wisconsin. There's also St. Augustine in Florida. Texas, always
overexuberant, has both an Augusta AND a San Augustine. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A READING LIST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Snow in August'' by Pete Hamill: An Irish-Catholic boy
befriends a rabbi in postwar Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Guns of August'' by Barbara W. Tuchman: Pulitzer
Prize-winning history of the 30 days leading up to World War I.
</P>
<P>
   ``Light in August'' by William Faulkner: Mixed-blood orphan Joe
Christmas is condemned to life as an outsider. &QL; 
 &QL; 
IT REALLY IS A LOUSY MONTH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   History has not been kind to August. Among the tragedies of the
eighth month:
</P>
<P>
   A.D. 79: Mount Vesuvius erupts near Pompeii (Aug. 24).
</P>
<P>
   1619: The first African slaves arrive in North America (Aug.
20).
</P>
<P>
   1814: During the War of 1812, the British capture and burn
Washington, D.C. (Aug. 24).
</P>
<P>
   1883: The volcano Krakatau explodes (Aug. 27).
</P>
<P>
   1914: Germany invades Luxembourg _ the first act of warfare of
WWI (Aug. 1).
</P>
<P>
   1923: President Warren G. Harding dies of a stroke (Aug. 2).
</P>
<P>
   1926: Rudolph Valentino dies (Aug. 23).
</P>
<P>
   1934: Adolf Hitler becomes Fuhrer (Aug. 2).
</P>
<P>
   1935: Will Rogers is killed in a plane crash (Aug. 15).
</P>
<P>
   1944: Anne Frank is captured by the Nazis (Aug. 4).
</P>
<P>
   1945: Hiroshima is bombed (Aug. 6).
</P>
<P>
   1945: Nagasaki is bombed (Aug. 9).
</P>
<P>
   1961: East Germany erects the Berlin Wall (Aug. 15).
</P>
<P>
   1962: Marilyn Monroe is found dead (Aug. 5).
</P>
<P>
   1965: The Los Angeles Watts riot begins (Aug. 11).
</P>
<P>
   1966: Charles Whitman opens fire from the University of Texas
clock tower (Aug. 1).
</P>
<P>
   1968: Protests turn violent at the Chicago Democratic National
Convention (Aug. 26).
</P>
<P>
   1969: Charles Manson's followers murder Sharon Tate and four
others (Aug. 8).
</P>
<P>
   1974: President Nixon resigns (Aug. 8).
</P>
<P>
   1977: Elvis Presley dies (Aug. 16).
</P>
<P>
   1990: Iraq invades Kuwait (Aug. 2).
</P>
<P>
   1996: Prince Charles and Princess Diana divorce (Aug. 28).
</P>
<P>
   1997: Diana is killed (Aug. 31). &QL; 
 &QL; 
Source: www.historychannel.com &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 1801EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000816.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3670 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-KOREA-REUNIONS-730(2T     08-16 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-REUNIONS-730(2TAKES)-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOREOGRAPHED VISITS CONTINUE FOR FAMILIES DIVIDED BY NORTH AND
SOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAMUEL LEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ On their first full day in South Korea
after half a century of separation from their families, 100 North
Koreans stepped into the bowels of capitalistic excess Wednesday _
a giant shopping mall.
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by a marching band playing a rousing rendition of ``Our
Hope Is Unification,'' an emotional song well known by both North
and South Koreans, the visitors walked under a five-story clock
encrusted with stained glass and through the stainless steel gates
of Lotte World in southern Seoul. A 29-acre mall, it has a 533-room
hotel, an amusement park, three shopping centers, an indoor golf
course and one of Asia's largest duty free shops.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the North Koreans were allowed to stop and shop at any
of the glitzy stores. Once off the bus, the group was whisked up
three flights of stairs into a dimly lit folk museum that features
miniature exhibits of scenes from 5,000 years of Korean history,
with the notable exception of the war that split the country in
two.
</P>
<P>
   Spying the visitors as they filed by, Jeon Ok-im, a clerk at a
women's clothing store, ran out into the main corridor to see them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been great if they could've come to see the
stores,'' Jeon said. ``But I guess they wouldn't have been able to
control them. The atmosphere would have been too free.''
</P>
<P>
   The North Koreans trekking through Lotte World Wednesday morning
were half of the group that flew to South Korea on Tuesday to be
reunited with the families they lost during the war 50 years ago.
The reunions are intended as the first step down the long road
toward reunification of the Korean peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   The other half of the group remained at their hotel, meeting
privately with South Korean family members. In the afternoon, the
two groups traded itineraries in yet another example of the bizarre
orchestration that marks what under normal circumstances would be a
series of intimate, intensely private family affairs.
</P>
<P>
   But the ground rules agreed upon by the two governments, rising
out of five decades of hostility and mistrust between the two
countries, make normality impossible. The North Koreans are staying
in a hotel on one side of the Han River, while their southern
relatives stay in a hotel on the opposite shore.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, their first meeting was a mass gathering in a
cavernous convention hall, bristling with boom microphones and
crawling with reporters and photographers.
</P>
<P>
   And on Wednesday, the North Korean visitors were hustled onto
buses and ferried to Lotte World, when they might have preferred to
spend the entire day with their families.
</P>
<P>
   In North Korea, 100 South Koreans visiting relatives there were
being subjected to a similarly rigid routine.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   South Korean officials chose Lotte World as the site for the
day's tour because of its proximity to the hotel where the North
Koreans are staying _ not to give them a lesson in free market
economics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The schedule is very tight, and they have to move around in
groups,'' said the Unification Ministry spokesman, Kim Hyun Do.
``If they were to go out further, the round trip could run up to
four or five hours.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that North Korean government officials, who visited
Seoul earlier this year, went on the same tour, which gave South
Korean officials experience and lessened the logistical
difficulties of the outing.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the noisy symbol of a free-market economy that
greeted them, the North Korean visitors were markedly reserved in
their comments and expressions, visibly mindful of the North Korean
officials who were their ever-present escorts, often holding their
hands as they walked along.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the minders nor the reunion's South Korean organizers,
however, anticipated Oh Soon-kyun, 52, and her daughter. Holding a
large piece of paper with the name of their North Korean family
member, they showed up at Lotte World determined to greet Kim Gyu
Sol, 66, one of the North Korean visitors and the brother of Oh's
husband.
</P>
<P>
   For logistical reasons, the South Korean government allowed only
five South Korean family members to meet with each North Korean
visitor, and Oh and her daughter had been excluded
</P>
<P>
   For a brief moment, Oh and Kim Gyu Sol embraced. With tears
glazing their faces, they whispered a few words to each other. But
Kim Gyu Sol pulled away, saying ``I have to go now,'' and rejoined
the tour group.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Inside the folk museum, Kim Gyu Sol and the other North Koreans
began a miniature journey through the history of their nation,
starting with scenes of stone-age ancestors hunting for food. It
was impossible to know whether the models brought to mind the food
shortages in their own country; both the North Korean visitors and
their South Korean counterparts had been warned not to discuss
matters relating to living conditions in North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The North Koreans moved from exhibit to exhibit, their faces
fixed in polite expressions that showed little evidence of awe or
envy toward the palaces of wealth and intricate historical tributes
that their Southern counterparts had built over the decades since
the end of the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already seen things like this before,'' said Moon Yang
Ok, 67, who came to visit her younger sister in Seoul. ``We have
these exhibits, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Ri Rok Won, 59, said the exhibits reminded him of his days as a
child in the South. ``I saw the real thing on a school trip a long
time ago,'' Ri said.
</P>
<P>
   But pressed to give his impression of Seoul, he glanced at his
North Korean escort and tapped on his ear. ``His hearing is not
good,'' his escort said.
</P>
<P>
   Ri Don, 82, was more candid. He said the 20-minute bus ride from
the hotel to the shopping mall was a bit nerve racking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad we didn't get in a car accident,'' he said. ``There
are so many cars!''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the warm smiles and welcomes from the people on
the streets made up for the congested streets.
</P>
<P>
   Pak Sang Op, 68, said the Seoul he remembered from 50 years ago
seemed to have deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Han River is the same, but it became a lot murkier,'' he
said. ``The city is just too crowded and doesn't have the freshness
it used to.''
</P>
<P>
   Jo Jyu Gyong, 68, felt differently. ``I'd like to go back to my
old campus someday,'' he mused. Now a celebrated academic in North
Korea, accorded the status of People's Scientist by the founder of
North Korea, Kim Il Sung, Jo graduated from the prestigious Seoul
National University.
</P>
<P>
   He said his mother had put him through university by peddling
goods. But during the war, Jo volunteered to serve in the North
Korean army and, like so many of the visitors on this trip, never
returned home.
</P>
<P>
   The tour ended with models of open-air markets and royal palaces
in the 18th century, and then the visitors watched a short
multimedia presentation of a major Korean naval battle in the late
1500s, which saw the defeat of Japanese invaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We share the same history,'' Pak mused. ``Unification will
lead to more glorious progress.''
</P>
<P>
   The North Koreans seem more convinced of the potential for
reunification than their Southern compatriots. Lee Jin-kyu, a
retired office worker sitting outside the mall and watching the
hubbub around the North Koreans, was somewhat skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the North Koreans seem to be saying, `Great Leader
this' and `Great Leader that,''' Lee said. ``I sincerely hope that
the two Koreas will soon become one. But it will be difficult if
they keep on saying things like that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
