<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3674 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBC-SCAROLINA-0817     08-16 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SCAROLINA-0817 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holtz has no excuses for 0-11 season in 1999
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Football coaches hate few things more than an excuse. You either
get it done or you don't.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Lou Holtz's first as head coach, the South Carolina
football team didn't get it done. The Gamecocks went 0-11 for the
first time in school history. As a result, they bring the nation's
longest losing streak _ 21 games _into the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   It was, as Holtz described it recently, ``The Lost Year.'' And
not only because of the defeats on the field, but because it was a
season where personal hardship made it nearly impossible to
concentrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back, there is really nothing else we could have
done,'' Holtz said. ``There were just extenuating circumstances,
some unforseen things that came up.''
</P>
<P>
   The circumstances are not excuses for the 1999 season:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  His wife, Beth,had been successfully battling throat cancer
only to have the disease reappear.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  His son Skip, the team's offensive coordinator, fell victim to
a mysterious illness and was hospitalized for almost a week in
September.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  His mother, Ann Marie, died in November, the day before the
Florida game.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A plane that was scheduled to pick up Holtz for a recruiting
trip crashed, killing the pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Given what happened in his personal life, going through 16
offensive linemen and six quarterbacks because of injury doesn't
seem quite so depressing.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest,'' Holtz said, ``I'm proud of the way I coped
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, on the eve of his second year in Columbia, the 63-year
old Holtz has been reinvigorated. In December, doctors at the Mayo
Clinic told Beth Holtz that her cancer was in remission. Friends
say Holtz has had a spring in his step ever since. And he's done
something he never had the emotional energy to do during the
tumultuous 1999 season: He's gotten a little mean.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't tough enough; I know that now,'' he said. ``But since
last December, I have been. We're not a good, solid, football team
now. But we can be _ and we will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Holtz cracked the whip academically on the players who had been
falling behind. His point: There is more to being a college
football player than just showing up for practice and playing
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting players to line up and play is easy. Developing a team
feeling is much more difficult and we're still trying to do that,''
Holtz said. ``We're in the SEC, and we have standards to meet. But
we have to meet them as a team. It's more than just going out and
playing football. We've got to become football players.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the South Carolina players are beginning to catch on.
Since June, members of the offensive line have been meeting on
their own to work out and watch film together. The offensive line
was the weakest of several weak links on the 1999 team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll take the blame,'' said junior guard Phillip Jones, a
graduate of Snellville's Brookwood High. ``It can be attributed to
us. But we also want to be responsible for getting it turned
around.''
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina ranked last of 114 Division I teams in total
offense (229.6 ypg). In the SEC, only Kentucky gave up more sacks
(53) than the Gamecocks, and the Wildcats threw the ball 191 more
times.
</P>
<P>
   But, again, facts _ not excuses _ led to such a dismal
performance. South Carolina suffered so many injuries on the
offensive line that defensive players who never had played offense
were starting for the Gamecocks in SEC competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will never happen again,'' Holtz said.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina has not only a re-energized coach but also a
goal. In his four previous Division I coaching stops, Holtz has
taken the team to a bowl in his second year.
</P>
<P>
   If South Carolina can get the offensive line stabilized, earning
a bowl bid might not be all that farfetched. Quarterback Phil Petty
is healthy again and will have two quality running backs in
sophomores Derek Watson and Andrew Pinnock. Senior wide receiver
Jermale Kelly has the ability to be a big-time player.
</P>
<P>
   The defense, which returns seven starters, never was a problem
last season. It finished fifth in the SEC (307.7 ypg) and 20th in
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the rest of the team had played like the defense, we would
have been fine,'' Holtz said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gamecocks will have a chance to break the losing streak at
home Sept. 2 when they host New Mexico State, which finished 6-5 a
year ago playing in the Big West. South Carolina plays its first
four games at home, including the SEC opener Sept. 9 against
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Holtz has decided that the best approach is to
pretend that this is his first year as the South Carolina coach,
that the horrors of 1999, both on and off the field, never
happened.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the losing streak. Focus on the goal. No excuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I think it is a realistic goal? Yeah,'' Holtz said. ``It's
probably not likely, but if some things fall into place, we could
make it kind of intesting for some people.''
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH CAROLINA
</P>
<P>
   -Location: Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   -Enrollment: 25,250.
</P>
<P>
   -Coach: Lou Holtz, 0-11 in his second year at South Carolina,
216-106-7 overall.
</P>
<P>
   -Stadium (capacity): Williams-Brice (80,250).
</P>
<P>
   -All-time record: 468-479-44.
</P>
<P>
   -SEC championships: None.
</P>
<P>
   -1999 record: 0-11 overall, 0-8 SEC.
</P>
<P>
   -Schedule: Sept. 2 vs. New Mexico State; Sept. 9 vs. Georgia;
Sept. 16 vs. Eastern Michigan; Sept. 23 vs. Miss. State; Sept. 30
at Alabama; Oct. 7 at Kentucky; Oct. 14 vs. Arkansas; Oct. 21 at
Vanderbilt; Oct. 28 vs. Tennessee; Nov. 11 at Florida; Nov. 18 at
Clemson.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
