<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3683 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CHINA-AD-COLUMN-2TAKE     08-16 1322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-AD-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGULATIONS HAMPER ADVERTISING IN CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (EDS: Numeral 8. is the correct initial in the byline; also moving
in `i' category.) 
 By JENNIFER 8. LEE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ When Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi set out to create a Chinese
television commercial for Daktarin, an athlete's foot medication
made by a unit of Johnson &AMP; Johnson, the advertising firm faced a
predicament. Chinese government regulations prohibit advertisements
from showing patients or symptoms _ critical elements for a
pharmaceutical commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi eventually resolved the problem by using weeds
as a visual analogy for the foot fungus. That satisfied the
regulators, but frustrated the ad agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Creatively, we could be 10 times better than now if it wasn't
for the regulations,'' lamented Philip Li, executive creative
director for Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi's Beijing office.
</P>
<P>
   Rigid government control, however, is the price to enter one of
the world's fastest-growing advertising markets. Li said he had
often had to rework commercials to address the objections of
Chinese censors _ or to avoid running afoul of them in the first
place. ``The regulations are always in the back of your mind,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising is just as problematic for the government. In
China's march from a centrally planned economy to a market economy,
officials have promoted advertising as an accelerator of economic
development and welcomed it as a way to supplant government
subsidies for many television stations and periodicals. On the
other hand, the government has also criticized advertising as a
conduit for both fraud and unwelcome foreign ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will try to be as lenient as possible, but whenever
anything touches cultural values or political stability, it is
something they have to crush right away,'' said Louisa Ha,
president of Dr. Ad Marketing International, a consulting firm
based in the United States that focuses on China.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola, for example, recently withdrew a multimillion-dollar
campaign for its Sprite soda because the ads featured a popular
Taiwanese singer, A-Mei, who had sung Taiwan's national anthem at
the inauguration of President Chen Shui-bian of Taiwan. China
regards Taiwan as a renegade province.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they allowed her to be on the commercial, they would be
allowing dissidence,'' Ha said. ``Politics is above everything else
in this country's agenda, whatever economic interests are
sacrificed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Those interests are not insignificant. In the 21 years since a
Shanghai station showed China's first television commercial, for a
Chinese tonic wine, advertising spending in China has soared from
zero to more than $7 billion, and by some estimates is as high as
$12 billion. The range results from discrepancies between published
rates and discounted rates that advertisers are actually charged,
coupled with the weakness of China's accounting system.
</P>
<P>
   While that is a fraction of the $165 billion spent on
advertising in the United States last year, China is one of the
world's fastest-growing markets. It surpassed South Korea to become
Asia's second-largest market behind Japan.
</P>
<P>
   As advertising has mushroomed, so has the government's
determination to keep it under control. In a country where the
media are monitored carefully for their political and social
influence, advertising is considered a privilege bestowed by the
government and not a commercial extension of the right of free
speech.
</P>
<P>
   In adjusting this privilege, the government has updated its
advertising rules more than 30 times in the last six years.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines range from vague principles, such as instructing
advertisements to not ``jeopardize the social order,'' to specific
prohibitions, such as those that forbid the use of state symbols
such as the flag or national anthem. Companies are also not allowed
to use superlative terms like ``best'' or compare their products
with those of competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The prohibitions have scuttled ads for such products as Bristol
Myers' painkiller Bufferin, which claimed to be ``the best,'' and
Colgate's diamond-headed toothbrush, which the company asserted was
superior to traditional rectangular toothbrushes. However,
Budweiser's slogan that it is ``America's favorite beer'' was
allowed to air after its brewer, St. Louis-based Anheuser-Busch,
provided statistical evidence to support the claim.
</P>
<P>
   While the regulations may seem severe, the government considers
them a necessary consumer-protection measure in a country where
soaps have claimed to help people lose weight and tonics promise to
make people smarter. In the United States, consumer sophistication
backed by government regulations has convinced most advertisers
that it is in their own best interest to shun exaggerated claims
and outright falsehoods in advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Self-regulation is the hallmark of maturity in an advertising
industry,'' said Hong Cheng, a professor of communications at
Bradley University in Peoria, Ill. ``This kind of system is still
in the making in China. That is why the government has to act as a
Big Brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the regulations went into effect, the government said it
has found 160,000 examples of false or misleading advertisements
and has imposed penalties of more than $54 million. The number of
``advertising malpractice'' cases handled by the authorities rose
36 percent last year, led by ads for drugs, medical services and
food.
</P>
<P>
   These included products called Jiannan Capsules (which
translates as Healthy Male Capsules) and Alaska Shengmin Lixiong
Platinum (Alaska Life Strength Chest Platinum). Several of the
cited products trade on the Chinese translation of Viagra, the
impotence treatment, which is not trademarked in China. The
government didn't identify the manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shadow of the regulations hangs over the advertising
creative process from beginning to end,'' said Louis Wong,
president of Beijing-based Megacom Advertising, who estimates that
half of his commercials have to be modified during the approval
process. ``It is annoying, but this is reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Television commercials, which receive the greatest scrutiny due
to their wide viewership, must be submitted to each regional office
of the State Administration for Industry and Commerce before
airing. Many companies submit their storyboards and script before
filming just as a precaution.
</P>
<P>
   The approval process is subjective and fragmented, with some
regional offices approving commercials that other offices reject. A
shampoo commercial that showed a glimpse of a bather's shoulder was
accepted in cosmopolitan Shanghai, for example, but banned in a
conservative neighboring province. Other commercials that received
storyboard approval were rejected after the final edit. Some
commercials are censored after they go on the air.
</P>
<P>
   Commercials that violate standards can sometimes be salvaged by
rewriting the script or making other adjustments, but some are
simply banned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of our problems are pharmaceuticals and things related to
underwear,'' said Wong. ``The problem is often over-exaggeration of
a product, or that it goes against the general moral standards of
the Chinese population.''
</P>
<P>
   Pharmaceuticals face the strictest regulations. That industry,
the largest spender in advertising, faces reviews by public-health
officials as well as advertising regulators. And, because of a
history of exaggerated claims for medicines, advertisers in China
are not allowed to show patients, children or symptoms. Nor can
they associate products with the names of doctors or hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Sexual modesty is also emphasized by the government. Models must
be covered at least 15 centimeters (5.9 inches) down from their
necks and 15 centimeters up from their knees, which can be
inconvenient for companies trying to sell shampoo or underwear.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are marketer for the underwear, you want to demonstrate
that a piece of underwear fits well,'' said Wong, whose firm is
working on an account for Embroform, a Hong Kong underwear company.
``But if you just featured a face of a woman up to the shoulders,
then what is the point of an underwear commercial?''
</P>
<P>
   His firm is looking into using computer animation for the
commercial, and in that way avoid the fate of a previous ad that
was censored because authorities thought a model's miniskirt was
too short.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign manufacturers aren't the only advertisers who have run
into trouble. The government itself has on occasion run afoul of
the censors. A commercial advocating condom use to avoid AIDS and
other sexually transmitted diseases was pulled late last year, two
days after it first appeared, when the State Administration for
Industry and Commerce decided it was too risque
</P>
<P>
   Regulations not only restrict the content of advertisements, but
the structure of the industry. China has 50,000 advertising firms
employing almost half a million people, an average of just under 10
people per company. To protect domestic agencies from foreign
competition and to limit foreign cultural influence, multinational
advertising agencies are required to set up joint ventures and are
limited in their equity. Foreign advertising executives said they
expect China to relax or eliminate that requirement if the country
is admitted to the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   While China's advertising market is experiencing dramatic
revenue growth, creative growth is unremarkable as a consequence of
all the restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at all the award-winning commercials in the Cannes
Festivals, I can bet 80 percent could not be in China because of
the content,'' said Wong. It's frustrating, he said, but he and
others knew to expect it when they walked into China.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want fun and creative,'' Li concurred, ``that's not
China.''
</P>
</TEXT>
