<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV03-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., SEP. 3, 2000. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 c.2000 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: To publish Bernard Gladstone's ``Home Improvement
Questions and Answers'' it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndication Sales. For purchase
information call toll-free 1-888-269-8796.) 
 (The NYTSS sales representative also has information on how to
subscribe to Gladstone's ``Home Improvement Questions and Answers''
weekly column which moves on Wednesdays.) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Water accumulates on the basement floor of our newly acquired
house after every heavy rain.
 &HT;    I've been told that other homes in this community had the same
problem but most owners have solved this by installing a sump pump
to get rid of the water.
 &HT;    Can you give me some idea of what a sump pump is and how it
works?
 &HT;    A: Sump pumps are usually installed in conjunction with drain
tiles that are installed around the perimeter of the basement floor
_ either under the concrete or in a trench cut into the top of the
concrete.
 &HT;    The drain tiles (plastic pipes) collect the ground water and
carry it into the underground sump or well where the pump is
installed.
 &HT;    A float switch inside this sump turns the pump on when the water
reaches a predetermined level.
 &HT;    This water is then discharged through a pipe that carries it
outside to a safe disposal area.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: The aluminum siding on my home is over 18 years old and much
of the finish seems to have worn off, so that it now looks dull.
 &HT;    Can this siding be painted, or must it be replaced with new
siding to make it look good again?
 &HT;    A: Aluminum siding can be painted with most good quality
exterior latex house paints, although there are some paints that
are advertised as being formulated especially for this purpose.
 &HT;    The siding must be thoroughly cleaned before you start,
preferably with a pressure washer that will remove all powdery
residue.
 &HT;    With most brands of paint, at least two coats are recommended.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: We have a problem with our recently laid flagstone patio.
 &HT;    Where puddles form after a rain the flagstone shows streaks and
stains _ apparently due to lime that seeps out from the cement
joints.
 &HT;    How can I remove or wash off these stains and is there any way
to prevent this happening again?
 &HT;    A: You should be able to clean the stains off by washing with a
solution of muriatic acid _ one part acid mixed with four parts
water. Mix the acid into the water in a plastic container (not
metal).
 &HT;    Be sure to wear rubber gloves and boots when you work with the
muriatic acid.
 &HT;    Spread on with a brush or mop and allow it to soak on the
surface for about five minutes or until it stops bubbling. Then
hose off with lots of water.
 &HT;    You can help prevent this happening again by applying a clear
stone sealer over the flagstone after it has dried for a couple of
days.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: We live in an apartment and constantly hear our neighbor's TV
set and stereo when he has them on.
 &HT;    Even when we ask him to turn them down (which he does
reluctantly) we can still hear the noise, especially when he plays
rock music.
 &HT;    Is there anything you can suggest we do to cut down on the
amount of noise that comes through the wall between his apartment
and ours?
 &HT;    A: There is really very little you can do other than actually
erecting a second wall in front of the existing one and filling the
space between the two partitions with acoustical insulation.
 &HT;    An alternative is to put up a second layer of drywall after
first nailing up horizontal resilient metal strips and then
fastening the new layer to these strips with drywall screws.
 &HT;    It would also help to install book shelves or cabinets filled
with books or other heavy objects along that wall and try to seal
off all openings in the wall with caulking compound.
 &HT;    Also, install insulating gaskets behind each electrical outlet
plate on that wall and apply caulking compound along the base of
the wall where it meets the floor.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NOTE: Drawing captioned ``SUMP PUMP'' goes with this column.
 &HT;    CAPTION: Sump pump will discharge water that accumulates in sump
when float switch is activated by rising water.
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.2000 Bernard Gladstone 
