<SLUG> BC-CVN-SANDERS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING THE `WHAT IF' GAME INVOLVING HENRY CISNEROS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BOB RAY SANDERS 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Every time I see Henry Cisneros, I play the ``what
if'' game: ``What if Cisneros had never ... well, you know, done
what he did in his personal life?''
</P>
<P>
   What if the former San Antonio mayor and former secretary of the
Department of Housing and Urban Development had run for the U.S.
Senate from Texas? Or for governor of the Lone Star State?
</P>
<P>
   When I answer those questions, I have no doubt that, before the
revelations about his not-so-private affair, he could have won any
statewide office he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   I am also confident that, instead of listening to the Democrats'
vice presidential nominee, Joe Lieberman, delegates to the
Democratic National Convention would have heard an acceptance
speech from Cisneros _ ``if '' ... Oh, well.
</P>
<P>
   He would have made a great running mate for Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But, what if?
</P>
<P>
   For years, Texas Democrats have been asking whether this
once-popular politician (and still popular citizen) could ever come
back and be successful as a candidate. Based on the reception he
got from his fellow Texans on Wednesday morning, the answer is yes.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, as Cisneros was waiting to take the stage at a
breakfast for the Texas delegation, former state Land Commissioner
Garry Mauro whispered in my ear: ``Four years. Four to six years
from now.''
</P>
<P>
   That was his prediction for when Cisneros would re-enter the
political ring.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros and his wife, Mary Alice, would make no predictions,
but neither ruled out a future run for public office. The couple
and their 13-year-old son, John Paul, just returned to San Antonio
after being away from Texas and from politics for a few years.
</P>
<P>
   They just moved into their San Antonio home last week, and
Cisneros is busy with a new business.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything else right now, he said, time is the one
thing against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years from now, I'll be a little old,'' said Cisneros, who
is 53.
</P>
<P>
   But what about four to six years from now?
</P>
<P>
   What if?
</P>
<P>
   During the speech to his home-state delegates, Cisneros told
them something they all know and long ago accepted: that the
Democratic ticket ``will not carry Texas in the year 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   All week, the Texans delegates have realized that their main
goal is not to deliver the state for Gore/Lieberman, but to be the
``truth squad'' to get the real story out to the rest of the nation
about Gov. George W. Bush's record in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis is also on electing more Democrats to Congress,
where they feel the party has a good chance of recapturing the
House and the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   They, too, are playing the ``what if'' game, and you'll hear it
for the rest of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   What if there had been a Democrat-controlled Congress when it
was time to vote on a patients' bill of rights, on requiring
background checks at gun shows or when it came time to confirm
nominees to the federal bench?
</P>
<P>
   Things would be very different now, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, there is another big ``what if'' floating around in the
minds of many of these delegates, a speculation they really don't
want to talk about out loud.
</P>
<P>
   What if there had been no Monica Lewinsky, Linda Tripp,
impeachment, Senate trial or that demonstration on the White House
lawn?
</P>
<P>
   What if, instead of spending all that time on lawyers and
depositions, the president could have devoted 100 percent of his
efforts to passing a second-term agenda?
</P>
<P>
   Well, Al Gore would not be behind in the polls right now. He
would be waltzing into the White House to the tune of ``Don't Stop
Thinking About Tomorrow''.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ray Sanders is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7775, or e-mail:
bobray(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
