<HEADER>
A3699 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DEM-DOCUMENTARY-2TAKE     08-16 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-DOCUMENTARY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTS IN AMERICA: A POLITICAL INTERLOCUTOR IS LEARNING ON THE JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK LYMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Philip Seymour Hoffman and Susan Sarandon were
seated on metal chairs near an open French window overlooking the
haze-choked Hollywood Hills, an American flag hanging listlessly
from a 20-foot pole attached to the ledge outside.
</P>
<P>
   Sarandon, who had just addressed the alternative gathering known
as the shadow convention in the chaotic, humid gloom of Patriotic
Hall, had come up here to the fourth-floor press room to be
interviewed by Hoffman. He acts as a kind of guerrilla guide to the
presidential campaign in ``Last Party 2000,'' a documentary being
directed by Donovan Leitch that has been shooting on and off since
March. How has it been going? Sarandon asked Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   He shrugged his shoulders and tugged at the bill of his cap.
``My head is in about 10 different places at once,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His was not the only crew working with digital cameras in and
around this year's Democratic National Convention. At times it
seemed as though people with cameras outnumbered the delegates.
</P>
<P>
   At least six camera crews were scattered around the crowded
lobby and sidewalk outside the shadow convention, with as many more
in the protest zone opposite Staples Center and on the official
convention floor inside. Add to this the individuals with digital
cameras clasped in their fists, and it seemed that no corner of the
crowded scene was left uncovered by filmmakers. But Hoffman, who
was committing a great deal of his time this year (though not all)
to the project, was probably the most famous face among them.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the crowd had fond memories of the earlier ``Last
Party,'' directed by Mark Benjamin and Marc Levin, on which Leitch
was a writer. Shot during the 1992 campaign and released in 1993,
it had a short flurry of success, particularly among young
audiences, though it was somewhat overshadowed by the critically
acclaimed ``War Room,'' a more traditional documentary offering
more of a behind-the-scenes look at that year's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The actor Robert Downey Jr. was the on-camera narrator of the
first ``Last Party,'' the subjective eye through which that year's
presidential election was seen. This year, Leitch said, he felt the
time was right to do it again. But with Hoffman _ the critically
acclaimed and prolific young actor, most recently seen on Broadway
in ``True West'' and on film in ``Flawless,'' ``Magnolia'' and
``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' _ the tone has shifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we did it with Robert Downey, he was like Puck,
frolicking through the convention,'' Leitch said. ``Phil is always
very aware of what is going on around him, and he's very
intellectual and very much wants to know what's going on. His
mantra is: Why should I care? Why is this important to me?''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman was intensely serious and preoccupied as he waited for
one of Patriotic Hall's ancient elevators to arrive with a shudder
and ferry him up to a news conference on the top floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the main reasons that I decided to do this was because
I really didn't know all that much about the political process,
outside of the basics,'' he said. ``I think a lot of people don't
know much more than that. This was an opportunity for me to learn
about it, how it really works, and maybe get more involved and
passionate about it.''
</P>
<P>
   It had been a procession of revelations, he said, about how the
political system functions and how difficult it can be to get
beyond the oratory and the masks and the security perimeters. He
was still digesting it, still learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think that maybe Phil has hit a wall here at the
Democratic convention,'' Leitch said. ``He's been so frustrated
with some of the responses he was getting, and tired of trying to
get behind the facades. I think he may be on the verge of a
breakthrough, where he'll feel compelled to take a stand. I'm
excited, because this is part of his character's development.''
</P>
<P>
   As might be expected in such an enterprise, a documentary on the
fly, it is a reasonably disorganized affair. ``I hope you don't
mind, the plan keeps changing all the time,'' said Rebecca
Chaiklin, one of the film's producers, between cell phone calls
setting up interviews. ``We really are kind of a guerrilla
operation.''
</P>
<P>
   The days begin with a meeting at which plans are made for
stationing the four digital cameras. But the crews try to remain
flexible, able to react to changing events and sudden interview
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   At the shadow convention the filmmakers had planned to hook up
with Bill Maher, host of ``Politically Incorrect,'' but instead
found themselves drawn into interviews with Sarandon, Rep. Tom
Campbell and a representative of Ozomatli, the Latino rock group
that had been playing in the protest zone when the Los Angeles
police pulled the plug on Monday night. Later on Tuesday they
planned to drive into South Central Los Angeles to interview people
on the street and then to go back to Staples Center for the
evening's official events.
</P>
<P>
   The group moved like a pack through the crowded lobby at
Patriotic Hall. Leitch was in the lead, Hoffman close behind, and
Chaiklin tried to follow them and talk on her phone at the same
time. Ben Weinstein, the director of photography, watched them
through the eyepiece of his digital camera while the sound
director, Jordon Pardes, trailed at the rear, his microphone
hanging from a pole over their heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plan is to do three things,'' Leitch said. ``First, we're
going to release some of our footage on an Internet site, some
issue-oriented material and trailers for the movie, along with
links to other campaign-related sites.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Then just before Election Day he hopes to have a soundtrack CD
available in stores, a compilation of protest songs from the 1960s
and '70s, covered by contemporary bands like the Stone Temple
Pilots. ``What we're trying to do is to build a bridge between the
protest generation of those days and the new generation today,''
said, Leitch, son of the '60s folk-pop singer known as Donovan.
</P>
<P>
   Around the same time the CD is released, a one-hour
making-of-the-soundtrack program will be seen on VH-1, the
pop-music cable channel. And then, around Inauguration Day in
January, the finished documentary will be given a limited release
in theaters, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really very much influenced by the movie `Woodstock,'
the way it looked and felt, and am going for something kind of like
that,'' he said. ``I especially liked that film's use of split
screens.''
</P>
<P>
   He may try something similar in showing President Clinton
speaking to the convention while the police and protesters are
clashing outside.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of hours have already been shot, he said, from the
primaries, from the campaign trail and now from the two national
conventions. The videotapes are shipped daily back to an editing
team in New York, where they are logged and digitized and the
process is begun to give the film some sort of structure. While a
good deal of the material may end up on the eventual Web site, the
version shown in theaters will be of standard length, which means a
lot of trimming and shaping. ``I don't want it to be longer than
100 minutes,'' Leitch said.
</P>
<P>
   As they have moved back and forth between the gatherings of
young political activists and the mainstream apparatus of the
national parties, the filmmakers have come to see that they are
dealing with two fundamentally different ways of looking at the
world, two universes that rarely meet and talk to each other,
Leitch said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately we have to find a way in the making of this film to
bring those two worlds together: the world of the people outside
the convention hall, the people on the streets, and the world of
the people on the inside,'' he said. ``We have to figure out how to
make them connect.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarandon smiled gently and leaned forward to hear Hoffman's
soft-spoken questions in the noisy babble of the interview room.
Weinstein hovered, Pardes' boom mike hanging like a pineapple over
everyone's heads. They were talking about Clinton's address to the
convention on Monday night, especially the theatrical lead-in
during which he was seen making his lone way through the strangely
empty corridors of Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was watching it, you know, I could feel a tear in my
eye, I really could,'' Hoffman said. ``I had to stop myself and
say, `Oh no, I'm getting moved, I'm getting manipulated.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
