<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3702 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SALZBURG-MUSIC-NYT &LR;      08-16 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALZBURG-MUSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPERA REVIEW: FINNISH COMPOSER'S DEBUT OPERA IS A LYRICAL
MASTERPIECE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALZBURG, Austria _ The Finnish composer Kaija Saariaho had
never considered writing an opera until 1992, when she attended the
director Peter Sellars' production of Messiaen's ``St. Francois
d'Assise'' here at the Salzburg Festival.
</P>
<P>
   She said she felt that she lacked a gift for music of narrative
sweep, which she assumed opera demanded.
</P>
<P>
   But Messiaen's contemplative opera was different, an interior
drama that traces the growth of grace in the conflicted saint's
soul. Transported by the work, Saariaho said, she thought to
herself, ``If that is opera, then I can write one.''
</P>
<P>
   She has done so. On Tuesday night at the Felsenreitschule, the
Salzburg Festival presented the world premiere of ``L'Amour de
Loin,'' a haunting and resonant work, with a libretto in French by
the Lebanese-born novelist and essayist Amin Maalouf, who, like
Saariaho, lives in France.
</P>
<P>
   In a way Messiaen's example emboldened the creators to write an
opera that was similarly internalized and reflective. Not much
happens in the story, loosely based on a historical figure, Jaufre
Rudel, a 12th-century troubadour and Prince of Blaye in Aquitaine.
In this operatic telling, Jaufre, sick at heart from his life of
princely excess, develops an idealized love for Clemence, the
beautiful Countess of Tripoli, whom he only hears about from a
pilgrim. The prince rhapsodizes Clemence in song, afraid to meet
her, lest reality spoil his ``love from afar,'' as the opera's
title is translated.
</P>
<P>
   To Saariaho's delight, several of the participants in the
Messiaen production became her collaborators on this project,
including Sellars as director, the soprano Dawn Upshaw and the
conductor Kent Nagano, who led ``St. Francois'' for the 1998
revival at Salzburg. Whatever the reaction to this new opera over
time, ``L'Amour de Loin,'' the most important offering of this
summer's ambitious festival, is an often transfixing and utterly
distinguished work. The ovations were prolonged and deserved.
</P>
<P>
   Though it was not intended as such, ``L'Amour de Loin'' provides
a jolt of sanity amid the political conflicts that of late have
been rattling the world, Austria in particular, over issues of
nationality, immigration, the sanctity of borders and the cultural
gulf between West and East. Maalouf treats these themes in his
effortlessly poetic text, one of the strongest librettos in some
time.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the story is touchingly simple, involving only three
characters. The self-absorbed Jaufre is convinced that the woman of
his fantasies is distant and unobtainable. Perhaps not, says the
pilgrim, who travels often between the western kingdom of Aquitaine
and the eastern citadel of Tripoli. He tells the prince about the
Countess Clemence, who lives in a far-off Arab land, with its
``oceans of sand'' and ``rivers of ash,'' which, of course, just
makes her seem more wondrous to the prince.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Clemence is from Toulouse, which at the time ruled
Tripoli. She spent five happy childhood years in France and longs
to return there. Yet, hearing of the far-off prince's devotion, she
too gets hooked by thoughts of a love that is pure because it is
unknowable.
</P>
<P>
   Idealized love is a well-worn theme, but Maalouf has found a
fresh way to revisit it. In a brilliant stroke, it is Jaufre's
vanity as a troubadour that finally compels him to cross the sea
and face his ideal woman. The pilgrim has sung the prince's love
songs to the countess, but only as best as he could remember them.
The prince is furious. The songs were never intended for Clemence's
ears. But if she is to hear them, then he wants her to hear them
properly. In the end, the long voyage and Jaufre's neurotic passion
undo him. He arrives mortally ill and dies in Clemence's arms.
</P>
<P>
   Maalouf's words invite music, and Saariaho has provided a lushly
beautiful score, structured in five continuous acts lasting two
hours. Best known for her explorations of sound, Saariaho continues
in that vein here with music that combines vivid orchestration, the
subtle use of electronic instruments and imaginative, sometimes
unearthly writing for chorus, which sings from the side of the
stage.
</P>
<P>
   The vocal writing is by turns elegiac and conversational. Her
harmonic language is tonally grounded, with frequent use of
sustained low pedal tones, but not tonal. Bits of dissonance,
piercing overtones and gently jarring electronic sounds spike the
undulant harmonies, but so subtly that the overall aural impression
is of beguiling consonance.
</P>
<P>
   As Sellars noted perceptively during a news conference,
Saariaho's music invites you ``to relax, to enter a beautiful safe
atmosphere, to lower your resistance.'' Yet in doing so the music
sometimes lacks urgency. Stretches of the score pass by, beautiful,
yes, but lacking in profile, just orchestral backdrops for the
singer's reflections.
</P>
<P>
   Every time the score startles us with rhythmic agitation, or
shouts and handclaps from the chorus, the range of Saariaho's gift
becomes clearer. Her evocations of the troubadour songs, with
medieval modal harmony and fragments of elegiac tunes, are
marvelous. But finally, you must accept a score for what it is, not
for what it isn't, and this one does what it set out to do with
great skill and authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   Sellars, a famously controversial director, is at his most
inspired here. His set designer, George Tsypin, has created a
magical medieval world in this coliseumlike theater. The lovers
from afar live in tall, isolated towers of glass with colored
spirals. Jaufre is conveyed up and down in a fantastic elevator;
Clemence climbs a rotating spiral staircase. To represent the sea
that separates them, the entire stage, speckled with light by the
designer James Ingalls, has been filled with shallow water through
which the pilgrim slogs, the prince rides a slow boat and, after
her idealized lover dies, Clemence wallows.
</P>
<P>
   The American baritone Dwayne Croft sings Jaufre with burnished
sound, virile energy and dreamy lyricism. Upshaw brings sublime
vocal beauty and poignant vulnerability to her portrayal. Sadly, a
health problem forced a close colleague of theirs, Lorraine Hunt,
who was to have sung the role of the male pilgrim, to withdraw. In
her place is the excellent Czech mezzo-soprano Dagmar Peckova.
Sellars elicits affecting portrayals from all three, who fearlessly
inhabit their roles. Upshaw ended the performance sopping wet and
emotionally exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   The remarkable Nagano, directing the SWR-Sinfonieorchester of
Baden-Baden, Germany, and Freiburg, Germany, with additional
musicians from Ircam, the contemporary music center in Paris, and
the Arnold Schoenberg Choir, led what seemed a confident, incisive
and shapely first performance of a complex score.
</P>
<P>
   Sellars, who was moved to tears during a news conference in
speaking about the work's creators, said that ``L'Amour de Loin''
was scheduled for productions elsewhere, details of which are to be
announced. He will have to adapt his conception, of course. Not
many opera houses can provide the resources he enjoyed at the
Salzburg Festival. There will be four more performances through
Aug. 30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 1833EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
