<DOCNO> NYT20000816.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3703 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-DECORATOR-COSTS-2TAKE     08-16 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DECORATOR-COSTS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A `GOOD EYE,' CHARGING BY THE GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: DECORATOR-PRICE)  
 By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In her book-lined Greenwich Village apartment, Judith
Young Mallin shuddered, recalling her intimidating brush with a top
interior design team. For Mallin, an expert in Surrealist art, it
was like entering a hall of mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   Divorced, she was undertaking the makeover of a 1910 small-scale
loft for her new, single life. With a budget of $200,000 in mind,
she agreed to a basic design fee of $15,000 and a construction cost
of about $190,000. Unspecified ``additional'' services ``requested
by the owner'' would be billed at up to $150 an hour, but because
her budget was tight, she avoided any extras, even using her own
furniture to avoid the designer markups.
</P>
<P>
   To her dismay, monthly bills for hourly fees started rolling in,
often exceeding $15,000. When the project quickly ballooned to over
half a million dollars, she panicked. Demanding a copy of itemized
charges, she found it loaded with services she assumed were
included in the fee: meetings, site visits, drafting reviews. Among
them was a $150 charge for a discussion the designers had with each
other about where to put a giant television set that Mallin said
she had told them she didn't want. She had even been charged for
meeting with them on how to scale back the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like trying to keep sand from running through my
fingers,'' Mallin recalled. ``I know artsy people. They don't use
decorators, so there was no one for me to call and say, `What do
you do?' And I still feel like I was incredibly naive.''
</P>
<P>
   Mallin is hardly alone in feeling mugged in a decorating
project. Few relationships are more fraught with inequalities and
potential misunderstandings than the one between client and
decorator _ the only mentionable business relationship in which a
perfect stranger is in your bedroom within 20 minutes of meeting
you, as one designer put it.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Bedol, a media industry executive, and his wife, Judith,
have worked with three decorators in 10 years. The first experience
was formative. At one point, the designer suddenly started bringing
in pieces that were out of their price range and ordering things
without their approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we confronted him,'' Bedol said, ``he told us that we
needed to spend more money because he'd lost some clients to the
stock market crash. And if we didn't spend more he couldn't keep us
on.''
</P>
<P>
   The services a decorator renders are often impossible to pin
down. There is no right way or wrong way to decorate a room. Nor
can a price tag be put on taste, or a so-called ``good eye.'' Add
to the psychological imbalance the mind-boggling complexity and
ever-shifting methods by which designers seek reimbursement for
their time-consuming services, which can include weekend shopping
at a tag sale and baby-sitting an electronics geek installing your
home theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're buying from me is time out of my life,'' said
Jarrett Hedborg, the Los Angeles designer whose clients include
Bette Midler, Jack Nicholson and Saudi Arabian royalty. He bills by
the hour, with a commission. ``Listen, me standing around with your
whiny plumber is simply going to cost you.''
</P>
<P>
   In today's flush economy, traditional billing methods are being
tested by a savvy new consumer who wants to know what things cost.
The old-school approach usually involves a designer's fee plus a
markup _ usually 25 percent to 40 percent _ on all the furnishings
that the decorator buys at the to-the-trade price. High-society
clients used to be too polite (or too snobbish) to ask, ``How
much?''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the easy availability of showroom catalogs and glossy
design magazines, and the arrival of eBay and Sotheby's and
Christie's online, ``people have great access to product now'' and
a much better idea what things might cost, said Mayer Rus, editor
in chief of Interior Design. It's a moment of transition, ``a
watershed moment,'' added Hedborg, with designers trying to figure
out how to get reasonable fees for their creative services, which
have expanded far beyond furniture procurement.
</P>
<P>
   If the system lends itself to abuse, it's partly because it is
largely unregulated. The American Society of Interior Designers,
with 20,000 members nationwide and a code of ethics for those who
add the ASID designation after their names, sets standards for its
members' expertise and education in 19 states, and can reprimand or
suspend members who violate the code.
</P>
<P>
   But no one can put a true price on either the designer's
creativity or the client's insecurities. The problem, Hedborg said,
``is that I'm selling my talent for a price based on an object.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to think I'm worth more than a table,'' he said. ``It
feels smarmy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bedol is one of many clients who feel duped by the markup
system. ``I'll never understand a system that gives decorators an
incentive to spend as much money as possible,'' he said. ``When
I've suggested to a few of them that there could be a bonus for
spending less, like they do in commercial work, they just laughed
at me.''
</P>
<P>
   Further complicating the situation, stores like ABC Carpet and
Home, Crate &AMP; Barrel and other retailers have started producing
furniture even a picky decorator might purchase. But what client is
going to be happy paying a designer markup on something picked up
effortlessly in a place like that?
</P>
<P>
   While many designers defend the old system as the most equitable
and respectful of the designer's talent, a growing number of
younger designers are working more on a business school model as
consultants, billing by the hour (built-in protection with
indecisive clients), charging an agreed-upon lump sum or a day rate
and sometimes even using the client's own credit card to pay for
purchases directly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a shopper; people hire me for a concept,'' said
Jennifer Post, one of the new school. ``I bill solely on a
project-fee basis, determined by the scope of the project, the time
involved and the amount of work. I don't charge any percentage on
fabrics, on the construction costs or on the hourly fee. I have my
client's credit cards because they like their free travel points.
There's no deceit, no cheating, no paperwork.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But even straightforward business methods don't always dispel
the mystery and the suspicions that surround decorating, which is
all about projecting an image. ``It's always awkward,'' said
Marjorie Garber, the author of ``Sex and Real Estate: Why We Love
Houses'' (Pantheon), a new book on the social pathologies
intricately linked to the home. ``These strangers are supposed to
become experts in your taste _ of which you're none too sure
yourself. And there's always the worry that if it's not expensive,
then you're not getting your money's worth. The money is what makes
it glamorous.''
</P>
<P>
   But glamour can cost. In thrall to a famous New York designer,
one couple on the upper East Side agreed to buy an unusual antique
desk with leather drawers for $90,000, based on photographs the
designer showed them. When the ``antique'' arrived at their house,
a substantial part had been newly remade. It was appraised
subsequently for no more than $10,000. They had a hard time
returning it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We suspected that the designer and the dealer were very cozy
and that there were kickbacks to the advantage of both,'' the wife
said. Though they questioned the designer's ethics, they loved his
aesthetic and would hire him again _ which is why they refused to
give their names. ``If the piece works and you love the look ...''
the woman tried to explain. She blames herself for not ``focusing
more'' on particulars.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the American Society of Interior Designers,
Jerry R. Harke, strongly urges clients to be more skeptical:
``Whenever you're buying an expensive antique, be sure to get an
independent appraisal.''
</P>
<P>
   John Landrum Bryant, who sells lighting fixtures, bathroom
hardware and furniture to designers and the public by appointment,
has seen both sides in action. ``The decorator's role,'' he said,
``is to infantilize the client to the point where the client feels
it's impossible to make any decision about anything, be it what
furniture to buy, what flowers to put on the table, even what
towels to use.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example, Bryant cited his own experiences accompanying his
interior designer on shopping trips to Paris. ``They always stay in
the fancier hotel _ the Ritz, or Costes is very popular _ while you
stay somewhere else much more modest,'' he said. ``If you're making
a commission on a seven-figure purchase, you can afford to pay for
the Ritz, too.'' Besides, he added, ``they have to troll for new
clients.''
</P>
<P>
   High-rolling decorators raise fewer eyebrows than the
inscrutable relationship between designers and their sources for
custom-made furnishings. Custom design is a highly inexact art,
with prices fluctuating depending upon many factors, including the
availability of fabric and workers, and the due date. Nearly all of
the more than a dozen designers interviewed for this article said
they had at some point been approached by suppliers and
manufacturers more than willing to pad their bills for the
decorator. Post, who has been in business for eight years, said she
was still surprised at how often suppliers whisper: ``What do you
want me to put on this bill?''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I tell them my billing is totally open to my clients,''
she said, ``they say, `You're so stupid!'''
</P>
<P>
   An architect who requested anonymity is now building a house
that is being furnished by an interior designer. ``I know the
interior designer is ripping off the client and the supplier is in
on it,'' he said. The architect has not said anything to the
client. ``They do good work,'' he said. He said that, once before,
he notified another supplier about a $15,000 error on a bill only
to have the supplier ask, implying a kickback offer, ``Whose name
should go on the check?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been tempted to tell the client,'' the architect said.
``But the suppliers would stop working with me because I was a
tattletale. It's really rampant, a never-ending spiral.''
</P>
<P>
   One furniture maker, who started out in the retail business and
now has a trade-only clientele, described a ruse in which he said
he had refused to participate. Twice, decorators have requested
that he send them his bill showing a ``retail'' price, which the
decorator would pay and then pass along to the client, adding his
normal markup. Then the decorator would then go back to the maker
and ask to be reimbursed for his usual discount _ thus being paid
twice.
</P>
<P>
   Vendors like that furniture maker point out that there is a lot
of room for adjustment on the bill's journey from supplier to
client. This can lead to the case of the $1,000 throw pillow.
</P>
<P>
   Keller Henderson of Keller Henderson Interiors in New York tried
to offer some perspective on the sometimes hair-raising prices
decorators charge, particularly to their Clients From Hell. ``Let's
say a client is really wringing you out,'' he said. ``You're
spending a lot of time shopping for things they don't like, and
you're losing your shirt. Somehow, you've got to recoup your
expenses.'' Suddenly a $350 pillow triples in price when it lands,
like a karate chop, on the client's silk-and-linen threaded sofa.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson said that another alternative, when clients become
difficult, is ``to drop them with the paint still wet on the
wall.''
</P>
<P>
   The absence of any visible price tags in showrooms tends to add
to the lay person's sense of being left in the dark. Gregory
Marshall, sales director at J. Robert Scott, a furniture showroom
chain, said, ``We don't tag furniture because it would scare the
customers away.'' He noted that friends, neighbors and relatives of
a designer's client will frequently call to check on prices, but
``we don't divulge any prices to anyone but the designer.''
</P>
<P>
   So is decorator pricing always a shell game? Clearly not. More
and more designers are spelling out their fees in lengthy
contracts. Few complaints get to court, despite the well-publicized
legal action in which Philadelphia clients accused the New York
design team of Stephen Sills and James Huniford of inflating
charges for furniture and fixtures. (Huniford said yesterday that
``the issues that remain unresolved are in private arbitration.'')
</P>
<P>
   The American Society of Interior Designers points out that in
the past three years, only 59 complaints have been lodged against
their 20,000 members. (Sills and Huniford are not members of the
society.) Only six complaints have resulted in disciplinary action.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very human business,'' said Karen Fisher, president of
Design Previews, which matches clients with decorators. Mike
Strohl, who represents more than 30 designers in the New York area,
said he often heard about clients who resort to the kind of
browbeating that could drive anyone to the brink: trying to buy
from vendors directly to avoid paying markups, demanding to see
endless options on every bathroom fixture and refusing to pay their
bills after custom work has been fully installed.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bohn, a New York designer, said, only half in jest: ``I
reduce my prices for people who don't make me crazy. If I don't
have to show you 50 of one thing, you get a discount.''
</P>
<P>
   While everyone thinks that his designer is living it up at the
Ritz, the designer is more likely to be beating the pavement like a
well-dressed Willy Loman. ``You look for hours and hours trying to
find the right thing, or maybe you spend months looking for a
certain fabric that only costs you $10,'' Diana Vinoly said. ``But
if you don't actually buy something, they really don't expect you
to bill them for that time. In the end, they are all always
shocked.''
</P>
<P>
   Vinoly entered the business through the tried-and-true method of
designing for friends, and has yet to turn it all into a profitable
business. But she has remained on good terms with her clients, once
the dust settled and the Japanese bamboo shades were hung. Glitches
that seemed unsurmountable melt into thin air with the first sigh
of awed admiration from a visitor, or the first quiet night at home
sprawled on the rolled-back couch.
</P>
<P>
   If Tolstoy had ever had his dacha ``done,'' he might have put it
this way: Happy clients are all alike. The unhappy ones you're
going to hear from.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
