<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3706 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-JEWS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      08-16 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEWS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JEW VS. JEW': SO MUCH RUMBLING THAT HE FEARS FOR THE FOUNDATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes at end of review; Jonathan Rosen is the
author of the novel ``Eve's Apple.'' His next book, ``The Talmud
and the Internet: A Journey Between Worlds'' will be published next
month by Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux.) By JONATHAN ROSEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I have nothing in common with the Jews,'' Franz Kafka wrote
crankily in his diary. ``Most days I don't even have anything in
common with myself.'' Kafka's complaint is funny in part because it
is so familiarly Jewish _ Moses, who tried to talk God out of
choosing him as a prophet, might have said as much. But for Samuel
G. Freedman, the fact that Jews don't get along is no laughing
matter. Invoking dire images of the fall of the Second Temple _ for
which Jewish tradition blames religious disunity _ Freedman
believes that American Jews have nothing less than a civil war on
their hands.
</P>
<P>
   To support this thesis, Freedman _ a former reporter for The New
York Times and the author of several books, including a compelling
portrait of a black church in Brooklyn _ focuses on some recent
episodes of American Jewish strife. These include the collapse of a
conversion panel in Denver made up of Orthodox, Conservative and
Reform rabbis; the lawsuit of five Orthodox students who wished to
avoid co-ed housing at Yale; a quarrel at a California synagogue
over liturgical emendation; and a zoning battle in a Ohio suburb
that pitted Jews of various affiliations against Orthodox
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Freedman, who is also a professor of journalism, builds his
portraits with great care. He has clearly done a vast amount of
reporting and research and has rooted his study in the history of
modern America. He strengthens his accounts of individuals with an
understanding of the communities they live in. He is good at
tracing the way a suburb grows from a few houses to a full-fledged
community and how the tenuous balance of ethnic fellowship is
maintained _ and disturbed. He evokes the simultaneous loss and
transfiguration that characterizes the immigrant journey into
American success.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the eruption of discord that Freedman sees as
representative of American Judaism, and his chapters are bent
around this thesis. This can give his examples a somewhat forced
quality. The lawsuit conducted by the ``Yale Five'' was, after all,
aimed at Yale University; the fact that the dean of students and
the president of the university were Jewish, something Freedman
makes much of, seems oddly irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   A battle at a Los Angeles synagogue over inclusion of the
matriarchs alongside the names of the patriarchs in the Amida, the
centerpiece of synagogue liturgy _ though it stirred the passions
of the congregation _ hardly seems a schismatic matter. One need
only think of the fate of Maimonides, the great medieval Jewish
philosopher, whose compilation of Jewish law, the Mishneh Torah,
was burnt as heretical when it first appeared, to realize how mild
much American Jewish discord is.
</P>
<P>
   Far more dramatic is the chapter that deals with the planting of
a bomb in a Florida synagogue to protest the appearance of Shimon
Peres and the Oslo accords he participated in. The act is presented
as an emblematic episode, yet the Orthodox Jew who hid the bomb
seems to have had a history of emotional disturbance, the rabbi of
the synagogue he attended was the one who tipped off the
authorities, and the bomber himself fully expected the bomb would
be found. (He called the police).
</P>
<P>
   The event, though it undoubtedly resonates more grimly after the
assassination of Yitzhak Rabin, has a completely different
character from that calamity, despite Freedman's implication that
Israeli religious discord is finding an echo in the United States.
Indeed the assassination of Rabin may say more about how Israel has
become like the United States than a bomb in a Florida synagogue
shows how the country is becoming like Israel. In Israel, where
Orthodox Jews have a share of political power and
government-sanctioned authority, the notion of religious civil war
is far more relevant. The rise of the Orthodox right wing in the
United States, which Freedman intelligently chronicles, may say as
much about American fundamentalist culture as it does about
Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is to suggest that there aren't real issues
dividing American Jews. Freedman, an excellent journalist, is
surely on the trail of a good story. But he has defined that story,
and in some sense religious life itself, so narrowly that American
Jews are all drafted by his book into conflicts that many may feel
touch only peripherally on their religious lives.
</P>
<P>
   This is especially apparent in several of his conclusions. He
speaks of the triumph of the ``Orthodox model,'' by which he means
the notion that ``religion defines Jewish identity.'' This may come
as a shock to a large number of Conservative, Reform and
Reconstructionist Jews, not to mention unaffiliated Jews with deep
religious identities. It is one thing to claim that secular Judaism
has fizzled as a movement. It is another to confuse religious life
with Orthodoxy. This is a particularly ironic conclusion given
Freedman's own understanding that millions of Jews who poured into
this country as immigrants in the early part of this century and
promptly vanished into assimilated culture were, by and large, the
products of Orthodox families. Was that the failure of the Orthodox
model?
</P>
<P>
   The boundaries of Judaism seem far more fluid than Freedman
would have us believe, even today. Freedman is no doubt right that
Israel once rallied American Jews in a way it now fails to, but it
is also true that Zionism itself has been, since the beginning of
the 20th century, a deeply divisive issue for Jews. But perhaps all
this is a way of quarreling with the subtitle of this book, which
implies a monolithic community capable of a single soul. American
Judaism may well have as many souls as it has bodies, a fact that
no doubt argues for the health of the religion.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Freedman provides a thought-provoking and timely
tour of Jewish-American religious ferment. Whether the conflicts he
chronicles are a throwback to earlier struggles, an omen of a
coming crisis, or the necessary accompaniment of the development of
a living faith is, of course, a matter of opinion.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   ``JEW VS. JEW: The Struggle for the Soul of American Jewry''
</P>
<P>
   By Samuel G. Freedman
</P>
<P>
   397 pages. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $26.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
