<SLUG> BC-CHAPTER-ANDVERSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF RELIGIOUS BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOOK REVIEW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Eschatology in Bible &AMP; Theology'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Kent E. Brower and Mark W. Elliott &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (InterVarsity Press, $24.99) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is not your preacher's end-times book. Well, maybe it is.
But it's definitely not ``The Millennium for Dummies.''
</P>
<P>
   Springing, in large part, from a July 1997 conference of the
Tyndale Fellowship in England, ``Eschatology in Bible &AMP; Theology''
presents material on topics including Revelation, Ezekiel, Paul's
thought, and writings on modern theology and physics. Commenting on
hell is E. Earle Ellis of Southwestern Baptist Theological Seminary
in Fort Worth. Particularly interesting are Alan Garrow's
dissection of Revelation and Crispin H.T. Fletcher-Louis' thoughts
on the Jerusalem temple.
</P>
<P>
   Readers may raise an eyebrow at stands taken by some of the
authors. ``Eschatology in Bible &AMP; Theology'' is definitely aimed at
advanced students and their instructors, with untransliterated
Hebrew and Greek terms cropping up regularly. Bring your lexicons,
and prepare to think. &QL; 
_ Reviewed by Alan Cochrum &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Offerings _ A Worship Album'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Third Day &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Essential Records &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Third Day's successful 1999 album, ``Time,'' earned a Grammy
nomination and a Dove award for rock album of the year and produced
four No. 1 singles.
</P>
<P>
   The safe thing would have been to capitalize on that momentum by
going back into the studio and recording another rock CD. Instead,
Third Day took a bold step and recorded a worship album.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe it wasn't that risky. After all, groups like
Delirious and the ``Passion'' series have made praise and worship
music popular. And it's a genre in which Third Day is accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a full album of worship songs _ five new cuts and six
live versions of previous Third Day songs _ is a departure, so much
so that lead singer Mac Powell almost apologizes on one of the live
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a Third Day concert, he tells the crowd, they've come
to a church service, one that features the popular Third Day sound
_ Powell's gritty vocals over a basic guitar-and-drums rock _ along
with lyrics that glorify God. The result is an album that should
appeal to hard-core fans and new listeners. &QL; 
_ Reviewed by Simon Gonzalez &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 1837EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000816.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3708 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx14;  BC-LONDON-THEATER-2TAKES     08-16 1327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONDON-THEATER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: BRITISH PLAYS TRADE ON THE UNEXPECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   By BEN BRANTLEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ It really isn't spoiling anything to reveal the final
lines of the two most recent plays by Alan Ayckbourn. They are, as
a matter of fact, exactly the same, though spoken by different
actors. And they are not concluding words that seem destined for
immortality: ``Ah, well. That's life, I suppose.''
</P>
<P>
   Before you start fretting that the prolific Ayckbourn has at
last depleted his wit, remember that in theater, as in life,
context is everything. It's not just what's said that's important,
but also when, where and how.
</P>
<P>
   When and where, in particular, have rarely counted for as much
as they do in Ayckbourn's ``House'' and ``Garden,'' the joyful,
mournful and intricately interrelated comedies directed by their
author at the Royal National Theater. Ayckbourn wrote the plays
concurrently in celebration of his 60th birthday, and they are
being performed simultaneously _ at the same time by the same
performers, who run between two different stages _ in what turns
into an invigorating celebration of the possibilities of theater.
</P>
<P>
   Ayckbourn is a comic chronicler of suburban discontent whose
technique is often as exotic as his subject matter is familiar.
Here he stretches his imagination and his actors' stamina to render
a single disastrous day as observed both within a country manor and
in the garden just outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``House'' and ``Garden'' are eminently enjoyable as individual
pieces. To see them in succession, however (I did both in one day,
and the sequence is immaterial), is a mind-flexing delight. Each
play deeply enriches the other while teasingly reminding us that
any view presented by a work of art is only partial. By the second
time you reach that concluding shrug of a comment _ ``That's life,
I suppose'' _ you may find that you have tears in your eyes because
you know so much more than when you first heard it, spoken by
somebody else.
</P>
<P>
   Who says the theater has reached a dead end? The current London
season is filled with confirmations of how protean the discipline
remains, as variable and potentially surprising as human beings
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Local observers may lament the Americanization of the London
stage, with its adaptations of Hollywood movies and reliance on
brand-name celebrities. But if you look past pandering hits like
``The Graduate,'' you'll discover an abiding, very British penchant
for playing with plays, a delight in demonstrating what theater can
do that other forms cannot.
</P>
<P>
   The sensibility is evident in everything from the blistering
revival of Peter Nichols' ``Passion Play,'' a 1981 study of
infidelity in which husband and wife are each played by two actors,
to the Globe Theater's production of ``Hamlet,'' in which the
soliloquies of the title character, played by Mark Rylance,
sometimes turn into boisterous exchanges with the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Just what gives a show an audacious freshness can range from the
use of actors to the choice of theater. The season's unexpected
sleeper, and the one London production already assured of a
Broadway transfer, is a hymn to actorly inventiveness: Marie Jones'
``Stones in His Pockets,'' in which two performers embody a baker's
dozen of characters to tell the story of an Irish village invaded
by a Hollywood production company.
</P>
<P>
   A 200-year-old comedy, Fanny Burney's ``Busy Day,'' finally
makes its West End debut, with a smooth, canny interpretation that
finds immediate accessibility through judicious exaggeration. And
the summer's classiest glamour tickets have been the Almeida
Theater's rotating productions of ``Richard II'' and
``Coriolanus,'' directed by Jonathan Kent and scheduled for a run
at the Brooklyn Academy of Music this fall.
</P>
<P>
   That Ralph Fiennes plays both heroes obviously has much to do
with their success. But it's important not to underestimate the
impact of the setting: the cavernous, derelict Gainsborough movie
studios in Islington, a mightily resonant backdrop for works
dealing with the fragility of empire, smashingly exploited by Kent
and his designer, Paul Brown.
</P>
<P>
   All of these shows benefit from what might be described as
stunts or gimmicks. Well, of course. Gimmicks, as the singing
strippers in the musical ``Gypsy'' so convincingly point out, are
the essence of show business.
</P>
<P>
   There is a difference, however, between gimmicks that exist
merely to capture crowds (like having a middle-aged movie star take
off all her clothes) and those provided by Ayckbourn's current
comedies, where what at first seems like just a clever gambit
actually deepens your response to the productions.
</P>
<P>
   I'll confess that when I first saw Nichols' ``Passion Play,'' in
a London production 15 years ago, I wasn't entirely convinced of
the necessity of giving onstage alter egos to the main characters.
Sure, there's duplicity involved in any marriage, but isn't part of
an actor's job to suggest layers of conflict?
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, this latest ``Passion Play,'' another product of
the invaluable Donmar Warehouse, made me feel that I had missed the
point the first time. Under Michael Grandage's gimlet-eyed
direction, this minimalist production brings out the shattering
core of Nichols' thesis: that adultery, as the straying husband in
the play suggests in a semantic meditation, adulterates,
fragmenting lives and polluting tranquillity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passion Play'' isn't just a matter of people saying one thing
while thinking another. Nichols' manipulation of his divided
characters is far more subtle, ultimately daring to suggest that
one ``self''is no more viable than another and that the inability
to reconcile the two is genuinely tragic.
</P>
<P>
   This revelation grows in painful increments through the
carefully graded performances of James Laurenson, Nicky Henson,
Cherie Lunghi and Cheryl Campbell _ as the torn spouses _ and of
Nicola Walker as the feckless young woman who comes between them.
The crucifix patterns in Christopher Oram's stripped-down set and
in Grandage's staging subliminally emphasize the religious agony of
the title.
</P>
<P>
   The play has the hubris to offer Mozart's Requiem as a comment
on an extramarital fling. But by the evening's end, the choice
seems entirely justified, echoing D.H. Lawrence's contention that
the cross is a symbol of how we are divided within ourselves. Like
the National's production of a very different look at the
corrupting effects of deception, Arthur Miller's ``All My Sons,''
this ``Passion Play'' leaves you flattened. And yet you know you
wouldn't have missed it for anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stones in His Pockets'' is, by comparison, a frolic. Jones'
account of an American movie crew wreaking havoc in a County Kerry
hamlet examines distorting cultural stereotypes in ways that tend
to be stereotyped themselves, and it could definitely profit from
editing.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly there's nothing new in the shallowness of the
Hollywood visitors who condescendingly rule over the villagers who
have signed on as extras. Nor is the somber history of a local
suicide comfortably integrated into the evening's dominant
balminess.
</P>
<P>
   Still, you're unlikely to stop smiling through most of the show
for the simple reason that everyone, from a desperate drug addict
to an excruciatingly earnest young movie goddess, is played by two
remarkably nimble actors, Conleth Hill and Sean Campion. Ian
McElhinney's direction capitalizes splendidly on the pleasure of
watching these metamorphoses, especially when it concentrates on
the blurred reality that sets in when Irish villagers play
Hollywood's idea of Irish villagers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at her look at us lookin' dispossessed,'' explains one
extra to another, defining their job description for that day. Just
how Campion and Hill register such levels of being, in ways that
happily include a brutal ``Riverdance''-style sequence, is a giddy
treat.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Globe Theater, which seeks to conjure the experience of
watching plays in the days of Shakespeare, has drawn criticism for
emphasizing crowd-pleasing accessibility over nuance. Yet it's this
populist dimension that makes the Globe such fun.
</P>
<P>
   Its current ``Hamlet,'' directed by Giles Block, may not have
the chic interpretive gloss of the Almeida's ``Coriolanus.'' It's a
doggedly conventional rendering with generally pedestrian
supporting performances. Yet it delivers its story with absorbing,
fast-paced clarity. And in Mark Rylance, who is also the company's
artistic director, it has a compelling Hamlet who wears both
royalty and ambivalence as if they were a jester's motley.
Rylance's prince, in feigning madness, is clearly caught up in the
clownish, theatrical pleasures of the role; he is also repeatedly
lanced with pain as he remembers the reality beneath the ruse.
</P>
<P>
   In emphasizing the showman in Hamlet, Rylance invites the
audience to share in the character's monologues. When this Hamlet
asks, ``Am I a coward?,'' it isn't just rhetorical. The groundlings
standing at the edge of the stage are eager to answer him. Watching
Rylance integrate such responses into his performance provides a
thrilling suggestion of the theater of 400 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The house, alas, appeared to be half empty the Friday I saw ``A
Busy Day,'' the first West End production of the Regency comedy by
the novelist Fanny Burney, best known today for her diaries and
letters. This neglect by audiences is a shame and a surprise. As a
literary curiosity, this story of romance and class conflict in a
socially unsettled London is fascinating, anticipating many of the
thematic threads more gently plied by Jane Austen.
</P>
<P>
   More crucially, the play, under Jonathan Church's direction,
emerges as a fiendishly vivid parade of aristocrats and parvenus.
The actors gleefully demonstrate that caricature can be a fine art,
especially Ben Moor as a half-witted peacock of a lord and
Stephanie Beacham (of ``Dynasty'' fame) as a gargoylish slave to
snobbery.
</P>
<P>
   If the course of love is bumpy in Regency London, it seems to be
no smoother in the contemporary English suburbs of ``House'' and
``Garden,'' where the chances of happy unions are devastatingly
remote.
</P>
<P>
   These complementary works, which follow the events both indoors
and out surrounding a misbegotten village fete, are notably
different in tone. ``House'' is the more verbal and socially barbed
play, as befits its interior setting, promisingly accented with
French windows. The alfresco ``Garden'' has an appropriately
bacchanalian flavor, with a firmer emphasis on physical comedy.
</P>
<P>
   As the plays anatomize three different souring marriages (as
well as several other varieties of sexual relationships), a gentle
melancholy rises above the comic fray, like the melodic solo in a
flute concerto. With an ideally balanced ensemble led by David Haig
and Jane Asher as the miserably married lord and lady of the manor,
``House'' and ``Garden'' find an illuminating common ground in
their respective forms of farce.
</P>
<P>
   The denizens of ``House'' may be the more articulate lot, given
to tidy metaphors that describe their plight. In ``Garden,'' the
same characters are more likely to express themselves by wrestling
or dancing or hiding in bushes. But in either play there's no
avoiding Ayckbourn's insistence that communication between people
is a pretty futile business.
</P>
<P>
   This is a play, after all, in which the most passionate and
satisfactory relationship is between an Englishman and a
Frenchwoman who can't speak each other's languages. Ayckbourn's
vivaciously orchestrated scenes of slapstick and volleys of
dialogue curiously add up to an existential sadness.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is infinite curiosity and affection in his view of
life's frustrations, and an infectiousness in the zest with which
he shapes that perspective into not one, but two, works of theater.
A warm, vital amusement, as well as a resigned fatalism, shine
through that simple curtain line: ``Ah, well. That's life, I
suppose.'' Isn't it a curse? And isn't it fun? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
