<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3710 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-PARTY17-COX     08-16 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-PARTY17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CRAZINESS AS USUAL AT CONVENTION PARTIES
 &HT;    By JILL VEJNOSKA
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's the party of inclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pearls for the girls! Pearls for the girls!'' Louisiana Sen.
John Breaux whoops as he swoops down on a slightly startled-looking
pair of women who suddenly find their elegant evening wear draped
in colorful Mardi Gras beads.
</P>
<P>
   The party that believes no one should go hungry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gumbo, it's VERY good for you,'' a chef says as he
practically pushes a ladle into the hands of a business-suited man
who has already loaded down his plate with crawfish and
manhole-sized onion rings at the ``Great Gumbo and Jammin'
Jambalaya'' food island.
</P>
<P>
   The party of universal health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Catch 'em, because it hurts if they hit you in the head,'' Ed
Lombard, clerk of the criminal court in New Orleans, tells the
crowd reaching for beads thrown off a parade float on a Paramount
Studios lot here.
</P>
<P>
   It's ``Mardi Gras Goes Hollywood,'' Breaux's contribution to the
swirling party circuit surrounding the Democratic National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's event was as lavish as the three parade floats brought
here from New Orleans, and as outrageously fun as the Day-Glo
orange satin outfit in which Breaux greets his hundreds of guests.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it may be the only time during convention week when a
politician actually tries to be photographed looking goofy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are hundreds of these of me,'' Breaux says, stopping
prancing around with a fringed yellow umbrella long enough to pose
for a picture with an arriving party-goer. ``After about a hundred
of them, it doesn't hurt you in Louisiana. It helps!''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Tuesday's party was not your typical event in a
week devoted to the deadly serious business of charting a major
political party's future and nominating the possible next leader of
the most powerful nation on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   But in some ways it's awfully typical: corporate America
throwing parties for the the politically connected.
</P>
<P>
   ``This goes on a lot,'' said Tony Anderson, standing on a movie
set street of fake brownstones and _ for this night only _ an
``Acme Oyster Bar,'' a ``Kickin' Cajun Grill'' and a ``Pat
O'Brien's Hurricanes'' stand. ``I went to a great party at Spago on
Sunday night. There were about 2,000 people there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spago party, which honored Rep. Dick Gephardt, the
Missourian who could become speaker should the Democrats capture
the House in November, was sponsored by major corporations such as
AT&AMP;T, BellSouth, Disney, Andersen Consulting and (Tony Anderson's
employer) Ernst &AMP; Young.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four corporations footed the bill for Breaux's party,
including AT&AMP;T, Brown &AMP; Williamson, Lockheed Martin, Merck and
Texaco.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these companies have business before the Senate Finance
and Commerce committees, of which Breaux is a member.
</P>
<P>
   But business, says Breaux, is not why he wanted to have this
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``In New Orleans, we have Mardi Gras to celebrate before
starting 40 days of Lent,'' said Breaux. ``Tonight, we're
celebrating before starting 40 days of campaigning.''
</P>
<P>
   While one might quibble with his math (some 80 days actually
remain until Election Day), there's no disputing that Breaux's a
heckuva lot of fun.
</P>
<P>
   That much was obvious even before he finally stopped dancing
onstage with Rockin' Dopsie and the Zydeco Twisters and went off to
change into his outfit for the parade of what he'd earlier
described as his ``Hollywood Krewe''.
</P>
<P>
   Just past 9 p.m., Breaux appeared high atop a float, wearing a
white satin outfit with orange and green plumes that made him look
like Liberace crossed with Elvis.
</P>
<P>
   At most of the other parties, it was Hollywood celebrities
rather than the Washington politicos who supplied the glamour.
</P>
<P>
   The list goes on and on _ from Brad Pitt, who sat next to
Hillary Rodham Clinton at a Saturday fund-raising dinner for her
New York Senate campaign that also featured Cher singing and John
Travolta buddying around with the president, to ``West Wing'' stars
Martin Sheen and Rob Lowe partying Sunday on their fake Oval Office
set with Vermont Sen. Patrick Leahy, Health and Human Services
Secretary Donna Shalala and First Daughter Chelsea Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's Bloomberg News-sponsored party at Spago (again) saw New
York's congressional delegation tucking in with Tom Brokaw,
Christie Brinkley and some of the ``West Wing'' cast (again). And
while Breaux's party was going on Tuesday, so was California
congresswoman Loretta Sanchez's controversial fund-raiser for
Hispanic Unity USA. The guest list for that party, which Sanchez
relocated from the politically incorrect Playboy Mansion, included
Shalala, former Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros and actor Bill
Maher.
</P>
<P>
   At Breaux's party Tuesday, current ``Angel'' and former ``Buffy
the Vampire Slayer'' star David Boreanez provided a near-perfect
commentary on the merging worlds of Washington and Hollywood this
week. Just inside the Paramount front gate, a check-in table bore
the sign ``Members of Congress and Administration.'' When someone
jokingly asked if he was a congressman, Boreanez, who was waiting
to be driven into the party on a golf cart, grinned slyly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe someday,'' he said as he was whisked off. ``Maybe
someday very soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Also at Breaux's party, held on the set where parts of ``Ally
McBeal,'' ``Frasier,'' and ``NYPD Blue'' are filmed, were former
Miss USA Ali Landry, football great-turned-broadcaster Terry
Bradshaw, a handful of congressmen, some lobbyists, Gore for
President campaign chairman William Daley, and the man who very
nearly became Gore's running mate, North Carolina Sen. John
Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most intriguing celebrity guest of all was a man
almost no one knew was there. Tipper Gore's father, Jack Aitcheson,
sat quietly at a table with his wife, Margaret, eating authentic
Louisiana food and drinking in the sounds of Big Bad Voodoo Daddy
performing live.
</P>
<P>
   Having arrived in L.A. the previous day following a three-day,
cross-country Amtrak ride from their home in Alexandria, Va., the
Aitchesons had already been sightseeing in Malibu and Beverly
Hills. Earlier Tuesday, they'd spent some time in a box above the
convention floor with several of the Gores' daughters.
</P>
<P>
   His feeling when Al Gore finally is nominated Thursday night?
</P>
<P>
   ``Awesome,'' said Jack Aitcheson, the former owner of a small
plumbing supply business. ``Absolutely awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? Somebody here may even decide to throw a party.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Vejnoska's e-mail address is jvejnoska(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
