<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3723 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-DEMENTED-REVIEW-     08-16 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DEMENTED-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMENTED FOREVER, OR JUST DULL?
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
The underground movie-making ``cinema terrorists'' of ``Cecil B.
DeMented'' have a chant to work themselves into a film-making
frenzy.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Demented forever,'' they shout in honor of their cult leader,
director Cecil B. DeMented.
</P>
<P>
   By all indications that's what director John Waters would like
to have written on his tombstone when he passes on to some grungy,
sticky-floored cinema in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Waters made his early reputation with sleazy gross-out stunts
and characters, back when it was the only way his films could get
attention. The movies were indeed demented, at least to the ruling
establishments of the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Having created his own personal genre, the John Waters film, he
has clung to it tenaciously, while adapting to success.
</P>
<P>
   It's not been easy. Whatever humor value his movies had _ and
actually, it was very little _ it was because what Waters was
showing was forbidden and utterly tasteless.
</P>
<P>
   What has changed since Waters did ``Pink Flamingos,'' ``Female
Trouble'' and ``Multiple Maniacs'' is that gross-out is now common
in movies _ granted, not to the extreme Waters sometime took it _
and Waters is forced, by economics, to work within the system. He
could still be making true underground movies like the hero
director of ``Cecil B. DeMented.'' But then he would not be touring
around doing interviews in huge suites in Four Seasons hotels.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Cecil B. DeMented,'' the director of the same name (Stephen
Dorff) is not merely outrageous but militant. He and his band of
filmmakers are so underground and anti-establishment they even hate
independent film. They despise everything Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   They kidnap fading A-list actress Honey Whitlock (Melanie
Griffith in an odd career choice) to force her to star in their new
movie.
</P>
<P>
   Waters' fans know that former kidnap victim Patty Hearst often
appears in Waters' movies (in this one, she plays the mother of one
of the young terrorists who kidnaps Honey). The kidnapping of Honey
parallels some of Hearst's own experience.
</P>
<P>
   Forced to do without imported bottled water and other luxuries,
Honey whines, begs, threatens and schemes to get free. Failing
that, she becomes _ or at least pretends to become, it's rather
vague _ a disciple of DeMented.
</P>
<P>
   Together they crash into theaters, Hollywood parties and
shopping malls to do guerilla filmmaking in which innocent
passers-by become extras and, if they get in the way, gunned-down
victims.
</P>
<P>
   All this is carried out with forced silliness and countless
in-jokes about Hollywood (such as the obscure names of filmmakers
that DeMented's crew tattoo on their arms).
</P>
<P>
   Even more than in his other recent efforts such as ``Hair
Spray,'' ``Cry-Baby,'' ``Serial Mom'' and ``Pecker,'' this movie is
all stunted outrageousness and very little actual humor. The movies
are no longer offensive, but they are still just not funny.
``DeMented'' is actually difficult to sit through because it's
dull.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, Waters' movies are not meant to be enjoyed by sober
critics in afternoon screenings, but at midnight shows where a
large, rowdy audience is mostly under the influence of something.
</P>
<P>
   Actors should be admired for taking chances, and Griffith at
least jumps into the role with both feet. What she lands in is
another matter. The film is so meandering that her performance is
wasted. Dorff, as DeMented, just seems to be ranting.
</P>
<P>
   The film's guest cast includes Waters regulars Mink Stole, Ricki
Lake and Hearst. &QL; 
``Cecil B. DeMented'' &QL; 
Starring: Melanie Griffith, Stephen Dorff &QL; 
Director/screenwriter: John Waters &QL; 
Rating: R, for strong crude sexual content, violence, language and
drug use. &QL; 
Running time: 88 minutes &QL; 
Grade: D+ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
