<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3725 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-TEXAS17-COX     08-16 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-TEXAS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By KEN HERMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Former San Antonio Mayor Henry Cisneros, billing
himself as a part-time campaigner eager to help longtime friend Al
Gore, Wednesday urged Texas delegates to the Democratic National
Convention to share the ``truth'' about GOP presidential nominee
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``No other Democrats in American can perform this service for
America,'' Cisneros told the Texans.
</P>
<P>
   After his speech, Cisneros, a former Clinton administration
housing secretary who moved back to Texas last week, said he's not
fully up to speed on what the truth about Bush is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been in Texas for the last number of years, so I
have not been up close and personal,'' he said. ``But I do know
that it is not correct to paper over some of the deficiencies that
exist in our state related to uninsured children and the number of
children in poverty and issues of inadequacies in our schools and
so forth.''
</P>
<P>
   The breakfast speech marked a return to politics for Cisneros,
who spent the last three years in Los Angeles as president of
Univision, the nation's largest Spanish-language television
network. He is now involved with a San Antonio-based company aimed
at developing inner-city housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I've been out of politics for a little bit and I'm
out of practice,'' he told the Texas delegates, who greeted him
with a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros' political star declined precipitously after his
romantic ties to former aide Linda Jones were disclosed in 1988.
Last year, he pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor federal charge
stemming from inaccurate statements he had made to the FBI about
payments he had made to Jones. Cisneros paid a $10,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   In his Wednesday speech, Cisneros was far easier on Bush _
opting instead to praise Gore _ than other speakers at the
delegation breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``George W. Bush has never said the word AIDS or HIV publicly,''
said state Rep. Glen Maxey of Austin. ``Do we want him in the White
House?''
</P>
<P>
   ``This man is a tool of the special interests,'' Rep. Eddie
Bernice Johnson of Dallas said at a delegation breakfast sponsored
by several corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, for the most part, stayed positive, speaking glowingly
of Gore as an ``intelligent, tough-minded man'' who is
exceptionally qualified for the top spot.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros urged Texas Democrats _ who now hold no statewide
offices _ to keep their chins up through what could be a difficult
election year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no illusions as a Texan about how difficult November is
going to be in Texas. I have no illusions about that and the
chances are, speaking honestly right here between us, that we're
not going to carry Texas in the presidential election of the year
2000,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we are going to win a bunch of congressional seats in
Texas. ... The Democratic Party of Texas is alive and well at the
grass roots, and it is going to be back in this election and in
elections to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros said ``missed opportunities'' in Texas will become
clear ``as soon as this (Bush) juggernaut is over.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have too many people living in poor housing in
Texas,'' he said. ``We still have too many people living without
good jobs in Texas. We still have too many children who are
uninsured in Texas. We still have too many seniors who don't have
the medical care they need in Texas. We still have too many
communities in Texas that have been left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   After the speech, Cisneros continued to deny that his return to
Texas is the first step toward rekindling a political career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no plans to run for office, no ambition,'' he said. ``I
swear to you I want to get on the ground in San Antonio and get to
work.''
</P>
<P>
   But he declined to say never.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never is a long time,'' he noted. ``Ten years from now, I'll
be a little old, but who knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros said he would back Laredo oilman Tony Sanchez if he
decides to run for governor in 2002. Sanchez, a Democrat, has been
a high-dollar supporter of Bush for governor and has raised more
than $100,000 for the Bush presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman's e-mail address is kherman(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
