<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3726 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-PGANOTES0817-COX     08-16 0397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PGANOTES0817-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Valhalla getBy Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. - After a couple of practice rounds at Valhalla,
site of the PGA Championship that begins today, something strange
has happened.
</P>
<P>
   The players like it.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them think that Valhalla is much better than it was in
1996, when it hosted a PGA 10 years after it was built.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants to see Winged Foot or a traditional golf course
with trees everywhere,'' two-time U.S. Open champion Lee Janzen
said, ``but I think this is a fantastic golf course and a beautiful
setting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected to come here and be very disappointed, but I'm not
disappointed at all,'' said Australian Stuart Appleby, who did not
play Valhalla in 1996. ``I sure don't know what everybody was
complaining about.''
</P>
<P>
   While the more traditional players dislike a mounded,
humps-and-bumps course, where weird bounces can decide a major, the
Valhalla's reviews are improving.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to (gripe) about it, then don't come,'' Buick
Open winner Rocco Mediate said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's matured a lot since the last time,'' Paul Azinger said.
``The course is in unbelievable shape. I've never seen fairways
like this before. You just can't get grass better than it is now.''
</P>
<P>
   Times have changed
</P>
<P>
   Before Tiger Woods began dominating, major championships were
wide open. It's not a development that has escaped Mark Brooks, who
defeated Kenny Perry at Valhalla in 1996 for his only major title.
Brooks hasn't won since. ``If the guy is stronger, faster, smarter,
all the other things, he usually wins,'' Brooks said. ``Right now,
I think he's right there. I hope he's peaked.'' . . .
Georgia-connected players in today's first round of the PGA are
Duluth residents Stewart Cink and Scott Dunlap; Sea Island's Davis
Love III, the 1997 PGA champion; Peachtree City's Franklin Langham;
club pro Mike Gill of Columbus; and Dalton's Michael Clark, who won
his first PGA Tour event, the John Deere Classic, last month. . . .
New looks: Steve Jones and his goatee; Paul Stankowski and his
peroxide-streaked hair. . . . New angle: John Daly recently
recording a country song in Branson, Mo., named ``You Can Lean On
Me.'' Daly said, ``My singing's terrible, but it's better than my
golf lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
