<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GODZILLA-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
``GODZILLA 2000'' IS OLD-STYLE MONSTER-MOVIE MAYHEM
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
When Hollywood usurped Japan's Godzilla franchise in 1998, fans
were as riled as their cranky reptile hero.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Instead of a lovable, doglike dino waddling on its hind legs and
waving its arms like a man in a rubber suit (which Godzilla always
was), Hollywood delivered a soulless, computer-animated lizard
engulfed by production overkill.
</P>
<P>
   But Japan has come to the rescue. Last year, its Toho Studios
issued a new Godzilla film, which hits the United States as
``Godzilla 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Disregard the name. This is old-style monster-movie mayhem,
which is to say, a Godzilla movie as God intended: a lovably
amusing foray into vapid plotting, bad dubbing and men in rubber
suits trashing miniature sets.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't appreciate such cheesy charms, then go hide in your
precious art house to await the next Shakespeare adaptation.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say this 23rd Godzilla entry lacks updating. A
few scenes are computer-generated, and the big boy is seamlessly
blended into long-shot exteriors of actual locations, with
bizarrely fanciful results.
</P>
<P>
   The testy titan also gets tweaking via new dorsal fins, a
worsened overbite and a spiffy warmup to his fire-breathing, as he
gargles flames before belching them out.
</P>
<P>
   But largely old formulas are intact: A noble scientist and
smarty-pants kid try to save Godzilla while witless government
types try to kill him, despite the fact that only Godzy stands
between Japan and yet another monstrous threat.
</P>
<P>
   In this case it's a huge spaceship that parks atop a Tokyo
skyscraper, siphoning off the city's data and energies.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow the ship and Zilla become rivals, zapping each other
until the vessel disgorges its own monster, which seems styled
after the alien of ``Predator.''
</P>
<P>
   Their rumble amid the crumble plays precisely like TV wrestling:
fake yet fun belligerence fired by bombast and signifying nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Even fans are apt to laugh at such vacant, if spectacular,
excess, but the biggest laughs may be unintended in a film whose
staged comic relief is limp and witless.
</P>
<P>
   Take the dubbing _ please. Oratorical voices sound parodistic,
and lines rarely match mouth movements.
</P>
<P>
   Anglo slang also sounds wacky, some jump-cuts are absurdly
abrupt, and human heroics are cornball, scored by equally corny
music.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the dialogue: ``Did you see that flying rock go
by?''
</P>
<P>
   Yet in its own weird way, this Zilla can be a thrillah.
</P>
<P>
   From a storyboard standpoint, its action scenes are
well-conceived, even if their execution is undercut by the budget.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, ``Godzilla 2000'' taps into a now-rare and
innocent sense of wonder.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't just about monsters. It's about awestruck responses
to the fantastic, whether that means balletic jets swooping to
attack or the awful yet amazing sight of a giant beast rumbling
forward like a force of nature.
</P>
<P>
   As a scientist says, ``It's like a scene from an old
science-fiction movie!'' Well, duh.
</P>
<P>
   Yet any sociological grounding has long lapsed. Godzilla no
longer is a cathartic metaphor for Japan's A-bomb traumas of World
War II. Rather, he's a durable film icon who deserves respect _
even if he's a big baby at heart.
</P>
<P>
   Godzilla, you see, never plays well with others. He stumbles
down streets like Pigpen of ``Peanuts,'' leaving dusty trails of
debris, and tends to get testy at the falling of a leaf _ or the
firing of a missile.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear what he wants, but we sense it's not peace and
quiet. Godzilla advances rather than retreats when attacked.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he's just looking for sheer, mindless adventure. If
that's your bag, too, then this rock-'em, sock-'em throwback to the
drive-in era is for you.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Godzilla 2000''
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Takehiro Murata
</P>
<P>
   Rating: PG for monster violence and mild language
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 97 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
