<HEADER>
A3728 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i BC-KOREASFAMILIES-817-CO     08-16 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREASFAMILIES-817-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia resident key player in Korean rapprochement
 &HT;    By Keith Graham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. - Across the Pacific in Korea, families divided
since the Korean War were reuniting in tearful, heart-tugging
scenes being flashed around the world.
</P>
<P>
   In his office adjacent to the University of Georgia campus, Han
Park was recalling another emotional moment nearly 20 years ago.
Park was in remote northeast China then, visiting ethnic Korean
families whose ties to their relatives in South Korea had been
similarly shattered by the war and the bamboo curtain that blocked
all communications afterward.
</P>
<P>
   He was hauling a video camera, shooting pictures that would then
be broadcast on South Korean television in hopes of helping
families rediscover long-lost loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   Riding in a cart pulled by a cow, he arrived at the home of an
elderly man who had begged him to visit. ``This old man is like a
skeleton,'' recalled Park, director of the university's Center for
the Study of Global Issues. ``I asked him whom are you looking for.
You know, he said my father. He was in his 80s. His father would
have been 100, 110 years old. And that really made me think.''
</P>
<P>
   Park sorrowfully told the man his father would likely be dead.
``People do not live that long,'' he said. But the man replied, ``I
would just be relieved if I saw my father's grave.''
</P>
<P>
   Park paused as he retold the story. ``When you are separated
like that, the same bloodline, unless you meet, you know, the pain
is still there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The reunions taking place this week affect only a few hundred
Koreans whose lives have been marred by that kind of pain, but they
symbolize a rapprochement between the divided Koreas that Park has
long worked to facilitate.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Gregg, former ambassador to South Korea and now president
of the Korea Society in New York, said Park is ``one of the
American architects _ if not an architect, certainly a contributor
_ to the breakthrough that's now taking place'' on the Korean
peninsula and potentially improving the prospects for peace in East
Asia.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, over the objections of the military regime that then
ruled South Korea, Park, a scholar who has taught in Athens for
three decades, traveled to North Korea for the first time. He's
been back ``35, 36, 37 times,'' he said, apologizing for no longer
recalling the exact number.
</P>
<P>
   Park admits to being nervous on his first trip to the isolated
Communist nation. And he's been warned on later trips _ especially
after one of his key contacts, Hwang Jang-yop, became a
high-profile defector _ that his personal safety could be in
jeopardy. But, over the years, Park has come to understand the
North Korean mind probably as well as anyone, according to Gregg.
</P>
<P>
   That understanding also made him uniquely situated to be an
informal go-between as North and South Korea weighed the options
before agreeing to their historic summit, which finally took place
in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I played some role in persuading them,'' said Park,
who acknowledged being ``one of'' the channels who conveyed to the
North that Kim Dae-jung was sincere in desiring a summit.
</P>
<P>
   Many times, the North Koreans said a meeting was out of the
question. But Park emphasized that he was not a messenger from the
South, but a foreigner _ an American _ trying to be objective, and
he tried to respond patiently to specific objections raised by the
North.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, Kim Jong-i
</P>
</TEXT>
