president in 1988 and lost, he organized a series of dinners where
he went around the room and asked each person to tell him where he
had gone wrong. It was excruciating, his friends said, but he
insisted on hearing the bad news. Gore responded, as he always has,
by going back to school. He put together a graduate seminar for
one, complete with a syllabus and a heavy-duty reading list, and
applied himself. Politicians often learn from and are even
transformed by a good drubbing at the polls, but few have pursued
their lessons as aggressively as Gore. By Melinda Henneberger and
