 PERSONALS: The Democrats' Tinseltown Balanchine 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Agriculture Secretary &UR; Dan Glickman &LR;  suggested that the only way &UR; Al
Gore  &LR; could top  &UR; Bill Clinton &LR; 's gladiatorlike approach to the
podium at the Democratic National Convention on Monday night, Aug.
14, is if the vice president jumped from a sky box and parachuted
down, says the Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   The choreographers who planned Clinton's arrival were his old
pals  &UR; Harry &LR;  and  &UR; Linda Bloodworth Thomason &LR; , creators of
``Designing Women'' (and the White House travel office scandal).
Harry Thomason told  &LR; Inside.com &LR;  that he got his inspiration from
the movies. ``I think I saw `High Noon' about a month ago, and I
thought, `They've been gunning for him for eight years.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In order for the plan to work, the Secret Service had to agree
not to appear in any of the camera shots. The corridors of the
Staples Center were sealed, and agents walked backward behind the
camera. Thomason had taped a rehearsal, with an extra playing the
president, in the dead of night. ``You could look at it and tell it
was good.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomason couldn't resist saying that the president had called
him from the White House on Tuesday, Aug. 15, to tell him ``that
everyone had been talking about The Walk,''  &LR; Inside.com &LR;  reported.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Gov.  &UR; Gray Davis &LR; ' presenting Clinton with an Oscar replica
at a party that Paramount threw for him on Monday night, Aug. 14,
raised some hackles, reports Variety. The Academy of Motion Picture
Arts and Sciences issued a statement saying, ``Both in its bylaws
and 72 years of careful practice, the Academy is resolutely
nonpolitical. We want to make sure the public understands that the
motion picture industry's highest accolade can be awarded only for
accomplishments relating to motion pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WHY GO COMMERCIAL? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Actress  &UR; Chloe Sevigny &LR;  explains, in the latest issue of
Interview, that she serves as a pitchwoman for advertisers because
of her high principles.
</P>
<P>
   There are not enough quality movies being made, she says,
``which is why I've had to turn to doing commercial work like the
H&AMP;M campaign.'' (H&AMP;M is a Swedish department store just arriving on
the New York scene.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate myself for doing things like that, but it's the only
way I can survive financially. I know (the ad) will be up on the
telephone booths for however long, and then it will disappear. A
film is there forever. . . . It's me surviving the movie industry.
I'd still rather do an ad than some romantic comedy that I would
later hate myself for.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHEN ROYALS DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In response to a query written long ago,  &UR; John Yelding-Sloan &LR; ,
an archaeologist who moonlights as a disc jockey and in that
capacity served at the  &UR; Queen Mother &LR; 's birthday party back in
June, has given Personals a rundown on royal dancing:
</P>
<P>
   The birthday celebrant didn't dance, but  &UR; Queen Elizabeth &LR; 
danced ``with a big smile on her face to the 15-piece swing
orchestra'' that had been imported from New York.  &UR; Prince Philip &LR; 
was in the disco, where the DJ presided, dancing with a woman the
DJ didn't recognize. The music was ``lots of Abba and Gipsy Kings,
that sort of Eurotrash crap.'' Some of the younger royals asked for
 &UR; Fat Boy Slim &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Steve Baker  &LR; sends word from Nevada City that poet  &UR; Gary &LR; 
 &UR; Snyder  &LR; gave a six-hour performance there last weekend of his epic
poem, ``Mountains and Rivers Without End.'' At the performance's
end, 350 die-hard poetry fans were hanging in there.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``I practice the yoga philosophy that I do not own anything on &LR; 
 &UR; this earth. I just use it for a time, and when I go, I leave &LR; 
 &UR; that Cadillac with the key in the ignition for someone else. But &LR; 
 &UR; those darn Napster people keep stealing my music. I've got five &LR; 
 &UR; record companies that admit they owe me millions, and they tell &LR; 
 &UR; me that if Napsters keep copying my songs for free off the &LR; 
 &UR; Internet, I won't get a cent. Yoga or no yoga, I labored all my &LR; 
 &UR; life to make those songs. Stop stealin' 'em!'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Ramblin' Jack Elliott  &LR; to &UR; Baird Jones &LR;  at the New York
premiere party for ``The Ballad of Ramblin' Jack.''
</P>
