<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3735 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-SUB-BOS &LR;      08-16 0329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCTIC AGONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The excruciating wait while rescuers struggle to reach Russia's
sunken submarine and the 116 men on board is a reminder of how
ephemeral life can be in the risky world of the military. Even in
the unlikely event they can all be brought to the surface alive,
the ordeal shows the vulnerability of even highly sophisticated
ships to fatal chance.
</P>
<P>
   The submarine, Kursk, got into serious trouble despite being
only five years old, one of the few vessels the post-Soviet Russian
Navy has built. It was surely made more vulnerable by chronic poor
maintenance resulting from extreme underfunding of the military,
but the sinking apparently was connected with a disaster, perhaps
an explosion in a forward compartment, that might have occurred on
even a well-maintained submarine.
</P>
<P>
   Early Russian reluctance to accept offers of help from abroad
has fortunately given way to willingness to give British and
Norwegian rescuers a chance to try to reach the crew. That act of
mutual accommodation is an important reflection of the way the
world has changed in the post-Cold War era. The Russian naval
maneuvers were a relic of that older, hostile era _ as was, to a
degree, the nearby presence of an American surveillance vessel that
may have detected the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   The disaster points to the need for additional cooperation among
Russian, American, and other naval programs. In the case of
submarines, compatible fittings for rescue vessels to reach
stranded crews is practical from both a technical and political
point of view. This should be discussed at the first opportunity.
Important models for such systems exist in the cooperative
international space station system.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the world waits to learn the fate of those trapped in
the cold bleakness of a crippled submarine _ perhaps 400 feet from
safety but also perhaps beyond help.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
