<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-LOPES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTONIO LOPES, 103, THOUGHT TO BE LAST NEW BEDFORD WHALER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Antonio Lopes was a fisherman. He worked the waters off the Cape
Verde Islands. When he was 24, he went looking for larger quarry:
whales.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Lopes, the man reputed to be the last of the New Bedford
whalers, died Aug. 7 in his home in the former Massachusetts
whaling port. He was 103.
</P>
<P>
   He was born and raised on the island of Sao Nicolau. He left the
island on Sept. 14, 1921.
</P>
<P>
   ``A man came to the island looking for whalers, on the schooner
William Graban. He told me to come, that America had a lot of work.
I believed him and went,'' Mr. Lopes said in a story published in
the Globe on Jan. 11, 1998. ``I never saw my family again, never
went back to my country.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no jobs here, so I went back out on a whaling
schooner, the Claudia. We were gone six months; whalers would go
out six months at a time. I made $13 before I left on the Claudia
and got another $25 when I got back.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Lopes said it was hard work. ``Sometimes you go two weeks
without seeing a whale, but you never sit. Never. You paint, you
wash the decks, always you wash the decks. You don't sit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd go down to the West Indies, then up to Newfoundland,
Canada, looking for whales. Sperm whales. There were 35 men on a
ship. The lookout, he sees one, he shouts, ``Thar she
blooooooooows! ``How far?'' the captain would yell, and we'd hear
``1 mile'' or ``2 mile,'' and the captain would order the
whaleboats in the water. If we got the whale, the lookout would get
$5 extra for each one he spotted.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Lopes was an oarsman on a 20-foot whaleboat. The boat had a
man steering, a harpooner, and a crew of four. ``We'd row and row
and row, 18-foot oars, lot of work, and the harpooner would stab
the whale, and then the next man, he would kill the whale, shoot
him in the head with a bomb, a gun that would shoot bombs. Blood
everywhere, but it would kill the whale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we'd have to row and row and drag the whale back to the
schooner. That was very hard, but we did it. Then we'd cut the
whale right there, in the water, big pieces. Other men would use
big poles to pull up pieces and put them in a huge pot on the deck
and cook the oil right out of the blubber, cook it right out, and
then the oil would run down below decks to a big iron tank. Most of
the fat was just behind the head of the whale, and we'd use pails
to scoop it out and put it in the big pot. Oil was the valuable
part; the parts that no give oil, they leave, let it go back in the
ocean. The sharks would eat it all. There were many, many sharks.''
</P>
<P>
   During his voyage on the Claudia, Mr. Lopes and his crewmates
dispatched 29 whales. ``That's a lot,'' he said. ``It would take
six hours to bring one in and then two, maybe three days to cut it
up and get all the blubber out and into the pot to get the oil.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he and his crewmates ate lots of beans, rounds of bread,
and plenty of whale meat. He said it tasted like hamburger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have many friends on the ship, most of them Cape Verdean,
like me,'' he said. ``One of my friends, Miguel Almeida, was a
harpooner; he died in 1972 in Providence. A few of the others died
only a few years ago. I am the last.''
</P>
<P>
   After another six-month whaling trip on the Graban, for which he
was paid $10, Mr. Lopes worked on the cranberry bogs, made nails
for Atlas Tack in Fairhaven, Mass., and was employed by North
Cordage Co. in New Bedford for 22 years.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves two daughters, Dorothy Lopes and Lydia Stevens of New
Bedford; two stepdaughters, Emily Almeida of New Bedford and
Frances Custodio of Wakefield, Mass.; four grandchildren, and 11
great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
