<HEADER>
A3742 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-KOREA-REUNIONS-BOS &LR;      08-16 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-REUNIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY REUNIONS SHIFT ATTITUDES ABOUT KOREAN UNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL _ Koreans, north and south, have passed a lifetime
excruciatingly close together on the map but forced painfully apart
by politicians and armies defending a Cold War border.
</P>
<P>
   But ideology means little to a mother separated from her son, or
to a wife who has waited half a century for her husband to come
home. The day after their first tear-drenched reunions in 50 years,
200 divided Korean families withdrew behind closed doors Wednesday
to rediscover loved ones who have become strangers, to dust the
cobwebs off lost lives.
</P>
<P>
   With his long-lost brothers in a Seoul hotel room, Oh Yong Jae,
64, North Korea's most celebrated poet, bowed three times before a
photograph of his parents engraved on a black stone and read aloud
a poem dedicated to the mother he never saw again after he ran away
to join North Korea's army as a teenager.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mother, you said you wouldn't die until you saw me, but you
are gone. I don't want to believe it,'' he recited, his voice
trembling as his brothers wept quietly. ``But time has no mercy.
Let us reunify our nation. Leave the systems and ideologies. Let us
simply reunify.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh's words sounded the theme of this week's historic reunions,
and could be a harbinger of what many here see as a flash-flood
rappochement between the two long-time enemy states. The family
reunions are the most tangible fruit of the first-ever summit
meeting of the leaders of the north and south two months ago, which
grew out of South Korean President Kim Dae Jung's ``sunshine
policy'' of engaging the Stalinist north, despite past broken
promises and military provocations by Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
   The surprisingly friendly summit and the emotionally-charged
reunions have fired the imagination of a public that nurses deep
wounds over the long separation. Most South Koreans now say the
idea of reunion in the not-too-distant future with the communist
North seems workable and even desirable _ a notion that would have
been laughable to many here even a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   And if the speedy-unification message being parroted by the
North Korean visitors and state media this week is any barometer,
attitudes in the North have shifted as well.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea's newspapers have stopped denouncing the South as
``the enemy.'' South Korea'a military has stopped referring to
``the northern puppet army.''
</P>
<P>
   South Korea's conservative opposition party, long wary of the
north, has dropped its objections to relaxing the anti-communist
security law, and even suggested that Seoul rewrite the
constitution to recognize Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
   A South Korean government survey found that 97 percent of the
public saw the June summit as a success. Nearly 91 percent believe
the north is changing, and 77 percent are prepared to shoulder the
burden of investment to develop their cash-strapped, economically
backward neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the credit for post-summit euphoria goes to the
unexpected charm offensive by Northern leader Kim Jong Il _ the
first performance on the world stage for the previously reclusive
leader. His joking, boisterious TV manner has spawned ``Kim Jong Il
fever'' here, with on-line fan clubs and smiling dolls of a man
whom South Koreans were taught to revile as a freak.
</P>
<P>
   His gestures of amity in the last two months _ an invitation to
South Korean media executives and an array of proposals for new
cross-border links _ have taken South Korean policy makers by
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know how to react, to be honest,'' one official said.
``Now he says, `Let's have two more reunions.' Nobody knows what
he'll say next.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is ready to trust a regime that reneged on its
promises after previous rounds of diplomacy. But for a public
captivated by round-the-clock television images of the dramatic
family reunions, this time seems different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt today when I saw these reunions that all those old
leaders of South Korea cheated us _ we are victims of our past
governments who wanted to keep the Koreas apart,'' said Kim Young
Hwan, 43, a taxi driver. ``I cried when I saw those families so
long separated. . . . The gap between North and South Korea is big.
But if these kinds of reunions go on, step by step, (reunification)
can happen. The first and most important thing is to trust each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear how soon reunification would be feasible
between the south's vibrant democracy, boasting one of the world's
largest economies, and the north's authoritarian regime, with its
antiquated controlled economy in shambles. In a June newspaper
poll, three-fourths of South Koreans agreed that unification would
take five to 30 years. A study by economists for Goldman Sachs
estimated it would cost $1 trillion, much more than it cost West
Germany to absorb the East.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the pricetag, there is a generational divide among
South Koreans on the issue: older Koreans favor reunification, but
those too young to remember the war see Pyongyang as more foreign
than Taipei or New York. Only 30 percent of elementary through
college students surveyed after the summit said life would improve
if the Koreas reunited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time North Korea needs something from us, they ask for
it, and we get nothing in return,'' said Kim Yong Jae, 19, an
engineering student. ``I've talked to other students, and we
believe if (reunification) doesn't happen in 10 years, it'll never
happen, because by then, it'll be our generation running the show,
and we have nothing to do with the North.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are painful words for the older separated families who say
they want nothing more than to live their remaining years together.
Ryang Han Sang, a North Korean, waited 50 years to come south but
has been unable to see his 87-year-old mother, because she is too
weak to ride an ambulance to the hotel in which the
carefully-controlled reunions are being held.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't see my mother, then it would have been better if I
had not come,'' Ryang, 69, cried in agony to his brothers in a
hotel room. ``There are a lot of things to talk about after being
separated for 50 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
