<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3745 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-CONCORDE-1STL     08-16 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-CONCORDE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN AND FRANCE OFFICIALLY RULE CONCORDE UNFIT TO FLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: UPDATES with France also ruling Concorde unfit, adds details
throughout; no pickup.) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ British and French aviation regulators withdrew
airworthiness certification from the Concorde Wednesday,
effectively ruling the world's only commercial supersonic airliner
unfit to fly until it can be protected against the catastrophic
safety flaws behind last month's fatal crash near Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Narrowing their assessment of what caused the crash,
investigators said they believed that a tire blowout had sent
chunks of rubber flying into a fuel tank, rupturing it and causing
it to erupt in flames as the plane sped towards take-off at 195
miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, French investigators said a 16-inch piece of metal
on the runway had ruptured the tire, setting off the sequence of
apparently freakish events that caused the plane to crash within 90
seconds of takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is uniquely different in this case is that tire debris
alone is thought to have led to this catastrophic accident,'' said
Malcolm Field, the chairman of Britain's Civil Aviation Authority,
the regulatory agency that ordered the grounding of British
Airways' Concordes Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The revocation Wednesday of the Concorde's airworthiness
certificate _ the document that permits airplanes to fly in the
airspace of the authority that issues it _ was the first since U.S.
authorities grounded the McDonnell-Douglas DC-10 for five weeks in
1979, aviation experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Air France and British Airways _ the only airlines
operating the Concorde _ decide that it is technically and
economically feasible to modify the aircraft or introduce new
safety procedures, the process could take ``months rather than
weeks,'' said Mike Bell, a senior official from the Civil Aviation
Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing the assessment of some aviation industry analysts,
Kieran Daly, editor of Air Transport Intelligence, an aviation Web
site, said, ``It will be a finely balanced financial question
whether to do these modifications or not.''
</P>
<P>
   British Airways said it had canceled Concorde services through
early September but would resume them at 24 hours' notice if the
airworthiness certification were restored.
</P>
<P>
   Air France grounded its five remaining Concordes immediately
after the July 25 crash of New York-bound Concorde Flight AF 4590,
which killed 113 people in the first fatal accident involving the
prestigious, supersonic airplane. British Airways grounded its
fleet of seven Concordes on Tuesday after learning that the
airworthiness certificate would be revoked Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways gave no clear indication whether it believed the
aircraft, which crosses the Atlantic in around three and one-half
hours at up to twice the speed of sound, would ever return to
commercial service.
</P>
<P>
   The Concorde has been plying scheduled transatlantic and other
charter routes for almost 25 years and had come to be seen as an
icon of prestigious travel for executives and celebrities ready to
pay up to $10,000 for a round-trip journey taking half the time of
a subsonic flight.
</P>
<P>
   As British Airways' flagship, the Concorde had also been seen as
an important magnet in drawing high-end travelers to the airline.
</P>
<P>
   Field, the chairman of the Civil Aviation Authority, said
Wednesday: ``It is clear to all of us in the CAA that a tire
blowout alone should never cause the loss of a public transport
aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   Field said the authority had asked Concorde's manufacturers, BAe
Systems, Airbus UK and Aerosaptiale of France _ to devise a plan to
insure that accidents could not be caused by tire blowouts. Under
aviation regulations, airplanes whose fuel tanks are vulnerable to
catastrophic damage from ruptured-tire debris may not be certified
as airworthy.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Concorde's spindly, stork-like landing gear is positioned
directly below the wings, fuel tanks and engines. But British
aviation experts say the British Concordes were modified to protect
the wings from damage by tire blowouts, while Air France Concordes
were not modified. Tire blowouts have been a worry for Concorde
pilots since the plane entered service in early 1976, according to
British aviation experts.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, there have been seven known tire blowouts when
fragments struck fuel tanks without causing fires, the experts
said. The modifications to the British Airways Concordes in 1993
involved changes to a water deflector on the undercarriage to
``reduce the energy'' from a ruptured tire, according to Derek
Blackhall, the head of the certification section of the Civil
Aviation Authority. Air France Concordes did not have the same
modification.
</P>
<P>
   But Mike Bell, a senior Civil Aviation Authority official, told
a news conference that it was ``quite unique, an unprecedented
event'' for a tire blowout alone to cause an air disaster.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Field rejected the idea that the demand for modifications
effectively meant the Concorde would never fly again. ``We would
wish Concorde to fly again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Claude Gayssot, the French transport minister, also said
the measures did not necessarily imply the end of supersonic
travel. ``Anyone who says it's the end for supersonic flights has
got it wrong,'' he told the daily newspaper Liberation, ``Traveling
fast is going to be increasingly in demand.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A British investigator, Ken Smart, of Britain's Air Accident
Investigation Branch, said the precise links between the sequence
of events that doomed Flight AF 4590 last month remained to be
established in detail.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, the damaged tire sent debris flying to puncture
one or more fuel tanks, allowing fuel to spill out and catch fire
within seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The airplane lost thrust in one engine, then in two. ``The crew
had no means to make them aware of the nature of the fire nor to
take action against it,'' he said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   He said the safety issues relating to the tires would take
``some time to resolve.''
</P>
<P>
   The head of France's Accident Investigation Bureau, Paul-Louis
Arslanian, told reporters in Paris: ``I hope the Concorde will fly
again, but I am an investigator of accidents, not a witch-doctor. I
cannot read crystal balls.''
</P>
</TEXT>
