<SLUG> BC-MA-NILE-VIRUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASS. TESTING SENIORS FOR NILE VIRUS INFECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RAJA MISHRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Thirty-five ailing seniors in the Boston area have been
tested for the West Nile virus over the last month but none had the
potentially lethal infection, state health officals revealed
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ten more people with suspicious symptoms will be tested in the
next few days, they said.
</P>
<P>
   All the cases involved patients in area hospitals who had West
Nile-like symptoms: fever, headache, body aches, and occasionally
skin rash and swollen lymph glands. Some of the patients turned out
to be infected with the herpes virus. Three-quarters of the people
tested were from the greater Boston area.
</P>
<P>
   Regular human testing is a standard part of tracking viruses,
but is also a sign that health officials are taking the possibility
of human infections seriously. Although health officals said they
remain skeptical that any serious cases now exist, they said
continued testing is crucial.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a case out there we want to know. It's important
to test samples every week,'' said Ralph Timperi, director of the
state lab where the tests took place. ``We expect to have a steady
stream (of human test samples) to look at.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been just three diagnosed human cases of West Nile
Virus this year, all in Staten Island, NY. Health officials there
tested 269 people before finding them. Boston officals are actively
making the rounds of city hospitals looking for people with
symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   To date, 12 infected birds and one group of mosquitoes have been
found. They have mostly been from the Jamaica Plain-Brookline area,
considered the state's only viral ``hot spot.'' Late Wednesday,
mosquito ground spraying was expected to take place in Jamaica
Plain, Brookline and Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   West Nile virus generally produces mild flu-like symptoms. It
can be fatal in 3 to 15 percent of cases, causing brain swelling or
encephalitis. Occasionally it causes meningitis, a less serious
inflammation of the membranes that surround and protect the brain
and spinal cord. The three Staten Island cases involved meningitis,
and all have since recovered.
</P>
<P>
   The elderly are especially vulnerable to the virus. The patients
tested here were mostly between 50 and 70 years in age.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts has several hundred cases of encephalitis a year,
with dozens of different causes. The 45 patients that were referred
for testing typically had a bout of encephalitis without a clear
cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those encephalitis cases without an explanation, West Nile
virus is now one of the things we now think about,'' said Bela
Matyas, medical director of the state Department of Health's
epidemeology program.
</P>
<P>
   Matyas' staff is making weekly calls to the Boston hospitals
near the Jamaica Plain-Brookline hot spot, inquiring about
unexplained encephalitis cases.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, several of the 35 people tested were found to have the
herpes virus and some had enteroviruses, a common type of virus
that in some cases can cause encephalitis.
</P>
<P>
   The first and most lethal West Nile virus outbreak occurred in
Queens, N.Y. in 1999, where 7 people died and 62 were sickened.
After the initial outbreak subsided, officials found that 2.6
percent of the residents of that Queens neighborhood had been
infected but most had mild or no symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   The state lab in Jamaica Plain is the only facility in the state
that has a West Nile virus sample to test human, bird, and mosquito
samples against. Hospitals have no way of spotting a case of the
virus on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting great cooperation from hospitals. When something
new like West Nile comes along, everybody is interested,'' said
Matyas.
</P>
<P>
   The mosquito population is now peaking and officals have
repeatedly warned the public to wear protective clothing, avoid
parks at dawn and dusk, use bug repellent and to empty containers
of standing water.
</P>
<P>
   The risk for infection remains miniscule, even in the Jamaica
Plain-Brookline hot spot. But some health experts assume that as
the summer wears on at least some people will become infected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think there would be some infections in the JP area,''
said Andrew Spielman, a professor of tropical public health at
Harvard' School of Public Health. ``I'm sure there are people out
there being bitten by mosquitoes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
