u l BC-DECORATOR-PRICE-NYT &LR;      08-16 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DECORATOR-PRICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECIFYING THE AMOUNT OF GREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (With DECORATOR-COST) 
By ELAINE LOUIE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There are as many ways to bill a client as there are
designers and architects. The confusion arises when the client
doesn't know the real cost of things, be they bolts of fabric or a
contractor's fee. Fabric, for instance, may have a list price for
the public, and a net price that is 25 to 40 percent lower and that
is available only to architects and designers.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Sonet, the publicist for the Donghia furniture and textiles
company and who represented its founder, the late interior designer
Angelo Donghia, recounted Donghia's rule about charging: ``Where
there's mystery, there's distrust. There should only be one price,
which is the net price. You make your money by charging a fee for
your expertise and the design work.''
</P>
<P>
   But the day of one price, with every showroom open to the public
and all prices revealed, has not arrived. The happiest client is
the one whose decorator or architect quotes the price that he has
paid, along with the markup to the client.
</P>
<P>
   Antiques present a special problem. When an antiques dealer buys
something, ``he can mark it up any percentage,'' said Mario Buatta,
the interior designer. He continued: ``If I go into an antiques
shop, I get a discount between 20 and 25 percent, and I sell the
antique at the price the antique dealer has written on it. If a
desk is $10,000, I can't suddenly buy it at $10,000 and resell it
for $80,000, because everybody has seen it as $10,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are billing approaches taken by six Manhattan architects,
designers and shopping consultants.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Buatta: For furniture and fabrics, Buatta pays the
discounted price, and the client pays either the list price, if the
goods come from a showroom, or, for antiques, the retail price
written on the tag. ``Go to Clarence House, the fabric showroom,''
he said. ``There's a list price of, say, $120 a yard. I pay $80,
the client pays $120.''
</P>
<P>
   If any construction is to be done, Buatta gives the contractor's
contract to the client, who pays the contractor directly. ``I
charge 25 percent of whatever the contractor charges,'' Buatta
said. ``It's too complicated any other way. All I have is the
design and supervisory fee, which is the 25 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   For out-of-town construction, Buatta charges a day rate of
$3,500 for occasional site visits, in addition to the fees already
mentioned for fabrics and furniture. ``But then I don't get 25
percent of the contractor's fee,'' he said, ``because I'm not there
to supervise it. They have to hire somebody else to supervise every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Post, interior designer: Post charges a one-time fee
based on the cost of the entire project _ including furniture,
fabric, lighting and construction _ and is set before the contract
is signed. For furniture and fabrics, clients pay the net price.
(Post pays with the clients' credit cards, keeping an itemized
list.) ``I don't care if they buy a Crate &AMP; Barrel couch, or spend
millions of dollars where everything is custom,'' Post said.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Gorlin, architect: For residential projects, Gorlin
charges 15 to 18 percent of the construction cost, which includes
appliances, custom cabinetwork, millwork and built-in lighting. For
furniture, draperies, rugs and fabric, he charges the discounted,
or net, price plus an hourly fee. ``They can see all the bills for
the furniture, draperies and rugs,'' Gorlin said. The hourly fee
ranges from $400 for Gorlin to $100 for a junior staff member.
</P>
<P>
   D'Aquino Monaco Inc.: Carl D'Aquino, an interior designer, and
Francine Monaco, an architect, use several approaches. ``Our books
are open,'' D'Aquino said. First, the client pays the net (or
discounted) price for fabric and furniture to showrooms that accept
the client's check. ``When a vendor won't accept a client's check
directly, we create a purchase order that we pay, and the client
reimburses us, knowing the exact fee,'' D'Aquino said. ``The
clarity is that the client knows the exact price of each and every
item they have.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the contract, the designers receive markups over net
price, one for the furniture, another for construction.
</P>
<P>
   For clients who appear indecisive from the outset, the firm
charges an hourly rate. The client pays the net price for
everything, plus an agreed-upon hourly fee that includes all work
done by the firm, whether by the partners or a junior designer.
``This method of payment would be to our benefit,'' D'Aquino said.
``The designer is protected.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is the flat fee, one lump sum for all the
contracting, painting and furniture. This fee, specified in the
contract, works best with the most decisive clients.
</P>
<P>
   The Decoration and Design Building: Most of the showrooms in the
D&AMP;D Building, 979 Third Ave., are open to the trade only. But for a
client who wants to shop at the building, Charlotte Zaslav, who
works for the D&AMP;D management, will consult for $100 an hour and
shop with the client in the building's showrooms, buying goods at
the net price and charging a 15 percent commission. She can be
reached at (212) 759-6894.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Windman, interior designer and purchasing agent: Some
individual showrooms at the D&AMP;D Building, like Donghia, might
recommend someone like Windman, who will act as a purchasing agent,
or shopper, for a client who lacks a designer or an architect. ``If
they're hiring me as a purchasing agent, I'll charge them net price
plus an additional 20 percent,'' Windman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
