<HEADER>
A3749 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-HAND-TRANSPLANT-BOS &LR;      08-16 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAND-TRANSPLANT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS QUESTION HAND TRANSPLANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He can write his name, throw a ball, turn the pages of a
newspaper. He can sense heat and touch and he can feel pain.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Scott can do all that with his new left hand, the first
ever transplanted to an American. But beyond that, Scott has
overcome a major challenge: he has come to feel that a dead man's
very visible part sewn to his arm is now his own.
</P>
<P>
   But, 18 months after the operation, Scott's case at the center
of a debate over the ethics of offering such risky surgery to
people whose lives are otherwise healthy. While the hazards of
anti-rejection drugs may be acceptable in a heart or liver
transplant to save a patient's life, doctors are divided over
whether a new hand is worth the risk of life-threatening
complications.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, 39, whose extraordinary case is detailed for the first
time in the current issue of the New England Journal of Medicine,
lost his left hand in a fireworks accident in 1985. Until January
1999 he had a mechanical prosthesis.
</P>
<P>
   Since the transplant, a 15-hour-procedure followed by months of
physical therapy and slow recovery, Scott has ``showed a remarkable
psychological adaption'' that suggests he was mentally strong at
the outset, said Dr. Martin Klapheke, a member of the team that
carried out the operation in Louisville, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   Scott has had three episodes in which his body tried to reject
the hand, but he has been remarkably free of complications except
for a long bout of stomach trouble and fatigue that had him
wondering if he'd done the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Klapheke said he was intially worried how Scott
would be affected when, soon after the operation, the media
breached confidentiality by naming the hand's donor, a 59-year-old
brain-dead man, and revealing ``tragic details'' of the donor's
life. But, said the psychiatrist, Scott remained stalwart. ``He
said `No, this is my hand . . . this is my blood pumping through
it, and I'm in control of it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The report in the New England Journal, by Drs. Jon W. Jones and
Warren C. Breidenbach of the University of Louisville School of
Medicine emphasizes the transplant's success to date, and the
doctors are planning to continue with them. A spokeswoman for
Louisville's Jewish Hospital, where the transplant was done, said
that over 300 potential candidates had contacted the team but for
one reason or another they were ruled out.
</P>
<P>
   Scott's success hasn't quieted medical and ethical concerns
about the transplants, and an editorial accompanying the report
calls for a go-slow approach.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James H. Herndon, chief of the Partners Health Care
orthopedic service in Boston, argues that regaining the use of a
hand doesn't justify subjecting patients to the risks of
anti-rejection drugs, which can lead to infections, lymphoma,
leukemia and other complications.
</P>
<P>
   Until better immuno-suppressive drugs come along, Herndon wrote,
the transplants should be limited to patients who are already
taking anti-rejection drugs for a life-threatening condition and
who also lose a hand.
</P>
<P>
   The Harvard surgeon is one of four hand surgeons at
Massachusetts General Hospital and two at Brigham and Women's
Hospital in Boston who are part of the Partners orthopedics
department. The surgeons perform complicated re-attachments of
severed fingers and toes and repair congenital defects. But
Louisville is the only U.S. center that has taken on hand
transplants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think patients will probably push the demand'' for hand
transplants ``and a few more centers'' may begin the operations,
Herndon said. He said that the transplants are ``long and tedious''
but can be done successfully because surgeons have had years of
experience with re-implantations.
</P>
<P>
   The surgeons in Louisville continue to seek transplant
candidates who have lost one or both their hands or forearms in
accidents or because of medical treatment (though not cancer). They
are not offering transplants of individual fingers, or feet or
legs.
</P>
<P>
   Klapheke, the psychiatrist for the transplant team, said that he
was originally skeptical about the value of the transplants _ until
he talked to candidates. Although he said he was intellectually
aware of how crucial the hand is to one's body image and to
interacting with people _ and even feeling competent _ Klapheke
found their stories more poignant than he expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very powerful thing to talk to a number of these
individuals and understand how much longing they have to replace
that hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Louisville team leader Breidenbach said the limitations on
transplant candidates that Harvard's Herndon proposes would make it
virtually impossible to qualify patients for the surgery. He also
argued that the success of the hand transplant patients worldwide
suggest that the limits aren't needed.
</P>
<P>
   Breidenbach said Wednesday in an interview that he is ``very
pleased'' not only with Scott's progress but with the entire world
hand transplant experience so far. With eight hands transplanted in
six patients and up to a year and 11 months' followup, he said,
``there's been no loss of a transplanted organ. All the patients
are doing well'' except for the world's first hand transplant
recipient who has proven unreliable in taking his medication.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
