<SLUG> BC-LATIN-MUSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATIN MUSIC CONFERENCE HIGHLIGHTS TALENT AND GROWING APPRECIATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (Critic's Notebook)  
 By JON PARELES   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Latin Alternative Music Conference, which
presented performances and panel discussions from Saturday through
Tuesday, set out to be the start of something big.
</P>
<P>
   About 700 musicians, recording-company executives, radio
programmers, Web site operators and journalists registered for the
conference at the New York Hilton and Towers. Many more people
showed up to hear bands from Mexico, Chile, Argentina, Colombia,
Venezuela and Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   And just about everyone believed that the music they love has an
audience eagerly awaiting it, if only they can make contact.
</P>
<P>
   It will take time and strategy. There is, of course, a language
barrier, though that has not stopped American and English rock from
being heard worldwide. And the music barely has a foothold on
American radio, where it's heard almost entirely on college or
public stations. Conference participants shared other ways to get
the music heard, with high hopes for satellite, cable and Internet
radio. Some compared the situation to collegiate rock in the early
1980s, when bands were just finding a circuit of clubs and college
gigs, and word of mouth meant survival.
</P>
<P>
   But that was before the spread of the Internet: With any luck,
the timetable will be faster for Latin alternative music.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the United States, the music faces the barriers of
national taste. Yet music video has bound Latin America together.
And Molotov _ a group of raucous, punk-rooted rappers who sometimes
tilt back toward Mexican rhythms _ has sold 1 million albums
worldwide, nearly a quarter of them in Spain. Molotov headlines the
Watcha Tour, a package of raucous rock en espanol bands, which
comes to the Tunnel in Chelsea on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Conference participants cited promising demographics,
particularly the growing number of Americans _ both immigrants and
native-born _ who speak Spanish and have a stake in more than one
culture. (Los Angeles County, which includes the factory town of
American entertainment, is projected to have a Hispanic majority
within the decade.) Whatever their roots, they've also been
bombarded by American pop, and there's no reason not to enjoy
whatever they want. Young Latinos and Latinas are bilingual and
used to crossing cultural borders; they don't have to shut anything
out. And as they casually juggle multiple idioms, they show how to
thrive in a globally networked 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much information that goes by,'' said Julieta
Venegas, a songwriter who grew up in Tijuana, Mexico, and is about
to release her second album. ``Naturally you learn to use it.''
Venegas is completely fluent in English, which she learned from
California television, but she writes in Spanish because, she says,
``I don't really feel things in English, and I don't want to fake
it.'' She sometimes plays a small Mexican accordion in her songs,
but she got the idea, she says, from hearing Joe Jackson and Tom
Waits. And her songs have the clear melodies and emotional impact
that could make listeners sing along before they worry about the
words.
</P>
<P>
   At the conference, no one tried to pin down a definition of
alternative. It is, in practice, music that's not heard on
commercial Spanish-language radio stations, which tend to play
salsa, sentimental Latin pop or established regional genres like
Mexican banda or Dominican bachata. Latin alternative tends to be
format-busting music. A band like Illya Kuryaki and the
Valderramas, from Argentina, is fully capable of using rapping,
rock guitars, Afro-Caribbean percussion and lounge-funk interludes
all in the same song, while the lyrics leap from personal
confession to social comment to surreal humor.
</P>
<P>
   The music already has a long pedigree. In Brazil in the late
1960s, rebellious rockers created tropicalia, embracing a giddy
modernity without forgetting homegrown traditions. Rock also got
footholds in Mexico, in Argentina and across Latin America, where
multinational marketing met a receptive public. In many places,
bands started out imitating foreign rockers while writing lyrics in
Spanish; gradually, however, local idioms peeked through.
</P>
<P>
   By now, the category rock en espanol has become far too
confining to hold music that stretches from Venegas' intimate pop
songs to the introspective rock of Aterciopelados to the funk of
Los Amigos Invisibles to the electronica of Nortec.
</P>
<P>
   The bands that performed during the conference rebounded Anglo
rock with their own warps and twists. Even when they dressed like
punks, band members were proficient musicians; they have to be to
slip in and out of multiple styles. A few, like La Ley _ one of
Chile's top bands _ simply imitated pompous '80s rock that sounds
shop-worn here. But Vallejo, a band from Austin that has songs in
English and Spanish, found a way to merge rap-metal with Southern
rock, Texas boogie and Caribbean rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   And Nortec, an electronica collective from Tijuana, calmly
bounced electronica across borders. The band's name comes from
norteno, the Mexican label for Tex-Mex music, and techno, and at
Irving Plaza on Tuesday night, the group projected videos and
slides with images of accordions, banditos and a digitalized
cactus.
</P>
<P>
   Its disc jockey-programmers built their music from cold
electronic tones that harked back to Kraftwerk, but also from the
sounds of the drums and cowbells in Mexican cumbia bands; one
segment took the beat of a norteno waltz and distorted it into a
techno chomp. It was recognizably local and internationally
up-to-date, and it was irresistible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
