<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3754 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-DEM-GORE-BIO-TRANSFOR     08-16 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-GORE-BIO-TRANSFORM-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN INDUSTRIOUS AND INTELLIGENT MAN STILL SEEKING TO DEFINE
HIMSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: an abridged version, DEM-GORE-bio-transform-abridged, is also
being filed.)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER and KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After Al Gore ran for president in 1988 and lost, just as he
turned 40, he organized a series of dinners where he went around
the room and asked each person to tell him where he had gone wrong.
What hadn't he known? What hadn't he done?
</P>
<P>
   It was excruciating, his friends said, but he insisted on
hearing the bad news _ in detail _ about a campaign that had
started out as an environmental crusade and ended as a New York
food fight. He heard that he had no economic vision and that he had
talked about technology and the environment in ways that people
could not understand. Oh, and his speaking style needed a ton of
work.
</P>
<P>
   Gore responded, as he always has, by going back to school. He
put together a graduate seminar for one, complete with a syllabus
and a heavy-duty reading list, and applied himself to the serious
study of tax policy and business history. He brought in a
mathematician to explain chaos theory. And he hired a speech
consultant and a dance coach _ ``a ballet type,'' he told one
friend _ to help him move more fluidly.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians often learn from and are even transformed by a good
drubbing at the polls, but few have pursued their lessons as
aggressively as Gore. No one can say that the man who will accept
the Democratic Party's nomination for the presidency Thursday night
has not diligently readied himself.
</P>
<P>
   Yet all this extensive preparation has not showed in the Gore
campaign, which at least until recently has seemed surprisingly
unfocused. while Gore been training to govern from quite a young
age, he has always had mixed feelings about the path to power that
is politics.
</P>
<P>
   He is a student by nature _ even after Vietnam, he treated his
moral hangover with a year of divinity school, saying he wanted to
impose some structure on the exercise. His extraordinary
willingness to learn and change has taught him much, but has also
left him wide open to the charge that he is constantly reinventing
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Reinvention isn't all bad. Back in 1981, when he was concerned
about where the Cold War was headed, Gore turned himself into a
bona fide arms-control expert in a single year by plunging into the
arcana of a subject he had previously known almost nothing about.
In the '90s, he got way out front in learning about issues that no
one else was paying much mind, like information technology and
global warming.
</P>
<P>
   ``His education is ongoing,'' said his Harvard friend Tommy Lee
Jones, the actor. ``Where 20 years ago he would have made outlines
with Roman numerals, now it would look like rectangles on top of
each other, equally well organized but not so linear, and probably
three-dimensional.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet this quality has been nothing but trouble for Gore in the
current campaign, mostly noted through small but symbolic personal
alterations, like his new Palm Pilot and his switch from dark suits
to earth tones _ changes that are insignificant in themselves, but
resonate because they remind many people of the way he's shifted on
some key issues, particularly gun control and abortion.
</P>
<P>
   It is the same story with his work ethic _ something Americans
profess to love. As a senator, Gore was so determined to shoehorn
extra work into his day that during weekends of back-to-back town
hall meetings he would get himself booked in two places at the same
time _ a trick that was possible, barely, because Tennessee
straddles two time zones.
</P>
<P>
   He adored the illusion of time-bending, a former aide said.
``I'd tell him, `You just missed 400 people in Knoxville because we
crossed back to some backwater county to see three people.' And
he'd say, `Yeah, but we get an extra hour.'''
</P>
<P>
   Gore is someone who makes all his hard work look like ... hard
work. Lacking the smooth moves of either his boss, Bill Clinton, or
his Republican opponent, George W. Bush, Gore is a plodder, who
hopes to be a tortoise to Bush's hare.
</P>
<P>
   But there's more going on than raw effort. Gore's intellect and
the willingness to use it are probably his most important assets.
His Harvard mentor, the presidential scholar Richard Neustadt, has
said that compared with American presidents in this century,
probably only Theodore Roosevelt had a keener mind. Gore's friends
often see him as a visionary.
</P>
<P>
   His oldest daughter, Karenna Gore Schiff, said: ``He likes to
ask, `What's the assumption here? What if we subvert it?' and one
of the things he could maybe do well if he wins the job is make new
connections, like between the economy and the environment, and ask,
`What if we were the leading exporter of ways to clean up the
environment?'''
</P>
<P>
   Those are not the kind of connections that crowds thrill to,
though. All Gore's smarts do not necessarily translate into an
ability to sway the public with feeling, as well as facts _ as he
is all too aware.
</P>
<P>
   One Clinton Cabinet member says that the interesting thing about
watching Gore in a meeting is the way he reasons, relying less on
anecdote and more on all that is known about a given topic than
most politicians do. Again, this is both a strength, because he is
able to analyze options dispassionately, and a liability, because
he fails to fully understand how important human stories are in
communicating about policy with the public.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
