<HEADER>
A3755 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-UNC-WIRED0818-COX     08-16 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNC-WIRED0818-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UNC expands wireless learning
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAPEL HILL, N.C. _ Arriving on Wednesday for the start of his
junior year, Mike Trinh said he was feeling the pang of ``e-mail
withdrawals.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as the 19-year-old at the University of North Carolina
at Chapel Hill wanted to hook up his computer to the Internet, his
dorm room was a mess of disassembled beds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Otherwise, I'd already be wired up,'' Trinh said.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from start-of-the-school-year housekeeping lapses, North
Carolina's flagship public university is taking major steps to
connect its students with computers.
</P>
<P>
   UNC-Chapel Hill is the latest _ and it says the nation's biggest
_ university to require undergraduates to own laptop computers.
</P>
<P>
   The college also is developing a wireless network that allows
users to connect to the Internet without plugging directly into the
university's high-speed data network.
</P>
<P>
   ``When students can take their computers and actually log on to
the Internet sitting under a tree or on a park bench, that's an
incredible technology,'' said James Moeser, UNC's new chancellor.
``It is going to transform the way learning takes place on the
campus.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting with the distribution of laptops to 3,400 freshmen, the
university says all of its approximately 15,000 undergraduates will
have laptops in four years.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, nine out of 10 college students are connected to the
Internet, according to the research firm Jupiter Communications.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 colleges are equipping their students with laptops,
said Kenneth Green, director of the Campus Computing Project, which
studies the role of information technology in higher education.
</P>
<P>
   Technicians have installed around campus 20 devices that allow
wireless laptop users to connect to UNC's data network _ without
the typical modem or phone line connection over a cable.
</P>
<P>
   Laptop users must be within about 50 feet of the devices,
initially installed in the student union, the Davis and House
libraries, the main dining hall and several other locations.
Another wireless venue is the Pit, an outdoor brick seating area
that's a popular gathering place for students.
</P>
<P>
   To work with UNC's fledgling wireless network, a laptop must be
equipped with an access card, which students can check out at the
campus library for three hours, or can buy in the student store for
about $150.
</P>
<P>
   The wiring of UNC is no less crucial ``than running water or
plumbing,'' said William Friday, UNC's president emeritus. ``You
have to deal with the age you are in.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Gogan, UNC's director of networking and communications, said
the wireless network will supplement _ not replace _ the extensive
network of wiring at the school. For more than a decade, UNC has
been wiring dorms, classrooms, libraries and other buildings to
connect to its data network.
</P>
<P>
   But Gogan said wireless networking is more suitable in public
gathering places and in classrooms that can't easily be wired
because professors, for instance, move chairs for different
classes.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1998, the university has encouraged students to buy
laptops, before requiring freshmen to do so this school year.
</P>
<P>
   In a voluntary program last fall, nearly two-thirds of freshmen
bought laptops and participated in pilot programs to help faculty
members plan for this fall.
</P>
<P>
   At UNC, students use personal computers and computers in
university labs to swap e-mail and, increasingly, to visit class
Web pages to check assignments and grades and do classwork.
</P>
<P>
   Laptops, administrators say, will allow students to take notes
during classes and connect with the Internet in buildings across
campus.
</P>
<P>
   UNC has adopted two models of the IBM ThinkPad laptop.
University officials say, so far, more than nine in 10 freshmen
have bought their laptops through UNC, which has made arrangements
for students to borrow money to buy the computers at a relatively
low interest rate.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, up to $3 million is available in grants to freshmen
who can't afford to buy the laptops, which can cost as much as
$2,924. The grants are redeemable at UNC Student Stores.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
