<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3756 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-DEM-GORE-BIO-TRANSFOR     08-16 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-GORE-BIO-TRANSFORM-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: the public.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gore is genuinely in love with the world of ideas, loves nothing
more than a good kibbitz about the multiverse, and apparently sees
how fractal geometry might improve our lives.
</P>
<P>
   He is a sucker for fun facts, too _ and always alert for
openings to share them. During his campaign visits to schools, he
has delivered spontaneous lectures on the Ice Ages, the Industrial
Revolution and the human genome.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview in his car, while en route to a New York
fund-raiser in the Hamptons, he started to explain how Long Island
was formed, then thought better of it and stopped himself. At
another point in the ride, he cried, ``Look at that!'' and pointed
to a sign about an exhibit called `Black Whalers.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know about the black whalers?'' he asked, very excited,
and went on to tell the history of the African-American community
in Sag Harbor, N.Y. ``I'm hoping they can find somewhere for me to
go to church here tomorrow, but my staff wants me to go to a diner
instead,'' he said, making a face. ``Better pictures,'' he added,
and rolled his eyes. (In the end, he did go to the church.)
</P>
<P>
   He seems to have quite a rich emotional life _ is clearly still
over the moon for Tipper, his wife of 30 years, and enviably close
to their four children. By all accounts, he is someone who actually
listens to his friends.
</P>
<P>
   He's also big on small gestures, like having a neatly pressed,
beautifully boxed $5 bill delivered to a consultant, Robert Shrum,
in his London hotel room last year after he lost a bet about
whether another top aide, Carter Eskew, was planning to propose to
his girlfriend. (Gore bet against true love and lost.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, he struggles with the kind of connections that most City
Council members find effortless.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent campaign stop in New York, where he had just
appeared on NBC's  &UR; ` &LR; `Today Show,' &UR; ' &LR;  he was working one end of a
crowd outside Rockefeller Center and TV weather man Al Roker was
working the other. It wasn't a fair match-up, because Roker had a
camera crew in tow, but the crowd did seem more enthusiastic about
meeting the other Al.
</P>
<P>
   Except for one middle-aged woman, who was jumping up and down
and clearly could not wait to greet the vice president. Yet when he
reached her, he not only failed to milk the moment, he raced
through it _ his eyes instinctively, and much too quickly, cutting
to the next person on the rope line, in search of someone who was
not quite as eager to meet him.
</P>
<P>
   At 52, Albert Arnold Gore is without question a complicated man.
He is a native of Washington, where he met the men who ran the
world through his father, Sen. Albert Gore, an up-from-nothing
child of the Depression whose stands for civil rights and against
the Vietnam War were out-of-sync with his Tennessee constituents
and cost him his seat in 1970. Yet young Al Gore had something of a
double life even in the capital, where he attended elite schools
yet dressed in a cousin's hand-me-downs and lived in a four-room
hotel suite because it was owned by a relative who gave his family
a break on the rent.
</P>
<P>
   He is also a real Tennesseean, who spent summers there, working
hard on the family farm, and while there he made his closest
friends, many of whom remain in his life today.
</P>
<P>
   He is someone who prays over meals and quotes the Bible. But he
is also devoted to science, and spends the time he's in the
helicopter en route to Air Force Two reading magazines like Nature,
Science and Discover.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his most deeply felt positions _ in support of both free
trade and the labor unions, for example _ create political
contradictions. And sometimes, he seems to be fighting himself as
much as he is Bush.
</P>
<P>
   He is on the one hand an incredibly careful man, yet at least at
times has been unusually willing to make himself vulnerable, as he
did in writing ``Earth in the Balance,'' a deeply confessional
environmental manifesto in which he ties man's mistreatment of the
environment to a lack of deep connection in dysfunctional families.
</P>
<P>
   One knock against Gore is that he has not shown himself to be
sufficiently human. But it may be that he has shown himself to be
all too human, someone who does sweat the small stuff and is cursed
with a level of self-awareness that does not appear to trouble
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, there was a million-dollar bash in the Hamptons in his
honor. Fireworks were in the offing, but they started badly, and he
had already turned to leave when they suddenly erupted into a
splendid celestial spectacle. Gore wandered out onto the lawn, by
himself, for a better look.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the time, he stood there alone, his silhouette rigid and
even lonely against the blazing night sky. Only when the model
Christie Brinkley playfully started snapping his picture did he
seem to realize he was supposed to look relaxed, like he was having
a good time.
</P>
<P>
   And from remarks he made later, it was clear that he had been
thinking about his quest to become president and whether he was
falling short. As he bid farewell to his hosts and guests, who had
paid $10,000 each to have dinner with him, he drew a pointed
analogy between the initial fizzle of the fireworks and his own
trajectory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that some of you were feeling momentarily disappointed
with the fireworks,'' he said. ``Some of you felt let down. Some
were even heart-broken. But you believed it was going to happen,
and it did. And I know that during this campaign, some of you have
felt like there were times when you wondered how it was going to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
