<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000816.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3757 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-DEM-GORE-BIO-TRANSFOR     08-16 1380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-GORE-BIO-TRANSFORM-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: to go.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On this particular occasion, the vice president pulled himself
back from the brink of further reflection and promised, from then
on, to do better.
</P>
<P>
   But in a life of constant movement and all-too-brief,
``good-to-see-you, good-to-see-you''-type encounters, Gore is an
unusually reflective person, and someone who thinks in a highly
psychological way.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, after his then-6-year-old son ran into the street
and was hit by a car right in front of him, Gore did what one
friend called ``psychotherapy by correspondence course,'' _ trying
to puzzle through his life, typically, by reading and listening to
personal development tapes.
</P>
<P>
   He passed out copies of a couple of the psychological texts he
was especially struck by, including one called ``How People
Change,'' by Allen Wheelis.
</P>
<P>
   In it, the author describes how he developed anxiety attacks as
a result of the summer that his cruelly demanding father made him
cut their lawn with a hand razor. And it is impossible to read it
without thinking of the summer that Gore's own father put him
through an equally pointless character-building exercise, making
him clear 20 hilly acres with a hand ax.
</P>
<P>
   The whole thing would have taken just a few hours with a
bulldozer, as Gore's high-school girlfriend in Tennessee, Donna
Armistead, remembers it. ``One day I stopped by, and he had got in
a nest of hornets. The poor guy was eaten up, but it didn't
matter,'' she said bitterly. ``His dad said it had to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Even now, amid the craziness of the campaign, Gore is a highly
interior person, who can withdraw deep inside himself quite
suddenly. He loved the wild, dark, out-there movie ``Being John
Malkovich.'' As opposed to Bush, who says the last movie he enjoyed
in a theater was ``Forrest Gump.'' One relative describes Gore as
``very edgy'' in a business that does not award a lot of points for
edge.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Gore had seemed happy as a student at Harvard, where he
was after all facing service in Vietnam, his mentor, Neustadt,
said, ``I'd have called him an intellectually interested kid, a
questioning, pondering kid. In social situations, he was pleasant,
and capable of enjoyment, but happy? There were always a lot of
issues Al was concerned about morally. I wouldn't have called him
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet not, it would seem, because he suffers from a lack of
confidence; This is a man who applied only to Harvard because it
never occurred to him that he wouldn't get in. When he became a
newspaper reporter, he seems to have assumed he would follow in the
footsteps of David Halberstam, a friend of his sister's, who had
won a Pulitzer Prize. He ran for Congress at 28 and began mounting
his first presidential campaign only 10 years later. If elected, he
would have been the youngest president in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   He was not ready, as it turned out, and he ended up an observer
in his own campaign, watching his surrogate, New York City Mayor Ed
Koch, fight the Rev. Jesse Jackson, Gore's one friend among other
Democrats in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statements made by Mayor Koch took me by surprise,'' Gore
said in a recent interview. ``I had no advance notice, was not
happy about it and didn't handle it very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Gore himself had snidely knocked Jackson, saying the country
was electing a president, not a preacher. Then he was overwhelmed
with guilt, horrified in particular by the racial implications of
the ongoing Koch-Jackson feud that he should have been aware of
when he sought an alliance with Koch. In the campaign's final days,
Gore was asking Jackson's forgiveness on an almost daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   Why would anyone have believed they were ready at that age?
</P>
<P>
   Gore had been a virtual grown-up since he was a kid, expected to
perform in the company of important adults. He had seen the
nation's leaders up close, and had not been daunted.
</P>
<P>
   In his first Senate term, which began in 1985, he was already
bored. And he simply could not wait to lead, he said, to take the
country where he felt it ought to go.
</P>
<P>
   His father was pushing him, even playing on his emotions by
saying he wanted to see his boy elected president before he died.
But aides say he was at least as influenced by the simple
availability of cash from the party's money men, once it became
clear that neither Gov. Mario Cuomo of New York nor Sen. Dale
Bumpers of Arkansas would make the race in 1988. And Gore's head
was turned by the media _ Washington reporters who in those days
could not get enough of him.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite two years after he was elected to the Senate, talk
show host John McLaughlin said to Gore during a television
interview: ``You've got the magical name _ Al Gore. Your father was
in Congress for 32 years. You've got character, you've got no clay
feet, no skeletons showing. You're intelligent. You're
well-informed. You've got a Vietnam War record. You've been an
investigative reporter, and you've got religious coloration, too.
</P>
<P>
   For one year you were a divinity student, and you're a devout
Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   You're almost too good to be true. Are you too good to be
true?''
</P>
<P>
   (Gore's answer, for the record: ``I don't know.'')
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's impeachment and Gore's own role in the fund-raising
scandals of recent years took care of that perception, of course.
And he can't say his mother hadn't warned him.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the mid-'80s, Dr. James Fleming, a Nashville physician
who was a friend of Gore's sister's and for a time the family
doctor, remembers a conversation at the family farm in Carthage
about then-Governor Clinton, who had just visited Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's mother, Pauline LaFon Gore, who like his father had grown
up poor and put herself through law school, has often been
considered the political brains in the family. And on this
occasion, she was adamant. ``She said he had bad moral character,''
Fleming said. ``She said, `Bill Clinton is not a nice person. You
shouldn't associate too closely with him.'''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Gore went on the ticket with Clinton, he says,
characteristically, because he thought he could help: ``I thought I
could make a difference, and maybe THE difference.''
</P>
<P>
   And he makes it clear that he believed his mother, and feels
superior to Clinton in certain ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy's done a great job, by and large, and has strengths I
don't,'' he said in the car the other day. ``But then, I have
strengths he doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, he added a line to his stump speech. ``I won't let you
down.'' The subtext being, of course: Unlike some presidents I
could name.
</P>
<P>
   But the phrase also reflects an important truth about Gore, who
was made responsible for his parents' hopes from an early age. He
was raised not to let his family down, and often talks about his
work and his life in a way that suggests he defines himself as
someone people are depending on.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's trying to be a good night watchman,'' said a Gore
relative. ``That's the kind of president he would be.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet because of his ambivalence about politics, in some past
races he has seemed focused only in the final stages of the
campaign, on deadline, like the former news reporter he is. There
is typically a last-minute flurry of ``new Al Gore'' stories,
detailing his metamorphosis from lackluster to ``newly energized''
campaigner. And aides certainly hope they see that beginning now,
as he bonds with his running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   On Long Island the other day, Gore said his own theory about the
many stories that begin, ``In yet another attempt to reinvent
himself today ...'' is that reporters sense that he is discarding
the vice presidential voice they have heard him speaking in for
nearly eight years and hear his newly presidential voice ``as
trying to be something they don't think I am.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel a dissonance that shows up in their interpretation
of what I say, how I look, my mannerisms. What they see is very
different from what they're certain I am. I'm not being dishonest,
though, and neither are they.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't stay that way, though,'' he predicted. ``Whether
people who go through it admit it or not, it's a growth
experience,'' he said, referring to the wild ride of a presidential
run. ``It's a transformative process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
