<SLUG> BC-CANADA-TOURISM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUISE SHIP TOURISM REVITALIZES NEWFOUNDLAND AND OTHER ATLANTIC
PROVINCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. JOHN'S, Newfoundland _ In the workaday harbor here, normally
plied by tugs, tankers and freighters laid up for repairs, Le
Levant offered a startling contrast on a recent day: a sleek French
cruise ship disgorging 50 affluent American tourists.
</P>
<P>
   To welcome the first visitors of Newfoundland's late-summer
cruise season, two young women in redcoat colonial uniforms played
flutes on the quay, and Sailor, a huge Newfoundland dog, wagged his
tail enthusiastically.
</P>
<P>
   Here on Canada's easternmost island, the scheduled arrival of 15
tourist ships this season is part of a larger psychological and
economic turnaround for a province often compared with Ireland, the
ancestral home of many of its 540,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Newfoundland has been Canada's poorest province, a
steady exporter of brain and brawn and a heavy importer of
financial aid from Ottawa. But echoing Ireland's recent experience,
Newfoundland recorded Canada's highest growth rate last year, 5.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Oil revenues are eating away at Newfoundland's need for federal
aid; a thriving crab and lobster fishing industry is replacing the
500-year experience with cod; and Newfoundland, with its coves and
quiet, is becoming a magnet for tourists. After stagnating for a
decade, tourism jumped by 50 percent over the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990s were the boom years for cruise ships in the Pacific
waters of British Columbia and Alaska. In the new decade, Americans
are discovering Atlantic Canada, from Nova Scotia to Newfoundland
to Labrador, and north into the eastern Arctic.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, 150,000 people, almost all Americans, are expected
to take cruises into Canada's eastern provinces, a sevenfold
increase since 1995. Halifax, Nova Scotia, the region's most
popular port of call, has reservations this season for 102 ships,
double the number in 1998. In Montreal, the number of passengers
disembarking at docks of the Old Port neighborhood is expected to
hit 38,000 this summer, double last year's level. Most of the
Atlantic Canada cruises start in Boston and New York.
</P>
<P>
   On Canada's Pacific Coast, British Columbia expects three times
as many cruise passengers as in Atlantic Canada. But if present
trends continue, by the end of this decade cruise traffic on the
two coasts will be roughly even, with 1 million cruise ship
passengers each summer turning Canadian waters into the Caribbean
of the north.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide, to capture future waves of retiring baby boomers,
cruise ship companies anticipate growth and have ordered 60 new
ships, worth $24 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means the cruise industry is going to be looking for new
destinations,'' said Gordon Slade, chief executive of the
Cruiseship Authority of Newfoundland and Labrador, a new
public-private entity here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our niche is really the adventure cruising,'' he said. ``We
offer what Alaska offers _ whales, seabirds and fjords. But we also
have what Alaska doesn't have _ the moving ice, icebergs.''
</P>
<P>
   Slade was down at the quay here to greet the French ship, which
had steamed from St. Pierre and Miquelon, two French islands off
the southwest coast of Newfoundland.
</P>
<P>
   Jan E. Robinson, a 45-year-old federal employee from Los
Angeles, greeted Sailor, the dog, and set off for sightseeing on
Water Street, which the city claims to be the oldest street in
North America. On her return, she pronounced St. John's, which
dates back to the mid-1500s, ``a beautiful city _ if I could figure
out how to come back, I would do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert W. Burgess, a 68-year-old retired manufacturer from
Massachusetts who was traveling with his wife, Nancy, was blunt
about why they were here. After 12 cruises, he said, ``we're
running out of places to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 1.1 million American tourists visited Atlantic
Canada, a record number that undoubtedly was lifted higher by the
lure of the weak Canadian dollar.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Americans are pretty free with their money,'' said Ernest
Gosse, a taxi driver who makes a point of circling by Harbour
Avenue when a cruise ship is in port. ``Last summer, I had one lady
who bought a little dory boat, a couple of sweaters for her
grandkids and two replicas of Viking ships.''
</P>
<P>
   Spurring North American interest in the Rock, as Newfoundlanders
affectionately call their island, are a number of recent novels,
most notably ``The Shipping News'' (Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster), a
novel by E. Annie Proulx that won a Pulitzer Prize in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Newfoundland is not well known _ this puts us out there,''
Slade, the cruise ship promoter, said of the book. ``More people
read it outside the province than inside the province. First person
I talked to who had read the book was from Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   For the cruise industry really to take off, St. John's, a
metropolitan area of 150,000 people, needs a way for people to fly
from Europe and the United States and then to take the cruise ships
one way.
</P>
<P>
   Canadians have been demanding an end to laws that restrict
flights between Canadian cities to Canadian airlines. An end to
such restrictions would clear the way for international flights to
stop here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canada should consider real airline competition,'' said Brian
Tobin, premier of Newfoundland and Labrador, in an interview. ``We
are not prepared to be quaint little Newfoundland, shrouded in the
mists of time, so Air Canada can be a monopoly for the next 50
years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
