<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORK-EUROPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S., FEARING SWINE FEVER IN BRITAIN, BANS IMPORTS
</HEADLINE>
  By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The United States ordered a temporary ban on swine
imports from Britain on Wednesday, joining several European
countries that acted after the discovery of swine fever in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The episode has evoked memories of Britain's battle with mad cow
disease, and rattled Britain's livestock traders once again.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are at their wits' end,'' said James Black, vice
chairman of the National Pig Association, an industry group whose
mood had just begun to recover after a two-year slump in prices.
</P>
<P>
   Swine fever is highly contagious, but is not considered a threat
to humans.
</P>
<P>
   The bans on British shipments of live pigs, pig semen and other
products follow the discovery of swine fever on farms in the East
Anglia region of southeast England. The outbreak is the first in 14
years.
</P>
<P>
   Swine fever is usually controlled only by the destruction of
infected animals. Thousands of animals have already been
slaughtered.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike mad cow disease _ bovine spongiform encephalopathy _
swine fever is not thought to threaten humans. Mad cow disease has
been linked in Britain to a similar ailment in humans,
Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, that has claimed around 50 victims in
this country and caused huge economic losses in British
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Hallie Pickhardt, a spokeswoman for the U.S. Agriculture
Department, said the department had ``placed a hold'' on all swine
imports from Britain. She said that U.S. officials were working
closely with their British counterparts to assess the extent of the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the United States imported just $11 million worth of
British pork products, a tiny amount of its total pork imports.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday the European Union, of which Britain is a member,
banned the importation of live pigs and porcine semen from England
to prevent swine fever from spreading to European herds, some of
which were decimated by outbreaks of the disease in the Netherlands
and Germany between 1997 and 1998. Like the United States, Spain
went further and outlawed imports of pig meat.
</P>
<P>
   British officials are trying to persuade European officials in
Brussels to limit the ban to live pigs from the East Anglia region.
</P>
<P>
   For many Britons, the ban has recalled the three-year duel
between Britain and the European Union over exports of British
beef, which was imposed in 1996 and finally lifted one year ago,
except in France. The beef ban stirred deep resentments among those
Britons opposed to what they saw as a meddlesome and hostile
European bureaucracy in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   The pig ban threatened to widen Thursday. A big supermarket
chain, ASDA, which is owned by Wal-Mart Stores Inc., has threatened
to take Belgian pate off its shelves in response to the European
action. An ASDA spokeswoman called the threat ''a symbolic
gesture.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 1935EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000816.0307 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3770 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-DEMS-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      08-16 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE MUST PUT MEMORABLE WORDS ON CROWNING MOMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ He's serious-minded. He's intelligent. He's
well-prepared. But for the challenge that Al Gore faces here, none
of that may matter.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night he claims a presidential nomination he has
yearned to capture for years. It would be a moment of high emotion
for any political figure, but is especially stirring for Gore. This
is the prize that has mesmerized, teased, and eluded, two
generations of men named Albert Gore.
</P>
<P>
   And so now Gore, a careful student of politics and an erudite
connoisseur of the political moment, knows the Democratic
presidential nomination requires a difficult bargain. Now that it
is being given to him, he must do what seems more difficult for him
than for most nominees: give himself entirely to it.
</P>
<P>
   In the American political tradition, that means delivering a
convention acceptance speech that is, alternatively, rousing,
poignant, inspiring _ and insightful. But the insights that
successful nominees bring to their acceptance speeches are
transmitted quietly, subtly _ and, above all, personally.
Successful convention speeches aren't full of the candidate's
insights. Successful convention speeches prompt listeners to gain
insights about the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   That is Gore's challenge, and his difficulty. He has been part
of the political wallpaper for eight years. He is, like the
Hollywood billboards here advertising a new fall-season film,
``Almost Famous''; the public thinks there is nothing new to learn
about him. And the unusual nature of his opponent, Governor George
W. Bush _ whose very appeal comes from his likeability and his
ability to skim blithely above the surface of things _ makes this
task all the more arduous. To draw a distinction between himself
and the GOP nominee, Gore almost always succumbs to the temptation
to show his command of the material, his mastery of detail.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presidency is not an academic exercise,'' Gore told former
Senator Bill Bradley of New Jersey during the winter primaries. The
line, which was crafted by Gore's daughter, was a devastating
critique of Gore's Democratic rival. But its lesson hasn't been
fully learned by Gore himself.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Democratic Convention here has had a vaguely
academic whiff to it, more like a seminar than a revival meeting.
For three days, the podium has been full of a parade of earnest
speakers, full of just the sort of specificity that was absent two
weeks ago in Philadelphia. The speeches about health care have been
full of statistics. The talks about Social Security have been full
of projections. There have even been panels of citizens and public
officials holding dialogues about issues.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the message rumbling out of Los Angeles so far has
been a blur _ lots of small type, no big headline. Wittingly or
unwittingly, the convention is a remarkable reflection of the
candidate the party is putting forward in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Now the convention reaches a new, critical stage, requiring Gore
to alter substantially the entire tone and focus of the proceedings
_ and of the public's view of himself.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has spent the last five months reaching for America's mind.
Thursday night he must touch its heart. He is perhaps the leading
debater in American public life today. Thursday night that skill is
of little use. An acceptance speech is not a debate. It is won more
often with poignancy than on points.
</P>
<P>
   The phrase ``New Frontier,'' outlined in an outdoor acceptance
speech here 40 years ago, helped propel John F. Kennedy to the
White House. When Bill Clinton, born in the tiny community of Hope,
Ark., told the 1992 Democratic convention in New York that he still
believed ``in a place called Hope,'' he stirred the nation _ and
the glow from that moment remained with the Clinton and Gore team
as they rode the backroads of America in their famous bus trips.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's task is much like President George H.W. Bush's in 1988.
Like Gore, Bush was vice president to a two-term president. Like
Gore, Bush was regarded as a pale imitation of the president. Like
Gore, Bush was familiar _ but largely unknown. And so he told the
New Orleans convention: ``Now you must see me for what I am: the
Republican candidate for president....And now I turn to the
American people to share my hopes and intentions, and why and where
I wish to lead.''
</P>
<P>
   All week a sense of anticipation has filled the Staples Center,
where delegates have exchanged pleasantries and political gossip.
The delegates expected a strong valedictory from the president and
they got it. They expected a series of appearances from party
luminaries and they got them. They expected an uplifting address
Wednesday night from Senator Joseph I. Lieberman of Connecticut,
the Democrats' vice presidential candidate, and they got that, too.
</P>
<P>
   They aren't quite sure what to expect from Gore, but they know
what they need from him.
</P>
<P>
   They know that he is behind in the polls. They know that he has
political skills. They know that he has to speak in a different
idiom, to a different audience, and for a different purpose, than
anything he has ever attempted before. And they know one thing
more: that the outcome of the election may depend in no small
measure on that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 1937EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
