</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jewish Center Festival highlights writers' fall tour
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fall is traditionally the biggest season in publishing. It's
also become a prime time for literary festivals. In the next three
months, dozens of authors will descend on Atlanta, Nashville and
several other Southern cities to hawk their latest books and
dispense wisdom to aspiring writers and fans.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's major literary event this fall will be the Marcus
Jewish Community Center Book Festival, to be held Nov. 11-20.
Headliners include Alan Dershowitz (``The Genesis of Justice''),
Peter Bogdanovich (``Peter Bogdanovich's Movie of the Week''),
Barry Scheck (``Actual Innocence''), and Ellen Goodman and Patricia
O'Brien (``I Know Just What You Mean: The Power of Friendship in
Women's Lives''). A mystery panel will feature Phillip Margolin
(``Wild Justice''), David Liss (``A Conspiracy of Paper'') and
Phyllis Richman (``Murder on the Gravy Train''). All events will be
held at the center, 5342 Tilly Mill Road, Dunwoody, 770-396-3250.
</P>
<P>
   Other big literary events this fall:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  William Styron and more than 200 other writers will be on hand
Oct. 13-15 for the Southern Festival of Books in Nashville.
Readings and panel discussions will feature Ha Jin, Clyde Edgerton,
Terry Kay, Josephine Humphreys, William Least Heat-Moon and others.
Most events are free. Information:
www.tn-humanities.org/sfbmain.htm.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Authors William Harris (``Delirium of the Brave'') and Steve
Harvey (``Bound for Shady Grove'') will conduct workshops at the
one-day Northeast Georgia Writers Conference in Gainesville on Oct.
14. Topics include breaking into Hollywood, creating suspense,
writing for children, creating a memoir and writing nonfiction.
Luncheon speaker Mary Rose Taylor, director of the Margaret
Mitchell House &AMP; Museum, will discuss the author of ``Gone With the
Wind.'' Conference fees are $59 for nonmembers, $20 students.
Information: 770-534-6715.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The first Georgia Book and Art Festival is scheduled for Oct.
21 at the Bailey-Tebault Historical House in Griffin. The daylong
event will feature Townsend Prize winner JoAllen Bradham (``Some
Personal Papers''), Herb Bridges (``Gone With the Wind: A
Definitive History'') and 30 other authors signing their books. An
art show and exhibit will showcase the works of 20 artists.
Admission: $5 for adults, children free. Information: 770-943-5699
or www.georgiawriters.org/book&AMP;artfestival.htm.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Winston Groom (``Forrest Gump'') will be the keynote speaker
at the Lost State Writer's Conference in Greeneville, Tenn., Sept.
21-24 at the General Morgan Inn. Individual critiques of
manuscripts are also offered. The cost for a 30-minute session is
$60 for writers registered by Sept. 10 or $75 for those registering
after that date. Register online at loststatewriters.xtn.net. Or
call 423-636-6738.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail:dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
