<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohioan goes from teaching to being Cowboys' placekicker
 &HT;    By Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas - Tim Seder gave up nearly everything in
his personal and professional life to become the Dallas Cowboys'
placekicker.
</P>
<P>
   Seder quit his teaching job in Ohio, indefinitely left his wife,
traveled 1,000 miles to a new city, rented a studio apartment,
found a roommate and kicked a football until the Cowboys were
satisfied they had their man.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Seder was a three-sport coach at Lucas High School in
Mansfield, Ohio. When he returned home from basketball practice one
day in the dead of winter, his life took a dramatic change.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I walked in the house, my wife said I'd better listen to
the answering machine,'' Seder said Wednesday during a break at
training camp.
</P>
<P>
   The call was from Steve Hoffman, kicking coach for the Cowboys.
There was a job opening in Dallas, and Hoffman wanted the
25-year-old teacher to apply. The salary and perks were good ...
but there was a catch.
</P>
<P>
   Seder's chances of making the squad were about 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Seder temporarily kissed his wife Melissa goodbye and followed
his dream of playing in the NFL. Who would have figured that
someone from tiny Ashland University who had not played competitive
football in three years would be offered that type of a deal?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not Seder.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the NFL was concerned, I never thought I'd have a
shot to kick,'' Seder said. ``I thought I was going to be coaching,
and I was striving to become better at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Seder's first tryout for Hoffman was memorable. Seder walked
into Texas Stadium with old soccer shoes that had holes on the
sides. When Hoffman asked him about his style of footwear, Seder
quietly said, ``That's all I got, coach.''
</P>
<P>
   When Seder's first kicked missed badly, Hoffman rolled his eyes,
wondering how he could make such a mistake. Seder responded by
nailing several in a row, all with tremendous height and distance.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman's hunch about Seder was starting to look good.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Cowboys called, Seder had never sniffed an NFL team.
He was not drafted after finishing college three years ago. He was
never a free agent. No team gave him much thought until Hoffman did
some research.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman, the NFL's only full-time kicking coach, was sorting
through a stack of nearly 200 videos when he came across a dark and
grainy tape of Seder kicking a football in a high school gym.
Former Ashland assistant coach Dave Jaumotte, now with the Detroit
Lions, told Hoffman at the 1998 NFL combine in Indianapolis that he
knew of a kicker _ Seder _ with great potential.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman contacted Seder and requested a tape. Seder's kicking
technique was good, Hoffman recalled, but the Cowboys were already
satisfied with their kicker, Richie Cunningham. So Seder's tape was
thrown into a stack with dozens of others.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman laughs when he talks about the tapes he receives almost
daily. He has tapes of kickers from Arizona State, Washington and
Michigan, not to mention England and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman's favorite came from a man who attempted 50-yard field
goals on a rainy afternoon. The kicker's young sons chased the
footballs. The ball always landed short of the goal post, splashing
in a mud puddle in the end zone. That tape no longer is part of
Hoffman's stack.
</P>
<P>
   Seder's story is important because the Cowboys entered training
camp without an experienced kicker on their roster. After two good
years, Cunningham lost his accuracy _ and his confidence _ midway
through the 1999 season. Veteran Eddie Murray finished the season,
but the Cowboys began to search for a young kicker who would make
the league minimum, $193,000.
</P>
<P>
   Seder performed well at a minicamp in April, earning himself a
spot on the summer roster, and became the No. 1 kicker when the
Cowboys released his only challenger, Rian Lindell, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The deeply religious Seder said he is ``blessed'' to be with the
Cowboys. When he signs autographs after practice, he writes Bible
scriptures about trust and confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Seder credits Hoffman for his early success with the Cowboys.
Among his adjustments, Seder has removed a ``hop-step'' on his
kicking approach to provide better balance.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman and Coach Dave Campo said Seder's ability is matched
only by his confidence. He has made three of four field goals
during preseason games _ his only miss was from 58 yards _ and
earned the job by outkicking Lindell in practice.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the hard part. Nothing really matters until the Sept.
3 openeout those two topics in our society. We love to be
titillated, but we chastise those who titillate us. We have one of
the biggesa dysfunctional family fighting its way to destruction.
Charlene, who writes women's erotica to support her 16-year-old
daughter and 14-year-old son, is both attracted to and repelled by
Clyde, who can't seem to leave her alone despite court papers
orderineir parents. The play also offers two other voices: a woman
whose dialogue represents Charlene's inner thoughts and a man who
represents a variety of characters, including the male part of
Charlene and the fears that Clyde has instilled in her.
</P>
<P>
   May, o all of us by the throat. A lot of people don't want to
see a play about domestic violence. That's why the humor is so
important.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   CLYDE: I used to think that porno flicks were all pictures and
no words _
</P>
<P>
   CHARLENE: Look, Clyde. I dt.
</P>
<P>
   CLYDE: Well, what do you call it? What was the title of your
last opus? ``Sperms of Endearment?!'' So what is that _ Bergman?
</P>
<P>
   CHARLENE: It's my homage to Jack Nicholson.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
