<P>
   Hulk Hogan sues over televised barbs
</P>
<P>
   By Jim Dyer
</P>
<P>
   c. 2000 Cox News Service s personal, unscripted, and, according
to Hogan, defamatory.
</P>
<P>
   The blond-locked behemoth, considered by many as the ``Babe the
words of Vince Russo, creative director of the World Championship
Wrestling Inc., in Smyrna, ``placed (Hogan) in a false light'' and
damaged his character and image.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't part of the script,'' said Hogan's lawyer, John
Taylor, of Atlanta, who adamantly denied the lawsuit was part of a
publicity stunt This is a real lawsuit,'' he said. ``What (Russo)
said was defamatory and a breach of contract.'' Worse yet, he
added, Hulk's children were in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan's match had been the featured ``main event'' at the July 9
spectacle in Daytona Beach, Fla. Russo changed the order of the
matches, then ordered Hogan's refuse to fight Hogan, the lawsuit
claims.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan, who won by default, left the ring with the title but was
immediately followed by Russo, who began disparaging him to the
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``All day long I'm playing politics with Hulk Hogan, because
Hulk Hogan wants to play his creative control card,'' Russo told a
national television audience, according to transcripts of his
speech contained in the lawsuit. Russo, who called Hogan a ``big
bald son of a -----,'' implied Hogan is dishonest, undeserving of
the title belt, and unworthy of respect from wrestling fans, claims
the suit, which seeks unspecified damages. WCW spokesman Alan Sharp
declined comment on the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Russo's commelawsuit, who must explore the fine line between
``scripted'' insults that are entertainment and ``unscripted''
insults that may be defamatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very unique legal issues,'' said Henry Holmes, Hogan's
personal attorney in Beverly Hills, Calif.
</P>
