<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-GORE-BIO-TRANSFORM-ABRIDGED-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN INDUSTRIOUS AND INTELLIGENT MAN STILL SEEKING TO DEFINE
HIMSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: A full-length version, DEM-GORE is also being filed.)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER and KATHARINE Q. SEELYE  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After Al Gore ran for president in 1988 and lost, just as he
turned 40, he organized a series of dinners where he went around
the room and asked each person to tell him where he had gone wrong.
What hadn't he known? What hadn't he done?
</P>
<P>
   It was excruciating, his friends said, but he insisted on
hearing the bad news _ in detail _ about a campaign that had begun
as an environmental crusade and ended as a New York food fight. He
heard that he had no economic vision and that he had talked about
technology and the environment in ways that people could not
understand. Oh, and his speaking style needed a ton of work.
</P>
<P>
   Gore responded, as he always has, by going back to school. He
put together a graduate seminar for one, complete with a syllabus
and a heavy-duty reading list, and applied himself to the serious
study of tax policy and business history. He brought in a
mathematician to explain chaos theory. And he hired a speech
consultant and a dance coach _ ``a ballet type,'' he told one
friend _ to help him move more fluidly.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians often learn from and are even transformed by a
drubbing at the polls, but few have pursued their lessons as
aggressively as Gore. The man who will accept the Democratic
Party's presidential nomination Thursday night has diligently
readied himself.
</P>
<P>
   Yet all this extensive preparation has not showed in the Gore
campaign, which at least until recently has seemed surprisingly
unfocused. While Gore been training to govern from quite a young
age, he has always had mixed feelings about the path to power that
is politics.
</P>
<P>
   He is a student by nature _ even after Vietnam, he treated his
moral hangover with a year of divinity school, saying he wanted to
impose some structure on the exercise. His extraordinary
willingness to learn and change has taught him much, but it has
also exposed him to the charge that he is constantly reinventing
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Reinvention isn't all bad. In 1981, when Gore was concerned
about the Cold War, he turned himself into an arms-control expert
in a single year by plunging into the arcana of a subject he had
previously known almost nothing about. In the '90s, he got way out
front in learning about issues that no one else was paying much
mind, like information technology and global warming.
</P>
<P>
   ``His education is ongoing,'' said his Harvard friend Tommy Lee
Jones, the actor. ``Where 20 years ago he would have made outlines
with Roman numerals, now it would look like rectangles on top of
each other, equally well-organized but not so linear, and probably
three-dimensional.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet this quality has caused trouble for Gore in the current
campaign, mostly noted through small but symbolic personal
alterations, like his new Palm Pilot and his switch from dark suits
to earth tones _ changes that are insignificant in themselves, but
resonate because they remind many people of the way he has shifted
on some key issues, particularly gun control and abortion.
</P>
<P>
   It is the same story with his work ethic. As a senator, Gore was
so determined to shoehorn extra work into his day that during
weekends of back-to-back town hall meetings he would get himself
booked in two places at the same time _ a trick that was possible,
barely, because Tennessee straddles two time zones.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is someone who makes all his hard work look like ... hard
work. Lacking the smooth moves of either his boss, Bill Clinton, or
his Republican opponent, George W. Bush, Gore is a plodder, who
hopes to be a tortoise to Bush's hare.
</P>
<P>
   But there's more going on than raw effort. Gore's intellect and
the willingness to use it are probably his most important assets.
His oldest daughter, Karenna Gore Schiff, said: ``He likes to ask,
`What's the assumption here? What if we subvert it?' and one of the
things he could maybe do well if he wins the job is make new
connections, like between the economy and the environment, and ask,
`What if we were the leading exporter of ways to clean up the
environment?'''
</P>
<P>
   Those are not the kind of connections that crowds thrill to,
though. All Gore's smarts do not necessarily translate into an
ability to sway the public with feeling, as well as facts _ as he
is all too aware.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is genuinely in love with the world of ideas, loves nothing
more than a good kibbitz about the multiverse, and apparently sees
how fractal geometry might improve our lives.
</P>
<P>
   He is a sucker for fun facts, too _ and always alert for
openings to share them. During his campaign visits to schools, he
has delivered spontaneous lectures on the Ice Ages, the Industrial
Revolution and the human genome.
</P>
<P>
   At 52, Albert Arnold Gore is without question a complicated man.
He is a native of Washington, where he met the men who ran the
world through his father, Sen. Albert Gore, an up-from-nothing
child of the Depression whose stands for civil rights and against
the Vietnam War were out-of-sync with his Tennessee constituents
and cost him his seat in 1970. Yet young Al Gore had something of a
double life even in the capital, where he attended elite schools
yet dressed in a cousin's hand-me-downs and lived in a four-room
hotel suite because it was owned by a relative who gave his family
a break on the rent.
</P>
<P>
   He is also a real Tennesseean, who spent summers there, working
hard on the family farm, and while there made his closest friends,
many of whom remain in his life today.
</P>
<P>
   He is someone who prays over meals and quotes the Bible. But he
is also devoted to science, and spends the time he's in the
helicopter en route to Air Force Two reading magazines like Nature,
Science and Discover.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his most deeply felt positions _ in support of both free
trade and the labor unions, for example _ create political
contradictions. And sometimes, he seems to be fighting himself as
much as he is Bush.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He is on the one hand an incredibly careful man, yet at least at
times has been unusually willing to make himself vulnerable, as he
did in writing ``Earth in the Balance,'' a deeply confessional
environmental manifesto in which he ties man's mistreatment of the
environment to a lack of deep connection in dysfunctional families.
</P>
<P>
   One knock against Gore is that he has not shown himself to be
sufficiently human. But it may be that he has shown himself to be
all too human, someone who does sweat the small stuff and is cursed
with a level of self-awareness that does not appear to trouble
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Even amid the campaign, Gore is a highly interior person, who
can withdraw deep inside himself quite suddenly. He loved the wild,
dark, out-there movie ``Being John Malkovich.'' (Bush had said that
the last movie he enjoyed in a theater was ``Forrest Gump.'')
</P>
<P>
   Gore does not suffer from a lack of confidence; he is a man who
applied only to Harvard because it never occurred to him that he
wouldn't get in. When he became a newspaper reporter, he seems to
have assumed he would follow in the footsteps of David Halberstam,
a friend of his sister's, who had won a Pulitzer Prize. He ran for
Congress at 28 and began mounting his first presidential campaign
only 10 years later. If elected, he would have been the youngest
president in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore was not ready in 1988, and he ended up an observer in
his own campaign, watching his surrogate, New York City Mayor Ed
Koch, fight the Rev. Jesse Jackson, Gore's one friend among other
Democrats in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statements made by Mayor Koch took me by surprise,'' Gore
said in a recent interview. ``I had no advance notice, was not
happy about it and didn't handle it very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Gore himself had snidely knocked Jackson, saying the country
was electing a president, not a preacher. Then he was overwhelmed
with guilt, horrified in particular by the racial implications of
the Koch-Jackson feud, that he should have been aware of when he
sought an alliance with Koch. In the campaign's final days, Gore he
was asking Jackson's forgiveness on an almost daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   Gore had been a virtual grown-up since he was a kid, expected to
perform in the company of important adults. He had seen the
nation's leaders up close, and had not been daunted.
</P>
<P>
   In his first Senate term, which began in 1985, he was already
bored. And he simply could not wait to lead, he said, to take the
country where he felt it ought to go.
</P>
<P>
   His father was pushing him, even playing on his emotions by
saying he wanted to see his boy elected president before he died.
But aides say he was at least as influenced by the simple
availability of cash from the party's money men, once it became
clear that neither Gov. Mario Cuomo of New York nor Sen. Dale
Bumpers of Arkansas would make the race in 1988. And Gore's head
was turned by the media _ Washington reporters who in those days
could not get enough of him.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite two years after he was elected to the Senate, the talk
show host John McLaughlin said to Gore during a television
interview:
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got the magical name _ Al Gore. Your father was in
Congress for 32 years. You've got character, you've got no clay
feet, no skeletons showing. You're intelligent. You're
well-informed. You've got a Vietnam War record. You've been an
investigative reporter, and you've got religious coloration, too.
For one year you were a divinity student, and you're a devout
Baptist. You're almost too good to be true. Are you too good to be
true?''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's answer: ``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's impeachment and Gore's own role in the fund-raising
scandals of recent years took care of that perception, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy's done a great job, by and large, and has strengths I
don't,'' Gore said of Clinton in a recent interview. ``But then, I
have strengths he doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Gore added a line to his stump speech. ``I won't let
you down.'' The subtext being, of course: Unlike some presidents I
could name.
</P>
<P>
   But the phrase also reflects an important truth about Gore, who
was made responsible for his parents' hopes from an early age. He
was raised not to let his family down, and often talks about his
work and his life in a way that suggests he defines himself as
someone people are depending on.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's trying to be a good night watchman,'' said a Gore
relative. ``That's the kind of president he would be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
