<SLUG> BC-AGGIE-INJURY0817-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A&AMP;M defensive end out for the seasonBy Randy Riggs
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Defensive end, not a deep position for Texas A&AMP;M
anyway, became even more shallow Wednesday with the announcement
that starting left end Rocky Bernard will be lost for the season
with a torn anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard, a senior whose 22 career starts rank fourth among Aggie
defensive veterans, was injured in a noncontact drill in practice
Tuesday. A&AMP;M officials said he will have surgery within a week to
10 days. Bernard has another year of eligibility remaining because
he has never redshirted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed,'' said Bernard, a 275-pounder from
Baytown Sterling who had four sacks last year. ``I was looking
forward to my senior year, but I will bounce back. I've learned
it's not the bad things that happen to you, but how you respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Junior Evan Perroni, who pressed Bernard for the starting job in
the spring, will move up. But A&AMP;M's depth at defensive end was
shaky even before Bernard's injury.
</P>
<P>
   It began in the spring when Lonnie Madison was moved from
defensive end to tight end because of concerns over projected
starter Michael de la Torre's recovery from a back injury. Then in
late May, defensive end Terry Nichols was killed in an automobile
accident in El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Highly regarded sophomore Ty Warren is the only experienced
backup, but he remains penciled in behind Ronald Flemons at right
end. A&AMP;M also has two true freshmen defensive linemen _ Marcus
Jasmin of New Orleans and Linnis Smith of Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to adjust and move forward because this really
hurts our depth,'' Coach R.C. Slocum said. ``This is a big
disappointment for us. Rocky had worked hard this summer and we
were counting on him being one of our leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
