<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE READY WITH DETAIL-FILLED SPEECH
 &HT;    By KEN FOSKETT
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Vice President Gore claims the spotlight for his
own Thursday night and delivers a speech accepting the Democratic
nomination for president that he promises will be part biography,
part vision and long on detail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they deserve specifics,'' Gore said aboard Air Force
Two en route to Los Angeles Wednesday. ``I think they deserve a
clear discussion of what the alternatives are and what we need to
do to move our country in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Three months in the making, Gore's speech will conclude the
convention and launch Gore into the fall campaign against Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas. The speech also marks the culmination of a
quest that Gore first began in 1988 when he ran and lost the
Democratic nomination for president.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly eight years as the junior partner to a popular
president, Thursday night's speech will be Gore's opportunity to
emerge from under Clinton's wing and claim the prize he has sought
for so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to it,'' Gore declared. ``This is a speech
that I have written, and I will deserve the credit or the blame.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore arrived in Los Angeles Wednesday after 10 days of
campaigning in key swing states. Standing in an airport hanger in
Burbank with his wife, Tipper, and running mate, Sen. Joe
Lieberman, D-Conn., Gore pumped his fists in the air and said he
was ``looking forward to addressing the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, he and Lieberman spoke before delegates from their home
states of Tennessee and Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   With Gore trailing Bush in most polls, there is considerable
pressure on Gore to deliver a strong address that galvanizes
Democrats and attracts undecided voters to his ticket.
</P>
<P>
   If Gore felt any of the pressure himself, he did not show it
Wednesday. Gore said he he had more ``butterflies'' about the
speeches that daughters Karenna and Kristin were scheduled to
deliver Wednesday than his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very relaxed about it,'' said Gore. ``I'm not
nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore will attempt to use his moment in the national spotlight to
show voters how his life experiences have shaped his commitment to
public service, senior Gore aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will also make a pledge to hold regular town hall meetings
both before the November elections and if he ascends to the White
House as a way to ``engage people in the spirit of democracy,''
said Chris Lehane, Gore's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   While calling the speech positive in tone, aides said Gore will
seek to contrast his proposals for Social Security and middle-class
tax cuts with those of Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people will get out of it is a clear idea of where he is
going to take the country,'' Lehane said. ``For the most part, this
is a very future-oriented speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Gerston, a political scientist at San Jose State
University, said Gore must excite more Democrats over his candidacy
and reach out to moderate and swing voters who haven't yet made up
their minds about Gore or Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to solidify the base of Democratic voters, to show
Democrats why he is just as good as Clinton,'' Gerston said.
Without trying to emulate Clinton, Gore has to at least convince
voters that he share's Clinton's compassion and sympathy for
people, Gerston said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing Al Gore could do is try to be Bill Clinton,''
he said. ``Because nobody can be as good.''
</P>
<P>
   Convention delegates, who Gore is relying on to provide energy
for the fall campaign, said they were anxious for Gore to step on
to the stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest hope is that he will come across as the charismatic
person he is rather than what he is seen as today,'' said Kim
Caridas, a union representative from Ohio. ``I think that would
help more than (addressing) the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he began conceptualizing his speech three months ago,
using easels and poster board to outline the themes he wanted to
address. Gore did not actually begin writing his speech until two
weeks ago, when he vacationed in North Carolina during the
Republican convention.
</P>
<P>
   Since the first draft was written, Gore continued to focus the
message and winnow the speech's length to fit approximately
one-hour time slot he has Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Gore relied on a handful of aides for input: message-maker
Carter Eskew, strategist Bob Shrum and speechwriter Eli Attie.
Gore's wife, Tipper, eldest daughter Karenna and brother-in-law,
Frank Hunger, also chipped in.
</P>
<P>
   Lehane said he was unaware of any input from Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is fundamentally a speech by him,'' Lehane said.
</P>
<P>
   The speech will reflect the thinking by Gore and his senior
advisers that Bush's acceptance speech to Republicans in
Philadelphia lacked specifics, and he plans to include more detail
in his own speech to delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been rehearsing his speech off and on oveton and
contrast him to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scepter is in his hand really looking forward to it,''
Eskew said. ``This is really an opportunity for him now to be the
main guy and to stand on that s e-mail address is
kfoskett(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
