<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-GORE-SPEECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE'S ACCEPTANCE SPEECH WILL BE SELF-WRITTEN SELF-PORTRAIT 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As Al Gore tinkers with the final version of his
address to the nation, his speech has come together in what he and
his aides describe as a political self-portrait, heavy on personal
biography, policy detail and a vision for the future, all crafted
in his own hand and in his precise syntax.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a speech I have written; I will deserve the credit or
the blame,'' he told reporters on Air Force II as he traveled
Wednesday morning from Michigan to accept his party's nomination at
the Democratic National Convention here.
</P>
<P>
   His aides emphasized that more than anything, Gore hoped to
seize the moment and present himself as the leader of his party.
This has been the plan all along, now that President Clinton has
exited the convention and the two staged a symbolic ``passing the
torch'' ceremony in Michigan on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is his main chance to be the main guy,'' said Carter
Eskew, Gore's top media adviser. ``That's something he's been
looking forward to for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Chris Lehane, Gore's spokesman: ``The scepter is in his
hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore suggested that he wanted to present a kind of unifying
vision of himself, connecting his policies with his life
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that those who watch and listen will feel afterward
that they have a clearer idea of exactly what I'm proposing to
do,'' Gore told reporters. ``They'll also know how the ideas and
proposals I'm making are rooted in the experiences that I've had.
I'll give a few specific examples. I'll tell them why I feel as
strongly as I do about the choices we have to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly buoyant, Gore held two rallies here Wednesday before
watching his oldest daughter, Karenna Gore Schiff, 27, place his
name in nomination, the first time a daughter has nominated her
father.
</P>
<P>
   All day, as he talked with reporters on his plane and at the
rallies _ and in the last few days on the campaign trail _ Gore has
been previewing his speech, saying it would be heavy on policy
details.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that you deserve to know exactly what the candidates
are proposing to do so you can make an informed judgment,'' he said
to cheers at a rally in a hangar at the Burbank airport, with Air
Force II parked in the background. ``I'm going to tell you!''
</P>
<P>
   At a second rally on the lot of Warner Brothers studios, he
presented his decision to discuss specifics as a political
``risk,'' saying: ``Tomorrow night when I address the convention,
I'm going to take the risk of laying out some specifics.'' Aides
said this was a deliberate counterpoint to criticism that Gore
comes across as too cautious and calculating.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than any of that, I believe it's time for all of us to
come together and lift up the ideal of the best America that we can
move toward,'' he said in Burbank, in a faint echo of John F.
Kennedy's speech when he accepted the Democratic presidential
nomination 40 years ago in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``In every generation we have to make the hard choices between
one direction or another, between going back to the past or forward
to the future,'' Gore said. ``Let others argue the case for the old
guard. We're the new guard, and we're going to bring positive
change to the United States of America.''
</P>
<P>
   Eskew said that Gore's speech describes differences with Gov.
George W. Bush, his Republican rival, but that it remains
``respectful.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gore said he began working on the speech two months ago,
rewriting it with the advice of Eskew and Bob Shrum, his top
message and media advisers, and Eli Attie, his speechwriter. In
what may be a first for a presidential nomination speech, Gore has
been tapping the speech out on a laptop computer and the aides have
been exchanging copies of it by computer disc. (Clinton, by
contrast, prefers to write longhand.)
</P>
<P>
   ``He goes through a process where he gets a draft and looks at
it and signs off on certain sections and zeroes in on things he
wants to refine and tweak,'' Eskew said.
</P>
<P>
   A motorcade took Gore and his running mate, Sen. Joseph
Lieberman, and their wives, Tipper and Hadassah, from the Burbank
airport to the Warner Bros. studios, where they were greeted by
delegations from Tennessee and Connecticut, ``home folks,'' as Gore
called them.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman noted that the television program, ``West Wing,'' was
produced on this lot and said of Bush: ``The closest George Bush
will get to the West Wing is a remote control!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
