<SLUG> BC-CVN-LEWIS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LEWIS 'AT PEACE' WITH MESSAGE ON LIEBERMAN
 &HT;    By MELANIE EVERSLEY
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Just hours before introducing vice presidential
nominee Joe Lieberman to the Democratic National Convention on
Wednesday, Rep. John Lewis was more worried about his voice than
his message.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic congressman from Atlanta said he was ``at peace
with himself'' about what he was going to say.
</P>
<P>
   But popping two slippery elm lozenges into his mouth, he said he
was concerned that his voice would not hold up. Apparently, all the
speaking Lewis has been doing during this gathering of 4,300
Democratic delegates has put a strain on his voice box.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, though, Lewis's vocal cords seemed just fine
as he roused the Gay and Lesbian Democratic Caucus to a standing
ovation, telling a story he has recounted many times of how, as a
boy, he and other children in his family helped hold down his Aunt
Seneva's house during a horrible storm.
</P>
<P>
   As the story goes, a nasty storm wound its way through Troy,
Ala. As each corner of the small house seemed to rise from the
ground, Lewis' aunt instructed the children to run toward that
specific corner. The children did that, back and forth, until the
storm subsided. It is a story Lewis tells often to illustrate how
persistence can win, even if one has little with which to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were little children walking with the wind,'' Lewis told
the room of 200 delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of you have been walking with the wind, but you never
even left the house,'' he shouted. ``I say to you, as members of
the gay and lesbian community, as delegates, as Democrats, that the
thunder may roll and the lightning may flash and the rain may fall,
but you must never, ever leave the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis told the delegates who represent the gay and lesbian
community that he could not reveal the exact nature of his speech
to Lieberman later that night, but he did give them this hint: ``I
know you will feel good about some of the things I will say in the
introduction.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Lewis brushed shoulders with the glitterati at a luncheon
at Paramount Studios filled with the stars of the Congressional
Black Caucus and the stars of Hollywood. Among them: Rep. Mel Watt,
D-N.C., entertainer RuPaul, black caucus chairman Jim Clyburn,
D-S.C., Stan Shaw, Rep. Al Wynn, D-Md., actor LeVar Burton and
others. Lewis sat next to actress Alfre Woodard, the two of them
occasionally whispering to each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just talking about the campaign,'' Lewis said, adding
he'd met Woodard while on tour with the autobiography he published
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was scheduled to speak Wednesday night just before
Hadassah Lieberman, who will then bring her husband onto the
podium.
</P>
<P>
   Though some critics have raised questions about Lieberman's
commitment to issues important to the African-American community,
Lewis said he did not see this as a threat to minority support for
the nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's going to be a major problem,'' Lewis said.
``The great majority of African-American delegates are with Senator
Lieberman. It's clear we have a choice to make, and with Bush and
Cheney we go back. With Al and Joe we go forward. Hopefully, we can
speed up the process of going forward,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Melanie Eversley's e-mail address is meversley(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
