<DOCNO> NYT20000816.0322 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3793 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEM-ALA-BLACKS-ART-NY     08-16 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-ALA-BLACKS-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALABAMA DELEGATES SAY PARTY DIFFERENCES ARE AS STARK AS BLACK AND
WHITE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo CVN2 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CARL HULSE   
 NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Members of Alabama's delegation to the Democratic
National Convention watched the recent GOP convention on television
and didn't like what they saw. To them, the black and white control
needed a little adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   African-American convention-goers from the state say they were
offended by GOP efforts to use the meeting in Philadelphia to
project an aura of racial inclusivity, when Alabama's GOP
delegation was almost totally white and dominated by men.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic contingent, with more than 50 percent minority
membership and a black chairman, better represents the true face of
a state with a significant African-American population, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It showed their true colors, they are not really inclusive,''
said Helen Carter, a delegate from Birmingham. She noted that even
though she is African-American, she was elected as a delegate in
the white majority congressional district of GOP Rep. Spencer
Bachus.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Reed of Montgomery, the head of the delegation, ridiculed
the GOP strategy of giving such black Republicans as retired Gen.
Colin Powell and Rep. J.C. Watts of Oklahoma prominent speaking
roles at a convention where the vast majority of the audience was
white.
</P>
<P>
   State Democratic officials noted that the Alabama GOP delegation
had no black delegates until one was named to replace an ailing
white delegate who could not attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was an insult for them to go out and lasso a black
man, tie him up to take him to the convention and then say we don't
discriminate,'' Reed said. The Democratic effort is much more
sincere, he said. ``We are trying to have full participation of
women and minorities,'' Reed added.
</P>
<P>
   National Democratic Party rules set standards for diversity in
delegations, including requiring they be at least 50 percent
female.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, hoping to show that the compassionate conservatism
ideology of nominee George W. Bush was making their party more
appealing to minorities, sought to highlight their African-American
members by putting them front and center on the podium. Condoleezza
Rice, an Alabama native and top foreign policy adviser to Bush, was
among them.
</P>
<P>
   Countering criticism from Democrats and the media that the GOP
convention was something of an illusion, Republicans said it was
fair to spotlight Republican minorities in an effort to swell their
ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Phillip Kinney, executive director of the Alabama Democratic
Party, said the low minority composition of the GOP delegation
stemmed from the fact that the party has not embraced positions
that appeal to minorities and instead continues to resist popular
policies such as affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is extremely easy to make claims of being a racially
diverse group and a group that is reaching out to minorities,'' he
said. ``It is much more difficult to do something, do things that
attract people to your party.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter said she viewed the GOP convention as an effort to hijack
the Democrat message of welcoming minorities, but she believes most
people see through the tactic.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is what they were trying to imitate,'' she said. ``But it
didn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington Bureau chief for the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
