u p BC-PROTESTS-GOALS-NNS &LR;      08-16 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROTESTS-GOALS-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTERS CAN'T AGREE ON WHAT TO DO WITH ECONOMY
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Wednesday, Aug. 16, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: Accompanies PROTESTS-NEWLOOK. 
 By ANDY DWORKIN  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just what do anti-globalization activists really want? How would
they change the international economic landscape? And what would
happen if those reforms actually took place?
</P>
<P>
   Activists blame the globalization of business for a host of
ills: lowering wages worldwide, polluting developing nations,
destroying well-paying U.S. manufacturing jobs, threatening unions
and widening the income gap between rich and poor.
</P>
<P>
   What the new gathering of environmentalists, unionists,
humanists and anarchists can't agree on is what to do with the
economy if they ever get hold of it.
</P>
<P>
   While some activists just want to tweak the booming system of
corporate-friendly international capitalism, others want to destroy
it. Proposals range from raising the U.S. minimum wage $1 an hour _
something both major parties back _ to having the government break
up large corporations or even kill off companies that don't operate
in the public interest.
</P>
<P>
   But, broadly speaking, the activists back a set of proposals
that point toward a new economy _ one with more government
regulation of business and trade, higher minimum wages and stricter
environmental standards, and rules that channel wealth from rich
executives and corporations to workers.
</P>
<P>
   The ideas could profoundly change what Americans pay and earn,
whom we work for and how we'll save for retirement. Nobody knows
for sure what the consequences of such reform might be, but experts
agree that the activists' proposals would tend to:
</P>
<P>
   _ Increase wages for many U.S. workers, especially the
lowest-paid Americans _ and perhaps raise wages for workers
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   _ Push the inflation rate up, especially for heavily imported
items such as clothing, while dragging down the prices of some
items such as apples.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cut into the profits of major international corporations,
probably limiting their growth and prompting layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Drag down the stock market, especially lowering the stock
prices of big international companies such as Nike, Unocal and
Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   - Boost the fortunes of some smaller domestic companies, as well
as those big corporations that already meet high wage and
environmental standards.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters like those gathered outside this week's Democratic
National Convention in Los Angeles hope the changes would also
redistribute wealth from the top tiers of society _ the richest
executives and investors _ down to the poorest Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Actual effects depend on whether the moderate or radical ideas
prevail and how quickly reform takes place. Intricate relationships
among trade, corporate growth, wages and prices make results harder
to predict. And as with all economics and politics, no one can
agree on whether a new system would help most Americans or create a
recession that would undermine our way of life.
</P>
<P>
   Consider, for instance, one hot-button topic _ what companies
pay foreign workers who make sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   Some protesters propose trading only with nations and companies
that pay a living wage. The definition of a living wage is nebulous
and hotly debated, but advocates say it should cover living
expenses for a worker and, some say, for the worker's family.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates for a U.S. living wage range from $6.50 an hour to
more than $8 an hour, not including health care coverage, according
to reform-minded groups including the New Party and Global
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Indonesia, some activists estimate that the
country's living wage is from 40 percent to 100 percent above its
minimum monthly wage of 286,000 rupiah, or about $33.50.
</P>
<P>
   Factories in Indonesia produce about a third of Nike's shoes.
Right now, a pair of shoes that retails for $65 costs stores about
$32.50 and costs Nike about $16.25, the company says. Of that
$16.25, $2.43 goes for labor _ though Nike's critics say the labor
cost is much lower, about $1.
</P>
<P>
   If Indonesian wages rose 40 percent, that would raise the labor
cost to Nike by about $1. At that point, Nike could choose to
either eat the increase, cutting its profits, or pass it on.
Retailers would face a similar choice. If everyone passed the cost
on, the $65 pair of shoes would cost $69.
</P>
<P>
   Nike rivals who also manufacture in Indonesia, such as Adidas,
would face similar price pressures, but shoes made domestically,
such as some New Balance models, would not.
</P>
<P>
   What's not easy to foresee is how many buyers would flinch at a
$4 price hike, for instance, and buy other shoes instead. Or
whether the price increase would hit consumers as higher costs or
stockholders as lower profits.
</P>
<P>
   It's also hard to predict the effect on Indonesian workers.
Small wage increases won't discourage companies, economists say,
but if Indonesia's wages suddenly get much bigger than competitors
such as China or Vietnam, Nike might move operations to those
nations.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   The hypothetical question is hard to answer, Nike spokesman Vada
Manager said. When deciding where to make shoes, Nike considers not
only manufacturing costs, but also tariffs, how skilled a country's
workers are, even the origins of materials.
</P>
<P>
   That's just one of the complex and confusing chains of causes
and effects that would influence a whole range of economic
activities _ wheat exports, oil imports, international trade in
lumber, steel and so on _ if the rules of international trade
changed.
</P>
<P>
   But protesters seem willing to risk the unknowns. They say that
allowing more global trade, without coupling that trade with wage
and labor standards, has let the wealthiest companies and
executives get even richer at the expense of poorer nations and
workers.
</P>
<P>
   (Andy Dworkin is a staff writer with The Oregonian of Portland,
Ore.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000816.0327 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3798 &Cx1f; tab-z
u p BC-PROTESTS-PR-NNS &LR;      08-16 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROTESTS-PR-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTERS CAN'T AGREE ON WHAT TO DO WITH ECONOMY
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Wednesday, Aug. 16, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: Accompanies PROTESTS-NEWLOOK. 
 By ANDY DWORKIN  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most labor activists from developing nations live lives of
unsung determination. But Roselio Reyes is a minor celebrity,
thanks to the publicity wars dominating the debate over global
trade.
</P>
<P>
   An earnest 22-year-old, Reyes used to work at a Nike apparel
factory in the Dominican Republic. A few years ago, Reyes says, he
was told to work overtime or quit. He quit, so he could go to
school, and since has been working to unionize his former
workplace.
</P>
<P>
   The story would end there, except Reyes hooked up with some of
the most determined and vocal activist groups waging the battle to
change big U.S. apparel companies, and Nike in particular. These
groups, including United Students Against Sweatshops, are among the
vanguard of an effort to put the brakes on unfettered corporate
globalization and to promote better wages and working conditions
for laborers.
</P>
<P>
   Reyes is now on his second activist-sponsored U.S. tour in two
years, hoping to drum up interest in global trade issues. He's
traveling with nine young activists in a Ford Chateau Sport RV,
protesting in sports stadiums and NikeTown stores. The trip has
drawn coverage, including a Sports Illustrated story by the father
of one of the activists. There also is a Web site
(www.behindthelabel.org) that calls Reyes ``the superstar of our
`Say No to Nike Sweatshops' tour,'' as well as a ``snappily
dressed'' Libra and baseball fan.
</P>
<P>
   The elevation of Reyes, and others like him, into a protest
celebrity is the fruit of an activist movement working hard on the
public-relations front. At the same time, multinational
corporations have added public-relations specialists who
concentrate on presenting the company's side in the globalization
debate.
</P>
<P>
   These days, anti-corporate activists don't just cultivate
workers and bargain with management. They also pick out heroes _
and target corporate villains _ to draw the attention of U.S. media
and get their message to a broader public.
</P>
<P>
   Another tried-and-true tactic: orchestrating high-profile
marches and sit-ins, from November's World Trade Organization
protests in Seattle to the street theater during the Democratic
National Convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The new protest movement has relied heavily on PR out of
necessity, says B.J. Bullert, a documentarian and communications
researcher who has studied the phenomenon. For years, many
activists largely were ignored by the media, governments and the
companies they aimed to reform. Bullert says young activists who
grew up in a media-saturated age, including some full-time PR
advisers to protest groups, realized they needed to reach a wider
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know that if you can't get media attention,'' she says,
``you don't have a voice in the world any more.''
</P>
<P>
   The work of Jeff Ballinger, a longtime labor activist, is one
example, Bullert says. For years, Ballinger studied working
conditions in Asia, especially at Indonesian shoe and clothing
factories.
</P>
<P>
   His efforts received mass media attention largely after he
connected with Global Exchange, a protest group that has a
full-time PR worker and contacts among mainstream journalists. The
groups were able to garner press by framing the labor question as a
David and Goliath story between the big company and poor workers,
Bullert says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew they were vulnerable,'' Ballinger says of Nike.
``I just didn't have the media savvy'' to spread the story.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to trying to package their concerns as human
interest stories, protest groups have taken a cue from previous
generations of protesters and taken to the streets. The tactic
found its greatest success in Seattle, where mass protests _ met
with an aggressive city crackdown _ drew heavy media coverage and
helped turn global trade issues into a popular public topic.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the multinational companies that activists target also
have entered the PR fray, as corporate PR departments spend more
time talking about issues such as environmental responsibility and
labor conditions. Companies such as Shell, Ford and Texaco _
criticized as heavy polluters _ produce ads and Web sites touting
their environmental efforts. Other companies, most notably Nike,
publicize programs to increase wages and improve factory
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, it was in part an offensive move and a defensive
move,'' says Vada Manager, a Nike spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Some activists worry that publicity and spin about globalization
has its problems, including the fact that complex controversies get
boiled down to a few easy-to-understand, good-vs.-evil stories.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Nike's factories, Ballinger says, most attention
focuses on wages. After Nike increased its wages several times, he
says, some activists are ready to declare victory and move on. But
Ballinger says much work still needs to be done to get factory
managers to bargain collectively with workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the public-relations dynamic takes over so thoroughly,''
he says, ``then you tend to lose the real message.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   As for Reyes, he says his time in the spotlight won his cause
modest success.
</P>
<P>
   His first trip to the United States _ a 1998 tour sponsored by
Unite, a garment-workers' union _ generated press, including a New
York Times report that accused Reyes' employer of paying low wages,
requiring overtime, abusing workers and firing union organizers.
</P>
<P>
   Reyes says that after the stories ran, Nike visited Yupoon, the
Korean owner of his former factory. Management soon cleaned the
factory's bathrooms, installed a water-purification system and
increased overtime pay, Reyes says.
</P>
<P>
   With this trip, Reyes hopes public pressure will get Nike to
lean on factory management again, this time to accept a union at
the factory. He knows it's not likely. Unionization progress has
been slow, hampered by insufficient resources and by widespread
fear among workers that union backers will be fired. Besides, he
says, the factory does its own successful PR work in its village of
Villa Altagracia.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the community,'' Reyes says, ``its reputation is good.''
</P>
<P>
   (Andy Dworkin is a staff writer of The Oregonian of Portland,
Ore.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
