<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service has filed or will file the following for
Thursday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee
at 213-336-1800 or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-CONVENTION-RDP (Los Angeles) _ Sen. Joseph Lieberman accepts
his party's nomination as vice president. Large chunks of his
prime-time speech are expected to be devoted to descriptions of
Vice President Al Gore as the Democratic ticket tries to put a new
face on Gore. By DAN FREEDMAN and STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-GEPHARDT (Los Angeles) _ Rep. Dick Gephardt rejected a
chance to be Al Gore's running mate because he thought his chances
to be speaker of the House were better than they were to become
vice president. When Gephardt addresses the Democratic National
Convention Wednesday night, many delegates in the hall will be
thinking ``what-if'' he had accepted. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-ECONOMY-CREDIT (Los Angeles) _ Treasury Secretary Lawrence
Summers discusses the nation's booming economy and how President
Clinton's policies have helped create and sustain that growth.
Summers also contrasts Vice President Al Gore's economic policies
to those put forth by Republican presidential nominee George W.
Bush. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-INTERNET (Los Angeles) _ Of course Al Gore didn't invent the
Internet, and he never really said he did. But the vice president
does know how to use it, according to Internet researchers who say
the Democrats are doing a slightly better job than the Republicans
in embracing their first national convention on the information
superhighway. By PATTY REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-GAYS (Los Angeles) _ They are on the podium, among the
delegates and raising funds here for various advocacy groups and
organizations. Still, core issues of the gay community are getting
short shrift at the Democratic National Convention. Is there room
in Al Gore's family-friendly agenda for gay adoption and other
measures sought by one of the party's core constituencies? By JULIE
MASON.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-PROTESTS (Los Angeles) _ As protesters focus on a theme of
police brutality, 70 bicyclists, including an Associated Press
photographer, are arrested near the site of the Democratic National
Convention. Most were charged with reckless driving for riding in a
circle. By LISA TEACHEY and DAVID IVANOVICH.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-CISNEROS (Los Angeles) _ Former Housing Secretary Henry
Cisneros, who left the Cabinet amid a scandal over a former
mistress, remains coy about whether he will take another shot at
politics. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-WHIP-RACE (Beverly Hills, Calif.) _ Inside the ritzy
ballroom of the Regent Beverly Wilshire, across the street from the
boutiques of Rodeo Drive, Rep. Nancy Pelosi of California is
working the crowd. In the realm of politics and raising money, the
seven-term congresswoman from San Francisco is a master in the art
of the political schmooze. This year's elections could be payback
time for Pelosi, 60. If Democrats win a majority in the House of
Representatives, the lawmaker hopes to become majority whip, the
third-ranking position in House leadership. By ZACHARY COILE.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-ACT (Austin, Texas) _ Education officials say the number
of Texas students who take the ACT college admission exam has
increased 23 percent over the past five years, and the average
composite score for Texas students has remained steady over the
past three years. By KATHY WALT.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HELEN-THOMAS (Los Angeles) _ Vice President Al Gore and Texas
Gov. George W. Bush were playing defense when they picked their
running mates. Gore's choice of Sen. Joseph Lieberman helps Gore
shield himself from the Republican claim that Bush will restore
``honor and dignity'' to the Oval Office. Bush's pick of Dick
Cheney helps Bush answer skeptics who wonder if Bush has the
``gravitas'' to be president. It's a strange system where one man
can pick the potential next president of the United States. By
HELEN THOMAS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ The bombastic Pat Buchanan, who
was nominated for president last week by one wing of the warring
Reform Party, may hope to lead the nation into a future of
continued prosperity and enlightened policies. But the ideas he
espouses are not those of the future. If put into law, they would
not perpetuate prosperity or illuminate the way ahead. They would
have exactly the opposite affect. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Already
filed.)
</P>
