<SLUG> BC-R-MCCAIN-CANCER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS AGAIN DIAGNOSE SKIN CANCER ON MCCAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (REPEATING to add photo note; no other changes.)  
(See also: MCCAIN-CANCER-HISTORY) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT12 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John McCain, the Arizona Republican who made
an unsuccessful run for the presidency, has been diagnosed with
malignant melanoma, a potentially severe form of skin cancer, on
his temple and arm, his aides said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who was successfully treated for malignant melanoma in
1993 when doctors removed a mole from his shoulder, was scheduled
to undergo more tests on Thursday and Friday at the Mayo Clinic in
Scottsdale, Ariz., and did not yet know the seriousness of his
condition.
</P>
<P>
   After the tests are complete, McCain will discuss the best
treatment options, which can range from minor surgery, if the
cancer is caught early, to chemotherapy, in the later stages.
Malignant melanoma is the most deadly form of skin cancer and the
least common, but if it is caught early it can be highly curable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The spots were confirmed to be melanomas after an Aug. 4
biopsy performed at the National Naval Medical Center in Bethesda,
Md.,'' according to a statement from McCain's office.
</P>
<P>
   Since his 1993 brush with cancer, McCain had been closely
monitored by doctors, who periodically removed suspicious moles or
lesions from his skin. Most of these lesions consisted of basal
cell carcinoma, the least worrisome and most common type of skin
cancer. Doctors had declared him cured last year, since the
malignant melanoma had not recurred for five years.
</P>
<P>
   The type of cancer McCain suffers from is sometimes associated
with prolonged exposure to the sun. The senator was a prisoner of
war for more than five years when his Navy jet was shot down over
North Vietnam, and during his captivity he was often exposed to the
sun.
</P>
<P>
   McCain had told few people about the latest diagnosis and
planned to go public with the information after he learned more
from doctors this week, but he did tell Gov. George W. Bush, who
defeated him for the Republican presidential nomination, last week
when Bush stopped by McCain's Arizona ranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``During a routine examination two unrelated spots were
discovered on Sen. John McCain. One is on his left temple, the
other on his left arm,'' said the statement released by his office.
</P>
<P>
   McCain will turn 64 on Aug. 29.
</P>
</TEXT>
