<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-WOODS0817-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PGA Championship opens today with Woods - who else? - as
favorite.
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. - They thought Pebble Beach might bring more
players into U.S. Open contention and help derail the Tiger Woods
onslaught. They said the same thing about St. Andrews before the
British Open.
</P>
<P>
   And now they're saying that Valhalla Golf Club is the type of
TPC-like venue that should open doors for many at the 82nd PGA
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Be serious. If Woods runs away again, as he has in winning the
U.S. Open by 15 shots and the British Open by eight, it won't
matter if one or 100 players tie for second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we thought St. Andrews would bring more people in
because it was hard and bouncy, and it didn't,'' Scotland's Colin
Montgomerie said. ``We thought Pebble Beach would bring people in
because it might get windy, and it didn't. . . . The guy seems to
be quite good on any surface he plays. . . . I think any golf
tournament plays into Tiger's hands right now. He's the guy with
the confidence. He's the best player in the world by a long, long
way.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it has become an upset when Woods does not win a major.
Starting with today's first round, history is waiting:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A victory would give Woods his third major in a row, which
would match Ben Hogan's achievement in 1953, when he won the
Masters, U.S. Open and British Open.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Woods would accomplish the first successful defense of a PGA
Championship since Denny Shute in 1936-1937
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  It would be Woods' fifth career major. His victory in the
British Open completed the career Grand Slam at age 24. It was his
fourth major title in his past five attempts.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  It would be his seventh PGA Tour victory this year, and 12th
in the last 24. He has earned $5,792,821, nearly doubling the take
of Ernie Els, No. 2 on the money list. Els has finished second in
the past three majors.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan's mark commanded the most attention this week, but Woods
contends that it does not enter his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a major championship,'' Woods said. ``It's like
going to the British Open and worrying about completing the Grand
Slam. I'm not here trying to duplicate what Hogan did in '53.
That's strictly a by-product of winning the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere has been the same as the other three majors of
2000. Woods speaks modestly about his chances early in the week,
then jumps out early and runs away. By Sunday, it's an exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to raise our standards to join his,'' Montgomerie
said. ``We can't afford to let him come down to ours. We are all
trying. We are all failing, but we are trying.''
</P>
<P>
   After a layoff, Woods worked on his game last week in the Buick
Open, where he finished 11th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm playing all right; I broke 80 all four days last week,
which is good for me,'' Woods joked.
</P>
<P>
   Valhalla is a course that sets up well for Woods. It is a
second-shot golf course, with emphasis on high trajectory. After
flattening his swing plane to stay under the expected wind at St.
Andrews, Woods has been working on his high shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it sets up well for anyone who hits the ball high,''
said Woods. ``That's the way Nicklaus golf courses are kind of
designed; you have got to bring the ball in high.''
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting that a victory on Sunday would align Woods with
Hogan. A tunnel-visioned Hogan was obsessed with finding
perfection. Woods, who is more fun-loving, searches for excellence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think there is such a thing as perfection,''
Woods said, ``because we're all human and technically imperfect.
But I've always been a big believer of professional excellence. . .
. I know I can never get to a point where I hit perfect shots every
time. I just want to become the best that I can be. To me, that's
professional excellence.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
