<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATIN-AMERICA-DELIVERY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-COMMERCE IN LATIN AMERICA HAMPERED BY ERRATIC DELIVERY SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any one of the 500 million people who live in Latin America can
sign on to the Internet, given access to a computer and a phone
line. They can buy a book, CD or anything else offered for sale on
the Internet, given a credit card. And they can have their purchase
delivered to their home or office, given luck.
</P>
<P>
   In many parts of Latin America, postal service outside of major
business centers is erratic at best. At times, the only reliable
national delivery system belongs to the soft-drink and potato chip
manufacturers who stock the bodegas and mom-and-pop stores present
in almost every community, no matter how small or remote.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the cities, packages from abroad can be delayed in
customs for days, and letters arrive weeks late, if at all.
</P>
<P>
   That, to a large extent, leaves the final leg of electronic
commerce in Latin America the province of private services. Each
big city has a few local fast-freight companies, and recently
specialized e-commerce companies like Sky Box Services allow Latin
Americans to have Internet purchases sent to an address in the
United States. Sky Box then carries them south and delivers them to
homes and offices, bypassing often unreliable local carriers.
</P>
<P>
   The most visible deliverers are the large international
companies like United Parcel Service, FedEx and DHL, and all are
expected to play a part in the growth of e-commerce in Latin
America. They have been preparing to handle the new business,
although they do not expect it to boom anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We liken the status of the Internet in Latin America to being
where the United States was in 1996,'' said John Menna, vice
president for marketing for Latin America and the Caribbean for
UPS. ``It'll take about four or five years to start seeing anything
substantial develop there. Nonetheless, UPS is putting in place all
the pieces and the infrastructure to facilitate electronic commerce
and the buying and selling of goods throughout Latin America.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Economic Commission for Latin America and the
Caribbean, the number of computers connected to the Internet last
year rose more rapidly in Latin America than in any other part of
the world. Even so, while the region accounts for 8 percent of the
world's population, it represents just 3.5 percent of Internet
users and less than 1 percent of global e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Many obstacles hamper development of the Internet in Latin
America. Poverty is so persistent that many people still lack
access to a telephone, and the possibility of buying a computer,
let alone logging onto the Internet, is reserved for a relatively
small group of city dwellers with sufficient incomes. Few people
have credit cards, which still are essential for e-commerce to
work. Computer literacy lags far behind levels in other parts of
the world, and telephone service competition has not yet brought
down the cost of Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the issue of delivery. ``Local delivery of
goods is something that many people in Latin America associate with
the local postal service, which in the past has been a very poor
service indeed,'' Menna said.
</P>
<P>
   To strengthen its Latin American operations, UPS is buying
Challenge Air Cargo, an airline that serves Latin America from
Miami. Besides increasing the UPS fleet, the acquisition provides
landing rights in virtually every developed country in Latin
America, a process that could have taken years had it been
negotiated nation by nation.
</P>
<P>
   The Challenge purchase ``clearly says that we think Latin
America is a growing region,'' Menna said. But e-commerce, he
added, ``is still all potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Competition is intense among the air delivery services. DHL
Worldwide Express has spent $30 million the last two years
preparing for more cargo, including substantially more e-commerce
deliveries. In 1998, the company bought three Boeing 727s, upgraded
its hub in Panama City and built a new hub in Buenos Aires. Last
year DHL also acquired DHL SA, a contract operation in Argentina
that was run by a local company. DHL is spending up to $10 million
to improve service in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   ``Latin America has an awful lot of people, an awful lot of land
and huge potential,'' said Colum Joyce, an electronic commerce
manager at DHL's headquarters in Brussels. ``But it's no different
from anywhere else in the world. There are a few relatively
concentrated points of consumption, and pickup on the Internet is
concentrating on those socioeconomic segments of the community.''
</P>
<P>
   The other big air delivery service in the region, FedEx, is
building a larger cargo handling operation at Miami International
Airport, the gateway through which most shipments to Latin America
pass. But its real focus is on streamlining the process for getting
goods in and out of Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Juan N. Cento, president of FedEx Express International's Latin
America division, said his company was helping customers, like the
hammock manufacturer in Merida, Mexico, he visited recently, design
and build their Web pages to take full advantage of the global
market available on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say, `Here's what we need,' and we help them with
everything from building a Web page to monitoring the shipping,
tracking and tracing of packages,'' Cento said.
</P>
<P>
   FedEx is also working to reduce customs delays for packages
coming into Latin America. It recently opened a new clearing house
at the Toluca Airport outside Mexico City that enables local
customs agents to clear shipments worth less than $200 on the day
they arrive. A similar system is planned for Campinas, Brazil, near
Sao Paolo, and will later be replicated throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``E-commerce is an increasingly integral part of the business
environment in certain markets in the region,'' said Gregory M.
Rossiter, a FedEx spokesman. ``But quite candidly, for FedEx, the
potential for e-commerce in the region as a whole is still a number
of years away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
