<HEADER>
A3808 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-SUNKEN-SUB-BOS     08-16 1286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SUNKEN-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH HOPE FADING, RUSSIA SEEKS NATO AID IN SUBMARINE RESCUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ If any of the crew of a stricken Russian submarine are
still alive, their world has gone pitch black and cold. Moving
about, or even talking, has become perilous _ if any still have the
energy to do it. There may still be food and water, but breathable
air is in short supply.
</P>
<P>
   After five days stranded on the floor of the Barents Sea, this
is the best-case scenario for the 116 Russian officers and crew on
the crippled nuclear submarine, the Kursk, say Russian naval
officers who have survived submarine accidents. This scenario
assumes things nobody knows for sure: that the crew survived
whatever disaster sunk the Kursk last weekend, and that they
managed to escape the forward parts of the vessel that flooded and
to reach undamaged compartments further aft, and that there was
enough air to keep everyone alive until now.
</P>
<P>
   After days of attempts by Russian ships to lower a rescue
capsule to the submarine were frustrated by bad weather and the
precarious angle of the sub, concern for the men on board the Kursk
forced Russia to reverse its earlier refusal of foreign assistance
Wednesday and ask Britain and Norway to help try to save the crew.
</P>
<P>
   The last-minute decision to accept aid from NATO countries _
which was offered when the Russian Navy first disclosed the
accident Monday _ was announced amid the first signs of criticism
here over the way Russian authorities are handling the crisis. One
concern raised by several analysts here is that national pride, or
residual fear of letting their former Cold War adversaries get too
close to their most modern submarine technology, had prevented
Russian authorities from calling for help sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our admirals know too well that disclosing secrets to the West
may easily land them in the clink, while risking sailors lives most
likely will not,'' commented Pavel Felgenhauer, a defense analyst
for The Moscow Times.
</P>
<P>
   And there were fears that the desperate call for assistance,
after officials insisted for days that Western aid was inferior and
was not needed, had come too late for the crew of the Kursk. A
Norwegian ship with a team of deep-sea divers and a British rescue
mini-submarine set out for the site but could take until Saturday
to get there. Naval officials have said the crew's air supply would
run out Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Russian ships repeatedly attempted to guide rescue capsules
through the stormy waters but, hampered by high seas, strong
underwater currents and poor visibility, could not dock with the
submarine, which is lying at a sharp sidewards tilt on the sea
floor 354 feet beneath the surface.
</P>
<P>
   For the men on board, the 60-degree tilt means that the
machinery and controls that line the crowded compartments are in
unfamiliar places, making it almost impossible to move about, said
reserve Captain Boris Kolyada.
</P>
<P>
   Few people alive can relate to the Kursk crew's ordeal the way
Kolyada can _ he was the executive officer on the Komsomolsk, a
Soviet atomic submarine that sunk off Norway in 1989, killing 42 of
the 69 crew members. One man who can, former Captain Vladimir
Yermolin, who survived a Soviet submarine accident in the early
1970s, said crew members could have trouble concentrating or lose
consciousness from the lack of air.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way to communicate with the outside world, no way
to mark the passage of time, nothing to do but wait to be saved,''
Kolyada said, describing what it is like on a stricken submarine.
``There is a complete loss of orientation. The temperature is
around 40 degrees. There are no warm clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Any emergency batteries for air purification or light would be
dead by now. And according to one report, in the Moscow paper
Kommersant Daily, the Kursk left its emergency batteries on shore
when it set out for exercises last week. The paper, citing naval
sources, said the batteries are a deficit item, and the vessel's
commanders decided they would not need them on what was supposed to
be a three-day trip.
</P>
<P>
   The report, if true, highlights the corner-cutting analysts say
is prevalent in the Navy, where post-Soviet funding cuts have left
most ships unseaworthy and affected even the most modern vessels
like the Kursk.
</P>
<P>
   President Vladimir Putin has called for Russia to restore its
armed forces to fighting trim, in part by ordering major exercises
of the kind the Russian submarine fleet has not seen since the end
of the Cold War. But Moscow-based defense analyst Alexander Zhilin
said the Northern Fleet, where the Kursk was based, was poorly
prepared for maneuvers on the high seas, raising the potential for
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   The rescue effort has revealed other unflattering details about
the Russian command chain. The daily Segodnya quoted a naval source
as saying that officials did not dare ask NATO for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only the president can take the decision to ask NATO for
aid,'' the paper quoted the source as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, on vacation in southern Russia, had been almost invisible
during the crisis until Wednesday, when in a brief television
interview he expressed his concern about the situation but said
rescuers were doing ``everything possible'' to save the crew. Putin
apparently gave the order to ask for foreign help after speaking
with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The British LR5 submarine has the capability to maneuver in
strong currents and attach itself to a tilted vessel, unlike the
modified diving bells Russian rescue ships have been using, which
have to be maneuvered from the surface. It is still unclear if the
British sub can dock with the Russian vessel.
</P>
<P>
   And the roundabout route the British rescue crew is taking _
flying through Norway rather than directly to a Russian base close
to the site of the incident, which will almost ensure the British
will arrive too late _ indicates that the Russians are still not
entirely committed to having the NATO rescuers involved.
</P>
<P>
   The change of heart on foreign assistance was just one of
several reversals, as officials continued to issue streams of
contradictory explanations about what is going on. ``Half of them
don't know what is happening and the half of them that do are
lying,'' said Alexander Nikitin, a former Russian submarine captain
who spent two years in prison for reporting on the hazards caused
by nuclear waste in the Northern Fleet.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian Navy chief, Admiral Vladimir Kuroyedov, said there
had been no communication with the crew since Saturday, but that
this was no real concern and that he was ``more confident'' about
the chances of rescuing the crew. On Tuesday, Kuroyedov had said
that the crew was tapping SOS on the hull of the Kursk, but that
the signal was getting weaker and that this was a grave sign.
</P>
<P>
   The submarine suffered extensive damage after an explosion in
the torpedo compartment at the front of the vessel, but the Navy
has given only sketchy and often contradictory details about what
happened.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy had said it had informed relatives of the crew of the
situation on board the Kursk, but relatives complained to reporters
that naval officials had refused to confirm to them whether their
loved ones were on board.
</P>
<P>
   Felgenhauer said it was impossible to believe anything the Navy
was saying. He cited officials' emphatic denials that the
submarine, which can carry 24 nuclear-tipped anti-ship missiles,
was carrying nuclear weapons when it went down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know if that's true,'' he said. ``That's probably
just a guess.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
