<DOCNO> NYT20000816.0338 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3816 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBO-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     08-16 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. IS STUCK WITH THE AVENGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're throwing us bones, scraps, scaled-down vestiges of what
we once had in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   They're giving us the Avengers of the Arena Football League, a
team that plays indoors and lines up eight players to a side like
you would see at a Sunday afternoon flag football game at Griffith
Park.
</P>
<P>
   They're giving us a team that will play under the World
Wrestling Federation banner of Vince McMahon in something called
the Xtreme Football League.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams and Raiders have now been gone five years from our
celestial sphere, and we have been reduced to having to accept
street corner handouts as replacements for the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   If someone told me 10 years ago that this would be the case, I'd
have told the person that would be about as likely to happen as,
well, my falling deeply in love with Georgia Frontiere.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, that might seem to some to be a more plausible
development since so many people have come to believe that, since I
mention Georgia so often, she has become an object of sublimated
lust, like the little boys in class who pinch the girls they fancy.
</P>
<P>
   Now we're down to waiting until next February 3 when L.A.'s XFL
team will commence its 10-game season that doesn't exactly have
football devotees here hyperventilating in anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   But the general manager of this new enterprise, Mr. John Kenneth
McKay, aka J.K. McKay, son of the legendary USC coach John McKay,
long-time L.A. attorney, former standout receiver for USC, Ed
Roski's legal counsel in the failed attempt to bring an NFL
expansion franchise to L.A., recipient of 29 Pat Haden scoring
passes his senior season at Bishop Amat, insists L.A. will become
enamored with its newest professional football entry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a tremendously entertaining brand of
football,'' says McKay, who made it official today that the team's
new coach will be Al Luginbill, former San Diego State head man who
spent the past five years directing the fortunes of the Amsterdam
Admirals. ``There are a couple of rules changes that figure to make
things a little more exciting. There will be no fair catches
allowed on punts, and the ball will be live at all times. And a
player can be in motion towards the line of scrimmage like they do
up in Canada and in the Arena league.''
</P>
<P>
   But the widespread perception of the XFL is that McMahon's
presence--- he's actually in partnership with NBC, which put up
$100 million for the broadcasting rights---will result in the games
being nothing more than scripted acts with the performers spewing
invective at one another and getting into staged brawls.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it's known many of the players will be miked, and
that cameras will be allowed into the dressing rooms, which
certainly can make one slightly suspicious of planned shenanigans
orchestrated by someone so schooled in the art as Vince McMahon.
</P>
<P>
   But J.K. McKay claims that the games in the XFL will be totally
legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way I'd be involved in this league if I thought the games
would be fake,'' he says. ``What's going to be so different about
this league is the presentation. Cameras and microphones are going
to be everywhere. There's going to be total access to both the
media and even the fans. We're going to see to it that a segment of
the fans during games have access to the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be very wide-open. It's definitely going to be a
fan- friendly game. And it's going to be inexpensive compared to
the prices in other professional sports. Tickets will go between
twenty-three and twenty-five dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   McKay says 38 players will be carried on an XFL team's game-day
roster, plus an additional seven who will be inactive.
</P>
<P>
   The standard player salary will be $50,000, except for the
quarterbacks, who will be command $60,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players can make quite a bit more in this league than in any
other except for the NFL,'' says McKay. ``And they can actually
make a lot more since we're going to have an incentive gimmick
built into each game. The players on the winning side each get to
split up $100,000, meaning each will earn an extra $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, if you're fortunate enough to get to the playoffs, the
winning players in the first game will make $10,000 each. And, in
the championship game on April 23, the winning players each will
earn $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you know this league's going to be pretty competitive. The
players on the championship team each can make over $100,000.''
</P>
<P>
   The eight-team league---there also will be franchises in New
York, Chicago, Las Vegas, Orlando, San Jose, Memphis and
Birmingham---will have its games shown on Saturday evenings on NBC
and Sunday evenings on UPN, plus on a yet unnamed cable outlet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have high expectations for this league,'' says the
47-year-old McKay, who played for the Southern California Sun in
1975 in the fledging World Football League when it folded three
quarters of the way through the season. ``The McMahon organization
has shown it knows how to market its product. We've got some
sizable up-front money from the TV networks. We're optimistic. At
least there's going to be professional football back at the
Coliseum.''
</P>
<P>
   True.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect we pro football beggars in Southern California aren't
exactly in a position to be too discriminate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 2015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
