<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3822 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-CAMBRIDGE-TECHNOLOGY-     08-16 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMBRIDGE-TECHNOLOGY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-CAMBRIDGE TECHNOLOGY CEO ALLOWED TO KEEP NEW JOB 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Gen3 Partners is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A judge refused Wednesday to force James K. Sims,
former chief executive of Cambridge Technology Partners Inc., from
his post at a new start-up.
</P>
<P>
   But Sims won a split decision in Superior Court. While he can
keep his job, seven of his employees have been restrained from
recruiting Cambridge Technology workers.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling inflamed an already tense struggle that Cambridge
Technology claims has contributed to a deluge of employee
departures. Sims, who was ousted from the company last year, sees
the lawsuit as a personal attack and has countersued.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm insulted they went after me,'' Sims said. ``I plan to
absolutely destroy them in court.''
</P>
<P>
   Cambridge Technology sued Sims in April, saying he had broken
his promise not to become a rival. Last month, the technology
consulting firm filed a request for a preliminary injunction,
seeking to prevent Sims and another former Cambridge Technology
executive from working at Gen3 Partners Inc. of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for Cambridge Technology argued that Sims and Arthur
Toscanini, a former Cambridge chief financial officer who now works
for Sims, had violated their noncompete contracts.
</P>
<P>
   But in her ruling, Judge Leila Kern wrote that the consultant
had not yet proven that the two executives and Gen3 Partners had
become rivals of Cambridge Technology.
</P>
<P>
   After analyzing the large consultant's Digital Strategy Practice
and Gen3's offerings, Kern wrote: ``It is equally probable as not
that these two companies are competing.''
</P>
<P>
   Cambridge Technology also claimed that Gen3 Partners had wooed
Wal-Mart.com, one of its big clients. In an affidavit, Sims
acknowledged that his company had sought the retailer's business
but later discovered that Wal-Mart
</P>
<P>
   .com was looking for work that Gen3 Partners did not perform.
</P>
<P>
   Kern also noted that, in an Aug. 7 article in The Boston Globe,
Wal-Mart said it was unhappy with the Web site and was no longer
working with Cambridge Technology. In fact, Wal-Mart.com has turned
to Sapient Corp., a technology consultant in Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   Gen3 Partners, however, did not win in other areas. Kern issued
a preliminary injunction against Toscanini and six other former
Cambridge Technology employees, restraining them from recruiting
the consultant's workers. That means they will not be able to
recruit from their former employer for two years after their
departures from Cambridge Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Absent from that list, however, is Sims. The animated and brash
executive apparently never signed a nonsolicitation agreement at
Cambridge Technology, which means he can continue to recruit from
his ex-employer _ at least for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   Following Wednesday's ruling, both companies claimed they had
triumphed in the first leg of their court battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision by the court is an important one for Cambridge
that vindicates our company's right to enforce our agreements and
protect our work force from unlawful raiding,'' Joseph LaSala, an
attorney for Cambridge Technology, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Sims said he had prevailed in a
personal attack against him. ``It was really terrible what they
tried to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Cambridge Technology said it had settled a
lawsuit with a start-up founded by Harold Gubnitsky, a former vice
president. Gubnitsky's company, Semtor Inc. of Fort Lauderdale,
Fla., has agreed not to hire any more Cambridge Technology
employees.
</P>
<P>
   But the feud between Cambridge Technology and Sims seems far
from over.
</P>
<P>
   Cambridge Technlogy has no plans to drop its lawsuit against
Sims and Gen3 Partners. Likewise, Sims does not intend to drop his
suit against Cambridge, in which he may ask for up to $10 million
in damages.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, competitors have watched the court case with
amusement. But several analysts say the disputes are distracting
Cambridge Technology at a time when it should be working to stem
recent losses, retain employees, and boost its stock price.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Cambridge Technology have spiraled downward from a
52-week high of $27 on Dec. 30. The company's stock price rose
43.75 cents Wednesday on the Nasdaq Stock Market to close at
$7.9375.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fundamentally, what Cambridge Technology Partners has to do is
worry about Cambridge Technology Partners,'' said Rob DeSisto, a
vice president at Gartner Group in Lowell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
