<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3830 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     08-16 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUDDY SALARY CAP GOOD FOR OWNERS, BAD FOR GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ It wasn't that long ago when the Cowboys
were winning world championships the old-fashioned NFL way, and the
historians will remember it as the end of an era. Kinda like when
Chubby Checker stopped twisting.
</P>
<P>
   The last decade started for the Cowboys this way:
</P>
<P>
   They evaluated talent, then drafted it or traded for it, then
developed it, then paid that talent a minimal going rate, then
stood back and watched Jerry and Jimmy hug each other and the
Lombardi Trophy on national TV.
</P>
<P>
   Who cared about any salary cap?
</P>
<P>
   Today, of course, just four seasons since the Cowboys' last 1995
Super Bowl team, the entire league is consumed with just that _ the
salary cap. It doesn't necessarily matter who's got the best
talent, best coach or best owner, survival from one season to the
next depends largely on which teams manage to remain ``cap
friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   Bean-counters and pencil-necked geeks in the front office are
just as likely to win you a Super Bowl as the stud quarterback
sitting there in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   It says here the NFL salary cap, which came to pass in 1994, has
destroyed the league as we once knew it by cheapening the product
on the field dramatically. So there.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jones, once dubbed ``Cap Daddy'' for his role in pushing
for approval among fellow owners, had a reply to that opinion here
yesterday, but first there's also this:
</P>
<P>
   Major-league baseball owners would immediately sell their souls
to the devil or Michael Irvin if they could copy-cat the football
salary cap. This system is viewed in baseball, at least by
ownership, as Utopia, Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Jones: ``If a vote on the salary cap was being held today, and
my voting interest strictly involved the Dallas Cowboys, then I'd
give them a big no. But because the Cowboys can't stand alone, my
vote would have to reflect what is best for the league. In that
regard, I'd stay with the system we have in place. It is best for
all, even though the cap has done damage to the Cowboys.''
</P>
<P>
   Much damage, actually. But Jones is an owner, and any
executive-level type in any business wants his employee salary
expense to be defined. The cap allows that in football. In
baseball, the players' payroll can consume 75 percent, or more, of
the budget.
</P>
<P>
   And just as important, the NFL salary cap allows the owners to
police themselves on spending to win.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of winning, the Cowboys had the dynasty working in the
first half of '90s. The pre-cap haul was three Super Bowls in four
seasons. Starting in 1996, however, this team has won one playoff
game. Overall, the league is weaker, so what does that say about
the post-cap Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had more players to lose, because we were a young team with
so much talent _ under the cap, we did lose more than other
teams,'' said Stephen Jones, the No. 1 cap man for his father. And
by the way, there's no geek in Stephen. He's a former college
football player. But his front- office job is as difficult, if not
more so, than that of Dave Campo.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, Jerry admits he miscalculated one important area when the
salary cap was implemented in '94. ``Financially, it appeared the
sounder way to go, and football-wise, I was confident we could
continue to compete for a long time because of the way the cap
rules were defined,'' Jones said. ``It was going to be a hard cap.
Every team would be limited in what they could do with the money.
And we already had the best talent.''
</P>
<P>
   But out in San Francisco, Carmen Policy uncovered a loophole. By
extending existing contracts, extra cap money could be generated.
The war was suddenly on between Jones and Policy, who ran the
strongest teams of the mid-'90s. Jones, of course, discovered
loopholes of his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``A hard cap suddenly became a soft cap,'' Jones said. ``We
could buy on credit. We could use future money. It all became a
huge mistake. It certainly hurt the Cowboys.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, we know the Policy plan chased the 49ers off a
football cliff. That franchise was destroyed by salary cap
mistakes. Currently, Jacksonville is also in trouble. Then there
are the Washington Redskins, who appear to be the cap-disaster of
the near future.
</P>
<P>
   To the credit of Jerry and Stephen, the Cowboys at least remain
competitive, despite constant cap squeezes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guesswork is involved at times, and so is luck,'' Jerry said.
``What has prevented us from falling into a mess like San Francisco
is being able to estimate and evaluate where we can move money
around. You need to stay aggressive. You also need to be very
careful. It's a juggling act. So far, we're OK. But the squeeze is
tight.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the Cowboys faced a potential cap crisis, but
Jones worked around that. Next year, due to the way contracts are
structured, will be another test. ``But frankly, I'm confident we
will have a handle on what's coming \Rin 2001\S, and also win again
under a salary cap system,'' Stephen Jones said. ``People ask me
when the big note is finally going to come due on us. But if we
continue to do our job on the cap, that note won't ever have to be
paid in full.''
</P>
<P>
   Football in the NFL has given way to this cap crud. The game
suffers, the owners make money, and baseball looks on with a
massive amount of envy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
