<SLUG> BC-NADER-MASTERCARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASTERCARD SUES NADER CAMPAIGN OVER TV AD PARODY 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mastercard International sued Ralph Nader's presidential
campaign Wednesday, saying that a Nader advertisement that parodies
one of the company's commercials violates its copyright and
trademark. The suit, filed in federal court in Manhattan, seeks $5
million in damages and an injunction preventing the campaign from
running the advertisement again.
</P>
<P>
   The Nader advertisement takes Gov. George W. Bush and Vice
President Al Gore to task on the need for campaign finance reform,
and for excluding Nader from the presidential debates. The
announcer reads, ``Grilled tenderloin for fund-raiser: $1,000 a
plate. Campaign ads filled with half-truths: $10 million. Promises
to special interest groups: over $10 billion. Finding out the
truth: priceless. There are some things money can't buy. Without
Ralph Nader in the presidential debates, the truth will come in
last.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nader campaign's premiere television ad, which began airing
in early August in major markets throughout the United States, will
continue to air in Los Angeles during the Democratic National
Convention, said Laura Jones, a spokeswoman for Nader. The campaign
plans to hold a news conference in Washington on Thursday to
respond to the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the 30-second ad has generated a ``tremendous
response.'' It has been successful, she said, in ``tapping into the
outrage'' for the way the current two-party political system works.
</P>
<P>
   ``This commercial has been successful precisely because it is
about how corporations are trying to shut down the political
process and shut out candidates who aren't beholden to them,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Chris O'Neill, vice president of global marketing for
Mastercard, based in Purchase, N.Y., said that the company had sent
a letter to the Nader campaign requesting that they stop airing the
ad. Discussions last week between Mastercard representatives and
the campaign ended without an agreement, O'Neill said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main goal is to stop the ad from running,'' O'Neill said.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Neill said that the company intends to ``protect the
ads,'' and that ``every day the ad airs, more damage is done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
