<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: DEVALUTION REJECTED
</P>
<P>
   President Fernando de la Rua told reporters he had no intention
of devaluing the Argentine peso or replacing the currency with the
U.S. dollar as suggested by former President Carlos Saul Menem. He
criticized his predecessor for publicly warning that Argentina was
on the brink of a devaluation or depression.
</P>
<P>
   CHILE: NEW RESTRAINTS ON PINOCHET
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Augusto Pinochet was stripped of his right to vote or enter
the Senate after Parliament was officially notified that the
Supreme Court had removed the former dictator's immunity as a
senator for life to face possible charges of human rights abuses.
Conservative senators promised to open a debate on the causes of
1973 coup that brought the general to power to show that Marxists
were seeking to start a revolution.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: FISHING CONFLICT
</P>
<P>
   A government fisheries boat rammed a boat manned by Quebec
Indians who were backing New Brunswick Indians in a dispute over
native fishing rights. The Indian boat was wheeling around the
federal boat, trying to keep fisheries agents from pulling up
lobster pots set by the Mi'kmaq natives of Miramichi, New
Brunswick.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: OUSTED LEADER'S APPEAL
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for deposed prime minister Nawaz Sharif told an appeals
court that his client had a right to divert a commercial flight
carrying Gen. Pervez Musharraf, the army chief he had just fired,
because he feared the general's arrival would destabilize the
country. Sharif was convicted of hijacking for diverting the flight
and was sentenced to two concurrent life terms.
</P>
<P>
   KASHMIR: ANTI-INDIA VIOLENCE
</P>
<P>
   Eight people were killed and 18 injured in violence in the state
of Kashmir and Jammu in incidents involving anti-India militants,
police said. In one, a grenade tossed at Indian security troops
missed and landed in a crowded market in Bijbehara, south of the
summer capital of Srinagar.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   MOZAMBIQUE: GOVERNMENT CRITICS HELD
</P>
<P>
   Police have detained five opposition party members in the port
town of Beira, saying they were planning to incite a nationwide
campaign of civil disobedience, the state news agency reported.
Officials in the opposition party, known as Renamo, denied such a
plot. But Renamo officials said party members were angry after
President Joaquim Chissano declined to appoint any Renamo officials
to provincial governorships last month.
</P>
</TEXT>
