<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-NOTEBOOK-0817-1stLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONVENTION NOTEBOOK: FROM DELEGATE DELAYS TO POLICE CHASES
 &HT;    Eds: Restores grafs lost in transmission
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Actress June Lockhart, best known for her TV roles
on ``Lassie'' and ``Lost in Space,'' watched a good portion of the
Democratic convention one night this week as she stood
shoulder-to-shoulder with photographers on the main camera stand
directly across from the podium on the convention floor. Lockhart
has been friends with many Washington-based photographers since the
mid-80's, having met some during Ronald Reagan's frequent trips to
his presidential ranch in California. She attends the annual White
House News Photographers Awards dinner in Washington every year.
</P>
<P>
   As the convention nears its end, there have been mounting
complaints about transportation provided for delegates and members
of the press. Some buses, designated to shuttle them from their
hotels to the downtown convention site and back, have showed up
very late.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, some delegates probably wished their bus hadn't
shown up at all. A bus load of Georgia delegates wound up calling
police on a cell phone when a shuttle driver refused to let them
off at their hotel. Three Los Angeles sheriff's vehicles, lights
flashing, stopped the bus and escorted passengers from the vehicle,
the delegates said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is the drivers haven't been instructed properly,''
Georgia party chairman David Worley told irritated delegates, some
of whom said they rode around for two hours on a bus when the
driver got lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been enormous screw-ups with transportation,''
Worley said. ``It's a major problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Each day of the convention is like any other party for the Ohio
delegates. Have a good time. Play hard. But when it's over, take me
home.
</P>
<P>
   That last part hasn't been easy. On Monday a violent clash
between police and protesters blocked streets after the convention
closed. Those fortunate enough to get a seat on a shuttle bus were
stuck and others had to walk more than a mile just to search for a
taxi.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, post-convention sailing appeared to be smooth for about
50 delegates as their shuttle bus headed back to the hotel. Then
came the crash
</P>
<P>
   A $50,000 sports car rammed a $40,000 SUV next to the bus on a
crowded Los Angeles street. A police officer accompanying the bus
riders got off to assist those involved in the accident.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 minutes passed for the tired group before the officer
got back on the bus. He pulled out his notebook and asked, ``Okay,
who saw what happened?''
</P>
<P>
   The officer smiled and didn't pursue the questioning _ just in
time to avoid another riot at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's a sobering thought for Democrats who think their
convention has viewers glued to their TV sets. Late Monday night,
after the convention session ended, several Los Angeles television
stations broke away from regular programming for live coverage of a
high-speed chase. TV helicopters followed the dramatic chase as LA
police pursued a red vehicle as it sped around the city. It
eventually crashed and the driver was arrested. Later, a recap of
local TV ratings for at least one station showed that it attracted
22 percent of viewers while other stations' recaps of convention
events drew only 4 percent to 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Black Caucus members rubbed shoulders with the
Hollywood elite during a luncheon at Paramount Studios on
Wednesday. As the program opened, the usually imposing and serious
Jim Clyburn, the Democratic congressman from South Carolina who
chairs the caucus, took the podium. He soberly looked out over the
star-dotted audience. It included Telma Hopkins, whose initial fame
came from being part of Tony Orlando's Dawn, the singer's backup
crooners.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good Lord has been good to me today,'' Clyburn announced.
``He made it so that I would not get to meet Telma Hopkins until I
was 60 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because,'' he added, ``I spent a certain amount of time in my
former life drooling over Telma Hopkins.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins giggled and turned a deep shade of red.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Howard Metzenbaum, the feisty 83-year-old former three-term
senator from Ohio, has spent much of his time at the Democratic
convention trying to motivate delegates to fight for party
candidates. After a rousing speech Tuesday to the Ohio delegation,
Metzenbaum got so many handshakes, hugs and hurrahs that he
proclaimed: ``I think I'll run as a write-in.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Gov. Roy Barnes and his wife, Marie, celebrated their
30th wedding anniversary at the convention. ``With Rodeo Drive
right out here, I don't know if I'm going to be able to afford
it,'' Barnes joked. Georgia delegates stayed in Hollywood, minutes
from the glitzy shopping boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reporters Kathey Pruitt and William Hershey contributed to this
report.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
