u f BC-HP-EARNINGS-NYT &LR;      08-16 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HP-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEWLETT-PACKARD CITES 23 PERCENT QUARTERLY GAIN, BEATING
FORECASTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Hewlett-Packard Co. on Wednesday reported
quarterly earnings that beat analysts' estimates, driven primarily
by strong sales of personal computers and printers. Its board also
approved a stock split.
</P>
<P>
   For the third quarter ended July 31, Hewlett-Packard reported
earnings of $1.05 billion, or 99 cents a diluted share, up 23
percent from $853 million, or 66 cents a share, in the comparable
period a year ago. Revenue rose 15 percent, to $11.82 billion from
$10.32 billion, in the third quarter of fiscal 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding equity gains, Hewlett-Packard had earnings of 97 cents
a diluted share, compared with similarly adjusted earnings of 71
cents a share in the comparable period a year ago. Analysts had
expected the company to earn 85 cents a share, according to First
Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard reported its results after the close of the
market. Its shares closed at $120 each, up $9.56, on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts attributed the jump in earnings largely to
higher-than-expected interest income, a more favorable tax rate and
other nonoperating contributors. Overall revenue growth of 15
percent was merely in line with expectations, they said, and the 13
percent sales growth of the crucial Unix business was
disappointing, particularly in comparison with sales growth of 42
percent in the most recent quarter for Sun Microsystems Inc., the
Unix market leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``The top line was sort of in line with the target, and the
bottom line above, but there were significant contributions to the
bottom line,'' said Laura Conigliaro, an analyst with Goldman,
Sachs, noting that tax considerations added 3 cents to earnings per
share, with 6 cents coming from higher interest income. ``It's a
good quarter, with evidence that there are better things to come,
with some of the strongest evidence from some ironic areas, PCs and
printers, where others seem to be struggling,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Milunovich of Merrill Lynch had a more positive
interpretation of the results, which marked the end of Carly
Fiorina's first four quarters as president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when you take out the extraordinary items, they appear to
have beat our estimates for operating income,'' he said. ``I think
it shows that HP continues to be on the recovery trail, that
Carly's initiatives are beginning to pay off, and that the company
is beginning to show some consistency in earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Hewlett-Packard saw declining revenue from commercial
desktop personal computers in the quarter, its home PC business
grew 62 percent in revenue and notebooks grew 93 percent. The
imaging and printing systems segment _ laser and inkjet printing,
and imaging devices _ grew 15 percent in revenue year over year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year at this time, we committed to becoming a more
aggressive and focused HP, delivering strong top and bottom line
growth on a consistent basis,'' Fiorina said in a statement.
``Today's results demonstrate the tremendous progress we're making
in all of our businesses around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Hewlett-Packard said its Unix server business had grown
by only 13 percent in revenue year over year, it reported order
growth of 23 percent in dollars and 43 percent in units. Fiorina
said the company had gained market share at the low end, increased
its lead in the mid-range, but slowed at the high end, in
anticipation of the launching of a new high-end server line, called
SuperDome, in mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   ``How is it that their sales of high-end product dry up when
they're in product transition while Sun's accelerate?'' said Daniel
Kunstler, an analyst with J.P. Morgan. ``I would say a relative
disappointment in Unix was offset by color printing and a strong
consumer business in general. Their sense of purpose really should
be geared toward Unix because that's where there's margin, and
that's where they've lost leadership they think they can regain.''
</P>
<P>
   A stock split of two shares for one, which was announced
Wednesday, will be effective Oct. 27. The quarterly results reflect
continuing operations and exclude the industrial instrument
business that was spun off this year as Agilent Technologies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
