<SLUG> BC-OPED-DEMS-BLACKS-BOSITIS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY BLACKS DOUBT LIEBERMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Thursday, Aug. 17, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By DAVID A. BOSITIS    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At the Democratic convention this week, good
manners reign supreme. Despite many doubts, most African-American
delegates are supporting Al Gore's choice for a running mate, Sen.
Joseph Lieberman. Even Maxine Waters, the outspoken congresswoman
from California, has announced that after talking to Lieberman
about his views on affirmative action, she is now on board.
</P>
<P>
   But outward party unity doesn't mean that internal fissures have
disappeared. Indeed, the selection of Lieberman points to some real
differences between Gore and black Democrats. And these differences
are important to his chances in November.
</P>
<P>
   There is general agreement among political analysts that the
election will be close and that the band of states between New
Jersey and Missouri, (plus North Carolina, Georgia, Florida,
Louisiana, Arkansas and Tennessee) are likely to determine the next
president.
</P>
<P>
   These states have significant numbers of black voters, who are
reliably Democratic, that is, if they go to the polls. To win this
election, Gore will have to ensure that black turnout is high.
</P>
<P>
   The problem? It's hard to imagine that his selection of
Lieberman will galvanize them to vote. As a pollster and researcher
who has long followed African-American politics, I know that of all
the people mentioned as Gore's possible running mate, Lieberman was
the one least likely to appeal to African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   There are political reasons why this is so. Despite his
reassurances this week, he was not known as a supporter of
affirmative action, especially after his favorable comments about
California's proposition that outlawed affirmative action in all
state programs. In addition, for four years, he has been chairman
of the Democratic Leadership Council, which represents moderate and
conservative Democrats as a counterweight to liberals like Jesse
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers have said that anti-Semitism among a minority of
the black population could play a role. There have been several
surveys, most notably those done for the Anti-Defamation League,
that suggest African-Americans are more anti-Semitic than white
Americans. I don't entirely buy the results of these surveys, in
part because anti-Semitism, like racism, is a difficult thing to
assess.
</P>
<P>
   In surveys, for example, I have heard African-Americans refer to
Jewish wealth, but many working class and poor African-Americans
talk that way about all white people.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the Democratic ticket, there is more a sense of
``why not us?'' Many black Americans feel they have been the most
loyal Democrats and wonder why a black politician hasn't been
selected by now. This feeling is not about anti-Semitism, but about
once again being left out.
</P>
<P>
   The root of black ambivalence about Lieberman, however, could be
more specific. The vice president chose the one man who carries
with him an implicit, some would say open, repudiation of Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's speech calling Clinton's actions immoral in the
Monica Lewinsky scandal was widely praised. Indeed, after Lieberman
was selected, this factor was cited favorably, and seen as helping
Al Gore distance himself from the president.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a news flash for you: Black Americans want to celebrate
Clinton. They don't care about his personal life. During his
administration, African-Americans have prospered as never before.
Incomes have risen faster than those of whites. Affirmative action
has been protected. Clinton made Africa part of his foreign policy.
The cabinet has been inclusive.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Bill Clinton already has a legacy _ he is the first
president to fully embrace black America.
</P>
<P>
   In the last eight years, African-Americans have gotten used to
being taken seriously. They want that influence to continue, and
are waiting for Gore to send a signal that it will. Unfortunately,
Al Gore's selection of Lieberman sends a different signal.
</P>
<P>
   Gore now finds himself in a position of having to assure black
voters that they will have a real voice in his administration, that
their concerns will be addressed. The pollsters can talk all they
want about reaching out to swing voters. But Al Gore knows he
cannot win without a high black turnout.
</P>
<P>
   (David A. Bositis is senior political analyst at the Joint
Center for Political and Economic Studies, a group that researches
issues involving blacks.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
