A3848 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-MILITARY-PAY-WIL     08-16 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-MILITARY-PAY-WILLIAMS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GOP'S PAY GAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Thursday, Aug. 17, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By CINDY WILLIAMS    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Democrats are saying this week in Los Angeles
that the military is strong and fit, while campaigning Republicans
contend that the Clinton administration has run America's defenses
down. It's a complex issue, but in at least one aspect _ military
pay _ Republican scorn is misplaced. The GOP platform says
Americans in uniform face a 13 percent ``pay gap'' relative to
their civilian counterparts. But when President Clinton took
office, the gap was already 11.5 percent, all accumulated in the
Reagan and Bush presidencies.
</P>
<P>
   The gap the Republicans cite does not reflect a direct
calculation of pay differences between the military and the private
sector; it compares pay raises since 1982. Proponents of higher
military pay like to use that year as their starting point because
it makes the gap look as large as possible. Basically, their
calculation presumes that since the draft was abolished in 1973,
the military has been paid fairly only once: in 1982, after two
years of double-digit pay increases under Jimmy Carter and Ronald
Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1983 budget, Reagan struck a bargain with Congress to
limit the military's pay raise to 4 percent, even though civilian
wage growth was twice that high. That created the gap _ making it 4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the 1980s, the gap continued to widen; the military
received raises that were generally smaller than those in the
private sector.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans might of course point out that Democratic congresses
passed the pay bills. But year after year in the 1980s, Republican
defense secretaries specifically requested raises for the military
that lagged behind the private sector. Most of the time, Congress
authorized what was requested.
</P>
<P>
   The emergence of the so-called pay gap did not signal that
Reagan and President George Bush did not respect or appreciate the
military; nor does its small growth under Clinton mean that he has
run the military down.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the 1980s and 1990s, administrations and congresses
worked to strike a balance between the military's needs and the
urgency of reducing federal deficits. At the same time, defense
commanders tried to balance the military's needs. Good pay is one
of several tools to attract and retain capable troops. As long as
the services were able to do this, pay raises were capped in favor
of spending on weapons, force structure and training. When
recruiting and retention faltered, defense leaders added more to
pay and other benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy paid off. In the Persian Gulf war in 1991, with the
reported pay gap already at more than 11 percent, the United States
fielded the best equipped and trained fighting forces in the world.
This year, after two years of weakness in recruiting, all four
services appear to be meeting their goals. If that success
continues, the Pentagon's priorities may swing again, and future
military officials may choose to devote scarce resources to
something else besides pay increases.
</P>
<P>
   (Cindy Williams, senior research fellow at MIT, was assistant
director for national security in the Congressional Budget Office
from 1994 to 1997.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
