<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3858 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-CELL-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      08-16 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELL-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE MORE THAN A BIG ASSAULT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The folks who made ``The Cell'' _ screenwriter Mark Protosevich
and Tarsem Singh, an award-winning TV ad director whose music
videos include REM's ``Losing My Religion'' _ claim that they were
out to take the next step beyond ``Silence of the Lambs'' with this
serial killer mindtrip.
</P>
<P>
   What they've come up with is more like the evil stepsister of
``What Dreams May Come,'' an over-the-top collection of
art-directed, superficially surreal images that impart sadistic
wish-dreams rather than New Agey muddle hugs. It's imaginatively
designed, undeniably, but with all the aesthetic taste of a fetish
fashion show _ and less heart.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Lopez wears many strange costumes, extreme makeup and a
grave demeanor as child psychologist Catherine Deane. She's
involved in a long-running, high-tech experiment to reach into the
shut-down brain of a young coma victim _ whose parents just happen
to be as rich as Microsoft, but who are growing tired of
bankrolling the slow process to revive their son.
</P>
<P>
   This involves Catherine's entering the kid's mindscape, trying
to gain his trust, then theoretically leading him out of his inner
prison, which looks like the Sahara, only with derelict ships. The
apparatus that enables this effort suspends Catherine and the boy
in a sealed chamber, clad in rubberized, circuitry-loaded
jumpsuits, where she's electro-chemically put into her own deep
sleep state in order to dream her way into his.
</P>
<P>
   If you think that sounds kinky, you ain't seen nothing yet.
Somewhere in the adjacent desert, a complete whacko named Carl
(Vincent D'Onofrio) is kidnapping young women, sealing them in a
hidden kind of fishbowl cell and videotaping their terror as the
chamber automatically fills to the top with water. He retrieves
said tapes for later self-pleasuring (the metal rings pierced into
his back also play a part in this lovely ritual) and bleaches the
drowned corpses to look like dolls before dumping them in
convenient arroyos.
</P>
<P>
   And if you think that's sick ... obsessive FBI investigator
Peter Novak (Vince Vaughn) tracks Carl down, but not before the
murderer suffers a brain seizure. The only hope of finding his
latest victim before she's automatically submerged is to send
Catherine into the dormant lunatic's mind. This is, as you might
imagine, potentially dangerous for the visitor's psyche, too,
seeing as how Carl's head is filled with horse-dissecting systems,
medieval torture methods and memories of his own twisted child
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   But hey, the clock is ticking ...
</P>
<P>
   Tarsem, as the director prefers to be called, rotates his
frames, step-cuts his montage, tosses in vulgarized ``2001'' light
shows, switches film stocks willy nilly and distorts sound like
crazy, and those are among the more sober tricks he employs to
remind us that we're in a crazy dreamscape where anything can
happen and, as characters keep reminding one another, ``nothing is
real.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not, but a lot of it is really disgusting. Tarsem and his
crew have genuinely grotesque imaginations, and the horrors
depicted in ``The Cell'' are as unpleasant to watch as anything
modern cinema has unleashed. Perhaps because they're wrapped up in
such a hokey, sci-fi/fantasy context, the graphic mortifications
lack the soul-chilling charge similarly upsetting scenes lent to
films such as ``Lambs'' and ``Seven.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, those pictures were made by movie directors, who knew
something about how much to show and what to leave to a viewer's
spiked imagination. Straight as he comes from the ad world, Tarsem,
whatever his gifts for composing a scene, has not yet learned that
throwing everything he's got in someone's face isn't necessarily
the most effective visual storytelling strategy.
</P>
<P>
   And even when the stuff he's hurling isn't designed to make you
hurl, it's still overwrought imagery with no variation in volume
control. When every shot in a movie is meant to wow you, none of
them really does the job. A lot of work went into making ``The
Cell'' a state-of-the-art sensory assault, but you'd get
essentially the same effect by locking people in a small room with
someone who won't stop screaming for two hours. &QL; 
---The film: ``The Cell'' (R; violence, nudity, language, drug use,
sex, children in jeopardy). &QL; 
The stars: Jennifer Lopez, Vince Vaughn, Vincent D'Onofrio,
Marianne Jean-Baptiste, Dylan Baker. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Tarsem Singh. Written by Mark
Protosevich. Produced by Julio Caro and Eric McLeod. Released by
New Line Cinema. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 47 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 2033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
