<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGAAIMEE0817-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Rebecca McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. - Having spent the past year battling the University
of Georgia, Aimee Bogrow is thrilled to be living in a residence
hall, looking forward to studying elementary Japanese and planning
on getting football tickets for her dad, a UGA alum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any ill feelings toward the university and don't
want there to be any grudges,'' she said. ``My intention is to go
to school and enjoy my classes. The race issue is now demolished,
and I won one for the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bogrow, 19, was one of three women who sued UGA, saying that its
admissions policies were unconstitutionally discriminatory because
they provided preferences to male and African-American applicants.
</P>
<P>
   In July, U.S. District Court Judge B. Avant Edenfield ruled that
UGA's use of race in admissions decisions was discriminatory, a
decision the university is appealing. On Tuesday, President Michael
Adams announced that UGA would suspend the use of race as a factor
in borderline admissions cases until the appeal is settled.
</P>
<P>
   Gender was removed as an admissions factor last year.
</P>
<P>
   Along with plaintiffs Jennifer Johnson and Molly Ann
Beckenhauer, Bogrow was sent a letter of acceptance a few weeks
ago. Johnson had already planned to attend Mercer University in the
fall but intends to come to Athens for spring semester. Like
Bogrow, Beckenhauer will start classes today, the first day of fall
semester, said Lee Parks, the women's attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Bogrow said she never expected to have such a role. She said had
been taught to stand up for herself and others, but hadn't thought
of joining a lawsuit against the state's largest university.
</P>
<P>
   She thought that if she followed her mother's advice and made
herself academically attractive, by making good grades at North
Springs High, by doing well on the SAT and by playing in school
bands, that she would go to UGA, as both parents did. But she
wasn't accepted initially, and her disappointment was almost
devastating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept thinking, where did I screw up?'' she said. ``Who
thinks about admissions policies, and exactly how they work? As the
lawsuit grew, I realized that the admissions standards weren't
right in the first place, and that even if I was admitted, I
wouldn't drop the suit until they dropped the race issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Bogrow found a job at MediaPlay and took 15 hours of classes at
Georgia Perimeter College. Denied admission to UGA for fall 1999,
she hoped to be heading to Athens in January 2000, but as the weeks
passed she knew her education would be delayed longer. At UGA, she
hopes to find a major appropriate for a career in law, an interest
she said has strengthened over the past few months. It's been a
valuable time for her, she said, teaching her ``that two or three
people can really make a difference in how the world is run.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
