<HEADLINE>
ARAFAT ANNOUNCES RETHINKING OF PLAN TO DECLARE PALESTINIAN STATE
NEXT MONTH 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, said on
Wednesday that the Palestinian leadership was ``reassessing'' its
plan to make a unilateral declaration of a Palestinian state on
Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
   That raised the possibility that the Palestinians will not,
after all, take a step that Israel has said would end all prospects
for an early peace agreement between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat made his remarks in Jakarta, the Indonesian capital,
where he stopped on a three-week tour of more than 20 Arab,
European and Asian nations that he began after the Camp David talks
failed last month. After a meeting with the Indonesian president,
Abdurrahman Wahid, Arafat said that the Palestinian leadership
would make a decision on the statehood declaration ``at the
beginning of next month,'' when a Palestinian umbrella group
controlled by Arafat, the Palestine Central Council, is to meet in
the Gaza Strip
</P>
<P>
   Although Arafat declined to say what the decision was likely to
be, his remarks were in keeping with reports from Western diplomats
in contact with the Palestinian leadership, who have said in recent
days that Arafat was on the verge of deferring the statehood
pronouncement, perhaps until November or later.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian leader hinted as much when he returned last
weekend from visits to Russia and other European states, and said
that he had failed to round up international backing for an early
statehood declaration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are reassessing this,'' Arafat said on Wednesday, after his
meeting with Wahid at Indonesia's presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
   But he stopped short of stating that the declaration would
definitely be deferred, saying that the Palestinians had received
letters from the Clinton administration and from the European
Union, promising that renewed negotiations on a peace pact would
aim at reaching a final agreement before Sept. 13, the anniversary
of the 1993 Oslo accords that launched the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   The aim of the accords was to reach a final agreement within
seven years that would settle contentious issues like Jerusalem,
and seal a mutual recognition by Israel and a Palestinian state of
each others' sovereignty and borders.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli newspapers have taken two views of the Palestinian
maneuvering. Some contend that Arafat is retreating from the
September date, bruised from the response on his travels. However,
another view that has gained ground is that he may privately
welcome the opportunity to maneuver himself out of the commitment
by blaming the lack of international support.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli leader, Prime Minister Ehud Barak, had warned
repeatedly that Israel would retaliate if the Palestinians
pre-empted a final peace agreement by formally proclaiming a state.
Barak and his top officials have said that one likely option would
be to counter the Palestinian move with the formal annexation of
145 Jewish settlements on the West Bank _ a key issue in the peace
talks _ as Israeli sovereign territory.
</P>
<P>
   Any such sequence would be likely to test to the breaking point
the relative calm that has prevailed between Israelis and
Palestinians in recent times, particularly in the volatile areas
around the Jewish settlements and in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Camp David negotiations collapsed last month,
primarily because of disagreements over Jerusalem, Israeli and
Palestinian officials have pointed to the absence of serious armed
clashes as a sign of the two sides' ability to work together, and
to maintain an atmosphere conducive to renewed negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Officials on both sides insisted again on Wednesday that they
would not compromise on their claims to East Jerusalem, but moves
towards a resumption of full-scale peace talks continued to gather
speed. For the first time since the Camp David talks, teams of
senior officials from the two sides met for what were described as
substantive exchanges on Jerusalem and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli team was led by Shlomo Ben-Ami, the acting foreign
minister, and by Gilad Sher, an aide to Barak. The Palestinian side
was led by Saeb Erekat and Mohammed Dahlan, senior aides to Arafat
who accompanied him to Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   Before the talks, Ben-Ami sought to dampen suggestions that a
new summit meeting between Barak and Arafat could occur soon,
possibly as early as mid-September. Speculation had been spurred
earlier in the day by an announcement from Washington that Dennis
Ross, the American official who has frequently shuttled between the
two sides in his capacity as the State Department's special peace
envoy, would arrive in Israel on Thursday, several days earlier
than previously announced.
</P>
<P>
   ``We mustn't raise our expectations too high because the issues
are very, very difficult,'' Ben-Ami said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The public mood ahead of the Ross talks was soured, at least
temporarily, by an incident in the early hours of Wednesday in
which Israeli troops shot and killed a 72-year-old Palestinian man
in a fusillade in Surda, a Palestinian village north of the West
Bank town of Ramallah. According to Israeli and Palestinian
accounts that were broadly similar, the victim, Mahmoud Abdullah,
who held U.S. citizenship, drew fire from an Israeli patrol when he
shot at the soldiers with a pistol from his rooftop.
</P>
<P>
   He died later after the Israeli troops, fearing further attacks,
held back Palestinian and Israeli medics from reaching the victim
for what family members said was at least an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Family members, including one of the victim's sons, Hisham
Abdullah, said that the elder Abdullah appeared to have gone to the
roof at about 3 a.m. fearing that noises he had heard outside
signaled a burglary attempt. Hisham Abdullah, who is employed as a
reporter by the Agence France-Presse news agency in Jerusalem, said
his father had called out ``Who's there?'' before apparently firing
a shot into the dark. The Israelis' return fire, which left the
Abdullahs' house pitted with bullet holes, struck Mahmoud Abdullah
in the head.
</P>
<P>
   The incident dominated radio and television broadcasts in
Israeli and in Palestinian-controlled areas for much of the day,
but did not lead to any immediate disturbances. Controversy over
the incident centered on the Israeli decision to open fire, which
was described as ``murder'' by the Palestinian communications
minister, Immad Falouji, who rushed to the scene.
</P>
<P>
   But an Israeli commander, Col. Gal Hirsch, said Israeli
investigators remained unconvinced about the Abdullah brothers'
account of why their father had opened fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still haven't got a clue as to what induced him to act in
this way,'' he said. ``But he fired, and when we're fired upon we
return fire and hit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
