<DOCNO> NYT20000816.0369 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3865 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-KINGS-OF-COMEDY-REVIE     08-16 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KINGS-OF-COMEDY-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT ORIGINAL, BUT STILL THE KINGS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Much has been made of the popularity of movies starring
African-American comedians this summer. But the success of such
witless vulgarities as ``Big Momma's House,'' ``Scary Movie'' and
``Nutty Professor II: The Klumps'' probably has far more to do with
America's love for a good fart joke than it does any mass
acceptance of African-American headliners. Low comedy has always
found a wide audience.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to see a movie featuring black comedians actually
offering funny and intelligent observations about America and race
relations, go see ``The Original Kings of Comedy.'' This concert
film, shot by Spike Lee, shows that the most profitable comedy
concert tour in history (the Kings grossed $37 million last year)
was also one of the funniest.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Kings'' revue stars Steve Harvey, Cedric the Entertainer,
D.L. Hughley and Bernie Mac. Cedric and Harvey star on the WB's
``Steve Harvey Show.'' Hughley headlines UPN's ``The Hughleys.''
But don't hold their iffy sitcom backgrounds against these guys.
They are masterful performers, superb storytellers and keen _
although not always particularly insightful _ observers of popular
culture.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey is the MC of the show, coming on first and then during
the intervals between comics. He has many of the movie's best
moments, including riffs on why black audiences didn't respond to
``Titanic'' and a classic baiting of an audience member who had
left his seat before the intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey's best material takes hip-hop music to task, for reasons
both innocuous (the distorted sound) and profound (lyrics filled
with misogyny and violence). Why, Harvey asks, did the Temptations,
despite their involved dance chorography, need just one microphone,
while rappers have 40 people on stage, each with a mike? And why
does anyone want to hear about blood-soaked T-shirts, when back in
the day of Earth, Wind &AMP; Fire and the Ohio Players, T-shirts would
be wet from sexual healing?
</P>
<P>
   Cedric, Harvey's television co-star, is a gifted physical
comedian, able to throw his barrel-chested frame into break-dancing
moves and deftly imitate the exaggerated ways different
neighborhood types smoke cigarettes. Cedric, like Harvey, is
decidedly old-school; his material has a graciousness and geniality
that's absent from so much of the bile that passes for comedy these
days.
</P>
<P>
   The other two headliners _ Hughley and Bernie Mac _ have plenty
of bite, though, particularly Mac, who often excuses his explosive
rants, stating, ``I'm saying what you're scared of saying.'' His
routine uses the ``MF'' expletive more often than a Samuel L.
Jackson movie. (At one point, Mac even breaks down the word,
explaining its usefulness in conversation.)
</P>
<P>
   Mac's edgy humor is most reminiscent of Richard Pryor and the
young Eddie Murphy, whose style (and concert films) obviously
inspired all these guys to some extent. Hughley is a little more
accessible, scoring best when explaining why black people usually
can't afford to be anorexic and have no need for extreme sports
like bungee jumping.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's too much like a lynching for us,'' Hughley says.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, making his third documentary and second concert film,
captures the excitement of the setting and the thrill the audience
members derive from both the performers and their own, oversized
reactions. There are a few backstage moments, but mostly this movie
is about the jokes, which come fast and furious. That most of them
are funny makes ``The Original Kings of Comedy'' one of the bright
spots of a pretty dull summer. &QL; 
---The film: ``The Original Kings of Comedy'' (R; for strong
language). &QL; 
The stars: Steve Harvey, D.L. Hughley, Cedric the Entertainer,
Bernie Mac. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Spike Lee. Released by Paramount
Pictures. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 50 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
