<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3867 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BRIT-TELECOM-GERMANY-     08-16 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRIT-TELECOM-GERMANY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH TELECOM EXPECTED TO RAISE STAKE IN GERMAN CONCERN 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ British Telecommunications PLC is expected to announce
Thursday that it will take control of Viag Interkom, a German
telephone company, by doubling its ownership stake to 90 percent in
a deal worth about 6 billion euros ($5.46 billion), according to
executives close to the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The move is part of British Telecom's increasing desire to take
controlling interests in its investments rather than minority
positions. British Telecom currently holds a 45 percent interest in
Viag Interkom.
</P>
<P>
   According to the executives, British Telecom, Britain's biggest
telephone company, agreed in principle Wednesday to the buyout of
Viag Interkom's other major shareholder, E.On AG, a German energy
concern, which also holds a 45 percent stake in the German
telephone company.
</P>
<P>
   Telenor AS, a Norwegian telephone company, owns the remaining 10
percent of Viag Interkom.
</P>
<P>
   While many formerly state-owned European telephone operators
like Deutsche Telekom and France Telecom have been on an aggressive
path recently by making prominent acquisitions _ Deutsche Telekom
has a deal to acquire VoiceStream Wireless of the United States for
$50 billion and France Telecom bought Orange PLC of Britain for
$37.5 billion _ British Telecom has clearly remained in the
background, plotting its next move with what some would call
English reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Though British Telecom's buyout of Viag Interkom is somewhat
prosaic by the standards set by its acquisitive European rivals,
the deal is an important step in the British telephone operator's
quest to create a pan-European footprint and gain a foothold in
Germany, one of the biggest markets for telecommunications,
particularly for wireless services.
</P>
<P>
   Viag Interkom is the third largest telephone operator in
Germany, controlling a fixed line network as well as a wireless
network. Viag Interkom's real attraction is its wireless network,
which has more than 2 million subscribers. While the wireless unit,
called E2, is small in comparison to its competitors _ it ranks as
the fourth largest _ it is one of the last available avenues into
the mobile telephone market in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Viag Interkom is currently in the midst of Germany's high-stakes
auction to win a third generation mobile telephone license that
will allow it to offer fast wireless data services. Like the
auction in Britain, which cost telephone operators here $35.5
billion in total, Germany's auction is also testing the wills and
pocketbooks of the bidders by reaching even loftier bidding
heights.
</P>
<P>
   Now the bid totals in Germany reached 47.7 billion euros, or
about $43.4 billion. The bids are seen as a bellwether for similar
auctions to be conducted in the future in both Europe and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Viag Interkom's most recent bid is for about 7.9 billion
Deutsche marks, or about $3.7 billion at current exchange rates. It
is crucial for British Telecom that Viag Interkom secure a license
so that it will be able to offer seamless third generation services
across all of the networks it owns to compete with the likes of
Vodafone Airtouch PLC, the world's largest mobile telephone
company.
</P>
<P>
   Viag Interkom's chairman, Maximilian Ardelt, said recently he
was certain that the company would win a license in the German
auctions, which are expected to end shortly.
</P>
<P>
   For E.On, which was created by the merger between the two German
utility companies Veba and Viag, the deal fits its strategy of
selling assets that are beyond its core business, allowing it to
focus more closely on its traditional strength, power generation
and energy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
