<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRE-FIGHTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. FOREST SERVICE SCRAMBLES TO FIND ENOUGH FIREFIGHTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Its bureaucracy stretched thin by the burdens of
battling wildfires scorching the West, the U.S. Forest Service has
begun bringing back retired workers, hiring employees' spouses and
taking other unusual steps to increase the number of people
available to fight the fires.
</P>
<P>
   The measures underscore longstanding concerns that the agency
does not have enough trained staff to handle a summer with severe
and widespread forest fires.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the inherent depth for fire seasons like this
one now,'' said Harry Croft, deputy director at the fire and
aviation management division of the forest service. ``We need a
massive injection of new people into this organization, or in 10
years, we are going to be sucking swamp water.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael P. Dombeck, chief of the Forest Service, sent a
memorandum to staff members in late July encouraging them to lend a
hand with the firefighting efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are experiencing shortages in virtually every incident
management position,'' Dombeck wrote, reminding his staff that ``we
all have roles and responsibilities during fire emergencies.''
</P>
<P>
   All Forest Service employees, regardless of job description, are
encouraged to undergo training so they can help fight fires, often
in a management or administrative capacity.
</P>
<P>
   The agency was unable to provide an estimate of the number of
staff members who have volunteered.
</P>
<P>
   Since the distribution of the memorandum, the fires have
significantly worsened, and the agency is scrambling to get enough
people into the field. In addition to encouraging administrative,
management and other office workers to abandon their desks for the
field, the agency is hiring retired employees, the spouses of
current ones and people who live near the fires.
</P>
<P>
   Retired workers often have skills that are in short supply,
Croft said. They can, for example, manage the money and paperwork
needed to pay contract workers hired at fire sites, and they can
make sure equipment is properly cared for and effectively deployed,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other workers are needed for jobs like driving trucks, providing
food and directing traffic near the fires.
</P>
<P>
   The Forest Service, a branch of the Agriculture Department, has
been criticized for much of the last decade for not having enough
employees trained to fight fires. In 1994, after one of the most
severe fire seasons in history, the agency set the goal of
``preparing 75 percent of its work force to be trained, qualified
and available to support fire emergencies by the year 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   That goal proved too ambitious; the agency estimates that only
about 50 percent of its staff is properly trained now.
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of
Congress, reported in August that if more Forest Service employees
were not trained, the service's ability to fight fires would be
greatly compromised. The GAO recommended making it a requirement
that ``all employees become qualified, in some manner, to
contribute to fighting fires.''
</P>
<P>
   But Croft said that was not practical because the agency had
evolved, and specialization of the work force was now necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Another report, released in January and commissioned by Dombeck,
said that the agency's ability to adequately fight large fires was
``diminishing'' because of significant changes in its work force.
Those changes include a shrinking services staff, a reduced
willingness among employees to ``support emergency fire efforts
occurring away from their assigned locations'' and the perception
that ``active fire participation is not career enhancing.''
</P>
<P>
   The best way to solve the current staffing problems, the report
said, is to create a national organization dedicated exclusively to
fighting large wildfires. That would mean abandoning the tradition
of encouraging all employees to be trained to fight fires.
</P>
<P>
   Croft, who endorsed the recommendation, said that times had
changed. ``We can no longer rely on people's good will to fight
these fires,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
