<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-CYBER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYBERSPACE CAMPING COULD LEAD TO OUTDOOR ADVENTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS COCOLES  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Want to know how to noodle a catfish? Does
spending a week snow camping sound like a cool way to forget about
the summer heat? Interested in joining the Christian Deer Hunter's
Association?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not. But if you're in search of outdoor adventure - from
the bizarre to the more traditional - look no further than
cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem ironic that you can learn a lot about activities
that actually require you to leave the chair in front of your
computer and go outside, but you'd be surprised what you can find
on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   I recently took such an odyssey through the Internet, and was
exposed to these valuable morsels: building the perfect igloo; the
gospel according to rock star/bowhunter Ted Nugent on his United
Sportsmen of America Web site; the art of kicksledding (It's a
Finnish snow sport touted as a ``physical activity for the
millennium.'')
</P>
<P>
   And I never once got sunburned, seasick or stung by mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   But I did find some intriguing and informative Web sites for
those wanting to experience the great outdoors as a novice or
veteran. Here are some of the best:
</P>
<P>
   The river wild: Whitewater rafting fans should check out
California Creekin' (www.creekin.net).
</P>
<P>
   River rafting has a lot of class to it. A river's dangerous
waters are ranked from Class I (being the tamest) to Class V (for
experts only).
</P>
<P>
   California Creekin' is the perfect site to check a river and
make sure a run is the right one for your trip. The Kern River
(Class II-III), from Kern Powerhouse No.3 to Isabella Reservoir
east of Bakersfield, is one of the close-to-L.A. trips highlighted.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best training run in Southern California,'' says
the description of the 2- to 4-mile (one-hour-or-longer) journey.
``There are many campgrounds along the north fork Kern, and many
nearby motels if you prefer not to rough it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gone fishing: California's fishing options are as diverse as the
state itself. A good place to find out why is www.calfishing.com.
</P>
<P>
   Don't have a boat? Check out the site's salute to float tubing,
``the poor kid's way of getting out on the water.''
</P>
<P>
   The Barni Zone should not be missed for any angler with a sense
of humor, though an introduction warns: ``Some anglers may become
offended by the remarks made in this section, but nothing is meant
to be personally demeaning.''
</P>
<P>
   The site's message board offers information on where the big
ones are biting.
</P>
<P>
   Go climb a rock: If you don't have a fear of heights, log on to
www.vertical-adventures.com for the thrill of a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Vertical Adventures Rock Climbing School offers courses
year-around, ranging from one-day classes to multi-day seminars to
advanced courses that focus on rescue techniques.
</P>
<P>
   If the name of the peak doesn't scare you, the Idyllwild Rock
Climbing School is offering classes and guided climbs up
!ital!Suicide Rock!off! in the San Jacinto Mountains through
August.
</P>
<P>
   Wild thing: L.A. Wild (lawild.rivals.com) is the quintessential
site for a weekend of exploring without having to drive far.
</P>
<P>
   Among the trips featured: hiking to the summit of Mount
Baden-Powell in the San Gabriel Mountains and sportfishing off the
Baja coast.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site's motto is ``Explore The Limits.''
</P>
<P>
   Girl power: For those who think handling worms is just a guy
thing, try Women's Fishing Online (womensfishing.rivals.com).
</P>
<P>
   One of the gems of this site is a section titled Meditations on
Fishing and Life, a tribute to what fishing means from the female
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people read for relaxation. A lot of people love to
swim. A lot of people (love) to travel,'' writes one woman from
Missouri. ``I love to fish. ... I've heard that every time you
fish, you add seven years to your life.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also Women's Hunting Online
(www.womenshunting.rivals.com).
</P>
<P>
   Shop till you drop: Check your credit card limit before logging
on because the Bass Pro Shops' online store (www.basspro.com) is
Toys R Us for adults.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 2047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
