<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3886 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OIL-MARKETPLACE-NYT &LR;      08-16 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: AS OIL RISES, PLEADING EYES TURN TO SAUDIS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The price of crude oil increased again Wednesday, even after an
American Petroleum Institute report the day before said that
inventories rose by an unexpected 7.4 million barrels last week and
the federal Energy Information Agency cited a smaller but still
strong increase of 3.4 million barrels.
</P>
<P>
   The price jump, with oil for September delivery up 13 cents, to
$31.80 a barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange, pretty much
sums up the current outlook for oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   With inventories in the United States still near 24-year lows,
the hope for price relief is in another significant rise in output
by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries. And that
boils down to OPEC's approving increased production from Saudi
Arabia _ or Saudi Arabia going it alone. The group's next meeting
begins early next month.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts think more oil will be pumped because, they say,
OPEC and especially the Saudis do not want to threaten economic
growth by leaving the price above $30 a barrel for the American
crude oil benchmark, West Texas intermediate.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, pressure from the United States on Saudi Arabia and
other suppliers, inside OPEC as well as outside, to produce more
oil will build quickly if the price does not retreat soon. It is
not far from the 9 &UR;  &LR; 1/2-year high of $34.14 a barrel it touched in
March just before OPEC's first production increase.
</P>
<P>
   This week, there have been new rumblings of concern from the
Clinton administration, which lobbied hard for increased OPEC
production before the supplier nations' meeting in June.
</P>
<P>
   It was reported on Monday that Energy Secretary Bill Richardson
had told a group of energy analysts a few days earlier that the
administration was re-examining ways to lend oil to refiners from
the Strategic Petroleum Reserve, presumably lowering prices as the
available supplies rose.
</P>
<P>
   Oil will almost certainly be a presidential campaign issue if
the price remains high, especially because of the connections to
the oil industry of the Republican ticket of George W. Bush and
Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Home heating oil prices are already on the rise again. Heating
oil for September delivery rose 0.37 cent a gallon yesterday, to
86.88 cents. It is up 13 percent in the last two and a half weeks
and is 26 percent above the average price from October through
February.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think informally or otherwise, there is likely to be a
supply response'' from OPEC before the meeting begins, said Michael
Rothman, senior energy analyst at Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   But the low inventory situation _ and traders' and speculators'
focus on it _ is leaving the oil market far more vulnerable to
upward price pressure than it was earlier in the year, when OPEC
members debated their first two production increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no shock absorbers,'' said Gary N. Ross, chief
executive of the PIRA Energy Group, ``and we are vulnerable to
price spikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts think that it will be difficult to quickly rebuild
inventories. They say that most OPEC nations cannot increase their
overall capacity to produce oil, providing them little interest in
higher output quotas that benefit only a few. Saudi Arabia and the
United Arab Emirates are the only OPEC nations that could produce
significantly more oil, the analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Then last week, the International Energy Agency reported that
several OPEC countries, including the United Arab Emirates, were in
fact producing below their capacity. Rothman quoted the agency's
monthly report for July as saying that the second-quarter inventory
buildup in the 29 members of the Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development, a group of the world's wealthier
nations, had been far less than normal for that time of year.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi Arabia seemed to have succeeded in taking the pressure off
oil prices _ and the focus off inventory levels _ when it finally
convinced traders, analysts and speculators last month that it
would produce 500,000 more barrels a day, a promise it first
surprised the oil market with on July 3.
</P>
<P>
   After wrangling within OPEC, the Saudi message got though as its
extra oil began to move. And with that, the price dropped to $27.43
a barrel on July 31 from $30.93 at the beginning of the month.
</P>
<P>
   But on Aug. 1, the American Petroleum Institute reported that
crude oil inventories in the United States had dropped by a
surprising 9 million barrels in the week ending July 28, leaving
inventory more than 40 million barrels below the level of a year
earlier. The following week, total inventory fell by 2.1 million
barrels more, bringing it to a 24-year low of 282.6 million
barrels. The price of crude oil was back above $30 the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's report from the American Petroleum Institute revised
the previous week still lower, so that the 7.4-million-barrel
increase brought inventories for the week ending on Aug. 11 to
286.4 million barrels.
</P>
<P>
   The only positive factor in the oil price's remaining above $30
a barrel is that OPEC members have an informal agreement to raise
production by 500,000 barrels a day if prices stay above a set
level for 20 trading days in a row. That level works out to a bit
more than $30 a barrel for West Texas intermediate, and the 20 days
up would be just before an OPEC meeting the second week of
September.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the producers' group could choose to ignore this
trigger. Or, a little jawboning would be enough to push the price
below $30 for a day, starting the 20-day period again. So the
upward bias on oil prices would remain until there were clear
increases in production.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
