<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS HOLD OUT HOPE TO SIGN AUBURN STAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Pitcher Chris Bootcheck, a first-round pick by the
Anaheim Angels in this year's draft, has enrolled for his senior
season at Auburn University, but the club believes he can still be
signed.
</P>
<P>
   It is normal for underclassmen to enroll in school even when
they are drafted. But once Bootcheck attends his first class at
Auburn for his senior year, the Angels will lose their draft rights
to him. Classes at Auburn start in about two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Bootcheck, the 20th overall pick in the draft, is represented by
agent Scott Boras, who is known as a tough negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is going as we expected it to go,'' Angels general
manager Bill Stoneman said. ``It's SOP (standard operating
procedure) with guys represented by Boras. I'm not saying he will
or will not go to school.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoneman won't say what offer the Angels have made to Bootcheck.
The No. 19 pick in the draft got $1.65 million and the No. 21 pick
got $1.2 million. There have been reports that the Angels' offer is
around $1.4 million, but Stoneman said, ``The numbers I've seen
thrown around are only speculation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made a fair offer,'' Stoneman added. ``With respect to
No. 19 and 21, as long as we've been fair with the player, then I'm
comfortable with whatever happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Boras is representing nine players who were selected in the
draft, and so far none have signed. Two of them, including
Bootcheck, are first-round picks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not counting,'' Stoneman said of Boras' players. ``I'm
only counting one guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bootcheck, 21, went 9-2 with a 3.76 ERA in 19 starts in his
junior year at Auburn. In his three-year career there, he's 25-10
with a 4.73 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have already signed their top pick, pitcher Joe
Torres, with a $2.1 million bonus. Torres, the 10th overall pick in
the draft, is pitching at Single-A Boise.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad stays hot: Darin Erstad hit his 20th homer of the season
Wednesday, setting a career high. He also became the fifth Angel to
reach the 20-homer mark, joining Troy Glaus (35), Garret Anderson
(31), Mo Vaughn (29) and Tim Salmon (26).
</P>
<P>
   It is the fourth time in Angels history the team has had five
players with at least 20 homers -- 1961 (Earl Averill, Steve Bilko,
Ken Hunt, Lee Thomas and Leon Wagner), '82 (Don Baylor, Doug
DeCinces, Brian Downing, Reggie Jackson and Fred Lynn) and '95
(Chili Davis, Jim Edmonds, Tony Phillips, Salmon and J.T. Snow).
</P>
<P>
   Glaus hit his 35th homer of the season Wednesday. It is the
fifth-highest total in Angels history, behind Reggie Jackson (39 in
1982), Bobby Bonds (37 in 1977), Leon Wagner (37 in 1972) and Don
Baylor (36 in 1979).
</P>
<P>
   Fastballs: Blue Jays closer Billy Koch hit 99 mph on the radar
gun several times in the ninth inning Wednesday. Vaughn took some
big cuts but eventually struck out. What if Vaughn connected with
one of Koch's fastballs?
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had gotten ahold of one it would've had to clear
customs,'' manager Mike Scioscia said. ``You would have had to put
a passport on it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
