<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3889 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-ART-     08-16 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-410(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSPECTS FOR RESCUE OF RUSSIAN SUBMARINE CREW FADING 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to expand and update; story grows by about 1,200 words and is
now 2 takes; former double byline becomes single byline; art note
added)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By PATRICK E. TYLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russian naval forces failed again Wednesday to dock a
rescue vehicle onto the sunken and disabled submarine Kursk as
President Vladimir Putin ordered his military commanders to accept
Western offers of assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's call for assistance came as hopes flickered that any of
the 118 crew members, from whom no signal was heard throughout the
day, would be able to cling to life as high winds and stormy seas
crippled rescue efforts in the Barents Sea, in the Arctic Circle.
</P>
<P>
   Britain loaded a rescue submarine into a Russian transport jet
Wednesday afternoon and flew it to Norway, from where it was to be
sent to the rescue site, which is some 35 miles off the Kola
Peninsula, where Russia's Northern Fleet is based. The Russians may
be counting on the British submersible to be more meneuverable in
the harsh tides and more adaptable in its docking mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
   At the scene, 22 Russian vessels were hovering in wind-tossed
seas over the heavily damaged and partially flooded hull of the
Kursk, trapped since the weekend 350 below the surface. Norway said
Russia had asked for divers and possibly additional ships to help.
</P>
<P>
   But it seemed unlikely that foreign experts could join the
operation before midday Saturday, and that is a day beyond the
deadline when the crew is likely to be out of breathable air,
according to the estimate made by Russia's navy commander, Adm.
Vladimir Kuroyedov.
</P>
<P>
   Russian navy officials acknowledged in interviews Wednesday that
most of the crew may have perished in the first hours of the
disaster, when an explosion apparently ripped through the forward
compartment of the submarine, sending the 14,000 ton vessel
crashing into the seabed, where it rolled to one side.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday and Tuesday, according to Russian officials, crew
members had been banging on the hull of the vessel, but they said
such signals grew more faint Tuesday and stopped on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Kursk was taking part in large-scale naval maneuvers last
weekend when an underwater explosion was detected by both Russian
surface warships and U.S. and Norwegian intelligence sensors
monitoring the exercises from a distance.
</P>
<P>
   A contingent of senior Northern Fleet officers was aboard the
Kursk, a navy spokesman said, and may have died on the bridge along
with the submarine's captain, Gennadi Lyachin, 45. Navy officials
initially reported the crew size at 116, but said Wednesday that
118 officers and crew were aboard.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Washington, a U.S. defense official said two enormous
explosions in close succession were detected on the Kursk last
weekend in the forward compartments at a time when a torpedo-firing
exercise may have been underway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a pretty good indication of how powerful those
explosions were,'' the official said, adding, ``the magnitude was
extraordinary,'' and would be consistent with torpedo blasts.
</P>
<P>
   He said there was no evidence the Kursk was involved in a
collision and that, based on U.S. estimates, some members of the
crew in the aft sections of the boat may have survived.
</P>
<P>
   Russian navy officials confirmed Wednesday that the Oscar II
class submarine had been equipped with an escape module built into
the conning tower, or sail, and that the module was designed to
separate from the submarine with explosive charges and float the
entire crew to the surface in time of disaster.
</P>
<P>
   However, Russian officials said that apparent damage to the sail
area and possible flooding of the bridge and the compartment under
the sail area may have made access to the escape module impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most Russian navy officials expressed the conviction that
some crew members survived and remain alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the absence of a signal means that all of them
are dead,'' said Rear Adm. Georgi G. Kostov, 72, a long time
commander of nuclear attack submarines and an instructor as
Russia's naval academy. ``What it means is that people are in a
sort of dormant, sleepy state and they can hold on if they had time
to put on warm clothing in the unflooded compartments.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``I think they are very cold. They have food,
they have some lighting. And the oxygen is running out with every
hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin, vacationing at the Black Sea resort of Sochi,
characterized the plight of the crew as ``difficult, and I would
say, critical,'' spoke by telephone with President Clinton for 25
minutes during the day. Clinton reiterated an offer of assistance
and Putin said he was ``actively considering'' such offers, an
administration official said in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, Britain and Norway said they had received
clearance from Russian military authorities to join the rescue
effort. Putin's decision seemed aimed in part to dampen criticism
that the military was not doing enough to save the crew.
</P>
<P>
   As the dramatic and dangerous rescue operation was pelted by
driving rain and sleet, a navy spokesman said that by late
afternoon Wednesday, small rescue submarines working in shifts had
conducted four separate dives attempting to dock on one of the
hatches of the Kursk in hopes that the hatch could be opened and
surviving crew members ferried to the surface. But strong currents,
poor visibility and the treacherous angle caused when the submarine
rolled to one side during the accident have frustrated every
docking attempt, Navy officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In each of the diving sessions, multiple attempts were made to
maneuver the rescue vehicle into position. One vehicle was damaged
during the day, officials said. The first dives on Tuesday also
failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole day was spent on attempts to dock with the
submarine,'' said Navy spokesman Igor Dygalo on Wednesday evening.
``During the last 24 hours, rough seas and a strong northeast wind
resulted more than once in danger of losing a rescue capsule.'' He
added that in one diving session, a rescue vehicle successfully
settled over the rear hatch of the Kursk, but then reported that
its own batteries were running dangerously low and was recalled to
the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Fleet spokesman Igor Babenko said docking attempts
would continue through the night, but he added that ``given the
fruitlessness of the attempts in the day and the worsening weather
conditions, one cannot expect any results before Thursday
morning.'' He added that the navy for now would continue pinning
its hopes on completing a successful docking with the Kursk using
the small rescue submarines and added that Navy officials would
delay other contingency plans, such as trying to float the stern
section of the submarine near to surface using huge pontoons.
</P>
<P>
   Babenko reiterated earlier estimates that ``the stores of oxygen
on the submarine are sufficient for the crew members to move
unaided and maintain physical functions for two more days.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Storm conditions in the Barents Sea were forecast to abate
somewhat in the next two days, with winds reducing from gale force
to 25-35 miles per hours and seas to drop from 10-12 feet to 6-8
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the families of Kursk crew members, some traveling
from distant parts of Russia, began gathering in the Severodmorsk,
where the Northern Fleet command is based near Murmansk to keep a
vigil as the air supplies inside the darkened submarine dwindled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought the submarine was so safe,'' said Valentina
Staroseltseva, speaking in an interview in Kursk, the southern
Russian city for which the submarine was named. ``We called it our
submarine. We were 100 percent confident in it. We really believed
in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Galina Belogun, the wife of an officer aboard the stricken
vessel, telephoned a newspaper in Murmansk to pour out her anxiety
</P>
<P>
   ``They tell us to hang on, and we, of course, are hanging on,''
said Belogun. ``Each person comforts himself, but when you turn on
a television it all begins again,'' she added, speaking by
telephone to a newspaper reporter in Murmansk. ``We can no longer
watch the news where they are saying how our men are dying. It is
unbearable.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia's airwaves throughout the day were full of frustration
and anger as the navy struggled with one of its worse disasters at
sea. Many criticized the military and Putin's government for
waiting too long to seek foreign assistance with rescue efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Eduard Baltin, a former commander of the Black Sea fleet, and
several former senior officers questioned how the Kursk could have
been conducting torpedo firing exercises in waters so shallow as to
risk a sudden loss of depth from a flooded torpedo tube that would
send the vessel crashing into the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think torpedo shooting at this depth is impermissible,
because it is the minimal depth in which this kind of submarine can
operate,'' said Kostov, who once commanded a division of
November-class attack submarines based on the Kola Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, it is too early to blame anyone,'' he added, ``but it
might be the fault of the fleet commander'' who was supervising the
exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Lukin, a vice speaker of the Russian parliament and
former ambassador to the United States, questioned the quality of
information coming from the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am worried by the fact that, according to Western
information, the malfunction occurred on Saturday, and according to
Russian official information, on Sunday,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the least understood aspects of the disaster were the
reports of major structural damage to the submarine beyond the
destruction in the forward compartment.
</P>
<P>
   Kuroyedov, the navy commander, said the first examination of the
hull of Kursk showed portions of deck housing torn away. ``The
submarine lies aground with a raised periscope,'' he added,
indicating, some experts said, that the central section of the
submarine was flooded, thus preventing the periscope to
automatically retract.
</P>
<P>
   Other navy officials said the conning tower, where the escape
module was located along with periscopes and antennae, was heavily
damaged. Some officials said it was still possible the submarine
struck a World War II vintage mine, or was involved in a collision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The causes of the accident will become clear following a
detailed examination of the entire submarine body,'' the navy
commander said. And as for the crew, he added, ``We shall remain
optimistic until Aug. 18.''
</P>
</TEXT>
