<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-CHIAPAS_ From the tropical coast to the Mayan highlands,
the fever for political change _ through ballots, not bullets _ is
sweeping Mexico's Chiapas state. On Sunday, Aug. 20, the state
famous for its armed Zapatista Mayan Indian rebels will elect a new
governor. In the wake of Vicente Fox's historic opposition victory
in last month's presidential election, polls show that change could
be contagious: Even in Indian communities once under tight control
by the ruling party, posters for a Fox ally are up on dirt-floor
homes. An old man wearing a ruling party shirt says he's not so
sure he'll vote for that party now. Chiapans appear to be slightly
favoring Pablo Salazar, a former ruling party member who is now
representing an alliance that includes Fox's conservative National
Action Party and the left-wing Democratic Revolution Party. If
Salazar wins, one of the main reasons for the Zapatistas rising in
protest is eliminated. Mexico's ruling party would be ousted from a
state infamous for its ruling-party corruption and grinding social
inequality. A historic new Fox-Salazar combination would be in
place that could usher in new negotiations with the rebels.
(Ferriss, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH PHOTO MUGS.
</P>
<P>
   Expected to move by Wed., Aug. 16, on the NYT wire.
</P>
<P>
   COSTARICA-INVEST _ SAN JOSE, Costa Rica _ Lured by cheap land, a
gorgeous countryside and pleasant climate, thousands of U.S.
citizens have moved to Costa Rica in recent years. Profile some of
these folks, from retirees to surfers. Have they found the dream
they wanted? Do locals accept them? Has the recent upswing in crime
tainted their tropical paradise? (Williams, Cox News Service). WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: With information for locator map.
</P>
<P>
   Expected to move by Wed., Aug. 16, on the NYT Wire in both
International and Financial categories.
