<SLUG> BC-FALCONS0817-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons lose defensive end Smith for exhibition, and perhaps
longer
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLOWERY BRANCH, Ga. - Falcons starting right defensive end Brady
Smith suffered a deep groin strain in Tuesday's practice that will
keep him out of Friday's preseason game against San Diego, and may
sideline him longer.
</P>
<P>
   The first serious injury of the summer for the Falcons comes at
the team's weakest position.
</P>
<P>
   Starter Patrick Kerney, who's trying to get used to left end
after registering 44 tackles and 2.5 sacks last year while backing
up on both sides as a rookie, will move to right end.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than start a reserve end _ Pellom McDaniels, Emil Ekiyor
or Sam Simmons _ Ed Jasper, who's competing to start at defensive
tackle, will start at left end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because that's where he's worked so far (as opposed to no work
at right end),'' said defensive coordinator Rich Brooks. ``It's to
get him reps. He's done reasonably well there and we want to see
what he does with the No. 1 unit.''
</P>
<P>
   Former starting defensive ends Chuck Smith and Lester
Archambeau, who combined for 15.5 sacks and 140 tackles last
season, were allowed to leave in free agency.
</P>
<P>
   Brady Smith, 27, signed a four-year, $10 million deal to join
the Falcons as a free agent from the Saints. In four seasons with
New Orleans, the 6-foot-5, 270-pounder had 97 tackles and 13 sacks.
</P>
<P>
   Team officials believe he is about to blossom. He had 16 starts,
33 tackles and six sacks last season, all career highs.
</P>
<P>
   He's been working in the spot previously held by Chuck Smith,
who last year had 84 tackles and 10 sacks.
</P>
<P>
   McDaniels, 32, is the Falcons' only reserve end with NFL
experience.
</P>
<P>
   He had 29 tackles last year with the Falcons at tackle and end,
but hasn't had a sack since he had 3.5 with the Chiefs in `97.
</P>
<P>
   If team officials make a move, they'll likely wait to see who is
released in the NFL's first roster cutdown on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The free agent pickings are slim.
</P>
<P>
   The top unemployed ends are 34-year-old Neil Smith, released by
Denver after registering 6.5 sacks (and 104.5 in his 12-year
career) in eight starts last season, Ferric Collons, Roy Barker and
Gabe Wilkins.
</P>
<P>
   Collons, 30, is 6-feet-6, 285 pounds and was brought to
Jacksonville in `94 by current Falcons vice president/football
operations Ron Hill. He had two sacks last year with New England.
</P>
<P>
   Barker, 31, is 6-feet-5, 290 pounds and had 12 sacks with the
49ers in `98. But he slipped so badly in Cleveland that he was
released before the end of last season.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkins, 28, is 6-feet-5, 308 pounds, but has battled serious
knee problems. He started 15 games last year for the 49ers, with
one sack.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper, 27, began working at left end in training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been playing tackle for so long,'' he said, ``that I'm
not used to taking two or three steps to get to somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
