<HEADLINE>
NEWS CORP. PROFITS FALL 14   PERCENT IN FOURTH QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The News Corp. said Wednesday that its after-tax profit for the
fourth quarter fell 14 percent. Profit before extraordinary items
was $184 million, or 18 cents per American depository receipt,
compared with $214 million, or 21 cents a share, in the comparable
period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue in the quarter, with ended June 30, rose 18 percent, to
$3.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The company reported earnings of 6 cents a depository receipt
after all extraordinary items, compared with a loss of 2 cents a
year earlier. The losses from extraordinary items were largely
attributed to the rollout of digital services of the News Corp.'s
satellite television company British Sky Broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   The results were slightly better than analysts' recent
expectations of 16 cents a share. But they were below the forecasts
made before the impact of dismal box office sales of ``Titan
A.E.,'' Fox studio's animated science fiction movie, was assessed.
</P>
<P>
   The company was most severely affected by an operating loss of
$53 million in the filmed entertainment division, compared with
operating income of $22 million in the similar period a year
earlier. Like several other studios, Fox raced into the animation
business, setting up its own studio. The unit took a $12 million
charge related to shutting the studio down.
</P>
<P>
   The largest improvement at the company was in the newspaper
division, where profits rose more than 50 percent, to $161 million
from $107 million a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Fox television network has suffered from a
decline in ratings, cash flow at the News Corp.'s U.S. TV
operations rose 4 percent. Expenses rose because of series
cancellations, the broadcast of additional Major League Baseball
games and generally higher costs for new programming, but increased
sales of prime time advertisements helped raise the unit's
operating income.
</P>
<P>
   The News Corp.'s depository receipts fell 18.75 cents to close
at $51.25
</P>
<P>
   The company has just agreed to acquire Chris-Craft Industries
for $3.5 billion in stock and cash. The Chris-Craft Television
stations carry the UPN network, which is owned by Viacom. UPN's
contract with the stations is up next year, and Viacom could shut
the network down. But Rupert Murdoch, who controls the News Corp.,
said Wednesday that he was open to negotiating with Viacom about
the network's future on Chris-Craft stations. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 2108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
