<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERIZON-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERIZON'S STRIKING UNIONS SET DEADLINE FOR SETTLEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a development that could drastically change the
direction of a 12-day walkout by more than 86,000 employees of
Verizon Communications, representatives for nearly two-thirds of
the striking workers said Wednesday that they would break off
negotiations if they did not reach an agreement with the company by
midnight Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, which
represents about 14,000 striking employees, mostly in New Jersey,
Pennsylvania and New England states, and the northern unit of the
Communications Workers of America, which represents about 38,000
employees in New York and parts of New England, made the statement
late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The threat to withdraw from the negotiations clearly puts
pressure on Verizon, which is trying to handle a growing number of
requests for repair and new service from customers, to reach an
agreement that deals with the unions' concerns about issues that
include workplace stress and job security.
</P>
<P>
   And it also puts pressure on a bargaining unit from the
Communications Workers union that represents about 34,000 workers
in several mid-Atlantic states, which is thought to be holding up
the talks out of intransigence over several issues, people close to
the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, at least in public, the unions put the pressure on Verizon,
the telephone giant formed recently by Bell Atlantic's acquisition
of GTE Corp. In a message sent to the unions' local presidents in
New York Wednesday, the union said a proposal from Verizon
Wednesday dealing with the movement of jobs resulting from the Bell
Atlantic-GTE merger fell short of expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company still refuses to abandon its position that the
percentage of jobs moved should be calculated on a net basis, with
incoming jobs counted as offsetting any jobs moved out, no matter
what craft is affected,'' the message stated. ``In addition, the
company's position on the overall percentage of jobs that can be
moved remains unacceptably high.''
</P>
<P>
   The IBEW union, for its part, is thought to be upset that an
agreement reached last week making it easier to organize in
Verizon's wireless division might not go far enough, a person close
to the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the union is not sure whether the agreement will
allow organizing in New Jersey with card check, a process in which
a majority of employees at a given work site can join a union by
signing cards instead of going through a formal election process, a
person close to the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon said it would try to address these issues, and others,
before the midnight deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all want to get this done quickly, as it seems the two
groups are tired like us, and want this to end,'' said Eric Rabe,
Verizon's spokesman. ``Maybe they're trying to send the remaining
bargaining party a message.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the Communication Workers unit that did not say
it would break off talks by midnight _ a region stretching from New
Jersey to Virginia and led by Vincent Maisano, a union vice
president _ has said it is more concerned with issues involving
mandatory overtime, because more of its members work as customer
service representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon is having a harder time negotiating with Maisano's unit
because of the mandatory overtime issue, a person close to the
talks said. Maisano could not be reached Wednesday for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the unions said they were working together to
resolve the strike.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations were expected to last through the night Wednesday
in an effort to clear up remaining issues.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Verizon is falling behind in meeting requests
for repairs and for installation of new telephone service. The
company said it had about 90,000 requests for repair Wednesday,
about a third more than normal.
</P>
<P>
   Cheri Grand-Anderman was among customers waiting for repairs
after her high-speed Internet access was knocked out 10 days ago
when vandals cut an access line near her Greenwich Village
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been exasperating: I feel like I've been slapped in the
face by Verizon,'' said Grand-Anderman, 31, who runs a public
relations company from her home. ``They haven't been the least bit
responsive in all my attempts to get my line repaired, even after I
told them I was losing thousands of dollars in business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
