u p BC-CVN-CONVENTION-RDP-HN     08-16 1543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-CONVENTION-RDP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
LIEBERMAN STRESSES HUMBLE ROOTS AS HE ACCEPTS NOMINATION &HT;    (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)
 &HT;    By STEWART M. POWELL and DAN FREEDMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES Democratic vice presidential candidate Joseph
Lieberman, the first Jewish American nominated for a major party
ticket, described himself to the Democratic National Convention
Wednesday night as the humble beneficiary of the American dream who
is eager to extend opportunities to others left behind.
</P>
<P>
   The 58-year-old senator from Connecticut also offered ``some
straight talking'' about Republicans, delighting convention
delegates with the quip that Republican presidential nominee George
W. Bush's idea of school modernization is ``buying a new calendar
for every building.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman delivered his nationally-televised address as
Democratic delegates formally nominated the Gore-Lieberman ticket
to carry the party's banner against Bush, in his second term as
governor of Texas, and Dick Cheney, the former defense secretary
turned oil services company executive.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, who credits the late President John F. Kennedy with
drawing him into public service, laid out the next step of the
cherished ``New Frontier'' enunciated here in Los Angeles by
Kennedy in 1960. ``I believe that the next frontier isn't just in
front of us but inside us to overcome the differences that are
still between us ... and to help every American claim the limitless
possibilities of our own lives,'' Lieberman declared.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, a graduate of Yale and Yale law school who was the
first in his family to attend college, recounted his humble
origins. His father had lived in an orphanage as a child, later
drove a bakery truck on the overnight shift and eventually owned a
liquor store.
</P>
<P>
   ``He taught us the importance of work and responsibility,''
Lieberman recalled, adding: ``Sometimes I try to see this world as
my dad saw it from his bakery truck.''
</P>
<P>
   Liberman's wife, Hadassah, the Czech-born daughter of Holocaust
survivors, introduced her husband to the convention as a principled
public servant ``shaped by the values that are his heart and
soul.'' Mrs. Lieberman called her husband ``just a regular Joe,''
adding: ``He's that and more.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier at an airport rally welcoming Gore and his wife Tipper
who arrived in the Los Angeles area Wednesday afternoon, Lieberman
mischievously told more than 1,000 supporters crowded into a
airport hanger to escape punishing sunshine: ``I've been waiting
for a week to say this line and I can't control myself anymore, _
in this election, will you help me win this one for the Tipper?''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, a veteran of nearly 12 years in the Senate who
patched up strains with African-Americans over his ambiguous
support for affirmative action, enthusiastically told Gore that
``this is the most excited and united Democratic Convention that we
have ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   As Gore stood by beaming, Lieberman told him: ``As I've walked
the floor of the convention and spoken to the delegates, this is a
convention that believes in you and loves you.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore set the stage for his own acceptance speech to the
Democratic faithful on Thursday night by vowing to lay out the
``specific hard choices'' that face the nation to harness the
nation's booming prosperity to bolster Social Security, improve
public education, provide prescription drug coverage to senior
citizens and get ``guns out of the hands of children and
criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, hoping to strike a contrast with what aides describe as
the ``happy-talk'' generalities offered by Bush at the GOP
convention in Philadelphia two weeks ago, vowed to tell voters the
details of what he wants to do so they can ``make an informed
judgment choosing the first president of the 21st century. ``Let
others make the case for the old guard,'' Gore declared. ``We're
the new guard and we're going to bring positive change to the
United States of America.''
</P>
<P>
   Late polls showed Gore and Lieberman have their work cut out for
them. A Voter.com-Battleground tracking poll of likely voters
released Wednesday showed the Bush-Cheney ticket leading the
Gore-Lieberman ticket by 9 percentage points, 49 percent to 40
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's eldest daughter, Karenna Gore Schiff, 27, a graduate of
Harvard and Columbia law school who often accompanies her father on
the campaign trail, delivered a personal key note address to
nominate her father as president.
</P>
<P>
   Schiff's address followed a well-received speech on Tuesday
night by Caroline Kennedy Schlossberg, the 42-year-old daughter and
last direct relative of slain President John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the proud father, said that having his own daughter
address the nation had him worried, adding: ``I've got more
butterflies about that than my own speech.'' Gore's name also was
put in nomination by his Harvard roommate, the craggy-faced actor
Tommy Lee Jones.
</P>
<P>
   In her remarks to the convention, Schiff recalled her father's
help building a dinosaur diorama, icing down an igloo for an
overnight winter camp out and his unwillingness to ``never laugh at
our big plans.'' She said her father was a ``man of faith in the
most gutsy, practical sense,'' who would work for affordable health
care, equal pay for women, abortion rights and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., who would become
speaker of the House with a Democratic takeover of the House on
Nov. 7, made a pitch for a change of leadership in the House which
in recent years has been wracked by strident divisions between
Republican leaders and minority Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders ``don't communicate _ they dictate,''
declared Gephardt, an ally of organized labor who had been on
Gore's list of prospective running mates. ``Democracy deserves
better. Hear me: We will replace `my way or the highway' with `Our
way together,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The delegates responded with a chant: ``Take back the House!
Take back the House!''
</P>
<P>
   California Gov. Gray Davis stirred the delegates by telling them
that Gore ``is not flashy...he's not some back-slapping good old
boy. He is a serious man of substance.''
</P>
<P>
   For Lieberman, his acceptance speech was a culmination of sorts
of a journey that began 58 years ago when he was born in Stamford,
Conn. His father, Henry, owned a liquor store, and his mother,
Marcia, raised him and his siblings as Orthodox Jews. Since
election to the Senate in 1988, Lieberman has fashioned himself
into a moderate-to-liberal lawmaker best known for occasional
stands against Democratic doctrine, including support for publicly
funded ``vouchers'' for private schools, opposition to affirmative
action and condemnation of the entertainment industry's
exploitation of sex and violence.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman was the first Democratic senator to publicly condemn
President Clinton's sexual dalliance with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky. William Bennett, the self-styled chief Republican
morals guru, described Lieberman as ``the closest thing in the
Senate to an Old Testament prophet.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, who ceases work on the Jewish Sabbath on Saturday,
says he will continue honoring the Sabbath and on three Jewish
holidays in the weeks before the Nov. 7 election. ``I'm just going
to do what I've always done and work extra hard on the days that
I'm campaigning,'' Lieberman said before his address.
</P>
<P>
   Pollster Frank Luntz, who advised the independent presidential
bid of Texas billionaire Ross Perot in 1992, said Gore's selection
of Lieberman is paying off because the selection ``has already
caused people to take another look at Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Luntz said Republicans are at a loss about how to react to
Gore's choice of Lieberman because the ``way he communicates is so
gentle and so moderate in tone and the fact that he attaches
spiritualness to that communication goes right to the heart of many
conservatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Luntz, who also advised then-Rep. Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., on the
1994 campaign manifesto ``Contract with America'' that helped the
GOP to retake the House and Senate for the first time since 1954,
said Lieberman helps Gore win back politically conservative Jewish
Americans who have gradually started to vote Republican.
</P>
<P>
   There are roughly 5.5 million Jews in the United States, 10
percent of whom are Orthodox Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Luntz said the 40 percent share of the Jewish vote that a
Republican like Ronald Reagan won in 1984 might seep away with
Lieberman on the Democratic ticket, leaving Bush with roughly 20
percent of the Jewish vote. Lieberman gave Gore a boost in the
polls, just as Cheney did for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Gore gained 17 percentage points on Bush following his selection
of Lieberman, according to a CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll. Gore cut
Bush's edge from 19 percentage points to 2 percentage points,
according to the surveys. Bush's selection of Cheney also gave the
GOP nominee a boost, enabling Bush to boost his margin by 10
percentage points, from 6 percentage points before he chose Cheney
to 16 percentage points after the selection.
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart Powell and Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920
or at stewarthearstdc.com or danhearstdc.com )
</P>
<P>
