<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3904 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEM-MARDI-GRAS-ART-NY     08-16 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-MARDI-GRAS-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUISIANA REVELRY SHAKES UP CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo cvn3 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (Eds: Carl Hulse is Washington Bureau Chief of the NYT Regional
Newspapers Group.)  
 By CARL HULSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Louisiana rocked the Democratic National
Convention on Tuesday night with an over-the-top Mardi Gras party
that practically registered on the Richter scale.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Breaux hosted the faux Fat Tuesday on a back lot at
Paramount Studios in Hollywood, a venue that provides urban street
settings for such television shows as ``NYPD Blue.'' It made for an
authentic Mardi Gras atmosphere as more than 1,500 people enjoyed a
parade with full-scale floats, Cajun and swing music and Louisiana
cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great,'' exulted Ben Jeffers of Baton Rouge, La.,
chairman of the Louisiana state Democratic party. ``It is just like
Mardi Gras. The streets are packed.''
</P>
<P>
   Two dozen top health, energy, defense and tobacco corporations
and the centrist Democratic Leadership Council underwrote the
lavish event, which was estimated to cost more than $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   But Breaux was not apologetic about the financial support of
special interests with major issues pending before Congress, saying
his bash was about catching Mardi Gras beads, not political arm
twisting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows you have parties at the convention,'' said
Breaux, who met early arriving guests dressed in neon orange Mardi
Gras garb and brandishing the traditional umbrella. ``We deal with
these people in Washington on a regular basis. They are not going
to get anything out of the party they don't already have back in
Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   But campaign finance watchdog groups have complained about the
level of extravagance at the parties thrown by lobbying groups at
both the Democratic convention and the earlier GOP convention in
Philadelphia. Unlike the GOP partiers, however, Breaux welcomed the
press to chronicle the festivities.
</P>
<P>
   The senator, always a colorful figure, was in rare form as he
took to the stage and joined the popular zydeco performer Rockin
Dopsie Jr., playing the washboard and dancing. He then changed into
a shimmering white Elvis-like costume to toss throws from a float
and get back on stage with the swing band Big Bad Voodoo Daddy.
</P>
<P>
   John Rother, a top lobbyist for AARP, was impressed by Breaux's
exuberance, which is atypical for the normally reserved members of
the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had seen everything,'' Rother said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., who works closely with Breaux on
complex issues such as Medicare and Social Security, said Breaux
might have earned support for a future presidential bid through
sheer showmanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``With John Breaux as president, I might show up at more of
those White House meetings,'' Leahy said. ``I've got enormous
admiration for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The guests gobbled shrimp, oysters, alligator and red beans and
rice, while guzzling hurricanes. Many declared the party, dubbed
``Mardi Gras Goes Hollywood,'' the best of the week.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeffers said there was more at work than simply providing a
fun evening under perfect weather conditions. He said the intent
was also to give convention organizers a taste of what it could be
like to hold the convention in New Orleans in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it goes a long way toward New Orleans being picked for
the next convention,'' he said. ``There is a reason to all this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
