<SLUG> BC-CVN-ECONOMY-CREDIT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
TREASURY SECRETARY CLAIMS MUCH OF ECONOMIC BOOM IS DUE TO
CLINTON-GORE &HT;    By MARK HELM
 &HT;    c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Claiming administration credit for much of the
nation's long-running boom, Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers
said Wednesday that the good times would not have been possible
without President Clinton's policies, which, he said, Vice
President Al Gore helped shape.
</P>
<P>
   Summers said the administration's 1993 budget plan, which began
to lower the government's deficits, was a key catalyst for bringing
the economy out of recession and into expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question it was the president who set the course toward
balanced budgets, and that has helped our national economy,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Summers said that by cutting deficits _ which stood at $290
billion in 1992 compared with a $124 billion surplus last year _
the administration freed up huge sums of money for businesses and
consumers to spend on goods and services and investments in new
technologies. That spending has led to greater productivity and the
booming economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Summers called Gore a ``partner'' with the president in crafting
the administration's economic policies. ``The president often
conferred with the vice president even before talking with his
economic advisers, and there's no doubt that (Gore) was a major
force in shaping our policies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The treasury secretary also credited the new
information-technology industry and the country's entrepreneurs. He
said they ``were, of course, absolutely necessary for success, but
they needed the tools to do the job and the confidence that the
government had its act together. If we had $2 trillion more in debt
_ like we would have without any changes in the early 1990s _ it
would have come out of money used for investment in the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The unemployment rate was 7.5 percent in 1992, compared with 4
percent in June. The inflation rate was 3 percent eight years ago,
compared with 1.5 percent last year. ``In the early 1990s, there
was an air of pervasive pessimism in this country that simply
doesn't exist today,'' Summers said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the role of Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan
in the economic surge, Summers praised his ``extraordinary record
of service'' but added that Greenspan held his job between1987 and
1993, when deficits were high, as well as between 1993 to the
present. Summers said some of the fed chairman's success in recent
years was due to Clinton's policies. ``It's a lot easier to manage
monetary policy when deficits are falling and surpluses are
rising,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Clinton has complained that he has not received
enough credit for the country's prosperity during his term in
office. And in his Monday speech at the Democratic National
Convention, he once more sought to refute Republican charges that
he did little more than have the luck to preside at a time when
business and technology were transforming America.
</P>
<P>
   ``To those who say the progress of the last eight years was an
accident, that we just coasted along, let's be clear: America's
success was not a matter of chance; it was a matter of choice,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the public has been reluctant to give him the credit he
thinks he deserves for the prosperity. In a Los Angeles Times poll
of 1,200 ``likely'' voters this spring, 15 percent gave Clinton
most of the credit, 24 percent credited the high-tech industry and
9 percent cited the Republican majority in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers present the Gore campaign with two major problems:
convincing people that the Clinton administration deserves more
credit for the economy and then convincing voters that Gore helped
create Clinton's policies.
</P>
<P>
   In another Los Angeles Times poll of ``likely'' voters conducted
earlier this month, 89 percent of those surveyed said the economy
was doing well, but 48 percent said Gore deserves no credit for the
good times. Thirty-four percent said he deserves some credit and 9
percent said he deserves a lot of credit.
</P>
<P>
   In that survey, 56 percent of likely voters said the country is
moving in the right direction while 36 percent said it is
off-track. But only 51 percent of the contented group favored Gore
and 37 percent favored Bush. Typically, the candidate of the party
holding the White House can expect to win as much as three quarters
of voters who say the country is on the right track.
</P>
<P>
   The Times polls each had a margin of error of plus or minus
three percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached by phone at (202) 298-6920 or by
e-mail at mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
