<HEADER>
A3907 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-OLY-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     08-16 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL EXPERIENCE LIFT U.S. SWIMMERS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ So many younger men. So many older women. The
2000 U.S. Olympic swimming team has the biggest age gap between the
leading female and male players this side of the London stage
production of ``The Graduate.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the experienced women can guide the inexperienced
men down the path to gratification in Sydney will be a central
theme of the Summer Olympics for the 47-person U.S. contingent.
</P>
<P>
   Public perception holds that the team assembled over the past
eight days at the IUPUI Natatorium is the H.M.S. Titanic, chugging
toward the giant iceberg in Australia that is Ian Thorpe and Co.
Yes, the Americans didn't set a single world record here while the
Australians, led by freestyle phenom Thorpe, lowered five global
marks at their Olympic selection meet in May.
</P>
<P>
   But the timing must be considered along with the times.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian Trials were held early enough in the year to
allow the host country's swimmers to peak in May and then resume
heavy training with an eye toward peaking again next month. Most of
the very best U.S. swimmers, on the other hand, have been logging
miles upon miles without interruption, building toward performances
that they hope will crest and form The Perfect Swim in the vicinity
of Sydney Harbour in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more Olympians I talk to, the more it seems a lot of
swimmers really have been projecting forward to the next meet,''
said Mark Schubert, the USC men's and women's and USA head men's
Olympic coach. ``I really believe we're going to be a lot faster in
Sydney.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite cutting back relatively little on their training, Studio
City's Lenny Krayzelburg turned in the fastest time in the world
this year in the 100 backstroke, Megan Quann clocked the leading
time in the world in the 100 breaststroke, and Brooke Bennett and
Tom Dolan posted the No. 1 times globally in the 800-meter
freestyle and 400 individual medley, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Those swims bode well for Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   And if there were eight events - five on the women's side - in
which the fastest time in the championship race didn't crack the
top-3 of the world rankings, well, it's a little early yet to be
conjuring the ghosts of 1988.
</P>
<P>
   That was the last U.S. team that was selected this close to the
Summer Games, and it performed dismally in Seoul. Only Janet Evans
and Matt Biondi captured individual golds. On Wednesday, U.S.
Olympic coaches Richard Quick and Schubert received this tidbit,
and we don't blame them for reflexively rejecting it.
</P>
<P>
   To lump the 2000 squad with the underachievers of 1988 is as
ill- advised as assuming a George W. Bush presidency would mirror
his father's. It was a different stage, a different time, with
different personalities in the lead roles.
</P>
<P>
   The 1988 team had holdovers from the 1984 squad - this was
particularly with the men - who performed as though they were happy
just to have made another Olympic team. Many women were too green
to go for the gold.
</P>
<P>
   That's where the experience of this year's female Olympians
figures prominently. It will be up to the likes of Dara Torres,
Jenny Thompson, Amy Van Dyken and B.J. Bedford (average age of the
foursome: 28 years) to lead by words and deeds in a way the veteran
men in 1988 did not.
</P>
<P>
   Torres, 33, who won the 50-meter freestyle during the final
session of the U.S. Trials, personifies a women's squad nearly old
enough to remember nylon-skirted racing suits. Thirteen of the 24
women have completed their collegiate eligibility, and Torres is
such a veteran of the Olympics she ought to qualify for some kind
of pension; Sydney will be her fourth Summer Games appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Josh Davis, 27, is the oldest swimmer among the U.S. men. His
experience as a parent - he and his wife are expecting their third
child early next month - will come in handy as eight of the 23
spots on the men's side are filled by teen-agers. That is a change
from 1996 when Tom Malchow, then 19, was the most boyish of the
men.
</P>
<P>
   Malchow made it back, but he has a 15-year-old, Michael Phelps,
on his tail. Phelps conceivably could chase Malchow all the way to
the medal stand in Sydney. Ditto 17-year-old Aaron Peirsol, who's
in hot pursuit of Krayzelburg, the world record holder in the 100
and 200-meter backstrokes. And not to be overlooked is
Krayzelburg's 19-year-old Trojan Swim Club teammate Eric Vendt, who
is nipping at Dolan's heels in the 400 individual medley.
</P>
<P>
   All the young blood has acted as a surge of adrenaline for
Malchow, Krayzelburg and Dolan, the only Americans who will go into
the Sydney Games with the added prestige (and pressure) of being
world record holders.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the men's side, we certainly have some phenomenal high
school athletes who busted onto the team,'' Schubert said. ``It's
very encouraging to see high school athletes breaking through and
not just making the team but establishing themselves as medal
contenders.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the intangibles. Gracing the U.S. team is Chad
Carvin, who overcame a diseased heart to make his longtime Olympic
dream a reality, and Gary Hall Jr., who is battling not only his
training mate, Anthony Irvin of Valencia, but diabetes, too.
</P>
<P>
   There's Thompson, who rebounded from a disastrous Trials
performance four years ago to emerge as one of this year's stars;
and Torres, who took seven years off and then dove headfirst into
training, working out up to eight hours a day to earn her way to
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Representing the U.S. is backstroker Courtney Shealy, who
lettered three years in volleyball at Georgia, and butterflyer
Tommy Hannan, who played quarterback for his high school varsity
team.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Krayzelburg, arguably the biggest name at the meet,
who cheered himself hoarse rooting for his Trojan Swim Club
teammates and friends on the U.S. national team to join him in
Sydney. We can't blame him for wanting them along: A team this
gutty, gifted, gracious and goal-oriented could go to Sydney and
have quite a ball, crashing the world's party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 2115EDT &QL; 
