<HEADER>
A3908 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-CDREVIEW-KIRKFRANKLIN     08-16 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CDREVIEW-KIRKFRANKLIN-1NC-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANKLIN CHARTS NEW GOSPEL WATERS WITH 1NC
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By DAVE FERMAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There will be some controversy surrounding ``Kirk Franklin
Presents 1NC,'' the debut CD by the nine-person, multiracial group
that Franklin has groomed and produced.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the CD includes traditional, old-school gospel and the sort
of hip-hop-laden modern praise music that Franklin has excelled at
for nearly a decade, while rising from obscurity in Fort Worth to
becoming arguably the most famous gospel artist in the world.
</P>
<P>
   But ``1NC'' (short for One Nation Crew) also finds Franklin (who
wrote or arranged all but one of the 18 tracks) taking this group
to different places _ different from where his music has gone
before, and different from where most of his urban gospel
contemporaries have gone, too.
</P>
<P>
   The first single, ``Nobody,'' merges slick, bubbly hip-hop
gospel with flamenco guitar. ``Unconditional'' also has more than a
bit of Latin flavoring. And then there's ``Could've Been Me,'' a
showcase for the group's sole white male vocalist, Brandon Kizer,
which merges rock guitar and a Christian rock-band feel with
compelling gospel harmonies. And, finally, there is the awesome
``Be Like Him,'' a merging of traditional American gospel with
African harmonizing that was recorded with the African group
Chosen.
</P>
<P>
   Some people will not like this.
</P>
<P>
   I am not one of them.
</P>
<P>
   To these ears, ``1NC'' does many things right: Franklin's
strengths as a songwriter and producer are in full force, the group
is a sure-handed, inspiring unit with several compelling lead
vocalists (my favorites being Myron Butler and Ashley Guilbert) and
the forays into diverse territories are invariably successful.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin's vision of racial inclusiveness in modern urban gospel
is one whose time has come and, in fact, has been evident on the
contemporary Christian charts for years. The surprising moves are
so well-integrated into the whole that they never seem jarring, and
the CD has a smart flow of tempos, sounds and lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the CD shows that Franklin is still willing to tackle
topics that most gospel artists shy away from; ``Donna'' is a look
at teen pregnancy, ``When You Fall'' deals with the idea of
inevitably making serious mistakes and finding redemption, and
``Lost Hearts'' takes modern society to task for permissive
attitudes and lack of feeling for others.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, then, ``1NC'' is one of the year's finest gospel
CDs. Franklin is still head and shoulders above most of his
contemporaries in writing, producing and vision, and 1NC is a
compelling, extremely talented new group. I predict great things. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman covers pop music for the Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDBU/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
