<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-PAULINE-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUGH ELDERLY AND FRAIL, PAULINE GORE REVELS IN HER SON'S BIG
MOMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On the day that her beloved Democrats were to
nominate her beloved son for president, Pauline LaFon Gore sat in
an elegant ballroom at the Regal Biltmore Hotel and greeted a long
line of admirers who had come to pay tribute to the 87-year-old
matriarch of the Gore family.
</P>
<P>
   She fussed over every guest, whether old friend or stranger,
lingering so long in some cases that Karenna Gore Schiff, her
granddaughter, felt obliged to move the crowd along. When Marcia
Lieberman paid an unexpected visit, Mrs. Gore rose from her chair
and offered a warm hug to the 85-year-old mother of her son's
running mate. She made no speech, but blew kisses to her
granddaughter after Schiff toasted her as ``truly an amazing
woman'' who had inspired thousands with ``her charm and grace, her
grit and determination and her idealism.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a remarkable moment in the remarkable life of Pauline
Gore, a woman who rose from humble beginnings to become one of the
first women to graduate from Vanderbilt University's law school,
who participated as a full partner in the 32-year congressional
career of her late husband, Sen. Albert Gore Sr., who endured his
painful defeat in 1970 and the death of their daughter, Nancy, in
1984, and who has been a bulwark in the political life of her son,
Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a bittersweet moment for Mrs. Gore, who will watch
her son's acceptance speech on Thursday night surrounded by family
but missing her husband, who died in 1998 after nearly 91 years of
life and 61 years of marriage. They met while she served him coffee
at the Andrew Jackson Hotel in Nashville, where both were law
students. Together they stoked their son's ambition, nurturing him
for public service since his earliest days and providing him with a
seamless political resume.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really were a lovely couple to behold,'' said Bill
McSweeney, a longtime family friend who recalls the Gores holding
hands while watching ``The Lawrence Welk Show'' on Saturday nights.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, Mrs. Gore has endured a heart attack, brain surgery
to remove a blood clot, and two strokes, one of which impaired her
vision. Her husband trained her to walk again after the strokes,
and she now strolls around the family farm in Carthage, Tenn.,
using one of his old wooden canes. The day after her surgery, she
asked her nurses to hook up cable television in her hospital room
so she could watch C-Span.
</P>
<P>
   She has good days, when she is just as lucid as ever, and when
her extraordinary memory is as sharp as the picture on a new
television set. On other days, family members and friends say, she
can appear tired and slightly confused. The vice president, who is
highly protective of his mother, no longer allows her to grant
formal interviews, and she has not done one for three years.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no sign Wednesday that Mrs. Gore, known to all as
Miz Pauline, was having a bad day. And her family and friends say
she has been completely attuned to her son's campaign in recent
weeks and thrilled to be attending the Democratic National
Convention. ``She is having a ball,'' said Schiff. ``This is her
cup of tea. She is completely in heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   While Mrs. Gore is no longer strong enough to wage the kind of
cross-country campaign she undertook during her son's 1988
presidential race, she has not been content to sit idly at the
farm. She speaks almost daily to her son _ three times on the day
of the New Hampshire primary _ and watches the Sunday political
talk shows, making mental note of who says anything nasty about her
boy.
</P>
<P>
   She attends Democratic events around Tennessee, took a prime
seat at last week's unveiling of the Gore-Lieberman ticket in
Nashville, and has made numerous unscheduled visits to the campaign
headquarters there. ``She says, `I just had to come check on
you,''' said Donna Brazile, Gore's campaign manager. ``She wants to
talk to the strategists and the lawyers. She wants to know who
everybody is, where they're from. And she reassures us that Al Gore
is going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Many who know Mrs. Gore well say that politics has been her
tonic. ``She can really be down and then she'll get involved in the
political process and she just seems to draw enormous strength from
it,'' said Jerry H. Futrell, a Carthage pharmacist and longtime
friend.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gore has long been considered the most astute political
mind in the family, a pragmatic strategist who continues to embrace
the old-fashioned notion that politics can be personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``She recognizes in this wonderful, sort of uniquely feminine
way how the human interaction in relationships are vital to social
change,'' said Schiff. ``She has been a hostess in many ways
throughout my family's political life but a hostess with real power
and insight.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who know the family well say that Al Gore drew more of his
temperament from his mother than from the father he followed into
the House and the Senate. Both mother and son, they say, are
reserved.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, Gore seems to have drawn strength and confidence from
his mother's enduring presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has given him the courage, the intellect, the background
and the confidence that comes from a strong family,'' said Peter
Knight, a former aide. ``He always knew they'd be behind him and
you have to have that confidence when you're running for president
of the United States.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
