<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3916 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-COX-CVN-STUDIO17-COX     08-16 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-CVN-STUDIO17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE ILLUSION OF POLITICAL REALITY
 &HT;    This article replaces Andrew Glass's regular Sunday column. It
is for immediate release.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``Yeah,'' said Chris Lehane, ``the whole thing is
an illusion. But it really seems authentic.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehane wasn't talking about politics _ a familiar subject to the
press secretary to Vice President Al Gore, who wants to move up.
</P>
<P>
   Gore had been in the movie capital for less than hour. Flanked
by 100-plus khaki-clad motorcycle policemen, he had been driven in
a black armored Cadillac with District of Columbia plates to the
``Main Street'' lot at Warner Brothers Studios. That was Lehane's
``illusion.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore family took a break from the midday heat in what's
known in the trade as a holding area _ ``Stars Hollow High
School.''
</P>
<P>
   Perched on the roof of the two-story ``school,'' Secret Service
agents, dressed in dark-blue work uniforms, peered out at who knows
what through oversized binoculars. Gore's limo was positioned
nearby the cordoned-off ``town square,'' where a party was under
way.
</P>
<P>
   The guests were the Tennessee and Connecticut delegations to the
Democratic National Convention. Gore's guests in the holding area
were Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut and his family.
</P>
<P>
   Set up in front of the ``school,'' Mickey Hart's rock band
played at a level that discouraged conversation. But the delegates
seemed content enough.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, however, they stirred and left their picnic tables to
rush to one side of the ``square.'' Secret Service agents began
whispering into their wrist radios.
</P>
<P>
   What's up, I asked one of them?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Martin Sheen,'' the agent said. ``He's right over
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheen, who plays a president in the CBS television show ``West
Wing,'' was signing autographs for the delegates. Other members of
the ``West Wing'' cast, which is filmed at the Warner studios, were
also having their pictures taken.
</P>
<P>
   Then Mickey Hart called it quits, and the candidates and their
families stepped out onto the bandstand. The cheers were somewhat
dimmed by the heat and the outdoor venue. But the television people
already had gotten all they needed of that from a hangar event at
Burbank Airport that took place when Air Force Two landed.
</P>
<P>
   Before introducing Gore, Lieberman said, ``we're having one hell
of a time.'' The first Jewish vice presidential nominee also noted
that he had spotted a sign during the motorcade that read: ``Viva
Chutzpah.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Lieberman, who had been talking that morning about ``our
Republican friends,'' delivered his punch line: ``The closest
George Bush will get to the West Wing is a remote control.'' The
delegates liked that.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was time to go. After shaking hands all around and
hugging many of the women delegates, Gore and Lieberman climbed
into Gore's limo and sped away on a 12-lane freeway that had been
cleared in both directions. They went to Gore's hotel, the same one
that President Clinton had vacated a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Now left on their own, the other members of Lieberman's family,
accompanied by a far more modest police escort, wound the way back
to their hotel. Since the freeways from Warner Brothers to downtown
Los Angeles were heavily jammed at the start of the evening rush
hour, their return trip from ``Main Street'' took a very long time.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
