<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3923 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-DIVERSITY17-COX     08-16 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-DIVERSITY17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DEMOCRATS SAY THEY'RE THE REAL PARTY OF DIVERSITY
 &HT;    By WILLIAM HERSHEY and MIKE WAGNER
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Democrats have had a good time yukking it up this
week about what they call the Republican ``delusion of inclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   If you want to see real diversity, these Democrats say, come to
Los Angeles and forget about the ``masquerade'' party the
Republicans held in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our convention, our party, our members truly is the face of
America,'' said state Sen. Rhine McLin, Ohio Senate minority
leader. ``The other side had to work awfully hard to get a few
faces of color in their convention crowd. It was a masquerade and
it would be a sad day for all minorities if (George W.) Bush got in
the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   In terms of sheer numbers, it's hard for even Ohio Republicans
to refute McLin.
</P>
<P>
   Of the Ohio delegates to the Republican National Convention who
responded to a Dayton Daily News survey, 82 percent were white, 12
percent were black and 6 percent were other minorities, including
Asians and Hispanics. Over all, 83 percent of the delegates to the
Republican convention were white.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio delegation in Philadelphia was split even about evenly
between men and women.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Los Angeles, 24 percent of the Ohio delegates are black,
4 percent are Hispanic and 1 percent are Asian. The delegation
includes 85 men and 84 women.
</P>
<P>
   Three percent of the Ohio delegation is made up of gays and
lesbians, a category not advertised by Ohio Republicans at their
convention.
</P>
<P>
   In diversity terms, the Ohio delegation compares favorably to
the Democratic National Convention as a whole. Over all, 20 percent
of the delegates are black, 10 percent are Hispanic, 3 percent are
Asian-Pacific and 4 percent are gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio Democrats exceeded the diversity goals they set for
themselves in several categories, said David Leland, state
Democratic chairman.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the goal was to include 36 black delegates, and the
party ended up with 41. The number of Hispanic delegates _ six _
was double the goal of three, said Leland.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Shinn, an Ohio Democratic delegate, said the party's
diversity is a strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our party doesn't fear differences. We don't fear diversity.
We embrace it,'' said Shinn, and attorney and president of the
Stonewall Democrats of Central Ohio, which includes gay and lesbian
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Romero, 41, an Hispanic delegate from Lorain, Ohio, said
that the perception that Bush and the Republicans have connected
with minority voters is a ``fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics in Texas are proud that Bush's nephew in Florida,
George P. Bush, has a Mexican mother, said Romero.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they also remember George W. Bush's father referring to
George P. As 'the little brown one,' `` Romero said.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio Secretary of State J. Kenneth Blackwell, the first black to
hold statewide administrative office in Ohio, said his party is
working hard to ``rebuild a competitive two-party system in the
African-American community.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a work in progress,'' said Blackwell, who was here this
week as a surrogate for George W. Bush, rebutting Democratic
claims.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's plans for cutting taxes and reforming Social Security by
allowing younger workers to invest a small portion of their Social
Security savings in the stock market will help African-Americans,
just as they will help all Americans, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio state Rep. Dixie Allen doesn't buy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I disagree with Ken Blackwell,'' said Allen, a delegate here.
``The party he has chosen is not the party of diversity. It does
almost nothing to assist minority people and their communities. I
don't have to go around Dayton recruiting African-Americans and
other minorities to join our party.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans can talk all they want about inclusion, but
people have long known the Democratic party is their only hope for
diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
