<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3925 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBC-TEXAS-JAMMER0817-     08-16 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-JAMMER0817-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas defensive back Jammer healthy, ready to hit again
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - Pity the wide receiver who lines up across from
Quentin Jammer the first day the University of Texas football team
dons pads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get to hit on Tuesday,'' said an antsy Jammer. ``Let's just
say whoever lines up against me will have a tough time getting off
the line of scrimmage.''
</P>
<P>
   Jammer is UT's most versatile defensive back. He's also the one
who craves the rush of a kamikaze hit more than any of his
defensive teammates.
</P>
<P>
   But he hasn't popped a receiver in almost a year.
</P>
<P>
   Jammer was set to have an all-star year last season at free
safety, but his season ended in August against North Carolina
State. Jammer barely made it into the fourth quarter of that first
game.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the game he had dislocated his left shoulder while
trying to make an arm tackle. The shoulder, which had been
troubling him for more than a year, was popped back in place and
Jammer returned only to reinjure the shoulder..
</P>
<P>
   A week later, doctors used four screws to tighten the shoulder
ligaments. Jammer spent the season watching Greg Brown not only
take over his position, but excel.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday morning, when the Longhorns gather for their first
full-squad workout, Jammer will be at a different position. In the
off-season, the UT defensive staff decided that with Brown more
than capable of handling free safety, they could move Jammer to
cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's such a great athlete, switching to corner hasn't been a
problem for him,'' Brown said. ``As far as the NFL is concerned,
corner is probably Quentin's best position. Whether he's a better
corner or safety, hey, he can play both.''
</P>
<P>
   Jammer's transition to corner has been smooth. He played the
position in high school at Angleton and started four games there as
a freshman in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's easier on my shoulder to move to corner,'' said
Jammer, who said his surgically repaired shoulder now tests
stronger than his right one. ``It's not something at first that I
really wanted to do. But I'm happy to make the move. I'm happy to
play corner. As an athlete, I feel I can play either position
really well.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-0, 200-pound junior gives the Longhorns that rare physical
cornerback who is big enough to match up against today's taller
receivers and physical enough to also play the run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quentin has got the physical size we're looking for,'' said
Everett Withers, UT secondary coach. ``He has a unique body type
for a corner because he's like 6-0, 6-1. He's a big guy, he runs
well, and he has good hips. And those long arms of his make him a
real asset at corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got unique skills. If he works hard during two-a-days,
he's got a chance to be something really special.''
</P>
<P>
   Jammer has yet to earn a starting spot _ he still is behind
Ahmad Brooks and Ervis Hill _ but his move to first team appears to
be imminent. Brooks and Hill, both juniors, have 26 starts between
them, but they are only 5-foot-8. Their lack of height became a
problem last season, when opposing offensive coordinators found
ways to isolate taller receivers against them.
</P>
<P>
   It's also likely that NFL scouts will be taking a peek at Jammer
while they're in town this fall to check out potential
first-rounders, seniors Casey Hampton, Shaun Rogers and Leonard
Davis. Jammer said he is not considering giving up his final year
of eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I haven't really thought about it,'' he said. ``I
might need that fifth year.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he has been thinking about that first day in pads. He
participated in spring workouts, but he wasn't given the go ahead
to pop his teammates until now.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has been out of action for a year, his hitting
reputation still is well-known.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jammer is good at jamming receivers at the line of
scrimmage,'' Withers said. ``He's got a good name for what he has
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes:
</P>
<P>
   Freshman running back Tyrone Richardson will not play this
season because of academic reasons. He hopes to return in the
spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is going to be difficult not being able to play this fall,
but I have some academic issues I have to take care of to return to
the team,'' Richardson said in a statement issued by UT. ``I am
going to take care of that this fall and hope to be back with the
team in January.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson's brief career with the Longhorns has been
sidetracked twice because of academics. He signed with UT in
February 1999, but was not able to report with his class last
August because he did not make the minimum test score on his
college entrance exams. Richardson sat out last fall, made his
score, then enrolled at UT at midterm.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Major Applewhite will be able to practice Friday,
although coach Mack Brown said he was unsure what Applewhite's
limitations might be. Applewhite underwent reconstructive knee
surgery to repair an anterior cruciate ligament. He suffered the
injury in the second half of the Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite said his knee ``feels great.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't swelled at all, not one time,'' Applewhite said. ``I
ice it so I won't get tendinitis. Sometimes I wonder why I ice it
because I haven't had any pain at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was released June 7 (by the doctors). If I would have had to
have played a game that day, I could have.''
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Suzanne Halliburton at
shalliburton(at)statesman.com .
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
