<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3927 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-SURV     08-16 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-SURVIVE-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVIVORS TELL OF SUBMARINE HORRORS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., N.H., Calif.)  By CHRISTOPHER DREW with DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though no one knows just what agonies have befallen the men on
Russia's Kursk submarine, other sailors who have been trapped
beneath the sea describe how quickly the air can turn toxic and
serious physical and emotional deterioration can set in.
</P>
<P>
   The classic image of the dangers of submarine warfare has come
from movies like ``Das Boot,'' where men huddle quietly together to
try to ride out depth-charge attacks and keep their hopes alive.
</P>
<P>
   But as Russian officials spoke with fading hope Wednesday of
saving the men on the Kursk, both Russians and Americans who have
been aboard other stricken submarines, including some cornered in
Cold War confrontations, said headaches were common within a day as
the air grew foul. And many men began gasping for breath and taking
to their bunks with throbbing head pain by the second or third day
as rising levels of deadly carbon dioxide began to consume them.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the second morning, some of us were kind of numb,'' said
Clifford A. Smith, who was on a diesel-powered submarine that was
forced by Soviet forces to go without fresh air for three days on
an early spy mission back in the 1950s. He said the conditions were
probably similar to what has been happening on the hobbled Kursk,
which is no longer able to produce its own fresh air.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the lights were dimmed, and special chemicals were
scattered to absorb some of the carbon dioxide, Smith said, the
crew's condition became so desperate that the sub's captain was
forced to surface _ and allow the Soviets to herd his submarine
away from their coast.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1980, former submariners say, one U.S. sailor had to be
sedated when a spy sub that he was on became temporarily stuck in
the sand in a Soviet seabed.
</P>
<P>
   It is not known how many of the Kursk's 118 crew members
survived the initial catastrophe that led to its sinking last
Saturday, and Russian navy leaders said Wednesday that they did not
know how many were still alive, if any.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials have said that an explosion, possibly
involving one of the Kursk's torpedoes, may have ripped a hole in
the front of the submarine, allowing seawater to flood several
compartments in the front of the sub and sent it spiraling down to
the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Many international experts think any air left in the sub may
have turned poisonous by now, and that nearly all those who
survived the explosion and flooding has probably been overcome by
the buildup of gasses like carbon dioxide, which everyone exhales.
</P>
<P>
   But one of those experts, Rear Adm. Georgi G. Kostov, an
instructor at Russia's naval academy, said Wednesday that it is
possible that some crew members could still be huddled to the rear
of the vessel. And even in describing the best-case scenario, he
painted a picture of an increasingly dank and choking environment
that would soon break even the bravest and most resilient sailor.
</P>
<P>
   The admiral said that if any crew members were still alive, they
would be very cold, as the near-freezing waters of the Barents Sea
undoubtedly has turned the submarine's metal hull into a giant
refrigerator. He also said the men would be getting ``sleepy, going
into a dormant state.''
</P>
<P>
   Kostov said they would still have food and possibly flashlights.
They also might have been able to burn some special candles that
give off oxygen. But, he said, ``the oxygen is running out with
every hour.''
</P>
<P>
   A look at several other disasters and close calls involving
submarines shows how little room there is for error in safeguarding
men caught in ocean depths that many experts describe as every bit
as treacherous _ and unforgiving _ as outer space.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the Russians' efforts to retrieve any survivors on
the Kursk with a giant diving bell most closely resembles what
happened after a primitive U.S. submarine, the USS Squalus, sunk in
1939.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Bryson, 82, who now lives in New London, Conn., recalled in
an interview Wednesday that he was trapped on the Squalus for some
36 hours in 240 feet of water. What he remembers is cold,
foul-smelling air and the fear he tried to tamp down inside him.
</P>
<P>
   Another Squalus survivor, Gerald McLees of Portsmouth, N.H.,
said the crew remained calm, with ``no hysterics or anything like
that,'' in the pitch blackness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got in a bunk, covered up and tried to sleep,'' McLees, now
85, recalled. He said he was just following orders and trying to
conserve oxygen by limiting his movements.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In World War II, many subs went down, some with crews terrorized
through relentless depth-charge attacks. Physicians say that some
of the ways that men die on submarines _ like drowning or gas
poisoning _ are exceptionally painful.
</P>
<P>
   Once diesel subs began being used for spy missions in the Cold
War, their crews were vulnerable to being trapped.
</P>
<P>
   While nuclear-powered subs can create their own air when their
reactors are running, diesel submarines had to stick a pipe above
the waves each night to bring fresh air into the boat.
</P>
<P>
   So in the case of Smith's submarine, the USS Gudgeon, and a few
others, Soviet naval forces were able to keep them from
ventilating, creating conditions over one to three days that would
have been similar to what any survivors on the Kursk faced.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 63, who now lives in North Fork, Calif., said the men on
the Gudgeon kept up their spirits through a determination to
survive.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, after a nuclear-powered submarine, the USS Seawolf,
snuck into the Soviet Sea of Okhotsk on an extraordinarily
sensitive mission _ to tap an underwater communications cable and
retrieve pieces of Soviet missiles _ it was stuck in the sand for
nearly two days before it could power its way off the seabed.
</P>
<P>
   Some former crew members said one enlisted man lost control and
began screaming. A medic was ordered to sedate him.
</P>
<P>
   What has made the Kursk crisis so unusual and suspenseful is
that it sank in relatively shallow water. Other subs that have been
lost in the nuclear era, including two U.S. submarines, have
plunged more than 10,000 feet into the depths.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than have any hope of rescue, these men died nearly
instantaneously when their vessels imploded from the crushing sea
pressures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 2132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
