<DOCNO> NYT20000816.0403 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3928 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEM-POLITICAL-SURFING     08-16 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-POLITICAL-SURFING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR NEWS AGENCIES, POLITICAL CONVENTION'S `NO NEWS' ISN'T `GOOD
NEWS' 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ By the middle of the afternoon Wednesday, most of
the major World Wide Web news sites were no longer able to resist
the story of the stricken Russian submarine at the bottom of the
Barents Sea.
</P>
<P>
   While cable-news channels continued to feature drama-free images
from the Democratic National Convention, on the Internet the news
about the submarine had taken the lead position on the CBS, MSNBC,
Fox News and CNN Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``No Signs of Life'' was the Fox site's headline.
</P>
<P>
   Of the major network sites, only ABC continued to cling to the
convention as its news lead, offering the insight that, yes, now is
time for Vice President Al Gore and Sen. Joseph Lieberman of
Connecticut to introduce themselves to the American people. That
was the boilerplate of the day, the theme emphasized on every
single one of the Web sites and by the cable news anchors.
</P>
<P>
   Most often, it quickly led to the unanswerable question: Would
Gore be able to rise to the occasion and make himself appear
sufficiently presidential to improve his poll numbers?
</P>
<P>
   The lack of drama in Los Angeles was perhaps best exemplified by
CNN's extensive coverage of the arrival of Gore's jet at Burbank
Airport. For what seemed like hours, Air Force Two taxied down the
runway and then sat on the tarmac, the camera focused on the dark,
gaping doorway, waiting for someone, anyone, to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks of watching _ first the Republican and then the
Democrat _ national conventions by flipping back and forth between
cable and broadcast channels, and surfing the Web, have shown how
the absence of news at the party conventions has often led news
organizations to depending on commentary to fill broadcast time.
</P>
<P>
   When news actually did break, like the clash between Los Angeles
police and a variety of protesters on Monday night outside the
Democratic National Convention hall, the tendency of most of the
channels was to show a few quick images and then to ask
commentators inside, who had no idea what was actually happening,
what they thought the clash meant.
</P>
<P>
   The Web, while promising a greater degree of immediacy and
immersion for political convention junkies, most often turned out
to be little more than electronic journals, closer to what might be
found in a weekly magazine than on a live television report.
</P>
<P>
   Many Web sites tried to make points by adding little games and
puzzles and quizzes _ and some of these were actually not half bad.
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC, for instance, had a game called ``Electoral Chess,'' in
which an Internet user could predict which states each presidential
candidate might win in November and see if it would be enough to
get their candidate the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Democracy Now had a protesters' version of Monopoly in which
users were offered the chance to ``buy a politician today!''
</P>
<P>
   Players could take the role of a major conglomerate and then
click through a series of windows. Web site users who picked AT&AMP;T,
for instance, learned that the corporation had $62.4 billion in
revenue in 1999, and had donated $2.9 million to the Republicans
and $1.5 million to the Democrats this year, and paid taxes
totaling $3.2 billion: ``Welcome to the White House,'' the final
window proclaimed. ``Thank you for your donations. You may drop by
anytime you want!''
</P>
<P>
   David Carr, writing on Inside.com, predicted how the major news
agencies would cover the Democratic convention, day by day.
Thursday's reports, he predicted, would center on the vice
president's efforts to finish writing his acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one of the major papers in America will buy into the
transparent canard that Gore _ a man who does push-polling on his
choice of neckwear _ is working the speech all by his lonesome,
revising draft after draft deep into the night,'' Carr wrote.
</P>
<P>
   And the Web chats continued. ABC's Sam Donaldson, who has taken
to the Web with an eager-beaverness second to none, has chatted
incessantly every night of both conventions. When his guest Harry
Thomason, the Hollywood producer and pal of President Clinton,
asked Donaldson how many people were actually out there listening
to them jabber, Donaldson had to admit that he didn't really know,
but it was far, far fewer than were watching the networks.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter, though, Donaldson said. ``We are the acorn and
from this acorn will grow a mighty oak,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
