<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CHENEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHENEY'S STOCK OPTIONS HOLD POTENTIAL FOR CONFLICT OF INTEREST 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This story has been added to Page 1 of The New York Times) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dick Cheney, the Republican nominee for vice president, retired
from Halliburton Co. with millions of dollars worth of stock
options that he cannot cash in until long after the new
administration takes office, the company announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney has previously said he would sell his stake in
Halliburton before he took office, assuming the Republicans win the
election. But Cheney would not be allowed to sell the options,
which cannot be transferred except on death. As a result, he would
have to either abandon the holding or keep it until after the
election, thus giving him a large stake in the future success of
Halliburton while he is serving as vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Dirk Vande Beek, a spokesman for Cheney, declined to say whether
Cheney would retain the options if he is elected. He quoted Cheney
as saying, ``I will do whatever the law requires. I will do
whatever I need to do to avoid any conflict of interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Halliburton's stock fluctuates in large part due to changes in
oil prices. As a result, if he held on to the options, he would
stand to profit if oil prices rose, a factor that the
administration's energy policies could affect.
</P>
<P>
   The chief financial officer of Halliburton, Gary Morris, said in
a telephone interview that under the Halliburton stock option plan,
there was no way for Cheney to transfer the options, such as by
giving them to a charity, before they are exercised.
</P>
<P>
   Halliburton said it would report an $8.5 million one-time
expense as a result of Cheney's departure. Morris said that covered
the value of the options and the restricted stock that had not yet
vested before Cheney retired, as well as an estimated bonus for
2000 that Cheney would receive if the company meets certain
financial goals that have not been disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be roughly in the neighborhood of $1 million,'' said
Morris of the bonus. ``It is not a big number.''
</P>
<P>
   The company declined to give the value of Cheney's pension,
which is based on contributions made by the company during the five
years he worked for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney owns restricted stock and options to purchase stock that
have a current value, based on Wednesday's closing stock price, of
just over $54, or $39.6 million. In May he cashed in options on
100,000 shares of stock for a profit of $3 million. All that value
came from grants from the company during his tenure; he has never
invested any money in the company.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's contract with Halliburton gave him the right to retire
after he reached age 62, but the board chose to waive that
provision for the 59-year-old former defense secretary. Had it not
done so, he would have forfeited options to buy 400,000 shares as
well as 140,000 shares of restricted stock. Morris said the company
calculated the value of them based on the assumption that they were
all sold at a stock price of $42.25, the closing value on July 25,
the day after Cheney was chosen as Gov. George W. Bush's running
mate.
</P>
<P>
   The stock has risen dramatically since then, however, and those
securities would now be worth $13.6 million, up from $7.7 million
on July 25. Moreover, because the options expire at various dates
from 2005 through 2009, the value of them would be much higher if
they could be sold, since a buyer would take into account the
possibility of future increases in the price of Halliburton stock.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, The New York Times reported that Halliburton board
members had been told the value of Cheney's package was $20
million. Morris said he was not familiar with that number, and said
he did not know how much the options package would be worth if
valued according to conventional options valuation models. In
previous Halliburton filings, the company has used assumptions that
would have valued the options as being worth more than $20 million,
but it was not clear what assumptions were used in estimating the
value of the package for board members.
</P>
<P>
   While the company did not give Cheney the right to exercise
options before he otherwise would have been able to do so, it did
remove the restrictions on 140,000 shares of stock. As a result, he
will be able to sell those shares whenever he wishes.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the 400,000 options that have not yet vested for Cheney
will vest in December, and thus could be exercised before the new
administration takes office on Jan. 20. But other options will vest
in December 2001 and others in December 2002. The value of those
options, if they could be exercised today, would be $3.8 million.
That value could rise substantially, of course, since those options
do not have to be exercised until 2008 and 2009.
</P>
</TEXT>
