<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-KENNEDY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUT WILL `THE AL SHOW' PLAY IN PEORIA?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BUD KENNEDY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. _ Nobody remembers anymore that ``Frasier'' was
a spinoff of ``Cheers.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore is hoping we forget that he is a spinoff of the Bill
Clinton presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Gore makes his big pitch Thursday night for a long-running show
of his own. For four years, he's played the dorky intellectual in
the rollicking Clinton comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Like a lot of supporting actors in California, he wants to hit
the Hollywood big time. But first, he had to start out in Burbank.
</P>
<P>
   As a middle school mariachi band inexplicably played ``La
Culebra'' (''The Rattlesnake''), Gore emerged from Air Force Two at
the Burbank airport Wednesday and gave the crowd a little preview
of his proposed show.
</P>
<P>
   We'll see the pilot episode Thursday night. Call it ``The Al
Show,'' replacing this week's reruns of ``The Clinton Show'' and
``The Kennedy Show''.
</P>
<P>
   Gore says he wrote the script all by himself. In fact, he said
Wednesday that he used poster board and an easel to write down his
ideas, which makes me wonder whether he met with himself for
brainstorming sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, he told a sweaty but giddy audience in a steamy
airport hangar that he wants to bring America a ``positive
change,'' yet ``continue the prosperity and progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Do we need a new plot or more of the same story line?
</P>
<P>
   Both, says ``Frasier'' Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In Al's show, teachers will be treated ``like the professionals
that they are,'' he said without explaining. The minimum wage will
go up, doctors will run health care, the air will be cleaned up and
guns will be kept ``out of the hands of criminals _ and of
children'' with mandatory trigger locks.
</P>
<P>
   Gore promised a hard-hitting first episode Thursday night. He'll
focus on the ``specific hard choices'' facing voters, he said.
</P>
<P>
   That would delight voters who otherwise see little difference in
Gore's show and its competition in the fall time slot, a remake
starring Texas Gov. George W. Bush in an updated version of a 1980s
hit.
</P>
<P>
   When Bush drew bad ratings in primaries last spring, his friends
were pleading with the directors to ``let George be George.'' It
worked.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Gore's friends plead with him. They want self-directed Al
to let himself be Al.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he should introduce himself,'' friend and Agriculture
Secretary Dan Glickman said Tuesday afternoon. Vice presidents are
such obscure characters that they require a new introduction,
Glickman said: ``He needs to tell the people where he wants to lead
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Glickman called Gore ``an extremely inquisitive man'' with ``an
extraordinary grasp of complex issues.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the problem: He's so complex, we don't understand where
he stands on many issues.
</P>
<P>
   (Bush poses no such puzzle.)
</P>
<P>
   If Gore has any bad words for Bush in his script Thursday night,
he will probably zero in on a subject where he and Bush obviously
follow a different story line: guns.
</P>
<P>
   Handgun Control hosted Democrats for a one-sided discussion
attacking Bush's gun law record Wednesday. Bush was blasted over
private sales at gun shows and because licensed Texans can pack
concealed handguns.
</P>
<P>
   None other than the secretary of Housing and Urban Development,
Andrew Cuomo, made Bush sound like a throwback to the Stone Age. He
said condescendingly that voters should elect the candidate with
``the intelligent position'' on guns, as if Bush and a majority of
Texas lawmakers are brainless lummoxes.
</P>
<P>
   That's not going to work for the Democrats. That's pompousness.
That's arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   That only works for ``Frasier.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bud Kennedy is a columnist for the Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
