<SLUG> BC-TIRES-RECALL-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL OFFICIALS SAY THEY WILL TOUGHEN STANDARDS FOR TIRES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)   By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Facing growing criticism that regulators should
have spotted problems with Firestone tires sooner, federal
officials said Wednesday that they were working on tougher tire
rules, particularly for sport utility vehicles and other so-called
light trucks.
</P>
<P>
   State Farm, the nation's largest auto insurer, said Wednesday
that it had sent an e-mail message to regulators in July 1998,
alerting them that it had received 21 claims involving Firestone
tire failures over the previous 6 1/2 years. The insurer's
officials also mentioned the problem during a routine telephone
discussion of pending safety issues with regulators a year ago,
said Stephen Witmer, a State Farm spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford Motor Co., which installed on its Ford Explorer sport
utility vehicles most of the tires now being recalled, has
acknowledged that it recalled some Ford Explorers overseas with
identical tires last year but did not tell the National Highway
Traffic Safety Administration, which is part of the Transportation
Department. The agency decided in the 1980s that its legal
authority did not extend to requiring reporting of overseas
recalls, and automakers stopped doing so voluntarily a decade ago,
said Joan Claybrook, the agency's administrator during the Carter
administration and now the president of Public Citizen, an advocacy
group.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators also no longer collect data directly from repair
shops on safety defects, a program that used to provide early
warning of safety issues. The agency maintained contact with an
extensive network of repair shops in the 1970s but allowed it to
disappear in the 1980s, when the agency's budget was cut in half by
President Ronald Reagan, who criticized the agency as an example of
excessive regulatory zeal.
</P>
<P>
   Safety agency officials defended their handling of the Firestone
tire problems Wednesday, saying that they had acted in a timely
manner once a pattern of consumer complaints to the agency had
emerged. The agency's current lawyers share the view of their
predecessors in the 1980s that there is an ``extraterritoriality
exemption'' implicit in the agency's statutes that prevents the
gathering of data on overseas recalls involving autos and auto
parts also sold in the United States, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Neblett, an agency spokeswoman, said that no one at
the agency Wednesday could recall having heard of any warning from
State Farm. But she cautioned that one agency employee who keeps
track of such warnings was not in the office this week.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs' lawyers also criticize the agency for not using its
subpoena powers to demand from them various documents that they
have obtained from Ford and Bridgestone/Firestone, a unit of
Bridgestone of Japan. The lawyers got them during the discovery
process of various lawsuits. The lawyers are prevented from sharing
the information openly because the companies labeled the documents
as trade secrets in providing them.
</P>
<P>
   But Rae Tyson, also an agency spokesman, said that the agency
was confident that it would obtain all relevant documents through
its own requests to Ford and Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   While continuing to study what went wrong in the 6.5 million
Firestone tires being recalled, regulators are starting to look at
how to draft new rules for tire design.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen R. Kratzke, the safety agency's associate administrator
for safety performance standards, said that new rules were needed.
More Americans are driving sport utility vehicles and other light
trucks, and Americans have been driving faster after the repeal of
the national speed limit of 55 mph, he said.
</P>
<P>
   High-speed travel puts more strain on tires. And tall vehicles
are more likely to roll over if they lose a tire, making it
particularly important that their tires are reliable, Kratzke said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``There's no question from looking at our data that a light
truck is more prone to roll over than a car'' when a tire fails,
Kratzke said. Virtually all of the 62 deaths attributed to tires so
far in reports to regulators were on sport utility vehicles that
rolled over.
</P>
<P>
   The current safety test for high-speed driving requires that car
tires not fail when driven on a machine for half an hour at 75 mph,
half an hour at 80 mph and half an hour at 85 mph. For off-road
tires and heavy-duty tires for large pickup trucks, the test is
conducted at a speed 5 mph slower for each of the half-hour tests.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the complaints involving the Firestone tires, which were
certified to the car standard rather than the off-road standard,
involved incidents that occurred during highway driving at a
minimum of 55 mph. Kratzke said that he was studying a requirement
that off-road tires and possibly heavy-duty tires meet the same
standards as car tires, and that all of these tires pass a test of
at least 100 mph.
</P>
<P>
   The safety agency began studying the problem of Firestone tires
in February, when a Houston television station's report on tire
problems prompted several dozen people in Texas to report similar
trouble to regulators. The agency opened a formal investigation in
May, its 20th by then in 2000 alone, after accumulating 90
complaints involving four deaths.
</P>
<P>
   All but two dozen of the complaints came in this year, even
though the Explorer has been on sale since 1990 and a handful of
lawsuits citing tire failures were filed as early as 1993. With
national attention on the problem, the number of complaints to
regulators has soared to more than 750, involving more than 100
injuries and at least 62 deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Witmer of State Farm said that the insurer had repeatedly
collected money from Firestone over the last three years after
contending that manufacturing defects in the tires made the tire
maker, and not State Farm, responsible for covering the cost of
claims. Firestone paid the first of these claims, for $9,700, in
October 1997, he said. State Farm's moves were first reported
Wednesday by The Los Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Karbowiak, a Firestone spokeswoman, said that the tire
maker frequently paid claims from insurers because it was cheaper
than contesting them.
</P>
<P>
   Allstate and Farmers Insurance, the nation's second- and
third-largest auto insurers, respectively, said that they were not
aware of a problem with Firestone tires until the last two weeks.
But both insurers said they were reviewing their records in
anticipation of filing possible claims with Firestone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
