u a BC-HIKE-HUT-ACCESS-ART-1     08-16 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIKE-HUT-ACCESS-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANDICAPPED HIKERS TACKLE A REMOTE SPOT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 3rd from last graf starting: All reached the hut, etc., to
add name of Dr. Susan Murray to those who made hike) (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IN THE WHITE MOUNTAINS NATIONAL FOREST, N.H. _ Over slick
boulders and thick roots, across narrow bridges and through mud
that coated their limbs, three hikers in wheelchairs and two on
crutches won a 12-hour struggle up the Gale Head trail here Tuesday
to reach a mountain hut that naysayers had said they would never
use.
</P>
<P>
   The moral being, said one hiker: Do not tell us where we will
not, and can not, go.
</P>
<P>
   Their destination, the Gale Head hut at an elevation of 3,800
feet, has just been rebuilt by the Appalachian Mountain Club.
During its construction, some club members and New Hampshire
newspapers ridiculed the idea of making the rustic 38-bed lodge
accessible to the handicapped, complete with a ramp and ``grab
bars'' in bigger toilet stalls. It was an absurd waste of money,
they said, because no one in a wheelchair was ever going to get
over the super-rugged 4.6-mile trail.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. Under their own power, but also helped mightily by
family, friends and volunteers who pulled, pushed and tipped them
over boulder after boulder, the three hikers in wheelchairs reached
the wood-shingled hut at sunset _ and, with the happy exhaustion of
any hiker and then some, rolled up the welcoming ramp to dinner.
</P>
<P>
   The hikers' achievement, and the controversy that spurred it,
highlighted a broader phenomenon in the country's wilderness areas:
a push to make everything from outhouses to campgrounds more
friendly to disabled people _ and the debate it sometimes raises
over the wisdom of trying to make the naturally hard-to-get-to
outdoors more accessible.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Forest Service officials say they have no plans to pave
trails or significantly change wilderness areas to conform to
federal disability rules. But, said Janet A. Zeller, who oversees
the agency's push for accessibility, ``When you get to a
person-built facility, you're beyond what nature has put there for
you, and you're into what people have built, and therefore it needs
to meet a standard so that when you get to a structure, you know
what to expect. It's that `Whew!' at the end of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   The national forests in the service's Eastern Region, which
ranges from Maine to Minnesota and Missouri to West Virginia, spent
$2 million in the last year and $18 million in the last eight on
improving accessibility, Zeller said, and has been working on
general guidelines for outdoor access.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the Gale Head hut, Appalachian Mountain Club
officials estimate they paid an extra $30,000 to $50,000 for a
building that was already costing about $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   But New Hampshire is a flinty-spirited state, and the
modifications to the hut were pricey because they were last-minute:
the mountain club learned only belatedly from the Forest Service
that the hut, even though it is among the club's remotest, must
comply with the accessibility rules for new buildings in the
Americans with Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the club's leadership did not mind. Walter Graff,
the group's deputy director, said that the hut ended up with a
better overall design, including widened hallways, a porch and the
elimination of steps up to the bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The AMC is about bringing people to the outdoors,'' Graff
said. ``The fact they're in wheelchairs or otherwise disabled
shouldn't prevent that.''
</P>
<P>
   But others did mind, or at least raised challenges. A local TV
reporter asked why, if people in wheelchairs could drag themselves
up the trail, they could not drag themselves up steps to the hut.
One Appalachian Mountain Club member wrote to the group's magazine,
``So what does a tired hiker see when he gets to the hut? A
wheelchair ramp. Any reasonable person is going to be shocked, then
bemused. What a waste of money.'' Another said that the federal
disability rules could be read to mean that all trails should be
paved, and demanded, ``When will AMC start to fight such insane
regulations instead of meekly acquiescing?''
</P>
<P>
   At Northeast Passage, a program at the University of New
Hampshire that works with people with disabilities, news that the
hut would be accessible at first prompted casual plans to try to
go, said Jill Gravink, the program's director.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Then, when the criticism started coming out, ``All of a sudden
it was, `Hey, we have to make this trip,''' she said. ``Nicole
Haley rolled into my office with a newspaper article and said, `I'm
doing this, are you guys coming?''' They took it as a real slap in
the face, like, `Who are you to tell me I can't do this? How do you
know how much of my own sweat I'm willing to put into getting up
there?'''
</P>
<P>
   (As for the TV reporter, Gravink said she responded, ``Why
bother putting steps on the hut at all? Why not drag yourself in
through a window?'')
</P>
<P>
   And so, after almost a year of planning, with organization by
Northeast Passage and help from We Media, an advocacy media group
for people with disabilities, along with other sponsors, the hikers
set off at about 7:30 a.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The three who used wheelchairs were trying out special Terra
Trek-brand models engineered for the most rugged terrain; they and
their helpers had devised a variety of tested but still
experimental tricks, from long poles that could let helpers lift
the wheelchairs almost like rickshaw bearers, to tethers that let
helpers pull the chairs like oxen, to simple planks that could be
laid over brook crossings or rough ground.
</P>
<P>
   Geoff Krill, a ski instructor and hotel clerk whose 60-year-old
father, Phil, helped push and pull his wheelchair, said that in
making the trip, he wanted to show people in wheelchairs that they
could get out and enjoy the woods, though not necessarily on such
difficult trails.
</P>
<P>
   The trail started out relatively gentle, though every root,
every rock demanded effort that able-bodied hikers would never
think about. Early on, Craig Gray, a management consultant and
Paralympic cross-country skier, took a tumble in his wheelchair
down a hill, but the teams of helpers quickly learned how to keep
their wheelchair athletes upright.
</P>
<P>
   By about 10 a.m., the going got slower, and at about 10:30 came
the one sour note of the day: a hiker who cursed at the group for
blocking the trail and said he thought the whole thing was
ridiculous, adding an expletive for emphasis.
</P>
<P>
   After lunch by a rushing river came the hardest part: the
infamous boulder-staircase known as Jacob's Ladder, with rounded
rock steps big enough to get any hiker huffing. The group tried a
modified Tyrolean traverse, lifting the wheelchairs off the ground
with ropes and letting their occupants pull themselves upward with
a pulley system.
</P>
<P>
   It worked, but not well, and the hikers in wheelchairs went back
to other techniques, including the move that Gray called the
``butt-up,'' in which he simply sat with his back facing the
boulder staircase and lifted himself from step to step using upper
body strength.
</P>
<P>
   Each wheelchair-hiker developed a different style. At one point,
the group around Nicole Haley, who has used a wheelchair since she
fell off a ladder two years ago, resorted to singing ``You've Lost
That Loving Feeling,'' to keep its strength up, and sent renditions
over walkie-talkies to other groups. Gray's team had a slightly
macho style, using exhortations like ``Let's eat that rock!''
</P>
<P>
   All reached the hut at sundown, too tired for ringing
pronouncements, having completed in 12 hours what takes an average
able-bodied hiker 3 1/2. Though Souley Marzouk, who was one of two
who made the trek on crutches, together with Dr. Susan Murray, did
say: ``This shows how determined we are, and how far determination
can take you. It wasn't easy but I guess we figured it wasn't going
to be, and that's why we did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon everyone went inside to the cozy wooden warmth for potato
soup and cheese steak _ and champagne _ at the hut's long tables.
They were to spend Wednesday relaxing at the hut, and Thursday
facing a whole new challenge: the way down.
</P>
<P>
   Would the hut's ramp ever really be used again? Would they ever,
really, want to do this again, after all the almost-tipping and
rib-bruising and grueling labor? Sure, said Krill, 29. ``Next time
I can get enough people to do it with me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
