<DOCNO> NYT20000816.0418 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3950 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-USC-LINEBACKERS-L     08-16 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LINEBACKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC LOADED AT LINEBACKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ For 10 days and nights, Zeke Moreno and Markus
Steele have spent nearly every hour together at USC training camp.
</P>
<P>
   They are constantly standing next to each other on the football
field, going through every linebacker drill. When finished, they
are roommates in a campus apartment at UC Irvine, with their free
time usually spent talking to each other.
</P>
<P>
   But they have never discussed the one subject that seems so
obvious. The one that USC is trumpeting across its media-guide
cover, with a photo of the pair sharing equal billing, and the
words ``Butkus Award Candidate'' atop their names.
</P>
<P>
   ``That conversation hasn't come up once,'' a surprised Steele
said. ``That's funny, not once have we talked about it.''
</P>
<P>
   It would seem a natural subject for two of the hands-down best
linebackers in the Pacific-10 Conference. Unless you really know
them.
</P>
<P>
   They both have a quiet coolness that doesn't crave large amounts
of public attention or hype. Moreno is more outgoing with the
media, but no one confuses him with R. Jay Soward, and he is more
apt to politely ask reporters how they are doing before answering
questions about himself.
</P>
<P>
   Steele is low-key in most public situations, becoming more
outspoken around close friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I'm louder than Zeke. I express my feelings,''
Steele said. ``He is the quiet one. I'm the loud one.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's not that simple. Moreno is the one who holds the
defense together on the field, calling signals and assuming
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``The linebackers are the quarterbacks of the defense,'' Moreno
said. ``If someone slacks off, I have to step up and tell them.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Steele: ``He'll show it on the field and tell guys we have
to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele is a more traditional lead-by-example personality.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they are a reason USC is ranked 15th in the nation and
considered to have perhaps the best defense in the Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   The pair is identical in one respect: their desire to stay on
the same page this season. They want to win football games, and all
this Butkus Award talk doesn't mean much if the Trojans stumble
through another 6-6 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're both proud and know how hard each other works,'' Moreno
said. ``It's a team game. If he wins the Butkus and we win the
Orange Bowl, I'll be happy. And vice versa.''
</P>
<P>
   The two also have fairly easygoing personalities, which allows
them to live together without getting on each other's nerves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always know Zeke has my back on things I do wrong,'' Steele
said. ``And I have his back. We'd have a big problem if we didn't
get along. You have to be eye to eye to play together.''
</P>
<P>
   But it isn't their ability to blend that makes them special.
Each has a penchant for big plays, with Steele coming off the edge
at weakside linebacker and Moreno plugging up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel they have an opportunity to be the cornerstone
of our defense,'' linebackers coach A.J. Christoff said.
</P>
<P>
   That means each has to raise his level of play, especially when
compared to USC's 1998 Butkus Award winner - middle linebacker
Chris Claiborne.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of fine-tuning we've been working on,''
Christoff said. ``You can be a good college football player, but
the room for improvement is great. Both players understand what
their weaknesses are and what they have to improve.''
</P>
<P>
   There's reason to believe each will be better. Especially
Steele. He spent half of last season playing with an injured
shoulder that limited his mobility. He suffered the injury against
Notre Dame, but it really was a reoccurrence of an injury he
suffered at Long Beach City College.
</P>
<P>
   In January, he had surgery to repair his shoulder and it feels
fine for the first time in two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``My shoulder is 100 percent and I can smash like anybody
else,'' Steele said. ``Now I can hit with both shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   If he's healthy, he should also be able to practice full-time.
If there was a weakness to Steele's game last season, it's that he
didn't always understand his assignments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Markus wasn't able to always get (proper) reads because he
couldn't practice because he had a lot of injuries,'' Christoff
said. ``He played on instinct and ability. Now, he's learning to
read within the context of the defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Steele admits he has a lot to learn this season from
Christoff, who was hired after Shawn Slocum resigned to return to
Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   ``He shows us how to do things right,'' Steele said. ``How to
read linemen better with his technique. That's what I need to
learn.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Moreno, he finally has a full season on his resume of
playing in the middle. His sophomore year, he was forced to play
outside linebacker while Claiborne manned the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had big shoes to fill with Chris gone,'' Moreno said.
``People didn't know what to expect from me. People didn't know
what my ability was. It's my turn to take control in situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're as confident as we've ever been, but that comes
with our experience. But I need to work. Just because I'm getting
more publicity doesn't mean I think I'm a better player.''
</P>
<P>
   That could be the key to success for both players. Christoff
believes each benefits from the poise they display on the practice
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sign of a skilled player is one that shows emotion when
you're in a game but can practice and improve his skills without
that high emotion,'' Christoff said. ``These kids carry out
assignments without needing to be on an emotional high.''
</P>
<P>
   They have also adapted to change. Both embraced the arrival of
Christoff before the biggest year of their careers, without
bitterness over the departure of Slocum, who stunned USC last
winter when he abruptly returned to work for his father, Texas A&AMP;M
coach R.C. Slocum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position coach is fun. He's more of a player. He laughs
and listens and jokes with us,'' Steele said. ``It was a great
change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
