<HEADER>
A3951 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-SWM-TRIALS0817-CO     08-16 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWM-TRIALS0817-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sluggish trials show U.S. has work to do
 &HT;    By Mike Tierney
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Sure, the U.S. swimmers looked sharp on the
starting blocks in their newfangled bodysuits. What about the
bodies wearing those back-to-the-future outfits once they dove in?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to improve,'' Richard Quick said of his women's
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a great combination of youth and experience,'' said
men's coach Mark Schubert.
</P>
<P>
   America's two coaches, sitting side-by-side, peeked ahead to the
Games in Sydney with contrasting outlooks Wednesday as the pool was
finally drained on the final night of the Olympic trials.
</P>
<P>
   Quick worried that only one U.S. woman _ Brooke Bennett in the
800-meter freestyle _ has floated to the top of the world rankings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the athletes who have the ability (to win) in most
events,'' he said. ``We will have to swim better than we have in
our lives to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Schubert expressed delight over a youthful turn by the male
side, with eight teens qualifying _ seven more than in Atlanta a
quadrennium ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``These young guys showed a lot of presence here,'' he said.
``They didn't seem overwhelmed.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Schubert might have been wearing rose-colored glasses
and Quick dark, foreboding shades. Though a team stocked with guys
who need fake IDs to buy a drink bodes well for Athens for 2004,
Schubert might be overly optimistic. Quick's side, more
star-studded, is better equipped to ward off host Australia and
help the U.S. remain the chlorined kings and queens of the swim
world.
</P>
<P>
   That's how an Aussie advance scout sees it.
</P>
<P>
   ``On balance, it looks to me as though we should be in front in
the male swimming,'' said Forbes Carlisle, a note-taking coaching
legend from Down Under. ``When it comes to female swimming, it's a
different matter.''
</P>
<P>
   If the guys need chaperones, the women's team is available. It
is older than ever, best illustrated by Dara Torres, 33, back from
a seven-year hiatus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's being accepted more by society and by athletes and their
families that your career isn't over after high school,'' Quick
said.
</P>
<P>
   Torres is at the forefront of a trend among veterans ingesting
creatine and other health supplements. The substances are not on
the IOC banned list, but their long-term after-effects are unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Quick, who personally coaches a strong stable that includes
Torres and two-time trials winner Jenny Thompson, has appointed a
specialist to monitor the swimmers' intake. ``I didn't want to
stick my head in the sand,'' said Quick, acknowleding that swimmers
are aware of drugs, legal or not.
</P>
<P>
   No world records were lowered at these Trials. None was set in
1996, either, and the Americans managed 13 golds (seven women, six
men) at the Games.
</P>
<P>
   As for the tepid times, several reasons were proffered:
</P>
<P>
   _ The shift of the Trials from March to August, designed in part
to keep all contenders training together during the summer, had
many focused on a roster spot rather than a record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we might have more (records).'' Quick said. ``It may
be that the focus truly is on Sydney. If your goal is (just) to
make the team, we won't have as successful an Olympics as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, both coaches welcomed the late-summer trials
dates. Schubert noted that springtime injuries could heal and
younger candidates had more time to develop.
</P>
<P>
   _ The elongated Trials. Schubert noted that NBC-TV requested
that races at the Games be stretched out over eight days, and U.S.
Swimming felt obligated to mimic the schedule here. Also, in some
events, qualifying rounds were added.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to keep your adrenaline and enthusiasm up for eight
days,'' said Schubert, referring chiefly to swimmers in multiple
events.
</P>
<P>
   A spent Thompson, after winning the 100 and 200 freestyle,
withdrew from the 50 on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   _ The overcrowded conditions. Qualifying standards for the
Trials are set low, largely to ensure full hotels in the host city
and fulls rows of parents, grandparents and siblings in the stands.
The warm-up pool often was I-285 at rush hour, prompting sprinter
Tom Dolan to complain that he was more conscious about kicking a
14-year-old in the head than preparing properly for his race.
</P>
<P>
   Quick noted that Olympic warm-up pools are equally chaotic.
``This helps you prepare for the Games,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ The bodysuits. Yes, the outfits that made males look like
modern-day Buster Crabbes and females dressed more modestly than
night-clubbers were not a cure-all.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some, the bodysuit is a very good thing,'' Schubert said.
``It's unfortunate people didn't have more time (to adjust).''
</P>
<P>
   Evidence is needed, he said, to match suits _ knee or calf
length? backless or not? _to body shapes and specific events. Some
swimmers did not know whether to soak the suits before slipping
into them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jury,'' said Quick, ``is still out.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said of the U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
