<SLUG> BC-DEM-CORZINE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEY TALKS, BUT WHEN CORZINE SPEAKS, FEW ARE THERE TO LISTEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo CVN5 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Jon Corzine, New Jersey's Democratic nominee for
the U.S. Senate, gave an energetic speech on the floor of the
Staples Center Wednesday in his debut on the national stage. But
hardly anyone saw it.
</P>
<P>
   His own state's delegates were off having lunch at an Irish pub.
A half-dozen Corzine campaign workers rounded up obliging partisans
from Maine, New Hampshire and Minnesota to fill New Jersey's seats,
wave signs, howl at the applause lines and chant his name.
``Cor-ZEEN!'' a few shouted, until they were corrected.
</P>
<P>
   It was, after all, only a little after 1 p.m., California time.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Corzine, whose name is pronounced COR-zyne, said he had
enjoyed his moment under the lights, despite having felt
``butterflies'' beforehand. And this has been a very different
convention for him. In 1996, when he was merely the co-chairman of
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., he spent only one night with the Democrats in
Chicago. After giving more than $150,000 to the party and raising
much more than that from others, he was rewarded with a skybox seat
during President Clinton's acceptance speech, the week's most
anticipated event.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Corzine's schedule has been grueling and mostly
unglamorous: As official head of the New Jersey delegation, he has
to sit through each morning's two-hour program of political
speeches over breakfast at the New Jersey contingent's hotel. And
he is doing his best to sell himself to local political leaders who
opposed him in the primary, as well as to journalists who have
criticized his campaign spending.
</P>
<P>
   But at times, Corzine still seems to be treated more like a
well-meaning fund-raiser than a political force in his own right.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine's largesse toward New Jersey Democrats did not stop at
the airport in Newark. For example, he put together $37,500 to buy
250 tickets to the postconvention concert on Thursday starring
Barbra Streisand, Enrique Iglesias and others, a benefit for the
Democratic National Committee. And he is throwing a lavish party
for the delegation at Luna Park in West Hollywood after the
concert.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine gave a smaller, private luncheon on Sunday in Santa
Monica, where he was greeted by Sens. John Kerry, Charles Robb and
Tom Daschle as if he were already a colleague. Supporters say there
is reason to be sanguine: Internal polls, they say, show him as
much as 16 points ahead of his Republican rival, U.S. Rep. Bob
Franks.
</P>
<P>
   The luncheon provided another stark contrast between the two
campaigns. At the Republican convention in Philadelphia, Franks
spent his days clamoring for attention, pleading for $1,000 checks
and arranging for events around the country that he hopes will
attract wealthy donors to invest in his candidacy despite the
possibility that he could be outspent by Corzine by as much as 5 to
1.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, meanwhile, had no trouble drawing such deep-pocketed
Democratic givers as Eli Broad, the billionaire largely responsible
for luring the convention to Los Angeles, and Preston R. Tisch of
the Loews Corp. conglomerate, to his luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   But he let his audience know that he did not want its money for
himself. Rather, he asked for contributions to New Jersey's
coordinated campaign, which officials say will spend more than $4
million on combined efforts on behalf of the party's presidential,
congressional and even local races.
</P>
<P>
   ``In New Jersey, the candidate running may be able to do some
things for himself in his own campaign,'' Corzine said in a
third-person understatement. ``We have the ability to make sure
Corzine 2000 does fine. But we work as a team; it's a seamless
thing. I hope when I come knocking on your door in the next few
weeks, you'll know it's not for Jon Corzine.''
</P>
<P>
   In his three-minute speech Wednesday, Corzine touched on
familiar issues but without the liberal language that characterized
his primary campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a time of tremendous prosperity,'' he said, ``a
time when Democrats have transformed record surpluses from record
deficits. It is our duty to use this prosperity to address the
unmet needs of the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   But he made no mention of his platform, which calls for heavy
spending on health care, long-term care and education programs.
Instead, he said, ``We must be bold in responding and proposing
ideas that fit within our means and pay down the debt.''
</P>
<P>
   Two aides to Franks, who managed to obtain convention passes
from someone they called a ``sympathetic New Jersey Democrat,''
seized on Corzine's toned-down rhetoric as inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't say `universal' once,'' said Michael DuHaime,
Franks' deputy campaign manager. ``He spent $35 million promising
universal this and universal that, and now he's backing off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
