<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-GYM-TRIALS0817-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Selection of top 12 could start a ruckus
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The 15 women and 16 men competing in the U.S. Olympic
Gymnastics Trials took a ``team'' picture Wednesday on the floor of
the Fleet Center. By Sunday night, the photo will resemble one from
the television show ``Survivor:'' faces crossed out of all but six
men and six women, the rest voted off by committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that everybody has the best interest of the U.S. team
at heart,'' said Augusta gymnast Jay Thornton.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Atlanta Olympics, the gymnasts with the best combined
scores from the national championships and the Olympic trials made
the team. This go-round, the entire women's team and the final two
men will be selected by a committee to maximize the group's
strength in each event.
</P>
<P>
   Bela Karolyi, brought out of retirement to coordinate the
women's program, and three others will choose the women's team
based on performances at training camps, last month's nationals and
the trials. They're supposed to reveal the Olympians 10 minutes
after the competition ends Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not have controversy,'' Karolyi promised as the
national championships concluded in St. Louis. ``I mean, there's
going to be some crying, some moaning. You know, that's the
sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Dantzscher says she has caught Karolyi watching her during
workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of gymnasts are intimidated by Bela,'' she said.
``I'm not. Why put that extra pressure on yourself? There's already
so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Dantzscher, Elise Ray, Kristen Maloney and Vanessa Atler are
part of the new generation of gymnasts, while Shannon Miller,
Dominique Dawes, Dominique Moceanu and Amy Chow return from
Atlanta's Magnificent Seven. Moceanu hurt her knee Tuesday, but
says she will still try to compete Friday night, when the
competition begins.
</P>
<P>
   This year, new rules only allow a Mag Six. ``I think that kind
of stinks,'' Dantzscher said.
</P>
<P>
   Miller is trying for her third Olympic team. Although Karolyi is
an unabashed admirer of her skills, she doesn't want anyone
thinking she'll get a free pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, I'll be in the top six and there won't be any
question about it,'' she said. ``The last thing I want is a
controversy.''
</P>
<P>
   But what if Miller is seventh and leapfrogs over someone who
places higher?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone wants to be in that situation,'' she
said, ``but no one wants to be left home, either.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Kim Kelly threatened to sue after placing sixth at the
trials, then losing her spot on the team. The federation appeased
her with a free trip to Barcelona.
</P>
<P>
   The selection procedure, said USA Gymnastics president Bob
Colarossi, ``is meant as an insurance policy if some unfathomable
or unintended consequence happens.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, top U.S. hopeful Dan Hayden had such a poor final
routine that he missed the Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   Said Colarossi, ``We can't let that happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
