</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-LIEBERMAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN REACHES OUT TO CEMENT RELATIONS WITH MINORITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos CVN4 and CVN7 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (Eds: This replaces DEM-GORE-ARRIVAL; in 16th graf, Throughout the
..., spelling of `serviche' is cq per quote.)  
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sen. Joseph Lieberman continued his efforts
Wednesday to win the full support of the liberal wing of the
Democratic Party as one of its prominent members, the Rev. Jesse
Jackson, went before the New York delegation to praise the historic
alliance between Jews and blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Against a backdrop of low-level grumbling by members of the
party's traditional base about the Democrats' centrist ticket and
platform, Lieberman visited in quick succession with leaders of
three important constituency groups _ gays and lesbians, Hispanics
and Asian Pacific Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   And at nearly the same time, Jackson told New York delegates
that Vice President Al Gore's selection of Lieberman as his running
mate was a bold expression of affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, he said, ``broke the quota of zero to make sure an
American Jew would be on the ticket. That's what affirmative action
is. It breaks the barriers of exclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson appeared as delegates here were buzzing about an
editorial in The Amsterdam News, the major black newspaper in New
York City, suggesting that Gore had selected Lieberman as a way of
currying favor from Jewish contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson made no direct mention of the editorial, and his
advisers said that discussion of relations between Jews and blacks
was not in response to it. Nonetheless, Jackson's affirmation of
relations between blacks and Jews during the past 20 years drew a
long and loud standing ovation from delegates.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference, Jackson said that he did not share the
view of the newspaper's publisher, Wilbert Tatum, but he declined,
in response to repeated questioning, to condemn Tatum's views.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any language that would threaten our unity is not helpful,''
Jackson said, ``but in a free speech society, we cannot stop people
from talking, whether you agree or disagree.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's remarks, and Lieberman's efforts to reach out to
members of minority groups, underscored complicated dynamics within
the Democratic Party that have slowly surfaced since Lieberman was
selected. It has exposed tensions between the liberal and centrist
wings of the party, as well as between blacks and Jews. Lieberman,
while proudly emphasizing his heritage, said Wednesday that he
hoped people would vote for him because of his qualifications, not
because of his religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're asking people to forget about the history,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   During Lieberman's round of caucus visits, he wooed members with
old-fashioned political appeals, reminding them of votes he has
made in support of their pet causes, promising future support. But
he also sought to establish a more personal connection by
repeatedly linking his heritage as an Orthodox Jew with the
cultural resistance that members of all minority groups have faced
throughout the country's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must say,'' Lieberman told the Asian Pacific Islanders
caucus of the Democratic National Committee, ``that when I look out
on this room I see the faces of my grandparents and my parents, and
I see the story of America. What a remarkable turn of events to
find Al Gore to have had the courage to break the barrier he did by
picking me.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is,'' he added, ``that once barriers fall for one
group, the doors of opportunity open wider for all Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's appearances Wednesday extended a highly public
fence-mending campaign that he began on Tuesday when he met with
the black caucus. Lieberman, a leading member of the centrist New
Democrats, has faced questions from liberal Democrats about his
criticism of some affirmative action programs and his support of
experimental programs to give school vouchers to children in
low-income neighborhoods. On Tuesday he reassured the black caucus
that he would support affirmative action, and Wednesday he spoke to
all three groups about the need for equal opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the promise of America,'' he said. ``We're not looking
for a guaranteed outcome. Just give us a guaranteed opportunity and
we'll work hard enough to earn the outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the caucus visits, Lieberman displayed a relaxed,
self-effacing manner. When he was introduced to the Hispanic
caucus, he joked about opening a kosher-Latino restaurant with such
fanciful dishes as ``gefilta fish serviche.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Lieberman was anxious to solidify his relationships with
these groups, they, too, seemed ready to embrace the Gore-Lieberman
ticket. He received enthusiastic receptions from all three
caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Asian group stood and chanted ``We want Joe.''
</P>
<P>
   During his meeting with the gay and lesbian caucus, a man yelled
``We love you, Joe.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hispanic caucus cheered him wildly and some members held up
signs that read, ``Viva Gore-Lieberman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I could get used to this,'' Lieberman joked.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Lieberman has pledged not to engage in harsh,
partisan attacks against the Republican Party, and Wednesday he
largely abided by that promise. He barely mentioned the Republican
nominees, George W. Bush and Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of my best friends are Republicans,'' he quipped at one
point.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he remarked some criticisms.
</P>
<P>
   Republican policies, he said more than once Wednesday, would
only ``squander'' the current prosperity, and he ridiculed the GOP
itself as ``the same old crowd'' _ intolerant, white, rich and
unrepresentative of America's diversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``They worked hard to create an appearance of inclusiveness on
the platform in Philadelphia a couple of weeks ago,'' he said.
``But at this convention, the inclusiveness and diversity are on
the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Tuesday, Lieberman said that part of his job
as a running mate included re-introducing Gore to the electorate.
On Wednesday, he worked hard at fulfilling that role. He described
their 12-year friendship, and recalled how they have often talked,
argued and prayed together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this man,'' Lieberman told the Hispanic caucus,
referring to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in Al Gore,'' he told the Asian caucus.
</P>
<P>
   Again and again, Lieberman described his selection as a window
into Gore's values and character. ``Al Gore said more about
himself, his trust in the American people, than he did about me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
