<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3967 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-TV-SURVIVOR0817-COX     08-16 0372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURVIVOR0817-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OnBy Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``I'm winning this thing,'' Sean Kenniff, a.k.a. Mr.
Clueless, announced right before he was voted off the island on
Wednesday night's ``Survivor,'' leaving four castaways for next
week's million-dollar finale.
</P>
<P>
   Sean had it right earlier when he said of his island mates:
``This is the most conniving bunch of people I've ever met in my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Wiglesworth avoided almost certain exile by winning the
immunity challenge. She characterized the group as she drank the
beer she won earlier during a reward challenge mud bath (where was
banished cutie pie Colleen Haskell when we needed her?): ``We're
not evil. We just play bad people on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   The remaining four bad actors:
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hatch: The one we most love to hate; a TV casting
director referred to him as ``Heather Locklear on `Melrose Place.'
'' Openly gay and brazenly manipulative, Richard concocted an
alliance that's kept him on the island despite being its most
despised citizen. He summed up Wednesday: ``Maintaining some kind
of thumb on all these people's personalities who I care very little
about is exhausting.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Boesch: The coot. Politically incorrect (hopes friends back
home don't think he's ``queer'' for associating with Richard), this
72-year-old ex-Navy SEAL with his scruffy gray beard and snarling
impatience looks like a survivor. For those handicapping the
winner, Rudy's the perennial sleeper. But he appears to be losing
it: during Wednesday's immunity challenge, we wondered if he
remembered his name.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Hawk: The toughie. Often as unlikable as Richard, and
occasionally in touch with her feminine side (like when she
befriended Kelly and cried). A Wisconsin truck driver, Susan tells
it like it is _ to anybody, usually to gain an advantage. For her
and Richard, surviving is high-stakes poker.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Wiglesworth: The waffler. Sometimes this 23-year-old
Nevada river guide appears ready to play on somebody's team; other
times she acts like a free agent. She's escaped banishment more
times than Rudy's griped about ``lesbians.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
