<HEADER>
A3969 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-BAXTER17-COX     08-16 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-BAXTER17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LIEBERMAN WON'T HELP, HURT GORE IN THE SOUTH
 &HT;    By TOM BAXTER
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Thursday morning the Georgia delegation is
scheduled for a visit from one of this convention's stars, Hadassah
Lieberman. After her husband's speech Wednesday night, and
considering her compelling personal story, she can expect a warm
reception.
</P>
<P>
   But how well will Sen. Joseph Lieberman, an Orthodox Jew from
Connecticut, play in the South this November?
</P>
<P>
   The likely answer is that, Florida excepted, Lieberman's
presence on the ticket isn't going to help Al Gore in those
Southern states where he trails George W. Bush. But he isn't likely
to hurt, either.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Roy Barnes delivered what will be the operative line in the
South last week when he referred to him as a ``northern Sam Nunn.''
</P>
<P>
   The sort of conservative-leaning Democratic centrism Barnes was
referring to was on display in Lieberman's speech, which included a
list of notable presidents that surely is unique at a Democratic
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``As every faith teaches us, and as Presidents from Lincoln to
Roosevelt to Reagan to Clinton have reminded, we must as Americans,
try to see our nation not just through our own eyes, but through
the eyes of others,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic running mate took the Republicans to task on
issues from education to health care to finance reform. He jabbed
the GOP for what he described as a Hollywood-style performance at
its Philadelphia convention, and borrowed Sen. John McCain's
``straight talk'' line.
</P>
<P>
   But interestingly, this running mate's speech was not as sharply
partisan as Dick Cheney's two weeks ago. Using the rhetoric of the
Senate, he referred to his opponents as ``our Republican friends,''
and called them ``decent and likeable men.''
</P>
<P>
   The only Bush line he admitted to being angered by was the
Republican's charge that the current administration has left the
country with a ``hollow military.''
</P>
<P>
   On balance, it did seem a very Sam Nunn-ish sort of performance.
``I think Lieberman is going to play better in the South than
people expect him to,'' said Herb Mabry, a Georgia delegate and
past president of the state AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   Labor, he said, should go ``all out'' for Lieberman, despite a
generally conservative voting record.
</P>
<P>
   One particular area of concern is how Gore's running mate will
play among African-American voters, crucial to Democratic victories
in the South. One of Lieberman's biggest tasks this week has been
to win the favor of Rep. Maxine Waters of Los Angeles, who had
expressed doubts about his voting record.
</P>
<P>
   But Curley Clark, a Mississippi delegate and president of the
Pascagoula NAACP, said he thought African-Americans ``will not be
as skeptical as some whites,'' because his nomination knocks down
another historical wall of discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Hall, a Florida delegate from Miami, said Lieberman will
have double advantage in her state.
</P>
<P>
   Not only should Lieberman boost turnout among Jewish Democratic
voters in South Florida, but he enjoys good relations with Cuban
Americans. She said the Cuban-American National Foundation,
generally a reliable supporter of Republican candidates, reportedly
may not endorse in this year's presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter's e-mail address is tbaxter(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
