<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. Moves to Improve Tire-Safety Rules
</P>
<P>
   Facing growing criticism that regulators should have spotted
problems with Firestone tires sooner, federal officials said
Wednesday that they were working on tougher tire rules,
particularly for sport utility vehicles and other so-called light
trucks. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon's Striking Unions Set Deadline for Settlement &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a development that could change the direction of the walkout
by more than 86,000 employees of Verizon Communications, union
representatives for nearly two-thirds of the striking workers said
Wednesday that they would break off negotiations if they did not
reach an agreement with the company by midnight Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard Reports 23 percent Jump in Earnings  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard reported quarterly earnings that beat analysts'
estimates, driven primarily by strong sales of personal computers
and printers. Its board also approved a stock split. Analysts said
that a large part of the 23 percent jump in earnings came from
higher-than-expected interest income, a more favorable tax rate and
other nonoperating contributors.
</P>
<P>
   NTT Unit in Talks on U.S. Venture
</P>
<P>
   The wireless arm of Nippon Telegraph &AMP; Telephone of Japan, the
world's biggest communications company, is in preliminary
negotiations to acquire a minority stake in the pending wireless
joint venture between BellSouth and SBC Communications, two of the
Bell local telephone giants.
</P>
<P>
   Prices Edged Up 0.2 Percent in July
</P>
<P>
   Consumer inflation increased 0.2 percent in July, the Labor
Department said, reassuring analysts that the Federal Reserve will
not raise interest rates on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's Options Limited on Stock
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney, the Republican nominee for vice president, retired
from Halliburton Co. with millions of dollars worth of stock
options that he cannot cash in until long after the new
administration takes office, Halliburton said. The company said
Cheney would not be allowed to sell the options, which he said he
would do before taking office. Thus, he will have to either abandon
the stake or hold it, giving him a large stake in the future
success of Halliburton while he is serving as vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Major Stock Indexes Stumble Lower
</P>
<P>
   Blue-chip stocks moved lower as worries about a slower pace of
consumer spending dogged retailers for a second day and investors
continued to lock in profits on recent gains. The Dow Jones
industrial average, slumped 58.61 points, to 11,008.39. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index edged down 4.58 points, to 1,479.85.
The Nasdaq composite index rose 9.54 points, to 3,861.20.
</P>
<P>
   Profit Drops at News Corp.
</P>
<P>
   News Corp. said after-tax profit for the company's fourth
quarter fell 14 percent. The company has just agreed to acquire
Chris-Craft Industries, whose television stations carry the UPN
network, which is owned by Viacom-CBS. Rupert Murdoch, who controls
News Corp., said he was open to negotiating with Viacom regarding
the future of the network.
</P>
<P>
   Oil Prices Rise 13 Cents a Barrel
</P>
<P>
   The price of crude oil rose to $31.80 a barrel even after the
American Petroleum Institute reported that inventories rose an
unexpected 7.4 million barrels last week and the Energy Information
Agency reported a smaller, but still strong, 3.4 million barrel
increase. That price jump pretty much sums up the current outlook
for oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   British Telecom to Increase Stake in German Firm
</P>
<P>
   British Telecommunications is expected to announce Thursday that
it will take control of Viag Interkom, a German telephone operator,
by doubling its ownership stake to 90 percent in a deal worth about
6 billion euros or $5.46 billion, according to executives close to
the deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
