r f BC-ELVIS--LIVE-SFCHRON &LR;      08-16 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELVIS--LIVE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEARS AFTER DEATH, ELVIS NOW TAKING CARE OF E-BUSINESS 
 &HT;     BY DAVID LAZARUS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ Live on the Net, it's dead Elvis.
<P>
   As the 23rd anniversary of Elvis Presley's death was
commemorated Wednesday by thousands of visitors to Graceland in
Memphis, Tenn., thousands more made a cyber-pilgrimage to the
King's final resting place via the first live Webcast of the annual
candlelight vigil.
</P>
<P>
   The Webcast was just one manifestation of Elvis on the Internet.
A search of the Web turned up more than 700,000 listings for
Elvis-related sites (although some, admittedly, were more concerned
with rock star Elvis Costello and ice skater Elvis Stojko.)
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no one else like Elvis,'' said John Butler of
Weehawken, N.J., whose site, Johnny's Elvis Presley Salute,
attracts about 1,000 visitors a month. ``He was one of a kind.''
</P>
<P>
   The people at Elvis Presley Enterprises, which controls Elvis'
estate and commercial legacy, have done their best to remain at the
forefront of online Elvis endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   This month, the company redesigned its official Elvis Presley
site at  &LR; www.elvis-presley.com  &LR; to include virtual tours of
Graceland and voluminous offerings of Elvis info and souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   The redesign was effected just in time for Elvis Week, which
rolls around each year at this time to commemorate the 1977 heart
attack of the then-elephantine man in the blue suede shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all exhausted here,'' said Todd Morgan, a spokesman for
Elvis Presley Enterprises. ``We're going to finish up Elvis Week
and then we're all going home and collapsing.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to broadcast this year's candlelight vigil live on
the Web, he said, came as part of efforts to improve Elvis' online
presence.
</P>
<P>
   Elvis, needless to say, would have loved the Net. Or so Morgan
insisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elvis embraced all new gadgets and technologies,'' he said.
``He had home video before anyone else. He had big-screen TVs. The
Internet would definitely have interested him.''
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps frustrated him a little as well. Those who watched
the live Webcast on Tuesday night generally saw little more than a
dark blur punctuated by a few flashes of light.
</P>
<P>
   Nighttime candlelight vigils, it's safe to conclude, do not lend
themselves well to postage-stamp-size video streams.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Sherry Yeaman, a spokeswoman for Santa Clara's Yahoo,
which provided the technology for the Webcast, said about &LR;   &LR; 10,000
Elvis fans tuned in via the Net to pay their respects to the King.
</P>
<P>
   Just to keep some perspective here, about 2 million people tuned
in for the most recent Victoria's Secret online lingerie fashion
show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still,'' Yeaman said, ``10,000 is pretty good. We have college
basketball games that might get 50,000. But 10,000 is pretty good
for niche content.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Jaffe of Grass Valley (Nevada County), whose site, Elvis
Presley Online, attracts as many as 3,000 visitors a day, believes
Elvis would have been thrilled by the idea that fans could download
his songs over the Net.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved to have his music out there in the world,'' Jaffe
said. ``He was a pretty generous spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, were he still around, Elvis would be similarly pleased
(and more than a little flattered) to see that a search of eBay for
Elvis stuff turned up more than 8,000 items being auctioned.
</P>
<P>
   Mementos of the King's too-brief tenure included an Elvis
Presley Rock &AMP; Roll Thermometer (``Exceeds the quality standards of
any metal thermometer on the market today'') and a set of five
Elvis matchbooks (``If you love Elvis, you gotta have these'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight thousand is a fairly good listing,'' said Kevin
Pursglove, an eBay spokesman in San Jose. ``It's one of our
most-active categories.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there are nearly as many Elvis items listed as there
are Beanie Babies (9,000) and way more than the number of Pez
dispensers (2,500).
</P>
<P>
   Pursglove said the amount of Elvis goodies for sale on eBay
spikes every year at this time as the faithful gather, both
physically and via the Net, to remember their fallen leader.
</P>
<P>
   And while eBay has seen its share of body parts and other
unsavory offerings, Pursglove said no one has dared blaspheme the
King's memory by offering, say, Elvis' kidney.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can offer your own kidney,'' he said, ``but don't mess
with the King.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Lazarus at davidlaz(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
