<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3976 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CVN-GEPHARDT-HNS &LR;      08-16 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-GEPHARDT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
GEPHARDT PROMISES BIPARTISANSHIP IF DEMOCRATS TAKE BACK THE HOUSE.
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JUDY HOLLAND
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ House Minority Leader Richard A. Gephardt, in an
overture to Republicans and independents, promised Wednesday that
if the Democrats win control of the House in November and if he
becomes speaker next year, he will lead the chamber with humility
and bipartisanship.
</P>
<P>
   He aroused cheers from delighted delegates at the Democratic
National Convention when he started his speech by shouting: ``Al
Gore will be elected and we will take back the House.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he told the crowd and a prime-time television audience, ``I
promise you that if we win a majority, we will be humble about our
beliefs and listen to the beliefs of others,''
</P>
<P>
   Pounding both fists on the podium and pointing to the delegates.
``We will work with the Republicans to try to find consensus and
bring all Americans along together. Hear me: When we win the House,
back we will replace `my way or the highway' with `our way
together.'''
</P>
<P>
   He was interrupted by chants of ``Take back the House,'' as
supporters waved placards saying ``Speaker Gephardt.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt accused the Republican House leadership of being
``one-sided, intolerant of other views _ unbending to compromise
and consensus.'' He said that over the last six years House
Republican and Democratic leaders have ``met maybe once a year'' to
discuss key issues. Of the GOP leaders, he said, ``They don't
communicate. They dictate. Democracy deserves better''
</P>
<P>
   Although he didn't mention any names, Gephardt' clearly aimed
his stinging reference at Newt Gingrich, the former House speaker
from Georgia who Democrats said was autocratic and who resigned
after Republicans suffered bruising losses in the 1998 election.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt has also feuded with House Majority Leader Richard K.
Armey and Majority Whip Tom DeLay, both of Texas, and he charged
that the Republican leadership is unwilling to approve a patients'
bill of rights, gun safety measures, a Medicare prescription drugs
benefit, President Clinton's plan to reduce class size in schools
and an overhaul of campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt's charges of Republican incivility and failure to
consult with Democrats were reminiscent of GOP charges eight years
ago that Democrats, who had controlled the House for the previous
40 years, were arrogant and failed to consult them. In fact,
Gephardt alluded to those charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were in the majorithy, we made some errors,'' he said.
``But we have learned from the past _ learned that while we have
strong beliefs we aren't always right, we do not have the answer to
every problem.''
</P>
<P>
   He urged his national audience not to believe ``that our
political well is is too poisoned, the partisan rift, too great.''
</P>
<P>
   Altough Gephardt has differed over the years with Gore,
particularly on the issue of expanded trade, he noted during his
speech Wednesday that he and his wife Jane have been friends with
Al and Tipper Gore for nearly 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore is a good man,'' Gephardt said. ``He is a decent,
caring man. He listens to his heart and his head. He loves his
family. He loves this country. He could be the best president this
country will ever have.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Gore and Gephardt were elected to Congress in 1976, and in
1988 they were bitter rivals in unsuccessful campaigns for their
party's presidential nomination. In March of this year, Gephardt
bowed out of the 2000 presidential race and endorsed Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt said in his speech that Gore ``knows that making the
right decisions requires more than a president. It requires a
majority in Congress to help make the right decisions for America's
families.''
</P>
<P>
   Gepardt, 59, was on Gore's short list of six possible vice
presidential choices last month, but he repeatedly said he
preferred to focus on winning back the House for Democrats, which
would ensure his selection as speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats thought Gephardt would be an attractive running
mate for Gore because the congressman hails from Missouri, a
crucial swing state and is viewed as a champion for working
families in a year when both parties are focused on helping
families. Gephardt, one of labor's staunchest allies in Congress,
also would have solidified Gore's backing from unions.
</P>
<P>
   But some critics thought centrist Democrats as well as
independents might view Gephardt as too liberal.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
