<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3979 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-GOODGUYS--LEADER-SFCH     08-16 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODGUYS--LEADER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEST BUY EXEC NAMED CEO AT GOOD GUYS  &HT;     BY CAROL EMERT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ Good Guys Inc. poached a top executive from rival
Best Buy Co. to help fix the troubled electronics chain and one day
take its helm.
<P>
   Kenneth Weller, who began his retailing career as a Good Guys
store clerk in 1982, was named president of the Brisbane
electronics company Wednesday. He is the heir apparent to Chairman
and Chief Executive Officer Ronald Unkefer.
</P>
<P>
   The move was ironic because Weller, by all accounts a popular
and charismatic sales executive, recruited a slew of valuable Good
Guys employees after moving to Best Buy in 1993, where he opened
stores in direct competition with Good Guys.
</P>
<P>
   The crossover is particularly interesting in light of widespread
rumors that Good Guys had been in talks in recent months about
being acquired by Best Buy, which is headquartered in Eden Prairie,
Minn.
</P>
<P>
   Best Buy, which runs eight stores in the Bay Area and 365 across
the United States, refused to comment on either Weller's move or
the rumored acquisition talks.
</P>
<P>
   Unkefer said Good Guys, which operates 79 high-end stores in
California, Washington, Oregon and Nevada, is not involved in
merger discussions. Asked whether such conversations had taken
place recently, he said, ``I can't say. I don't want to comment at
all about those kinds of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Sources said Best Buy considered running Good Guys as a
secondary chain targeting upscale consumers and technophiles. The
talks ceased after an agreement could not be reached, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Unkefer did confirm that Good Guys is negotiating to move its
high-profile Brisbane headquarters on San Francisco Bay to a
cheaper site in Hayward.
</P>
<P>
   Good Guys reportedly will receive a multimillion-dollar buyout
of its Brisbane lease. Due to a staff downsizing, it is already
subletting three floors of the five it leases in an office building
visible from Highway 101.
</P>
<P>
   Unkefer would not discuss the lease terms, saying no deal is
final. But Good Guys' quarterly report, filed with the Securities
and Exchange Commission on Monday, says the company may break even
this year instead of posting a loss in part because of ``earnings
that could be achieved from leased real estate transactions being
negotiated.''
</P>
<P>
   Weller, who starts September 1, rejoins Good Guys at a crucial
juncture. The company has posted a net loss in each of the past
four fiscal years and, despite earlier projections for profits this
year, will either break even or see a small loss in fiscal 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Unkefer, who founded the chain as a San Francisco stereo shop in
1973, returned last summer after a several-year hiatus to try to
turn the business around. But all did not go according to plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came in last July, I thought I could fix everything in
90 days and be a superhero,'' Unkefer said in a telephone interview
Wednesday ``My timing was a little off.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Unkefer noted, ``We lost $40 million last year, so
we've made $40 million in progress'' by reaching close to
break-even in 2000. ``If we could do half as well next year, I
would be a hero,'' Unkefer said.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Gordon, an analyst with Banc of America Securities in San
Francisco, sees clear signs of a turnaround at Good Guys.
</P>
<P>
   Losses are narrowing and sales in some key categories, such as
televisions, digital cameras and digital video disc players, are
improving. In categories excluding computers and home office
equipment, which Unkefer discontinued last year, sales rose a
healthy 4 percent in the quarter ending June 30.
</P>
<P>
   Good Guys has also begun renting excess space in two stores to
Tower Records and is looking for other tenants, which should help
improve its store productivity, Gordon noted.
</P>
<P>
   But the top priority at Good Guys is improving its sales force.
</P>
<P>
   Unkefer has made some changes, such as reorganizing the sales
staff and laying off less knowledgeable workers. Weller said he
wants to ramp up their knowledge of products and infuse them with
enthusiasm that will translate into better customer service and
higher retention rates.
</P>
<P>
   Current and former Good Guys executives described Weller in
Moseslike terms. ``He is a leader of people, the best I ever worked
with,'' Unkefer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a tremendous motivator, a tremendous teacher,'' said
Robert Gunst, who served as Good Guys CEO from 1993 until last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Unkefer, who worked closely with Weller for 10 years during the
'80s and '90s, asked Weller to rejoin Good Guys even before Unkefer
had officially resumed the CEO role last year.
</P>
<P>
   But Weller was hesitant to make the jump, in part because he was
not sure that Good Guys would pull through, and in part because he
was waiting for millions of dollars of Best Buy stock options to
vest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were waiting for the stars to line up,'' said Weller, who
still has many allies at Good Guys from his earlier stint there.
</P>
<P>
   Weller joined Good Guys in 1982 as a store clerk in Concord. He
had just moved to the United States from his native Great Britain
as his first career as an amateur horse-racing jockey was coming to
an end.
</P>
<P>
   Weller said he moved to California in pursuit of a love interest
and planned to stay for only two years. But in 1986, he was
promoted to vice president of sales and is credited with helping
Good Guys grow from 11 stores to 45 during his seven years in that
role.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Weller moved to Best Buy and became a senior vice
president for sales, opening 60 stores in seven years throughout
the West and the South. He will join the Good Guys board in
addition to assuming the president's mantle.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carol Emert at  &LR; cemert &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
