u f BC-AT&AMP;T-OVERHAUL-NYT &LR;      08-16 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-OVERHAUL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T OVERHAUL PLAN MAY BE DECIDED UPON IN SEPTEMBER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Exclusive) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With its stock price down, AT&AMP;T will probably decide on a
significant restructuring in September, possibly including a
leveraged buyout, led by John C. Malone, of the company's consumer
long-distance telephone business, people close to AT&AMP;T said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The company is considering a broad range of potential moves
meant to emphasize its strengths. Those options may increase over
the next few weeks: the people close to the company said that
AT&AMP;T's investment bankers were hard at work developing new
strategies. A person close to AT&AMP;T's senior leadership said that at
least a preliminary decision would probably be reached at the next
board meeting, scheduled for the third week of September.
</P>
<P>
   However, a person close to the discussions said it was unlikely
that an announcement would be made shortly after that meeting.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a potential buyout of the consumer unit, other
options include issuing new shares meant to track the consumer
unit, issuing shares meant to track AT&AMP;T's cable television
operations, and simply selling one or both of those units to other
publicly traded companies.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, AT&AMP;T might choose to do nothing. Support on the board
for C. Michael Armstrong, the chairman, is strong. But at the
moment, many analysts believe that he cannot survive next year
unless the company is revamped or the prospects for AT&AMP;T as
currently structured somehow brighten significantly.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the view has been bleak. AT&AMP;T's shares have lost
almost 37 percent of their value this year _ closing Wednesday on
the New York Stock Exchange at $32.125, up $1, and not much above
the 52-week low of $29.625 touched on Aug. 8.
</P>
<P>
   The sell-off has come as the company's core consumer
long-distance business shrank more quickly than most analysts
expected and the once-robust unit serving business customers has
also stumbled. At the same time, AT&AMP;T's move to become the nation's
No. 1 cable television provider has not yet been as successful as
many investors had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   So now, with a market value around $121 billion, AT&AMP;T is worth
only somewhat more than the $96 billion it paid to acquire the
cable giants Tele-Communications Inc. and the MediaOne Group.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the individual value of each of AT&AMP;T's operations,
including the consumer and business services units, as well as the
wireless holdings, AT&AMP;T's top executives and board members believe
that the company is worth $225 billion to $300 billion, a person
close to the company said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The most vocal proponent for change has perhaps been Malone, the
former chairman of TCI and an AT&AMP;T board member. Malone, whose
stake in AT&AMP;T has declined in value by $1 billion during the
stock's slide, has said that AT&AMP;T is trying to do too many things
at once.
</P>
<P>
   A person close to Liberty Media, Malone's television programming
operation, said Wednesday that he was not seriously entertaining
the idea of trying to acquire all of AT&AMP;T. For one thing, Liberty
Media, which trades as an AT&AMP;T tracking stock, cannot issue
additional shares without AT&AMP;T's approval, according to a person
close to AT&AMP;T. And even if Liberty Media is spun off, a takeover of
the parent company is not in Malone's current plans, said the
person close to Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   But Malone could still play a major role in a remaking of AT&AMP;T,
and not just as a board member.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more intriguing options on the table is for a
Malone-led leveraged buyout of the consumer long-distance
operations. That business, which made AT&AMP;T the giant it is today,
is now shrinking amid ruthless price wars and the entry of huge
regional Bell companies into the long-distance arena.
</P>
<P>
   Still, long-distance service generates rafts of cash. This year,
the unit will probably produce about $8 billion in cash flow _ or
earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization, on
perhaps $20 billion of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   In any potential sale, a Wall Street analyst said Wednesday that
the consumer unit would probably not fetch more than twice those
earnings, or $16 billion. And, in any case, the unit's cash flow
could easily support a significant debt load. Malone, known as a
financial wizard, would almost surely be able to put together the
necessary financing, if he so chose.
</P>
<P>
   A person close to AT&AMP;T's continuing deliberations cautioned,
however, that for now the leveraged-buyout option did not appear
any more likely than any of the others under consideration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
