<HEADLINE>
UNITED TESTS NEW SYSTEM TO SEND FLIGHT DELAY ALERTS  &HT;     BY VERNE KOPYTOFF
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ United Airlines passengers could get some relief
soon from flight delays and cancellations.
<P>
   The company is testing a service that sends messages with
updated flight information to passengers via their cellular and
home telephones, electronic organizers, personal computers and fax
machines.
</P>
<P>
   The tests come as United Airlines is beset with flight delays
and cancellations because of labor troubles, bad weather and
crowded skies.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  However, Dan Black, director of e-commerce for United, said
his company first considered the messaging service before its
latest troubles began this spring.
</P>
<P>
   The technology, created by Centerpost, a Chicago company, will
allow United to communicate with customers by e-mail or automated
telephone calls. The program presumably would be more convenient
for customers because they would no longer have to call about
flight schedule changes or fear being far from a telephone just
before their flight is scheduled to take off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps customers control their time,'' Black said. ``If they
know about their flight being delayed or canceled, customers can
better manage their time.''
</P>
<P>
   The United test is expected to begin in 35 to 40 days and will
include several thousand passengers, Black said. The service will
be free during the trials but it is unclear whether travelers will
have to pay a fee if United adopts the technology for its
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  To use the service, travelers must sign up at a Web site and
choose how to receive their messages. Juergen Stark, chief
executive of Centerpost, said travelers can, for example, choose to
get urgent messages about flight delays on their cellular
telephones and less-pressing ones such as fare sales and
frequent-flier postings on their e-mail accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Many airlines already use e-mail and faxes to a limited extent
with travelers to send confirmation codes and notices about fare
sales. United implemented a program in December to e-mail
passengers who register online about delays and cancellations in
their flights.
</P>
<P>
   Centerpost's program could be the most-comprehensive use of
automated messaging by an airline, according to Eric Arnum, editor
of Messaging Online, a daily newsletter that tracks the messaging
industry.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  He said United may be able to save money with the program by
hiring fewer people to call passengers when their flights are
canceled. It could be particularly useful, he said, for business
travelers who are difficult to reach when away from home.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  As it is, United rarely calls passengers when their flights
are delayed. Moreover, the automated information the company
provides on the telephone often is unreliable.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Verne Kopytoff at verne(AT)sfgate.com
</P>
