<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3982 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-BOFA--WITHDRAWAL-SFCH     08-16 1665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOFA--WITHDRAWAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAST CASH 60 MILES: BOFA'S EXIT LEAVES TOWN IN THE LURCH, WITHOUT 
 BANK  
 BY SAM ZUCKERMAN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR; Bridgeport, Calif. _ This little town on the eastern slope of
the Sierra Nevada, set in one of the wildest and most beautiful
places in California, is about to experience something scarcely
imaginable to the average urbanite _ life without a bank.
<P>
   At the end of September, Bank of America will close its
Bridgeport branch, the only banking office in this tourist town of
700 people. Unless another institution moves in at the last minute,
local residents with banking business will have to travel more than
120 miles round trip south to Mammoth Lakes or north to
Gardnerville, Nev., over a highway that can be treacherous in the
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, local merchants say, a stop at the bank to deposit
cash and lay in a supply of change is a routine errand, a chore
many of them do every day. When BofA pulls out of Bridgeport, that
task will become a time-consuming and potentially dangerous ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Mills, proprietor of Hays Street Cafe, a restaurant on
Highway 395 at the south end of town, said he will go to
Gardnerville to bank, taking him away from his business for three
or four hours, a disruption he says he can't afford.
</P>
<P>
   ``A typical trip for me now is five minutes,'' Mills said of his
daily 100-yard walk to BofA. When the bank is gone, ``I can't
imagine doing the trip more than once a week. I don't like the
mileage and the cost of fuel. And I'll have to hire someone else
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, law enforcement officials say they worry that local
residents will hoard thousands of dollars between trips to the
bank, leaving them vulnerable to robbers in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have some serious concerns about the amount of cash people
will have on hand and will have to take long distances,'' said Mono
County Sheriff Daniel Paranick. He said his office has already
received several applications for concealed-weapon permits from
anxious residents.
</P>
<P>
   In this age of megamergers and Internet banking, the
disappearance of a single bank branch is hardly unusual. To save
money, big banks have closed thousands of branches across the
country while they channel customers to cheaper alternatives such
as ATMs or stripped-down offices in supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were to look at any of the big banks, everybody has a
hot list of branches to close,'' said Gordon Goetzmann, a retail
banking specialist at First Manhattan Consulting Group.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases though, when a branch shuts, there is another bank
nearby. What's unique about Bridgeport is that BofA's office is the
only banking facility for 60 miles. Its loss will create hardship
for local residents that can't be compared with the inconvenience
caused by the shuttering of a city or suburban branch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it hard to believe that a community can be left
bankless,'' said Valerie Roy, a former regulatory compliance
officer with Boston's BayBank, now a banking specialist with
TowerGroup, a Massachusetts consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgeport isn't the only small California town that has faced
the loss of its bank. During the 1990s, communities such as Julian
(San Diego County) and Pescadero lost their only banks.
</P>
<P>
   But neither Pescadero nor Julian was as isolated as Bridgeport.
Pescadero residents, for example, would have had to drive 13 miles
to Half Moon Bay to bank. And both communities persuaded
independent banks to move in to fill the vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   Although BofA officials regret the problems Bridgeport is
facing, they say they can't justify keeping a money-losing facility
open. With just $7.5 million in deposits, about one-10th the size
of a typical urban office, BofA's branch is simply too tiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at our entire retail delivery network and clearly
Bridgeport was on the bottom,'' said Larry Knutson, the Bakersfield
executive who runs BofA's branch network in the Sierra region. ``We
couldn't make money at $7.5 million in deposits and, in this day
and age, the investors want you to make money.''
</P>
<P>
   Bridgeport seems like another world from the metropolitan sprawl
of San Francisco and Los Angeles. ``This is really the last
frontier of California,'' said Paranick, the county sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   The town lies at 6,500 feet, in a vast place of big skies,
rolling rangeland and soaring peaks, where sagebrush ends and pine
trees begin. Although Mono is one of the California's biggest
counties in land area, only 11,000 people live here and they seem
to be outnumbered by the cattle grazing in the mountain shadows.
</P>
<P>
   During the summer, the trip to Bridgeport from the Bay Area
takes only five hours over the Sierra through Sonora Pass. When
snow closes the road in winter, the only access to town is Highway
395, the main route between Los Angeles and Reno.
</P>
<P>
   The highway brings thousands of tourists from April to
September, most of them from Southern California, looking to do a
little fishing _ the state-record brown trout was caught here _ or
hang out with the family in a cabin by a mountain lake. The
visitors drop millions of dollars of cash in Bridgeport's bars,
restaurants, gas stations, motels, resorts and trinket shops.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are mostly blue-collar people,'' said Jim Reid, owner of
Ken's Sporting Goods store in town. ``They don't have a whole lot
of credit cards. They're just regular folks.''
</P>
<P>
   BofA opened its Bridgeport office in 1960, the first bank in the
county since the early 1930s. Mono was the only county in the state
without a BofA branch back then.
</P>
<P>
   The new 2,000-square-foot office, built from the ground up in
the angled-roof ranch house style popular at the time, achieved the
bank's ``long cherished dream to have a branch in every county of
the state,'' according to a local press report at the time.
</P>
<P>
   In flyers distributed to local residents, BofA pridefully noted
that the office featured ``modern design, windowless teller
service, the newest in streamlined banking'' and was ``completely
air conditioned.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, as big city banking grew impersonal,
Bridgeport's BofA branch remained a throwback to the vision of
founder A.P. Giannini, who built an empire doing business with
little people. The bank extended credit to business owners at the
beginning of tourist season and took in their receipts as visitors
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had all the business in town. You got to know all your
customers well,'' recalled Joyce Meade, who recently retired after
working 51 years for BofA, including 15 years as Bridgeport branch
manager.
</P>
<P>
   But, to BofA's top executives, Bridgeport was a nuisance. By the
early 1990s, the bank had decided to sell the Bridgeport branch to
another financial institution. No takers could be found.
</P>
<P>
   About four years ago, the bank tried again, including Bridgeport
in a package of some two dozen branches put up for sale in small
towns across the state. BofA says the Bridgeport office was the
only one it couldn't unload.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the bank kept scaling back its Bridgeport operation.
By 2000, the branch employed just three people and operated only
five hours a day, except on Fridays.
</P>
<P>
   Folks in Bridgeport found out in June that BofA was planning to
leave. County administrator John Wohlmuth said bank officials
notified him of their plan during a routine meeting about the
county government's banking business.
</P>
<P>
   Bank customers received form letters at the end of June, right
on the 90-day notification deadline required by law, telling them
the bank was ``consolidating'' their accounts at the Mammoth Lakes
branch.
</P>
<P>
   Residents were stunned by the news. Several began organizing
immediately, writing letters of protest to BofA officials and
printing flyers.
</P>
<P>
   In press releases and letters to local residents, BofA explained
that the Bridgeport branch wasn't doing enough business to stay
open. That didn't impress folks in Bridgeport, who point out that
the bank makes $2 billion in profit every quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the headquarters had moved to North Carolina,'' said
Kellie Annett, co-owner of Mono Village, a resort 14 miles outside
of town, referring to the 1998 takeover of San Francisco's BofA by
NationsBank. ``But I didn't believe they had become so big and
uncaring.''
</P>
<P>
   BofA's Knutson said the bank has gone out of its way to
accommodate its Bridgeport customers. For example, the bank will
offer daily courier service for noncash items. And bank officials
point out that several private ATMs will remain in town to dispense
cash, though they won't be able to accept deposits.
</P>
<P>
   BofA won't budge on its September 29 closure deadline and won't
transport cash for customers, Knutson said.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgeport folks now say their best hope is to bring another
bank or thrift into town. And several area bankers say they are
weighing the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the information we have so far, which is limited, we
do have an interest,'' said Ron Martin, chief executive of Oak
Valley Community Bank based in the San Joaquin Valley town of
Oakdale.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the obstacles are daunting. The deposit size of the BofA
branch is about half the minimum needed to make a go of the
business, said Thomas Meuser, chief executive of El Dorado Savings
Bank, a Placerville thrift that several years ago bought BofA's
branch down the road from Bridgeport in Lone Pine.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the roughly $800 cost of an armored car trip to
Bridgeport could be prohibitive for any potential buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Martin, chief executive of Nevada State Bank, said his
institution is trying to determine the feasibility of putting in
some kind of merchant automated teller system that could accept
cash deposits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our people in Gardnerville really want something to work out
in the worst way,'' he noted. ``But we are not making any
promises.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Sam Zuckerman at szuckerman(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
