<HEADER>
A3983 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEM-PATRICK-KENNEDY-A     08-16 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-PATRICK-KENNEDY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A KENNEDY, AND THE LIFELINE OF THE PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos _ CVN6,8 _ are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Tuesday evening might have looked like Kennedy
Central at the Democratic convention, but the family member who is
the biggest star inside the party these days was not on the podium
in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick J. Kennedy, 33, the second-term congressman from Rhode
Island, has achieved stardom in the behind-the-scenes world of
money and politics, collecting millions of dollars for his House
colleagues and Democratic congressional candidates. In his role as
chairman of the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee,
Kennedy has impressed his older and more seasoned colleagues,
including Rep. Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., the House minority leader, who
is also a committee leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the brightest and hardest working young fund-raiser to
hit the Democratic Party since Tony Coelho,'' said Mark Weiner, the
treasurer of the Democratic Governors' Association and a big-league
Democratic money man himself.
</P>
<P>
   Under Kennedy's stewardship, the D Triple-C, as the committee is
called in political shorthand, has collected $62 million since
January 1999, Erik Smith, the committee spokesman, said. With the
fierce struggle for control of the House in the November election,
this record haul is a potent weapon for Democrats. House Democrats
actually have more cash on hand than their Republican counterparts,
a historic reversal.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, hopeful congressional candidates and his
grateful colleagues from the House celebrated Kennedy's
transformation into a Democratic money machine at a party for 1,500
people at the Egyptian Theater, a lavishly restored movie palace on
Hollywood Boulevard that first opened in 1922 with Douglas
Fairbanks in ``Robin Hood.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy is, in a way, a Robin Hood for the Democrats. At
Kennedy's urging, individual donors are giving more money to his
committee than ever before. Since his appointment in December 1998,
Kennedy has initiated tiered giving, starting elite groups for
Democratic donors of $50,000 and $100,000. Kennedy has been on the
road almost constantly, raising money for Democratic House races,
including trips to San Diego, Seattle and Atlanta. He even
persuaded Tony Bennett, whose private performances can cost as much
as $250,000, to donate a concert next weekend in Newport, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   That is proof, committee staff members say, that Kennedy has a
lot of celebrity power at work. ``Patrick can call up a CEO and ask
for money,'' a staff member said. ``The name helps. Patrick gets
his calls returned.''
</P>
<P>
   Such bluntness is not out of character for Kennedy, who is a
bold speaker, given to occasional outbursts complete with
foot-stamping and a high-pitched strain to his voice that makes him
sound more like a croaky teen-ager and less of a congressional
heavy.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, he spoke passionately to delegations in a series of
breakfast meetings: about the important symbolism of one uncle's
nomination here 40 years ago and another uncle's assassination here
32 years ago, as well as the spinal tumor that threatened his life
years ago. As a politician, Kennedy is energetic and displays the
hallmark Kennedy charm. As he approached the meeting of American
Indians, several older women rushed out to hug him, tears in their
eyes. It seems that everyone at the convention calls him by his
first name.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, those who would accuse Kennedy of selling
out. There are some ironies at work in Kennedy's fund-raising:
Two-thirds of the money the committee has raised was in the form of
large, unlimited contributions known as soft money, the type of
donation used for party building that Democrats are trying to
eliminate. And Kennedy's father, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy of
Massachusetts, helped draft the Federal Election Campaign Act of
1976, which was intended in part to limit soft-money donations.
</P>
<P>
   Darrell West, a professor of political science at Brown
University, who has written a biography of Patrick Kennedy, said
that Kennedy was openly flouting the rules his father wrote in 1976
to rebuild his party's finances. ``It is deeply ironic the way
Kennedy is using soft money,'' West said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's spokesman, Larry Berman, said: ``Well, the Republicans
made the rules. And Patrick just wants to play on a level playing
field.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy is reputed to have a bit of a temper; in March, for
example, he physically confronted a 58-year-old female security
guard at Los Angeles International Airport. The Los Angeles city
attorney's office considered filing misdemeanor battery charges but
declined. Kennedy acknowledged that he had acted rudely and
apologized.
</P>
<P>
   So much fund-raising leaves him little personal time, he said.
He is not married. ``Marriage gives you the image of stability,
gravity and maturity,'' he said as he rushed out of the Omni to
more receptions and interviews. He paused for a moment, then added:
``You know, all of those important things that are missing from my
life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
