<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3987 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEM-MEDIA-STRATEGY-NY     08-16 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-MEDIA-STRATEGY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATE AND MESSY, BUT NOT BAD NEWS FOR THE GORE CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  By PETER MARKS and ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At first glance, things might seem not to have
gone particularly well for the organizers of Al Gore's Democratic
convention these past two days.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's speech began almost 30 minutes late on
Monday. On Tuesday night, the evening was weighted down with a
procession of speakers from the party's past, so that by the time
the keynote speaker began delivering his address, prime time was
fading, delegates were sneaking out the door and the networks were
losing interest quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The roll call Wednesday night was scheduled to end _ well, on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   All of this looks fairly bad by conventional measures of
modern-day conventions, which are heavily focused on live network
news coverage. But none of it may matter.
</P>
<P>
   There were some grumblings _ outside the Gore campaign _ among
senior Democrats on Wednesday night about the evident absence of
discipline, particularly in contrast to what was on display at the
Republican National Convention in Philadelphia two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in part because of planning _ and in part, one top
Democratic official acknowledged, because of sheer luck _ the
management of the spectacle and the media in the Democratic
convention seems to be playing, if in slightly messy ways, to the
advantage of Gore, if not necessarily to the Democratic Party at
large.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the keynote speaker did not take the stage until nearly 11
p.m., Eastern time, on Tuesday. But for days, aides to Gore have
said that the last thing they wanted voters to pay attention to
that night was what was taking place on the stage here.
</P>
<P>
   The voters' attention was supposed to have been focused on Gore
meeting Clinton in Michigan _ and Clinton leaving the stage.
</P>
<P>
   The convention, meanwhile, was used as a place to deal with the
party's obligations, generally to the left-wing of the party.
</P>
<P>
   If that drew little attention from the general public, Gore's
centrist Democratic aides said, all the better.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's check the box day,'' one aide said.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, Clinton talked so late that he bumped David Letterman
back a few minutes, and wiped out the lucrative East Coast news
stations.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Clinton's aides were described as frantic over the
clock as they waited for Clinton to go on to the podium, Gore's
aides were sanguine, confident that viewers would hang in for
Clinton's last pitch.
</P>
<P>
   And the ratings proved them right.
</P>
<P>
   This seeming display of disorganization by the Democratic Party
pushed Hillary Rodham Clinton's speech 20 minutes late and right
into the living rooms of millions of American television viewers,
many of whom would not have seen the speech by the first lady (and
candidate for the Senate in New York) had it gone on time.
Democratic officials insisted this was pure coincidence. Network
officials, forced to pick up the speech, were at best dubious. Mrs.
Clinton's aides were serenely silent.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party has never been known as a model of
efficiency, and Democrats have long joked that they would have
trouble arranging a two-car funeral.
</P>
<P>
   The display of Swiss precision offered by the Republicans in
Philadelphia seemed designed, in part, to highlight the sloppier
ways of the Democratic Party, and the Democrats seem at time to
have been happy to oblige the Republicans make that argument.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprising, some Democrats have sought to make inefficiency
seem a virtue. ``Look, we are more free-wheeling,'' said Edward G.
Rendell, the general chairman of the Democratic National Committee.
``Look at all the speakers that we have. I think we have 240
speakers.''
</P>
<P>
   Rendell acknowledged that having Clinton speak after 11 p.m.,
Eastern time, was less than ideal. ``But I wouldn't make too much
of it,'' he said. ``And they've done much better since the first
night. And the first night they were relaxed because they had a
fail-safe because they knew the networks would not pull the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   And the fact is that while inefficiency might have served the
Democrats well these first two nights _ or at least not hurt the
party _ things began to change Wednesday evening with the first of
what Gore's aides view as the only truly meaningful nights of the
week.
</P>
<P>
   The first was Wednesday night, when Gore was nominated by his
daughter, Karenna Gore Schiff, and introduced by a biographical
film, directed by Spike Jonze, all designed to add some color to
Gore's gray outlines. The second is Thursday, when Gore delivers
his acceptance speech. One of Gore's aides said flatly Wednesday
night that that would happen by 10:15 sharp. (A few minutes later,
this adviser amended his advisory: ``Or maybe a few minutes after
that.''
</P>
<P>
   In some measure, the lax organization serves neither Gore nor
his party. One of Gore's senior aides said Wednesday night that
Clinton would draw an audience no matter how late he spoke, within
reason. Another Democrat outside the campaign described it as a
``critical mistake,'' adding, ``It is unconscionable that one of
the greatest political speeches you and I have ever heard went on
until 11:40.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation was no different on Tuesday night. The only event
that Gore's aides really cared about was the speech by Caroline
Kennedy Schlossberg, an event so unusual that they assumed that
viewers would tune in and that the late news would give it abundant
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's advisers _ some of whom admitted they had not even
bothered watching the convention _ said they were less than
distressed that speakers like Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, Jesse Jackson
and Bill Bradley might not have escaped the notice of most American
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   NBC News did not even broadcast Tuesday night, a decision that
Gore's advisers did not quarrel with. The prime-time network
television audience for the convention, though strong on Monday
night, when Clinton spoke, had died down considerably by Tuesday,
according to Nielsen Media Research.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
