<SLUG> BC-NIPPON-BELLS-WIRELESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIPPON'S WIRELESS UNIT IS SAID TO BE IN TALKS ON U.S. VENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH SCHIESEL with ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The wireless arm of Nippon Telegraph &AMP; Telephone of Japan, the
world's biggest communications company, is in preliminary
negotiations to acquire a minority stake in the pending wireless
joint venture between BellSouth Corp. and SBC Communications Inc.,
two of the local Bell telephone giants, people close to the talks
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the discussions were unclear Wednesday, but one
person close to the talks said the Japanese wireless unit, known as
NTT DoCoMo, was negotiating to buy no more than 20 percent of the
SBC-BellSouth venture.
</P>
<P>
   The venture could be worth more than $60 billion and would be
the second-biggest wireless operation in the United States after
the wireless joint venture between Verizon Communications, which
was formed by the merger of Bell Atlantic and GTE Corp., and
Vodafone AirTouch of Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The BellSouth-SBC venture would serve more than 16 million
customers and would offer wireless service to areas with more than
half of the nation's population.
</P>
<P>
   One person close to the talks added, however, that the
discussions were only in their earliest stages and could fall
apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not even baby talk,'' the person said. ``This is
babies looking at each other across the room.''
</P>
<P>
   The talks were reported Wednesday by the Web site of The
Financial Times.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for BellSouth and SBC declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this summer, NTT DoCoMo lost a battle to acquire another
U.S. wireless operation, VoiceStream Wireless Corp. VoiceStream
ended up agreeing to be acquired for $50 billion by another
overseas communications company that was looking for a U.S.
presence, Deutsche Telekom of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   SBC and BellSouth hope to win approval for their venture from
the Federal Communications Commission by the beginning of October.
</P>
<P>
   To compete against other national wireless providers like
Verizon, AT&AMP;T and Sprint, the SBC-BellSouth venture hopes to
acquire wireless licenses in the parts of the nation where it now
has none.
</P>
<P>
   NTT DoCoMo's deep pockets could help the venture acquire the
additional licenses it desires, which could cost billions of
dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 2240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
