<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: OTHER PLAYERS TO TEST TIGER AT VALHALLA 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ When you think of Louisville sports, you think
of the Kentucky Derby at Churchill Downs, or Muhammad Ali, who now
has a boulevard named for him. Or you think of all those Louisville
Slugger bats; the new minor league baseball stadium, Louisville
Slugger Field, with a statue out front of Pee Wee Reese, a local
marbles champion who grew up to be the captain and shortstop of the
``Boys of Summer'' Brooklyn Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   But with Tiger Woods in town, golf is suddenly center stage in
Louisville as never before.
</P>
<P>
   When Mark Brooks won the 1996 Professional Golfers Association
Championship in a sudden-death playoff with Kenny Perry here at the
Valhalla Golf Club, they put themselves and Louisville on the golf
map, but only briefly.
</P>
<P>
   Neither has won a PGA Tour event since then, and Valhalla hasn't
had another tournament until now.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods is at Valhalla to defend the PGA title he won last
year in a back-nine duel with the now 20-year-old Sergio Garcia of
Spain at Medinah No. 3 outside Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Even more important, the world will be watching to see if the
reigning U.S. Open and British Open champion can be the first to
win three consecutive major titles (or even three in one year)
since Ben Hogan won the Masters and the two Opens in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   But as well as Woods is likely to play, the PGA has a recent
history of somewhat surprising champions, occasionally even
somebody who emerged from relative obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   Woods dominated this year's two Opens as no other golfer ever
has, winning by 15 strokes at Pebble Beach and by 8 at St. Andrews.
But the more difficult the course, the more it favors a dominant
golfer. If Brooks and Perry were the best at Valhalla in 1996,
maybe less familiar names will create another PGA dogfight for
Woods, who openly sighed in relief when his winning putt fell last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Life is like that at the PGA, where the course is seldom set up
as treacherously as an Open course and where so many golfers have
had a chance to win. Over the last quarter of a century, the PGA
has had many more first-time or only-time major winners than the
Masters and the two Opens.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1975, there have been 10 golfers whose PGA title has been
their only major _ Davis Love III, Steve Elkington, Paul Azinger,
Wayne Grady, Jeff Sluman, Bob Tway, Hal Sutton, John Mahaffey and
Lanny Wadkins, as well as Brooks. And since 1975, the PGA was the
first major for six players who went on to win other majors _ Vijay
Singh, Nick Price, John Daly, Payne Stewart, Larry Nelson and David
Graham.
</P>
<P>
   Over that same span, the Masters was the only major for only
four golfers, and each of the Opens was the only major for six.
</P>
<P>
   So while Woods, according to the oddsmaker Danny Sheridan, is an
even-money favorite, look for somebody else to challenge him, if
not dethrone him _ maybe Ernie Els, Phil Mickelson or a mystery
guest (as Garcia was last year).
</P>
<P>
   Especially at Valhalla, designed by Jack Nicklaus, who will be
playing with Woods and Singh on Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sets up well for anybody who hits the ball high,'' Woods
said. ``That's the way Nicklaus courses are designed. You've got to
bring the ball in high. I've traditionally played well on Nicklaus
courses.''
</P>
<P>
   But why Valhalla? Isn't Valhalla just the name of the great hall
where the souls of Viking heroes feasted and celebrated with the
gods? And why is it suddenly Tiger Woods' latest stage for a major
title?
</P>
<P>
   In golf, major championships are usually held at courses aged by
time, tradition and history. In contrast, Valhalla is even younger
than Tiger Woods and nowhere near as mature. He's 24, it's only 14.
</P>
<P>
   But the PGA is here because the PGA of America, which rules the
nation's club pros, owns 50 percent of the Valhalla Golf Club and
by year's end will own all of it. The PGA is scheduled to return
here in 2006, followed by the Ryder Cup matches in 2007.
</P>
<P>
   Even Woods has said that an older, more traditional course, like
Baltusrol, the New Jersey brute that has held seven U.S. Opens,
would have been a ``better fit'' for the 2000 majors. So don't be
surprised if somebody else's name is a better fit on the PGA
trophy.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 2242EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
