<SLUG> BC-OLY-ARCHERY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITHOUT HUISH, ARCHERS STILL HOPE TO HIT TARGET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By NEVIN BARICH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You would think not having its individual gold
medal winner from 1996 would be tough to overcome for the U.S.
men's archery team, which also is trying to repeat as the Olympic
team gold medalist in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans lost one of the `96 Games' most popular athletes
when Justin Huish of Simi Valley withdrew from the team in March
after being arrested for alleged possession of marijuana with an
intent to sell.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the U.S. returns two archers from `96, including Richard
``Butch'' Johnson of Woodstock, Conn., who also made the `92
Olympic team and holds three world records.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Johnson won the National Indoor Championship for the
sixth year in a row, took first in the Gold Cup and placed third in
the Arizona Cup and the German Grand Prix Tournament of Champions.
</P>
<P>
   The other members of the men's team are Rod White of Mt.
Pleasant, Iowa, a member of the `96 Olympic team he was fourth at
the U.S. Trials but was moved up when Huish withdrew
</P>
<P>
   and Vic Wunderle of Mason City, Ill., who easily won the trials
by 94 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll have a pretty good team, even a little better
than last time,'' White said. ``I think we might be better
shooting-wise.''
</P>
<P>
   The early indication is mixed. The team was fifth at the Sydney
International Golden Arrow last September and at the Golden Arrow
Grand Prix in Turkey in April. But at the Tournament of Nations in
Germany in May, the U.S. was a disappointing 15th.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, we can shoot very well,'' returning men's coach Lloyd
Brown said. ``We've just had some problems getting them to perform
well together. They've done better individually. But hopefully,
we'll have that all worked out by the time we get to Sydney.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. women are among the medal favorites with a strong blend
of youth and experience. Janet Dykman of El Monte is the lone
returnee from the 1996 team. She finished first at the U.S. Olympic
Trials last year and is hoping to lead the U.S. women to its first
medal since its bronze at Seoul in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, winning a medal is the biggest thing,'' said
Dykman, who helped the women to a team gold medal at the Golden
Arrow Grand Prix. ``I mean, it's not a life-or-death thing, but
yeah, that is the ultimate. What else would you be working so hard
for?''
</P>
<P>
   The women's team will also rely on the experience of Denise
Parker of Salt Lake City, who was the youngest archer to compete in
the Olympics when she made the 1988 team at age 14. Parker also
made the 1992 team but failed to qualify for the Atlanta Games. But
she's back for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen-year-old Karen Savatto of Enfield, Conn., won five
competitions this year, including the Junior World Trials. In 1999,
she won the individual gold medal at the Sydney International
Golden Arrow, her first international competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is among the best mixes of athletes I've ever seen
in my years of archery competition,'' Dykman said.
</P>
<P>
   Women's coach Nancy Myrick, coaching her first Olympic team,
agrees: ``All three women are shooting very well right now. All of
them are very equal, very seasoned and very hungry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 2246EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000816.0449 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3992 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CVN-CONVENTION-RDP-2N     08-16 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-CONVENTION-RDP-2NDLD-WRITETH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
LIEBERMAN STRESSES HUMBLE ROOTS AS HE ACCEPTS NOMINATION &HT;    (EDS: Edits and trims throughout)
 &HT;    (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)
 &HT;    By STEWART M. POWELL and DAN FREEDMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES Democratic vice presidential candidate Joseph
Lieberman, the first Jewish American nominated for a major party
ticket, told the Democratic National Convention Wednesday night
that the Gore-Lieberman team wants to extend the American dream to
those left behind _ including Texans, who he claimed were suffering
bad air, water and health insurance coverage under Gov. George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman delivered his nationally-televised address as
Democratic delegates formally nominated Al Gore and Lieberman to
carry the party's banner against Bush, in his second term as
governor of Texas, and Dick Cheney, the former defense secretary
turned oil services company executive.
</P>
<P>
   The 58-year-old senator from Connecticut offered ``some straight
talking'' about Republicans, delighting convention delegates with
the quip that the Republican presidential nominee's idea of school
modernization is ``buying a new calendar for every building.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman criticized Bush's record in Texas on air quality,
water purity and the absence of health insurance for large numbers
of women and children. He dismissed the Republican National
Convention two weeks ago in Philadelphia as pure theater, saying:
``We may be near Hollywood, but not since Tom Hanks won an Oscar
has there been that much acting in Philadelphia.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, who credits the late President John F. Kennedy with
drawing him into public service, laid out the next step of the
Democrats' cherished ``New Frontier'' that was enunciated here in
Los Angeles by Kennedy in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that the next frontier isn't just in front of us but
inside us to overcome the differences that are still between us ...
and to help every American claim the limitless possibilities of our
own lives,'' Lieberman declared. He quoted Gore to the effect that
``It's not just the size of our national feast that is important
but the number of people we can fit around the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, a graduate of Yale and Yale law school who was the
first in his family to attend college, recounted his humble origins
as the grand child of immigrants. His late father had lived in an
orphanage as a child, later drove a bakery truck on the overnight
shift and eventually owned a liquor store. Lieberman added:
``Sometimes I try to see this world as my dad saw it from his
bakery truck.'' He said his proud, 85-year-old mother sitting in
the convention hall ``never felt younger than she does today.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman called Gore ``a man of family and faith...a man of
courage and conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's wife, Hadassah, the Czech-born daughter of Holocaust
survivors, introduced her husband to the convention as a principled
public servant ``shaped by the values that are his heart and soul''
who also remained ``just a regular Joe.''
</P>
<P>
   An hour before Lieberman's speech, waves of protesters occupied
the streets outside the Staples Center, the site of the convention.
Waving ``New Trial for Mumia'' and ``Nader for President'' signs,
they formed human chains as police nervously lined up on either
side.
</P>
<P>
   Through a bullhorn, police gave the protesters 15 minutes to
leave the intersection. They complied and _ for the moment _
averted a repeat of mass arrests that occurred Monday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier at an airport rally welcoming Gore and his wife Tipper
who arrived in the Los Angeles area Wednesday afternoon, Lieberman
mischievously told more than 1,000 supporters crowded into a
airport hanger to escape punishing sunshine: ``I've been waiting
for a week to say this line and I can't control myself anymore, _
in this election, will you help me win this one for the Tipper?''
</P>
<P>
   Late polls showed Gore and Lieberman have their work cut out for
them. A Voter.com-Battleground tracking poll of likely voters
released Wednesday showed the Bush-Cheney ticket leading the
Gore-Lieberman ticket by 9 percentage points, 49 percent to 40
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's eldest daughter, Karenna Gore Schiff, 27, a graduate of
Harvard and Columbia law school who often accompanies her father on
the campaign trail, nominated her father as president with touching
recollections of her father's help building a dinosaur diorama,
icing down an igloo for an overnight winter camp out and his
willingness to heartily embrace ``our big plans.'' She said her
father was a ``man of faith in the most gutsy, practical sense''
who ``wants to see goodness prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Schiff's address followed a well-received speech on Tuesday
night by Caroline Kennedy Schlossberg, the 42-year-old daughter and
last direct relative of slain President John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., who would become
speaker of the House with a Democratic takeover of the House on
Nov. 7, made a pitch for a change of leadership in the House which
in recent years has been wracked by strident divisions between
Republican leaders and minority Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders ``don't communicate _ they dictate,''
declared Gephardt, an ally of organized labor who had been on
Gore's list of prospective running mates. ``Democracy deserves
better. Hear me: We will replace `my way or the highway' with `Our
way together,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The delegates responded with a chant: ``Take back the House!
Take back the House!''
</P>
<P>
   California Gov. Gray Davis, in an indirect reference to Bush,
stirred delegates by telling them that Gore was ``not some
back-slapping good old boy. He is a serious man of substance.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Pollster Frank Luntz, who advised the independent presidential
bid of Texas billionaire Ross Perot in 1992, said Gore's selection
of Lieberman has paid off because it ``caused people to take
another look at Gore,'' helping to cut Bush's lead over Gore from
19 percentage points to 2 percentage points. Luntz, who also
advised then-Rep. Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., on the 1994 campaign
manifesto ``Contract with America'' that helped the GOP to retake
the House and Senate for the first time since 1954, said Lieberman
helps Gore win back politically conservative Jewish Americans _ 40
percent of whom had voted for Ronald Reagan in 1984. There are
roughly 5.5 million Jews in the United States, 10 percent of whom
are Orthodox Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Since his election to the Senate in 1988, Lieberman has
fashioned himself into a moderate-to-liberal lawmaker best known
for occasional stands against Democratic doctrine, including
support for publicly funded ``vouchers'' for private schools,
opposition to affirmative action and condemnation of the
entertainment industry's exploitation of sex and violence.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman was the first Democratic senator to publicly condemn
President Clinton's sexual dalliance with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky. William Bennett, the self-styled chief Republican
morals guru, described Lieberman as ``the closest thing in the
Senate to an Old Testament prophet.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, who ceases work on the Jewish Sabbath on Saturday,
says he will continue honoring the Sabbath and on three Jewish
holidays in the weeks before the Nov. 7 election. ``I'm just going
to do what I've always done and work extra hard on the days that
I'm campaigning,'' Lieberman said before his address.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's selection of Cheney also gave the GOP nominee a boost,
enabling Bush to boost his margin by 10 percentage points, from 6
percentage points before he chose Cheney to 16 percentage points
after the selection.
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart Powell and Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920
or at stewarthearstdc.com or danhearstdc.com )
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
