<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3993 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEM-DIARY-ART-NYT &LR;      08-16 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-DIARY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILMMAKER OPENS A DOOR TO SHOW GORE BEING AL; HARD WORDS ON SOFT
MONEY; WAR STORIES; WHO NEEDS BUNNIES?
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo CVN11 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spike Jonze, the 29-year-old director of ``Being John
Malkovich,'' and one of the coolest filmmakers in Hollywood, picked
up the phone several weeks ago and got what he called one of the
biggest surprises of his life. The Gore campaign asked him to fly
to Nashville and hang out with Vice President Al Gore and his
family, and then make a movie about the Gores for the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, whose supporters include such directors as Steven
Spielberg, Sydney Pollack, and Rob Reiner, could have probably
called on any filmmaker in Hollywood. But one of Gore's favorite
films in recent years is ``Being John Malkovich,'' which was
praised by critics as one of the most original and offbeat movies
in years.
</P>
<P>
   Written by Charlie Kaufman, the movie is about a struggling
puppeteer who finds a portal to the brain of actor John Malkovich
(played by the actor). As a result, people line up to be inside his
head. The movie is about the culture's obsession with fame; Jonze
has been one of the most successful directors of music videos and
commercials in the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   Jonze, whose real name is Adam Spiegel, and who is heir to the
Spiegel clothing catalog fortune, said that he just completed
editing the campaign film on Tuesday night. ``I was definitely
surprised when they called,'' he said. ``They asked me if there
were any ideas I had of the things I'd want to do. The idea was for
me to see what he really was like. I went to meet him. I bought my
little video camera. No crew. Just me and my camera.''
</P>
<P>
   The film has jagged MTV-style editing. It is an affectionate
portrait of a relaxed and laughing Gore at his family's farm, at
the dinner table with his wife and daughters, deciding what film to
watch on video, swimming in heavy surf at the beach and riding on a
military helicopter. In the film, Gore joked on Air Force Two about
his reputation as an uptight politician, pointing to his wife,
Tipper, who is barefoot. ``She insists on going barefoot _ it
completely messes up my image,'' he said. Tipper Gore cheerfully
replied: ``That's my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore even kidded about his role as vice president. ``The guy
standing motionless on stage behind the president _ what the hell
makes him think he can be president?'' Gore joked at one point.
</P>
<P>
   Jonze indicated that he never cared too much about politics _
until now. ``It was incredibly interesting to be around all that,''
he said. ``I liked him a lot. I had a fun day.''
</P>
<P>
   Hard Words on Soft Money  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing like watching two billionaires in a catfight
over money. The bad blood between the entertainment mogul David
Geffen and Eli Broad, the Los Angeles civic and financial leader,
continues. At a lunch Geffen served on Tuesday at his 9-acre,
15,000-square foot French chateau-style mansion in Beverly Hills _
which he bought for only $47.5 million in 1990 _ the mogul told
assorted movie and media stars that he was happy to have one of the
few parties here that didn't require a six-figure check for
admission.
</P>
<P>
   But Geffen has been the object of open criticism about not
writing a big check. The criticism has come from Broad, who with
Geffen was one of the co-chairmen of the host committee that lured
the Democrats to Los Angeles. Broad, who has even more billions
than Geffen, has said that Geffen backed out of his commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Geffen doesn't speak publicly of Broad. But someone close to
Geffen said he had given millions to the Democratic Party and was
not going to be ``intimidated'' by Broad into ``underwriting the
Democratic convention,'' which he said had been made clear from
``day one.''
</P>
<P>
   War Stories  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam. Thirty years ago the Democratic Party tried to forget
the war that began in the administration of John F. Kennedy and
reached its peak in the Lyndon B. Johnson years. But the convention
here is raising the Vietnam issue _ specifically who served there,
and who didn't _ in an effort to contrast Vice President Gore, who
served near Saigon, with his Republican rival, Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, two Democratic senators and combat veterans
wounded in Vietnam, Max Cleland of Georgia and Bob Kerrey of
Nebraska, were given prominent speaking roles. Thursday night,
several Vietnam veterans will introduce Gore, who served in the
military for two years and in Vietnam as an Army reporter. By
contrast, Bush served in the Air National Guard and was not called
to Vietnam. Bush's running mate, Dick Cheney, used deferments to
avoid being drafted. And Sen. Joseph Lieberman, the Democratic vice
presidential candidate, also used deferments first as a student and
later as a parent. Lieberman has said that he has ``felt some
remorse'' about not serving.
</P>
<P>
   Who Needs Bunnies?
</P>
<P>
   Even without the Playboy mansion, Rep. Loretta Sanchez's
fund-raising bash for Hispanic lawmakers was hopping on Tuesday
night. Sanchez, D-Calif., had been pressured by party leaders to
drop the Playboy mansion as the spot for her blast, even though
Gore himself has accepted money from Hugh Hefner, the founder of
Playboy. The Democratic National Committee feared the Playboy party
would be a public relations debacle and run counter to the
Democrats' attempts to portray themselves as the party of family
values.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the party seemed most of all a huge public relations
coup for Sanchez, who held forth Wednesday night in a plunging
black gown and upswept hair as a hundred reporters and television
crews recorded her every word at B.B. King's Blues Club at
Universal Studio's City Walk, the new site of the party. ``Al Gore
has accepted money from Playboy,'' Sanchez said pointedly. ``And he
would have to give you his reasons as to what he's done with that
money and where it goes and why he takes it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
