<HEADLINE>
L.A. POLICE, PROTESTERS CLASH OUTSIDE DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LISA TEACHEY 
and DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Police clashed with thousands of angry
demonstrators Wednesday outside the Democratic National Convention
but avoided the kind of confrontation that left several injured
earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   As smiling Democrats lined up inside the Staples Center to laud
the attributes of standard-bearers Al Gore and Joseph Lieberman,
infuriated protesters outside the hall shouted at hundreds of
heavily armed police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Some protesters threw bottles, stones and other debris at
police, who responded with rounds of rubber bullets fired into the
crowd. Also, witnesses said, police used rubber bullets and
nightsticks to push photographers out of their way.
</P>
<P>
   A California Highway Patrol officer was struck in the chest. He
was taken to a hospital, a patrol official said.
</P>
<P>
   The officer was hit shortly after dusk as protesters drifted
away from a major intersection near the convention center after a
tense, hour-long standoff that appeared on national television to
have ended without incident.
</P>
<P>
   At the same intersection Monday night, police on horseback
charged into a crowd of protesters who set fire to trash piles
instead of leaving the area after a rock concert. Several rounds of
rubber bullets were fired as part of the effort to protesters from
the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's protest near the Staples Center followed a mass
rally at police headquarters in downtown Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Complaining of what they described as ``mass incarceration,''
``police brutality'' and the taking of ``political prisoners,'' the
protesters burned a U.S. flag while officers in riot gear stood
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday evening, the total number of people arrested
during protests reached 189.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving police headquarters, hundreds of people marched
through the streets of downtown Los Angeles where business owners
had boarded their storefronts.
</P>
<P>
   En route, police shoved demonstrators and bystanders off the
sidewalks and into the streets. Officers fired rubber bullets at a
photographer standing in their way and pushed him to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Angry protesters then surged forward, shouting ``Shame! Shame!''
before police supervisors and rally organizers intervened and
stopped the incident from escalating.
</P>
<P>
   A television cameraman also claimed to have been hit by
baton-wielding police.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the American Civil Liberties Union prepared a
lawsuit _ which attorneys planned to file on Friday in federal
court _ accusing police of targeting journalists assigned to cover
Monday's street battles.
</P>
<P>
   ``A free press guards against tyranny and abuse of power, and
those who abuse power inevitably seek to control the images we see
and the stories we hear,'' said Ramona Ripston, executive director
of the ACLU's Southern California office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The LAPD on Monday evening illustrated these axioms starkly by
targeting members of the press as they were covering the LAPD's
massive, sweeping violations of individuals' civil liberties.''
</P>
<P>
   The Civil Liberties Union lawsuit names Al Crespo, a free-lance
photographer who is believed to have been shot three times with
rubber bullets.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether the police have been targeting reporters,
police spokesman David Kalish said ``absolutely, positively not.''
</P>
<P>
   In a more peaceful moment Wednesday, 37 protesters engaged in a
sit-in at the Rampart police station, a facility rocked by numerous
allegations of abuse by officers.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday evening, police arrested 70 bicyclists who
authorities argued were driving recklessly through the streets of
downtown Los Angeles. Among those arrested were two reporters,
Brian Bland of Associated Press Radio and Flynn McRoberts of the
Chicago Tribune. They were released after posting bail.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, police arrested 45 protesters who authorities
suspected of conspiring to break into and vandalize two business
that sell furs. The group also had allegedly targeted a McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they seized flammable materials, slingshots with
paint balls and make-shift flame throwers from the animal rights
protesters.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators allegedly were terrorizing employees at the
businesses, banging on windows and painting store signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We moved in and thwarted their attack,'' Kalish said.
</P>
<P>
   Police stopped street vendors from selling water to people using
the area designated by convention organizers for protests.
Previously, the water vendors had enjoyed a brisk business on the
streets outside the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going to happen ... when all these people start running
out of water?'' asked Donald Anderson, who had been selling water
around the convention site for several days. ``This is
ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
