<SLUG> BC-CVN-INTERNET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS ARE MORE PLUGGED IN, ANALYST SAYS &HT;     

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Of course Al Gore didn't invent the Internet, and
he never really said he did.
</P>
<P>
   But the vice president does know how to use it, according to
Internet researchers who say the Democrats are doing a slightly
better job than the Republicans in embracing their first national
convention on the information superhighway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans had a lot of gizmos and they had a high `neat'
factor, but there was really nothing there. The reality didn't live
up to the hype,'' said Christopher Hunter, policy analyst and
Internet observer at NetElection.org, a research project at the
University of Pennsylvania's Annenberg Public Policy Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats appear to be a little better plugged in,'' he
said. ``They've got computer terminals at each delegation on the
convention floor where delegates will cast their votes. They have
360-degree cameras stationed around the Staples Center, and their
streaming video and `podium chats' are a very positive use of the
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Pseudo.com, a private company, had 360-degree cameras in
Philadelphia during the Republican National Convention. Here, the
Democrats themselves installed the same type of technology.
</P>
<P>
   While Texas Gov. and Republican presidential candidate George W.
Bush only mentioned the Internet once in Philadelphia _ in a joke
about Gore _ the vice president is expected to discuss the future
of the medium, as he has on the campaign trail. And Democrats also
are embracing another opportunity the Republicans neglected: The
Jumbotron at Staples Center frequently touts the party's Web site,
www.dems2000.com.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Purpuro, deputy chief of staff for the Republican National
Committee, has said that the GOP is not devoting as much energy to
promoting the Internet. A majority of Republicans are already
online, he said, and the private sector is doing a good job of
moving the technology forward.
</P>
<P>
   But while Democratic convention organizers may be more
enthusiastic Internet pioneers than their GOP counterparts, Hunter
said he is still somewhat disappointed: ``The Democrats so far
haven't delivered.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter and his fellow Internet users were most interested in the
Democrats' promised ``podium chats,'' touted as a chance to ask
questions of each departing speaker for 10 to 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   After Monday night's big speech by first lady and Senate
candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton, Hunter logged on to see if he
could ask her a question. The response was essentially: We're not
doing that tonight. Check back tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm impressed that they did have live people on the other end
responding to us, but it wasn't really a chat, wasn't really live,
and I didn't get to ask one question of one speaker,'' Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 2255EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000816.0455 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3999 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-WATSON-NYT &LR;      08-16 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WATSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT B. WATSON, 86, FORMER HARVARD ADMINISTRATOR 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert B. Watson, dean of students at Harvard University during
the student uprisings of the late 1960s and later the driving force
behind the construction of sports facilities as the university's
athletic director, died on Aug. 12 at his home in Cataumet, Mass.
He was 86.
</P>
<P>
   A popular but firm administrator in the early part of his career
at Harvard, Watson was taken aback by the events of April 9, 1969,
when he and other administrators were forcibly removed from their
offices by student protesters at the height of the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   ``The breakdown of civility among students and faculty alike
were direct attacks on everything he stood for,'' said Zeph
Stewart, who was a senior tutor and house master at the time, ``and
he himself and his unwavering loyalty to the old Harvard became
targets of rebellion.''
</P>
<P>
   As Watson described it in 1987: ``Being a college dean then was
like living in the public square of a small city occupied by enemy
aliens. There was no place to take refuge from the maddening
crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Reared in the Boston suburb of Wellesley, Watson attended St.
Mark's School and graduated from Harvard in 1937 after lettering in
football and crew.
</P>
<P>
   After a few years at J.P. Morgan in New York, he joined the Navy
in 1940. He married Polly Blodgett about one month after the
bombing of Pearl Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   She survives him, along with three daughters, Gail Barber of
Bedford, Mass., Jeannie of Weston, Mass., and Joanne Watson
Spievack, of Cambridge, Mass.; two sons, Peter T., of Bainbridge
Island, Wash., and Robert Jr., of Richmond, Va.; a brother, Edward,
who lives in New Hampshire; and nine grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   During the war, Watson served as executive officer on the
destroyer Leary. He survived for five hours in the cold waters of
the North Atlantic when his ship was torpedoed on Christmas Eve
1943.
</P>
<P>
   He gave his life jacket to another man and clung to a piece of
wood until early morning, when another warship rescued him and 56
crew mates; the 220 other men on board died. He told his children
that his St. Mark's letterman sweater had saved his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thought that kept recurring was: what I should do with
my life if I was lucky enough to be picked up?'' he wrote later.
``The answer that came back repeatedly was: involve yourself in
some field relating to the young.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson returned to Harvard in 1946 as an associate dean,
becoming the college's first dean of students in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, he touched off a debate over the university's
enforcement of the hours during which students were allowed to
entertain women in their rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are public laws in this state,'' he said at the time,
``and it's our positive duty to deal with fornication just as we do
with thievery, lying and cheating, by taking severe disciplinary
measures against the offenders.''
</P>
<P>
   But arguments over parietal rules were timid compared with the
1969 protest against U.S. involvement in Vietnam and other
grievances. Students shoved and dragged Watson and eight other
deans out of the main administration building before locking the
doors with bicycle chains.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, the deans watched as 400 policemen charged the
building and pulled the students, some of them bloodied, from the
hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those crazy times, it was really important to be as
straight and square as he was,'' said Fred L. Glimp, the dean of
Harvard College at the time, who was also forcefully removed in the
University Hall uprising. ``There wasn't much you could do about
the emotional issues, but you'd try to keep the students from
emotionally throwing themselves into impossible situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson served another year as dean and made dozens of court
appearances as students who took part in the first and three other
building takeovers were tried on charges of trespassing and
assault.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, he became athletic director and began a multimillion
dollar renovation of Harvard's sports facilities, which Glimp
called the ``most archaic in the Ivy League.'' Watson helped set in
motion projects that included building a pool and a track before he
retired in 1977.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
