 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
HOMOSEXUALS HAVE SOME HIGH-PROFILE ROLES, BUT STAR TREATMENT A
MIXED BLESSING
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
By JULIE MASON &QL; 
C.2000 Houston Chronicle &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Gays and lesbians are getting the star treatment
at this year's Democratic National Convention, turning up in
unprecedented numbers among the speakers and delegates.
</P>
<P>
   While that might be expected because they are a core
constituency of the party, some convention participants said this
year's high profile is a mixed blessing. That's because certain key
issues to the lesbian and gay community are not high on the
Democrats' agenda this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not forget that anyone can still be fired from their job
in 39 states, including Texas, for being gay,'' said Sloan C.
Wiesen, spokesman for the Gay and Lesbian Victory Fund, a
Washington-based nonpartisan organization.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 4,370 delegates at the convention, 212 are lesbian, gay
or transgendered. At the recent Republican National Convention in
Philadelphia, 18 openly gay delegates also set their party's record
for attendance this year.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic podium, six convention speakers are
homosexual, and others, such as the parents of Matthew Shepard, a
gay University of Wyoming student who was murdered in 1998, are
speaking on related themes.
</P>
<P>
   But while nondiscrimination and anti-hate crime measures are
frequently invoked by gay and straight convention speakers, in many
states such laws remain goals for the Democratic Party rather than
achievements.
</P>
<P>
   Thornier issues rarely heard or publicly championed at the
convention include laws that would permit gay adoption and same-sex
marriage, neither of which is addressed in the party's platform.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many activists said they feel a growing tolerance in the
nation for lesbians and gays, and a welcome from the Democratic
Party.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Army Col. Grethe Cammermeyer, a lesbian discharged from
the military in 1992 under its then-mandatory discrimination
policy, noted how far the party has come since 24 openly gay
delegates converged at the 1984 convention in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really do have an inclusive community and an inclusive
party,'' Cammermeyer said. ``We are part of the party that's going
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   And in an election year that has seen both major parties drift
to the center on issues such as education, trade and health care,
Republican and Democratic stances on gays at the convention provide
some of the sharpest contrasts to date.
</P>
<P>
   At the Republican Convention in Philadelphia, U.S. Rep. Jim
Kolbe, an openly gay Republican from Arizona, gave a speech during
prime time on the issue of free trade.
</P>
<P>
   Some delegates that evening expressed their disapproval by
either boycotting the speech or bowing in prayer during his
address.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats gave a prime-time speaking spot to Elizabeth Birch, a
lesbian mother of twins who is president of the Human Rights
Campaign, the nation's largest gay and lesbian political
organization.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the convention this week, the Gay and Lesbian
Victory Fund hosted a brunch in West Hollywood that raised $200,000
for its mission of electing qualified, openly gay public officials.
</P>
<P>
   As a sign of the gay and lesbian community's clout within the
party, the event featured appearances by House Minority Leader
Richard Gephardt and Energy Secretary Bill Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   Wiesen, who called the confluence ``historic,'' said gay and
lesbian Democrats generally agree the easier issues with broader
consensus are the ones that should be tackled first.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're dealing with conflict, you don't target the
hardest, most divisive and emotional issues first,'' Wiesen said.
``If people are in agreement on some of the more basic issues like
discrimination, let's make that the law of the land first and then
go on to squabbling over other things.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
