 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
CISNEROS WARMLY RECEIVED, BUT COY ABOUT RETURN TO PUBLIC OFFICE
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
By CLAY ROBISON &QL; 
C.2000 Houston Chronicle &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Fallen star Henry Cisneros was warmly greeted by
Texas Democrats on Wednesday, but he remained coy about whether he
ever will take another shot at public office.
</P>
<P>
   The former Clinton Cabinet member and San Antonio mayor, whose
political career was derailed by an extramarital affair and a
federal indictment, seemed to rule out a race for governor in 2002
or any other campaign in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   But he left the door open for other political opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never is a long time, you know. Never, never. You know, 10
years from now I'll be a little old but who knows?'' he told
reporters after speaking to Texas delegates to the Democratic
National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can tell you is I've made choices and gotten people to
invest in a business with the assurance that this is what I'm going
to dedicate myself to for a very long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, 53, moved back to San Antonio, his hometown, last week
after a 7{-year absence to launch a company that will concentrate
on building affordable housing with a major homebuilder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no plan to run for office, no ambition. I swear to you
I want to get on the ground in San Antonio and get to work, and
it's going to be very challenging work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros said he intended to remain active in civic affairs and
in rebuilding the Texas Democratic Party. He said he also will
spend a limited amount of time campaigning for presidential
candidate Al Gore this fall if he is asked to do so.
</P>
<P>
   He said he planned to support Laredo businessman Tony Sanchez
Jr., who is expected to announce later this year that he will seek
the Democratic nomination for governor in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   At present, Democrats, who once had a stranglehold on Texas
politics, hold no statewide elected offices in Texas. And Cisneros,
despite his personal baggage, is viewed by some as the party's best
shot at recapturing a major statewide office.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's office and the U.S. Senate seat held by
Republican Phil Gramm will head the statewide ballot in Texas in
2002.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he would do if he were recruited to run for governor
or the Senate, Cisneros replied: ``There are other people who can
do a better job at it, and (whom) I would be happy to back.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros was mayor of San Antonio for eight years and then
headed the Department of Housing and Urban Development during
Clinton's first term.
</P>
<P>
   His affair with former fund-raiser Linda Jones, made public in
1988, led to a federal investigation that Cisneros had lied about
payments to Jones during an FBI background check into his
nomination as HUD secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros ended the case last year by pleading guilty to one
misdemeanor charge and paying a $10,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros returned to San Antonio from Los Angeles, where he
spent the past 3{ years as president and chief operating officer of
Univision Communications Inc., the nation's largest
Spanish-language television network.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros told Texas Democrats that Gore was more qualified for
the nation's highest office than ``any person who has run for the
presidency'' because he has been intimately involved with White
House decision-making for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
