<HEADER>
A4141 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEM-SCRIPTED-NYT     08-16 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-SCRIPTED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PERSONAL TOUCH IS NOW PARTY PROTOCOL 
</HEADLINE>
  By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Karenna Gore Schiff, the candidate's daughter, on
Wednesday night filled the role once played by governors, senators,
former presidents and former first ladies by seconding her father's
nomination to be president, praising him in prepared remarks for
balancing family and government work, and helping her with a
dinosaur diorama after a long day of congressional hearings.
</P>
<P>
   In their unending quest to make national conventions into sunny
talk shows they hope the networks will broadcast, the parties have
banned internal party argument over policy, serialized roll calls
over three nights and miniaturized important speeches (except by
President Clinton).
</P>
<P>
   The keynote speech, a first-night event intended to set a
convention tone (and to propel a speaker like Harold Stassen or
Earl Warren or Mario Cuomo into national prominence) vanished
entirely from the Republican calendar. Here among the Democrats, it
might as well have. Rep. Harold E. Ford Jr. of Tennessee, a
30-year-old second termer, delivered it as the second night's
session ended, after the networks had quit.
</P>
<P>
   Nominating speeches were first used to persuade delegates to
vote for a candidate. Once nominees began to be settled before
conventions began, their purpose became persuading a party and a
nation of the breadth of his support.
</P>
<P>
   Today, if any purpose remains, it is to humanize and
depoliticize. Two weeks ago in Philadelphia, the Texas Republican
with the second most at stake in the election, Lt. Gov. Rick Perry,
nominated his boss in less than a minute: ``Mr. Chairman and fellow
delegates, I am proud to nominate the current governor of the great
state of Texas and the next president of the United States _ George
W. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a formality, preceding the formality of the
state-by-state roll call that the party's rules have not gotten
around to eliminating as a time-wasting relic of the past. But
those pronouncements were administered in small doses over three
days.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's presentations, a nomination by Tommy Lee
Jones, Gore's Harvard roommate, and seconding speeches by Schiff
and Lois M. DeBerry, a Tennessee legislator, were personal
reflections. Joe Andrew, national chairman of the Democratic Party,
said they could answer an important question about Gore: ``What
kind of decisions did you make before you were in government?''
</P>
<P>
   Other speakers, he said, dealt with issues and Gore's record in
government. Indeed they have, sometimes with a level of
exaggeration that Gore himself would envy. Sen. Edward M. Kennedy,
for example, credited Gore with helping pass the children's health
insurance legislation, when, in fact, Gore followed White House
orders in May 1997, and disappeared, after promising Kennedy he
would come to the Senate to break a tie by voting for the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's speakers were chosen, Andrew said, to help
America ``know Al Gore more as a person.'' The same assignment will
fall Thursday to the candidate's wife, Tipper, and she will use
photographs she has taken to help make her point.
</P>
<P>
   Jones may have a political following, but only in Hollywood, and
Schiff and Mrs. Gore have none at all. But the Democrats, like the
Republicans, are counting on their conventions as television shows,
not as tools for party unity.
</P>
<P>
   And if there is one thing they fear more than a long speech, it
is the disease of dissent. Bush's campaign officials not only
thwarted debate about abortion or a new primary calendar, they
deemed it destructive to let delegates debate for a few minutes
about whether to make Republican National Committee members
automatic delegates.
</P>
<P>
   And Democrats, congenitally incapable of marching in perfect
lock step, confined their uncertainty about whether the party was
liberal enough to grumbling to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   It is true, of course, that disagreement and uncertain outcomes
would make news and perhaps persuade the television networks to pay
more attention. But that raises the fear that a party that fights
over something would look bad to the public.
</P>
<P>
   One veteran Republican, Bill Brock, the former national
chairman, disagrees. ``A convention without contest,'' he said ``is
a convention without a lot of heart ...''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Martin J. Plissner, the retired executive political
director of CBS News, put it, keynotes, nominating speeches and
platform fights ``go back to the era when conventions had decisions
to make.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
