<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIM-610&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORRES WON'T BOW TO GODS OF YOUTH, WINNING TRIAL AT 33
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Dara Torres won the women's 50-meter freestyle
Wednesday night in 24.90 seconds, becoming, at age 33, the oldest
woman to win a race at the U.S. Olympic swimming trials. Her
half-minute swim, however, was preceded by hours of instruction
from an entourage of 10 experts who aided her in everything from
her psychological state to her nutrition to the manipulation of her
lymph system.
</P>
<P>
   After a layoff of seven years, in which she worked as a fashion
model and a television commentator, Torres returned to swimming a
year ago and has now qualified to swim three individual events and
three relays next month at the 2000 Summer Olympics in Sydney,
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   It is unprecedented for anyone to return to an elite level of
swimming after so many years away from the sport. During her
retirement everything changed, from the way strokes are performed
in the water to the way athletes eat and train.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Quick, coach of the U.S. women's Olympic swim team and
Torres' personal coach in Palo Alto, Calif., said swimmers have
become a bit like race cars, spending minutes at peak performance
and hours in the body shop being tinkered with by mechanics. In
races decided by hundredths of a second, the slightest advantage
can be significant.
</P>
<P>
   Quick's methods have been productive at the trials. Jenny
Thompson, one of his swimmers, won both the women's 100-meter
butterfly and 100-meter freestyle. Torres won the 50-meter
freestyle and finished second in the 100-meter butterfly and
100-meter freestyle. Misty Hyman won the 200-meter butterfly. As
the trials concluded Wednesday night, Torres defeated the reigning
Olympic champion in the 50 freestyle, Amy Van Dyken, who finished
second in 24.99, continuing her own comeback from shoulder surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The Stanford group is hardly the only one to develop a training
regimen as high-tech as the bodysuits worn at these trials. Gary
Hall Jr. won the men's 50-meter freestyle on Tuesday with a
nutritional regimen that resembles that of Fusaichi Pegasus, the
winner of the Kentucky Derby, according to Hall's coach in Phoenix,
Mike Bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Quick said his idea for an inclusive regimen came from an
article he read about how Martina Navratilova traveled with a
psychologist, nutritionist and strength coach during her heyday on
the women's tennis circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, wow, how could I put that in place for swimmers?''
Quick said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he paid the expenses at the trials for a 10-person group
that included a nutritionist, two massage therapists, a physical
therapist, a performance expert, a lymph system manipulator, a
chiropractor, two stretching experts and an instructor in Pilates,
a strength and stretching regimen. Torres and Thompson also pay
separately for strength training with Robert Weir, a British discus
and hammer-throw champion.
</P>
<P>
   Torres works four to six hours a day outside the pool on various
aspects of her physical and mental preparation, Quick said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people wonder how she achieved so much so quickly,''
he said. ``I guarantee that if you follow her around for one week,
you'd be exhausted just by the schedule. She's crowded two to three
years of training into 13 months.''
</P>
<P>
   The experts have agreed to work without pay, Quick said, adding
that he had created a foundation to raise $90,000 to $100,000 to
pay for their travel and housing expenses at the Olympics. Half the
money remains to be raised, with the Summer Games beginning on
Sept. 15. He will borrow money, if necessary, to get the entourage
to Sydney, Quick said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to have these athletes shortchanged at the most
critical moment in their careers,'' Quick said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Torres won two gold medals on relay teams before retiring in
1992. Her resurgent career represents the possibilities now
available to women in the age of professional Olympic sports a
generation after the gender-equity mandate of Title IX. Prize money
and endorsements sustain careers that, three decades ago, were
forced to end in high school. But Torres has needed acute vigilance
to remain at the top into her 30s.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Luepnitz, a nutrition expert, monitors Torres'
protein-laden diet of six meals a day, and he draws her blood every
two weeks to analyze her oxygen-carrying capacity, lactic acid
buildup and immune system. He gives her up to 25 supplement pills a
day. Richard Diana, a performance expert, is a proponent of Knowing
Awareness Thinking, which aids athletes in achieving a confident,
uncluttered mind-set before races.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of building confidence,'' Quick said. ``You can
have a fire to train and still not have confidence to perform.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale Perry massages Torres' lymph system to help rid her body of
toxins. A pair of trainers, Bob Cooley and Tom Longo, perform
Meridian Resistance Flexibility exercises, which include walking
over her legs and her back to relax the muscles. Team Torres also
uses a device to help cool her after races, putting a rubberized
sleeve around her legs and pumping in cold water.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of it has to do with nutrition'' Torres said of
her resurgence. ``Richard is one of the best coaches in the world.
He knows how to train sprinters. He's added a lot of recovery into
our workouts. The weight training is different and the mental
attitude is different.''
</P>
<P>
   Because so little is known about women performing at their peak
into their 30s, however, the Torres regimen remains one of trial
and error. She said her tired legs gave out on her in the 100-meter
freestyle, and she has experienced repeated cramping during the
trials.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Don Catlin, who operates the Olympic drug-testing lab at
UCLA, cautioned that athletes who take supplements risk testing
positive for some banned substances because of improper labeling.
Dr. Gary Green, an internist at UCLA who is head of the NCAA's
drug-testing program, said few peer-reviewed studies had been done
to correlate the effect of supplements on performance enhancement.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to show scientifically whether legal supplements
can mimic the effects of banned drugs is for athletes to take the
supplements and then take steroids, and then compare the
performances, Green said. ``No one is going to do that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The most direct impact on performance could be a placebo effect,
he said. And even high-tech gadgets, Quick said, ``can't substitute
for hard work, dedication and consistent effort.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
