<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4139 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-PROTESTS-0817-COX     08-16 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-PROTESTS-0817-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONVENTION PROTESTS SIMMER BUT DON'T BOIL OVER
 &HT;    By MIKE WAGNER and KATHEY PRUITT
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A protest Wednesday by more than 5,000
demonstrators, mainly targeting police brutality, started with an
Indian war chant, flirted with violence and ended with mild
skirmishes.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters and police shoved each other during several minor
altercations during the two-mile march that started at downtown's
Pershing Square and ended at the Staples Center, the convention
site. While waiting to enter the area designated for protests,
demonstrators hurled bottles and other objects at police.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hate the police, the police don't like them much either,
and this convention was like a timer on the bomb that's been built
between them,'' said the Rev. Jim Conn, a Methodist minister from
nearby Long Beach who attempted to calm the crowd. ``I just hope it
doesn't blow up. The past history of this city, the heat and all
the media coverage is a recipe for something bad to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The images of police facing off with protesters is nothing new
to Los Angeles and the kind of attention the Democratic Party was
hoping to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   The march did little to wipe away memories of the videotaped
police beating of Rodney King, which led to the city's 1992 riots.
Los Angeles and violence were again in the spotlight earlier this
summer when vandals set fires and rampaged local businesses after
the Los Angeles Lakers' NBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's demonstration continued a week of convention
protests that at times have disrupted state delegates and occupied
the national media.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the convention's first day, violence erupted after a
concert by Rage Against the Machine, an anti-authoritarian band
from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Officers, some on horseback, charged into a crowd of 8,000
protesters, dispensing pepper spray and rubber bullets to disperse
the crowd. Some of the 300 protesters engaged with police responded
by throwing pylons, cans, bottles, asphalt and a
handicapped-parking sign. At least four people were hurt, none
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The intensity of Wednesday's march rose when the demonstrators
stopped in front of Los Angeles police headquarters. They spewed
profanity at the officers, burned American flags and threatened to
``take out'' any officer who laid a hand on a protester.
</P>
<P>
   Long rows of officers, fully decked out in riot gear, surrounded
the demonstrators and kept the protest from spilling into other
streets. Unlike Monday, police showed restraint when confronted by
protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Some officers returned stone cold looks to the insults and video
cameras that were thrust inches from their helmets. Others officers
laughed at the chaos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them are these 15-year-old kids who need a good
spanking from their parents,'' said Officer Dan MacDonald, who was
on the front line of the protest and started laughing when one
protester fell hard from a skate board. ``They ought to bring in
ice cream trucks and they might go away.''
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators represent a diverse collection of causes and
political stripes. Many are protesting corporate globalization, the
death penalty, treatment of the homeless and several prisoners they
believe are innocent.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters were led by a truck displaying hundreds of names
and pictures of people around the country who demonstrators say
were killed in altercations with police. The demonstration began
around noon in Pershing Square where about 10 people told personal
stories of family members who died in fights with police or while
serving a jail sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Before the march, many of the police and protesters were talking
and even joking with each other. ``It's our job to keep this
peaceful and show these people that we all live together,'' said
Lt. Don Farrell.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many of the protesters said the cops were itching for a
fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want peace, they want to keep hitting and killing
people,'' said Whitney Zack, a New Yorker who led much of the
protest. ``We live in fear of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The protest spilled into the area surrounding the convention,
but ran into a wall of police, which led to a 50-minute stand-off
between the groups. The protesters linked arms, forming a human
chain in front of police.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, six hours after the protest began, police negotiators
were able to persuade the demonstrators to move out of the area.
Police threatened to arrest any protesters who continued to linger
near a blocked-off intersection.
</P>
<P>
   The convention ends Thursday and police expect a final round of
protests.
</P>
<P>
   Some delegates said they were ``saddened'' and ``angry'' that
the protests outside the convention have taken center stage from
politics and the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came here to fight for Al Gore, not watch a bunch of people
fight outside,'' said one delegate from Kansas, who didn't want to
be identified. ``It seems like Al Gore just can't catch a break in
this election.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
