r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-BLUEJAYS-L     08-16 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-BLUEJAYS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS LOSE BUT AVOID BIGGER DISASTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The Anaheim Angels endured one loss Wednesday
afternoon but avoided a second and potentially more devastating
loss before 32,497 at SkyDome.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Delgado's two-run homer off Angels reliever Lou Pote in
the bottom of the ninth inning lifted the Toronto Blue Jays to an
8-6 victory. The good news for the Angels came while they packed
their bags for New York - Tim Salmon, who was hit on the left thumb
by a line drive while on third base, returned from the hospital
with the news that X-rays were negative.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon was on third with one out in the sixth inning when batter
Troy Glaus ripped one at him as he led off third base in foul
territory. He raised his hands to protect his face and the ball got
him on the thumb. He stayed in the game for the moment and scored
on a single by Glaus but then left for the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was hurting and it was throbbing,'' Salmon said.
``The first thing that comes to your mind is maybe you broke it.
I'm thinking, 'OK, what's going to happen next?' You think of all
the negative things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had my fair share of freak things. Fortunately it's not
broken. And it's not on the joint, so it shouldn't give me any
trouble holding the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon will be re-evaluated today and his status is listed as
day to day. Glaus, who hit his team-leading 35th home run earlier
in the game, was relieved Salmon was OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way to react,'' Glaus said. ``You just hope to save
all the important parts.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Glaus' homer, the Angels also got a homer from Darin
Erstad (No. 20), three hits from Kevin Stocker and took a 5-3 lead
into the bottom of the seventh inning. But Angels starter Scott
Schoeneweis gave up a couple of hits and a run before Angels
manager Mike Scioscia went for help.
</P>
<P>
   In came Mark Petkovsek, who was pitching in his third
consecutive game and fifth in the club's past six games. He fell
behind in the count 2-0 to Tony Batista, when Batista launched a
two-run homer to left that gave the Blue Jays a 6-5 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, guys are stretched a bit,'' Scioscia said of a tired
bullpen. ``You'd like to give them a breather here and there. You
want to finish not only healthy but strong. Without Al (Levine) and
(Troy Percival), those are two big voids that have to be filled in
the set-up roles and middle relief roles.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis might have gotten out of the inning himself had he
been able to field a sharp grounder back at him by Delgado. Instead
of turning an inning-ending double play, the ball caromed off his
glove to second baseman Adam Kennedy, who got the out at first.
</P>
<P>
   But it allowed one run to score and kept the inning alive for
Batista.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stepped on the mound and said 'Let's get a ground ball right
back to you,' '' Schoeneweis said. ``Then, bam, a ground ball right
back to me. I can't believe what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow you wake up and it's one more in the loss column, no
more, no less,'' Scioscia said. ``Guys are playing hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Koch (6-2) worked a perfect ninth for the victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
