<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BLEE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVID H. BLEE, 83, CIA SPY WHO REVISED DEFECTOR POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES RISEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ David Henry Blee, a legendary U.S. spymaster who
played a critical role in dispelling the climate of paranoia that
paralyzed the CIA's espionage operations against the Soviet Union
in the 1960s, died on Aug. 4 at his home in Bethesda, Md. He was
83.
</P>
<P>
   Placed in charge of the CIA's Soviet Division in 1971, Blee made
a historic break with the agency's eccentric chief of
counterintelligence, James Jesus Angleton, effectively ending
Angleton's broad and destructive influence over the agency's
operations against Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Angleton's belief that virtually every Soviet citizen
who tried to defect was actually a double agent sent to dupe the
Americans, the agency's operations against Moscow had been tied in
knots for years. Angleton's theories had prompted the CIA to rebuff
many Soviets who tried to offer their spy services, and ultimately
led to the secret imprisonment under brutal conditions of one KGB
officer who defected to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Although as chief of counterintelligence Angleton was not in the
agency's Soviet Division, his long tenure as chief spy hunter gave
him enormous influence. Angleton's belief that the CIA was falling
prey to a KGB ``monster plot'' of deception led to a witch hunt for
Soviet moles within the agency. Careers were destroyed as one
longtime agency officer after another came under suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   But Blee, a longtime Middle East hand, rejected Angleton's
theories and threw open the doors to defectors and potential Soviet
spies, an approach that younger intelligence officers eagerly
embraced. Blee, a Harvard-educated lawyer, avoided an open
confrontation with Angleton as he ordered the 180-degree shift.
</P>
<P>
   With the backing of agency's director, William E. Colby, Blee
brought in lieutenants he had worked with in the Middle East and
South Asia who had not been tainted by the Angletonian mole hunt.
They reinvestigated long-neglected espionage leads.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the architect of the program that turned the
clandestine service back on target against the Soviets after all
the years of Angleton,'' said Haviland Smith, a former CIA officer.
</P>
<P>
   Blee's policy shift quickly bore fruit; in the 1970s the number
of well-placed spies working behind the Iron Curtain increased
sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Blee's success can be indirectly measured by the number of
Soviet spies working for the United States who were betrayed by
Aldrich Ames, a CIA officer in the Soviet Division. In 1985, when
Ames began to spy for the KGB, he turned over the names of at least
10 Soviet intelligence officers working for the agency. The KGB was
shocked by how deeply it had been penetrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a greater intellectual command of overseas operational
activity than any officer I ever knew,'' said Clair George, a
former agency deputy director of operations.
</P>
<P>
   David Henry Blee was born in San Francisco on Nov. 20, 1916, and
graduated from Stanford University in 1938. After graduating from
Harvard Law School in 1942, he enlisted in the Army in 1943. After
a brief assignment with the Army Corps of Engineers, Blee was
transferred to the Office of Strategic Services, the wartime
predecessor to the CIA. He joined a small team that was landed by
submarine on the islands off the coast of Thailand to monitor the
Japanese fleet.
</P>
<P>
   The excitement of wartime clandestine operations got into his
blood, and he joined the nation's new peacetime spy service when it
was founded soon after World War II. He stayed until his retirement
in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   One of Blee's biggest early triumphs came in 1965, when he was
the CIA station chief in India. Svetlana Stalin, the daughter of
the late Soviet dictator, showed up at the U.S. Embassy and asked
for political asylum. In an interview this year, Blee recalled that
while Washington dithered about how to respond, he put her on an
airplane and spirited her out of the country to safety.
</P>
<P>
   He soon became chief of the CIA's Near East Division, which
handled espionage in the Middle East, before taking over the Soviet
Division in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Blee ended his career in the same job that Angleton had occupied
for so many years, running the agency's counterintelligence
operations.
</P>
<P>
   He retired just as the CIA was coming to grips with the most
serious betrayal by one of its own officers up to that time, the
defection of Edward Lee Howard, a CIA case officer who had been
fired just before his scheduled assignment to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Before his dismissal, Howard had already been briefed on many of
the agency's most sensitive operations in the Soviet Union,
including the case of Adolf Tolkachev, a Soviet aviation design
expert who had given the CIA a trove of secret information on
Soviet military aircraft. What was not known at the time of Blee's
retirement, however, was that another intelligence officer, Ames,
had volunteered to the Soviets just as Howard was being exposed.
</P>
<P>
   Blee is survived by his wife, Margaret Gauer Blee; four sons,
John David and Robert Henry, both of Bethesda, David Cooper, of
Alexandria, Va., and Richard Earl, of Washington; a daughter,
Elizabeth Blee Fritsch of Washington; and four grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
