<HEADLINE>
MISCONCEPTIONS ABOUT GORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ What's the biggest misconception about Democrat Al
Gore?
</P>
<P>
   A panel convened by the American Enterprise Institute and the
Brookings Institution on Wednesday dealt with that issue.
</P>
<P>
   Here is what the speakers said:
</P>
<P>
   ``He will be bolder as a president than he is as a candidate.
That's part of his history.'' _ Gore biographer David Maraniss.
</P>
<P>
   ``The misconception is, he'll be capable of achieving real
reform. Because to do that he's going to have to contend with
people who have been implacable foes of education reform in this
nation.'' _ former California Gov. Pete Wilson, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a man of strong opinions, but most of them were
expressed in private over the last eight years. He's going to face
a challenge in trying to sell the idea to voters that he was a
player.'' _ Gore biographer Bill Turque.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Bill Bradley's candidacy died, Al Gore is now positioned
to become the single best basketball-playing president in the
history of the United States. He is that good. I don't think he
gets the full credit for that.'' _ U.S. Rep. Edward J. Markey of
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will take a great interest in international affairs.'' _
former Democratic Sen. James Sasser of Tennessee, a former
ambassador to China.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing we never talk about is the reason why Al Gore has
been so passionate about issues of technology and the environment
and global warming and so on is not because they are academic...but
it's because they affect people, and he understands they are things
that will affect people into the next century. You cannot ignore
the fact that pollution still does kill children, and technology
does improve the lives of people living in rural areas.'' _ Roy
Neel, Gore's former chief of staff.
</P>
</TEXT>
