<SLUG> BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: EASY NIGHT FOR GOLIATH _ THIS TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBORO, Mass. &UR;  &LR; _ The tiny island of Barbados has not a single
yard of railroad track, exactly one airport and only one regular
television channel. Put 11 Bajans on a field with 11 Americans,
however, and who knows what could happen?
</P>
<P>
   This was the operative theory early Wednesday night, as this
small nation represented gigantic fear and trembling to the United
States, or at least to that small segment of Americans aware of the
threat.
</P>
<P>
   This is the menacing charm of soccer, because one stinker of a
game, one wayward ball, one flub, one grotesque penalty call, can
upset millions of dollars' worth of preparation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The little minnow gets a chance to beat the big guy,'' said
Bruce Arena, the coach of the U.S. national team, who was dependent
on beating Barbados Wednesday night to have realistic chance of
qualifying for the 2002 World Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   The minnows did not fluster the Yanks, and there were fewer of
them as the game progressed. Two Bajans were tossed out in the
first half for gratuitous fouls, and the Americans went on to
overpower them, 7-0, which is precisely what logic would dictate
against a nation of a quarter of a million residents.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans, however, never have a reason to be relaxed in
World Cup soccer. The bigger soccer nations generally thump them,
and the smaller soccer nations scare them, at least.
</P>
<P>
   The land of the Whoppers, the land of Clinton, the land of
Jordan, the land of various Simpsons, the land of Madonna, had
every chance of being embarrassed by an island 2 1/2 times larger
than Washington.
</P>
<P>
   This is not some kind of Dream Team game, in which Charles
Barkley could come out and mock Angolans. This is a sport in which
the Americans do not dominate, a healthy anomaly given the way the
United States distributes its burgers and its sneakers and its
icons all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Yanks were humbled by Germany, by Iran, by Yugoslavia,
during the 1998 World Cup, and each of those losses was perfectly
understandable.
</P>
<P>
   The World Cup qualifying rounds produce the true terror. The
United States must meet all these modest countries from Central
America and the Caribbean, with their aspirations, their
resentments, their youth kicking tattered soccer balls or perhaps
even stuffed socks, while U.S. youth are playing with their
computers and watching Derek Jeter and Keyshawn Johnson get their
exercise for them.
</P>
<P>
   Every four years, it comes around. The United States had to go
down and suffer a draw with Guatemala in a small town chosen for
its isolation, which it did in early July.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the month, in Costa Rica, in a stadium jammed with
people who get only a few chances in life to root against Goliath,
the United States lost when a Jamaican referee made an imaginative
hand-ball call on an U.S. defender whose hands were placed,
textbook-style, at his sides.
</P>
<P>
   The rule in soccer is, get your draws on the road and your
victories at home _ particularly against the little nations. There
was not great national pressure Wednesday night. The majority of
Americans are enjoying the pennant races, keeping an eye on
football training camps, vaguely aware that the Summer Games are
coming up next month.
</P>
<P>
   This is not Italy, where if the national team had one point on
the road and about to play Liechtenstein, all of Italy would come
grinding to a stop like one of those four-hour strikes they love to
pull.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer nations quiver in a spot like this. Italy lost the final
of the European Championship last month, and its coach, the
national hero, Dino Zoff, resigned after his strategy was publicly
criticized.
</P>
<P>
   While Arena does not have a nation on his back, he did have a
few impetuous types at the U.S. Soccer Federation watching how the
Yanks performed Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I feel the pressure,'' Arena said. ``I probably put
pressure on myself, but this is how I earn my living. I don't take
it lightly. We haven't started well.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbados had stunned Costa Rica at home, using only one
prominent professional, Gregory Goodridge, 28, who plays for
Bristol City in England's Second Division.
</P>
<P>
   Never having budgeted for this second round of qualifying games,
the Barbadian federation is going more broke with every game. Its
team was ranked 102nd in the world while the United States was
ranked 19th, but there was always the chance of a ball skittering
any which way, producing chaos. Wednesday night Goliath shrugged
off the minnows. It is not usually that easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the nature of the game,'' said Arena, who is quite
intelligent enough to see the sick humor of the process, which the
rest of the world enjoys.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
