<SLUG> BC-NY-CHINESE-HOSPITAL-660words-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY SHUTS UNLICENSED CHINESE MEDICAL CLINIC 
</HEADLINE>
   By SARAH KERSHAW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Over the last three years, a clinic in Queens has
claimed to have treated thousands of patients, most of them Chinese
immigrants, offering everything from traditional herbal medicine to
cancer treatments. But neither the clinic nor its doctors were
licensed, the authorities said Wednesday after shutting it down and
arresting six people.
</P>
<P>
   At Main Street and 39th Avenue in Flushing, the heart of the
large Chinese immigrant community in Queens, the third-floor clinic
used three names, including the New York Beijing Hospital of
Traditional Chinese Medicine, said Richard A. Brown, the Queens
district attorney. Investigators shut it down Tuesday and arrested
the hospital's owner and five others on its staff, Brown said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said the clinic came to the attention of the authorities
after a patient who became infected after a gynecological procedure
sued for malpractice, and the doctors there said they could not be
sued for malpractice because they did not have licenses. The woman
said that doctors had given her an improper herbal prescription
after they removed an intrauterine device. She became ill and had
to spend 12 hours in a hospital emergency room, according to court
papers and her lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said they seized thousands of medical files,
handwritten and in Chinese, from the center, where doctors in white
lab coats wore stethoscopes and tended to patients on examining
tables. Law enforcement officials said they were trying to
determine how many patients had undergone medical procedures in the
clinic.
</P>
<P>
   The clinic advertised heavily in Chinese-language newspapers. At
its Web site, www.theworldhealth.com, it claimed to have diagnosed
thousands of illnesses since its founding in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   An advertisement in The World Journal, the city's largest
Chinese-language newspaper, pictures one of the doctors and reads,
``Famous doctor; good, secret, unique prescriptions.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation underscores the difficulties of regulating
underground medical clinics that cater to immigrants. Unlicensed
storefront clinics and herbal medicine shops that treat patients in
their back rooms are common in Flushing, doctors and other experts
say. They attract uninsured immigrants who may be more comfortable
using Chinese medicine and seeking treatment from other immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, the clinics are staffed by medical personnel who
were licensed in their native countries but who have not been
certified in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   All six of the unlicensed Flushing doctors had trained as
physicians in China and were licensed there, said their lawyer,
Hugh H. Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Mo, who is representing three of the doctors in the civil
lawsuit brought by the patient who had the gynecological treatment,
said that despite the clinic's advertising for other services, ``it
is a legitimate business that sells Chinese herbs and food
supplements.''
</P>
<P>
   The authorities charged the clinic's owner, Shou Dong Wang, 42,
of Bayside, his wife, Jing-Yi Hao, 41, and another doctor, Guo-Wu
Liu, 84, of Elmhurst, with second-degree assault in connection with
the surgery performed on the patient.
</P>
<P>
   They were also charged with second-degree reckless endangerment,
with a scheme to defraud other patients and with violating a state
education law requiring a medical license. They face up to seven
years in prison, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Three other doctors, Ying Ming Liu, 71, and Pei-Song Guo, 49,
both of Flushing, and Jiu-Song Kan, 31, of Elmhurst, were charged
with a scheme to defraud patients and with violating state
licensing law and face up to four years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   All six were arraigned Wednesday and all but Wang, the owner,
who was released on a $5,000 bail, were released without bail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
