A4164 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-GLF-PGA-NYT &LR;      08-16 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WHILE wOODS EYES HISTORY, HIS OPPONENTS EYE HIM  
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ For anyone not named Tiger Woods, it has
become even more difficult to win major championships.
</P>
<P>
   The domination of Woods and the challenge facing his competitors
have become the main themes heading into the PGA Championship,
which begins Thursday at Valhalla Golf Club. By winning three of
the last four majors, the last two in runaway fashion, Woods has
made a clear statement that he is the world's best player, by a
wide margin.
</P>
<P>
   If Woods wins this weekend, he will become the first player
since Ben Hogan in 1953 to win three consecutive majors, another
milestone for the player who has put an indelible stamp on golf at
age 24.
</P>
<P>
   But while Woods is chasing history, where does that leave
everyone else? There is a new sense of urgency among the world's
other top players, who realize that with Woods taking most of
golf's biggest prizes recently, there isn't much left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, Tiger is going to be the player to beat for the
foreseeable future,'' said Darren Clarke of Ireland, who defeated
Woods earlier this year at the Andersen Consulting Match Play
Championship. ``He's probably going to win two out of the four
majors every year. That is going to leave two for other players to
win. The fact that Tiger is going to play so well gives less
opportunity for the rest of us to win. Any time you have a chance
to win a major, it has more importance now than it did before.''
</P>
<P>
   So with world-class players like Colin Montgomerie, Phil
Mickelson and Lee Westwood still looking for their first major
championship, the year's final major will have an intense feel to
it. All eyes will be on the 9:13 a.m. threesome featuring Woods,
Vijay Singh and Jack Nicklaus, whose mother, Helen, died Wednesday
at age 90 in Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his mother's death, Nicklaus announced Wednesday that he
would play in the tournament to honor her wishes. But at age 60,
Nicklaus could be playing his final PGA Championship, and his peers
and the gallery realize the magnitude of that fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think of major championships, you think of Jack
Nicklaus,'' Tom Lehman said. ``As long as I have been playing golf,
he has always been teeing it up in the majors. It will be very
strange not to see Jack's name on the roster in a major
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Nicklaus won 18 majors, including five PGA
Championships, most players would settle for just one. Some great
players have never won the PGA Championship, including Arnold
Palmer and Tom Watson. And the PGA has been the most difficult
major to defend. Nobody has won back-to-back PGA Championships
since Denny Shute in 1936 and 1937, so Woods figures to sweat this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, everyone will have to sweat. With midday temperatures
about 90 degrees this week, along with high humidity, anyone who is
not in shape will suffer. Woods' shirt has been drenched during
practice rounds, and players will have to drink plenty of fluids.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never sweated as much in my whole life,'' said Sergio
Garcia, who lost to Woods by one stroke in an exciting back-nine
duel at last year's PGA.
</P>
<P>
   But the heat may be more intense on several players who believe
they are overdue to win a major. Among this group is Montgomerie,
who has won the European Order of Merit seven consecutive times,
but has never won a tournament in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie looked good Wednesday, having lost 20 pounds since
the British Open. He hoped having less weight would improve his
stamina, and his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just woke up one morning and said, `I don't want to be
overweight anymore,''' he said. ``I decided to go on a very strict
diet and fitness regimen. It is going to be somebody very tough
that is going to win this, mentally as well as physically.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the U.S. Open, where par was a good score for everyone
except Woods, Valhalla should allow players on top of their games
to shoot low scores. All four par 5's are reachable in two shots,
and though the rough is thick, the fairways are generous.
</P>
<P>
   Many believe that Valhalla is the perfect place for a player to
win his first major, but time will tell. Six of the last seven
majors have been won by players who had already won one. Paul
Lawrie, who won last year's British Open, was the only exception.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how much people analyze this tournament, Woods
will be the main focus, and how he plays on Thursday and Friday
will go a long way toward setting the tone of the event. The last
two majors haven't been close, and Woods shows no pity,
particularly in majors. Will anyone beat him at Valhalla? We are
about to find out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger has taken it to a different level,'' Montgomerie said.
``Everybody has to get to the next level if they want to compete.
When Michael Jordan started playing basketball, people had to
improve to compete. When Carl Lewis started running, people had to
improve. When Pele played football, people had to improve. Muhammad
Ali was the same. He raised the standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger is the best player in the world by a long, long way, and
we have to raise our standards to join his. We're all trying. We
are all failing, but we are all trying.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
