</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITH-MEMORABILIA-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMITHSONIAN'S CONVENTION COLLECTORS ATTRACT A LOT OF ATTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Paul Doak pulled the shiny, bright-blue Bill
Bradley button out of his pocket and prepared to put it in his
briefcase.
</P>
<P>
   A simple transfer. A few seconds in time. But long enough for
Harry Rubenstein to decide he wanted that button.
</P>
<P>
   He pounced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Harry Rubenstein with the Smithsonian,'' he told Doak,
handing over his business card. Yes, THAT Smithsonian, the big one
in Washington. ``We'd like to have that button.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing on the floor of the Democratic National Convention near
his fellow Democrats from New Mexico, Doak was dubious. Give away
his prized button? Just like that?
</P>
<P>
   After all, Doak was on Bradley's New Mexico steering committee.
The button was designed especially for convention supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about a trade?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never trade,'' Rubenstein said. Sensing Doak's reluctance,
Rubenstein played his trump card.
</P>
<P>
   Come to Washington someday, he said. ``I'll give you a private
tour of the collection.''
</P>
<P>
   Deal sealed. And another piece of American political history
made the transition from private ownership to a permanent place in
America's best-known museum, which already houses the microphone
that Franklin D. Roosevelt used for his fireside chats and Thomas
Jefferson's lap desk.
</P>
<P>
   Rubenstein is only part of the Smithsonian's team on the 2000
campaign trail. Since 1988 he has been teamed with Larry Bird, the
other half of the museum's ``Harry and Larry'' team.
</P>
<P>
   They are an eye-catching duo. Larry is the taller one, a
6-footer with a striking pair of bright-red gym shoes on his feet.
Harry is 5 feet 7 and carries a small, red backpack.
</P>
<P>
   Both have gray hair. Both are 49-year-old curators at the
Smithsonian's Museum of American History. Both carry large, black
portfolios in which they carry away their historic treasures.
</P>
<P>
   The two sometimes complete each other's sentences. Asked how
people feel when they are asked for a donation, Bird said, ``Tons
of doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Rubenstein, ``Their first response always is ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Incredulity,'' Bird said.
</P>
<P>
   The two don't take just anything.
</P>
<P>
   Of course they seek the funny hat and the witty placard. More
important, they want pieces that tell the story of the convention.
So this week they have gathered up signs dealing with health care _
``Affordable Rx Drugs for Medicare'' read one _ because Democratic
speakers keep mentioning a patients' bill of rights and a
prescription drug benefit for seniors.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the night the former senator from New Jersey and Al
Gore's lone rival for the nomination spoke to the convention, the
pair looked for Bradley souvenirs. After talking to Bradley
supporters, Bird and Rubenstein came away impressed that support
for Bradley remained high.
</P>
<P>
   That became part of the convention's story. So the Bradley
button was something Rubenstein wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're lucky you got that,'' Doak said as he handed over the
button. And then he offered a final, only half-in-jest warning to
Rubenstein. ``I'm going to come out there, and I'd better see it,''
he said about the button.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be there, Rubenstein said, before continuing his
meanderings on the convention floor.
</P>
<P>
   Said Doak later: ``I'm giving it to a good cause. The
Smithsonian is a national treasure.'' Rubenstein's no-nonsense
approach also helped. ``He looks like a man of his word.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday when the Kennedys spoke, Bird and Rubenstein
scrambled to come up with the prized souvenir of the night _ a
narrow, blue-and-white placard that simply said, ``Caroline.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The things we're often looking for are what people can't give
up in the moment,'' Rubenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Republican convention in Philadelphia the two snatched a
hand-written sign that read, ``McCain-iacs for Bush,'' which said
something about the bitter struggle that Sen. John McCain of
Arizona waged with George W. Bush for the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like spontaneous stuff,'' Bird said. ``An act of spontaneity
in an otherwise homogenized event.''
</P>
<P>
   In Philadelphia the duo also snagged one of their most valuable
souvenirs ever _ a $15,000 camera that produced a 360-degree view
of the convention floor for the Pseudo.com Web site. Why? The
camera signaled the Internet's new prominence in dispensing
political information.
</P>
<P>
   Bird had to do some fast talking with Pseudo Chief Executive
David Bohrman to get the camera. Fortunately for the Smithsonian,
Bohrman had a strong sense of history.
</P>
<P>
   The two prowl the floor, usually in tandem, their big portfolios
sometimes drawing quizzical stares. The objective is to take away
more stuff than they probably can use; don't want to come up
short-handed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest fear,'' Bird said, ``is someone someday will pull
open a drawer and say, `Man, they sure missed it. What were they
thinking?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The two have plenty of memorabilia from which to pick.
Democrats, for example, race out dozens of mass-produced signs from
a storage room beneath the bleachers before major speakers make
their entrance.
</P>
<P>
   But Bird and Rubenstein have noticed that delegates have become
more eager to haul home mass quantities of signs. At times that
makes it more difficult to find the items they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's collecting because of eBay,'' Rubenstein said of the
Internet site that features people selling every type of heirloom
imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   Another hurdle: The Smithsonian almost never pays for donations.
</P>
<P>
   The two usually start slowly in convention weeks so that they
can size up the crowd and the gathering. That the two have become
media darlings of a sort also has slowed them down. All kinds of
reporters have been attracted to their mission, making them the
subject of features in The New York Times and on the Today show.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years they have learned some lessons about their work.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know what you need until you see it,'' Bird said.
</P>
<P>
   Another one: ``There's never one item that says it all,''
Rubenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's this, from Rubenstein: ``It's still amazing to me
how generous people are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
