<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NOTEBOOK-GORE-IMAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL NOTEBOOK: POLITICAL ADVISERS ON HOW GORE CAN APPEAR
PRESIDENTIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELEANOR RANDOLPH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now comes the moment when Vice President Al Gore gives his big
speech, and most knowledgeable Democrats have the good sense to be
scared to death. Gore's best attributes do not shine past the
teleprompter, and over the years, the microphone has not been his
friend.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, advice on how to make a smashing acceptance speech
does not come cheap. Who knows what it cost to wipe that smirk off
Gov. George W. Bush's face in time for his big moment in
Philadelphia? But we found a number of expert speechwriters, image
makers and commentators willing and even eager to provide Gore with
a few suggestions gratis. Perhaps they are like surgeons happy to
be called in on a difficult case. It's also possible that the
Republicans want to see Gore fail and the Democrats want to be able
to say ``I told you so'' if he does. At any rate, here is a sampler
of their advice:
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Spencer, who was President Ronald Reagan's campaign
strategist, believes Gore's team ``ought to calm him down a
little.'' He explains: ``The first thing is not to run out to the
podium like a kid at a high school basketball game. Don't high-five
everybody. I laugh every time I see it. He skips, hops and jumps
through the crowd. It's outrageously unpresidential.''
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Sorensen, who was President John F. Kennedy's primary
speechwriter, offers a more succinct recipe. ``He must sound not
like he's programmed, not like he's a politician, and not like he's
a professor but like a president,'' Sorensen advised.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Rafshoon, who was President Jimmy Carter's image maker,
believes in sobriety and separation. ``He needs to give a very
substantive speech, and he needs to just talk about what he's going
to do as president and not even mention the last eight years,''
Rafshoon offered. ``Clinton didn't do him a bit of good the other
night. All he did was, he made a good case for Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafshoon and Bill Carrick, a Democratic strategist, agree that
it is time to ignore the advisers. ``At this point, you just do
what's in your gut,'' Carrick said. ``It's a great moment. There
are 40,000 people prepared to love him. All the armchair
quarterbacks, forget them all.''
</P>
<P>
   There are widely varying views on the notorious stiffness
problem. Our New York Times colleague William Safire, who once
wrote speeches for the notably unlimber Richard Nixon, suggests
that Gore could surprise people with a lighter touch. He recalled
that the vice president demonstrated at this year's Gridiron dinner
in Washington that he does a good job with self-deprecating humor.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer, however, views humor as hazardous. ``You should never
try jokes if you aren't very good at it,'' he warns.
</P>
<P>
   And finally Bill Maher, the host of television's ``Politically
Incorrect,'' made this last-minute plea: ``Al Gore should examine
the backgrounds of the delegates at the Democratic convention, and
after realizing that they all have at least fourth-grade
educations, not talk to them as if they don't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
