<HEADLINE>
IRS FALLS DOWN ON SERVICE TO SMALL BUSINESSES, REPORT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Small businesses, farmers and the self-employed pay
44 percent of all taxes the federal government collects. But a new
report says they seem to have the most difficult time deciphering
the tax code and paying what they owe.
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office found that the IRS spends much
more time trying to correct problems than trying to avoid them and
that many small-business operators find tax time frustrating and
confusing.
</P>
<P>
   ``IRS has not operated in a way that best enables it to serve
small business,'' said the study, which was requested by Sen. Kit
Bond, a Missouri Republican and chairman of the Senate Committee on
Small Business.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS says that it is aware of small-business complaints and
that numerous changes are being made to make the department more
taxpayer-friendly, as ordered by Congress in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   IRS Commissioner Charles Rossotti said steps to improve service
include simplifying forms and publications, eliminating
instructions that only apply to large businesses, setting up
special call-in sites for assistance, and providing ``clear, plain
English'' answers to taxpayer questions on Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Bond has held hearings on problems that small businesses have
with the IRS. Bond said the report, which includes a survey of
1,000 businesses nationwide and interviews with IRS officials,
``confirms what small-business owners have been telling us for
years _ the tax code is just too difficult for most people to
understand, and the IRS has not operated in a way to serve small
business effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   The GAO report said the IRS acknowledged that small businesses
are more likely than other taxpayers to have compliance problems,
mainly because of tax laws that involve several layers of filing,
reporting and deposit requirements.
</P>
<P>
   At a hearing last year, Brian Gloe of Rosse Lithographing in
Kansas City testified that his company has to file more than 180
IRS forms annually, including some forms to merely verify the
filing of other forms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small businesses may not always have the kind of resources
needed to deal with those complexities,'' the report said. It found
that 94 percent of small businesses, defined as having less than $5
million in assets, hire professional tax preparers.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS focus is on correcting problems instead of preventing
them, the report said. According to the IRS, 11 percent of its
budget is for customer assistance to avoid problems, 72 percent is
spent on compliance and 17 percent is for processing returns and
adjusting taxpayer accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that encounter compliance problems and a backlog of
taxes may end up having to go out of business, the GAO report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other words, by the time IRS determines that a small
business has a compliance problem and sets out to correct the
problem, it may be too late,'' the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 2321EDT &QL; 
