<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4171 &Cx1f; tad-z
b p BC-CVN-MAIN17-1STLD-COX     08-16 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-MAIN17-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LIEBERMAN CELEBRATES TICKET AS GORE IS NOMINATED
 &HT;    Eds: Inserts Jones, DeBarry quotes; minor editing throughout.
 &HT;    770&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Vice President Al Gore claimed the Democratic
Party's presidential nomination Wednesday night in a historic
roll-call vote that also made Sen. Joseph Lieberman the first Jew
nominated as vice president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is America a great country or what?'' Lieberman said in
accepting the No. 2 spot on the ticket. ``Only in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman arrived on the podium to the musical theme from
``Chariots of Fire,'' the Academy Award-winning movie about the
1924 British Olympic track team led by Harold Abrahams, a Jewish
sprinter.
</P>
<P>
   Paying homage to his parents and blue-collar upbringing in
Connecticut, Lieberman spoke of ``the importance of work and
responsibility,'' key elements of the centrist ``New Democrat''
movement in which both Gore and Lieberman are rooted.
</P>
<P>
   But Lieberman also invoked the legacy of John F. Kennedy with
words that acknowledged his own historic role in American politics
and sought to assure restless liberals that the centrist ticket is
well versed in the traditions of the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that the next frontier isn't just in front of us,
but inside of us _ to overcome the differences that are still
between us, to break down the barriers that remain, and to help
every American claim the limitless possibilities of our own
lives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Lewis of Georgia, a hero of the civil rights movement
in the 1960s, strove in his nomination speech to put to rest any
doubts about Lieberman. Recalling Lieberman's involvement in voting
rights drives in the once-segregated South, he called the senator
``my brother.''
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut senator was introduced to the convention
delegates by his wife, Hadassah, the child of Holocaust victims.
She described Lieberman as a man whose sense of community ``reminds
him to embrace our nation's diversity and celebrate our
differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's choice of Lieberman, an Orthodox Jew with the reputation
as ``the conscience of the Senate,'' was widely viewed as an
attempt to further distance the vice president from the scandals of
the Clinton presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's acceptance speech did little to suggest otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known Al Gore for 15 years,'' Lieberman said. ``I know
his record and I know his heart. I know him as a public servant and
I know what it is like to sit with him around the dining room
table. We have discussed _ sometimes even debated _ policy issues.
And we have shared private moments of prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, a Southern Baptist and former Vanderbilt University
seminarian, arrived in Los Angeles hours before the roll-call vote
of the states that formally gave him the presidential nomination he
had sought for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president will accept the nomination Thursday night
with a speech that looms as the most important address of his
24-year career in politics.
</P>
<P>
   Upon his arrival at the Burbank airport Wednesday, Gore said his
acceptance speech would make clear ``the big choices'' American
voters will face in this year's presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   ``You deserve to know exactly what the candidates are proposing
to do so you can make an informed judgment,'' Gore said. ``I'm
going to tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore, who continues to trail Republican nominee George W.
Bush in public opinion polls, also faces the challenge of
presenting himself as a more appealing figure.
</P>
<P>
   That process began Wednesday with a series of nominating
speeches that was designed to introduce the American TV viewing
audience beyond the Staples Center convention hall to ``Al Gore,
the principled fighter,'' as the producers billed the third night
of the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the people who know Gore best delivered the nominating
speeches: actor Tommy Lee Jones, Gore's roommate at Harvard; Lois
DeBerry, a state legislator in Gore's home state of Tennessee; and
Karenna Gore Schiff, Gore's oldest child and the mother of his
1-year-old grandson, Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad is a man of faith in the most gutsy, practical sense,''
said Schiff. ``He wants to see goodness prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Schiff, who has emerged as one of the vice president's most
important advisers with a talent of her own for politics, added:
``I'm not asking you to support Al Gore because he is my father,
even because he's been a great dad for his kids. What really
matters is what he will do for all our kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore joined his daughter in an unannounced visit to the podium
following her address. The two embraced and waved to the cheering,
sign-waving delegates before departing.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Jones painted an affectionate and very human picture of Gore,
calling him ``the closest thing I've had to a brother.''
</P>
<P>
   He reminisced about his college-year visits to the Gore home in
Carthage, Tenn., where they spent time ``catching a loose cow,
going canoeing and hunting, and chasing through the woods with coon
dogs in the middle of the night.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jones also shared how Gore ``struggled to hold on to this
faith'' following the assassination of Robert F. Kennedy and the
U.S. involvement in Vietnam, only to emerge as someone who ``has
the brains _ and the heart _ to change the whole world.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman set the stage for Gore's speech with his own critique
of the Republican ticket that was nominated in Philadelphia, citing
the poor standing of Texas in providing health care and in
preventing air and water pollution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two weeks ago, our Republican friends tried to walk and talk a
lot like us,'' he said. ``But let's be honest: we may be near
Hollywood, but not since Tom Hanks won an Oscar has there been that
much acting in Philadelphia.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said, ``I'm glad the GOP has changed their rhetoric,
but I wish they would also change their policies,'' he said. ``As
my friend John McCain might say, let me do some straight talking
about their record.''
</P>
<P>
   He singled out the GOP's education policies, suggesting that a
Republican administration would not provide adequate financial
resources to modernize the public school system. ``To me, it seems
like their idea of school modernization means buying a new calendar
for every building,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
