<HEADER>
A4172 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      08-16 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD SERVICE SHOULD BE THE RULE, NOT THE EXCEPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's no excuse for going back. I gave into ``convenience''
and kept dropping in. But this time I mean it. I'm not patronizing
that office supply store again.
</P>
<P>
   In several visits over the years (I know, I know, what took so
long?) I have encountered nothing that remotely resembles customer
service:
</P>
<P>
   The cashier who maintained a personal phone conversation with a
family member while scanning my purchases and taking my money. She
neither looked up nor spoke to me.
</P>
<P>
   The employee who pointed to the back of the store and said the
item might be on aisle 9. I found it on aisle 7.
</P>
<P>
   The employee who said he was new, didn't know the answer and
walked away. I assumed he went to ask someone. After a few minutes,
it was clear he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   The two workers who held an animated gripe session about their
shift schedules while three customers waited at the counter.
</P>
<P>
   The item that was on a sale table but scanned at a higher price
at the register. The cashier said the computer price ruled.
</P>
<P>
   The trash barrel that overflowed at the front door.
</P>
<P>
   That's it. Finally, absolutely, I'm done with the place.
</P>
<P>
   I haven't just seen one person having a bad day. I've
encountered a succession of badly trained, poorly supervised people
who clearly don't want to be there and don't have a natural
customer service bone in their bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, when I have on occasion written columns
endorsing better customer service by front-line workers, some
readers have responded that I'm an idiot.
</P>
<P>
   I shouldn't expect any better, they say. After all, these are
entry-level employees who aren't paid enough to put out the extra
effort. Their employers don't deserve any more.
</P>
<P>
   Poppycock.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody who draws a paycheck anywhere has entered into a
contract. A paycheck isn't a gift for just showing up, although
that certainly helps. A paycheck is given partly for helping to
fulfill the organization's goal: to meet customer needs and
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Too many unmet customer expectations eventually translate into
too few customers and a ``Going Out of Business'' sign on the door.
</P>
<P>
   The burden rests partly on management to hire decent people,
train them and supervise them properly. It also falls on the
individual worker to exercise initiative, sensible judgment and
good intentions.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't some ``the customer is always right'' diatribe.
Sometimes the customer is dead wrong. Many a worker has the horror
stories to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   But most customers don't march in to inflict pain and suffering
on diligent worker bees. Most customers need something and want a
smooth transaction.
</P>
<P>
   It'd help a whole lot of people a whole bunch if ``It's not my
job,'' ``I don't know,'' ``It's not our policy,'' ``I'm new and
they haven't told me yet,'' ``It's not my department'' and ``I
wasn't here when that happened'' disappeared from workplace
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   It'd help a whole lot of people _ patrons and purveyors _ if
more time were spent searching for satisfactory solutions than
ignoring or griping about the way things are.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
