<SLUG> BC-NAIA-MOVE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAIA SUGGESTS PERKS IT WANTS TO RELOCATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRAD COOPER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Auto leases and country club membership fees
are some of the items the NAIA is shopping for from 39 communities,
including Olathe, Kan., trying to draw the sports organization away
from Tulsa, Okla., records show.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics is
considering another relocation eight years after it abruptly
decided to leave Kansas City. The association had been in Kansas
City 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   The NAIA sent 39 cities a ``request for proposal'' that outlined
areas the cities should address in their proposals to the group.
Kansas City was not among the cities.
</P>
<P>
   Among the suggested inducements were auto leases for two staff
members and country club initiation fees for at least three
staffers. Country club initiation fees can range between $4,000 and
$40,000, depending on the kind of membership.
</P>
<P>
   The NAIA also wants cities to address whether they would provide
a relocation package, including moving expenses, moving assistance
for staff, and job search and placement for the spouses of
organization staffers, according to the document.
</P>
<P>
   The organization also wants each community to indicate its
financial commitment to the NAIA project. Such a commitment could
include land, cash or the donation of products and services from
any source.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Carr, managing director and general counsel for the NAIA,
said the organization was not looking for a government handout.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really is looked at as a proposal that would come from
the public and the private sector,'' Carr said. ``We definitely
don't expect a city or a county to just write us a check out of
their funds.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Rolnick, director of research for the Federal Reserve
Bank in Minneapolis, has spent nine years researching and writing
about economic incentives given to businesses.
</P>
<P>
   In his research, Rolnick said, he hadn't seen a case where a
government gave a business an amenity like an auto lease or golf
club membership to relocate.
</P>
<P>
   The NAIA's request for proposal was obtained by /{The Kansas
City Star/} from the city of Olathe under the Kansas Open Records
Act.
</P>
<P>
   Whether city taxpayers or the private sector would pay for the
expenses was left to each community to decide. What was clear from
the proposal was that the NAIA wanted help from the community to
relocate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NAIA is asking for a great deal of support from our new
partner,'' the proposal states. ``The NAIA is pursuing a joint
effort to raise the capital necessary to secure land and build the
new facility for the NAIA and the community.''
</P>
<P>
   The NAIA, an organization made up of 331 mostly small colleges,
caught Kansas City leaders off guard in September 1992 when its
council of presidents voted unanimously to move to Tulsa.
</P>
<P>
   But now it's time to put the past behind, said Kevin Gray,
president of the Greater Kansas City Sports Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it (the NAIA's possible move from Tulsa) tells you is
that the grass isn't always greener on the other side,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The organization is looking for a site that is between 14 and 15
acres to accommodate a complex between 62,000 and 79,000 square
feet.
</P>
<P>
   The NAIA said it was looking for a new site because it was
adding new programs that required more space. Tulsa is a candidate
for the new headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Other cities that have expressed interest include Branson;
Lexington, Ky.; St. Louis; Orlando, Fla.; Buffalo, N.Y.; Cleveland;
and Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   Cities have until Wednesday to submit proposals. The NAIA will
pare that list to five by Sept. 7, and a final decision is expected
by mid-January. A move could occur as early as July 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Carr of the NAIA said the group was only suggesting some items
that each community could provide. That did not necessarily mean
those were requirements for attracting the organization, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the country club fees, Carr said the organization
conducted a lot of business on the golf course, including the
wooing of corporate sponsors. He said it was an incentive that
could be provided by the private sector without much cost to the
community at large.
</P>
<P>
   Carr said the auto leases were another way a community could
contribute without incurring significant costs. When the NAIA moved
to Tulsa from Kansas City in 1993, Carr said, two local car
dealerships in Tulsa were active with the local sports commission
and chamber of commerce, and the dealerships agreed to provide
cars.
</P>
<P>
   NAIA officials said the organization's headquarters would
benefit the community. They said the organization had injected an
estimated $69.9 million into the Tulsa economy since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Tim McKee, vice president of economic development for the Olathe
Chamber of Commerce, said he did not foresee any taxpayer subsidies
being used to draw the NAIA to Olathe. McKee said the chamber had
been trying to bring the private sector together to support the
city's bid.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Olathe chamber probably would pitch two or three
sites for the NAIA to consider. One that has been mentioned is at
Renner Road and 119th Street. The City Council is considering a
plan to offer tax breaks to develop three corners of that
intersection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We obviously would like them to come to town,'' McKee said.
``They bring a lot to the entire metro area.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; tag1:To reach Brad Cooper, Johnson County municipal reporter,
call {(816) 234-7724} or send e-mail to {bcooper &LR; kcstar.com}
</P>
<P>
   &LR; tag1:The Star's Steve Rock contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
