<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON GIVES INFIELDERS REST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The offense is dreadful, the losses are mounting, so Los
Angeles Dodgers manager Davey Johnson went away from the norm and
rested three of the regular infielders. Only shortstop Alex Cora,
who platoons with Kevin Elster, started Wednesday's series finale
against the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Eric Karros, second baseman Mark Grudzielanek and
third baseman Adrian Beltre each rested while Jim Leyritz and F.P.
Santangelo each started for the first time in more than a month. It
gives the trio two days off because of today's off day. Dave Hansen
started in place of Beltre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I can take a step back and refocus and come back Friday,''
said Grudzielanek, who is 3 for 20 on the road trip and also made
two defensive miscues in Tuesday's loss. ``I think there should
have been more of this throughout the year, giving guys days off.
It's important, even for guys like Sheff (Gary Sheffield) and
(Shawn) Green.''
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek, who missed nearly two weeks last month with an
illness, had appeared in 108 of the first 118 games and Karros had
appeared in 114 games. Sheffield played in his 116th game against
the Marlins and Green has played in every game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just to give a little bit of a rest,'' Johnson said.
``Give some other guys a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, Santangelo made his first start since July 13,
though he missed time while on the disabled list and while serving
a five-game suspension. Leyritz's start at first was his first
since joining the Dodgers in late July. He started two games at
catcher, the last being July 9.
</P>
<P>
   Santangelo is hoping that getting a couple of at-bats back to
back can trigger something. Santangelo has had a disappointing and
frustrating season, but he said his recent rehab appearance at
Single-A San Bernardino might have triggered a memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got back into my old stance that I had in Montreal,'' said
Santangelo, who belted his first career pinch-hit homer Tuesday.
``That's the way I was swinging on the rehab assignment. The night
before (a pop-out), it was my first at-bat in 14 days. The hitting
coach there, Jack Clark, asked me why I was spread out and I said I
didn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort in rhythm: Right-hander Darren Dreifort has won six
straight, has a 2.33 ERA since the All-Star break, and yet keeps
getting pushed back in the rotation as the Dodgers try to protect
him against arm weariness the last six weeks of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about that,'' Dreifort said. ``Why worry about
it? You don't control it.''
</P>
<P>
   But what Dreifort does care about is how he's thrown since the
All-Star break. He's won a career-high six straight decisions, and
has been the Dodgers' best pitcher over the past month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all starts with the rhythm,'' said Dreifort, who is 10-7
with a 4.35 ERA. ``Once you feel like you're in rhythm, your
mechanics should all into place. You still get out of it from time
to time, but maybe I recognize quicker what I'm doing and can back
into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds ands ends: Catcher Todd Hundley said his sore right knee,
which kept him from starting Tuesday, felt much better and he
should be able to start Friday. ... With right-hander Chan Ho Park
missing his start with flu-like symptoms, the Dodgers altered their
pitching rotation. Kevin Brown will pitch Friday, Park will go
Saturday, if healthy, and Dreifort will throw Sunday. If Park is
ailing late in the week, Dreifort would be moved up to Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
