<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BRADLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL BRADLEY IS ASKED TO HEAD U.S. OLYMPIC COMMITTEE 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five months after dropping out of the race for the U.S.
presidency, Bill Bradley has been asked if he wants to be chairman
of the U.S. Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Norm Blake, the USOC's chief executive, said Wednesday that he
had spoken by telephone with Bradley, the former New Jersey
senator, three or four weeks ago at the request of the
organization's nominating committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was seriously considering it, and I was very
impressed with how he conducted himself,'' Blake said. ``He wanted
to be sure it wasn't a figurehead position, and wanted a job where
he could make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, a former New York Knicks player, gave no decision and
Blake was awaiting Bradley's response to a tentative date for a
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who spoke Tuesday night at the Democratic National
Convention, played for the 1964 U.S. Olympic basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   Anita Dunn, a spokeswoman for Bradley, said, ``He is considering
a number of options, but he's not commenting on any specific
conversations that he's having with anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The USOC's nominating committee is expected to recommend a slate
of officers, including chairman, by Sept. 1. The USOC's board of
directors will vote in December.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his direct contact with Bradley, Blake said, ``I will
embrace whomever the nominating committee recommends.''
</P>
<P>
   The USOC reorganized last year under a corporate model by
creating a more powerful CEO position out of the former executive
director's job, and turning the formerly volunteer president's job,
now held by Bill Hybl, into the chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman, who is not paid, would have broad international
responsibilities and a significant role in Washington. Steve
Richards, chief of the nominating committee, confirmed that ``as
part of the process of looking at a variety of candidates,''
Bradley was contacted.
</P>
<P>
   Richard declined to say whether Bradley was the only outsider
being considered for chairman. Paul George and Sandy Baldwin, two
USOC vice presidents, are being considered. Also, Sandy Knapp, of
USA Gymnastics, said Wednesday, ``I'm in the candidate pool.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-16-00 2344EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
