<DOCNO> NYT20000816.0493 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 23:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4201 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-WILLEY-COL-AZR &LR;      08-16 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLEY-COL-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-WILLEY-COL-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    DEMOCRATES NEED TO HONE MESSAGE(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By KEVEN WILLEY(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (LOS ANGELES) - Dick Cheney wasn't referring to the Democratic
National Convention when he criticized Democrats earlier this month
for ``opportunities squandered.'' But he could have been.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Democrats' vice presidential nominee, Joe Lieberman,
capitalized handsomely on his prime-time opportunity Wednesday
night to introduce himself and his compelling life story to
American voters, much of the rest of the Democrats' quadrennial
show thus far has failed to live up to key strategy expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Take Tuesday's speaker lineup. To the party faithful crowded
into Staples Center, it was a nostalgic, popular, star-studded
cast. But giving Jesse Jackson and Ted Kennedy prime television
exposure violates nearly every modern-day party tenet.
</P>
<P>
   They are, after all, old-school liberals. Hardly representative
of the youthful New Democrat modernism that President Clinton
worked so hard to legitimize since winning the White House in 1992
and that Al Gore must project if he hopes to attract new voters to
his presidential ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the keynoter was a fresh-faced young congressman from
Tennessee named Harold Ford. And he gave it his best. But following
the likes of Jackson, Kennedy and still-popular former Sen. Bill
Bradley to the podium was simply too great a burden.
</P>
<P>
   In a twist symbolic of squandered convention opportunities, the
keynoter's speech was actually shorter than that of the supposed
warm-up act. But no matter. He was pushed out of prime time by the
party elders who preceded him to the podium and so hardly anyone
heard what he had to say anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' lack of discipline this week is just as evident
off the convention floor. While the Republicans can rightly be
accused of flaunting ``an illusion of inclusion'' at their
convention in Philadelphia earlier this month, their efforts paid
off in projecting a clearly focused message to the American public:
Opportunity for all Americans and we are uniting behind the goal of
achieving it.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats this week have gone to the opposite extreme,
actually unifying around very little. Mostly they are splintered.
</P>
<P>
   For example, there are more caucuses than state delegations.
You're a blue-eyed, former drug-abusing, lesbian Latina union
activist who has been victimized by global warming and wants to
save the whales? No problem. There's a celebration for you
somewhere in LA this week.
</P>
<P>
   It's a newfound sense of entitlement, this identity-by-caucus,
born perhaps, as one Democratic strategist speculated, from ``the
hubris of victory.'' Republicans, by contrast, all sang resolutely
from the same choir book in Philly. Dull, yes. Also effective.
</P>
<P>
   Whether this splintering of message, this thematic
disorganization, is a harbinger of Democratic frustration at the
polls this fall remains unclear. But Republicans managed to close
their convention in Philly having significantly boosted their image
among Americans nationwide. Democrats have yet to prove they will
do the same.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Willey at keven.willey &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (a)arizonarepublic.com or (602) 444-8499.
</P>
</TEXT>
